<HEADLINE>
COHEN GOES TO HOUSE TO DEFEND RAIDS ON IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-WHIP,
IMPEACH-TRIPP, IMPEACH-HILLARY, IMPEACH-NY.) (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With congressional Republicans wary about
Wednesday's raids on Iraq, the White House on Wednesday night
dispatched the most prominent Republican in the Clinton
administration _ William Cohen, the secretary of defense _ to offer
personal testament to the integrity of the attack from the well of
the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   For slightly more than 90 minutes, Cohen spoke to a closed
gathering of lawmakers. He offered a detailed accounting of the
decision to attack, and asked for bipartisan support of the action.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared with the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen.
Henry Shelton, and the director of central intelligence, George
Tenet, at the invitation of Newt Gingrich, the departing House
speaker, who unlike some of his colleagues was notably restrained
in his reaction to the raid.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was described as a generally civil and orderly
session during which Cohen repeated many of the details he had
offered in a televised briefing _ until Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas,
the combative House majority whip, startled his colleagues and
Cohen by demanding to know whether he believed that national
security would be endangered if the House were to proceed on
Thursday with a vote on the impeachment resolutions against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen at first declined to answer, according to officials who
were present, saying that such a decision should be left to the
House. DeLay pressed the question, and the Republican secretary
responded with a plea for support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the tradition throughout history that when we have
people out there with the risk of dying, it's good to have good
bipartisan support,'' Cohen said, according to a witness. The
remark was greeted by applause from throughout the chamber, said
one of those present.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen continued: ``Unity and bipartisan support is important for
the morale of the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   While briefings for committees or congressional leaders are not
unusual in times of military action, the unusual politics of
impeachment accounted for the extraordinary sight of a defense
secretary testifying in the well of the House to the honesty of his
commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen dominated the session, a testimony to his stature in this
part of Washington: Cohen served in the House from 1973 until 1979,
and as U.S. senator from Maine from that year until Clinton
nominated him in 1997. Cohen's decision to put his own reputation
behind the integrity of the attack clearly influenced some, though
not all, of the lawmakers who attended Wednesday night's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., said Cohen ``went to great lengths
to point out how he had never had politics as his consideration for
the military action,'' and that Cohen said he would not have
acquiesced to the attack if politics were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Gekas, R-Fla., said he was inclined to believe that
the attack was not politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless I find evidence that there was a calculated timing, I
have to give the president the benefit of the doubt,'' Gekas said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., chairman of the House National
Security Committee, said Cohen had assured the members of Congress
that ``events dictated'' the raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some accepted it, who wanted to, and others didn't,'' Spence
said of his colleagues' reactions. Spence was more reserved in
offering his own perception. ``I've heard it before,'' he said,
adding that he thought the attack could just have easily been
launched in November, or next week.
</P>
<P>
   After Cohen's presentation, Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La., the
speaker-designate, said the House would vote on Thursday on a
resolution in support of troops involved in the action.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's meeting came after a raucous day on Capital Hill, when
many Republicans were raising direct questions about whether
Clinton had timed the attack to undercut Republican plans to vote
on the impeachment resolutions. The debate, which was supposed to
begin Thursday morning, was put off after the attack began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
