<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA LOCKER-ROOM CHATS HIT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Bruins have learned as much in the locker room
as on the court this season, and the knowledge has little to do
with the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Lavin has arranged for a slew of coaches and former
athletes _ including Jerry West, Rafer Johnson, A.C. Green, Ronnie
Lott and Larry Brown _ to speak to the Bruins about managing their
lives and improving their market value.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights:
</P>
<P>
   _Johnson, the gold medal decathlete, talked about being an
African-American college student during the dawn of the civil
rights movement and his relationship with Robert Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   _Lott described his childhood desire to play basketball for
UCLA, until he realized his future was in football at USC. ``He got
worked into a frenzy,'' Lavin said. ``I think the guys were a
little scared.''
</P>
<P>
   _Former UCLA players Kiki Vandeweghe, Mitchell Butler and
Darrick Martin talked about their personal triumphs and failures.
Martin described his sour relationship with former coach Jim
Harrick and its effect on his performance.
</P>
<P>
   _West, the Hall of Famer and Lakers executive, expressed
frustration about dealing with modern players, urged the Bruins to
select positive role models and warned: ``Don't be an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   It hit home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us how to be a pro on and off the court, how to be in
the spotlight,'' Bruins guard Rico Hines said.
</P>
<P>
   Each speaker was well received _ Lavin, a lifelong San Francisco
49ers fan, was especially taken with Lott _ but the Bruins best
identified with the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked Butler, Green and Martin,'' forward Travis Reed said.
``They're pros, and that's where I want to be. I'd rather listen to
them than anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Necessity: With Baron Davis on the court, the Bruins
outscored Nevada Las Vegas 49-30. Without him, they were outscored
37-23. Davis remains on a restricted-minutes program and probably
will play 20-25 minutes Saturday against Cal State Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``His medical team sees it as a marathon, not a sprint,'' said
Lavin, who hopes Davis will be cleared to play 30 minutes a game in
January.
</P>
<P>
   A look ahead: Next year's schedule is complete, and it's a good
one. The Bruins will host Pepperdine, Iona, Purdue, Gonzaga and
DePaul, and they'll visit Syracuse and North Carolina, which
replaces Duke as the major intersectional television game.
Pepperdine features former assistant Lorenzo Romar, while Purdue
coach Gene Keady is Lavin's former boss and mentor.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA will not participate in a November tournament because of a
late-summer trip to Italy. The NCAA does not allow foreign tours
and preseason tournaments in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Short stuff: Top recruit Carlos Boozer visited campus last
weekend and watched the Nevada Las Vegas game from midcourt, six
rows up. Ex-Duke star Grant Hill was conveniently seated two rows
above Boozer, casting a massive shadow. The Bruins and Blue Devils
are slugging it out for his signature.... Forward JaRon Rush,
shooting 19.2 percent from 3-point range, is taking extra practice
each morning to find his groove.... Forward/center Jerome Moiso is
averaging 17.5 points since Lavin's threat to bench him in Puerto
Rico for not shooting.... Forward Travis Reed is shooting 90
percent from the foul line after making just 33.3 percent last
year. ``That has to be some kind of record for the greatest
turnaround in the history of college basketball,'' Lavin quipped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
