<HEADER>
A4194 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     12-17 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SO much has changed since the day in 1992 when Drayton McLane Jr.
fell into our midst like a turnip off the back of one of his
grocery trucks.
</P>
<P>
   He was the wide-eyed innocent then, the benevolent grandfather
type who would deliver us from the evil clutches of John McMullen,
the Great Satan long before angry Iranians hung that label on our
entire nation.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a no-nonsense businessman so out of his element, so
unfamiliar with the warped realities of the professional sport in
which he was suddenly chin-deep, that he once sat at a budget
meeting and questioned the entry for team per diem on road trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I have to pay for their meals?'' he asked. ``I
already give them good salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Tee-hee.
</P>
<P>
   How charming to think the owner of a major-league baseball
franchise could be so full of naivet about the dirty details of the
industry in which he had just invested millions. How long, you
wondered, would it take for him to understand the infield-fly rule
and that a closer isn't the guy who locks up the Astrodome at
night?
</P>
<P>
   Just three years later, McLane had become an expert at the
municipal blackmail game, threatening to sell the Astros to a man
with a bag of cash in Northern Virginia if Houston didn't build him
a stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Give him this: He's a quick study, capable of changing colors
faster than a chameleon.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us _ and McLane down on his knees _ to Roger
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   If we are to believe any of the poor-mouthing and the speeches
about fiscal responsibility that McLane has delivered, then he
should phone agent Randy Hendricks today and tell him to go peddle
the Rocket on another street corner. No wheedling, no
counteroffers.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1994 during the calamitous labor war, when the owners
canceled the World Series and left their sport hemorrhaging, McLane
was one of the hardest-line owners. With a payroll at the time of
roughly $26 million, he showed us the insides of his empty pockets
and preached the need for salary controls. He also hammered away
that his low-revenue Astros could not engage in bidding for
top-dollar free agents with the Yankees, Braves, Dodgers, Indians,
Rockies and their ilk.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a payroll that will already top $50 million next
season, McLane continues to waltz with Hendricks about bringing
Clemens home to Texas, even if means renegotiating an $8
million-a-year contract to something just this side of Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   By making a counteroffer to the agent's outrageous demand and
keeping the lines of communication open when the price is so high,
McLane is going against the advice of his management team, which
includes knowledgeable baseball men such as club president Tal
Smith and general manager Gerry Hunsicker.
</P>
<P>
   More significant, by continuing his
teen-age-boy-sniffing-after-the-prom-queen act, McLane is
demonstrating he is no different than any other baseball owner. By
even broaching the subject of a renegotiated contract, he is
contributing to an economic system that is cannibalizing the game
and which he claims to abhor. By overruling his general manager,
McLane proves his ego outweighs his sense.
</P>
<P>
   The simple reason Hendricks slithered around Hunsicker to
negotiate with McLane is that the owner, caught up in the rah-rah
hype, is more apt to take a bite of the apple, even if it means
crippling the team in the process. You saw the way McLane stood by
his high-profile seat behind home plate at the Dome, giddy from
backslaps, basking in the glow of the Astros' 102-win season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you make me a champion?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, golly, Beav.
</P>
<P>
   It was never better for McLane than the two months when Randy
Johnson lit up Houston with his fastball and the owner swam in
congratulations. Just imagine the compliments he'd get for
delivering the Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the grocery distributor is now hooked on the
adulation, which is turning him into an enabler who allows a
destructive economic system to get more rotten to the core.
</P>
<P>
   Some of McLane's baseball people didn't think it was a good idea
to offer Johnson $33 million as a free agent, believing that
spending just part of that money to boost other areas of the team
was the more prudent path.
</P>
<P>
   Those same folks surely don't want to gut what has been built in
order to add Clemens at a budget-busting and logic-smashing price.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the baseball minds who need convincing but McLane. Just
six years since falling off the grocery truck as a brand-new kind
of owner, one turnip looks like all the rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
