<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS BACK WHERE THEY STARTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For three-quarters of one game, the Los Angeles
Kings were almost whole.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Blake was playing after missing 15 games with a broken foot,
oft-injured center Jozef Stumpel was in the lineup, and the goalies
were healthy.
</P>
<P>
   That was Saturday, when the Kings (8-18-3) defeated Vancouver
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   This is now: Blake will miss the second game of the three-game
suspension he picked up thanks to a slashing penalty early in the
third period against the Canucks, and No.1 goalie Stephane Fiset
will be sidelined tonight when the Kings play host to the New York
Islanders. Only Stumpel remains.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset suffered what team physician Dr. Ronald Kvitne said was
``tightness'' in his right groin during practice Wednesday. On Oct.
18, Fiset suffered a right groin strain and was sidelined 10 days.
In his first game back, he suffered a left groin strain and missed
another month.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Fiset is listed as day to day, though his initial strain at
first was called a one-game injury and ended up lasting longer.
Jamie Storr, who missed one month with a groin strain earlier this
season, is scheduled to play tonight. Manny Legace was recalled
Wednesday from the Long Beach Ice Dogs to serve as Storr's backup.
Legace is just getting over a strained back, and another goalie in
the Kings' system, Ryan Bach, also has a groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to recalling Legace, the Kings promoted rookie right
wing Pavel Rosa from the Ice Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa, 21, has had injury problems of his own, recently missing
14 games with symptoms of post-concussion syndrome related to
concussion and inner-ear problems that sidelined him for most of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot, 195-pound Rosa, who has never appeared in an NHL
game, had 13 points in 16 games with the Ice Dogs. He is considered
one of the Kings' top prospects, and two years ago had 63 goals and
153 points in the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa replaces winger Eric Lacroix on the Kings' roster. Lacroix,
who was placed on the injured-reserve list Wednesday, is expected
to miss about a month with a broken collarbone. Perhaps Rosa can
give the Kings' offense a lift. The Kings have scored fewer goals
than all but two of the NHL's 27 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Blake upset: Blake sounded off on the three-game suspension
handed to him by NHL vice president Colin Campbell for his slash on
Vancouver's Harry York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a joke,'' Blake said. ``You've got one guy who
thinks he can do anything he wants. They've got no decision-making
process at all.... He said it was a two-handed baseball swing. If
I'm going to two-hand a guy, I'm going to break his arm.''
</P>
<P>
   X-rays were negative on York, who suffered a bruise on the play
and is not expected to be sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was that bad, Vancouver would have sent (a videotape to
the NHL),'' said Blake, who learned of the three-game suspension
after a telephone hearing Monday. ``The hearing is useless.
(Campbell) had his mind made up before going into that hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake said that after the slash, teammate Luc Robitaille skated
over to referee Don Koharski, who had assessed Blake a five-minute
major and game misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luc said to Koho, `Is he going to get suspended?''' Blake
said. ``He said, `No, but I'm going to give him a major.' I've done
worse in games and gotten two minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was concerned his remarks could lead to further
discipline from Campbell, Blake shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to fine me $1,000 probably,'' said Blake, who
already has lost $83,304.69 as a result of the slash. ``Maybe he'll
see what I said and say, `I'm going to give you a few more games.'
''
</P>
</TEXT>
