<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS DEFEAT RANGERS, 6-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The opponent may have been the Rangers,
with Wayne Gretzky, Brian Leetch and Petr Nedved, but the Devils
never emphasized defense on Wednesday night at the Continental
Arena. Instead, they looked to attack from the outset, producing
more than five goals for the fifth consecutive game, this time a
6-3 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys believe in themselves and they're scoring,'' Coach
Robbie Ftorek said after New Jersey's third consecutive victory
over New York this season extended their unbeaten streak to eight
games (6-0-2). ``All the guys play aggressively when we have the
puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott and Jay Pandolfo led the Devils with two goals
each, with Sheldon Souray and Bobby Holik also scoring goals for
the Devils, who improved their record to 18-7-3, best in the
Eastern Conference. The victory also set a team record of at least
five goals in five straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is working well for us right now,'' said Petr
Sykora, who had a Gretzky-like game with three assists. ``We have
four lines scoring goals and that's good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky assisted on power-play goals by Kevin Stevens and Adam
Graves and scored the last goal for the Rangers on a breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lousy in our zone,'' Coach John Muckler said. ``This
is the worst I have ever seen a team play in their own zone. It's
just a guessing game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur, who has started 13 of the last 14 games and is
undefeated in his last eight starts, earned his 14th victory of the
season (14-7-3) with 23 saves. Chris Terreri has the other four
victories in as many starts.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with enthusiasm before only their second sellout crowd
of the season _ their first also came against the Rangers _ the
Devils displayed plenty of resiliency around Mike Richter, who
faced 27 shots in his 10th consecutive start for the Rangers
(11-12-7).
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took the lead on Pandolfo's eighth of the season, 3
minutes 40 seconds after the opening face-off, when he stepped into
the slot and converted a rebound of a shot by Scott Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers tied it on a shot by Kevin Stevens during their
first manpower advantage. His goal was his first in eight games and
the fourth power-play goal in two nights for the Rangers. Although
the Devils were aware of the Rangers' efficiency with the man
advantage, they took four penalties in the opening period, two by
Holik.
</P>
<P>
   One of Holik's penalties carried over into the second period,
allowing the Rangers to take control in the early stages of the
period. But the Devils quickly reversed the tables and scored the
next three goals.
</P>
<P>
   Souray gave the Devils the lead with his first of the season at
6:39 when he beat Richter over the glove moments after Arnott had
hit the post in the same sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott caught Richter too far away from his goal at 11:20
seconds for his eighth goal, and Holik extended the lead to three
goals with his 11th just 55 seconds later, when his shot from the
high slot found its way through a crowd in front of Richter.
</P>
<P>
   After Graves narrowed the gap for the Rangers just 30 seconds
into the last period, Arnott scored another goal before Gretzky got
his sixth of the season and Pandolfo sealed the victory with an
empty-netter with 46 seconds left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 0021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
