<SLUG> BC-CABLE-INTERNET-ACCESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OVER ONLINE ACCESS COMING TO SAN FERNANDO VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Two cable television giants are poised to offer
lightning-fast access to Web surfers in the suburban San Fernando
Valley, using a technology that could change the face of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With an online connection through cable television lines, users
will be able to download files in seconds rather than minutes, at
speeds more than 1,000 times faster than telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   But woven into the technology is a growing national debate that
will begin playing out tonight in Los Angeles. The battle pits
cable companies such as Tele-Communications Inc. and Time Warner
against companies including America Online and Earthlink, who want
their services to be available through the new cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   The cable companies want to require consumers to pay for their
high-speed Internet service, and if they want AOL or another
service, they would pay for that as well.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Board of Information Technology Commissioners tonight
will begin hearing from consumers and technology industry lobbyists
on both sides of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're looking at a civil war between cable and
Internet service providers, and what we have to look at is if this
merger will take away from competition,'' said Alan Arkatov,
president of the board. ``We have to look out for consumers on
public policy issues like choice, access and competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is scheduled for 7 p.m. at the California State
Office Building in suburban Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   The city could require cable companies to allow consumers a
choice of Internet service -- from AOL, for instance -- as a
condition of the renewal or transfer of their franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime next year, the five-member board will recommend whether
the city should approve a transfer of the cable franchise for the
East Valley and other parts of the city from TCI to a new entity to
be formed when the cable company completes a $48.3 billion merger
with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Cable company officials said it won't be worth their money to
build the high-speed networks if they have to allow competitors to
use them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are forced to open up our network, we would have little
incentive to make the $1.8 billion investment to upgrade our
network. That could have a chilling effect on us going forward and
offering the technology,'' said Andrew Johnson, a spokesman for TCI
and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The high-speed connection would come packaged with TCI's
Internet service (At)Home, Johnson said. A customer who wants to
continue using America Online or another Internet account instead
of (At)Home would have to pay for both services.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said that arrangement amounts to a cable-company
monopoly over Internet access. Online service providers predict
they will lose business and jobs, setting Los Angeles further back
in the technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a significant concern that the cable companies will
try to get a monopoly . . . and every (service provider) will lose
business,'' said Lee Thoburn, vice president of business affairs
for Earthlink.
</P>
<P>
   TCI serves about 95,000 households in the San Fernando Valley
and 26,000 in neighboring Ventura County. The company is in roughly
400,000 Southern California homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, which plans to launch a high-speed access system
called Roadrunner in mid-1999, serves about 120,000 customers in
the West Valley and surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
