<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWL TRIP TO DYE FOR GIVES FRAN A SUNNY DISPOSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most compelling Christmas ``present'' of the year for TCU
football is bearing down upon us, and it doesn't come in a bright
red sleigh or accompanied by the tinkle of silver bells.
</P>
<P>
   It rides, instead, on a hairdresser's whim.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not the Sun Bowl. That's New Year's Eve. We'll get to
that by and by.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking really big here. We're talking about putting your
'do where your mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about the blond bombshell that's ready to explode
right in the middle of Frog Alley.
</P>
<P>
   A warm round of applause, please, for head coach Dennis
Franchione, soon-to-be sun-bleached blond, wannabe surfer and Jan
and Dean impersonator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help me, Rhonda,'' Franchione sighed yesterday, or words to
that effect. ``I just don't want to look like an idiot on national
television.''
</P>
<P>
   I said we'd talk about the game later, Fran. For the moment, try
to concentrate on your hair and what color it may be by the weekend
or soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Bright yellow? Platinum blond? Shades of purple or green? Based
on what we've seen around the Frogs' football team these days,
anything's possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping I can just put something in and then wash it out,''
Franchione said. ``My hair's so gray, I'm not sure how it's going
to take to color being put into it. ''
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, about to find out.
</P>
<P>
   It's either that, or totally lose face with his Horned Frogs
footballers, who face off against Southern Cal in El Paso on Dec.
31.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like the safest pop-off line in the world back in
August, when a local TV station showed up to do a feature on the
fact that TCU's receivers had all dyed their hair blond.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-thinking Royce Huffman, his eyes twinkling, turned to
Franchione while the cameras were rolling, and said, ``If we win
the WAC or get in a bowl game, you'll dye your hair blond, too,
right coach?''
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't take that bet? The Frogs were coming off a 1-10
campaign in '97, and Franchione was in his first year. Bowl game?
TCU had been in a total of three in the previous four decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' Franchione said, chuckling. Why not? What were the
chances?
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Frogs' stunning 6-5 turnaround, the even more
surprising Sun Bowl invitation and tomorrow Franchione will meet
with his hairdresser to talk about going blond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait until I see what she says I should do,''
Franchione said, squirming. ``I don't think she thinks I should do
it. Maybe a wig, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. That won't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put Coach Fran on the spot,'' Huffman said. ``It's taped.
It's in the video archives. He's not getting out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   This won't be easy for a man who is fastidious about his
appearance. Franchione's shoes are always shined. His ties always
match. His trousers are always perfectly creased and pressed.
Unlike most of us, he rarely drips barbecue sauce on his shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just so out of character for him because he is so
meticulous,'' wife Kim Franchione, who is already blond, said.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione doesn't just get his hair cut, he gets it ``done.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he doesn't have a thing to wear with blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure,'' he said, ``that my wife will have some
suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's not go there.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly when a blond Franchione and his surfboard will show up
at his office adjacent to Amon Carter Stadium _ and, more
important, on the practice field in front of his Horned Frogs _ is
anybody's guess. Sometime between Christmas and New Year's Eve
would be a good bet. Maybe even the day before the game, as a
motivational ploy.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs may need it.
</P>
<P>
   TCU is already the easy punchline to the latest jokes
circulating in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, Leezard, Leezard, Leezard,'' was one headline when it
was announced that the Trojans would meet the Frogs in the Sun
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``A light workout for the Trojans,'' an LA columnist sniffed of
the matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe USC will feel the same way. Whatever, Franchione's
challenge now is to convince the Frogs that getting into a bowl
game isn't enough. Now they need to kick some California tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll have any problem with that one,''
Franchione said. ``One thing I've noticed about our players, they
relish playing the Oklahomas, the Air Forces and the USC's. I'm not
worried about selling them on the idea that they can beat USC. They
get excited about these kinds of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are not going to be a lot of high expectations
placed upon us, except by ourselves, but we're going out there to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're Cinderella. Now we have to find out if the glass slipper
really fits.''
</P>
<P>
   Cinderella? Another blond, right?
</P>
<P>
   For the record, I'm picking TCU.
</P>
<P>
   By a very thin, but fashionably blond, hair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
