r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     12-17 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL GREED, BUT RANGERS SHOULD WAIT, TRIM BAIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many media precincts from here to Canada are breathlessly
reporting that Roger Clemens is consumed with greed.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I understand. But what's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is hereby convicted as charged, plus he's a repeat
offender of first degree greed. But why then don't we also indict
the sky for being blue, lions for being hungry, the ocean for being
wet and Ricky Williams for being a nice kid.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is a baseball player. A premier baseball player. Follow
the dotted lines. Baseball player ... greed. Baseball owner ...
greed.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hicks is hailed locally as the ``owner of all owners.'' He
wants to win, baseball or hockey. He will pay whatever is
necessary, baseball or hockey. Hicks has studied the Clemens'
financial ransom. He said he's a go on it. Greed understands greed.
Greed is good in baseball. It's a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the Rangers should continue their current course of
action on Clemens _ pursue this trade like crazy. If anything, Doug
Melvin has gone too crazy. What, Doug, was Rick Helling doing in
that Clemens care package offered to Toronto? No, no, no. Not
Helling. Not even close. Eventually, this deal won't take that
much.
</P>
<P>
   If Clemens is pitching in Arlington next season, he will
instantly become the most popular and productive jock in our
domain. Bigger than any Cowboy, bigger also than the cowboy known
as Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens will be a clubhouse leader, popular with teammates of
all persuasions. As a fierce competitor, none in the worldwide jock
kingdom surpass him. Clemens is the best pitcher in baseball, and
with him, the Rangers instantly improve about 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But he also wants his money. He's a greedy sonuvabuck, who
cannot be truthful about his intentions. Clemens keeps trotting out
that tired line about ``wanting a ring and wanting to be close to
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens would pitch in Ethiopia if the money was stacked high
enough. That's why he's in Toronto in the first place. Clemens was
constantly talking two years ago about the importance of his Texas
roots, and then the Blue Jays came along and offered to make him
the highest paid pitcher in baseball (at the time). Clemens
followed his hip pocket and went straight to Toronto, which on my
map is somewhere north of Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   That contract of $8 million a season is now a huge market-value
bargain. But the Blue Jays were naive enough to offer escape
clauses for Clemens. The smell of free-agent money in the past few
weeks _ Randy Johnson signing for $13 million a season followed by
Kevin Brown for $15 million _ induced Clemens to say bye-bye to
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Were you expecting loyalty? Then don't offer escape clauses to
any baseball player. Greed wins again. Sorry, Toronto, but that's
the way we are in America.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays have a massive headache with Clemens. It's the
strangest case ever in the strange financial world of baseball.
Clemens has two years remaining on an existing contract, but he's
also the same as a free agent. Again, blame Toronto for the
contract structure.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way the Blue Jays can bring Clemens back for the '99
season _ the populace up north is very angry with him, and so are
assorted teammates. More than anything else, the Blue Jays also
have financial problems in ownership. They are cutting payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto wants a package of established, low-priced players in a
trade. The team that gives up that would also have to pay
free-agent money to Clemens. One or the other, yes. But both? No
way.
</P>
<P>
   One other hammer held by Clemens is the right to veto any trade
made by the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have agreed with Clemens on the new dollars, and
also hold a geographical advantage (notice that the dollars are
listed first).
</P>
<P>
   This week, Mr. Melvin, the hard-working GM, left the baseball
winter meetings in Nashville, Tenn., frustrated after trying for
four days to make the Clemens deal. But to be back in Arlington
empty-handed is actually a break for Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   He had already offered too much _ meaning Helling in a trade
package. Toronto was dumb enough to say no. The only other top
Ranger who fits what Toronto wants is Rusty Greer. But don't give
up him, either. Not now.
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, all that debate two weeks ago on Pudge Rodriguez
for Clemens? Strictly media fabrication, both here and in Toronto.
The Blue Jays never asked for Pudge and the Rangers never offered.
Pudge makes too much money for Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Just be cool, Doug. Wait this one out. The heat is on in
Toronto. The closer it gets to spring training, the more antsy the
Blue Jays become.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is better than Johnson, better than Brown. And he knows
he has every occupational right to be greedy. The Rangers have
every reason to be smart. If they land Clemens, great. If they
don't, then at least the big effort was made and, once again, Hicks
didn't let money stand in the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
