<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CELEB-PROTEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBS, POLITICOS STAGE RALLY AGAINST CLINTON IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hoping to stoke public anger over the possible
impeachment of President Clinton, a mix of Hollywood celebrities
and political figures told a rally of about 1,000 people that
Congress is defying the will of the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about my friend, President Clinton,'' said movie
megastar Jack Nicholson, wearing his trademark sunglasses. ``It's
about the presidency . . . I don't think any of us want to cripple
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties could stop this tomorrow. I'm just here to say
Merry Christmas and I hope they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally began around noon at the Federal Building on Wilshire
Boulevard -- before Wednesday's bombing of Iraq became public, so
no speakers alluded to the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebrities who spoke included Barbra Streisand, husband
and wife Ted Danson and Mary Steenburgen and Andrew Shue of the TV
show ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   Also addressing the audience were the president's brother, Roger
Clinton; former Republican Rep. Alphonso Bell; state Sen. Tom
Hayden, D-Los Angeles; Los Angeles County Supervisor Yvonne
Brathwaite Burke; county Federation of Labor chief Miguel
Contreras; and Maulana Karenga, a professor at California State
University, Long Beach, who created the Kwanzaa holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Streisand lambasted Congress members favoring impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't they know they have a sacred constitutional duty to heed
the will of the people?'' she asked. ``No matter how many times
they have been told, the Republicans still won't listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Steenburgen warned Republicans that in the next election, voters
won't forget how they voted on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flame you're all excited about right now will not consume
Bill Clinton,'' she said. ``You will not burn him at the stake and
use the American Constitution as kindling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a political process!'' said Shue, yelling into the
microphone. ``A political process means it comes from the will of
the people. The people say no!''
</P>
<P>
   ``No! No! No!'' the crowd chanted in response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues are not what the Jerry Springers of Congress and
janitors of history are looking for,'' Karenga said. ``It's all
about the right wing's attempt to seize power to reverse hard-won
gains.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally was organized by TV producer Norman Lear's People for
the American Way and the Rev. Jesse Jackson's Rainbow Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
