<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TEXAS-MUONEKE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS' FORWARD TRYING TO LEARN COURT ETIQUETTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Speculation was that the association of Rick
Barnes and Gabe Muoneke would spark a confrontation similar to a
blue norther coming face-to-face with a warm front sweeping in off
the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the Type A personalities _ the new Texas men's
basketball coach and the Longhorns' angry young man _ has, however,
produced a coexistence not unlike the kindred relationship of
thunder and lightning.
</P>
<P>
   What both describe as a good relationship apparently withstood
Barnes' private and public dressing-down of Muoneke after he
punched a Wisconsin player in the gut during Tuesday night's game
at the Erwin Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabe responded like he's always responded,'' Barnes said
yesterday. ``He responds to definite direction. He knows I'm not
messing around with it, either. He needs to know who's in charge.
And he knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he was disappointed by the apparently unprovoked
action because the two have repeatedly talked about redirecting
Muoneke's aggressive court nature, and he believed Muoneke was
making an effort. But Barnes reiterated that he'll suspend Muoneke
if a similar incident occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabe knows what the consequences will be if it happens
again,'' Barnes said. ``But like I said, it won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes apologized to the Wisconsin players and said he'll likely
order Muoneke to write a letter expressing similar sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, perhaps, Muoneke appeared contrite in the
aftermath _ not sullen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wrong,'' he said. ``I lose my cool, lose my head
sometimes. I have no excuses about it. It's not going to happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Muoneke is one of his new coach's most enthusiastic
champions, which is a change from last spring, when he threatened
to transfer after Barnes drew his disciplinary line in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He challenges you, makes you challenge yourself,'' Muoneke
said. ``It's funny. He makes you feel like you're the best person
out there, but he keeps it in a team concept. It's a phenomenal
thing, and I'm glad to be in a position to be here with him. He
knows where I'm coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7 junior forward is averaging a team-leading 16.7
points and six rebounds _ a noticeable improvement over the
cumulative averages of 8.2 points and 4.8 rebounds of two seasons
under former coach Tom Penders.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke said he welcomes Barnes' structured, multiple-option
offense as much as he does his line-in-the-dirt philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing coach Barnes understood was that I was
frustrated,'' Muoneke said. ``Where I come from, if you work hard,
you succeed. To this day, I believe that. Maybe the success won't
come until later on, but it will pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was doing a lot of good things, and I wasn't getting
any of the benefits. I'd post up and never get the ball. That might
sound self-centered, but if someone on my team is the worst player
I've ever seen, if he's working his butt off _ I'm going to give
him the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said that Muoneke is perhaps his hardest-working player.
And if he maintains that ethic and can learn to challenge his
aggressive nature, Barnes believes he has a tremendous upside.
</P>
<P>
   Others who know Muoneke say his on-court personality belies a
sensitive, caring nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gabe is one of the most misunderstood players on the
team,'' center Chris Mihm said. ``A lot of people think Gabe is out
of control, crazy out there \Ron the court\S. But his emotion is
what makes him a good player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an aggressive player. But he's totally different off the
court. He's one of my good friends. We talk about things a lot.
There is a gentle side to him, the good guy who is fun to hang out
with.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents Nik and Njideka, who are natives of Nigeria, have
steeped Muoneke in the culture of his homeland. His full name
translated from Nigerian is Nnadubem (God guide me) Gabriel Muoneke
(spirit that creates). His major is geosystems engineering and
hydrology. He hopes one day to return to Nigeria, where he spent
two months of the summer of 1997, to help better manage the
country's oil industry for the betterment of all the population and
not just the privileged.
</P>
<P>
   He also is deeply concerned about his personal relationships.
His family lived in inner-city Houston from the time he was 5 until
he reached middle-school age, when his father became professor of
mathematics at Prairie View A&AMP;M. Muoneke graduated from Cypress
Falls High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger, I was picked on so much _ more by blacks
than whites _ because of my name and the deep accent I had,''
Muoneke said. ``When we moved to the suburbs away from the crime, I
had the mentality of inner-city Houston. So, now, instead of being
made fun of because of what or who I was, I was made fun of because
people thought I was angry. I wasn't even close to being considered
angry in inner-city Houston, but when we moved, I was considered
nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I went through what I did. Because I don't want to
make anybody else feel the way people made me feel. Off the court,
I'm very sensitive about those things. But on the court, I could
care less what the world thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said the latter attitude has to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabe has felt the officials were looking for him, and based on
his past, they should be looking for him,'' Barnes said. ``It took
him two years to get that reputation, and it might take him a
lifetime to change it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what? He's going to have to go above and beyond.
Sooner or later, he's got to stop being his own worst enemy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
