<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA LOCKOUT TALKS AS STAGNANT AS EVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hollywood is still pondering who plays the title
role _ David Stern or Billy Hunter _ but the NBA is ready to
produce its own version of ``The Grinch Who Stole Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Day games had long ago been canceled, and now the NBA
is stealing the holiday season's most cherished value:
</P>
<P>
   Hope.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have no plans to meet before Dec. 25 and might not
renew negotiations in the 169-day labor dispute until closer to New
Year's Day, placing the league dangerously close to canceling the
1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Talks broke off Saturday after less than an hour, and NBA
Commissioner Stern is leaving New York on Friday to take a week's
vacation in Aspen, Colo. Though Stern will be on-call at all times,
negotiations are off for at least the next 10 days, said Hunter,
director of the players' union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be resolved before Christmas,
no,'' Hunter said Wednesday. ``If we're going to meet, in all
probability it will be the week between Christmas and New Year's.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the league must start play by Feb. 1 to accommodate a
50-game schedule, that leaves precious little time for a
settlement. Four weeks are needed to complete a settlement, have
teams sign free agents, make trades and hold training camps.
</P>
<P>
   That means a deal needs to be struck the first week of January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we're going to find ourselves locked into the
12th-hour scenario,'' Hunter said. ``I think at this stage it's
almost like poker, and I think what they're trying to do is see who
blinks first.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter remains confident the NBA is not ready to kill the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me how critical or extreme things are, they can't
be too extreme ... (considering) Commissioner Stern is planning to
vacation next week in Aspen, Colo. If that's the case, then I would
assume that Jan. 1 is not a drop-dead date.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern has consistently refused to give a drop-dead date, saying
the season will simply expire on its own at some point.
</P>
<P>
   NBA officials are downplaying the commissioner's vacation as a
factor, saying he can be back in New York in four hours if needed
for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect that to happen. Hunter and Stern not only
aren't talking, they're posturing over who will call whom to resume
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said he has been the one to call Stern on several
occasions and wants the commissioner to make the first move. Stern
insists it was he who called to set up the most recent talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to Mr. Hunter's assertions, last week's meetings were
convened at my initiative alone,'' Stern said. ``The meetings that
followed on Thursday and Saturday were thus the result of my
initiative and were without precondition.''
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred and eight games have been lost during the lockout
as NBA players and owners bicker about how to divide $2 billion in
revenue. There are signs they are inching toward settlement,
though.
</P>
<P>
   During Saturday's session, the players offered for the first
time to cap some high-end salaries. Under the proposal, players who
have been in the league for six years or less would be capped at
$10 million per year. Players with seven years experience or more
could still make any amount, but teams would be subjected to luxury
taxes as follows: 75 percent tax on salaries over $15 million, 100
percent tax on salaries between $15-$18 million, 150 percent tax on
salaries between $18-21 million and 200 percent tax on salaries
over $21 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 0105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
