<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4239 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     12-17 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE image is still there: the floodlit stadium, fullback Alan
Ameche smashing through from the one-yard line, the clock that
stopped forever at 8:15 of the first overtime period in pro
football history as the Baltimore Colts beat the New York Giants
23-17.
</P>
<P>
   Four Hall of Famers who played 40 years ago in what has been
called ``The Greatest Game Ever Played'' agree on one thing: It
wasn't the greatest game of any of their careers or even of that
month.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Unitas and Artie Donovan of the Colts went two-on-two
with Frank Gifford and Sam Huff of the Giants this week in a
conference call arranged by the National Football League. They
talked across the decades, but what they said was hardly
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt that it wasn't a real good football game
until the last two minutes,'' offered Unitas, ``and then the
overtime. We played pretty well, but we should have blown New York
out of the stadium, and we didn't. Then we had to come from behind
in order to tie and then go on to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always forget that a couple weeks before, in the game
that clinched the division and put us in the playoff, San Francisco
had us down 20-7 at the half, and we came back to beat 'em (35-27).
That was a much better game. Our defense shut out Y.A. Tittle in
the second half, and that was quite an accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   From the other sideline, Gifford expressed the same sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the phone with Wellington Mara (the former owner of
the Giants), and he was like me, wondering what all the fuss was
about,'' Gifford said. ``We played a better game a week earlier
when we shut down Jim Brown and Cleveland 10-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Huff and Donovan made the vote unanimous. So, OK, what is the
big deal, then, about the game they shared three days after
Christmas in 1958?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first sudden-death game,'' said Unitas, ``and it
came in a championship game, and that was enough to make people
feel they had seen something fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened on national television,'' said Huff, the ferocious
middle linebacker, ``and up to then there hadn't been much pro
football on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question,'' said Gifford, ``that the game had a
huge impact. We played the championship game in New York in 1956,
and it wasn't even a sellout. You look at all the players from this
one who went into the Hall of Fame, and I think there had never
been that much talent on the field at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Also noteworthy is the fact the game was played virtually on the
doorstep of Madison Avenue. And even though the Giants lost, it all
came together for the greater glory of pro football.
</P>
<P>
   And while these legends may downplay the heroics, they seem to
remember every play, every close call, every misstep. Forty years
later, Gifford opened the conversation by apologizing for fumbling
twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that I cost us the game,'' said the halfback who was
one of the sport's first golden boys. ``I gave it up once as we
were going in for a score, and the other set up a Baltimore
touchdown. Is that how you remember it, John?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell the truth,'' said Unitas, his voice deep and dry,
``about all I remember is that we scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford also figured in the game's most controversial play. The
Giants were leading 17-14 with less than two minutes left in
regulation when he carried on third-and-four from his own 40. The
Giants insisted he made the first down, but Baltimore's Gino
Marchetti suffered a broken leg on the play, and in the confusion,
the referee gave New York a dreadful spot, short of the first down
by a yard. If the placement had been different, the outcome might
not have been one for the history books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have run out the clock,'' said Gifford, ``and the
game would not have gone into overtime, and we wouldn't be having
this conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Marchetti and I made the tackle on that play,'' chimed in
Donovan, the beefy tackle, ``and Gino broke his leg when our guy,
Big Daddy Lipscomb, fell on him. Lipscomb used to hurt four or five
of his own teammates every game by piling on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Gifford was on the ground, screaming, `I made the
first down! I made the first down!' I said, `Aw, shut up and go
back in the huddle. What are you hollering about? You didn't make
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the most tortured memory for Gifford came after Don
Chandler's punt gave the Colts the ball at their 14-yard line. Now,
Unitas went to work, hitting three passes to Raymond Berry for 62
yards. With time running out, in came Steve Myrha to kick a short
field goal and tie the score at 17.
</P>
<P>
   The players milled around at midfield, many of them unaware that
the league had agreed to go to overtime if the game ended in a
deadlock. The weary captains trudged out for the coin toss. The
Giants won the flip, went three plays and out and had to punt,
putting the ball back in the hands of a quarterback who was on the
brink of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants went to school that day at Johnny U.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction to the game was anger,'' said Huff. ``I was a
competitive player, and I needed the cash. The difference between
winning and losing was about two grand. I was angry at the way John
was able to throw the ball to Raymond Berry. He knew where to
attack the defense, he found our weakness, and he knew how to
exploit it. You look at the play-by-play, and it was Unitas to
Berry, Unitas to Berry. After 40 years, that still rings in my ear.
We couldn't stop it, and that was the difference in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts' last drive covered 80 yards in 13 plays. Unitas hit
Berry for 21 yards and sent Ameche up the middle for 23 more, then
lofted a sideline pass to Jim Mutscheller to the New York one.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Colts had first-and-goal at the three,
leading 14-3 with a chance to bury the Giants. But Ameche, known as
The Horse since his college days at Wisconsin, was stopped on a
sweep from a yard away. This time he made it, ending the first
fifth quarter ever played 23-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Sam,'' asked Donovan, ``I gotta ask you a question. Did
you think your defense was better than ours?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, yes,'' snapped Huff. ``If you had to play against
Unitas, you'd have gotten beat, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We played against him in practice,'' retorted Donovan, ``and
beat him all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gifford makes that first down,'' Huff said, getting in the
last word, ``no one would have ever heard of the '58 Colts.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end, the standing-room crowd of more than 64,000 was as
spent as the players. Marchetti ordered the stretcher bearers to
put him down in the end zone so he could watch the Colts race the
clock to the tying points. He was alone in the locker room when
Ameche scored, but the silence of the New York fans told him his
team was moving.
</P>
<P>
   Unitas knew he had arrived when he returned to New York two
weeks later and went out to dinner with his wife to one of the
city's posh nightspots, the Harwyn Club. The headwaiter recognized
him _ the hot new celebrity in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right this way, Mr. Unitas,'' he sang out, leading the couple
to a corner table, the most prominent in the place. It was at that
very table, the headwaiter confided proudly, that Eddie Fisher and
Liz Taylor had their rendezvous the night before Eddie flew home to
tell Debbie Reynolds he wanted a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Hall of Famers from that 1958 championship game will be
honored by the NFL during the pre-game coin toss at Super Bowl
XXXIII. They include Berry, Donovan, Marchetti, Jim Parker and
Lenny Moore for the Colts and Gifford, Huff, Roosevelt Brown, Don
Maynard and Tom Landry for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   It may or may not have been the game of Gifford's life, but a
question still haunts him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landry was our defensive coach, a genius even then,'' Gifford
said. ``I keep wondering why he didn't make an adjustment when
Unitas was hitting all those passes late in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   They were young in 1958, but the game still makes them crazy
after all these years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
