<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROSCLEMENS-HNS     12-17 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROSCLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. is still continuing his pursuit of
Roger Clemens. Only he doesn't intend to break the bank in the
process.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Wednesday, McLane said the Astros have no interest in
exceeding for Clemens the three-year, $33 million offer they made
to keep free-agent pitcher Randy Johnson. Johnson, who spent the
final two months of the 1998 season in Houston, signed a more
lucrative contract (four years, $52.4 million) with the Arizona
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ought to be a pretty close level right there,'' McLane
said. ``That was a far reach for us at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, the Astros and Clemens' agents, Alan and
Randy Hendricks, aren't even in the same ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the Hendricks brothers sent to McLane a
proposal for a restructured contract worth $43.5 million over three
years, with a $15 million option year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't surprise me if he stays in Toronto,'' said McLane,
who re-entered the sweepstakes to land baseball's only five-time Cy
Young Award winner just hours after Astros general manager Gerry
Hunsicker called a news conference Sunday to announce the club was
dropping out of the race. But if McLane won't top what he offered
Johnson, his undisclosed counteroffer would have to be considerably
less than the Hendrickses' first proposal.
</P>
<P>
   McLane, who put the odds of Clemens' wearing an Astros uniform
next season at ``30 to 40 percent'' at best, had a phone
conversation with Randy Hendricks on Wednesday, with both sides
agreeing any further talks would likely not be held until the
beginning of next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten so complicated,'' McLane said. ``Most deals happen
fairly quickly and decisively. This hasn't been quick or decisive.
It's just wandered.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Toronto general manager Gord Ash shot down rumors
regarding an addendum to Clemens' contract that would make him a
free agent if he is not dealt within 90 days of a trade request.
Clemens demanded a trade from the Blue Jays on Dec. 2, which would
give the Blue Jays until March 2 _ coincidentally the beginning of
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the contract speaks of free agency,'' Ash said.
``We have an agreement. Roger Clemens is under contract with us for
1999 and 2000. The last two years of the contract will be honored
unless he walks away into retirement, which isn't going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of his signing with Toronto in 1996, Clemens and
former Blue Jays president Paul Beeston, now president of Major
League Baseball, reached a handshake agreement that gave Clemens
the option to demand a trade if he felt the club wasn't committed
to building a contender. And because Clemens would be dealt in the
midst of a multiyear contract _ he is to receive $16.1 million over
the final two years of his existing agreement _ he would, under
baseball's Basic Agreement, have the right to demand another trade
following the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   When told of the addendum report circulating in Canada, McLane
said neither he nor any of his baseball people had any knowledge of
Clemens' so-called ability to become a free agent if not traded by
March. If the side agreement is not filed with Major League
Baseball, it could be a violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly haven't read the contract, but I doubt seriously
any contract is that way,'' McLane said. ``To my knowledge, it's an
airtight, four-year contract with two years to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who had not spoken publicly since demanding a trade,
broke his silence Wednesday while playing in a golf tournament in
California, saying he was bothered by the Astros' brief withdrawal
from negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little upset about some of the comments they made
toward my agents, because I thought that was uncalled for,''
Clemens told Fox Sports News. ``I think they might be back in
there; I'm not really sure. It's hard to say at this point, and I'm
so distant from it right now. I basically know what handful or so
teams are involved in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money part of it will work itself out. Even more so, I'm
looking to obviously try and get closer to home. If not, to a
contender where I know I can chase 300 wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets said Wednesday they were pulling out of the
Clemens derby, leaving the Astros, Yankees, Rangers and Indians as
the chief suitors. And if a suitable deal can't be worked out, what
are the chances of Clemens' returning to the Blue Jays next year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Gord (Ash) the other day there is a remote possibility
Roger could return to Toronto,'' Randy Hendricks told the Toronto
Sun. ``Roger's question to me is, Why consider going back when some
people are trying to tar and feather him? They should decide what
they want. All he did when he was there was win two straight Cy
Young Awards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
