<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4251 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FOOTBALL-COLUMN-L     12-17 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FOOTBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW THAT THEY'RE IN, FLORIDA ST. WILL WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There might be something slightly out of whack
with the ease No. 2-ranked Florida State slid into the role of
favorite against undefeated and top-ranked Tennessee in the Fiesta
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But as usual, the oddsmakers usually know something we don't.
Actually, in this case, they know something we know too.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles are so strong on defense, they could go to Tempe,
Ariz., with Bobby Bowden at quarterback and manhandle the
Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   It's got the makings of a mismatch, and clearly shows what a
shame it would have been if Florida State had not gained admission
to the first BCS national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is a fine team, worthy of many accolades. But the Vols
haven't seen anything approaching what will hit them Jan. 4. Their
offensive line is going to find out what an NFL defense feels like,
and won't feel afterward like they've grown from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles' defense has allowed two touchdowns just once all
season, and that was when quarterback Chris Weinke threw six
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's defense, which plays at a different speed than
everyone else, ends all debates about this game. But there are
other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols had their hands full with Mississippi State, and had to
squeak past quality teams like Syracuse and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did we mention that Florida State's Peter Warrick is the
best wide receiver in the country?
</P>
<P>
   The X-factor is Bowden, who makes his third appearance in a
championship game in six years.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Bowden a special coach? Just look at how he's
developed the quarterbacks. After Dan Kendra was injured for the
umpteenth time, he simply moved Weinke into the starting spot.
After a rough start, Weinke completed more than 200 passes without
an interception until suffering a season-ending neck injury.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the coming Outzen party, the debut of previously
buried quarterback Marcus Outzen, nicknamed The Rooster because of
his red hair.
</P>
<P>
   Outzen, the third-string quarterback, has been effective if
unspectacular to close out the season. He threw no interceptions
against Florida, passed for 167 yards and ran for 61 more.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't hurt Florida State with mistakes, and plays just well
enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with Notre Dame, which looked like a high school
offense once Jarious Jackson got injured, and backups Arnaz Battle
and Eric Chappell looked as if they had never thrown a forward
pass.
</P>
<P>
   And here's another reason Tennessee will lose, a reason everyone
else is too scared to mention. With offensive coordinator David
Cutliffe gone for Mississippi, it looked like Punky Brewster
replaced him calling plays in the SEC championship game every time
ABC's cameras showed the pressbox.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting news: Expect Hart High wide receiver Jerry Owens to
end up at UCLA, although Oregon and USC are still among schools
under consideration. UCLA should also land offensive lineman Lenny
Vandermade of Mater Dei....
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Brad Pyatt of Arvada, Colo., is leaning toward USC
although he will visit Colorado this weekend. The Trojans are also
ahead in the battle to get Esperanza offensive lineman Nate
Steinbacher, who visited Nebraska last week. Corona offensive
lineman Shane Lehmann will choose between UCLA and USC.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Trojans picked up a gem in wide receiver Kareem
Kelly of Long Beach Poly, he still has to achieve the necessary
score on his Scholastic Assessment Test....
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee will have its usual stellar recruiting year, but the
Vols may have hurt themselves for next year's recruiting class.
Tennessee rescinded a scholarship offer to lineman Leo Bell of
Moeller High in Cincinnati the day after Bell orally committed last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's teammate is Anthony Munoz, Jr., the son of former USC
lineman Anthony Munoz. Junior figures to be one of the most heavily
recruited lineman in the nation next season, and is considering the
Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   We'll get back to you: One reason established coaches are
reluctant to join John Robinson at Nevada Las Vegas is his
three-year contract. Many assistant coaches reason that Robinson
will pull his three-year hitch, collect about $1 million, then bail
out. That won't leave much of a future for the staff, which will
have to look for jobs once a new coach succeeds Robinson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
