<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-REDWINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINGS ZING BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Match a masterpiece against a work in progress and
what do you get?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Red Wings 5, Bruins 3.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and don't forget to check the scoring summary for the math.
What happened Wednesday night at Joe Louis Arena argued the case
against statistics sometimes not telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can take (Steve) Yzerman off one line and switch (Sergei)
Fedorov in his spot,'' said Bruins coach Pat Burns, succinctly
summarizing the depth of the two-time defending Stanley Cup
champions. ``That's it, one little switch like that, and there's no
drop-off in how they play.''
</P>
<P>
   Depth and speed, the ferocious 1-2 punch of the mighty Winged
Wheels, eventually sent the Bruins careening out the doors of The
House That Ilitch built. The Bruins remained alive with their bold,
unyielding checking game for about 30 minutes, but a pair of late
second-period strikes by the Wings, by Larry Murphy (power play)
and Martin Lapointe (shorthanded), built a 4-2 lead by the
40-minute mark that the Bruins couldn't negate.
</P>
<P>
   No team in the NHL can skate, shoot, and score with the Wings.
Only Dallas and Phoenix can come close, and it could be only the
latter that has a reasonable shot at upending the champs. They are
fast. They are balanced. And if they ever think about easing into
cruise control, they've got the laser eyes of coach Scott Bowman
aimed like crosshairs at the backs of their helmets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One line with Fedorov,'' said Burns, ``and then another line
with Yzerman. All you can do is roll your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, losers of two in a row for the first time in six
weeks, never could get the lead. With 8:49 gone in the first,
Nicklas Lidstrom cheated in 10 feet from the blue line on the power
play and blasted a slapper past Byron Dafoe, giving Detroit the
advantage. With 4:25 to go in the period, Jason Allison connected
for his eighth goal of the year to tie it. The only assist went to
_ guess who _ Sergei Samsonov, who helped create the scoring play
with his pass out front from behind the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings pulled away in the second, scoring three times _ at
even strength (Mathieu Dandenault), on the power play, and
shorthanded. The latter two strikes crushed the Bruins. They
countered Dandenault's goal with Dmitri Khristich's team-high 13th
of the year but then watched Murphy and Lapointe score within 67
seconds to lock up the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the Stanley Cup champs, twice, and you do that by
having a whole team,'' said Bruins forward Steve Heinze. ``The only
other way you do it is by having Mario Lemieux when he was playing.
Teams with four lines like that, they fill gaps and holes. Even
what you'd call their fourth line with (Kris) Draper, that line's a
threat. It's a heck of a team.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the trademark Boston checking effort kept it
manageable, even winnable, until the Murphy and Lapointe daggers.
Murphy was left alone at the inner edge of the right circle to lift
a high forehander over a fallen Dafoe. Lapointe blitzed to the left
post in a man-short situation (Yzerman in the box) and one-touched
a bullet feed off the right wing boards by Draper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frustrating part,'' said Heinze, ``is that you do it for
30 minutes but not for 60. That just shows it's a mental lapse on
our part. We're in good enough shape to do it for 60, but we let
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wings stopped attacking in the third period and nearly got
burned. Shawn Bates made it a one-goal game with 1:31 to play,
scoring on a rush with a Khristich relay. The Bruins pulled Dafoe
with 40 seconds to go, got some pressure with the extra skater, but
watched Darren McCarty send in a long backhander for the 5-3 final.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the champions because they have a lot of depth,'' said
Allison. ``That's why, when you're up against them, every line has
to do the job every shift. No one can take a shift off. You look
up, they've got a 4-2 lead, and there's Yzerman in our corner,
fighting off two guys for the puck, and almost coming up with it.
Tells you what kind of team they are. But still, we can compete
with 'em. No excuses. We can beat 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe one day, when the work shows more progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
