<SLUG> BC-FBO-TEXAS-HIGH-SCHOOL-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHENVILLE QUARTERBACK TAKES AIM AT RECORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEPHENVILLE, Texas _ The Texas high school passing records are
replete with familiar names such as Detmer, Kubiak, Watson, Morenz,
Clements and a kid named Hutka from the small town of Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville quarterback Kelan Luker is among them now. By
Saturday night, they could be in his rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to leading the Yellow Jackets to the Class 4A
Division II championship, Luker can set state single-season and
career passing records when Stephenville (14-1) meets La Marque
(13-0) at 4 p.m. on Saturday at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Luker has 4,411 yards this season and needs 106 to break the
mark of 4,516 by Rogers' Patrick Hutka in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   With 8,008 in his high school career, Luker needs 214 yards to
surpass Huntsville's Steve Clements (8,204 from 1986-89) and
Mission's Koy Detmer (8,221 from 1989-91) on Texas' all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an accomplishment to be up there with those guys,'' Luker
said. ``But I don't think it'll mean that much unless I get a ring
on my finger. Your stats don't matter unless you're a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Gary Kubiak (Houston St. Pius X), Jeff Watson (A&AMP;M
Consolidated) and Shea Morenz (San Angelo Central) before him,
Luker's future beyond high school is beckoning. Baylor, SMU,
Colorado, Texas Tech or Kansas could sign the 6-foot-2, 210-pound
Luker, known for his release and deep-route strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only has Kelan arrived,'' Stephenville coach Art Briles
said, ``but I think we've arrived as a team. We've expanded and
developed and are still trying to improve daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all equates into the astronomical numbers we've put up on
that side of the ball. To do that, your defense has to give you
that chance, which I think has been overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   And to think, Luker was almost a ``Six-man football''
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Stephenville Middle School coach Alan Luker, led
Panther Creek to Six-man state championships in 1992 and '93. Kelan
was in the eighth grade, while older brother Seth, a 255-pound
junior lineman, had grown too large for the Six-man game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly a good move on our part,'' Alan Luker said.
``It gave both boys an opportunity to play big-time football.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving to 11-man football seemed logical, Alan said, given
Seth's size and Kelan's arm, which at 13 was stronger than most
Six-man high school quarterbacks Alan had ever coached.
</P>
<P>
   The Lukers considered moving to Brownwood, but were later sold
on Stephenville's wide-open offense. Just how wide open it would
become under Kelan, no one really knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelan's just been at a place that passes a whole lot, and he
fits right into this program,'' Alan said. ``From the time he was
7, Kelan could throw baseballs, footballs and basketballs. It
didn't surprise me he could throw a football better than the other
two. He's just blessed with a good arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville already has two state records this season. Luker's
top target, Cody Cardwell, has set marks for receiving yards for a
season (2,336) and career (4,257).
</P>
<P>
   Also, Stephenville's offense needs 169 yards to break the 1953
Sugar Land team's all-time national record of 8,375 total yards in
a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first game, it seemed so easy to get over 500
yards,'' Luker said of an offense that has averaged 547.1 yards in
15 games. ``We figured we could do it every game if we put our
minds to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Or in Luker's case, his arm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
