<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PRO-BOWL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS PUT FIVE IN PRO BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When Leon Lett learned he was] one of the five
Cowboys players selected] to this season's NFC Pro Bowl team
yesterday, he was wrapped up in a bearhug by tackle Erik Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And Nate Newton, arguably the most surprising pick, expressed
appreciation about being recognized for a sixth time _ one year
after having what he called the worst season of his career.
</P>
<P>
   But the honorees, which also included Deion Sanders, who was
named as a starter at cornerback and kick returner, starting tackle
Larry Allen and reserve safety Darren Woodson, were more solemn
than celebratory. Pro Bowl play hasn't been exactly omnipresent
during the team's current three-game losing streak that has made
Sunday's matchup with the Philadelphia Eagles crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual goals are not as good when the team is not
winning,'' Newton said. ``Late in my career, I want to win as many
games as I can and get back to the Super Bowl. Now things look dim.
We've got to win one to get in the playoffs and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' five selections tied Atlanta and Green Bay for
second-most in the NFC behind Minnesota's nine. Additionally,
Allen, who made the Pro Bowl as a guard the past three seasons, is
just the third offensive lineman in NFL history to be selected at
two different positions.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is the first Cowboys player ]to be selected as a kick
returner. And Newton, who made five consecutive Pro Bowls from
1992-1996, ties Rayfield Wright (1971-76) and John Niland
(1968-1973) for most Pro Bowl selections by a Cowboys offensive
lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to be recognized by your peers,'' said Newton,
who battled weight and injury problems last season and wasn't
guaranteed a job this season until he made a commitment to
off-season conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was my worst in the NFL. I never thought I could see
myself play to that level. When I saw that, I said if they would
have me back, I would give a better effort all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Newton dropped more than 70 pounds in the off-season and credits
Cowboys trainer Joe Juraszek for helping him. ]However, Newton said
none of ]it means anything unless the Cowboys ]make a run for ]the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who was selected for the seventh time in his career
(his third with the Cowboys), has been honored as a kick returner
for the second time. He made the Pro Bowl as a cornerback and kick
returner while with Atlanta in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said the award still is special because ``it's a way of
knowing that you did your job and you did it well.''
</P>
<P>
   However, when asked if he would actually play in the Pro Bowl
this year _ Sanders did not participate after being selected in
1996 and 1997 _ he was noncommittal.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that he has missed the past three games with a
sprained big toe and is questionable for the Eagles game, Sanders
said he has other concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to play here first,'' he said. ``It's getting to the
point where it's really frustrating. And we are playing terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys need Sanders to return to the Pro Bowl level he was
playing at before injuring his toe against the Cardinals on Nov.
15. He has ]five interceptions, including one he returned ]71 yards
for a touchdown. He leads the NFL in punt returns with an average
of 15.6 yards per return and has returned two punts for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been one of my best seasons when I've been out there,''
Sanders said. ``And it's not over. I think the Lord has a few more
things for me to do on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Lett made the Pro Bowl in 1994 and was considered to be having a
Pro Bowl season in 1996 before being suspended for a year for
violating the league's substance abuse policy. In his first full
season back, Lett has recorded modest numbers. He has 44 tackles,
including four sacks, and leads the team in tackles for losses with
seven and quarterback pressures with 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised \Rto make it\S,'' Lett said. ``It feels good.
I feel like I'm playing OK. But the defense has had a setback the
past few games, and we've got to get better. That's the most
important thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
