r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-L     12-17 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS ROLL TO 6-1 WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There have been two constants since the Mighty
Ducks joined the NHL in 1993. Guy Hebert has provided the team with
consistantly solid goaltending, while the power play has been
consistantly bad.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has changed in net. Hebert is playing better than ever.
Wednesday he extended his shutout streak to 191 minutes, 47 seconds
before giving up a meaningless goal late in the third period of the
Ducks' 6-1 victory over Nashville before 14,222 at the Pond on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But this year there is finally some power in the Anaheim power
play.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks tied a club record with four power play goals against
the Predators _ two by Travis Green and one each by Teemu Selanne
and Steve Rucchin _ as they continue to surge up the league's power
play rankings and the Western Conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks (12-11-6) have won three consecutive games, are 4-0-1
in their last five and moved ahead of Edmonton and Colorado into
fourth place in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was as good as it (the power play) has been all year,
but it can get better, said demanding Anaheim coach Craig
Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to seasons gone by the Anaheim power play unit is
flying high.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Ducks ranked 24th, converting only 11.7 percent of
their opportunities. Anaheim came into the game ranked ninth in the
league (17.9 percent) and they have now scored at least one power
play in 18 of its 20 previous games.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jamie Pushor got the Ducks started fast when he
scored an even strength goal _ his first in 38 games _ on the
Ducks' first shot of the night at 3:15 of the first period. Then
the power play took over, taking advantage of the Predators, who
rank 23rd in penalty killing.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin and Selanne combined at 6:11 of the first. Selanne had a
full head of steam going down the right wing, took Rucchin's lead
pass, cut to the middle and easily chipped a backhander over rookie
goalie Tomas Vokoun for his 10th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks added a club-record three power play goals in the
second period and Selanne added an even strength goal in final
minute. Paul Kariya assisted on all four goals, setting a team
record in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second period we knew we had them down and didn't let
up, said Hartsburg of the Ducks were 1-of-8 on the power play in a
3-1 loss in Nashville on Nov. 27. ``Our power play probably lost
that game for us, tonight it won the game for us.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks scored only four power play goals in the first nine
games this season before Hartsburg moved Kariya to the point
position. Anaheim has since scored 25 power play goals in its last
20 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started to turn when we put Paul at the point, said
Hartsburg. ``It's so important to have a quarterback at the point
and get shots through.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the second period goals were the direct result of Kariya
shots that Vokoun couldn't handle. Green scored once after Rucchin
batted the rebound his way and Rucchin scored on a rebound himself.
</P>
<P>
   Green scored the other power play goal when his shot banked in
off the skate of Nashville's J.J. Daigneault.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell Paul don't be afraid to shot, said Selanne. ``The key
is making the right decision when to shot. He doesn't shot when
somebody is in front of him. And if guys overplay him we have more
room down low and now we have guys like (Marty) McInnis and Green
who can take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in Anaheim's powerful display was another brilliant
performance by Hebert. The Anaheim goalie stopped 36 Nashville
shots before Denny Lambert scored with 4:06 left in the game and
ended his bid for a third consecutive shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been exciting for the whole team, the fans to see how
long we could keep it going, said Hebert. ``But the most important
thing was that we got a big win out of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
