 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2508 - December 17, 1998   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2508 -- Dec. 17, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. IRAQ : THE ROLLBACK FANTASY Using the Iraqi opposition to
overthrow Saddam Hussein is one of the hottest foreign policy ideas
in Washington today. The basic idea is simple : The U.S. should
refuse to accept the continued rule of Saddam Hussein and help
install the Iraqi opposition in his place. As Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott put it, ``The doctrine here has to be rollback,
not containment.'' By Daniel Byman, Kenneth Pollack and Gideon
Rose. (Byman is a policy analyst with the RND Corporation. Pollack
is senior research professor at the National Defence University.
Rose is deputy director of national security studies and Olin
Fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations.) From Foreign Affairs
magazine. 6,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
THE MYTH AND REALITY OF GEORGE SOROS Ten years ago, when they
started pulling down the statues of dead Communists, George Soros
set about creating a new identity for himself. That identitiy is
now as complete as the most highly polished sculpture, and now
stands in the middle of the capitalist equivalent of Red Square.
Soros transformed himself from the most narrowly self-interested
financial speculator into the most broadly disinterested
commentator on global finance. He has created a new role: the
Player-Commentator. His opinions carry more weight in the markets
than his money ever did. Commentary by Michael Lewis. Bloomberg
News. 1,000 words. (Michael Lewis, the author of ``Liar's Poker,''
``The Money Culture'' and ``Trail Fever'' is a columnist for
Bloomsberg News. The opinions expressed are his own and do not
represent the judgment of Bloomberg LP or Bloomberg News.) 3. IT'S
A RELIEF NOTHING BAD HAPPENED YET Clinton's trip to Israel and
Palestine came at a dramatic crossroads moment for both him and his
hosts. It is a sign of how far things are from the triumphant
celebration originally planned for the occasion that the most
reassuring thing that happened was nothing. There was real physical
danger from fanatics and political danger of another visible
breakdown blowing up the Wye accords. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
STREP THROAT MICROBE MAY ESCAPE ANTIBIOTICS BY
</P>
<P>
   HIDING IN CELLS Strep throat is the most common bacterial
infection in children. Untreated, it can lead to serious
complications. Antibiotic treatment often fails to completely
eradicate the infection, allowing patients to become carriers who
can spread the bacterium, and putting them at risk for a recurrence
of strep throat. Researchers from Israel report that some strains
of the bacterium that causes this infection carry a gene that may
allow them to escape antibiotic treatment by enabling them to slip
into the cells, where antibiotic levels are much lower. This
finding may lead to new treatments that may make it possible to
eradicate this disease. By M. McCarthy. Lancet News Service. 1,000
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
BIOLOGISTS CLOSE IN ON THE TICK-TOCK GENES In one of the
weirdest-sounding experiments in recent times, scientists reported
that they had been able to reset human biological clocks by shining
intense light on the backs of people's knees. This was, however,
only one in a burst of stunning experiments that are revealing new
insights into the ways that biological organisms keep and tell
time. By Sandra Blakeslee. From New York Times Science Times. 1,400
words. 6. TRAGEDY LIVES ON IN THE CHILDREN OF THE DISAPPEARED
During the Argentine military's ``dirty war'' of 1976 to 1983, it
is estimated that more than 30,000 people were killed or just
disappeared. The 'Grandmothers of the Plaza de Mayo' - a group of
women who lost their sons, daughters, nieces, nephews or
grandchildren during the junta - have registered more than 200
children, kidnapped and given away, often to military and police
couples. Javier Vildoza, 20, believes he may be a son of the
'desaparecidos' - the people who disappeared. The past is still
alive in the womb of the country and, in spite of the punishment
for some of the major culprits, Argentines haven't been able to
grasp its immense evil. By Tomas Eloy Martinez. 1,500 words. 7.
BLUEPRINT : THE SHOCK OF THE FAMILIAR In a frenzy to move products,
design is exploding, mutating, multiplying. The rules of
composition, colour and balance are breaking down ... from grocery
store to furniture showroom to couture salon, 1999 means design
anarchy. By Herbert Muschamp. From The New York Times Magazine.
2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
ANNUAL REVIEW OF SANTA'S HEALTH Santa Claus may be able to travel
around the world in a single night, but when it comes to his
health, he's no Superman. Here is Medical Tribune News Service's
annual review of the state of Santa's health and some good tips on
how he could adopt a healthier lifestyle. By Merritt McKinney.
1,000 words.
