A4517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-DAD-BOOK18-CO     12-17 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-DAD-BOOK18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dad's dilemma: `Jerk' may be just stretched thin _ sound
familiar?
 &HT;    By Scott Benarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Are you one of those dads who tells the
boss you're going to a late-afternoon meeting when you're really
picking up your kids from school or day care?
</P>
<P>
   Do you spend little time with your children because you worry
the company will think you're too involved as a parent and not
committed to the team?
</P>
<P>
   Many fathers have been caught in this trap for years, trying to
play the good corporate soldier and the available, understanding
Daddy _ without shortchanging either role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows working mothers have conflicts, but `working
father' is a redundancy. Guys work; that's what they do,'' says
James Levine, director of The Fatherhood Project at the Families
and Work Institute in New York. Levine is author of the recently
published ``Working Fathers: New Strategies for Balancing Work and
Family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We found guys were feeling the same as women were,'' Levine
says. ``Women don't have a monopoly on guilt; men also feel guilty
being away from home so much.''
</P>
<P>
   A hefty majority of men, 70 percent, feel at least some conflict
in balancing work and family life, Levine found in a 1997 national
study of the workforce. That's a 10 percent increase over a similar
survey he did in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between working moms and dads, Levine says, is
that men ``didn't feel they had company sanction to talk about it.
As companies developed family-friendly polices, the issue was
framed in terms of mothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it wasn't macho to discuss such things.
</P>
<P>
   But Levine _ who has studied and spoken to corporations around
the country _ says men should not be afraid to raise the issue of
family time with supervisors. More companies and institutions are
realizing, albeit slowly, that rejiggering schedules so men can
attend to their children improves their security and emotional
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finally at a point,'' Levine says, ``where we're seeing
widespread attention and concern about the role of dads, their
absence from families and what can be done by businesses and
community organizations to get dads more involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine says that women he's met generally seem delighted about
the shift in attitudes toward working fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we get concerns that to pay attention to dads is to
deflect attention from women's issues,'' he says. ``It's not
either-or. In the end, we can't support mothers unless we support
fathers as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But dads don't have to wait for their employers to adopt
policies to improve their family life. Levine gives this advice:
</P>
<P>
   _ SPEND TIME WITH YOUR SPOUSE: ``I see lots of guys so guilty
over not being with their kids they forget about the marital
relationship. Don't forget. One-on-one time with your partner, away
from your children, is important.'' A shaky marriage makes it more
difficult to support and raise the kids. Levine suggests ``dating''
at least once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Don't feel guilty about not spending that time with your child.
And don't worry about whether you can afford it; the goal is to
spend time, not money, together.
</P>
<P>
   _ SPEND ONE-ON-ONE TIME WITH EACH CHILD: Each child needs
one-on-one time with dad, even if it's just going for a walk or to
the corner store for a doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   When you arrive home from work, join the activity your child is
already involved in. Ask kids specific questions about their day.
General ``How was your day?'' questions usually get a brief ``OK''
response.
</P>
<P>
   Take your kids to work during off hours so they can see what you
do while away.
</P>
<P>
   And remember: Children need your affection, so don't be afraid
to give hugs. Both parents can and should be sources of comfort.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEP INTO YOUR CHILDREN'S WORLD: Visit their day care centers,
schools, doctors. Get to know their friends. Walk your child to the
bus stop before work.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of your children's daily life is heavily influenced
by the time they spend with teachers, coaches, physicians. Getting
to know them improves how they deal with your child when you're not
around.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let Mom be the designated reader at home or chauffeur to
school or the doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be with your child. Be a part of his universe,'' Levine says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
