<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDE-FROSTY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meltdown a possibility, but this frosty gig ain't bad
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Matt Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jeez, it's stuffy in here. Is that sweat
rolling down my shins?
</P>
<P>
   It's 11 a.m. at the public clubhouse in Boynton Beach, Fla. I'm
lumbering to the door, psyching myself up to face a raucous mob of
preschoolers. I'm wearing a big, fuzzy Frosty the Snowman suit.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm hoping to discover something new about people and
Christmas. (At least that's what I'm telling myself. I'm really
here because someone gave me little choice. More about that later.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There he is, there he is, there he is!'' a little girl shrieks
as I enter a room crammed with excited tots. I'm stumped at first
because I can hear the kids but can't see them through the eyeholes
of the oversized spherical head. Then I look down through the
mouthhole below my chin and _ bingo _ there they are, around my
knees, grinning, squealing, saying ``hi.''
</P>
<P>
   Instinctively, I start bouncing up and down, waving my hands
like a fruitcake. In a silly, high-pitched voice, I ask the kids
their names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Brian. I saved a chip for you,'' a little boy says,
thrusting a Tostito up my mouthhole.
</P>
<P>
   My wife roped me into this. She helped arrange the outing for
the Boynton Beach West Mom's Club, a group of women who gave up
jobs and salaries to raise their kids. Each mom chipped in a
precious $2-$6 for the Frosty suit rental and souvenirs. For that,
they expect more than an appearance by Frosty. They want a
performance.
</P>
<P>
   So, I pat the children on the heads. Do my best Barney laugh.
Kneel down for bear hugs and frenzied picture-taking.
</P>
<P>
   But I suddenly realize I have zipped myself into a thermal
deathtrap. Besides the hot, heavy suit, I'm wearing snowboots and
insulated leather gloves. Plus, I'm a skinny guy, so my T-shirt is
stuffed with sofa pillows to fill out the suit. My own hot breath
lolls over my eyelids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sit down, Frosty, time for some pictures,'' someone says,
tugging at my elbow. I sit and start hoisting kids onto my lap,
including my own son, 3, who doesn't catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Through the mouthhole, I see the tops of their heads _ little
bowl cuts and pigtails brushed to perfection. Through the eyeholes,
I see moms stooped with their point-and-shoots, frantically shaking
their cameras when the flashes don't fire.
</P>
<P>
   They call to their kids: Smile, Rachel. Smile, Blake. No, Jack
don't say smile, just do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your name, little boy?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you been a good boy this year?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. Guess what? I know that's just a costume.''
</P>
<P>
   Next.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting hotter in here. A tiny girl I can't see, who thinks
she's talking into Frosty's left ear, offers me some of her drink.
Slowly and graciously, she pours the water onto my wrist. I savor
its coolness.
</P>
<P>
   I recognize many of these kids from picnics and drop-off time at
preschool. And their personalities are as varied as snowflakes:
Some are sweethearts, some are crybabies, others have great futures
as nuns, tobacco attorneys or professional wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   But almost all have the same reaction to Frosty. They giggle
with delight. They come back for more hugs or high-fives. I'm
thinking, Hey _ they really believe I'm Frosty!
</P>
<P>
   And that's when I see the truth in the old saying that Christmas
is for children. For us grownups, it's always about maxing-out our
credit cards, waiting in line at the post office, hustling the
just-snapped holiday photos to the one-hour developer.
</P>
<P>
   At least someone still gets it, I think.
</P>
<P>
   As I rise and list toward the exit, the squeals of ``Bye,
Frosty!'' keep coming. And inside this puffy, steamy Frosty head, I
am beaming.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
