<HEADER>
A4519 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRETTY-PLATES18-COX     12-17 2439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRETTY-PLATES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putting your best plate forward
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS, INFO BOX at end of file
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``It's too pretty to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   You hear that time and again at restaurants and dinner parties,
but figure you have to be a chef to create edible works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Not true. It takes only a bit of creativity and a few helpful
tools to produce a plate worthy of an art title.
</P>
<P>
   You want your foods to stand out on holiday tables, when many of
us break out the good china and silver. The foods can look as good
as the rest of the house with only a few chef's tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be misled in thinking that beautiful plates require
gourmet foods, either. A baked chicken with rosemary potatoes can
be alluring, if plated correctly. ``Plating'' is the term chefs use
for what we amateurs call presentation.
</P>
<P>
   It's more than an artful twist, however _ there's psychology
behind placing and choosing foods to go together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to have lots of contrasts, textures, busy things
going on for the eye to enjoy,'' said Gerard Reuther, chef at
Janeiro's in Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   He cherishes the maroon and gold-detailed Versace china used at
the restaurant to cradle his ``tresse de sole et lasange a'ma
facon'' _ a braided fish and pasta dish. The two colors of fish and
three colors of pasta make this a colorful, striking presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Texture and color contrasts are important. ``You want different
textures on the plate. You don't want all the foods to be smooth or
all rough _ and white potatoes with the white fish _ no.''
</P>
<P>
   An elaborately rich place setting _ flowers, glassware, fine
silver _ gives the diner the feel that this a special dinner, he
said. ``This creates the impression that this is fine dining _ it's
what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Mattioli, executive chef at the Ritz-Carlton in
Manalapan, keeps the plate design simple if the food is dramatic.
``Simplicity _ you must know when to say `when' if you are
decorating a plate. Too many cooks try to put too much on the
plate, then your eye cannot focus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If you are plating a piece of chicken, the vegetables or starch
should be kept in smaller proportion, maybe even tucked under it,
so the chicken stands out. Only a bit of sauce _ of a contrasting
color _ should dot the plate. Small vegetables or a creative piping
of potatoes could complement the dish.
</P>
<P>
   The Alsacian chef used a wintry-looking glass plate, with etched
glass stripes for his appetizer or salad of cooked tomato stuffed
with fruits and nuts. ``The winter season means heavy foods; so you
want a lighter plate, so everything doesn't look so heavy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The softness of the tomato is played against the crisp nuts and
chunks of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Around the outside of the plate, he loosely scattered pieces of
the fruits, nuts and spices that are used in the stuffing, giving
the guests a ``taste'' for their eyes of what they will soon taste
with their mouths. Cinnamon sticks add texture and a hint of other
flavors in the dish.
</P>
<P>
   Suit the foods to the season and region, he said. For instance,
``in Florida, the tomatoes are ripe now, so while we have them, we
should feature them,'' he said. You could use apples instead of
tomatoes, but apples aren't Florida foods.
</P>
<P>
   For artist and chef Colin O'Daly of Roly's Bistro in Palm Beach
Gardens, designing a plate is like meditation. ``You see it in your
mind's eye first, and you can tell whether it's right or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest mistake most amateur cooks make is crowding the
foods on the plate, or using plates that are too small, O'Daly
said. Foods must have space, ``just as a painting makes use of
blank canvas to create a focal point.''
</P>
<P>
   The finer restaurants use oversized plates to give food plenty
of space.
</P>
<P>
   He says to think about small portions _ and then keep them
small. Avoid the urge to ``over-decorate.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized contrasts. ``For instance, I'd probably use a
cool-colored plate or one that gives a cool feeling for a spicy
dish, and maybe a brighter plate for something not so spicy. Use a
fancy plate for a simple-looking food, or a plain white or
solid-color plate for an elaborate stacked food.''
</P>
<P>
   Arranging foods of different heights makes the plate visually
more appealing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But don't work so hard that your guests notice. It should look
effortless. The baked apple in a pastry crust he makes for dessert
is a dish that can be constructed in advance, leaving plenty of
time for the host to enjoy the dinner, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The plates can be decorated and waiting in the refrigerator for
the warm apples to be set atop the piped chocolate design. Baking
the crust at the last minute is all that's left to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This baked apple is a dish you'd see at boy's school,'' O'Daly
said. ``Yet on a beautiful plate like this, with just ice cream
below it, and just a little sauce and a bit of a drizzle of
chocolate, look at what you've got. It's the ordinary elevated to
the elaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTIFUL FOODS: IT'S IN THE PLATING
</P>
<P>
   Here are recipes from our chefs and instructions on plating the
foods.
</P>
<P>
   BRAIDED SOLE, SALMON AND PASTA
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds lemon sole fillets
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound salmon fillets
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces dried red lasagna noodles, cooked al dente _ see note
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces dried black lasagne noodles, cooked al dente _ see note
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces spinach lasagna noodles, cooked al dente _ see note
</P>
<P>
   2 whole shallots (for sauce)
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, chopped, for confit
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fish stock _ divided use
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 whole beefsteak tomatoes, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 leek, cut julienne style
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Note: The vegetable and squid (black) noodles are available from
gourmet markets and fresh pasta markets. If squid pasta is not
available, plain pasta noodles can be substituted, though colors
will be red, green and off-white in finished dish.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare vegetable confit: Saute chopped shallots, leek and
diced tomato in 2 tablespoons butter; cook for 10 minutes. Add
cream, salt and pepper to taste; stir well. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare sauce: Saute whole shallots in 2 tablespoons butter.
Deglaze pan with white wine, scraping bottom of pan. Cook till
mixture is slightly reduced in volume. Add 1/2 cup fish stock and
reduce further. Add heavy cream and cook for 5 minutes. Add
remaining butter in small pieces; cook to incorporate about 1
minute. Add lemon juice, and salt and cayenne pepper to taste. Set
aside; reheat when ready to plate food.
</P>
<P>
   Cut fish fillets and lasagna noodles into 6-inch by 3/4-inch
slices. For each plate, make 4 slices of sole, 2 of salmon and 2 of
each noodle; stack on a tray.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the design by placing fish and noodles on baking pan as
shown in photo on cover _ interweave the pasta with fish strips in
alternating colors of each.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 1/2 cup fish stock over all, and broil for 4 to 5 minutes,
or until fillet strips are done, but not dried out. Remove from
broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Place some of confit in center of each plate, spreading just
slightly. Carefully lift fish from pan using wide spatula; set on
top of confit.
</P>
<P>
   Add a small drizzle of heated sauce at table over each plate.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from Chef Gerard Reuther of Janeiro's, Palm Beach.)
</P>
<P>
   BAKED TOMATO STUFFED WITH NUTS AND DRIED FRUITS
</P>
<P>
   8 beefsteak tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons honey (thyme or acacia is preferred)
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces butter
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce pistachios
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce sliced almonds
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce walnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce pecans
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons apple cider vinegar _ optional
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce dried apricot pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce dried prunes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon _ optional
</P>
<P>
   12 black peppercorns _ optional
</P>
<P>
   Mint leaves, cinnamon sticks for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Wash tomatoes. Cut 3/4-inch slice off top of each tomato;
reserve. Scoop out inside of tomato _ reserve for other use as
desired. Chop nuts and fruits coarsely, reserving 1 tablespoon each
for garnishing.
</P>
<P>
   Heat saucepan over medium heat; add honey and caramelize until
golden brown. Add butter until melted, then add chopped nuts and
fruits.
</P>
<P>
   Add lemon juice, vinegar, mint, cinnamon and black peppercorns
if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Stir well over medium heat to toast nuts slightly; remove from
heat. Stuff tomatoes carefully, taking care not to tear skin of
tomato. Replace top of each tomato and place tomatoes in a buttered
baking dish. Bake at 300 degrees for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes will be soft; take care when lifting them to plate.
</P>
<P>
   On a large clear glass plate or solid white plate, place tomato
slightly off center. Skew top of tomato slightly to reveal
stuffing. Scatter bits of reserved fruits and nuts as garnish
around plate. Top each tomato with mint leaf; add cinnamon stick if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This could be served warm or cold. Apples could be
substituted for tomatoes if desired, though more baking time would
be required (20 minutes more or until apple is soft.)
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from chef Joseph Mattioli, The Ritz-Carlton, Manalapan.)
</P>
<P>
   BAKED APPLE IN CAVADOS BUTTER SAUCE WITH PASTRY CRUST
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup golden raisins (or sultanas, if available)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Calvados (apple brandy)
</P>
<P>
   4 apples, cored (Reinette preferred, but any cooking apple will
work well)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces frozen puff pastry dough, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons superfine sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces (about 2 1/4 tablespoons) butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons semi-sweet chocolate pieces melted with 1/2
teaspoon vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   Soak raisins in Calvados for at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Drain, reserving Calvados. Remove core from each apple, and peel
top about 1/2 inch around center. Take slice off bottom of each
apple so it stands firmly upright.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle raisins with cinnamon; toss to coat. Stuff a few
raisins in center of each apple; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out puff pastry on lightly floured surface to 1/2-inch
thickness. Cut four ovals to wrap around apples; brush edges of
each with egg yolk.
</P>
<P>
   Enclose an apple in each oval of pastry. Seal the edges well,
and crimp with small knife. Brush each top with egg yolk; make a
small cut in the top of each as a vent.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees for about 20 minutes. Remove from oven and
dust generously with superfine sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Place under a hot broiler briefly to cook sugar and give a nice
shiny glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cook brown sugar, water and honey in heavy-based
saucepan to a pale amber color. Stir in butter and cream, reserving
about 2 tablespoons, then add reserved Cavados.
</P>
<P>
   Strain sauce; keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Before plating, chill plates slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Melt chocolates and shortening; pour into tiny parchment cone.
Draw fine lines in a random pattern on each plate to edge of plate
(or use a ruler).
</P>
<P>
   Position each apple slightly off center on plate. Drizzle sauce
over apple, or spoon between lines of chocolate for abstract
design. Serve immediately. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from chef Colin O'Daly of Roly's Bistro in Palm Beach
Gardens.)
</P>
<P>
   CHEFS SHARE THEIR TIPS ON PRESENTING FOODS
</P>
<P>
   Here are tips on plate designing from well-known chefs:
</P>
<P>
   _ The first rule is flavor _ make sure the foods deliver what
they promise. If they're not cooked properly, no amount or plating
will save them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take inspiration from foods you see in fine restaurants. Note
how chefs place the foods on the plate, and the kinds of plates
used. Look at food magazines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Think through the foods that will go on a plate together
before cooking. Are there contrasts in texture, color and flavor?
</P>
<P>
   _ Practice first, especially with an elaborate dish or design,
to make sure you can pull off the plating in a dinner or party
setting for several guests at once.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't try to design every course of a meal. While it's good to
separate courses for plated foods, you can still serve a plain
tossed salad, or a bowl of soup.
</P>
<P>
   _ Every plate should have a focal point _ one food should draw
the eye first. It doesn't have to be on the center of the plate; it
can be off-center.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put the main food on the plate, set it on the table, step
back, and look at it. Add only one other food at a time. Use a
larger plate, a different color or a textured one to create the
mood you want.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use one stunning design technique per plate. If you've
``painted'' a sauce on the plate, don't dust the rim with sugar or
cocoa. If you've created a pastry garnish, don't add six other
garnishes. Let only one stand out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use one attractive raw ingredient from the dish to get the
diner ready for what they're about to taste.
</P>
<P>
   _ All garnishes on the plate should be edible.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Post wire and staff reports.
</P>
<P>
   PUT YOUR BEST PLATE FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   It's more than just a little creativity _ sometimes, it's the
right tool to help you jazz up your food. Here are things to have
on hand:
</P>
<P>
   A SQUEEZE BOTTLE: As trite as it seems, painting a plate with
sauce-squiggles still impresses, especially with desserts.
</P>
<P>
   A BAMBOO SKEWER OR CAKE-TESTING WIRE: Draws the lines through
those sauce squiggles to create the feather-like designs.
</P>
<P>
   A PASTRY BAG WITH LARGE STAR TIP: Don't just plop potatoes and
purees onto plates _ pipe them out in an attractive pattern.
Another tip, especially for mashed potatoes _ brown them slightly
after piping or dust with finely chopped herbs. (You also can use
it as intended: to create fanciful pastry doughs or pipe cream onto
a dessert.)
</P>
<P>
   A SIEVE: To shake cocoa or powdered sugar or even fine salt onto
a stencil for a pattern on a dish.
</P>
<P>
   A PARING KNIFE, GARNISHING KNIFE AND ZESTING TOOL: These peel
and cut hard veggies and fruit peels into fanciful shapes, and in a
pinch, turn chocolate or pastry pieces into interesting designs.
</P>
<P>
   A FEW OVERSIZE PLATES: Chefs serve foods with plenty of space
around the plate; it's a design trick made possible by oversized
plates. The magic behind this trick _ don't overload the plate.
</P>
<P>
   A PASTRY BRUSH: Gets rid of loose crumbs from cakes, or other
distractions. Can be used with a light sugar-water glaze or a light
oil to give foods ``shine'' just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
