<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We can't resign highways to becoming scrap zones
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ It would appear, as one drives the nation's
highways, that mankind made a deal with the devil just after Henry
Ford came along to change our lives forever.
</P>
<P>
   We could travel faster than horses, said the devil, but as our
visual fare we would have to line up the corpses of the dead _ dead
cars, that is _ for eternity along our highways.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is that driving cross-country one commonly finds one's
self whistling past graveyards, like the one at Elm Mott on I-35.
</P>
<P>
   Actually it's not one auto graveyard but several, about as
picturesque as the Iraqi retreat out of Kuwait _ automotive hulls
as far as the optic nerve can stretch. Recently with the blessing
of the McLennan County commissioners its numbers were allowed to
multiply.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? Maybe, learn to say no.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitican communities spend lots of money trying to improve
images and foster economic development. Despite all this, too
commonly just before a visitor hits the ``welcome to'' sign, he or
she is repulsed by roadside signs like this.
</P>
<P>
   Real highway turn-off
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not whether or not to have auto salvage yards. They
are a necessity, as are other means of disposing of and recycling
our refuse. But seemingly it would be public policy to limit their
blight, particularly in our transportation corridors.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the 3-1 majority that approved a permit for Stephen
Harvey's wrecking yard at Elm Mott, McLennan County Commissioner
Joe Mashek said he would support the application because he wants
to ``go by the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The implication was that commissioners had little choice.
</P>
<P>
   The further implication was that because interstate-hugging Elm
Mott was already an auto-salvage mecca, one more yard couldn't
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Were commissioners powerless to say no? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents insisted that the commissioners could have chosen one
of several reasons to say no, including the presence of residences
within 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people in nearby Waco wish the commissioners would have
said no based on Article 8, Section 3.06 of the county junkyard
ordinance, under which a permit can de denied if the junkyard is
found ``detrimental to the economic welfare of McLennan County,''
which all highway corridor blight is.
</P>
<P>
   Grandfathered junkyards
</P>
<P>
   County officials point out that the new salvage yard will be
required to erect screens to spare motorists' eyes, so it will be
the least of our concerns, blight-wise. The real problem is
junkyards which were in place before passage of the 1970s-vintage
Highway Beautification Act, which requires such screening. Many of
those ``grandfathered'' junkyards do little or nothing to spare us
from their pitiful palor.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Bird Johnson, your country needs you.
</P>
<P>
   Just as you pointed out how billboards were stealing scenes from
our countryside, you need to point out how rows of dead autos
diminish things even worse.
</P>
<P>
   The country needs your radiance along a roadside as you point
out the bleeding of our vistas. It needs you to say that which
everyone says but nobody seems to do anything about.
</P>
<P>
   Policy makers, at the state and local level, should know that
they are not powerless to curb this blight. They can say ``no'' to
junkyards in highway corridors, even if others have come before. At
the state and national level they can change laws so that
grandfathered salvage yards have to comport themselves as do those
that abide by the Highway Beautification Act.
</P>
<P>
   The devil in Henry Ford's wondrous idea was pollution of many
sorts. We've been far more vigilant about the pollution that comes
from our tailpipes than that which will rust away our days, and our
great-grandchildren's days, along our highways.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
