<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Getting at the truth on Desert Fox
 &HT;    (For release, Dec. 20, 1998.)
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``General Faversham is a director of Her Majesty's Royal Chelsea
Flower Show and senior fanfare officer for Desert Fox who will now
report to you on the effectiveness of our strikes. General.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you. Beginning on 16 December, combined forces of the
United States and United Kingdom began precision missile attacks on
military targets inside Iraq. As you can see by these videotapes,
each and every missile dropped right down the smokestack of the
intended target, inflicting heavy damage to materials but not to
the civilian population. We are assessing incoming reports and
shall further update you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning. My name is Ahmed Kassem Arif, deputy
communications officer for the Baghdad district, and one of its
most prominent fig salesman. We have brought you here to downtown
Baghdad to show you that American missiles have killed wantonly. As
you can see, this was a pita factory with absolutely no military
significance. (Psst, Hasan, shut that door!) This once again proves
the brutality of the American satans and their British
subordinates. As a result of this hit, every child in eastern
Baghdad carries with him many shrapnel wounds, while those who
don't nevertheless are suffering from illnesses brought about
earlier by the economic restrictions placed on the peaceful people
of Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN here, as we walk among Iraqi citizens to get their opinion
of the early attacks. You, sir, how do you feel about being bombed
in the middle of the night?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible. These people are satans. I was at home
watching a late soccer game on TV when the missiles flew overhead.
I hear they missed all their targets and hit only women and
children. Allah will exact a revenge for this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``General Faversham. Ridley here from CNN. I've just come back
from downtown Baghdad, where I was taken to one of the ground zero
points by Iraqi officials. What I saw was a broken water pipe,
missile fragments and a lot of water in the street. What was the
purpose of hitting this target?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The water pipe, my man, the water pipe. We had reason to
believe that pipe carried through it what is called `heavy water,'
which as you know is one of the components for creating nuclear
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, with all due respect, the water pipe was coming directly
out of a toilet behind a coffee shop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Precisely. These people are treacherous. They will use any
venue to achieve their goals. Toilets are natural venues for
beginning work on weapons of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Would someone convey to the American government, especially
their presidents, that we, the people of Iraq, do not appreciate
our leader being referred to only by his first name. First, Bush
would say only `Saddam.' Now Clinton the Fornicator does the same.
`Saddam,' he says, only `Saddam.' Would your President Roosevelt
have called Adolf Hitler simply `Adolf'? Of course not. Do not be
so informal with our great leader. And stop with those bombs and
missiles. You can't hit the side of a barn with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Faversham here again. Despite Iraqi claims to the contrary,
our data show heavy damage to their ability to wage war. We have
destroyed all their fixed facilities between Beijing and
Saskatchewan, and have inflicted equally heavy damage on their
mobile targets, including every automobile that has left Baghdad in
the last six days, as they are likely vehicles to transport heavy
water from Baghdad toilets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean `data shows,' General, not `data show.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, Yank, you speak your English, I'll speak mine. Do I
complain when you pronounce `miss-ill' when it should be
`miss-ile'? Next!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, the Iraqis claim one of the missiles struck the house of
the daughter of Saddam Hussein. Is that considered a military
target? Did you think Saddam, himself, was there at the time?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The house definitely was a military target. If it had a
bathroom and pipes leading from it, it represented a danger. We
used our `wildcard' strategy on that, something we developed to
bomb Moammar Gadhafi's tent several years ago. You never can tell
when those guys are going to be at home, so it's worth a shot. We
only hit the toilet, however.''
</P>
<P>
   And now this from U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan:
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't we all get along?''
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
