A4554 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN20-COX     12-17 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The atrocities of attack politics
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bombing in Iraq not only degraded Saddam Hussein's ability
to wage chemical, biological and nuclear war. It also further
degraded American politics _ however much that might have seemed
impossible beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   The competition in such matters has been stiff, but surely one
of the season's most unseemly sights was that of many Republicans
rushing to declare President Clinton had gone after Iraq just to
distract them from the pleasures of his imminent impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   A more callow act of partisanship would be hard to imagine. But
there was Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, no less, disavowing
the president's decision even in the heat of battle. Rep. Gerald
Solomon (R-N.Y.) called the timing the ``lowest thing'' he had ever
seen. Republican former Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger
said it ``stinks to high heaven.'' Georgia Rep. Bob Barr of course
frothed, this time with a goofy theory that Clinton launched the
attack so he could then say the example of the U.S. military had
taught him at long last how much honor counts and thus weasel out
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Even the ordinarily quite sane Sen. Richard Lugar of Indiana,
one of the GOP's wiser foreign policy heads, lamented that the
president so lacked authority any longer that he would be unable to
rally support for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   If so, might that just maybe have anything to do with six years
of unremitting Republican demonizing of him? But even as Lugar
spoke, one poll showed 80-plus percent of Americans do support the
attack, and in another poll only 30 percent _ the base-line number
in any matter involving Clinton _ thought the president was up to
no good. And notable foreign opposition came just from the usual
suspects _- France, China and Russia, each with major big-money
reasons for its open-ended indulgence of Saddam's games.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who had been paying attention, the attack could have
come as no surprise. When Clinton called back our B-52s in November
after Saddam made a literally last-minute promise to restart arms
inspections, the president made it plain that another Iraqi lapse
would bring prompt military action. No more talking. No more
warnings. After chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler blew the
whistle on Saddam's continuing noncompliance and pulled his team
out of Iraq Tuesday and with the Muslim holy month of Ramadan
impending, it was virtually certain the United States and Britain
would shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had nothing to gain politically by attacking except the
further enmity of Republicans already steeped in it. GOP leadership
had made it clear the party was hellbent on the president's
impeachment, come what may and contrary public opinion be damned.
Putting the vote off a day or two was all that was ever in the
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Are so many Republicans by now in such a deep and permanent
anti-Clinton fit they really suppose he would order U.S. troops
into battle just for that? Apparently. Most were more circumspect,
but the number who leaped to attack the president instead of Saddam
Hussein was appalling. This is what years of attack politics has
brought us to.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
