<HEADER>
A4728 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-EMILY-WATSON-ART     12-17 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-EMILY-WATSON-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER POWERFUL ROLE FOR EMILY WATSON 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Emily Watson in ``Hilary
and Jackie.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    While Emily Watson is hardly a household name in Hollywood, when
the Oscar nominations are announced in early l999, the British
actress is likely to show up again--for the second time in three
years.
 &HT;    This time it will be for her role as the late British cellist
Jacqueline du Pre, in ``Hilary and Jackie,'' a true tale of sibling
rivalry run amok.
 &HT;    Watson made her remarkable screen debut in ``Breaking the
Waves'' (1996), Lars von Trier's powerful film in which she played
the disturbed wife of a paralyzed oil worker. The impression she
made has never quite faded. Now she's done it again in an equally
disturbing story.
 &HT;    Watson never goes the easy route as she portrays the brilliant
but troubled du Pre who died in l987 from the degenerative nerve
disease multiple sclerosis.
 &HT;    The story is based on the book by du Pre's sister and her
brother Piers. Hilary is played by Australian actress Rachel
Griffiths, last seen in this country as the best friend in
``Muriel's Wedding'' (1994).
 &HT;    Hilary du Pre, also a musician, never climbed to her sister's
heights and the memoir she penned could be seen vengeful. Certainly
it paints an unflattering picture of the cellist who one critic
said used the instrument to create ``music that wept.''
 &HT;    What will undoubtedly be one its most shocking revelation is
Hilary's acquiescence when her sister, married to the famous
pianist and conductor Daniel Barenboim, asks to sleep with Hilary's
husband Kiffer Finzi, played by David Morrissey.
 &HT;    The very tall, slim Watson owns it's the sex swap in ``Hilary
and Jackie'' that has caused the most attention. Says Watson:
``Jackie couldn't sit down and say 'My life's a mess.' She lacked
the emotional vocabulary to deal with things. So her way of saying
'I need somebody to love me just for me, not for my cello,' is to
say 'I want to sleep with your husband.'''
 &HT;    To be convincing as du Pre in the wheelchair, dying slowly and
losing the ability to make music, ``was a lot easier than most of
things I've done,'' says Watson, ``because there's such a lot
available on Jacqueline and such a lot written about her. There
were all the videos--and of course all her recordings. The hard
part was to learn to play the cello--or at least I had to look as
though I was playing.''
 &HT;    Watson says at 14 she actually studied the instrument for six
months. ``But for me that was all. But Jacqueline often was quoted
as saying the cello was incredibly sensual and that as a woman
you're forced to embrace it with your body. So it became like a
lover. It fulfilled her life in many ways and it left her lonely.
Isn't that what lovers do to us?''
 &HT;    Much time also was spent learning to play a victim of the muscle
disease. ``The great tragedy was that she was a 'primary
progressive'--it's the worst kind of sclerosis because it moves
quickly and affects the entire body,'' says Watson. ``At the end
her body was constantly trembling and flailing.''
 &HT;    Watson, a brilliant talent in her own art, says playing du Pre
taught her a lot. ``I think it's a valuable lesson for every artist
because it's such a cautionary tale. You can have talent and
celebrity and those things can take you to a very dark place
because we really don't understand what it's all about. You need a
sane voice to keep pulling you back to reality... Whenever I'm
feeling too grandiose I go home and do the ironing.''
 &HT;    Watson, married to actor-writer Jack Waters whom she met while
both were with the Royal Shakespeare Company, says her skyrocketing
career has not affected their marriage. ``We spend as much time as
we can together--and make those moments count.''
 &HT;    Since the du Pre role Watson has completed ``The Cradle Will
Rock,'' under Tim Robbins' direction, playing a street urchin in
the film which Robbins also wrote. She is deeply into yet another
book-to-screen memoir--''Angela's Ashes,'' based on Frank McCourt's
best seller about a family growing up poor in Ireland.
 &HT;    ``Since 'Breaking the Waves' I'm in that enviable position of
turning down a lot of scripts and being offered the best there are
for women of my age,'' says Watson, 32. ``But I'm really aware that
this business is more about luck than talent. I was just lucky that
Helena Bonham Carter backed out of 'Breaking the Waves' at the last
moment.''
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or by fax at 212-499-3382.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) &QL;
</P>
