though I was playing.''
 &HT;    Watson says at 14 she actually studied the instrument for six
months. ``But for me that was all. But Jacqueline often was quoted
as saying the cello was incredibly sensual and that as a woman
you're forced to embrace it with your body. So it became like a
lover. It fulfilled her life in many ways and it left her lonely.
Isn't that what lovers do to us?''
 &HT;    Much time also was spent learning to play a victim of the muscle
disease. ``The great tragedy was that she was a 'primary
progressive'--it's the worst kind of sclerosis because it moves
quickly and affects the entire body,'' says Watson. ``At the end
her body was constantly trembling and flailing.''
 &HT;    Watson, a brilliant talent in her own art, says playing du Pre
taught her a lot. ``I think it's a valuable lesson for every artist
because it's such a cautionary tale. You can have talent and
celebrity and those things can take you to a very dark place
because we really don't understand what it's all about. You need a
sane voice to keep pulling you back to reality... Whenever I'm
feeling too grandiose I go home and do the ironing.''
 &HT;    Watson, married to actor-writer Jack Waters whom she met while
both were with the Royal Shakespeare Company, says her skyrocketing
career has not affected their marriage. ``We spend as much time as
we can together--and make those moments count.''
 &HT;    Since the du Pre role Watson has completed ``The Cradle Will
Rock,'' under Tim Robbins' direction, playing a street urchin in
the film which Robbins also wrote. She is deeply into yet another
book-to-screen memoir--''Angela's Ashes,'' based on Frank McCourt's
best seller about a family growing up poor in Ireland.
 &HT;    ``Since 'Breaking the Waves' I'm in that enviable position of
turning down a lot of scripts and being offered the best there are
for women of my age,'' says Watson, 32. ``But I'm really aware that
this business is more about luck than talent. I was just lucky that
Helena Bonham Carter backed out of 'Breaking the Waves' at the last
moment.''
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
