<HEADER>
A4760 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-17 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MUST GO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I recognize the voices.
</P>
<P>
   These people have called before and left messages on my voice
mail. Invariably, they've been angry, hostile tirades assailing me
as a left-winger, as a Republican-hater, as a charter member of the
lying media cabal.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? Now, they're my buddies. Now these same people are
calling to laud me for my judgment that President Clinton should be
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful. They're the mirror images of the Democratic
left-wingers who call to castigate me as a reactionary when I
oppose hate-crimes legislation and argue for parole reform to keep
violent criminals in jail longer.
</P>
<P>
   I'm in journalism, not in partisan politics. I don't think that
either party has all the answers, and I don't think journalists
should be enrolled in political parties _ not even journalists in
special circumstances, like me, whose job is to express opinions
along with reporting news.
</P>
<P>
   That used to be the tradition in the military, too. Career
soldiers, in deference to the constitutional imperative that
military people remain subservient to civilian leadership, used to
stay completely out of partisan politics. Unless I'm mistaken, the
very first ballot that Dwight D. Eisenhower cast was a vote for
himself, after he retired from the army and ran for president.
</P>
<P>
   So no judgment I make on political issues is motivated by party
membership or loyalty. It's motivated by an examination of the
facts and my personal interpretation of their meaning. And my
interpretation of this mess in Washington is that Bill Clinton is
unfit for office. I believe, from my understanding of history and
constitutional scholarship, that the framers would have bounced him
for lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   The lies, distortions and irrelevant distractions that have
surrounded this whole disaster are too numerous to examine here.
The only pertinent issue is whether Bill Clinton's perjury before
the grand jury is sufficient cause to throw him out.
</P>
<P>
   His more thoughtful backers say it isn't _ that presidential
impeachment is meant only to cleanse government after offenses
against the state and only when a majority of the public is willing
to go along.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the framers were worried about a chief executive so
determined to have his own way that he ignored the law. They were
worried about a despot in the White House who, once elected, would
view himself as answerable to no one.
</P>
<P>
   Perjury is a felony, a serious crime _ a high crime by
definition. Given the nature of the president's oath _ to defend
the Constitution and to honor the democratically enacted law _
Clinton's decision to perjure himself at least once, and probably
twice, qualifies as a betrayal of the court system and a crime
against the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind, too, that the framers created the Constitution as
a heavy anchor on raw democracy. It can't be altered by a
passionate but temporary majority. Instead, amending the
Constitution requires an overwhelming display of public sentiment
over an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   They fretted over the majority's momentary madness. And with
good reason, too.
</P>
<P>
   So is an election being overturned here? Not unless, somehow,
Bob Dole ends up as president. Al Gore will. We voted for him,
remember?
</P>
<P>
   Was Clinton set up? You bet. Are many of his enemies scary,
sanctimonious creeps? Yep. But once he perjured himself, did any of
that matter? Nope.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Clinton's crime weighs less than Richard Nixon's. But the
framers didn't intend Nixon's misconduct to become the minimal
standard for removal. And they didn't intend that perjury over
money would count, but not perjury over sex.
</P>
<P>
   It's inconceivable to me that James Madison, et al, could
countenance the continued service of a president whose sworn oath
on a Bible can't be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm with them.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
