<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANAMA CANAL CHRONOLOGY
 &HT;    With PANAMA-CANAL-$ADV20.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following is a chronology of events related to Panama and the
Panama Canal:
</P>
<P>
   1878 -- Frenchman Ferdinand de Lesseps, builder of the Suez
Canal, wins a concession to build another canal in what is now
Panama. But disease and jungles take their toll -- including nearly
20,000 lives -- and his company goes bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   1903 -- President Theodore Roosevelt engineers the separation of
Panama from Colombia so that a canal can be built. The Senate
approves a treaty that allows the United States to build the canal
and grants it ``all the rights'' within a new Panama Canal Zone
that it would possess ``if it were sovereign'' in that territory.
</P>
<P>
   1914 -- The canal opens after 10 years of work, during which
$400 million is spent.
</P>
<P>
   1964 -- Anti-American riots break out in Panama, killing three
Americans and 21 Panamanians. The negotiation of a new treaty
begins.
</P>
<P>
   1968 -- Gen. Omar Torrijos takes power in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   1977 -- Torrijos and U.S. President Jimmy Carter sign two
treaties: one dealing with the operation and transfer of the canal,
the other establishing the canal's ``permanent neutrality.''
</P>
<P>
   1979 -- The treaties take effect.
</P>
<P>
   1981 -- Torrijos dies in a plane crash. Gen. Manuel Noriega
begins his ascent to power.
</P>
<P>
   1989 -- The United States invades Panama to overthrow Noriega.
He's taken to the United States and convicted on charges of drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   1999 -- The U.S. transfer of all Panama Canal properties is to
be completed.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
