<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4780 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-CANAL-$ADV20-C     12-17 1957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YANKEES GOING HOME: U.S. CONTROL OVER PANAMA CANAL (GRUDGINGLY)
WINDING DOWN
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 1500 words.
 &HT;    With CANAL-HISTORY-$ADV20, PANAMA-MILITARY-$ADV20,
PANAMA-RIVALS-$ADV20, PANAMA-BOX-$ADV20.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ The year is 1977, when mood rings and
platform shoes are hot, and a soft-spoken president named Jimmy
Carter signs two very controversial treaties with his
pistol-packing friend from Panama, Gen. Omar Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   The treaties are a milestone in U.S.-Latin American relations,
requiring the United States to relinquish control of the Panama
Canal -- long a symbol of American domination and Yankee ingenuity
-- to Panama by high noon on Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The historic signing sparks massive celebrations in this small,
but proud country, and so moves Torrijos -- the nationalist
strongman -- that he weeps like a baby on his wife's shoulder in
Carter's presence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, the turn of the century seemed eons away.
</P>
<P>
   But now the sun is finally setting on this strategic outpost, a
presence the United States has enjoyed for 95 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Carter said emphatically that signing the
treaties was simply ``the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an honoring of our obligation to treat each other in
the hemisphere fairly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the deadline fast approaching, the Pentagon has already
moved the U.S. Southern Command to Miami, and reduced the number of
U.S. troops here to about 4,300 -- down from roughly 10,000 in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   By August, just 300 U.S. troops will remain, and then, only in
caretaker roles.
</P>
<P>
   But like a husband and wife headed for an amicable divorce, both
sides are suffering a rush of last-minute doubts.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, there are misgivings over whether Panama,
a small country with no military and only 2.8 million people, can
successfully oversee one of the world's most valuable waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Not only must Panama maintain the canal's smooth operation, but
it must convert seven U.S. military bases -- housing everything
from schools to airports -- to private use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they have the capability to run it, but they'll
never be able to protect it from sabotage, which is my concern,''
said John Sweeney, an analyst at the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative think tank in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that the Panamanians, for example, would never stand
up against leftist rebels in Colombia, a violence-plagued country
bordering Panama to the South.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics caution of rampant nepotism, fearing that the
canal could become a cash cow for financially strapped governments
and a jobs provider for whatever leader's in office.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Panama, where the transfer means long-sought
sovereignty, newspaper polls consistently reveal that a whopping 70
percent of the population supports a continued U.S. military
presence beyond the year 2000, particularly when the question is
framed in economic terms.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military has poured more than $300 million a year into
the local economy, and has provided more than 16,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Panama is a teenager whose daddy has been taking
care of everything,'' said Roberto Eisenmann, founding editor and
publisher of La Prensa, Panama's main daily newspaper. ``It's kind
of scary to go out on your own, but you eventually will get over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   One Panamanian who dreads the U.S. departure is Luis Pineda.
</P>
<P>
   A shoe-shine man, Pineda has worked in a shady spot on the army
base at Fort Clayton, which borders the canal, since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He earns $500 a month, or twice the salary of most Panamanian
professionals, shining boots for U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This job has brought me a good life by buying me a new house
and putting my four children through school,'' said Pineda, 48.
``Without it, I'd be on the streets selling newspapers, washing
cars, or doing whatever I could find to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Panamanians work as maids, secretaries, and
groundskeepers. Still others own businesses, such as restaurants,
that count U.S. troops and their families among their best -- and
sometimes only -- customers.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. flag has flown in Panama since 1903, when President
Theodore Roosevelt engineered Panama's separation from Colombia so
that the ``big ditch'' could be constructed. Over the next decade,
the United States completed the canal, one of the world's greatest
engineering marvels, at a cost of $400 million and thousands of
lives.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, the United States stationed as many as
100,000 troops in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-mile-long canal is likened to a water ladder that permits
ships to be lifted, step by step, through three sets of locks to a
height of 85 feet, allowing them to pass from the Atlantic to the
Pacific and back again.
</P>
<P>
   More than 13,100 ships traversed the canal last year, hauling an
estimated 4 percent of the world's goods.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the traffic, which generates $600 million in tolls
each year, moves toward, or from, the United States. The Panamanian
government derives $100 million in profits, while the remainder is
used for operation and maintenance of the canal.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been a source of friction for decades, with Latin
American countries accusing the United States of heavy-handedness
when originally negotiating for control of the canal.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, Torrijos dubbed the U.S. presence a
``colonialist tumor.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Carter acknowledges that signing the treaties was one of
the most unpopular moves he has ever had to make.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, countless critics -- former President Ronald Reagan
among them -- called it the giveaway of an important U.S. asset.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved the treaties by just one vote, and only
after Torrijos threatened to blow up the canal locks if the United
States failed to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still get letters every month, 20 years later, condemning me
for giving away the canal,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Carter chastises the U.S. government for not living
up to the spirit of the treaties.
</P>
<P>
   He said, for example, that the United States has been slow in
relinquishing property.
</P>
<P>
   With just a year to go, the United States has yet to turn over
4,000 structures out of a total of 7,000.
</P>
<P>
   Far worse, Carter said, is that the United States has failed to
adequately clean up thousands of acres of mostly rainforest
surrounding the canal. The United States has used much of the area
as a testing ground for weapons, meaning it is contaminated with
unexploded grenades and other munitions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military says it will clean up 10,000 acres, but that
it can't clean up another nearly 8,000 acres of mostly mountainous
property -- covered with thick, dense jungle -- without seriously
impacting the character of the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some areas, we'd have to bulldoze the trees, and the
(resulting) erosion would be horrendous,'' said U.S. Army Col.
David Hunt, the chief treaty implementation officer.
</P>
<P>
   He added that there are 56 species of animals living in the
forests that are protected by law.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pastor, a professor at Emory University in Atlanta who
helped negotiate the treaties, agrees that the United States hasn't
fulfilled its duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is suggesting we clean up everything, but can we do
better? The answer is yes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, both Pastor and Carter say they have great confidence
in Panama's ability to run the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanians themselves point out that, even with the United
States in charge, 94 of every 100 canal employees -- out of a work
force of 9,500 -- have been Panamanian.
</P>
<P>
   And in preparation for the next century, the Panamanians already
have launched a $1 billion modernization program.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the canal's Gaillard Cut will be widened by the
year 2002 to accommodate two-way, unrestricted traffic 24 hours a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, ships must transit the narrow stretch one at a time,
and only in daylight hours, which causes time-costly traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   It takes eight hours for the average ship to transit the entire
canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our top priorities will be to develop the canal's
infrastructure so that it can be used to lure tourists here,'' said
Nicolas Ardito Barletta, director of the Inter-Oceanic Regional
Authority, which is charged with overseeing the transfer of
properties. ``Each year, 300 cruise ships pass through the canal
but they don't stop because we don't have the facilities for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, Panama plans to operate the canal more like a
private corporation than a government agency, and as such it has
already privatized ports and dry docks.
</P>
<P>
   But even this has drawn consternation.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison Whampoa Group, a huge conglomerate based in Hong Kong,
now a part of China, won contracts to operate Panama's two biggest
ports, Balboa and Cristobal, which sit at each end of the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that communist China will now be in a position
to delay U.S. warships from passing through.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. and Panamanian officials say these fears are overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are laws that say the canal must be neutral,'' Hunt
said. ``There can't be any blockage of the canal.''
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian authorities insist the canal will be financially
independent and well-insulated from party politics.
</P>
<P>
   It will be run by the Panama Canal Authority, a board made up of
11 members appointed for staggered, nine-year terms so that it is
hard for any one president to pack with cronies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appointees have to be approved by the legislature in
Panama,'' said Mercedes Morris Garcia, the authority's spokeswoman.
``Panama has matured a tremendous amount socially and
politically.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is so confident over the canal's future.
</P>
<P>
   One example often cited is the Panama Canal Railroad, which runs
the length of the canal between Panama City and Colon on the
Atlantic coast. Transferred to Panama in 1979, the railroad's
workforce quickly mushroomed from 117 to more than 500. Losing
money and lacking maintenance, the railroad was abandoned in
disrepair in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the Kansas City Southern Railway Co. agreed to invest
$60 million to rebuild the railroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Panamanians wanted to allow passengers to use the railroad
and it just didn't work for them,'' Hunt said. ``But Panamanians
are already managing the canal, and the technical expertise is
definitely there.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the United States, including President Bill Clinton, had
hoped until recently to maintain a presence here beyond the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The United States negotiated for more than two years with Panama
to establish a multinational anti-narcotics center in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   But the negotiations broke down in September after the Americans
insisted on being able to mount military operations from Panama
unrelated to the anti-drug efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The center would have been located at the Howard Air Force Base,
which has been the United States' principal airfield in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Now that base, which supports the bulk of the aircraft involved
in U.S. anti-drug efforts in South America, will shut down May 1.
</P>
<P>
   So, at least for now, it appears that Panama's confidence and
ability will be tested, whether critics like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transfer is a matter of national pride in Panama,'' Garcia
said. ``Panama will finally be the master of its own destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
