<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4781 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-MILITARY-$ADV2     12-17 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-MILITARY-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CURTAIN FALLS ON SLICE OF AMERICAN LIFE CARVED IN PANAMANIAN
JUNGLES
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 800 words.
 &HT;    With PANAMA-CANAL-$ADV20.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALBOA, Panama _ Sgt. Reginald Thomas will sorely miss this
place, with its barbecues, banyan trees, and balmy weather.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, he has rarely ventured beyond the
comfortable confines of the U.S. Army base at Fort Clayton, just
north of this Pacific coastal city.
</P>
<P>
   And why should he?
</P>
<P>
   The all-American enclave boasts nightlife, tennis courts, a
movie theater, a bowling alley, appealing housing -- even
dirt-cheap boat rentals.
</P>
<P>
   But the base's days are numbered and Thomas must steel himself,
like thousands of other Americans, for relocation to another U.S.
base next year outside of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first overseas experience and it's been good,''
said Thomas, 27, of Atlanta. ``I would say everyone is pretty upset
about leaving here.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Panama Canal treaties signed in 1977, the United
States promised a gradual pullout from Panama, slowly relinquishing
pieces of the Canal Zone -- and eventually the canal itself -- by
Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Zone was created in the early 1900s, when the United States
constructed the canal and wrangled permanent control of the
waterway, as well as a lush 10-mile parcel of land on either side
-- the Canal Zone.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the Zone was inaccessible to Panamanians without
authorization. People born in the Zone were considered U.S.
citizens. Some lived their entire lives within the Zone, as did
their children.
</P>
<P>
   The Zone's lone employer, besides the military, was the powerful
Panama Canal Company. It subsidized housing for Americans working
in Panama. It also boasted its own highly respected police force
and school system.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government controlled the Zone -- cordoned off by a
fence from the rest of Panama -- until 1977.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Zone no longer paid taxes to the United States
but it did bear the stamp of Middle America.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of backyard barbecues here every weekend,''
Thomas said. ``We also play a lot of basketball and do a lot of
running.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning, the Zone has been the jungle's very own
Mayberry, a place with virtually no crime or poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, red-roofed duplexes with air-conditioning -- a
rarity here -- stand alongside winding streets, with sidewalks,
that bear names such as Robinson Place and McIntosh Lane. American
flags adorn many of the roomy dwellings that sit on neat,
landscaped lawns filled with palm trees and iguanas.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three cars sit in each driveway. Spacious, well-groomed
parks -- and even Popeye's and McDonald's -- are close by.
</P>
<P>
   Residents employ Panamanian maids, play bingo at night, and
listen to American music at a pub-like bar called The Loop.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. pullout closes the curtain on this little slice of
Small Town, U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   Before the treaties, some 3,700 Zonians, as they're called here,
worked on the canal. But less than 500 American employees are left,
or 6 percent of the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, more than 4,300 U.S. troops also remain here,
but that number will be reduced to about 300 by August, and will
dwindle to zero by next December.
</P>
<P>
   As goes the U.S. presence, so goes the Christmas tree sales by
the Boy Scouts and the hearty Thanksgiving dinners in the mess
halls. The military's ``Tropic Times'' newspaper will stop
publication, and the Southern Command Network will cease its daily
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   The Elks Club, the Little League, and the Knights of Columbus
are already long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a wonderful place to bring up children,'' said
Maritza Pearce, who raised a son and a daughter on the base at Fort
Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my children grew up and left home, I had to warn them
about what it would be like on the outside,'' she said. ``They'd
been sheltered here and so I wanted them to know that the rest of
the world would be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, some Panamanians have resented the American
bubble, which has contrasted so sharply with nearby neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Omar Torrijos, who negotiated the Panama Canal treaties
with former U.S. President Jimmy Carter, was famous for having once
said: ``I don't want to enter the history books. I want to enter
the Canal Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, with Panamanians already in control of most of the
Zone, the area's manicured properties are a far cry from the
littered squalor that characterizes El Chorrillo, an unsafe,
pastel-colored tenement only a short drive away.
</P>
<P>
   In this crowded, impoverished neighborhood, children in torn
clothing play in streets that are strewn with broken glass and old
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, some 40 percent of Panama's 2.8 million people live in
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on there won't be these little enclaves here that are
totally cut off from the rest of Panama, and I think people are
happy about that,'' said Mercedes Morris Garcia, spokeswoman for
the Panama Canal Authority, which will run the canal after 1999.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   With the U.S. pullout, Panama will inherit seven military bases
and 7,000 buildings -- everything from schools to churches -- in
the Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Panama has grand plans for converting these properties to
civilian use in a way that reaps enormous economic benefits for the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Panama hopes to become a banking, tourism, education, and
transportation hub, a destination for everyone from cruise ship
passengers to American graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Panama plans to convert Fort Clayton into a ``City
of Knowledge,'' a sort of American university on the canal that
uses the facilities of the military bases. The barracks, for
example, will become dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the first thing we want to do is build cruise ship
facilities on the Pacific and the Atlantic (coasts) with the hope
that 300,000 to 400,000 passengers on cruise ships will be coming
here within five years,'' said Nicolas Ardito Barletta, head of the
Inter-Oceanic Regional Authority, which is responsible for the
assimilation of the Zone into Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some U.S. citizens plan to stay on in Panama beyond
1999, lured by amenities that have nothing to do with U.S.-style
perks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be retiring here because I love it,'' said Col. David
Hunt, the chief treaty implementation officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nights are cool, and in 45 minutes I can be at the
beach,'' he said. ``They really have it all here, from old ruins to
scuba diving.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
