<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4782 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-RIVALS-$ADV20-     12-17 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-RIVALS-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEIGHBORS PROPOSE FRESH CHALLENGES TO PANAMA'S MONEY-MAKING
DITCH
 &HT;    With PANAMA-CANAL-$ADV20.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Dec. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ With its money-making ditch, Panama has
long been the envy of its neighbors, particularly Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a century after French engineer Philippe Bunau-Varilla
frantically persuaded the United States to take over a failed
French attempt to build a canal in Panama, Nicaragua's dreams for a
canal of its own still haven't died.
</P>
<P>
   And other countries, too, are offering fresh proposals to
challenge the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
   But whether any of them fly remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone could amass the kind of money that would
be needed to build a rival to the Panama Canal,'' said U.S. Army
Col. David Hunt, who is in charge of implementing the 1977 Panama
Canal treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Under these treaties, the United States must relinquish control
of the Panama Canal to Panama by Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But still fresh challenges abound, especially in Nicaragua which
has nearly twice the population of Panama but only a fourth of the
gross domestic product. They are galvanized by the continued growth
in canal traffic and by predictions that the Panama Canal could
reach capacity some time between 2010 and 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic through the Panama Canal is expected to increase by 2 to
3 percent a year over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   One group, Canal Interoceanic de Nicaragua, or CINN, has been
hatching a plan for a so-called ``dry'' canal since 1995, and it
recently submitted viability studies for the proposal to the
Nicaraguan government.
</P>
<P>
   The government is expected to rule on the idea by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, CINN would head a private consortium, led by U.S.
financier Don Bosco, that would have to pay the staggering cost of
more than $2.3 billion to build two new ports and a railway across
the isthmus.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy behind dry canals is this: ports are constructed so
that containers can be shifted to train or road and then
transported across land to a waiting ship on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   All the plans seek to divert traffic from the Panama Canal,
which reaped $600 million in tolls over the past year from more
than 13,100 ships.
</P>
<P>
   To remain competitive against future rivals, the Panamanians
have launched a $1 billion modernization program that's designed to
widen the narrow Gaillard Cut -- where the canal was carved through
the Continental Divide -- which should increase the canal's
capacity by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The widening, which will permit two-way, unrestricted traffic,
will be completed by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing everything we possibly can to increase capacity
so that we do not reach the saturation point,'' said Mercedes
Morris Garcia, spokeswoman for the Panama Canal Authority, which
will run the canal after next year. ``We are committed to running
the canal efficiently and to making the canal competitive in the
next century.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
