<HEADER>
A4785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN18-COX     12-17 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: WHO IS THE REAL DESERT FOX?
 &HT;    Eds: Due to rapid news developments, Andrew Glass's Sunday
column is moving this week for immediate release.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When it comes to Iraq and impeachment, the
wag-the-Buddy theories aired on Capitol Hill and abroad miss the
point. It's that Saddam Hussein and Bill Clinton enable each other.
The rocks in Saddam's head fit the holes in Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam's actions solicited a deadly rain of American missiles.
His aim was to dissolve the coalition that has been aligned against
him since before the Persian Gulf war, and thus change the stalled
calculus that has rendered oil-rich Iraq the poor pariah of the
Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   By gaming his moves beyond the next CNN live report, Saddam has
shown himself to be a true Desert Fox, as the air campaign against
him has been dubbed.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam's plan seems to be working. Russia, China and France
remain furious over what the United States and Britain have done,
particularly the autonomous way in which Washington and London
acted.
</P>
<P>
   From a tactical point of view, there's merit in disabusing
Saddam of his long-term hope of leading Arab armies into Israel.
But Americans still need to pay heed to their long-term interests
around the world, which are not necessarily served by dropping
smart bombs and passing resolutions of praise for the brave fliers
whom Clinton has put in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   When Saddam stayed Clinton's trigger finger by letting United
Nations inspectors return in mid-November, he knew the Americans
would revoke his parole if he stepped out of line. But Saddam, by
his actions, still issued an invitation for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton knew that Saddam knew. That's why planning for Desert
Fox began weeks ago. The U.N. report that Saddam had again strayed
from his box may have caught the impeachment-bound Congress
unawares. But the president had put that card into his own game
long before the press and most other folks realized it was in his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   In bombing Iraq, Clinton hasn't lifted the threatened shame of a
scarlet ``I'' stamped into his record. His critics believe that if
he lied about Monica and Paula, he could be lying as well about the
Beast of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton has shown himself to be bit of a fox too,
although not in the same league as Field Marshal Erwin Rommel, the
original Desert Fox, who led the German Afrika Corps in World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, Clinton is engaged in a delicate game: how to
portray himself as a victim of a partisan witch hunt while finding
the few Republican votes he needs in the Senate in January (along
with those of nearly all the Democrats) to abort the risk and
further shame of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   When the Desert Fox became implicated in the failed plot to kill
Adolf Hitler and end the war, his first thought was the need to
protect his wife and family. To do so, Rommel swallowed a poison
pill on Oct. 13, 1944. He was buried with the highest military
honors that the crumbling Nazi state could muster.
</P>
<P>
   It's an outcome that probably didn't occur to the military
planners who were so self-consciously unmindful of the president's
predicament before Congress when they chose to call their action
``Operation Desert Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
