<SLUG> BC-POWER-OUTAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY BLAMES SAN FRANCISCO OUTAGE ON WORK CREW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK and ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Pacific Gas and Electric workers who caused
a massive blackout in the San Francisco area on Dec. 8 ignored
three required safety procedures that could have averted the
outage, a senior utility executive said.
</P>
<P>
   E. James Macias, a senior vice president of PG&AMP;E, said Wednesday
the utility was investigating to find out ``how we can have that
many controls in place and still have everything go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The blackout was caused when the crew working at the PG&AMP;E
substation in San Mateo failed to remove a ground line before
reconnecting the power.
</P>
<P>
   Macias said company rules require a ``supervisory review''
before undertaking the process, a checklist of exactly what the
crew is supposed to do before turning the power back on, and the
presence of an observer while the work is in progress.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Macias said, the review did not take place, the
checklist was not followed and there was no observer on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Six of 18 ground lines were left connected when the power was
switched on. The power surged through the lines into the ground,
creating an electrical fault that shut down power to about a
million people for up to eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Macias said PG&AMP;E has installed a second protective system
designed to avoid a similar problem if the situation were to
reoccur at the San Mateo transmission station. It has also added
workers, both in San Mateo and at other stations.
</P>
<P>
   A system designed to keep the power loss from spreading and
knocking out other substations did not function.
</P>
<P>
   ``This protective system did not work, and we don't know why _
whether it was human error and it was not turned on, or something
else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said a study of the incident showed that about one-fourth of
a second after the power was turned on, the closest substations
were already starting to shut down. Half a second later, Macias
said, there was a small explosion that caused oscillation of
electricity through the system ``like a rubber band,'' and caused
the shutdown, which spread to two San Francisco generation plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tripped off to protect themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Macias said the utility was investigating to determine whether
there was a mechanical or electrical failure in the system,
although no such failure has been detected.
</P>
<P>
   The incident cut power to hospitals, commuter trains and dozens
of buildings in the Financial District. Traffic lights stopped
working, and a 75-year-old woman died when she was hit by a
tractor-trailer rig while trying to cross a street. Dozens of
people were caught in elevators. And hordes of displaced downtown
workers crowded street corners as business came to a standstill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     12-17 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUND IN OHIO: THAT `YOU'VE GOT MAIL!' GUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a deep and resonant voice, pleasant enough but ever so
slightly affected. It's not exactly James Earl Jones, but more
along the lines of Ted Baxter in the old ``Mary Tyler Moore Show.''
And it's vaguely familiar, the kind of distinctive sound that makes
you think, ``Have I met this guy before?''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you haven't met Elwood Edwards, whose Dickensian
name is as memorable as his voice. Unless, perhaps, you've wandered
through the booming metropolis of Orrville, Ohio, where he lives
with his wife, Karen. But you may be one of the 14 million
subscribers who hear his voice all the time on America Online. He's
the ``Welcome. You've got mail!'' man, the guy behind the
relentlessly perky greeting the on-line service has used since
1989. He's also the voice of ``File's done'' and the inevitable
log-off, ``Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are icons and there are icons. Elvis and Einstein are
big icons; Elwood Edwards is a ``Jeopardy'' question icon, a nice
man who unwittingly became the voice of the biggest on-line service
provider in the business. He never applied for the job of the
mailman; he never asked to extend the welcome mat. It just worked
out that way. Back in September 1986, he was a broadcast announcer
in the Washington area; out of curiosity, he bought his first
computer, a Commodore 64, which is now a museum relic. The computer
came with software called Q-Link, which was the on-line service of
Quantum Computer Services (which later became AOL). He decided to
check it out and ended up in a chat room for Christians. ``I
received an on-line message from KarenJ2, and it simply said,
`We're almost neighbors.' '' He lived in Gaithersburg, Md.; she
lived in Fairfax, Va. ``It was just friendly conversation, and we
chatted on line every once in a while over the next few months,''
says Edwards, 49.
</P>
<P>
   The cyberbuddies eventually met for dinner. ``It was July 6th of
1987,'' the man with the voice recalls. They got married the next
year. At the time, Karen was working in Quantum's customer services
department, and one day, she overheard AOL founder Steve Case and a
few programmers discussing adding a voice to the service. ``She
said, `Why don't you try El? He's a broadcaster.' '' Try him they
did. Edwards recorded the four phrases on a cassette recorder, and
they've been using those simple recordings ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think I'm the mailman, always bringing good news,''
he says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   He's not employed by AOL, never has been. He allows that he has
received compensation for his voice, which the company says is
heard 27 million times a day. ``I'll go so far as to say that my
relationship with AOL is very satisfactory,'' he admits, ``but I
don't elaborate any more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most AOL members tend to think the voice is computer-generated,
but that's likely to change soon. The ``Welcome'' man is heard
repeatedly in the upcoming film, ``You've Got Mail,'' a sort of
cyber love story starring Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks. Edwards hopes to
generate interest for the voice-over business he runs out of his
home after the film is released. (You can see his photograph and
hear ``the voice'' at his Web site, members.aol.com/voicepro.)
</P>
<P>
   A silver-haired, bespectacled man who stands at 6-foot-6,
Edwards has been in the broadcast business since he was a teenager
in North Carolina. ``I made a pest of myself at the local radio
station,'' he recalls. ``I had fallen in love with the idea of
being a DJ, and the people at the radio station figured, `If we
don't do something with this kid, he'll never stop hounding us.' I
became a DJ back then.''
</P>
<P>
   He's worked steadily in both television and radio announcing,
selling products, that sort of thing. He's not exactly recognized
every day for his quirky contribution to on-line lore: ``I don't
walk around saying, `You've got mail,' '' he notes. His wife,
however, will tell anyone who will listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people will be talking about the mailman in the chat
rooms on AOL, and women will say they've had a crush on `that
little man' for years,'' says Karen, whose own voice comes out an
octave higher than her husband's, with a distinct drawl. ``I pop up
and say, `That little man is 6-foot-6.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Edwardses are certainly one of the first _ if not the first
_ married couples to have met in an on-line chat room, which is a
small claim to fame. Were they a tad nervous about meeting in
person? ``I was a lot nervous,'' Karen says. ``I almost didn't show
up. My friends thought I was crazy and said he could have been an
ax murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   He was just the mailman, though, even though he hasn't written a
postal letter in quite a few years. ``I like to think I have a
friendly voice and it doesn't grow old,'' he says, before
delivering that oh, so familiar sign-off. You know how it goes,
deep with a slightly lower tone on the second syllable:
``Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 20, Sage Weil is another aspiring DJ, but not on the radio;
he just likes spinning at parties and raves in his spare time. Like
Edwards, he's a bit of an icon in the on-line world, a community
where a simple idea can reach millions. Weil invented the Webring,
an alternative to search engines or hubs that enables users to
navigate the Web through rings of themed sites hooked together in a
virtual circle.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1995, Weil was a high school junior in Ashland, Ore. A
computer user since the fourth grade, he started his own Web site _
``mostly ranting and raving'' _ and linked it manually to sites
launched by his friends. In August of that summer, he was visiting
his father in Northern California; ``I was bored, so I wrote a CGI
(common gateway interface) script'' that enables webmasters to hook
their sites together in a ring. By clicking on hypertext links at
the bottom of the page, users can jump to the next site in the ring
or choose a random site or obtain a list of the next five sites.
Weil then started a site called Webring.org and offered to share
the technology with anyone who asked. Soon after, a ring of
English-as-a-second-language sites was launched.
</P>
<P>
   This young man's idea, born of boredom, has enjoyed meteoric
growth.  &UR; Today &LR; , there are 70,000 rings linking 981,000 Web sites;
the rings specialize in everything from mermaids to museums, from
Winnie the Pooh to Scooby Doo. Last year, Webring was sold to
Starseed, Inc., and last week, Starseed merged with Geocities, the
burgeoning on-line community. Weil, now a junior majoring in
computer science at Harvey Mudd College in Claremont, Calif., made
a sizable chunk of change on the deal. But he doesn't like to dwell
on that: ``It's not something I really like to attach to myself,''
he says. ``The Geocities merger was a big distraction, and now
we're focusing on developing the system to give the user what they
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Weil remains committed to his original notion of sharing the
Webring software and allowing everyone to start their own rings on
their own terms, free of censorship and advertisements. The pop-up
windows that are a constant annoyance on Geo- &QC; 
cities will not automatically appear on rings listed on Webring.
``That's an annoying issue because everyone keeps asking about
that,'' Weil says. ``We let the ringmasters have complete control.
They can let in whoever they want.'' Webring doesn't censor its
sites and enables anyone to participate for free. It also has a
search engine of its own that provides links to thousands of rings
organized by myriad topics.
</P>
<P>
   Weil didn't have to go to college to land a job, but he seems
utterly unimpressed with the glittery trappings that come with
unexpected success. ``It depends on what you're after,'' he says.
``If all you want is a salary, that's fine. But I'm actually
interested in learning something.'' What's next for the lord of the
rings? ``I have no idea. Right now I'm bogged down in finals, but
after that I'll do whatever inspires me, I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
