<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILLS STILL GIVE A THRILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I take it as a matter of personal pride that, as my aging
friends talk more and more wistfully of retiring to Florida and
Arizona, their southbound train leaves me at the station.
</P>
<P>
   I am the guy in the black-and-white Ray Milland movie . . .
train station in the snow, topcoat collar pulled up and fedora
pulled down against the ferociously swirling snow . . . the big
steam engine begins chuff-chuffing away, perhaps to Florida,
leaving me, after goodbyes, wading back into my snow world.
</P>
<P>
   Many people believe early season snow is some kind of blessing,
but after the holiday season a pain. This is the extreme of the
mental aging process that clocks itself backwards over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Snow at Easter may seem a little unreasonable to a child ready
to get on with bicycles and baseball down in the flatlands. But
right up to Easter is fine, a whole season of the stuff refreshing
itself storm after storm.
</P>
<P>
   Adults don't often feel that way, though skiing families are
always happy to have a late-season blizzard up in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   But as people grow away from childhood, snowstorms can cease
right after February vacation, thanks, and real hidebound grownups
want it gone after Christmas. Snow, that white silent blessing,
becomes for them mere window dressing for a short and increasingly
tacky commercial season.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I'm with those who believe that the migration to the Sun
Belt raises the average level of intelligence on both ends. When
you stop to realize that the best use of time for such people is
playing golf, well, you know . . . no need to say any more than
that about the snow-haters.
</P>
<P>
   These folks should figure out at some point that as their wish
to retire to the sunny south increases with age, the state of
Florida itself has become a manifestation of some geriatic
disorder. For confirmation of this, head straight over to the
pavilion at the public beach in Naples and eavesdrop on the
octogenarians arguing over their bets at the dog track. The scene
is straight out of ``Seinfeld''.
</P>
<P>
   My brother-in-law who lives in Florida, an inveterate
six-hours-per-day watcher of the Weather Channel, likes to call
when things get bad. To him bad begins here around late September
when the mean temperature drops below 60 degrees. And
frost-on-the-pumpkin season gets him shaking his head wondering why
anyone at all is left back in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he calls us in the height of a blizzard, or just
afterwards. He'll talk about everything but the weather _ kids,
cars, the effect of NAFTA on foreign goods. Then will come that
silence. All you snow-country folks with southern relatives know
the one I mean. And into the silence then will come that tentative
_ cute, maybe _ insinuatingly mousy question: ``So, how's the
weather up there?''
</P>
<P>
   With a robust roar I tell him: ``The weather is absolutely
gorgeous. New snow's piled 2 feet against the garage. The sun came
out after the storm and the snow just glitters. I just got back
from a nice cross-country ski in the woods. It's beautiful up
here.''
</P>
<P>
   And he'll say: ``You can have it. I'll give you about five more
years and you'll be asking me to send the real estate section from
the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   I do not argue any more. I do not want to sound like a guy who
buys a dog of a car and spends the next three years talking about
what a beauty she is. Starts every morning. Good heater. Radio.
Rides like a magic carpet.
</P>
<P>
   No, let the snow-haters think what they want. I don't have any
New England real estate to sell them, and I certainly have the
decency not to call down there to ask how the drought's going.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the snow, and the world of winter that we in the
north country deal with, each in our own way. I honestly do not
know if I would love winter as much were I not a skier, or even _
heaven help us _ a golfer awaiting the opening of the links in
spring.
</P>
<P>
   My sailing friends who do not ski cuss snow for four months,
then go down for a Caribbean vacation to bridge them through. All
of which is wonderful stuff, but after a couple of weeks of a
warm-country vacation, get me back to the land of the long blue
shadows and nights of ringing cold that polishes the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Get me to the Vermont woods on a pair of snowshoes during a
storm when the wind makes the hardwoods rub together and groan
overhead, new snow coming so thick it seems to froth up out of the
earth itself.
</P>
<P>
   If the predictions of medical science are anywhere near
accurate, and the human life span elongates enough, I just may well
get old enough to want to lie on a Florida beach in January. When
I'm about 173 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, snow . . . bring it on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
