A4802 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-SHAHEEN-BOS &LR;      12-17 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-SHAHEEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAHEEN HOLDS KEY TO PRESIDENTIAL BIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ They are wooing Jeanne Shaheen, not with
chocolates or with roses, but with cold, hard cash.
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority leader, gave
the Democratic governor $50,000 for her reelection this year.
Nebraska Senator Bob Kerrey sent $30,000. Senator John F. Kerry
took her out to lunch and threw her an elegant fund-raising bash at
his Louisburg Square home.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Vice President Al Gore has steered $91.7
million of federal grants to New Hampshire over 1998, frequently
delivering the good news in person. And he was planning another
visit this week, until the impeachment crisis crested in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   These are heady times for Shaheen, the popular leader of the
first-in-the-nation primary state. Every Democratic politician who
is even remotely thinking about running for president is courting
her, and with reason.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire governors have a long history of choosing a
favorite presidential candidate and lending support, organization,
contacts and guidance with winning results. Republican Governor
Sherman Adams almost single-handedly won the New Hampshire primary
for General Dwight D. Eisenhower in 1952, mounting a successful
write-in campaign even though Eisenhower never set foot in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Adams went on to become White House chief of staff. So, too, did
John H. Sununu, the Republican governor who orchestrated Vice
President George Bush's primary victory in 1998, providing the
momentum to grab the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen already boasts a prescient track record. Though she
backed Kerrey's unsuccessful bid in 1992, she was instrumental in
helping a little-known Georgia governor named Jimmy Carter win the
primary in 1976. And she ran another dark horse candidate's primary
bid in 1984. His name was Gary Hart, and he won New Hampshire,
upsetting the heavy favorite, Vice President Walter Mondale.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has power, she's enormously popular, Democrats across the
board respect her and like her,'' said Jeff Woodburn, the outgoing
chairman of the state Democratic Party. ``If she decides to get
behind somebody, he'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, praise for Shaheen and acknowledgement of her skill and
power run along bipartisan lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a state that only has five full-time political
officeholders _ and four of them live in Washington _ she's the
biggest and only game in town,'' said Thomas Rath, a Republican
adviser to Lamar Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee who is
busy competing for the support of GOP Senator Judd Gregg.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting down for an recent interview before she rushed through a
light snow to catch a flight to Washington, Shaheen insisted she
has made no decisions about the 2000 presidential campaign. Right
now, she said, she is focused on resolving the thorny
education-finance issue that plagues the state, putting together
the biennial state budget, and getting inaugurated next month.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom, however, puts Shaheen with Gore, and has
Gore stamping out the competition in the Democratic primary.
Evidence that she leans toward Gore could be gleaned from her
choice of political consultants and the decisions of her friends.
</P>
<P>
   Political consultants Mandy Grunwald and Marla Romash work for
both Shaheen and the vice president. Three friends sponsoring
Shaheen's inaugural are with Gore, one of her two finance co-chairs
is with Gore, and key political allies in the House and Senate have
already committed to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaheen's past choices indicate a willingness to sign up
with lesser known candidates. And her 1992 choice for president,
Kerrey, may be running again in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things my involvement in presidential
politics in the primary here has taught me is that there is no
conventional wisdom about what will happen,'' she said, brushing
off the notion that she has already made up her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, predictions about what New Hampshire voters will do are
often wrong. Shaheen said she remembers reading Time magazine in
January of 1984 when she was running Hart's campaign. Mondale's
name was on the cover, and the piece said the Mondale train was
leaving the station and that people should hurry up and get on
board, she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Less than a month later, Hart won the New Hampshire primary,''
Shaheen said. ``It turned the race upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, more than a year before a single person casts a vote in
the primary, Shaheen is benefiting from all of the attention.
National Democrats flocked to the state to help Shaheen get
reelected and to help the Democratic Party take control of the
state Senate for the first time since 1912.
</P>
<P>
   From Gephardt to Kerrey to Gore, Democrats contributed to
Shaheen's campaign coffers, held fund-raisers, and spoke up on her
behalf. And she admits that the money will influence her decision
when she picks a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I think it's a factor,'' she said. ``You always want
to help the people who have helped you. It's a little different
problem when you have a bunch of people help you.''
</P>
<P>
   So many people want to be in her good graces that when Shaheen
needs something from the federal government for her state, she has
many well-placed friends to turn to. There are the ``friends'' in
Congress, such as Gephardt, Kerrey, Kerry, and Paul Wellstone, the
Minnesota senator. There is the all-Republican New Hampshire
delegation. And, of course, there is the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a whole apparatus set up to help the state,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a governor's endorsement does not always work.
Stephen Merrill, the former Republican governor, spent months
soaking up the flattery from Bob Dole, Phil Gramm, Steve Forbes,
Patrick Buchanan and Alexander back in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Merrill pinned himself to Dole, criss-crossing the
state on behalf of the crusty Kansan. But he said he watched in
dismay as voters stubbornly insisted on going their own way,
spurning Merrill's choice in favor of Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched people interviewed on television saying, `I
appreciate where Governor Merrill is in this race, and I'm going to
make up my own mind like Governor Merrill would want me to,' '' he
said, laughing at the memory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BASE18-COX     12-17 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BASE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANTI-IMPEACHMENT FORCES CAUGHT FLAT-FOOTED
 &HT;    EDS: This story, which originally moved late Wednesday, is being
updated for Friday publication for all needing.
 &HT;    630 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a postponed but still-looming vote in the
House of Representatives, stunned Democrats are puzzling over the
revival of an impeachment effort they thought they'd snuffed out.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the outnumbered pro-impeachment forces had steadily
gained momentum. But where were the labor unions and the rest of
President Clinton's political base? Where were the Wall Street
financiers and business leaders to warn against the uncertainty?
</P>
<P>
   Despite a last-minute flurry of activity from Democratic allies,
many of Clinton's champions were barely visible for the past five
weeks, as momentum gained for impeachment in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was almost disbelief that this was actually going to get
to this level,'' said Naomi Walker, spokeswoman for the AFL-CIO.
The labor organization had suspended its stop-impeachment efforts
after the Nov. 3 elections in which Republicans unexpectedly lost
seats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought (Republicans) had heard what they said in
November'' and would give up on impeaching Clinton, Walker said.
The unions have hurriedly reassembled a lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street and in corporate America, the silence has been
deafening.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, a former Wall Street investment
banker, has made no apparent attempt to whip up concerns about the
economic effects of an impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the underlying economy, which is in the long run
what drives markets ... I think the most likely scenario is still
to look forward to solid growth and low inflation,'' he said
Wednesday, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have business leaders expressed a general concern about
instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is a business issue,'' said Frank Coleman,
spokesman for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. He said his members,
instead of viewing it as an economic question, are asking, ``Do we
really want to do this?'' and ``Don't we want to draw the line
somewhere?''
</P>
<P>
   The president's admitted misconduct also has been a factor. It
has sapped some of the enthusiasm from defenders, according to
longtime Clinton ally, Will Marshall, president of the Progressive
Policy Institute. The research group is an off-shoot of the
moderate Democratic Leadership Council that Clinton helped found
and has been a strong policy partner of this White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plenty of people have rallied behind the president and
defended him over the course of the last year,'' Marshall said.
``And many of them felt burned when he, in the end, was forced to
admit what had happened'' in the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said ``most people think he acted deplorably,'' and he
added many Democrats have therefore shifted their focus from
Clinton himself to defending ``the results of a democratic
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has had the steady backing of African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson led a prayer vigil-turned-rally that drew
an estimated 2,000 to the U.S. Capitol on Thursday, the day the
impeachment date originally was scheduled to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defenders, many of whom sported labor union jackets,
carried anti-impeachment signs at the rally, and when a speaker
asked the crowd if the president should be impeached, the group
shouted, ``Never!''
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson has not been highly visible in the Clinton defense
in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, our presence will have made a statement,'' Jackson
said in calling for the 11th-hour vigil. ``If we lose the vote, at
least we were witnesses to this action.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Hollywood supporters also waited until the last
minute, when the battle appeared to be lost. Barbra Streisand and
Jack Nicholson were headliners at a star-studded rally Wednesday in
Los Angeles. But by then, the undecided lawmakers were already
lining up in Washington to announce they would vote for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
