<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERSANTA: `HO, HO ... UH-OH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of my little girls wants a microscope for Christmas. She's
liable to end up with two, thanks to my stupid approach to on-line
shopping. Look upon my folly, and beware.
</P>
<P>
   Locating an Internet shopping site that sells microscopes isn't
a problem. Plenty of on-line retailers carry them. I quickly found
one at eToys (http://www.etoys.com), a clean, well-designed site
with lots of Christmas booty. But after filling up an electronic
shopping cart with the microscope and several other items, I held
off on buying, in order to do a bit more research.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I'd decided to close the deal, eToys was fresh out
of microscopes. Frustrating, yes, but also convenient. The eToys
site is linked directly to its inventory system, so when it runs
out of something, shoppers find out immediately, and can start
looking elsewhere. Many other on-line stores keep on selling
product long after they've run out. It may be a day or two before
you're told the goodies are not on their way.
</P>
<P>
   My boss, for instance, ordered some educational software from
the ebWorld site (http://www.ebworld.com), which is run by the
well-known Electronics Boutique retail chain. A day later, it
e-mailed him to say that the software was sold out, and would he
mind waiting for them to backorder it? At another time, perhaps,
but not 10 days before Christmas. The boss is now waiting to see
how long it takes ebWorld to cancel his order.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I placed my truncated order with eToys, then began a
search for the missing microscope. Any of the major Internet search
engines will serve; indeed, most of them have separate listings of
on-line retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The shopping area of the Yahoo search service listed a retailer
in Ohio who sold an appealing microscope for children. I'd never
heard of the retailer before--just some small Midwestern company
that had hustled itself onto the Internet. But what of it? When
you're rushing to make newspaper deadlines and play Santa, there's
a temptation to buy from the first shopkeeper you see.
</P>
<P>
   I placed the order, but my Microsoft Web browser crashed right
at the end of the transaction--go ahead, laugh. This small disaster
left behind a residue of uncertainty. Did the deal go down, or not?
A call was made to the merchant's toll-free number and was shunted
to a voice mail system, which announced that it was accepting no
messages, because the mailbox was full. A day later, it's still
full. So we have a merchant who can't be bothered to answer its
phones. Or its e-mail, for that matter--I tried that too, with no
results.
</P>
<P>
   Why not go back to Yahoo and demand satisfaction from one of
their listed merchants? Because Yahoo explicitly warns customers
that they take no responsibility for the stores they list. Other
Web sites, such as Excite, offer a listing of certified retailers.
Buy from them, and Excite pledges you'll be satisfied. But Yahoo
leaves its customers twisting in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo makes no secret of its retail policies, and it was my
fault for ignoring them. And the retailer may be an honest outfit
swamped by Christmas orders. My order could be on the way right
now. Trouble is, I have no way of knowing.
</P>
<P>
   If I'd done my homework before ordering, I'd have noticed that
the merchant doesn't seem to belong to any of the various
consumer-protection groups now watchdogging the on-line shopping
business. There's the Better Business Bureau's BBBOnline
certification, for instance, or the consumer privacy seal of
approval offered by TrustE. These are signs of a trustworthy
outfit. Or I could have shopped on a Web site or on-line service
that guarantees satisfaction. The America Online shopping network
offers ironclad guarantees; if one of its merchants don't come
through, AOL promises to back you up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I got careless, and with Christmas eight days away, my
blunders won't come cheap. I must hunt up another microscope,
either on line or in person at some crowded mall. There's a chance
that my little darling will wind up with two microscopes. Maybe she
and her sister will open a pathology lab, to help pay for college.
That'd be some comfort to their old man, an Internet veteran who
misplaced all his hard-won savvy just in time for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   (ou can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
