<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVER RETURNING TO SCENE OF CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martha Swetzoff's life was forever transformed in the early
morning of May 21, 1968, the day her father's life came to a brutal
end.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman Swetzoff, 47, one of Boston's pioneer dealers of
contemporary art and the owner of a Newbury Street gallery, had
been badly beaten in his Bay Village home. Neighbors on Winchester
Street that Monday morning ignored his pleas for help as he ran
down the street bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Swetzoff's violent death marked the beginning of a long quest
for peace for his family, especially his two children, David and
Martha. Martha was just 9 when her father was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Swetzoff is now a 40-year-old filmmaker whose moving
documentary on her father's still-unsolved murder, ``Theme:
Murder,'' was shown last month at the Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The film is more than a labor of love or an attempt to preserve
and define her father's legacy. It is also an attempt to come to
terms with the grief, guilt, and alienation that afflict so many
who survive the tragedy of the murder of a loved one.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the filmmaker's search for truth, as the documentary
attests, has been stymied by the very agency charged with
determining the truth: the Boston Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the killing, ``Theme: Murder'' concludes,
detectives did not interview the most obvious suspect. And a new
generation of detectives _ with Swetzoff's camera running _ denied
her access to her father's murder file, justifying their refusal by
saying they had reopened the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Swetzoff, a slight, engaging woman with an easy laugh, said her
long journey to the heart of her father's slaying was unplanned.
She attempted her first documentary on the murder 20 years ago, as
a Harvard sophomore. She learned then, she said this week, how
little she had known of her father and his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that there was something like objective truth that
you could find by investigating something like this, and I thought
that I would feel better from engaging the process,'' she said of
that first effort. ``Instead, I felt worse.''
</P>
<P>
   After that project, she dropped out of Harvard for four years,
playing electric guitar in an all-female punk band, Bound and
Gagged. She returned to Harvard and, after graduating, began
working on other documentary projects.
</P>
<P>
   But her most important story remained unfinished and untold.
</P>
<P>
   The Swetzoff Gallery was one of many galleries that opened on
Newbury Street after World War II, introducing abstract
expressionist art to a startled, sometimes indignant, audience.
</P>
<P>
   Though Swetzoff married in the 1950s, it was an open secret in
Boston art circles that he was a habitue of the subterranean gay
bars typical of the time. After a divorce in the early 1960s, his
life became even more mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to his family, he had bought a house in Greece, where he
often traveled, and apparently began a relationship with a Greek
boxer, who moved in with him in Bay Village.
</P>
<P>
   Though the roommate alerted police to the crime, he was never
interviewed by detectives, and moved away days later, as Martha
discovered in 1989. Eventually the boxer settled in New York City,
where he got married and raised two children. He died five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Swetzoff, in the documentary, interviewed Lieutenant Steve
Murphy and Captain Tim Murray of the department's ``cold case''
squad to ask why the man was never interviewed and whether
homophobia played any role in the investigation. She also asked for
access to the file on her father's murder.
</P>
<P>
   But Murphy and Murray opened the interview by informing her, on
camera, that the case had been reopened, meaning that they would
answer no specific questions about the case. Neither man returned
telephone calls from the Globe, but their documented rebuff to
Swetzoff suggests that they might be as interested in shielding the
facts from public view as they are in solving the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Swetzoff is reluctant to ascribe ill will to the department, but
she is left, once again, with no answers to the great mystery of
her life.
</P>
<P>
   She says she is not sure how much relief an indictment in the
case, however unlikely, would bring. She scoffs at the
pop-psychology notion of closure, as if her father's death were
something to move beyond, to get over.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in this culture want to assume you can live without
pain,'' she said. ``Well you can't.''
</P>
<P>
   (Adrian Walker is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
