<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-GOREY-2TAKES-     12-17 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-GOREY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS A DARK AND GORY NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YARMOUTHPORT, Mass. _ Pray come join us, gentle reader, as we
celebrate this cozy season of sugar-plum fantasies and Martha
Stewart confections, of chestnuts roasting and cherubs pressing
their noses to the toy store window, with a visit to the home of
author and illustrator Edward Gorey, the misanthrope of mistletoe
himself.
</P>
<P>
   This Christmas finds the darkly brilliant, notoriously reclusive
Gorey _ the high priest of humbug, the anti-Martha _ having a
dickens of a time turning traditional holiday sentiment inside out.
</P>
<P>
   You will espy Gorey's house perched at the edge of a quaint
village green, unfestooned with twinkling lights or plastic
reindeer. The lot is overgrown with bittersweet and honeysuckle. A
barn and shed sit out back, buckling under the weight of the
proprietor's excess book collection. The front porch creaks
underfoot. The doorbell rings _ or does it? No movement inside. Not
a creature is stirring, not even a cockroach.
</P>
<P>
   A rap on the glass, and a bearded figure appears. Gorey, you
surmise. He does not introduce himself. Perhaps he assumes you
know. Perhaps he is indifferent if you do not. In either case, the
door opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you like cats,'' he says solemnly. ``If you're
allergic, we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the 200-year-old Cape-style house are books _ piles of
books, boxes of books, minitowers of books _ stacked upon every
conceivable surface. What appears to be the rusting contents of a
1932 barn sale take up what little space is left. No wreaths or
garlands lay scattered about, spreading their Yule perfume.
Instead, in the kitchen where the 73-year-old Gorey insists upon
sitting, dressed in faded denim and tattered tennis shoes, the
pungent smell of cat urine fills the air. As if on cue, a feline
form hops onto the kitchen table, sniffing you indelicately.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's harmless,'' Gorey assures you, and indeed that may be
true. In the archetypal Gorey story, however, wherein babies get
eaten by bears and small children are crushed by cars, comfortable
assumptions simply do not exist. You therefore pet the cat warily.
Gorey smiles. A good beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The pretext for this visit is publication by Harcourt Brace of
Gorey's hundredth-or-so book, ``The Haunted Tea-Cosy: A Dispirited
and Distasteful Diversion for Christmas.'' Commissioned by The New
York Times Magazine, the text and illustrations are a gleefully
gothic reimagining of Dickens's ``A Christmas Carol.'' The plot
shall not be rehashed here, since summarizing any Gorey plot is
beside the point. Let's leave it that the story has to do with
fruitcake, large insects, and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the pretext vanishes soon enough. Though his publisher
has been lining up interviews and book signings in hopes that
Gorey, creator of such underground classics as ``The Gashlycrumb
Tinies'' and the ``Amphigorey'' series, will make the leap from
cult favorite to bestseller, he could care less, it seems. He makes
it plain that he would rather leap into the Cape Cod Canal than
prattle on with journalists whose flattering attention might
service book sales.
</P>
<P>
   O tannenbaum!
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is important to me, I assure you,'' he says with a
manic giggle, ``least of all `finding a new audience,' as you put
it. I could care less about that. Personally, I got trapped into
doing this book by the Times. I thought they wanted me to
illustrate a rewrite of Dickens, but when I asked them to send me
the manuscript, they never did. When I insisted, they sent a copy
of `Christmas Carol.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gorey scowls. ``Oh,'' he cries, in rising pitch, ``I thought,
for Pete's sake! You expect me to do this in four pages? `Oh no,'
they said. Well, anyway, I did it. It took me two days. Once the
book was ready, I wanted to publish it on Valentine's Day or
Easter. But naked greed intervened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gorey explains that for nearly 20 years he has lived alone in
this house, kept company by five cats and a well-used satellite TV
dish. To say he doesn't get out much _ much less pine to be the
next Stephen King _ would be an understatement. He imagines death
coming for him while he idles beside the ``Cape Cod 5 Miles'' sign
on Route 3, trying to get home from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself getting more reclusive, not less,'' Gorey says.
``I hate to travel. Hate it! And this time of year I'm at my
blackest. I try to avoid the holidays as much as possible. I was
never all that enamored of Christmas anyway. People associate me
with Christmas or Halloween _ why, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, says Gorey, twisting the rings on six of his bony
fingers, ``they're pushing this book of mine. Why? So I'll make a
little more money. Oh wow.'' He chortles. ``I don't have anything
to spend it on. More books? More CDs? I mean, why bother?''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation, warming now, begins to wander as if blown by
the jet stream. And that's OK. You are in no hurry, and neither is
he. Periodically Gorey's mind touches down on interesting runways,
like the untimely death of his longtime publisher, Peter Weed, who
drowned in Lake Winnipesaukee a few years ago. Or on the fact that
Gorey has not left the United States since 1975, when he undertook
a perfectly enjoyable trip to Scotland, which, he says, ``I've been
meaning to repeat but for some reason never have. Perhaps I shall
go to Kyoto.'' Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise Gorey's attention drifts willy-nilly to obscure
authors (Irish novelist George Birmingham) and famous ones (Tom
Wolfe, whom Gorey detests); to pop culture (Gorey's TV addictions
include ``The X-Files'' and ``Buffy The Vampire Slayer'') and
current events (``The day before Clinton was going to tell all
about Monica Lewinsky,'' says Gorey, ``I said, I cannot stand
hearing another word about this. So I haven't watched one second of
news since. Or read a newspaper. The whole world could be going up
in flames, and I wouldn't know it. It's so soothing.''); to Wes
Craven movies, Chinese mathematics, the Sci-Fi Channel, and any
number of other subjects that strike his eclectic fancy.
</P>
<P>
   When more or less forced to circle back to his own work, Gorey
says that this summer, while setting aside two more book projects
long overdue, he experienced ``this big, blinding flash of
revelation. My books aren't really about anything. That's why it
felt very easy to do them. I don't know what inspires me. I just do
them. Or not do them! Basically, I'm incredibly lazy. I got so
bored last summer, I went back to doing puppet shows. I can drone
on endlessly in mindless conversation that nobody really knows what
I'm talking about. Aren't you glad you asked?``
</P>
<P>
   You nod. The cat purrs.
</P>
<P>
   Happy holidays from Edward's house to yours!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1342EST &QL; 
