<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      12-17 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS TO DO BEFORE CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have already dragged home the tree, dug out the ornaments
and checked the lights, and put everything on the tree, baked all
the goodies, ordered the turkey, and filled all the wish lists of
family and friends and wrapped them, then there is nothing to do
until the Big Day.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have not, then consider this potpourri of Christmas
things and chores to make the few days a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   Finding last-minute gifts is a good start.
</P>
<P>
   If there are handypersons in your circle of family and friends,
chances are they have a pretty full tool kit. But there are still
things you might be able to get, as a major gift or stocking
stuffer.
</P>
<P>
   But don't surprise them; they know what they want, and it's best
to get a hint or two.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what Home Depot thinks are in a handyperson's kit, in
addition to hammers (more than one, perhaps), saws, and power
tools.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of saws, give serious consideration to a Japanese-style
saw; it cuts on the pull rather than the push, creates a very
narrow kerf, and is easily guided to follow the penciled sawing
line. Chances are pretty fair that the handyperson doesn't have
one.
</P>
<P>
   And the list, please:
</P>
<P>
   Eight-inch adjustable wrench (a crescent wrench is a good
example, and a good design).
</P>
<P>
   Four-in-one screwdriver. Well, maybe; it would be better to have
a set of several different sizes, one set with regualr slot head,
the other a Phillips head, the head with the cross-shaped slot.
</P>
<P>
   See, you already have some possibilities for gifts, even without
consulting the handyperson.
</P>
<P>
   Channel lock pliers.
</P>
<P>
   Vise-Grip pliers.
</P>
<P>
   14-inch pipe wrench.
</P>
<P>
   Small nut driver.
</P>
<P>
   13-piece Allen wrench set.
</P>
<P>
   Tape rule. Again, maybe. The handyperson might already have more
than enough.
</P>
<P>
   Utility knife. And plenty of blades.
</P>
<P>
   Try square. Why it's called that can confuse any handyperson.
</P>
<P>
   Socket wrench set.
</P>
<P>
   Flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   Electric tape.
</P>
<P>
   19-inch tool box with three drawers and a removable tray.
</P>
<P>
   Power tools are another item to consider, including the cordless
tools, which have been around a while but are better than ever. But
if in doubt, forget everything and give a gift certificate so the
choice is out of your hands, and there is little need for
schlepping to the store for an exchange.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The stains of Christmas
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the stains of Christmas, usually occurring on the
eve of the big day, the day itself, and afterward. Stains are a
nightmare for the homeowner before, during, and after the holidays.
They can be a nuisance throughout the year, but particularly
annoying during festive occasions, because there can be so many of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Other than preventing them, the best way to handle stains is to
be prepared to act quickly.
</P>
<P>
   These five simple strategies are from the MAIDS International:
</P>
<P>
   1. Be fast. A spill becomes a stain when it's allowed to set,
and time is a good stain-setter. Whenever possible, blot spills
immediately with a clean cloth. Scoop up solids with spoon or
knife.
</P>
<P>
   2. Be gentle. Blot _ don't rub, fold, squeeze, or wring. Rough
handling can force dirt deeper into whatever is being stained.
</P>
<P>
   3. Be cautious. Test any cleaning solution before using. Let the
solution set for a few minutes before blotting.
</P>
<P>
   4. Use cold water. Heat makes some stains permanent.
</P>
<P>
   5. Be prepared: Before guests arrive, fill a spray bottle with
the MAIDS International Solution to Holiday Stains:
</P>
<P>
   One teaspoon mild laundry detergeent.
</P>
<P>
   One teaspoon white vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   One quart cool water.
</P>
<P>
   This solution is safe for washable fabrics and most carpets. If
a spill occurs on a non-washable fabric, use dry-cleaning fluid
instead.
</P>
<P>
   And, to be ready for anything, make up a stain-killer kit, a
tote box that you can carry to the various spills.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the box with sponges, cloths, paper towels, detergent,
baking soda, dry-cleaning fluid, salt, white vinegar, ammonia, and
rubbing alcohol. Keep bleach on the shelf, and do not combine any
of these cleaners. Some combinations such as bleach and ammonia
produce a deadly gas.
</P>
<P>
   Next, know your stain. You can't treat it properly unless you
know what it is. There are greasy stains, non-greasy stains, and
combination stains.
</P>
<P>
   Treat non-greasy stains with detergent and water or water alone.
Treat greasy stains with dry-cleaning fluid, followed by water.
Combination stains may need treating with both.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, make a list of stains and tape it to your
stain-killer kit.
</P>
<P>
   Non-greasy stains include alcohol, beer, wine, blood, candy,
catsup, ketchup, chocolate milk, chocolate, clay, coffee, cola,
cologne, fruit juices, graphite, gravy, ice cream, jelly, milk,
soft drinks, syrup, soil, tea, urine, and water colors.
</P>
<P>
   Greasy stains include butter, oleo, calamine lotion, any oils,
cosmetics, crayons, felt tip markers, many glues, black grease,
gum, hand cream, ink, lipstick, mascara, mayonnaise, nail polish,
ointment, oil paint, rouge, salad dressing, and wax.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, have a joyful holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
