<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4819 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-17 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT STEP: RESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Iraq will not save him. The US House of Representatives will
impeach President William Clinton. The vote will break down more or
less on party lines. As time passes, Clinton's support in the US
Senate will evaporate, leading inexorably to his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   For months now, it has been an article of faith among the
political cognoscenti that Clinton ``could not'' be convicted in
the Senate. I wrote something along these very lines just three
weeks ago. The mathematics were correct (55-45 GOP
majority/two-thirds majority needed to convict), but the
conclusions drawn were not.
</P>
<P>
   Politics is chemistry, not mathematics. And the chemical
reaction of the House Judiciary Committee's vote last Friday,
combined with the president's erratic behavior in response to it,
has created a new political dynamic. When the full House votes to
impeach, as surely it will, the case against Clinton will no longer
be viewed as ``lying about sex.'' The truth of the matter will out.
And the truth of the matter is that Clinton broke laws he was sworn
to uphold.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his political career, Bill Clinton has defined
himself by his enemies and argued his way out of trouble by blaming
them for all the fuss. When the Lewinsky scandal broke, Clinton did
what he always does in crises. He lied. He politicized the process,
demonizing his adversaries. And he argued his case in the context
of a diversionary issue, which in this case was sexual privacy.
Clinton knew that the media would wallow in sex to excite their
circulation figures and Nielsen ratings. He knew that the
electorate would recoil at the ``invasion'' of his privacy. His
team conducted polls just to make sure.
</P>
<P>
   It worked for much longer than anyone could have predicted. It
isn't working anymore. According to an ABC News ``Nightline'' poll,
more than 80 percent of the nation now believes that Clinton lied
under oath. Newt Gingrich has stepped aside, taking himself out of
the mix. Ken Starr's performance before the House Judiciary
Committee belied the White House caricature. And the whole issue of
Bill Clinton's misconduct has suddenly become deadly serious. It
isn't about sex anymore. It's about perjury, witness tampering and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   On these three counts, there is no doubt that the House
Judiciary Committee's majority counsel, David Schippers, laid out a
compelling and convincing case that the president is guilty as
charged and should be impeached as a result. The case can now be
weighed on its merits. It is no longer laden down with Clinton vs.
Starr, or Clinton vs. The Vast Right Wing Conspiracy or Clinton vs.
The Media. Its Clinton vs. the Constitution of The United States of
America. And most everyone is beginning to understand that
circumventing the Constitution for the benefit of Bill Clinton is a
fool's errand.
</P>
<P>
   At any moment, reaching back all the way to last January,
Clinton could have averted this outcome had he simply told the
truth. After the midterm elections, Republicans practically begged
him to give them the political cover they needed to accept a
censure resolution. It is a measure of Clinton's arrogance and
selfishness that he instead gave them the back of his hand with his
haughty and dishonest answers to House Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde's 81 interrogatories.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will lie until the last dog dies,'' wrote Michael Kelly in
The Washington Post a few months back and was that ever true.
Clinton's dishonesty has now brought him to the brink of ruin. It
will cost him everything he worked for and everything he dreamed of
since he shook President Kennedy's hand on the White House lawn all
those years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton was first elected president, he brought with him a
cadre of aides, assistants, and associates known as FOBs. The
acronym stood for Friends of Bill. There were hundreds of these
people and they wore their FOB buttons like badges of honor.
</P>
<P>
   There are no FOBs anymore. Bill Clinton has no friends in the
House of Representatives. He has no friends in the Senate. The
Washington establishment despises him. Republicans loathe him. The
media believe he is incapable of telling the truth. And Democrats,
if you asked them in the strictest confidence, would not disagree
with the assessment of columnist Kelly. ``He's an unusually good
liar'' are the chilling words of Senator Robert Kerrey of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   When the roll is finally counted in the House, the votes won't
be there for Bill Clinton. He has, through his ceaseless mendacity
and shameless conduct, exhausted whatever reservoirs of good will
remained. The endgame has commenced. Bill Clinton is alone. Soon,
he will be impeached. Sooner rather than later, he will be gone.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
