<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DOGPATCH' DONNYBROOK BITES HERALD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something about talk radio that doesn't exactly elicit
the best from a guest. On Monday, Boston Herald columnist Don Feder
_ whose Nov. 30 column derided the idea of statehood for Puerto
Rico, which he labeled a ``Caribbean Dogpatch'' _ appeared on
WRKO's morning show. Perhaps inspired by the sophomoric ethnic
insults of host Jeff Katz, Feder had this to say about the crowd of
Latinos who gathered outside the Herald Dec. 7 to protest the tone
of his column:
</P>
<P>
   ``They were out there on a weekday, which to me indicates that
either they don't have jobs or their jobs aren't all that important
to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, there is no meeting of the minds between the
Herald and Latinos who were deeply insulted by Feder's column.
Herald City Hall reporter Jose Martinez, who helped cover the
Puerto Rican statehood issue, said that anger at Feder's column
``was the unifying element in every interview'' he conducted.
``Personally I thought the guy overstated his case and went on to
attack Puerto Ricans as Puerto Ricans,'' said Martinez. ``Which is
racist in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, a group of Latino activists presented Herald
publisher Pat Purcell with a list of demands. On several issues _
such as a Herald commitment to foster more Latino hiring, to
provide internships for Latino students, and to meet regularly with
community representatives _ progress was made. But one participant,
David Cortiella, says that on ``the two fundamental issues of
principle, we were not satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   To wit: The Herald will not issue a fuller apology over the
``content'' of Feder's piece. (Purcell published a Dec. 8 apology
to those offended, but defended Feder's right to his opinion.) Not
surprisingly, the call for the Herald to cease publishing Feder's
column will also go unmet.
</P>
<P>
   In a Globe interview, Feder said ``no one has contested the
facts'' of his column. ``The only thing I sort of regret is the use
of the term `Dogpatch,' '' he added. While he took the term from
the hillbilly home of the Li'l Abner comic strip, Feder said some
protesters ``think I was calling Puerto Ricans dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   With neither side backing down, Monday marked the kickoff of a
two-week boycott of the Herald as organizers try to persuade Latino
merchants not to carry the paper in their stores. One other
outgrowth of this confrontation might have more staying power.
According to Cortiella, the community is organizing a media watch
group to monitor Latino press coverage in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The University of Maryland is a college basketball powerhouse
this year. But the cheering at the campus paper, The Diamondback,
has to do with another kind of basketball record.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Maryland Court of Appeals upheld a circuit court
decision by ruling that the Family Education Rights and Privacy Act
(FERPA) _ which protects the confidentiality of ``educational
records'' _ did not preclude The Diamondback from getting access to
the student athlete parking records. (The paper's suit, filed in
1996, centered on a Maryland basketball star who amassed around
$8,000 in parking fines.)
</P>
<P>
   But there is far more at stake here than just some hyperactive
meter maids. For years, a battle has raged between colleges and
student journalists over FERPA, which is also used to shield campus
judicial proceedings from public scrutiny. Educators say it is
critical to safeguarding student privacy rights. But critics,
including some groups of concerned parents, claim FERPA serves to
effectively hide the incidence of drinking, drugs, and sexual
assault on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense I have from speaking to college editors is that many
of them do believe there are serious crimes being dealt with in
these proceedings that no one even knows about,'' said Mark
Goodman, executive director of the Student Press Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, student newspapers, including those at the
University of Georgia and Miami of Ohio, have been using the law to
crack open campus records. With FERPA under siege in court, Goodman
predicts a move to amend it in the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, amid serious self-flagellation, the American Society of
Newspaper Editors (ASNE) released a study on public perceptions
about journalistic credibility. (ASNE president Edward Seaton
introduced the results by alluding to the profession's ``spring and
summer from hell.'')
</P>
<P>
   The survey _ based on 3,000 phone interviews and 16 focus groups
and directed by the Massachusetts-based Urban &AMP; Associates _
contained heaps of doleful news about how the real world sees
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is particularly new. But the most dire warnings may
be in the section about the growing chasm between the media and the
masses. More than half the respondents believe the press is ``out
of touch with mainstream Americans'' and two-thirds think editors
and reporters are more cynical than normal people.
</P>
<P>
   The truly eye-opening comments came during the focus groups. One
participant declared that journalists ``like to see adverse things
happen to people.'' Another put it even more starkly: ``You
wouldn't be a good reporter if you were a nice person.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the talk about on-line porn, steamy chat rooms and
seductive cyber romances, could the Internet actually be killing
carnality? When a survey by Ogilvy Public Relations asked people
what they'd be doing if they weren't surfing the Net, 14 percent
claimed to be passing up ``intimate relations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
