<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4825 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS &LR;      12-17 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATING INCONTINENCE THE BIOFEEDBACK WAY  
 HIV FOUND IN SEMEN AFTER ANTIVIRAL COURSE  
 RISE IN TB RISK SEEN IN CERTAIN ITINERARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Treating incontinence the biofeedback way
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Urinary incontinence is a very common problem among women,
especially ones over 60. It's also very easy to treat, a new study
has reported.
</P>
<P>
   The report looked at how women can control their bladder by
learning how to contract and relax their pelvic muscles while
keeping their abdominal muscles relaxed. They then use that
knowledge to make their pelvic muscles relax and contract when they
feel an urge to urinate, giving them more control and more time to
reach a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   That biofeedback approach was compared with the more common drug
treatments used today, and biofeedback proved more effective: It
generated an 80.7 percent reduction of incontinence episodes,
compared to 68.5 percent for drugs and 39.4 percent for placebos.
And only 14 percent of those using the behavioral therapy wanted to
try a different treatment, compared to 75.5 percent of those on the
drugs or placebo.
</P>
<P>
   The tests were run by researchers at the University of Alabama,
along with ones at several medical centers in Pennsylvania, and
they involved a total of 197 women aged 55 to 92 with
bladder-control troubles. Nationwide, more than 15 million people
suffer incontinence, with the problem more pronounced among but not
limited to the elderly, and considerably more common among women
than men.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, in the current Journal of the American Medical
Association, ``has clearly established that biofeedback is an
effective and completely proven treatment for incontinence,'' said
Dr. Neil M. Resnick, chief of gerontology at Brigham and Women's
Hospital and author of an accompanying editorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think it should be an either-or with drugs and
biofeedback,'' added Resnick, who runs the nation's oldest center
to treat incontinence. ``The great news is that biofeedback is one
more proven effective therapy that we can add to our
armamentaria.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIV found in semen after antiviral course
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three-drug cocktail used to battle AIDS is so effective that
it lowers levels of HIV to the point where the virus isn't
detectable, but that doesn't mean it isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, one set of researchers found that the infection
persists at low levels in blood cells, and now another set of
scientists is reporting that HIV also can persist in semen, which
means it can be transmitted sexually. The researchers, from Thomas
Jefferson University, reached their conclusion after studying semen
and blood samples from seven men infected with HIV virus who were
on effective antiviral therapies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggests that anyone who is HIV infected should always
practice safe sex,'' said Dr. Roger J. Pomerantz, director of the
Center for Human Virology at Thomas Jefferson and an author of the
article in the current New England Journal of Medicine. ``Are they
as contagious or as transmissable as someone who's not getting the
therapy? No. It's going to be difficult to spread, but the virus is
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we know where these infected cells are, we can think
about novel approaches to ablate them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rise in TB risk seen in certain itineraries
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contagion also is a worry with tuberculosis, especially for
people who have traveled to or had visitors from a country where
the disease is widespread.
</P>
<P>
   That's the conclusion of a study published by the American Lung
Association involving 953 children in California. It found that
those who'd traveled to countries like Mexico, India, China, and
Haiti, where there is a lot of TB, were 3.9 times more likely to
have a positive skin test than children who hadn't traveled. And
children who had a household visitor from a country with a high
prevalence of TB were 2.4 times more likely to test positive.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that it's relatively easy to test for TB and to
cure it, if it is detected early.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time anyone has actually shown there's an
increased risk,'' said Dr. Mark N. Lobato, lead author of the study
and a medical officer at the Division of Tuberculosis Prevention at
the Centers for Disease Control. While the study zeroed in on
children, it applies to adults, too, he said, and it is especially
relevent these days, when ecotourists and others are visiting
exotic parts of the world and staying with local residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
