<HEADLINE>
STOCKING-STUFFERS FOR TECH HEADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This is it. Christmas is nigh. Trying to find
the right gift for a tech head can give you the vapors. Here are
suggested gifts, some expensive, some not:
</P>
<P>
   _ ETower 300, $499. This is the computer that's making the Dells
and Compaqs of the world sweat. The eTower 300 comes with a zippy
300 MHz Intel Celeron processor, 32 megs of RAM, a 3.2-gigabyte
hard drive, a 56K modem, a 24X CD-ROM drive and a bundle of
software including Windows 98. It's all packed into a sturdy,
compact metal tower that features front-mounted USB and game ports.
Monitor not included. Made by eMachines. Information: call
1-877-566-E4ME or www.e4me.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clio, $999. This is part of a new class of portable machines
with a subset of the Windows operating system _ called Windows CE _
running an abridged version of the Microsoft Office suite of
software on a small device you can easily carry. The Clio is the
beauty queen of this crowded field. You can e-mail, browse the Web,
work on spreadsheets and do a bunch of other stuff with this little
3-pound, 5-ounce wonder, powered by a battery that lasts up to 12
hours between charges. The ample screen folds back so you can
compute using the included pen. An ideal gift for someone who
spends a lot of time on the road. By Vadem. Information: call
1-888-GOVADEM or click to www.vadem.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trackman Marble Plus, $59.95. This is probably the most
comfortable mouse I've ever used, with its wide palm rest and
flowing, large thumb-run marble that sends the cursor easily across
the screen. There's a middle finger scroll wheel, so you don't have
to use those skinny on-screen scroll bars. Comes with its own
software so you can assign functions to the three buttons.
Compatible with all PCs, but not Macs. By Logitech. Information:
www.logitech.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lego Mindstorms, $199. Sure, there are tons of educational
building-block sets around. But how many of them can construct a
robot that will fetch a beer? Denmark-based Lego has entered the
digital age with these Frankensteinian building blocks that let an
inventor build and then program Lego-based block contraptions. At
the heart of the system is the RCX, a programmable microcomputer
that runs small motors, and light and touch sensors distributed
throughout the constructed toy. Information:
www.legomindstorms.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Galileo Galilei's Sidereus Nuncius, $25. Sidereus Nuncius
(``The Sidereal Messenger'') was Galileo's earth-shaking tome that
tore apart ancient assumptions of cosmology. Based on his
telescopic observations, Galileo here describes the first detailed
lunar observations and the discovery of the moons of Jupiter. This
CD-ROM contains a beautiful, detailed reproduction of the original
work, together with an English translation of the original Latin.
The CD lets you zoom in up to 600 percent to examine full-color
details of the maps and other illustrations the astronomer included
in his work. Pages are also printable. Runs on both Mac and PC. To
order: 650-470-0150 or www.octavo.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gran Turismo, $39.95. After a long commute home, there's
nothing like cranking up the Aston Martin and flooring it around a
winding race track. Gran Turismo, from Sony PlayStation, lets you
pick from 150 cars ranging from a shiny new Aston to a dowdy used
Nissan to race around a variety of winding tracks. What makes this
a stand-out console game is the realistic performance
characteristics, especially the burning rubber donuts you can
perform while waiting for the rest of the field to catch up. From
Sony.
</P>
</TEXT>
