<HEADLINE>
STATE SEEN LOW-BALLING CAR INSPECTION FEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Cellucci administration is so eager to prevent a
driver revolt against tough vehicle inspections planned for next
year that it may not be charging motorists nearly enough to cover
the estimated $215 million cost of the emissions testing contract,
service station owners warn.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have pledged that drivers would face no
more than a $5 increase in the current $15 vehicle inspection fee
when the new testing program starts. That would make Massachusetts
inspections cheaper than in states with similar programs, such as
Connecticut, where safety and emissions testing costs $45 or
Pennsylvania, which averages $43 per test.
</P>
<P>
   And service station owners, who will have to install costly
machines called dynamometers to check tailpipe exhaust under the
new program, fear that they will be hard pressed to recover their
investment unless inspection fees are higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is advocating for an outrageously high fee. I'm not.
We're advocating for a fair fee,'' said Jack W. Pierce, Jr.,
executive director of the New England Service Station and
Automotive Repair Association. ``I don't see how the Commonwealth
is $10 to $15 under everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The new emissions tests, intended to reduce summertime smog,
have been debated for years as first Gov. Weld and now Gov.
Cellucci sought to design a testing system that would not outrage
the state's 4.1 million vehicle owners. In 1995, under federal
pressure, Massachusetts almost set up 50 stand-alone testing
centers statewide, but the program was shelved after driver
complaints about such a system in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the administration wants to offer the pollution checks
through 600 to 1,200 existing inspection stations. But the state
has taken so long to devise the program that the EPA plans to
impose sanctions on the state that would delay major construction
projects, such as new power plants.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials are taking the concerns of the EPA
and station owners in stride, arguing that their cautious,
driver-sensitive approach has the best chance of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention here is to create a program that frankly places
the motorist first,'' said Assistant Environmental Affairs
Secretary John Rodman. ``We want to be fair to the repair industry,
but we think that what we're proposing is a dramatic improvement
over the original EPA proposal that put them all out of business''
in favor of the testing centers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pierce said, the state's drive to avoid significant
inspection fee increases under the new program contrasts with other
states that have upgraded emissions testing. In Connecticut, where
the state has 26 testing centers statewide, customers pay $20 for
the emissions test alone, and another $25 for safety checks.
</P>
<P>
   New York has held the inspection fee to $25 by using government
funds to reduce costs, he said, while in Pennsylvania, where
service stations set their own rates, vehicle inspections now cost
an average of $43.
</P>
<P>
   If combined safety and emissions tests here cost $20, Pierce
noted, the state and service stations would need at least a decade
before the new inspection fee money covered the original cost of
the testing contract now being negotiated with Keating Technologies
of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they can do it,'' Pierce said, admitting he didn't know
all the details of the state's inspection financing scheme.
``Reasonable people can differ.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
