<HEADLINE>
LEE, BACON CAPITAL SET SIGHTS ON A ROCKY REIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of Boston's deeper pockets are stepping into a $1 billion
investment venture in one of the market's most dicey vehicles: a
rocky real estate investment trust.
</P>
<P>
   The Thomas H. Lee Co. and Alan Leventhal's Beacon Capital
Partners Inc. are among a group of four investors that have
proposed sinking the money into Patriot American Hospitality Inc.,
a cash-strapped trust that owns and operates hotels. Leon Black's
Apollo Management and a California firm are the other investors in
the proposal that would give them about 30 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how much each partner would kick into the deal.
But the minimum investment is said to be $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is similar to some of Lee's other investments in
one aspect: It helps pump cash into an operating business
struggling with big debts run up in acquisition sprees. That was
the plan behind Lee's hugely successful investment in the
Cambridge-based software marketer Learning Co., which agreed to be
sold to Mattel Inc. this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriot proposal is a greater departure for the year-old
Beacon Capital, created by Leventhal and partner Lionel Fortin a
year ago after they closed on the $4.4 billion sale of Beacon
Properties Corp. to Sam Zell's Equity Office Properties Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon Capital raised $470 million and set out to buy midsize
office properties, particularly buildings it could renovate or
somehow remarket to add more value.
</P>
<P>
   It started with local purchases that gave the company 2 million
square feet in East Cambridge, then ventured farther from home but
bought cautiously. The company bought property in Dallas and struck
two development deals on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon Capital was widely seen as angling for an initial public
stock offering by the end of this year, though Leventhal would
never say so publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the devastating market for real estate stocks that
put Beacon Capital's IPO plans on ice has a great deal to do with
its new investment opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot American is one of four paired-share real estate
investment trusts that can both own and operate property with
special tax advantages. Though much of that advantage has since
been eliminated, Patriot had already organized and grown itself
into a substantial owner/operator of hotel properties.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot American, based in Dallas, bought seven hotel companies
in the last year and ran into big trouble doing so. It ran up debts
of $1.7 billion that come due within the next 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market had been the answer for real estate investment
trusts that needed to fund acquisitions. But prices sank this year
and new stock sales were no longer a money-raising option.
</P>
<P>
   The market was a double-whammy for companies like Patriot
American. Their stocks were already slumping and then the ensuing
cash crunch made them even less attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot stock, which traded above 28 at the start of 1998, sunk
to 6 3/8 last month. News of the investor group moved the stock
ahead by 3/4 to 7 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriot is obviously troubled and its most immediate issue is
liquidity,'' said Barry Vinocur, editor of Realty Stock Review.
``You've got a company in trouble in part due to its own making and
in part due to what's happened in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The new investment deal is not a sure thing. Though Patriot
American managers agreed to the investment in principal, details
have to be worked out and some investors are hoping a better offer
comes along.
</P>
<P>
   For Beacon Capital, the prospect of buying a real estate stock
for about a third of its 52-week high may beat the risk-reward
proposition of any real estate deal.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon Capital is loaded with money but has been tight with it
so far. By Sept. 30, it still had $192 million in cash and
extremely low leverage. Beacon has told investors it might borrow
to leverage up to 60 percent of its investments, but that figure
was just 16 percent at the end of the last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Vinocur said Beacon Capital looked hard at 10 office buildings
that were put on the market by the Equitable Cos., but walked away.
Equitable announced a deal last week to sell the buildings for $470
million in cash and debt to TrizecHahn Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal said Beacon Capital wasn't changing directions away
from direct office property investments with its pitch to Patriot
Ameirican. But he didn't sound like he was in a hurry to strike a
rash of new deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have maintained very high return objectives and we have to
be very selective,'' said Leventhal. ``We're getting in at a good
value but also where fundamentals for growth are there. There are a
handful of those opportunities out there. We don't see a lot of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
