<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-WESTERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIING THE WEST'S CHOICE SPOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Susan and Ken McCain and their three kids began planning
their ski vacation out west this year, the choice came down to two
Colorado resorts: Aspen or Vail.
</P>
<P>
   With dozens of ski areas in the West, these became finalists
largely because Susan once vacationed with friends at Vail while
Ken took a year off in his five-year college plan to ski bum at
Aspen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only ski town I can think of with a real
old-fashioned hardware store, and I worked there,'' says Ken, a
financial planner who has been back a half-dozen times since the
early '70s, when he first saw the Rockies. ``I just want the kids
to see some real ski history, and Aspen is history. It still has an
original lift tower preserved from 50 years ago in the middle of
town. It's a kind of museum piece.''
</P>
<P>
   For Susan, Vail was site of her first Western ski experience in
1981, and she still hasn't gotten over the impact of first seeing
the back bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never seen anything bigger than Bosquet (in
Pittsfield),'' she says. ``We got there at night, and the next
morning, when I took that first lift ride at Lionshead, I nearly
fainted.''
</P>
<P>
   As the snow goose flies, Aspen and Vail are just miles apart.
And despite the presence of the many resort towns that have grown
up in the Rockies since the McCains first went west _ many of them
within an easy drive from Denver _ these two remain the icons of
Western skiing.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, they are great ski areas, among the best in the
world by any measure. Which offers the better skiing is a
subjective matter. But both are steeped in ski history, even though
a skiing establishment had already taken shape, much of it in the
East, long before these two post-war areas appeared.
</P>
<P>
   As the presiding royalty of the Colorado Rockies, Aspen and Vail
are rivals with distinct personalities, and sniping between the two
is far from uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aspen used to be a great town,'' says Richard Lorne, a Beaver
Creek (Vail) regular, ``but now it's just a glitzy Hollywood East
theme park. I mean, it's OK if you want to go hang out looking for
movie stars.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the owner of a high-fashion boutique on Spring
Street, Aspen, echoed Gertrude Stein's famous line: ``Of course the
skiing's wonderful at Vail. But at Vail there's no there there.
It's just a great big generic ski area with an interstate highway
running through the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, though it might be hard for either critic to overstate
the merits of his own ski area, they are overly dismissive of the
other. Both Vail and Aspen have strong cases to make.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two, Aspen is more historic. Through most of Aspen's
century as a gold and silver mining town, Vail was a sheep pasture
just on the west slope of the Great Divide of the Rockies. In the
late 19th century, the town had nearly 20,000 residents, but it
quickly became a forgotten backwater after the silver market
collapsed and the gold standard was adopted in 1893.
</P>
<P>
   For 40 years, Aspen languished as a tiny ranching community of a
few dozen people. Then, after World War II ended, Friedl Pfeifer,
one of the 10th Mountain Division veterans who built modern
American skiing, strung the first chairlift up the face of Ajax
(the tower of which is still on display, as McCain remembers) and
the second great Western resort _ after Sun Valley, Idaho _ was
born.
</P>
<P>
   In Aspen's first two decades, the town was a funky, rawboned ski
town where ski bums from the East wore cowboy hats for the first
time since they were 8-year-olds. The simplehearted love of skiing,
plus an odd job or two, could hold body and soul together for a
season of about 160 days on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Aspen is still charming in its way, and the old Victorian
burnish still glows through an oft-lamented modern, huge-money
glitz that has always threatened the simple community spirit at
Aspen's center.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the modern day ski bum has a hard time making
ends meet at either Aspen or Vail, and that most live well outside
of town and usually work two jobs to support a dwindling number of
skiing days.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, Aspen is getting almost offensively star-studded,
though the town is fighting growth almost as hard as it did in the
days when Hunter S. Thompson ran for sheriff on a platform of
closing Highway 82 to keep the tourists out.
</P>
<P>
   But what has only improved at Aspen is its skiing, largely
because of increased terrain. Each of four ski areas has its
distinct flavor, and at least one _ Buttermilk _ is perennially
underrated so that you often can have the place to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Snowmass, largest of the four areas, has a somewhat
undistinguished village area (compared to downtown Aspen) but some
of the finest skiing anywhere, ranging from the ultimate of all
cruising areas, Big Burn, to the no-kidding experts-only area, The
Cirque. Were Snowmass the only mountain offering at Aspen, it would
be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Aspen Highlands, while once a rawboned steep 'n' deep area used
mainly by local powder hounds, is Aspen's latest acquisition and
provides the greatest challenge, with a number of precipitous
3-mile runs down the length of its nearly 4,000-foot vertical. With
only about 400 acres, the Highlands still has the greatest drop of
the Aspens.
</P>
<P>
   Ajax _ or Aspen Mountain itself _ has the character that once
drew the great skiers of the world to it. With lots of steep,
powdery, natural bump runs that give you 3 miles of skiing without
stopping, Ajax is noted for its expert terrain, without much for
lower-level skiers. Greatest drawback is that those lower-level
skiers add to the horrific crowds that build on this 600-acre
mountain (compared with the 2,100 of Snowmass).
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Aspen may not have much of that funky mining-camp feel
of the old days, as swishy high couture chains have ousted the
local shops, but it is still untouchable in ski country for its
dining and other apres-ski life. And for the celebrity-struck,
there's nothing close.
</P>
<P>
   Though Vail is _ as Aspen's diehard touters have it _ ``new'' to
the game (only 36 years old) and has a feel of neo-Tyrolean about
it, it is also true that many Europeans who ski at Vail _ including
ski racers who have seen everything _ call it their favorite
resort.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived by Pete Seibert (another 10th Mountain veteran) as a
massive interconnect of intermediate slopes and vast back bowls,
Vail was built not as a reshod mining town but as a modern,
skier-friendly village for _ as Seibert envisioned _ the masses of
new skiers coming in the '60s and '70s. That was its purpose and
that is why Vail often tops the national polls as the No. 1
American ski area.
</P>
<P>
   While Vail is well-known and impressive in its own right, the
new action has been out at Beaver Creek, where the luxury resort
town (about 20 minutes west of Vail) has finally been completed.
Beaver Creek _ now home of one of the world's great downhill runs _
is a blend of fabulous skiing, most of it blue-cruisy, but with
some truly challenging in the Birds of Prey runs.
</P>
<P>
   Also new in the Vail lineup is Arrowhead, a longtime local area
that stretches the real estate further west and offers largely
low-end cruising terrain and an out-of-the-mainstream feel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the Alpine World Championships, the off-year skiing
Olympics, were held in Vail, and this winter, a decade later,
they're back. Starting with Hermann ``The Harmannator'' Maier,
Olympic gold medalist from Nagano, to Italy's gold-winning Deborah
Compagnoni, to an entire lineup of young US skiers determined to
become known at these hometown games, the Vail worlds are a
precursor to the 2002 Olympic Games to be held at Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   With 400 athletes of the World Cup in town and the thousands of
attendant race coaches, officials, and fans, the first two weeks in
February may not be the best vacation planning for Vail. But for
true ski racing fans, it will be a spectacle as it was a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the United States team is missing Tommy Moe, AJ Kitt, and
Kyle Rassmussen, all of whom retired, and Picabo Street, who
injured her knee. And Alberto Tomba has also hung them up. But
there's plenty to watch for race fans, who will find the access to
the aciton extremely easy. Like everything else done at Vail since
its conception in 1967, the racing is staged with skiers in mind _
by skiers, for skiers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
