<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FOOLING: UMASS NOW ALL BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ There was plenty of reason to celebrate.
The University of Massachusetts had beaten Northwestern (La.) State
in Saturday's NCAA Division 1-AA semifinal, ensuring the second
trip to the national championship game in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the euphoria was put on hold. Instead, the mood in the
locker room was quite subdued. Businesslike. Coach Mark Whipple
surveyed the room and could not have been more pleased: The
Minutemen, who rebounded from last season's 2-9 campaign to earn a
postseason berth for the first time since 1990, showed once again
they were quick learners.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is new to the current Minutemen, who have staged
arguably the most successful season in the program's history. No
one could have held it against any of them for losing their
emotions a few times. Instead, they responded as if they had been
there before, knowing that the big prize still lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were like, `All right, let's get drug-tested, get on the
bus and charter home, and get rested because we have a big game
next week,' '' said Whipple. He and the 11th-seeded Minutemen
(11-3) arrived in Chattanooga Wednesday night in preparation for
Saturday's 2 p.m. game against top-ranked, top-seeded Georgia
Southern (14-0).
</P>
<P>
   ``After (last Saturday's) game, they were not that euphoric,
like they were after the McNeese win,'' said Whipple, referring to
the Minutemen's first-round win at sixth-seeded McNeese State, the
school's first playoff victory in 10 years. ``I'm happy about that.
They want to save the celebration for another week.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week marked the second time Whipple had taken a program to
a national semifinal. His 1992 University of New Haven team went
unbeaten through the Division 2 semifinals, where it lost at
Jacksonville (Ala.) State, 46-35.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple said one reason that team did not advance to the final
was that it faced an intangiable this season's team had already
overcome once it reached the semifinal round: winning a playoff
game in a hostile road environment _ particularly one in the South.
</P>
<P>
   The farthest the 1992 New Haven team had traveled all year was
Shepherdstown, W.Va., to play Shepherd College in its
regular-season finale. Against Jacksonville State, the Chargers
played before a partisan crowd of 5,084 and trailed, 21-14, then
rallied to take a 35-34 lead with 5:34 left in the game. But
Jacksonville State came up with two touchdown runs in the final
4:35 for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team is better prepared to win a national
championship than that New Haven team that went to Alabama,'' said
Whipple. ``That was the significance of the McNeese State win. We
learned a lot, and that helped last week, when we beat Northwestern
State.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minutemen are the only squad in the 16-team playoff field to
win twice on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveling to Alabama was new and different (for New Haven),''
said Whipple. ``It was the first time we had traveled that far.
Jacksonville State was a wishbone team that ended up winning the
game because it played great defense. Georgia Southern is a similar
team. The only saving grace is that the game is in Chattanooga and
not at Georgia Southern.''
</P>
<P>
   With his team's attitude intact, Whipple said he will spend the
week talking about the importance of playing a solid game from
start to finish. That will be key against Georgia Southern, which
has scored 170 first-quarter points and 150 fourth-quarter points
this season (611 total). GSU's opponents have scored a total of 308
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we will have a great week of practice,'' said
Whipple. ``We are still searching for that one great game. Not so
much a perfect game, but an excellent game. We played a great
second half last week, but we haven't done so from the start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
