<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUMPS OF COAL FROM THE DUKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't you just love those ``personal'' mimeographed Christmas
letters that arrive in the mail at this time of year? It's usually
some boring cousin or former friend too lazy to send a fruitcake
and delusional enough to think you care what happened to them in
the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda is off at college, studying liberal arts (translation:
she's costing us $30 grand a year and can't pick a major). Chad is
traveling abroad (can't get a job). Jan is getting into needlepoint
(we're sleeping in separate bedrooms), and the cats are busy
tearing up the carpet in our new screened-in porch (I'd like to
drown 'em).
</P>
<P>
   Well, brace yourselves, Red Sox season ticket-holders, because
Dan Duquette's annual Christmas letter is in the mail, and this
year's edition is a real knee-slapper. A friend picked it up early
on the Sox web site (remember that the Duke says the Sox web site
and his radio show are the two best ways to keep abreast of ball
club news).
</P>
<P>
   The missive gets off to a rollicking start . . .
</P>
<P>
   Our purpose in this letter is to communicate directly with you,
our loyal and valued customers.
</P>
<P>
   (Pass the shovels, it's gonna get deep in here.)
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra, who demonstrated his sincere appreciation for
all Red Sox fans' loyalty and support during a memorable moment
after our final game, had another outstanding year to secure his
name among baseball's consistent elite.
</P>
<P>
   (I drafted Nomie and signed him. He's my guy and he's a team
player, unlike that fat slob Mo Vaughn.)
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox appreciate Mo's contribution during his years with
the organization and recognize the significance of his loss.
However, our fans continue to indicate to us that they have a clear
understanding of the strong effort we made to sign Mo.
</P>
<P>
   (I hire only people who agree with me and my mail is screened
and I have no contact with real Sox fans, so I don't know what they
are thinking. But the people here in my office tell me you all
understand why we let Mo go.)
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, we remind our fans not to lose sight of the fact
that virtually our entire club is returning next year.
</P>
<P>
   (Sure, we lost half of our offense, but we've still got Reggie
Jefferson and Troy O'Leary.)
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams has remarked many times since the end of last
season about how pleasantly surprised he was with the successful
combination of young catchers Jason Varitek and Scott Hatteberg.
</P>
<P>
   (Hey, we know these guys are Triple A, but we figure we can fool
you suckers with minor league catching for another year.)
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis . . . will rejoin the successful core of Red Sox
outfielders including Troy O'Leary, Damon Buford, Darren Bragg and
Troy O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   (Reminds you of Rice, Lynn, Evans, and Yaz, doesn't it?)
</P>
<P>
   Nixon has risen through the Red Sox minor league system and has
given Red Sox fans a glimpse of his undeniable ability . . .
</P>
<P>
   (I couldn't think of anything to say about Trot, so why not try
and fool the fans by citing his ``undeniable ability''?)
</P>
<P>
   Newly-acquired infielder Jose Offerman wil be a welcome addition
with his speed, defense at first or second base, and his bat.
</P>
<P>
   (I overpaid this guy by $6 million, and his defense reminds me
of Dick Stuart, but Stat Man likes him.)
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, because of the strength and depth of our minor
league system, we were able to acquire Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   (I know that's a whopper, but these lemming fans will probably
buy it.)
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of John Harrington and the entire Boston Red Sox
organization, I would like to express our sincere gratitude to you
for your loyalty, a loyalty that we do not take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   (Suckers!)
</P>
<P>
   The unfortunate reality of our ticket price increase this year
is a product of our shared desire to be competitive in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   (We don't have to pay Mo this year, we didn't sign any big free
agents, we gouged you with a 15 percent hike, we kicked the peanut
vendors off the streets, but we ``desire'' to be competitive.
Hahahaha.)
</P>
<P>
   All of us here at Fenway Park wish you and your family a happy
and safe holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   (Here's a lump of coal for your red stocking . . . from the Red
Sox.)
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
