<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-GORY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     12-17 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-GORY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 YARMOUTHPORT, Mass.: ... to yours!  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bits of assimilated Gorey-iana:
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Chicago, where his father worked as a reporter for
the Hearst newspapers, covering what Gorey recalls as the crime
beat. An only child, he rarely saw his father in the years before
his parents divorced, when Gorey was 11. The couple remarried 16
years later. In between, Gorey's father took up with a nightclub
singer named Corrina Mura, best remembered as the singer in
``Casablanca'' who rouses Rick's patrons to sing ``La
Marseillaise.''
</P>
<P>
   A bookish child, Gorey read all of Victor Hugo by age 8
(something he would not do today ``on threat of torture,'' Gorey
snickers) and began to draw semiseriously when he was still in
diapers. Children's literature and illustrating were and are
consuming passions of his. Later these obsessions were augmented by
Gorey's great love for the ballet, for movies, and most notably for
the theater, the medium in which he most often collaborates these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Richards, a Cape-based actor and community theater veteran,
has worked closely with Gorey in 10 local productions since 1987.
Written and directed by Gorey himself, the plays and puppet shows
are, like the rest of the artist's oeuvre, quirky, surrealistic,
hilarious, and often maddeningly inaccessible.
</P>
<P>
   Working with Gorey is ``not like any theater I've ever done,''
says Richards. ``The writing is so precise and complex, you need to
know what you're doing. But they're all works in progress, too.
What we end up doing is not necessarily what Edward has drawn up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorey's career took comparable swerves. After a stint in the
army, he matriculated at Harvard in 1946, where he fell in with a
group of artists, writers, and poets that included Adrienne Rich,
Donald Hall, Robert Bly, and Frank O'Hara, with whom Gorey roomed.
The group's center of intellectual energy was the Poet's Theater in
Cambridge, to which Gorey also gravitated. Other than publishing
some drawings in the Harvard Lampoon, however, Gorey gave few
indications that he would make himself a career as a professional
artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to have my own bookstore, until I worked in one,'' he
recalls. ``Then I thought I'd be a librarian, until I met some
crazy ones. I hoped to get into publishing, but at 28 my parents
were still helping me out. Which wasn't good at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorey moved to New York in the early '50s, his home _ aside from
extended stays on the Cape _ for the next two decades. Staff jobs
at Doubleday and Bobbs Merrill supplemented income from his book
jackets and illustrations. Gorey's first book, ``The Unstrung
Harp,'' appeared in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one had seen anything quite like it, certainly not from a
contemporary artist. Gorey's perverse, Edwardian-inspired
penmanship and absurdist wit captured the fancy of admirers like
The New Yorker's Edmund Wilson. In later years, as Gorey withdrew
from the Manhattan demimonde, his work achieved more mainstream
recognition. He won a 1978 Tony award for costume design on
``Dracula,'' the long-running Broadway hit. Posters he designed for
the New York City Ballet and New York City Opera, along with the
opening sequence for PBS's ``Mystery!'' series, made Gorey's work
instantly familiar to millions of new fans.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all and even to this day, Gorey self-published small
batches of exquisite books like ``The Doubtful Guest'' and ``The
Curious Sofa,'' a pornographic romp (``Still later Gerald did a
terrible thing to Elsie with a saucepan'') that has become a
collectors' item. Early Gorey books that sold new for 50 cents now
trade for $750 or more. A major Gorey drawing fetches $5,000 to
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Andreas Brown, owner of the Gotham Book Mart in Manhattan, has
played a pivotal role in furthering Gorey's career, both
commercially and aesthetically. Brown has mounted exhibitions of
Gorey's drawings, arranged for Gorey's earliest work to be reissued
in anthology form and even persuaded Samuel Beckett, who became a
huge fan of the artist's, to publish two texts accompanied by Gorey
illustration.
</P>
<P>
   Says Brown, ``Edward is as uncommercial as any creative person
I've ever known. You have to nudge him, but you must not nudge him
too aggressively. He'd come to his own openings, but only
reluctantly. He never made a fuss, he just tolerated us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorey is also hard to categorize, Brown points out. His books
are neither kids' books nor adult books nor books of cartoons, at
least in the conventional sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose his aesthetic soulmate is someone like Edward
Lear,'' says Brown. ``But there are no classic 19th-century
illustrators or contemporary graphic artists quite like Edward. He
truly is a unique and peculiar genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he were ever accused of being too macabre _ too
downbeat _ for the mainstream, Gorey shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he replies, ``nobody ever quite said that. From the
beginning, though, everyone thought I'd be much more popular than I
am. Publishers expected to do much better with my books than they
did. I can't explain it. I've never even tried to do anything but
what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for cult worship, lately manifested by multiple Gorey Web
sites and such, Gorey (who doesn't even own a computer) expresses
both bafflement and dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little more of it than I care to have,'' he says
with a deep sigh. ``When I think of other things that attain cult
status, they strike me as somewhat feebleminded. I mean, I suppose
it's better being a cult object than nothing at all. But I don't
see how anyone has time to be really famous. I might get people
dropping by who are slightly'' _ he raises one eyebrow _
``unhinged.''
</P>
<P>
   He proposes continuing the conversation over lunch. Climbing
into Gorey's black VW, the one parked outside with the OGDRED
vanity plate (part of one of Gorey's anagram pen names), you make
your way to Jack's Outback, a local bistro where Gorey takes
sustenance _ nutritional and social _ virtually every day.
</P>
<P>
   On the counter rests a large bowl filled with bills and coins.
Above it a sign reads, ``Pray Forget Not the Widows and Orphans.''
The illustration is by Gorey. You peruse the day's menu, scrawled
upon the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``No fruitcake?'' you ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fruitcake?'' says Gorey in mock disbelief. ``My mother used to
spend entire summers making fruitcake. She wrapped them in brandied
cloth. I always gave them away. I could never bear to say, `Mother,
I hate fruitcake.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He scribbles down his lunch order. ``Actrally, someone gave me
one a few years ago,'' he says, eyes twinkling. ``I ate it. It
wasn't bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyeux Noel!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
