<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING HOW TO E-TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I never thought: When I grow up, I want to have my own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, when I was a girl, the idea of people sitting at home
watching television was just a dream in some inventor's mind and
the closest I ever got to a conference call was when the party who
shared our line picked up the phone while I was talking.
</P>
<P>
   But here I am, on the cusp of the millennium, the proud owner of
a Web page of my very own. For two months now, I've been leading a
parallel existence in cyberspace, meeting every week with about 200
visitors, corresponding with them through e-mail, entering into
what at times feels like a ghostly shadow life.
</P>
<P>
   My correspondence with my Web site guests bears little
resemblance to letters from readers that I can hold in my hand,
each of them with a unique style of writing and choice of paper,
each clearly marked with a return address. My brain is used to
visualizing the writer of a real letter. I picture a person. I
position her on my map of the world. I take her thoughts into my
mind. When I've finished with a pile of snail mail, it feels like
having eaten a satisfying meal.
</P>
<P>
   It may be gone, but it's made a lasting impression.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, it was strange to watch all traces of my first 25
e-mails disappear with the press of a button. The words on the
screen, at least in this early stage, felt totally disembodied. The
lack of ordinary signifiers left me feeling disoriented. Are Pat,
Chris, and Terry male or female? Where in the world is
blank.net(at)gobbledygook? And though I'm able to face a stack of
regular mail calmly, I still feel an enormous pressure to answer my
e-mails at one sitting. I have to get through them before another
batch of messages arrive and overwhelm me.
</P>
<P>
   So I did not savor. I did not reflect. I did not carefully
compose my replies. I skimmed. I dashed something off. I deleted.
And when I was done, there was nothing, not even a memory
differentiating one message from the other. When I finished with my
task, it felt like having eaten a meal while watching a video. The
only reason I knew I'd done it was because everything on my plate
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   I've since discovered there are mailboxes in cyberspace for
saving messages. I've printed out a few I wanted to save. I've come
to appreciate that I have readers in Louisiana and Alaska and
California, some of whom read me in their local papers, others who
receive weekly copies of my column from their moms. People send
e-mails who would never write because once you arrive at my site,
it's so sinfully easy to click on my address.
</P>
<P>
   I'm blessed. The folks who visit my site are mostly trying to be
helpful _ sending me their favorite soy recipes, sharing the
information that delphi.com offers free forum space so that family
members all over the country can keep in touch via the Internet,
passing along inspirational stories, expressing their concern that
it may not be safe to make myself so accessible. The dearest insist
that I need not reply. Others ask me questions about how I got rid
of my pantry moths or where my husband and I stayed during our
visit to the Cinque Terre. Our exchange is a quick Q &AMP; A, a truly
interactive process.
</P>
<P>
   With a difference, though. Nobody beats around the bush on
e-mail. They skip the niceties. They give it to you straight.
</P>
<P>
   Take this comment on how I look in my Web site photos. ``There's
something out of proportion about your eyeglasses,'' writes someone
who calls herself krog. ``They're a little too Sally Jesse
Raphael.'' Doesn't SJR's signature look involve red glasses? Mine
are tortoiseshell and they look fine. Well, I used to think they
did. Now I'm not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Here's more e-talk. ``By the way, you look much better than one
would think from reading your column.'' Now that's a statement with
the power to stop me cold. Do I write like a homely person? Do I
sound like someone whose soul has been seared by the pain of not
being pretty enough? If I were to construe that comment as a
compliment (no easy task), I could conclude that I can't be
mistaken in print for a dumb beauty pageant contestant, but why
insult beautiful women?
</P>
<P>
   Now that we're so interactive, I can ask you to help.
</P>
<P>
   What in the world did she mean?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net(tilde)weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
