<HEADER>
A4854 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-LOST-BOS &LR;      12-17 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LOST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CALM LOOK AT A HARROWING DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
LOST AT SEA 
An American Tragedy 
By Patrick Dillon 
Dial Press, 264 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Feb. 14, 1983, two crabbing vessels capsized and sank, with
the loss of all hands, off the Aleutian Islands _ within hours of
leaving port and almost certainly within a few miles of each other.
The winds were light and the seas calm, for those waters, but there
had been no distress calls, no maydays.
</P>
<P>
   That the Americus and the Altair were sister ships from the same
port, Anacortes, Wash., and many of the 14 men in the two crews
were friends from boyhood, would have marked it as a devastating
tragedy for that close-knit community.
</P>
<P>
   But two other Alaskan crabbers had already been lost that
season; another was to go down just two weeks later; and by the
time the winter crabbing season closed, eight vessels had capsized
and sunk, with the loss of 21 crewmen.
</P>
<P>
   As West Coast journalist Patrick Dillon explored the story of
the Americus and the Altair, it became clear to him that the fatal
combination of perilous Arctic waters, a short and frenzied
crabbing season, and the absence of safety regulations had created
the conditions for disaster and death.
</P>
<P>
   For New England readers, ``Lost at Sea'' will prompt comparison
with Sebastian Junger's best-selling ``The Perfect Storm.''
Junger's yarn had the advantage of a memorable storm, the Halloween
``No-Name'' northeaster of October 1991, whose brunt had also been
felt along the New England coast, and of the descriptions of the
sea's fury in radio transmissions from the lost swordfisher Andrea
Gail and ships that survived the storm.
</P>
<P>
   There are wrenching moments in ``Lost at Sea,'' as when the
crewmen on two other Anacortes crabbers, standing by the capsized
hull of the Americus, watch it sink with the knowledge that the
bodies of their friends are entombed within it.
</P>
<P>
   But Dillon is not trying to compete with Junger, for his story
focuses on the investigation to determine why the two vessels had
been lost _ and the ensuing effort to pass safety legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The very way that the crab fisheries operated created the
conditions for disaster. The 80- to 100-foot vessels would gather
at Dutch Harbor in the Aleutians, carrying extra fuel from their
home ports (where it was cheaper). After offloading the extra fuel,
they would load some 200 700-pound crab pots and head for the
fishing grounds off the Pribilof Islands, set the pots, return for
a second load _ and then head off to drop these and pull the first
drop when the season officially opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a season these vessels were participating in.''
writes Dillon, ``it was a short-term frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Americus and the Altair were state-of-the-art vessels
with experienced crews; they were apparently capable of operating
safely even in extreme conditions. Their designer was so confident
of their seaworthiness that he speculated that the Americus and
Altair must have collided.
</P>
<P>
   But a two-year investigation by the Coast Guard and National
Transportation Safety Board determined that because of the placing
of additional fishing gear on the decks, and the practice of
offloading fuel and then filling crab tanks with seawater, the
vessels were inherently unstable. The result, concluded the
principal investigator, a professor of mechanical engineering, was
``synchronous rolling,'' a series of short, sharp heels from which
the vessel does not recover. ``Even in small seas,'' he said, it
would have taken ``only a few rolls'' for the overloaded crabbers
to capsize.
</P>
<P>
   And worse, the skippers were unaware of the consequences of the
routine loading and tanking practices they followed. ``The captains
and crews,'' writes Dillon, ``sailed out into the Bering Sea that
last time, as they had always done, in the comfort of complete
ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it took a grass-roots lobbying campaign by a
Washington insider _ a diplomat's wife whose son had been lost in
the sinking of another crabber _ and the efforts of Massachusetts
Congressman Gerry Studds to secure passage of safety legislation.
</P>
<P>
   This is an understated book, long on the findings of
investigators and short on the emotions of survivors. But in a
vividly written epilogue, Dillon recounts his experiences as a
crewman on a crabber for four weeks during the 1995 winter season.
</P>
<P>
   As they reached open water, Dillon writes, ``the seas got
bigger, and I noticed that an overtone of violence and anger began
to pervade my crewmates as they worked. . . . Coils of line and
links of chain were slammed about, curses came more readily, and
taunts became harsher. The crew, it seemed, was working itself into
a state of violent equilibrium with the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was, Dillon writes, ``the one more experience'' he felt
it necessary to have in order to understand the tragedy of the
Americus and the Altair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
