<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4862 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-SHRINKING-BOS &LR;      12-17 1767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SHRINKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPERS, LOCAL TV FIND AUDIENCE SHRINKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ AND DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a 1993 article in Wired magazine, ``Jurassic Park''
author Michael Crichton declared himself an expert on dinosaurs and
predicted another extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my mind, it is likely that what we now understand as the
mass media will be gone within 10 years,'' proclaimed Crichton.
``Vanished without a trace.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most prophecies, Crichton's pronouncement contained a
heaping dose of exaggeration, but it also contained a grain of
truth, especially for two pillars of the mass media: newspapers and
local television newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither medium is likely to disappear, but many of their readers
and viewers have, suggesting that newspapers and TV newscasts are
confronting one of the starkest challenges in their history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local TV news viewership is declining nationally, and the same
thing is true of network news and newspapers,'' said Tom
Rosenstiel, vice chairman of the Project for Excellence in
Journalism. ``People are less interested in the news as journalists
define it because they have more power to define the news for
themselves. They can troll Web sites, look for information on their
hobbies, or check out the ballgame scores on line as soon as they
end.''
</P>
<P>
   The fallout in the Boston area is suggested by some telling
numbers. Since the 1990s began, The Boston Globe's weekday
circulation has decreased by about 50,000, roughly 10 percent,
while the Boston Herald's daily circulation has dropped by about
87,000 copies, almost 25 percent. The Patriot Ledger in Quincy has
lost more than 15 percent. According to a 1998 survey of the top 50
markets by Scarborough Research, the Boston area ranked second with
69 percent of adults regularly reading a daily paper. That sounds
impressive, but as recently as 1994, the number was 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is no rosier on the TV side. Last month, viewership
of the three leading Boston newscasts dropped 50,000 households
from the levels of the previous year. But that was nothing compared
with the losses local stations have sustained over the long term.
When measured against 20 years ago, the combined audiences for the
11 p.m. newscasts of the three top news stations _ WCVB-Ch. 5,
WHDH-Ch. 7, and WBZ-Ch. 4 _ are down 190,000 viewers, about 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   So where have all the faithful readers of newspapers and
watchers of the TV newscasts gone? To sleep, to cyberspace, to
cable TV, or perhaps they're just stuck in Boston traffic.
Lifestyle changes and the ``time famine'' afflicting dual-earner
households are key factors, as is the inescapable fact that the
public stage holds fewer colorful newsmakers and less-compelling
issues nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Gone from the local political scene are larger-than-life
figures, from Kevin White to William M. Bulger, who brought eyes to
the TV screen and the front page. Vanished with them are the kind
of momentous battles _ over busing, taxes, and social spending _
that galvanize public interest.
</P>
<P>
   Waning interest in news ``has to do with the economic and
political community having smoothed out the bumpy ride that used to
bring politics into sharp relief,'' said political consultant Lou
DiNatale.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Chervinsky, who polls for the Globe and Channel 4, said
his surveys show a steady decline of public interest in subjects
like politics. ``People spend less time with the newspaper and TV
news because, ultimately, people are less concerned with issues
that do not directly affect them,'' said Chervinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to cherry-pick topics of personal interest is one
reason analysts say the news-on-demand nature of the Internet and
such cable channels as CNN and New England Cable News has made them
increasingly strong rivals to newspapers and TV newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   The volume of Internet traffic doubles every 100 days, with an
estimated 5 million to 7 million more households going on line each
year. While there is conflicting data as to whether that cuts down
on reading of newspapers and viewing of newscasts, media executives
in Boston _ a city that Newsweek magazine has dubbed one of the
world's 10 most cyber-savvy cities _ are already drawing
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past two years, there's been a sea change in how
people get their information,'' said WCVB-Ch. 5 news director Candy
Altman. ``Now, if you're at work and you want to know something,
you log on to any one of a number of sites. News is now a
24-hour-a-day, seven-days-a-week available resource for people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``During the day, people are exposed to so much more information
than they used to be: on line at home and at work, radio news,
cable news,'' said media consultant Marty Sender. ``By 11 o'clock,
what is there left to say?''
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers of the 11 p.m. newscasts have also migrated to the
two 10 p.m. newscasts in Boston, on WLVI-Ch. 56 and WFXT-Ch. 25,
though analysts believe many have also tuned out newscasts in favor
of syndicated reruns of shows like ``Friends'' and ``Frasier'' or
original entertainment programs on cable. In addition, network
prime-time audiences _ on which local affiliates rely for lead-in
audiences for newscasts _ are off 9 percent this season.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research Inc. has concluded that ``consumers'
dependence on TV, newspapers, and radio wanes as time on line
increases.'' As an example, one survey found that after spending
several years on line, consumers tend to choose the Internet over
newspapers as a source for stock quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, traditional news organizations are adapting to
these realities. Altman notes that many Internet ``hits'' during
major news events come from readers visiting TV-run Web sites such
as Channel 5's, and says newscast audience measurements must take
that added audience into account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspapers are very aggressive in having a very strong
position on line,'' for both ``offensive and defensive'' reasons,
said Kevin Lavalla, managing director of newspaper publishing at
the Veronis, Suhler &AMP; Associates investment banking firm. Given the
rapid proliferation of newspaper Web sites, he added, the newspaper
company of the future may produce a product that is part electronic
and part newsprint.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe's Web site, for example, was launched about
three years ago. It has attracted 60 on-line partners and averages
between 20 and 25 million page views per month, and almost 2
million people say they visit the site at least once a month.
Signficantly, the majority of that cyber-traffic comes during
business hours on Monday through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One factor working in favor of the on-demand media, which can be
accessed at work, is the time crunch. A major study released by the
Newspaper Association of America _ called ``So Many Choices, So
Little Time'' _ found that nearly half of those who didn't read a
daily paper complained of a shortage of free time.
</P>
<P>
   When UMass journalism professor Ralph Whitehead started
commuting from Western Massachusetts to Boston a quarter-century
ago, he didn't hit serious traffic until Concord. Now the
bottlenecks start near Gardner. ``A.M. commuting times are a big
competition to the morning newspaper,'' said Whitehead. One
possible indicator: During this decade in which Boston's dailies
have lost circulation, the morning-drive audience of WBUR-FM (90.9)
has increased by about 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of specialized news, another threat to the old media
order is viewer fragmentation caused by the niche programming
available on cable (an option that seems more attractive this year,
with a network prime-time lineup widely viewed as dismal). Among
the top 10 TV markets in the country, Boston has the highest
percentage of cable subscribers (79 percent).
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Jim Thistle, the director of broadcast journalism
at Boston University and a news director at channels 5 and 7 in the
1970s and early 1980s. ``On the day Kenneth Starr was in the
Capitol testifying, the networks carried his opening statement, but
when the congressmen started to ask their questions, the networks
fled,'' said Thistle. ``So I went right over to MSNBC,'' an
all-news cable network.
</P>
<P>
   So many viewers are choosing the cable option, and the audience
for local news has shrunk so drastically, that Boston news stations
can now win the ratings race with far fewer viewers. ``It's a whole
different ballgame,'' said Thistle. ``You're in a bloody
competition for an eroding audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The erosion in Boston's newspaper audience is in line with
long-term trends afflicting much of the industry. According to
statistics compiled by Veronis, Suhler &AMP; Associates, total national
weekday circulation plunged from 63.1 million in 1984 to 56.7
million in 1997. According to the newspaper association, 67 percent
of Americans regularly read a daily newspaper in 1977. Twenty years
later, that figure had fallen to 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trends are sobering,'' declared the association's survey.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of those 65 or older are regular newspaper
readers, as opposed to 36 percent of those between 18 and 34. While
58 percent of those with incomes over $50,000 are regular readers,
that number drops to 41 percent of those earning less than $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lavalla, the investment banker, said the devoted newspaper
reader fits a familiar lifestyle pattern: When you marry, buy a
home, and send your children to the local schools, ``suddenly,
you're very interested in your community. You need to read the
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   But changes in population patterns mean that increasing numbers
of Boston-area residents do not have the local newspaper habit. A
new economic report by MassINC and the Teresa and H. John Heinz III
Foundation shows that between 1990 and 1997, 220,000 more
Massachusetts residents left the state than came here. At the same
time, the state has seen an influx of roughly 112,000 immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our population is changing. Massachusetts really is becoming a
very different state,'' said Tripp Jones, executive director of
MassInc. ``The repercussions of this change are certainly
far-reaching.'' And they may well extend to news habits.
</P>
<P>
   Even among longtime residents, those habits are changing. John
Gorman, who runs the Opinion Dynamics polling firm, once read four
daily papers and made sure his office was filled with 10 to 15
copies of the Globe. Today, he consumes far less newsprint and
keeps only 2 copies of the Globe at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here has a Web browser,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
