<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-MANURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOVELING FRESH MANURE NOW MAY SAVE A LOAD OF WORK LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now is the time to shovel out the barn, load up the manure pile,
and head for the garden!
</P>
<P>
   Don't have a barn? Or a manure pile? Well, excepting my
well-dogged back yard, neither do I, but I do have a list of
sources of free manure.
</P>
<P>
   There's a turkey farm with a bodacious pile (and some truly
noisy and nervous feathered neighbors), a miniature horse farm (and
all that that would seem to entail), and a couple in Carver with
some horses and assorted other farm animals that like to stand
around and watch, wide-eyed, as I heave shovelsful of barn
sweepings into the back of my pickup.
</P>
<P>
   So I have plenty of fresh manure, and you can, too, simply by
keeping your eyes open when you travel, perhaps placing a notice in
the local paper's classified ads or on a well-placed bulletin
board. You'll need a truck or a car you really don't care about, a
shovel, maybe plastic containers (if you are lucky enough to find
some cows).
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the source, this is all ``hot'' manure, meaning it has
not broken down, or composted, and cannot be placed on top of or
next to living plants. It can be composted in a bin or pile for a
month or more, but I prefer to spread it directly on barren plots
in so-called sheet composting. That's what I'll be doing this
month. I'll mix it with wood ashes and some not fully composted
plant material and layer it on several inches thick, mostly in the
veggie garden and some in the front rose garden (though not right
up against the plants). After two months, it is safe to plant seeds
and seedlings, and for dormant perennials to re-emerge because the
manure has rotted enough.
</P>
<P>
   Along with composted plant material, nothing is better than
manure for improving the soil, and hence the garden, and although I
get to shovel the manure three times (into and out of the truck and
then onto the beds), the real work doesn't start until Steve's
Special Manure Mix (yum) is down.
</P>
<P>
   That's when a host of bacteria and fungi and earthworms have at
it. The bacteria, in breaking down the material, can consume some
of the nitrogen that plants need. That's not a problem during cold
weather, when plants are dormant or not present at all. Because
horse manure is more wood chips than manure, and the larger chips
take longer to break down, nitrogen may remain in short supply, and
I will add chemical fertilizer high in nitrogen early next growing
season.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the manure-compost mix will be adding, not tying up,
nitrogen. While some of that nitrogen comes from the manure and
compost, conditions also become ripe for azotobacter bacteria,
which ``fixes'' nitrogen from the air.
</P>
<P>
   Nitrogen is one of the three primary nutrients. Phosphorus and
potassium are the others. Chemical fertilizers are marked with
N-P-K numbers, the letters being the chemical symbols for those
elements. A 10-10-10 fertilizer has 10 parts of nitrogen and enough
phosphorus and potassium to make 10 parts each of phosphate and
potash, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Plants need another 13 elements, probably more, to grow,
including calcium, magnesium, and sulfur, which are called
secondary elements; carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen; and the
micronutrients iron, manganese, boron, molybdenum, copper, zinc,
and chlorine. Building the soil with manures and composts and other
materials is the way to ensure a good mix of everything.
</P>
<P>
   Plant biochemistry is complex (and boring, my wife says), but a
few of the uses of these chemicals are: nitrogen helps to form
amino acids, which are used in forming cell protoplasm; nitrogen
and manganese are part of the chlorophyll molecule, necessary for
photosynthesis; phosphorus stimulates early root formation and
growth; potassium is important in plant metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   As my manure and compost decomposes, carbohydrates and proteins
break down and release nutrients such as nitrogen, sulfur, and
phosphorus. Fats, waxes, and resins, more resistant to breaking
down, provide sulfur and phosphorus. And lignin, very resistant to
rotting, helps form humus, the colloidal remains of organic matter.
This crumbly stuff, stuck together, helps texture the soil, leaven
the battering effect of rain, buffer soil pH, and retain moisture
and nutrients in solution.
</P>
<P>
   Another crumbly, stuck-together material is worm castings. Worms
eat organic matter, transforming the nutrients into forms that are
more available to plants. The castings also perform some of the
physical functions of humus. Worms also produce enzymes that enable
bacteria to work more efficiently. Worms are good, and I am blessed
with a billion or so.
</P>
<P>
   Other processes undertaken by soil organisms include
ammonification, in which ammonium is released, providing nitrogen
in a form useful to plants, and nitrification, which converts some
ammonium to nitrates, also useful. Organisms also convert sulfur in
complex organic forms into sulfates, which can be used by plants.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be busy in a week or so, shoveling manure, working up a
sweat in the cold of December so that in spring I won't have to
sweat the tilth and fertility of my soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
