<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING SANTA THROUGH A MAGICAL LENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I saw the real Santa,'' 5-year-old Nader says solemly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You did?!'' asks Shirley Gallerani, with appropriate
astonishment. ``Where?''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the furniture store. I knew he was the real Santa by his
beard.''
</P>
<P>
   None of Nader's preschool classmates at the Rockwell Center at
Lasell College in Newton, Mass. dispute his analysis. The beard,
they agree, is a dead giveaway, a sure-fire strategy for spotting
fake Santas. Gallerani, director of Lasell's laboratory schools,
delights in imagining each of these youngsters sitting on Santa's
lap, scrutinizing his beard for telltale signs that this is yet
another man playing dress-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The imagination is so rich at this age, Santa is magic for
them,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That he's magical is what allows children to accept that there
is only one Santa and many impersonators. After all, how else could
the real Santa get to all the stores and listen to all the
children's requests? ``He has to have so many helper Santas,'' one
child tells Gallerani, ``because he has so many toys to make and he
has to teach the reindeer to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point, however, the magic wears thin. The 4-year-old may
accept on faith that chubby old St. Nick can make it down a skinny
chimney just because he can. The 7- or 8-year-old may not be able
to tolerate such a discrepancy of logic.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what our children's ages, the trick for parents is to
see Santa through their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know parents who are uncomfortable with Santa because it's a
lie,'' says developmental psychologist Melanie Killen, an associate
professor at the University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   If it is a lie, it's one that's OK to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a deception with bad intent,'' says Killen. Gallerani
says, ``To think of it as a lie is unfortunate because it deprives
children of a wonderful fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   From imaginary friends to the Tooth Fairy, toddlers and
preschoolers buy into magical characters for two reasons, says
child psychologist Richard Weinberg, director of the Institute of
Child Development at the University of Minnesota: Children are
cognitively unable to separate fantasy from reality, and they gain
autonomy by being able to exercise control over them. If a
4-year-old thinks Santa took two bites from the cookie on the
mantle, who's to say he didn't?
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for a 3- to 5-year-old to buy into Santa so
much that he's frightened. ``The idea of some big, bearded man
coming to the house at night can be scary,'' says early childhood
educator Ellen Galinsky. Rather than chide him for his fear _
``Don't be silly, Santa's a good guy'' _ validate it: ``I know some
kids do worry about having Santa come to our house.'' That may be
enough to calm him.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, some preschoolers may like the idea of sitting on
Santa's lap but change their mind once they get there. No matter
how long you've been standing in line, no matter how much you want
that photo, honor a change of heart matter-of-factly: ``It's OK to
leave. We can try it another time/year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beginning to question
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By 5, many children begin to question Santa but won't
necessarily tell you so. Killen says they continue to pretend
because they enjoy it, just as we do. Some may even think that by
voicing their doubts, they jinx Santa or themselves. Indeed, some
children may keep their questions to themselves for years.
</P>
<P>
   Even if your child is developmentally at the stage where he
probably is questioning Santa, this is not one of the subjects
where you need to initiate a conversation just to make the topic
speakable. ``They have enough bubbles burst in their lives as it
is,'' says Weinberg. ``If they want to hold on a little longer, I
wouldn't question why.'' Killen says leaving it to a child to
decide when to let go of the fantasy is a way to grant autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Once your child does start to ask questions _ How does he make
the reindeer fly? How does he get to every house? Does he really
eat our cookies? _ take your cues from her. If she's easily
satisfied with a mysterious smile, a twinkle in your eye, and an
``I-always-thought-he-was-real'' answer, she's likely testing the
waters but wanting to hold on a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   Galinsky's son and daughter fell into that category beginning at
about age 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would leave Santa a note and he would leave them a poem.
It became a game, to figure out the handwriting or match the ink to
our pen,'' she says. Even at 9, Lara still was ambivalent. One
summer on a family vacation in Italy, she lost a tooth. As always,
she left the Tooth Fairy a note. Galinsky stayed up half the night
with a dictionary, writing back in Italian. ``She was confused for
quite a while after that,'' she says. Galinsky is president of the
Families and Work Institute in Manhattan and co-author of ``The
Preschool Years'' (Ballantine).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Enjoying the ritual
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For some children, being strung along isn't appropriate. If a
child says in a clear way, ``I want to know,'' then it is not only
deceitful but disrespectful not to be truthful, says Killen. Even
as you acknowledge Santa isn't real, however, there are ways to
enable a child to continue to enjoy the ritual:
</P>
<P>
   --Talk about how even as an adult, you still enjoy the fun and
fantasy of Santa: ``It's a wonderful story; it makes me feel good
to think about Santa, even though I know he isn't real.''
</P>
<P>
   --Talk about how Santa symbolizes the spirit of giving: ``I know
Santa isn't real, but what I love about him so much is the way he
makes people feel good about giving.''
</P>
<P>
   --Talk about not spoiling it for younger children: ``This is our
secret; your sisters still believe.'' Killen says a child can feel
grown-up to help you maintain the fantasy for others.
</P>
<P>
   At least once a year, Gallerani says she'll overhear one
preschooler challenge another's belief in Santa: ``My mom/my
brother says Santa isn't real.'' She tells teachers to respond in a
way that satisfies both children's needs _ ``In Jimmy's family,
they believe in Santa; in Todd's family, they don't'' _ without
getting into the validity of either point of view.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same strategy Killen recommends for families who
don't celebrate Christmas. ``Santa needs to be talked about because
it's everywhere,'' she says. ``Luckily,'' she adds, ``since kids
are exposed to diversity at an early age these days, they can
handle the concept that in our family we don't celebrate Christmas
or believe in Santa Claus, but other families do, and we want to be
respectful of their traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The parental adjustment
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In many families, it's often harder for us to let go of our
children's belief in Santa that it is for them.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago at bedtime, 8-year-old Kate Nolan of Mansfield
said to her mother, ``It's hard to believe Santa makes all those
toys and delivers them in just one night, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He can do that. He's magical,'' said her mother, Joanne.
</P>
<P>
   When Kate responded, ``It would make more sense to me that you
and Daddy buy all the stuff,'' Joanne's heart sank. ``Don't you
like the idea of Santa?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do, but it just doesn't make sense to me. He's too big for a
chimney. We don't even have a chimney.''
</P>
<P>
   Joanne was quiet, contemplating this milestone of her first-born
and the loss it meant for her as a parent. When Kate said, ``Mom, I
really want to know,'' she bit the bullet and admitted Santa wasn't
real. Now Kate was quiet. Joanne tried to see in the dark if she
was crying. ``Are you OK with that?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really nice you and Daddy buy all that stuff for
us,'' Kate said. Kate wasn't crying, but Joanne was. Her daughter
was even more grown-up than she had imagined.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --To avoid the greediness that can come when children think
everything comes from Santa, set some rules when your children are
young. For instance, Santa only brings stocking gifts, or only one
present per person. That way, you can have conversations about
value and price of gifts, when appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't take a preschooler to see Santa unless she asks to go.
</P>
<P>
   --Children of all ages love rituals. You don't have to believe
in Santa or observe Christmas to create some.
</P>
<P>
   --Take turns to open gifts. That helps focus children on another
person's pleasure in receiving, which you can translate into the
joy of giving: ``Did you see how much Grandpa liked your gift?
Didn't that make you feel good inside?''
</P>
<P>
   --In families where Christmas isn't observed, it's not unusual
for children to wish for Santa. Avoid becoming defensive or angry.
Instead, validate her feeling or grant her her wish in fantasy:
``Our house would look pretty decorated, wouldn't it?'' ``If we did
celebrate Christmas, what would you ask Santa for?''
</P>
<P>
   --The predictability of Santa and the Tooth Fairy can be a
source of comfort and security.
</P>
<P>
   --Many children who don't believe or outgrow believing in Santa
nonetheless believe in the Tooth Fairy. It's a good example of how
children use magical thinking; it doesn't trouble them to know one
is not real and to think the other is and shouldn't bother us,
either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT: If you receive a hand-me-down car seat, find out
if it's more than six years old or been in a crash. Parts may be
worn or damaged, jeopardizing safety, according to Century, a
manufacturer of car seats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
