<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE OTHER HAND, MAYBE NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This column was supposed to be in the paper on Monday. But on
Sunday I felt unwell, so I called in sick.
</P>
<P>
   Before I called in sick, I agonized over it. Should I call in
sick? Do I really feel bad enough not to show up at work? I felt
pretty awful. But how awful? How awful do you need to feel to call
in sick? Don't I owe it to my employer to drag myself in and write
something? On the other hand, I felt dreadful. Which is worse, a
bad column or no column at all?
</P>
<P>
   I went back and forth, and forth and back and pretty soon I felt
even worse. So I called in sick. And then I felt really terrible. I
shouldn't have given in. I should have crawled to my desk and
produced something, anything. On the other hand, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I saw a new doctor and was given a long personal
history to complete before my appointment. I was zipping right
through it, before I came to a question that stopped me cold: What
are your hobbies and interests?
</P>
<P>
   Do I have any hobbies and interests? I thought of friends who
are passionately involved in horses, cooking, golf, tennis, yoga.
All sorts of things. I'm not interested in anything, particularly.
What's wrong with me? Is it a character flaw, not having a hobby?
Why don't I have a hobby? I should have a hobby. On the other hand,
why do I need a hobby? Is it absolutely necessary? I've gotten to
this point in life without one. And what, exactly, does a hobby
have to do with my allergies? I suppose that if I did have a hobby
I might be allergic to it. Is this a good reason not to have one?
</P>
<P>
   Sitting there, churning all this over, it occurred to me that
maybe my hobby is second-guessing myself. But is second-guessing a
hobby? Or a neurosis? Or a bad habit? Whatever it is, it's
exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   Second-guessing is probably why I was a failure as an editorial
writer. If I hadn't second-guessed every issue I still might have a
job writing editorials about campaign finance reform and Globe
Santa. As a dyed-in-the-wool second-guesser I felt compelled to
consider every point of view on every issue. On the one hand this.
On the other hand that. On the third hand something else. I was
seldom sure what to think of anything. (You might not think there
could be more than one point of view on Globe Santa but I thought:
Maybe he should give needy children more than toys, maybe he should
branch out into clothing and food and other stuff. Or maybe not. I
knew this line of thinking was madness, but I couldn't help it.)
</P>
<P>
   There are people who never seem to have any doubts, who
apparently glide through life secure in the knowledge that they're
thinking and doing all the right things. I envy their lack of inner
turmoil. I assume they lack inner turmoil. Maybe they don't lack
it. Maybe they're eaten up by it. Maybe they struggle not to let it
show. On the other hand, maybe they're self-confident. Or possibly
stupid. I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, watching the impeachment fiasco unfold, I found myself
thinking that it would be convenient if, like so many of our
elected representatives, we could simply vote the party line in all
of life's decisions, large and small, from what flavor ice cream to
order to where to live, whom to live with. Maybe that's what makes
cult membership appealing to so many people. They're relieved of
the miserable business of making decisions and then wondering if
they've done the right thing. On the other hand, cult membership
does have its drawbacks, as we've seen.
</P>
<P>
   Why am I writing this column? It's a mistake. I could be writing
about Hillary Rodham Clinton's amazing regenesis as a modern media
goddess. But who wants to read any more about Hillary Clinton? And
what could I say that hasn't already been said, and said better? On
the other hand . . .
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
