   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Dec. 18.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IRAQ/IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code on all stories; some cross-filing to
``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans six pages of combined coverage of the
attack on Iraq, impeachment and the impact of each on the other.
</P>
<P>
   With these two lede stories:
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ The ledeall: military and
political developments, casualties. By R.W. Apple Jr. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Ledeall on impeachment developments. By
Alison Mitchell. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   And these others:
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-MILITARY (Washington) _ What the Pentatgon says about the
attack; any news on new forces being used. By Steven Lee Myers.
(1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-GOALS (Undated) _ What happens when the bombing ends? How
effective is bombing for accomplishing U.S. goals; and what are
those goals? By Serge Schmemann. (1200 wortds)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-TIMING (Washington) _ On the timing of Butler's report and
of the attack. By John M. Broder, Jeff Gerth and Barbara Crossette.
(1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-REACT (Washington) _ More reaction, from Capitol Hill and
around the country. By Eric Schmitt. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-POLL (Washington) _ Overnight poll shows support for
Clinton. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-CLINTON (Washington) _ Day developments at the White House.
By James Bennet. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-CABINET (Washington) _ Defense Secretary Cohen, a
Republican, and others put their credibility on the line for
Clinton. By Frank J. Bruni. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-GINGRICH (Washington) _ When it mattered, Gingrich,
outgoing speaker and the foreign policy ally of Clinton, is back in
the House. By Francis X. Clines. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-GORE (Washington) _ Developments involving the vice
president. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Netanyahu makes a
veiled warning to Iraq not to attack Israel; Israelis are urged to
get gas masks. By Joel Greenberg. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-EUROPE (Paris) _ European reaction, focusing on the French
and Germans. By Craig R. Whiteny. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-BRITAIN (London) _ Prime Minister Blair strongly defends
Clinton against ``wag the dog'' charges, in the latest installment
of the Tony-and-Bill story. By Warren Hoge. (350 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ARABS (Kuwait City) _ Reaction from Arab Governments and
people. By Douglas Jehl. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SOUTH (Dateline to kum) _ What do Southerners, often
bedrock supporters of military, say about the attack? By Kevin
Sack. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SOLDIERS (Dateline to kum) _ Voices from a military base in
the U.S. By Rich Bragg. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Russian ratification of START-2 treaty,
which had been set for next week, suffered a big setback with the
American attack. At best, ratification will be substantially
delayed. This comes against background of deteriorating
American-Russian relations on proliferation and other foreign
policy issues. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-IRAQ-REPUBS (Washington) _ In their early reaction to
the the Iraqi strike, did the Republicans miscalculate? By Richard
L. Berke. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-IRAQ-LOTT (Washington) _ Why Trent Lott, the Senate
Republican leader, broke with the code of supporting presidents
when American troops in action. By David E. Rosenbaum. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-POSTPONE (Washington) _ How bitter was the argument in
the Republican caucus on whether to postpone the impeachment vote?
By Katharine Q. Seelye and Melinda Henneberger. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-PROTEST (Washington) _ Jesse Jackson and others protest
on the Capitol steps. By Steven A. Holmes. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Others as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET (London) _ Pinochet wins his appeal of a ruling that
the former Chilean dictator is subject to extradition. The House of
Lords says the case must be heard again because of a judge's links
to Amnesty International. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-SPAN (Madrid) _ Reaction to the ruling in Spain, which
had sought the general on human rights charges. By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO Pristina O'Connor
</P>
<P>
   Developments.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-PROTEST (Jakarta) _ At least one person is dead in a
big clash between students and security forces. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENTS (Beijing) _ Developments in the trials of
dissidents who had sought to form a new party. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-REPORTER (Mexico City) _ An American reporter, Philip
True of the San Antonio Express News, is found brutally killed in
Mexico, apparently after being sexually assaulted. He had been
missing for 17 days. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ITALY (Istanbul) _ Outrage expressed in Turkey over
developments on Kurdish leader held in Italy. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
