<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ The World Meteorological
Organization, in conjunction with other national organizations,
including NASA, announces that the average global surface
temperature in 1998 was the highest since they started keeping such
records in 1860, with global surface a degree and a quarter
Fahrenheit higher than at the turn of the century. Experts
attributed the record-breaking warmth to a combination of global
warming and El Nino, and said next year would probably be cooler.
By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-INTEGRATE (New York) _ Shaken by leadership turmoil in
its early days as America's largest financial-services company,
Citigroup has accelerated the integration of its banking units in a
headlong effort to prove that commercial bankers and investment
bankers can mix. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The financial markets show little reaction
to the Iraq situation. At 1:50 p.m., the industrial average was up
57 points, or 0.7 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 17 points,
or 0.9 percent. Elsewhere, prices rose 0.2 percent in Tokyo and 1.5
percent in Hong Kong. They gained 1.1 percent in Frankfurt, 0.7
percent in London, 1.7 percent in Brazil and 0.9 percent in Mexico.
On the American debt market, the long bond was down 17/32 point,
with the yield at 5.03 percent. The dollar fell. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ The Iraqi tensions caused oil prices to
jump more than 7 percent Wednesday, but today they are down 3
percent. Meanwhile, oil ministers from three major producing
nations, Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico, meet in Madrid in
another effort to find a way to push up prices. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-AIRLINES (Undated) _ Looking at whether the attack on Iraq
has had any impact on air travelers. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The trade deficit unexpectedly
narrowed in October as exports, paced by renewed demand for farm
products, grew at a faster rate than imports. October's trade
deficit fell to $14.19 billion after narrowing in September to a
revised $14.37 billion.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-GM (Shanghai) _ General Motors starts production at its
$1.5 billion joint-venture Buick plant in Shanghai. The launch has
been years in the making _ and now that output has finally begun,
the market has withered. Already, the American company is saying
that the factory may have to build smaller vehicles than planned.
By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Action at the Microsoft
antitrust trial: Depositions are released. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
