<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4879 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BOOKS-2TAKES-HN     12-17 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BOOKS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC TOMES HIT THE RIGHT NOTES FOR THE HOLIDAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALLAN ULRICH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Books about opera are hot this holiday season, but serious folks
will find nourishment in a spate of critical biographies of
important composers. Here's a rundown of what's new in print for
the musically insatiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinderella and Company: Backstage at the Opera with Cecilia
Bartoli.'' By Manuela Hoelterhoff. Knopf. $25. 262 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the most entertaining music book of the year, and one
of the most illuminating. Hoelterhoff, the former Pulitzer
Prize-winning opera critic of the Wall Street Journal set out to
write a blow-by-blow biography of meteoric Roman mezzo-soprano
Bartoli. She turns out to be highly gifted, terribly whimsical and
somewhat phobic.
</P>
<P>
   But the contemporary opera business in which Bartoli moves is
what engages Hoelterhoff more than her subject. Ego, stupidity,
fear and greed run rampant in this shark tank, and nothing seems to
escape the writer's jaundiced eye.
</P>
<P>
   The book contains its share of rascals (Luciano Pavarotti, and
the overhyped ``love couple,'' Roberto Alagna and Angela Gheorghiu)
and its heroes (Renee Fleming, Patricia Racette). The highlight is
Hoelterhoff's wittily discursive account of the planning for the
epic James Levine Met gala a few years ago; the reader doesn't know
whether to cry or laugh at the ineptitude, but it's much easier to
settle for the latter. Hoelterhoff dares you not to.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Story of Opera.'' By Richard Somerset-Ward. Abrams.
$49.50. 304 pages.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to impress a neophyte with the grandeur of opera,
this is the book. Somerset-Ward provides an uncontroversial history
of the form, from its beginnings to the present day, with a
side-trip to popular music theater. One encounters a few errors in
the text and captions (Herbert von Karajan never conducted
``Gotterdammerung'' at the Met). Yet the opulent photos often take
the breath away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chronicle of Opera.'' By Michael Raeburn. Thames and
Hudson. $45. 256 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Every opera fan needs this book. With the unavailability of
Loewenberg's ``Annals of Opera,'' it was time for a year-by-year
listing of opera premieres and debuts by prominent singers. Here it
is, from the first entry, Bargalli's ``La Pellegrina'' (1589) to
Henze's ``Venus and Adonis'' (1997). The sidebars, citing important
world events, and the succulent visuals make this book one to keep.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Who in Opera.'' By Joyce Bourne. Oxford University
Press. $35. 457 pages.
</P>
<P>
   So, who are (1) Struhan, (2) Nina Micheltorena and (3) Palmieri?
Bourne's delightful opera guide, with its entries for more than
2,500 characters, will be a handy book to have around during
holiday parties for operaholics. Of special interest are the essays
commissioned from luminaries on their most rewarding
characterizations. (The answers to the above: (1) The Marschallin's
Major-Domo in Strauss' ``Der Rosenkavalier''; (2) Ramerrez's old
inamorata in Puccini's ``La Fanciulla del West''; and (3) a
political prisoner whose mock execution offstage turned out to be
the real thing in Puccini's ``Tosca.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Season of Opera, From Orpheus to Ariadne.'' By M. Owen Lee.
University of Toronto Press. $30. 241 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar from his Met broadcast intermission features, Lee
collects several of his essays and lectures in a volume that deals
with opera as a potent reinterpretation of myth. Much of the
writing is provocative, though I remain unconvinced by the author's
contention that Richard Strauss' ``Ariadne auf Naxos'' is the
greatest opera of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Callas by Callas, The Secret Writings of La Maria.'' By Renzo
and Roberto Allegri. Universe. $35. 166 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Can you live without this? The Allegris have prepared a new
biography of Maria Callas, centering around the diva's personal
letters. The book includes many previously unpublished photos and
is larded with bits of obscure Callasiana, like, whatever happened
to the soprano's immense wealth? The answer lies within.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Concerto, a Listener's Guide.'' By Michael Steinberg.
Oxford. $35. 506 pages.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Symphony patrons have been blessed with
Steinberg's illuminating program notes _ the best anywhere _ for
almost two decades. Steinberg's annotations on the symphony were
published a few years ago. Here is the companion volume (and the
final installment, devoted to vocal and choral works, will appear
later). You'll find most of the standard concertos, plus a few _ by
John Adams, Bernd Alois Zimmermann, Frank Martin and Erich Wolfgang
Korngold _ that augur to become part of the regular repertoire. If
this is under your Christmas tree, consider yourself lucky.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Beethoven.'' By Maynard Solomon. Schirmer. $30. 554 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The revised edition of Solomon's outstanding critical biography
updates the author's thinking on his subject since 1977, especially
in light of contemporary scholarship; and Schirmer has added a
pictorial biography of the composer. Solomon's objective account of
Beethoven's life is so engagingly written and yet so enlightened
that it claims pride of place on the bookshelf.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou Harrison, Composing a World.'' By Leta E. Miller and
Frederic Lieberman. Oxford University Press. $35. 385 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, both faculty members at the University of
Californiat at Santa Cruz, have come up with the first full
critical biography of one of the great luminaries in their
neighborhood. The pair trace the events of Harrison's life, then
devote most of the book to the composer's world _ his affinity for
and incorporation of Asian modes and tunings, his politics,
homosexuality and even the reviews he wrote for the New York Herald
Tribune back in the 1940s. A 73-minute CD with Harrison's music is
included. An overdue tribute and doubly welcome on that account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Partch, a Biography.'' By Bob Gilmore. Yale University
Press. $35. 468 pages.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd and quite wonderful that the first critical biography
of a composer who defined mid-20th century American iconoclasm
should come from a British scholar; Partch does truly belong to the
world. Until now, Partch's own writings, often leaning to polemic,
have been the best source on his life. But Gilmore provides a
smooth narrative of a visionary career and how Partch came to build
the bizarre, fabulous instruments, that, even 25 years after his
death, have won him a huge following among a younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dialogues and Discoveries: James Levine, His Life and His
Music.'' By Robert C. Marsh. Scribner. $27.50. 331 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh has been conducting interviews with the Met's artistic
director for 25 years and he has observed Levine since he was an
assistant to George Szell in Cleveland in the 1960s. He has edited
these colloquies for publication, prefacing them with a short
biography and following them with studies of Levine's working
methods and his recordings as conductor and pianist. What emerges
is a complex portrait of an artist obsessed with the power of music
to change the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Violin Book.'' Robin Stowell, editor. Miller Freeman. $75.
126 pages.
</P>
<P>
   This limited, slipcased edition is as seductive to the eye as it
is nourishing for the mind. The sundry contributors cover the
anatomy and acoustics of the violin, the famous violin makers, the
legendary performers and the evolving repertoire. Space is found,
too, for recommended recordings and all manner of fiddle lore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Amadeus Book of the Violin.'' By Walter Kolneder. Amadeus
Press. $49.50. 597 pages.
</P>
<P>
   This English translation of Kolneder's final 1993 edition isn't
as opulent as the above, but it is considerably more informative.
The volume traces the construction, history and repertoire of the
violin with Teutonic thoroughness; it is liable to become a
standard reference work. In an age when books on music are
published fitfully (or not at all) in America, Oregon-based Amadeus
Press continues to issue meaningful _ and often indispensable _
additions to the library.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1419EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-BABYDOC-1218-CO     12-17 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-BABYDOC-1218-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS HAITIAN EXILES SEEK HIS ARREST IN FRANCE, 'BABY DOC' DUVALIER
CLAIMS HE DID NOTHING WRONG
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 500 words.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Emboldened by the arrest in Britain of former Chilean
dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet, a Haitian-born photographer in
France plans to announce legal action Friday aimed at bringing
ousted Haitian dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier to trial for crimes
against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people were massacred or tortured to death
during the 31-year reign of ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier and his father,
Francois, known as ``Papa Doc.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in the weekly French newsmagazine VSD, which hit
newsstands Thursday, Duvalier said he was innocent of any
wrongdoing, and that he deserved credit for helping usher democracy
in to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed an interest in returning to politics some day, and
said that ``his greatest desire'' would be returning to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   A 1987 constitutional ban that prohibited infamous Duvalierists
from holding political office in Haiti expired in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely not afraid because I have done nothing
wrong,'' Duvalier was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the 1980s I put the country on the road to democracy,
and I abolished the death penalty in 1983,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But to the delight of Haitian groups in the United States,
Gerald Bloncourt recently formed a committee in Paris that hopes to
bring Duvalier to justice.
</P>
<P>
   Bloncourt said Tuesday that he had gathered all the ``necessary
elements'' for a lawsuit and would announce legal action at a press
conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's acting on behalf of more than 60,000 Haitians
killed or tortured at the hands of Duvalier's notoriously brutal
Tontons Macoutes militia.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian groups welcomed the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much doubt that Duvalier personally attached electrodes
to anyone's body parts, but he was in command so he should be held
responsible,'' said Merrill Smith, director of Haiti Advocacy Inc.,
a non-profit lobbying group in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Named ``president for life'' at age 19 following the death of
his father in 1971, Duvalier, now 47, was forced into exile in
France after being overthrown in 1986 by a U.S.-supported coup.
</P>
<P>
   Although Duvalier is reportedly broke and getting by on handouts
from supporters, he has maintained a peaceful existence away from
the spotlight -- that is, until Pinochet's case emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was arrested in October and is being detained in
Britain while Spain seeks his extradition to face charges of murder
and torture of its citizens during his 17-year reign, which ended
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise twist to the case, Britain's highest court on
Thursday ordered a new hearing into whether Pinochet is immune from
prosecution, setting aside a previous ruling that he is not immune.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's House of Lords had been asked by Pinochet's lawyers to
discard its previous judgement declaring he had no immunity on the
grounds that one of the judges involved was biased because of his
close ties to the human rights group Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Lords said Thursday that it would re-hear
Pinochet's case next month.
</P>
<P>
   The actions against Pinochet have inspired Haitian exiles in
France to seek a trial for Duvalier.
</P>
<P>
   Although French government authorities have claimed they've lost
track of Duvalier, police sources have said that he's been seen
recently in Paris and in Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   The interview in the newsmagazine was conducted by a French
journalist who was taken ``somewhere in France'' by one of
Duvalier's friends for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Since Pinochet's arrest, the Haitian government has encouraged
Haitian exiles to take Duvalier to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Haitian government is quite supportive of this effort,''
said Ira Kurzban, the Haitian government's Miami-based legal
adviser. ``We have substantial paperwork that could assist with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazel Ross Robinson, the Haitian government's lobbyist in
Washington, said Haitians in the United States want Duvalier to be
held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People suffered so much under Duvalier and people want him to
take responsibility for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added that Haitians also would like to see action taken
against Raoul Cedras, who savagely repressed the poor nation after
seizing power in 1991. By 1994, when Cedras was forced into exile
by a U.S. invasion, an estimated 3,000 to 5,000 Haitians had been
killed or tortured to death.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cedras reportedly lives in a posh neighborhood in Panama
City where he owns a penthouse apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
