<HEADLINE>
`MIGHTY JOE YOUNG' ON CABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the ``Mighty Joe Young'' remake just around
the corner, the people at Turner Classic Movies have a suggestion:
</P>
<P>
   See the original.
</P>
<P>
   They've made it possible to view the 1949 classic (from the
creators of ``King Kong,'' Willis O'Brien and Ray Harryhausen) at 8
tonight. Terry Moore stars as a gorilla breeder who is persuaded by
an unscrupulous nightclub owner to bring her 12-foot gorilla to the
States as an attraction. But the sideshow act is upset when Joe
goes on a rampage. In true Hollywood fashion, however, Joe gets the
chance to redeem himself when an orphanage catches fire and
helpless children are trapped inside.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Johnson, Robert Armstrong and Frank McHugh also co-star in
Ernest Schoedsack's production, which boasts outstanding special
effects for its time.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Mighty Joe Young'' opens Christmas Day and stars Bill
Paxton (``Twister'' and ``Apollo 13.'') and Charlize Theron (``Two
Days in the Valley'' and Woody Allen's ``Celebrity'').
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the ``See the Original'' theme, TCM presented
``The Shop Around the Corner'' earlier this week. This Jimmy
Stewart-Margaret Sullavan romantic comedy about two bickering
co-workers who fall in love through a lonely hearts club has been
updated for the '90s in ``You've Got Mail,'' which stars Tom Hanks
and Meg Ryan and opens today in theaters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY NIGHT FEVER: Actor John Travolta, who shot to stardom
in ``Saturday Night Fever,'' and regained it playing a hired killer
in ``Pulp Fiction,'' will be the recipient of a career achievement
award at the 10th annual Palm Springs International Film Festival
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation will come Jan. 9 at the festival's Saturday
night awards gala at the Palm Springs Convention Center. Jack
Valenti, president and chief executive of the Motion Picture
Association of America, will be the first recipient of the Sonny
Bono Visionary Award, established in honor of the late entertainer
and congressman.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the Motion Picture Association, Valenti oversees the
interests of the U.S. film and television industries in the global
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta's screen credits include ``Urban Cowboy,''
``Phenomenon,'' ``Get Shorty,'' ``Broken Arrow,'' ``Michael,''
``Primary Colors'' and the upcoming ``A Civil Action.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonny Bono Award is devoted to a person in entertainment who
demonstrates visionary skill in film. Bono started the film
festival in 1989 in this city, where he once was mayor before being
elected to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Debbie Reynolds will also be honored with a lifetime
achievement award. Her big break came in the 1950 MGM musical
``Three Little Words,'' which starred Fred Astaire and Red Skelton.
After her follow-up performance in the Busby Berkley musical ``Two
Weeks in Love,'' studio mogul Louis B. Mayer cast her as Gene
Kelly's leading lady in ``Singin' in the Rain,'' which may be the
greatest screen musical of all time.
</P>
<P>
   FREE SCREENING: The Los Angeles County Museum of Art's Bing
Theatre offers a free screening of the 1945 drama ``Mildred
Pierce'' at 1 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Crawford won a Best Actress Oscar as the housewife who
takes a waitressing job and becomes enamored of Zachary Scott. Her
spoiled daughter, (Ann Blyth) makes a play for him, too, leading to
four-star adaptation of James Cain's novel about murder for cheap
love.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is at 5905 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles. For
information, call (323) 857-6000.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
