<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS STADIUM SITE OVERSHADOWED BY BUILDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ That was one giant step forward Tuesday for
Connecticut officials in their efforts to bring the New England
Patriots here, but the journey is not done.
</P>
<P>
   And the next step is likely to be more troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the General Assembly's approval of a $375 million
deal for the National Football League franchise, Connecticut
officials must now assemble the land on which the stadium will
stand. The targeted parcels are mostly a mix of largely
underdeveloped land and parking lots along the Connecticut River.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also two large and important buildings on the
land, and how to go about removing them and paying for the
relocation is still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Both buildings are owned by CTG Resources Inc., an energy
holding company. One, the Connecticut Natural Gas Co.'s steam
energy plant that heats and cools downtown Hartford, is just about
where one end zone of the proposed stadium would be. The other
building, the gas company's headquarters, extends out from that end
zone to the prospective site for 50-yard-line seats.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings loom over both the site and Connecticut's plans
for the new home of the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   While the financial package approved overwhelmingly by the
General Assembly provides money for the stadium, it provides no
money for the purchase of the land or the development rights. In
fact, it makes no mention of the specific site at all.
</P>
<P>
   All it says is that, ``The state must acquire by condemnation,
purchase, lease, lease-purchase or otherwise the real property for
the stadium facility site and the infrastructure improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My current understanding is that the companies are going to
donate the land for the site,'' said Dean Pagani, Governor John
Rowland's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that might be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fiondella, the president, chairman and chief executive
officer of the Phoenix Home Life Mutual Insurance Co., has been
leading the corporate charge to redevelop the site as Adriaen's
Landing, a $1 billion development of mixed uses, including a
stadium, a convention center, retail space, residential space, a
hotel and activities centers. Phoenix owns about 30 percent of the
land, only a sliver of which is designated for use for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four years _ long before Patriots' vice president
Jonathan Kraft saw the plans for the site and figured the stadium
ought to be for the Patriots and UConn football, instead of just
the Huskies _ Fiondella has been trying to rally other businesses
and the state and city governments to the cause of redeveloping
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   It has been Fiondella's idea that Phoenix, CTG and the other
major landowners _ The Travelers Group and the City of Hartford _
would form a land-management company, to be called the Adriaen's
Landing Management Company. The companies would donate the land to
the land management company, and then the management company would
sell the development rights.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, the parcels on which the stadium would stand _
mostly on CTG Resources land _ would be yielded as part of the
development deal for Adriaen's Landing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the original plans for Adriaen's Landing, which have been
proceeding publicly since May, well before the Patriots expressed
an interest, the state set up the Capitol City Economic Development
Administration to preside over the redevelopment. Earlier this
year, the state appropriated $350 million to get Adriaen's Landing
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, an agreement on the companies donating the land in
return for the development rights has not emerged from the
negotiation among the companies and the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still some discussions to be held on how all of that
will work out,'' said Keith Anderson, a spokesman for The
Travelers. ``There has been no agreement, yet, and what will come
out of this I really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if the negotiations are successful, it is unclear how
much the companies will seek for the development rights they would
sell in return for donating the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a revenue projection that says what the return
will be for the shareholders of the companies or the residents of
the city,'' said Deputy City Manager Patricia Williams. ``Frankly,
there has been no room for an appraisal. The project has great
support, but it has not progressed to a detailed study.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Fiondella insists that the ultimate price tag on
the development rights is not important.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't really about how much money we are going to make,''
said Jon Sandberg, a spokesman for Phoenix. ``These companies are
acting out of a sense of enlightened self-interest. It is important
for them and for the city that Hartford is redeveloped, that it is
viewed as a destination and that we begin to retain some of the
young people, the working force of the future, that is leaving
Hartford, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   If an agreement is not struck, the state may have to resort to
costly and potentially lengthy condemnation proceedings. That has
the potential of delaying the start of construction of the stadium.
If there is a major delay, according to officials familiar with the
details of the bill passed by the General Assembly Tuesday, the
Krafts would still have the right to back out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The major stumbling block appears to be CTG Resources Inc. While
Phoenix and Travelers have some parking lots on the land, which
will have to be replaced if employees are going to have some place
to park their vehicles after Adriaen's Landing and the stadium
rise, CTG Resource's subsidiary, Connecticut Natural Gas, would
have to move both its headquarters and the steam plant somewhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective bill is $100 million, some portion of which
could come from the development costs of Adriaen's Landing.
</P>
<P>
   But what officials at CTG Resources have in mind is unclear.
They were not commenting beyond a statement by a company
spokeswoman that discussions about the land are ``ongoing and
productive.''
</P>
<P>
   In a press release issued in May, CTG Resources president and
chief executive officer Arthur C. Marquardt said that the company
was pleased about the prospect of joining in the Adriaen's Landing
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, moving all of our operations would be a huge
undertaking,'' Marquardt said. ``But if all the other pieces can
come together to make this happen, we think it would be well
worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the other pieces, according to business and government
sources close to the negotiations, is the possibility that CTG
Resources, through its subsidiary, Connecticut Natural Gas, might
become the energy provider to all of the facilities encompassed
within Adriaen's Landing, including the stadium. CTG Resources has
said publicly that would represent a 25 percent increase in its
downtown heating and cooling business.
</P>
<P>
   CTG Resources, which announced in July of 1997 that it was
seeking to diversify and expand its business, has said it would
invest nearly $30 million of its own money as part of the steam
plant relocation if it becomes the energy supplier to Adriaen's
Landing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company has publicly discussed a possible joint
venture with the Connecticut Resources Recovery Authority to
produce steam at the recovery authority's trash-to-energy plant in
the South Meadows section of the city, replacing the steam plant on
the stadium site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
