<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4949 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS &LR;      12-17 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONTRACT TO SPELL OUT BUILDING PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the next several weeks, the bill that Connecticut lawmakers
passed to build a $375 million stadium in Hartford for the New
England Patriots will become a 250-page development contract that
must be signed by both team owner Robert Kraft and Governor John
Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   The document will contain the nitty-gritty language, spelling
out in detail exactly how the stadium will be built. The
development agreement is expected to be completed before a Jan. 15
deadline and once Kraft signs it, he will be legally bound to move
the team there, officials say, or face legal action. Once the lease
between the team and the state is enacted, sometime during the
stadium's first year of operation, Kraft would have to pay the
state's remaining cost of financing the stadium if the team leaves
before the 30 year lease expires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The development agreement irons out the details not contained
in the bill. Even though the bill is long and extensive, it's still
pretty much a guide, a map of what is supposed to take place,''
said Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani. ``There should be a fairly
significant portion of it done already because the lawyers involved
in putting the legislation together have been working on the
development agreement at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The document could include a firm date for the stadium opening,
now targeted at 2001. But in order to meet that construction
deadline, the site must be cleared by next July, officials said.
The agreement will also explain in detail how funds will be spent.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft and Rowland, though, dismiss any suggestion that bumps
could be encountered in the next several weeks as the final
development agreement is completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into hypotheticals about how this might
not happen,'' Pagani said. ``The stadium is going to get built.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
