<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4965 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-Calls-PA     12-17 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-Calls-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SHUSTER WEIGHS IMPEACHMENT FOR SECOND TIME, MURTHA WON'T
IMPEACH
</HEADLINE>
    BY Lisa Fine  
   c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 16 -- The first time Rep. Bud Shuster was
considering impeaching a president, it was 1974 and President
Richard Nixon resigned before the House of Representatives could
take a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty four years later, the Everett Republican is part of the
historic process again, and is still unsure how he'll vote on
impeachment articles against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster, who is among a dwindling number of moderate Republicans
whose swing votes could determine whether the case against the
President will go to the Senate, is under pressure from seemingly
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is reading the various reports and documents,'' said Tim
Hugo, Shuster's chief of staff. ``He is taking this responsibility
very seriously, having been through this before with Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's office has received comments from about 600 callers,
about 60 percent of whom were in favor of impeachment, Hugo said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Hugo said, the White House called. They responded to
Shuster's request to see a copy of Clinton's answers to the House
Judiciary Committee's questions.
</P>
<P>
   But pressure from either party will not sway Shuster, Hugo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about partisan politics for Shuster,'' Hugo said.
``It is a constitutional obligation and one he takes very seriously
having been through it before. He is reading every word of
testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuster has been the target of an ethics investigation, which
was recently reopened, a point that aides say doesn't make Shuster
any more or less sympathetic toward Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The House Ethics Committee is investigating whether personal and
professional ties between Shuster and his former chief of staff Ann
Eppard, who became a lobbyist in 1994, may have benefited her
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not a part of the decision at all,'' Hugo said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rep. John Murtha, D-Johnstown, has definitely made up
his mind. And half of the 250 callers that phoned his office since
Monday support his decision to oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   `` We've had times where you can't get through on the lines,''
said Murtha's spokesman Brad Clemenson. ``Some people are asking
why won't you impeach him if he's done something wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   But Murtha remains unswayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still hasn't seen anything that has risen to the level of
an impeachable offense,'' Clemenson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1457EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BASE18-COX-1S     12-17 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BASE18-COX-1STLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 WRITE   1ST LEDE WRITETHRU-
   Updates with dates for debate and vote, and changes crowd
estimate at Jackson rally
   ANTI-IMPEACHMENT FORCES CAUGHT FLAT-FOOTED
   650 words
   
   By JULIA MALONE
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a vote looming Saturday in the House of
Representatives, stunned Democrats are puzzling over the revival of
an impeachment effort they thought they'd snuffed out.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the outnumbered pro-impeachment forces had steadily
gained momentum. But where were the labor unions and the rest of
President Clinton's political base? Where were the Wall Street
financiers and business leaders to warn against the uncertainty?
</P>
<P>
   Despite a last-minute flurry of activity from Democratic allies,
many of Clinton's champions were barely visible for the past five
weeks, as momentum gained for impeachment in the House. The full
House is scheduled to begin impeachment debate Friday before
Saturday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was almost disbelief that this was actually going to get
to this level,'' said Naomi Walker, spokeswoman for the AFL-CIO.
The labor organization had suspended its stop-impeachment efforts
after the Nov. 3 elections in which Republicans unexpectedly lost
seats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought (Republicans) had heard what they said in
November'' and would give up on impeaching Clinton, Walker said.
The unions have hurriedly reassembled a lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street and in corporate America, the silence has been
deafening.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, a former Wall Street investment
banker, has made no apparent attempt to whip up concerns about the
economic effects of an impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the underlying economy, which is in the long run
what drives markets ... I think the most likely scenario is still
to look forward to solid growth and low inflation,'' he said
Wednesday, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have business leaders expressed a general concern about
instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is a business issue,'' said Frank Coleman,
spokesman for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. He said his members,
instead of viewing it as an economic question, are asking, ``Do we
really want to do this?'' and ``Don't we want to draw the line
somewhere?''
</P>
<P>
   The president's admitted misconduct also has been a factor. It
has sapped some of the enthusiasm from defenders, according to
longtime Clinton ally, Will Marshall, president of the Progressive
Policy Institute. The research group is an off-shoot of the
moderate Democratic Leadership Council that Clinton helped found
and has been a strong policy partner of this White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plenty of people have rallied behind the president and
defended him over the course of the last year,'' Marshall said.
``And many of them felt burned when he, in the end, was forced to
admit what had happened'' in the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said ``most people think he acted deplorably,'' and he
added many Democrats have therefore shifted their focus from
Clinton himself to defending ``the results of a democratic
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has had the steady backing of African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson led a prayer vigil-turned-rally that drew
hundreds of people to the U.S. Capitol on Thursday, the day the
impeachment date originally was scheduled to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defenders, many of whom sported labor union jackets,
carried anti-impeachment signs at the rally, and when a speaker
asked the crowd if the president should be impeached, the group
shouted, ``Never!''
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson has not been highly visible in the Clinton defense
in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, our presence will have made a statement,'' Jackson
said in calling for the 11th-hour vigil. ``If we lose the vote, at
least we were witnesses to this action.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Hollywood supporters also waited until the last
minute, when the battle appeared to be lost. Barbra Streisand and
Jack Nicholson were headliners at a star-studded rally Wednesday in
Los Angeles. But by then, the undecided lawmakers were already
lining up in Washington to announce they would vote for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1459EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4968 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-GUERILLA-WAR-THR     12-17 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-GUERILLA-WAR-THREE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `ROLLBACK' FANTASY _ HOW ABOUT SPONSORING A GUERILLA WAR? 
</HEADLINE>
      (This is Part III of a three-part article adapted from ``Iraq:
The Rollback Fantasy,'' from Foreign Affairs. For purchase
information _ the rates are not prohibitive -- contact one of these
New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
    (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
   
 By Daniel Byman, Kenneth Pollack, and Gideon Rose  
 c.1998 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Proponents of toppling Saddam Hussein's regime in Iraq have
advanced an option known as ``the Afghan approach.'' They argue
that the United States could simply help the Iraqi opposition mount
an insurgency on the model of the Afghan mujahideen, the Nicaraguan
Contras or the Viet Cong.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, however, is that one key to successful guerrilla
war is a friendly neighboring country willing to provide the
insurgents with a secure base _ and none of Iraq's neighbors are
viable candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan approach calls for the United States to help the
Iraqi opposition establish a safe haven next to the theater of
operations. It would then recruit, train and equip a force that can
conduct a guerrilla insurgency against Saddam's regime. Guerrilla
warfare is the strategy of the weak, who can win only by slowly
wearing down their opponents' strength while slowly building up
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Following Mao's classic three-step approach _ start on the
defensive, force a stalemate, then go on the offensive _ the
opposition would start small and avoid conventional battles with
the Iraqi army until the rebels had a good chance of winning. After
many years, the insurgents would topple Saddam's regime and gain
control of the country.
</P>
<P>
   One can surely surmise that this plan, which requires only a
modest commitment of outside resources and no risk of substantial
American casualties, would be acceptable to the United States,
where it could be sold to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that the Afghan plan is unacceptable to U.S.
regional allies, and their cooperation would be needed for it to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Successful guerrilla insurgencies require a secure rear area
where the rebels can train new recruits, shelter dependents, care
for their wounded, stockpile weapons and supplies, prepare for new
operations, and retreat and regroup in the face of government
offensives.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan played this role for the Afghan mujahideen, Honduras
did so for the Nicaraguan Contras, South Africa for UNITA, China
and later North Vietnam for the Viet Cong and so on. But no country
on Iraq's borders will host the opposition today. None of them is
prepared to live in a state of open warfare with Iraq for as long
as the rebellion takes to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to prove _ most of the candidates for the job can
be dealt with quickly. Saudi officials have repeatedly stated that
they are not willing to go to war with Iraq indefinitely. Besides,
the Saudi territory bordering Iraq is sparsely populated desert _
awful terrain for mounting an insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait, while eager to see Saddam go, is also chary about a
long-term state of belligerency _ and also has uninhabited desert
on its Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, which supported past measures to overthrow Saddam, has
consistently balked at allowing direct military moves against Iraq
from its territory, and it too has a vast unpopulated desert on its
Iraqi frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Syria was always only a half-hearted member of the anti-Saddam
coalition and has never been willing to participate in direct
military operations against Iraq, even during the Persian Gulf War.
It too has mostly uninhabited desert on its Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves only two plausible candidates, Turkey and Iran.
Turkey is certainly geographically suitable; the Turkish-Iraqi
border area consists of forested mountains and is well populated.
Unfortunately, the Turks have removed themselves from the running
because they know that any anti-Saddam insurgency based in Turkey
and northern Iraq would center around the Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   Ankara worries that supporting such an insurrection would fuel
Kurdish political aspirations in general and embolden its own
Kurdish rebels. Despite repeated pleas from U.S. officials, the
Turks actually prefer to keep Saddam Hussein in power and have even
favored his efforts to reassert control over Iraqi Kurdistan.
</P>
<P>
   Iran, the final possibility, is the ideal staging ground for an
Iraqi insurgency. Indeed, it has sponsored both Kurdish and Shiite
guerrillas over the last four decades. Iran's border with Iraq runs
through abundant mountains, hills, forests and swamps; many
communities actually straddle the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Yet since the United States and Iran are barely on speaking
terms these days, getting them to cooperate in sponsoring an
anti-Saddam insurgency would pose a formidable obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Other problems with the Afghan approach stem from the lengthy
time frame it would take to work. First, a long, drawn-out
guerrilla war in Iraq would eventually stick in the craw of world
opinion. The United States would find itself increasingly isolated
at the United Nations and elsewhere, which would affect other
foreign-policy issues _ including maintaining the sort of sanctions
and inspection regimes that keep Saddam relatively weak and
contained.
</P>
<P>
   Second, this plan might eventually get rid of Saddam, but it
says nothing about how to manage the challenge he poses in the
present and foreseeable future. By embracing the Afghan approach,
the United States could easily find itself stuck in a couple of
years with a rebellion still in its larval stage and a resuscitated
Iraq increasingly free from international restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, even if the Afghan approach succeeded, it might open up
a Pandora's box of new troubles. Destabilizing Saddam is not the
same as installing a pro-U.S. government in Baghdad. Instability in
Iraq could eventually lead to a military or security-service coup,
but this would not necessarily help the Iraqi National Congress,
the country's umbrella opposition group, or any other pro-Western
group gain power.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Iraq might even collapse into civil war. The result of
an Afghan-like insurgency, in other words, could be an Afghan-like
descent into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Daniel Byman is a policy analyst with the RAND Corp. Kenneth
Pollack is senior research professor at the National Defense
University. Gideon Rose is deputy director of national security
studies and Olin Fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations. The
opinions expressed herein are their personal views. This article is
adapted from a longer version in Foreign Affairs.) &LR;
</P>
