<SLUG> BC-MITCH-MARINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINES RETURN TO NICARAGUA, THIS TIME ON AID MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHINANDEGA, Nicaragua _ Children on school buses and
market-bound farmers driving horse-drawn carts pulled off the road
to gawk as convoys of U.S. military construction equipment moved
down their pitted highways on a mission to provide hurricane
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Six hundred bulldozers, graders, jeeps and trucks, painted
camouflage green and driven by U.S. soldiers with crew cuts, rolled
out this week from the Pacific Coast port of Corinto in 30 small
caravans, bound for the northern provinces of Esteli, Matagalpa,
Jinotega and Nueva Segovia, where rains from the hurricane named
Mitch washed out roads and bridges and demolished homes, crops and
livestock.
</P>
<P>
   The convoys were a remarkable sight for Nicaraguans, not only
because of the massive display of equipment and the substantial
reconstruction assistance it represents, but because they mark a
new chapter in the uneasy history of relations between the United
States and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   As the military machines rumbled slowly through riverbeds where
concrete bridges had been washed away, they were accompanied by
Nicaraguan soldiers. That escort was in stark contrast to a time
less than 10 years ago when the Nicaraguan army was defending
against attacks by the U.S.-funded and trained contra rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Nicaragua's newspapers and television broadcasts are filled with
reports marking the arrival of the troops and with discussions of
the irony of the military presence, in light of both the contra war
that sought to oust the leftist Sandinista government and episodes
with the Marines earlier in the century.
</P>
<P>
   From 1909 to 1925 and again from 1926 to 1933, the U.S. Marines
occupied Nicaragua, installing and ousting presidents at will and,
in the process, provoking the resentment of the Nicaraguan
population. Nationalist leader Augusto Cesar Sandino, from whom the
Sandinistas took their name and their inspiration, waged a fierce
guerrilla war against the U.S. troops. Unable to defeat Sandino's
ragtag army, the Marines withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   Anastasio Somoza Garcia, a Nicaraguan military leader, had
Sandino killed and declared himself president in 1937. He and his
sons would rule the country until 1979.
</P>
<P>
   With the return of the U.S. military this week, a headline the
daily La Prensa read Tuesday: ``The north will be `invaded' today
by North American soldiers.'' Wednesday's newspaper headline:
``Marines return to the Segovias: history repeats itself, but this
time in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   One young Marine, Lance Cpl. Carlos Perez, sat under the shade
of a tree Tuesday in the town of El Realejo, where soybean fields
serve as a staging area for deploying the American equipment. He is
one of 220 Marines in the country providing logistical support for
the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, from Puerto Rico, chatted with his buddies as he waited
for orders to ship out. His destination was Ocotal, the capital of
Nueva Segovia and the site of one of Sandino's fiercest attacks on
the Marine barracks, which still stand on one side of the town's
central plaza. But unlike his Nicaraguan hosts, Perez was oblivious
to the history there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just here to purify water,'' he said. ``That's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Tracy Leahy, a helicopter crewman from Los Angeles, was
more conscious of the effect of the U.S. military presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a delicate situation, with the tensions of the past,''
Leahy said.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy will help deliver equipment and personnel to Wiwili, a
remote town on the Coco River, along the Honduran border where the
Army plans to replace a health clinic that was washed away Oct. 26
by the hurricane. The humanitarian effort takes place in a region
where the contra rebels repeatedly destroyed health clinics, as
well as schools, bridges and electrical generators during the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The storm, which stalled over Central America for days, killed
more than 9,000 people and left as many as 2 million others
homeless in Honduras, Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. reconstruction project in Nicaragua involves 1,800
military personnel who will rebuild bridges and roads, repair water
systems, build a health clinic and provide primary and preventive
medical care in rural communities damaged by the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   The troops are scheduled to work for about six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be opening up secondary roads to allow farmers to get
their crops to market, because without that, the short-term
disaster could hurt them in the long-term,'' said Army Col. Lynn
Collyer, who is in charge of the support teams that will provide
food and shelter for the military engineers and medics.
``Everything we're doing is going through the Defense Ministry, the
Health Ministry and the Ministry of the Interior.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the current president, Arnaldo Aleman, is close to the
United States, the country is nevertheless approaching this new
cooperation with care.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicaraguan military escorts not only serve as protection for
U.S. soldiers, but signal that the United States does not have free
run of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the National Assembly has been debating whether to
allow the president to extend the soldiers' stay to get more work
done. The head of the Nicaraguan army assured legislators this week
that the American presence would not become permanent because the
Nicaraguan constitution prohibits foreign military bases in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   However, some Nicaraguans, particularly Sandinistas who have
vivid memories of the U.S. intervention of the 1980s, fear the
humanitarian project could be a pretext for further interference in
Nicaragua's internal affairs, perhaps even an attempt to influence
the outcome of elections.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Chavarria, who oversees several small development
projects for peasant farmers in the province of Leon, estimated
that one-third of the population supported the U.S. assistance,
one-third opposed it and the rest were indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   Though Chavarria considers himself a Sandinista, he said he
thought the military assistance might be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The help is needed,'' he said. ``And we're living in different
times now. Maybe this is an opportunity for the U.S. to show us
it's capable of dealing with us differently than it used to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
