<SLUG> BC-HAITI-BABYDOC-1218-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   AS HAITIAN EXILES SEEK HIS ARREST IN FRANCE, 'BABY DOC' DUVALIER
CLAIMS HE DID NOTHING WRONG
   With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
   EDs: Optional add begins at 500 words.
   By SHELLEY EMLING 
   c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Emboldened by the arrest in Britain of former Chilean
dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet, a Haitian-born photographer in
France plans to announce legal action Friday aimed at bringing
ousted Haitian dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier to trial for crimes
against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people were massacred or tortured to death
during the 31-year reign of ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier and his father,
Francois, known as ``Papa Doc.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in the weekly French newsmagazine VSD, which hit
newsstands Thursday, Duvalier said he was innocent of any
wrongdoing, and that he deserved credit for helping usher democracy
in to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed an interest in returning to politics some day, and
said that ``his greatest desire'' would be returning to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   A 1987 constitutional ban that prohibited infamous Duvalierists
from holding political office in Haiti expired in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely not afraid because I have done nothing
wrong,'' Duvalier was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the 1980s I put the country on the road to democracy,
and I abolished the death penalty in 1983,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But to the delight of Haitian groups in the United States,
Gerald Bloncourt recently formed a committee in Paris that hopes to
bring Duvalier to justice.
</P>
<P>
   Bloncourt said Tuesday that he had gathered all the ``necessary
elements'' for a lawsuit and would announce legal action at a press
conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's acting on behalf of more than 60,000 Haitians
killed or tortured at the hands of Duvalier's notoriously brutal
Tontons Macoutes militia.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian groups welcomed the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much doubt that Duvalier personally attached electrodes
to anyone's body parts, but he was in command so he should be held
responsible,'' said Merrill Smith, director of Haiti Advocacy Inc.,
a non-profit lobbying group in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Named ``president for life'' at age 19 following the death of
his father in 1971, Duvalier, now 47, was forced into exile in
France after being overthrown in 1986 by a U.S.-supported coup.
</P>
<P>
   Although Duvalier is reportedly broke and getting by on handouts
from supporters, he has maintained a peaceful existence away from
the spotlight -- that is, until Pinochet's case emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was arrested in October and is being detained in
Britain while Spain seeks his extradition to face charges of murder
and torture of its citizens during his 17-year reign, which ended
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise twist to the case, Britain's highest court on
Thursday ordered a new hearing into whether Pinochet is immune from
prosecution, setting aside a previous ruling that he is not immune.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's House of Lords had been asked by Pinochet's lawyers to
discard its previous judgement declaring he had no immunity on the
grounds that one of the judges involved was biased because of his
close ties to the human rights group Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Lords said Thursday that it would re-hear
Pinochet's case next month.
</P>
<P>
   The actions against Pinochet have inspired Haitian exiles in
France to seek a trial for Duvalier.
</P>
<P>
   Although French government authorities have claimed they've lost
track of Duvalier, police sources have said that he's been seen
recently in Paris and in Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   The interview in the newsmagazine was conducted by a French
journalist who was taken ``somewhere in France'' by one of
Duvalier's friends for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Since Pinochet's arrest, the Haitian government has encouraged
Haitian exiles to take Duvalier to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Haitian government is quite supportive of this effort,''
said Ira Kurzban, the Haitian government's Miami-based legal
adviser. ``We have substantial paperwork that could assist with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazel Ross Robinson, the Haitian government's lobbyist in
Washington, said Haitians in the United States want Duvalier to be
held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People suffered so much under Duvalier and people want him to
take responsibility for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added that Haitians also would like to see action taken
against Raoul Cedras, who savagely repressed the poor nation after
seizing power in 1991. By 1994, when Cedras was forced into exile
by a U.S. invasion, an estimated 3,000 to 5,000 Haitians had been
killed or tortured to death.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cedras reportedly lives in a posh neighborhood in Panama
City where he owns a penthouse apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
