<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   THE MOOD ON CAPITOL HILL IS HARDLY MERRY
   620 words
   By BOB DART
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Oh Holy Night'' blared from a boom box set beside
a Christmas creche on the steps of Congress on Thursday, but
seasonal peace and goodwill could barely squeeze into the cacophony
of emotions on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Mistrust overpowered any sense of merriment on this day of dual
crises, and crusaders from conflicting causes rallied their
followers with claims of spiritual support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this for 19 years, and this year is the most
strange,'' observed Rita Warren, 70, the grandmother from Fairfax,
Va., who set up the Nativity scene on east side of the Capitol and
played an audiotape of Christmas carols.
</P>
<P>
   On a nearby corner, Fred Phelps, pastor of the Westboro Baptist
Church of Topeka, Kan., stood with some of his flock _ calling for
the impeachment of President Clinton and condemning the bombing of
Iraq. Wearing a cowboy hat, Phelps carried a sign bearing a
caricature of Clinton and the words ``Impeach Fags'' in one hand
and an Iraqi flag in the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``This nation is going to hell in a handbasket carried by the
pervert-in-chief,'' said Phelps, who said he has followed the
president to several sites to lead similar protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picketed his mother's funeral in Hot Springs, Ark.,'' he
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hundreds of Clinton supporters congregated near the
Capitol Christmas tree for an anti-impeachment rally led by the
Rev. Jesse Jackson. Arriving by the busload, many wore jackets
bearing the names of labor unions. Asked by a speaker if Clinton
should resign, they chanted ``Never. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   The profusion of protests was borne out on placards in the
crowd. While some carried pro-Clinton messages such as ``Impeach
Congress,'' others said ``Don't Bomb Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, in this season, unite and heal the wounds,''
implored Kurt Schmoke, the mayor of Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, standing by her figures of Joseph, Mary, the baby
Jesus and the three wise men, Rita Warren had her own causes to
espouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Italy in World War II during the bombing,'' she
recalled. ``I was praying for the children in Iraq all last night.
If Clinton doesn't get impeached here, the Lord will take care of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The military action had brought an unexpected delay to most
House members who returned from holiday recess for the impeachment
debate and possible votes Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The inconveniences fall especially heavy on about 40 lame-duck
members who are legislatively homeless. Their offices already are
occupied by other members in anticipation of the start of the new
Congress on Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Known for catering to the comforts of his charges, Majority Whip
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, set up desks for the Republican ``departing
members'' in his suite of offices in the Capitol. Some Democrats
were working on folding tables in a converted banquet room in the
basement of the Rayburn House Office Building, and others found
refuge in the offices of other members.
</P>
<P>
   In this Departing Member Center, blue partitions divided the
room into cubicles, and the lame ducks were assigned a desk, chair,
telephone and computer. None was happy about being called back to
cast this last vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible way to go out,'' Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind.,
told ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Retiring after 34 years in Congress, Hamilton said, ``There are
1,001 other issues I would prefer to vote on'' than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee member Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., is moving
over to the Senate but kept his office until the impeachment
hearings ended. On Wednesday, his staff filled and moved boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been packing, and the phones been ringing off the hook,
and there's impeachment (which Schumer opposes),'' said Nicole
Rutberg, a staffer. ``It's been hectic.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
