<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHADOW-FILM-REVIEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``THE EMPEROR'S SHADOW'': WAS A UNITED CHINA WORTH ANY SACRIFICE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about absolute power! When an assassination attempt is made
on the life of the first Chinese Emperor, Ying Zheng (Jiang Wen),
while he is traveling through the countryside, his order to have
everyone within three miles of his party killed is instantly and
unquestioningly obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   Does this make Ying (who is known today as Qin Shi Huangdi) one
of history's all-time worst monsters? Not according to ``The
Emperor's Shadow,'' which portrays Ying as a shrewd but misguided
idealist who believes that the securing of his power to realize his
dream of a united China is worth any sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Zhou Xiaowen's entertaining epic-size portrait of Ying,
who rose to power in the third century B.C., you have the
inescapable sense of a film steeped in politics. After Ying
conquered and united several feuding Chinese kingdoms, his empire
lasted for a scant 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie illustrates in its scenes of ferocious battle-ax
combat, torture and mass beheadings, Chinese peace and unity were
achieved at a staggering human price.
</P>
<P>
   Did the end justify the means? Ying insisted it did. At the same
time, the film implicitly compares his brutal exercise of power
with China's Cultural Revolution under Mao Zedong. That campaign to
re-make and unify the country didn't last long either.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about ``The Emperor's Shadow,'' which opens Friday in
Manhattan, is splendidly oversized. The ``shadow'' of the title is
Gao Jianli (Ge You), Ying's childhood friend, a man as fiercely
opposed to violence as the future emperor is its unquestioning
advocate in the name of expedience. A physically fragile musical
genius and master of the zither, Gao as a child shared a wet nurse
with Ying.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunningly dramatic early scene, the teen-age Ying and Gao
are about to be beheaded by a conquering army. Moments before the
ax is to fall, Gao begins strumming his instrument. The music gives
Ying the courage to face an imminent death from which both are
spared at the very last second.
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, the two boys steal into the tent of the
enemy leader, who is dead drunk, drag him into a ditch and bury him
alive. In the film's eeriest moment, they put their ears to the
dirt and listen in wonder to his muffled death throes.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the film jumps ahead many years. Ying, now the
imperially ambitious ruler of his own realm. sends for Gao, who
lives in the neighboring kingdom of Yan, which Ying's army has just
conquered. A believer in the power of music to stir masses of
people, Ying intends to make his childhood friend his court
composer and hopes he will write an imperial anthem.
</P>
<P>
   But Gao, who would rather die than serve such a brutal leader,
goes on a hunger strike. When Ying enlists his eldest daughter and
favorite child Ying Yueyang (Xu Qing) to try to save Gao's life,
the two fall in love, and after a frenzied bout of lovemaking, the
daughter, who had lost the use of her legs in a riding accident,
suddenly finds herself able to walk. But since Ying has bethrothed
her to the son of his most trusted general, the two are unable to
marry.
</P>
<P>
   Passion, politics, a life-and-death power struggle between two
intractable Olympians of opposing temperament: this heaving,
nostril-flaring historical drama asks big questions about imperial
ambition and art, about the value of friendship versus loyalty to
one's principles.
</P>
<P>
   You may not have heard of these people, but like historical
characters who are household words, they are larger than life,
exercising the will of their unbounded egos while arrogantly
strutting across the world's stage.
</P>
<P>
   THE EMPEROR'S SHADOW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Zhou Xiaowen; written (in Mandarin, with English
subtitles) by Lu Wei; director of photography, Lu Gengxin; music by
Zhao Jiping; art directors, Cao Jiuping, Duo Guoxiang and Zhang
Daqian; produced by Jimmy Tan and Chen Kunming; released by Fox
Lorber. Running time: 123 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jiang Wen (Ying Zheng), Ge You (Gao Jianli) and Xu Qing
(Ying Yueyang).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1550EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
