<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5078 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     12-17 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV20-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CLINTON, THE PERFORMANCE OF HIS LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) ,
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like Richard Nixon a quarter century ago, Bill
Clinton is not going to give up the power and perquisites of the
presidency without a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   We can argue endlessly about the timing of Clinton's order to
fire missiles at key targets in Iraq, but there can be no argument
about the embattled president's authority to issue the order.
</P>
<P>
   Until the moment he gives up the presidency, whether voluntarily
or not, he can _ and undoubtedly will _ wield the authority of his
office as he deems proper.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the furor over impeachment proceedings in Congress,
Clinton, like Nixon, will perform his duties as if there are no
possible barriers to his filling out the term to which he was
elected. That would mean remaining in the White House until Jan.
20, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   To almost anyone who remembers Nixon, Clinton's plucky
performance in visiting Israel and Palestine-controlled Gaza last
week was eerily reminiscent of Nixon's triumphal journeys through
Egypt, Israel, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Jordan and the Soviet Union in
June 1974, just two months before his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The tragic irony of Clinton's and Nixon's misdeeds was brought
into clear focus far from the halls of Congress as people in other
lands acclaimed them as heroes.
</P>
<P>
   After a tumultuous reception in Alexandria, Egypt, Nixon
remarked to President Anwar Sadat: ``There is an old saying that
you can turn people out but you can't turn them on. They have
touched our hearts, and I'm sure the hearts of millions of
Americans who saw that welcoming on television.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gaza last week, Clinton told the cheering Palestine National
Council, ``This has been a remarkable day.'' And indeed it was. The
Palestinians had just voted to eliminate from their doctrine a call
for the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   History undoubtedly will record Nixon and Clinton as among
America's most intelligent and tenacious presidents, while at the
same time emphasizing their character flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a painful, life-threatening attack of phlebitis and the
demands of his doctors that he discontinue his trip, Nixon went
through all the receptions, speeches and tourist events that had
been planned for him.
</P>
<P>
   Returning from the Middle East, Clinton undoubtedly knew that
his congressional foes would accuse him of ordering an attack on
Iraq to frustrate the impeachment process. But, like Nixon, he did
his thing.
</P>
<P>
   When the Founding Fathers wrote the Constitution, little did
they anticipate that 211 years later their blueprint for removing a
president from office would collide the implementation of his
constitutionally decreed authority as commander-in-chief of the
armed services.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what happened. Impeachment proceedings had to be
suspended briefly by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctant decision of many Republicans to give higher
priority to attacking a foreign foe than to impeaching the chief
executive demonstrated that even members of House and Senate who
view the president as a charlatan and want him removed from office
understand the political imperative of supporting the
commander-in-chief in a military crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has America faced such a strange choice. But then America
never has had a president quite like Clinton _ one who manages to
retain his high standing with voters despite shoddy personal
behavior and the determination of his congressional opponents to
impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   But the greater ordeal still lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   As Nixon was the architect of his own downfall, Clinton likewise
has brought his troubles on himself.
</P>
<P>
   He may at times appear to be a forlorn figure, with diminished
influence, but, like Nixon, he will be an active president until
the termination of his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   With his order to fire missiles at Iraq, the president should
have quieted contentions that from here on out he will be a
president without power or portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the White House in disgrace, Nixon made a
comfortable life for himself writing books and touring the world.
His philosophy, he said, was to never give up.
</P>
<P>
   That also would appear to be Clinton's philosophy. While
politicians ridiculed the timing of the assault on Iraq, the
president emphasized that all of his national security advisers,
including military professionals, supported his decision.
</P>
<P>
   At the historic session in Gaza, Hillary Rodham Clinton's sad
expression seemed at times to reflect her understanding that all
the hope and glory of the moment could evaporate within weeks or
months.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, congressional Democrats and Republicans, frozen by
partisanship into unyielding positions, had been unable to
determine how to fulfill the old Gilbert and Sullivan admonishment
to ``let the punishment fit the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nixon's day, some Republicans crossed over to join Democrats
in condemnation of a Republican president. This time, the opposing
sides could not achieve a consensus on the proper punishment for
Clinton's crime of lying in a court deposition and to a federal
grand jury about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the lengthy, Judiciary Committee hearings
Wisconsin's Thomas Barrett, a Democrat, looked about him and
protested, ``Something is wrong here.''
</P>
<P>
   The wrong he detected was absolute partisanship by the committee
members. Republicans, sitting in the majority, demanded impeachment
of Clinton. Democrats, in the minority, opposed impeachment and
urged censure.
</P>
<P>
   Except for South Carolina Republican Lindsey Graham, who voted
against one count of impeachment, members of the two parties
remained bound by partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   If the ``comeback kid'' is to save his presidency, he is going
to have to give the performance of a lifetime when the 106th
Congress convenes in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1554EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
