<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAU DE MISS PIGGY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a known fact that desperate shoppers will buy just about
anything at Christmastime, which could explain the thinking behind
the new Miss Piggy fragrance line called Moi.
</P>
<P>
   Moi perfume sells for $24 a bottle at Bloomingdale's and is said
to smell like ``a rendering plant in August.'' No, wait, that was a
typo. It's supposed to smell like ``a bouquet of seductive flowers
warmed with `come-hither' notes of warm blonde woods.''
</P>
<P>
   As a guy who once gave his wife cocktail napkins for a Christmas
gift, I am probably not the best person to ask whether you should
or shouldn't give Miss Piggy perfume to that special someone in
your life unless, of course, you want that special someone out of
your life very quickly, in which case I recommend you buy her a
barrel of the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   This is in no way meant to disparage Miss Piggy, Kermit or any
of the other Muppets, all of whom are terrific and would probably
make good elected officials in the sense that, being nothing more
than elaborate socks, they are very trustworthy, and even more
importantly, chaste.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean that many women yearn to smell like Miss
Piggy, seductive flowers and notes of warm blonde woods
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   For all her charms, Miss Piggy is still a pig, or, more
accurately, a pig sock, an olfactory and/or semantic distinction
that many women may have trouble making.
</P>
<P>
   If you have ever been downwind from a pig farm, the word
``bouquet'' takes on an entirely different meaning from that
intended by the makers of Moi.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be a problem?
</P>
<P>
   ``One might think that, but I think that Miss Piggy herself is
so lovable that she brings with it not the normal feeling about pig
scents,'' Nancy Lueck, a Bloomingdale's spokeswoman, told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Piggy is the Elizabeth Taylor of that world,'' said
Topper Schroeder, one of the developers of the new perfume. ``This
is not your ordinary pig,'' he added, referring, one hopes, to Miss
Piggy and not Elizabeth Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I am not the only one who has doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think of when you think of Miss Piggy's smell?
It's not good,'' said Laura Ries, president of Ries &AMP; Ries, a
marketing strategy group in Atlanta. ``She's a Muppet. Who wants to
smell like a Muppet?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Big Bird, possibly, or maybe Oscar the Grouch. (One can
only pray that the fragrance-makers do not get it in their heads to
make a scent based on Rizzo the Rat, The Count, Gonzo or Animal.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I may be, and probably am, wrong about this whole
thing. Aside from the fact that she is not, technically, real, Miss
Piggy has a lot of wonderful qualities, so many that Elizabeth
Taylor ought to be honored to be mentioned in the same sentence
with Miss Piggy instead of the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Piggy is strong, capable, independent and self-assured, yet
at the same time very feminine. She has written best-selling books,
appeared in hit motion pictures and television shows and been on
the covers of People, Life and TV Guide.
</P>
<P>
   She is certainly not the kind of person (pig? puppet?) that
would take kindly to people taking cheap shots at her new fragrance
line or, worse yet, raising questions about the personal hygiene of
her and her kin.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'm so embarrassed by this whole thing that I'm going
to run out and buy several bottles of Moi for my wife this
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   It's got to be a step up from the cocktail napkins.
</P>
<P>
   Right?
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
