A5102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-RUSSIA-1218-COX     12-17 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RUSSIA-1218-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   STRIKES ON IRAQ PROMPT BITTER CRITICISM FROM RUSSIA, OTHERS
   With US-IRAQ-1218.
   By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
   c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The threat of retaliation from Iraq may be slight. But
the United States and Britain came under an intense diplomatic
counter-attack Thursday from Russia, bristling over the decision to
strike Iraq without prior United Nations consultations.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin said the strikes ``grossly
violated'' international law and Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
called them ``outrageous.'' Russia said the attacks could scuttle a
plan by Russia's parliament to approve the long-delayed START II
nuclear reduction treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of parliament, the Communist-dominated Duma,
overwhelmingly approved a resolution accusing the United States and
Britain of ``international terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   China, France, Iran and others also denounced the attacks on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the harshest condemnation came from Moscow. Since the end of
the 1991 Gulf War, Russia has resolutely opposed efforts to punish
Iraq with military force for its failure to cooperate with United
Nations weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has relished the prominent diplomatic role, projecting an
image of itself to the world as something more than a tattered
superpower beset by domestic economic and political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   In seclusion in recent weeks recovering from pneumonia and
exhaustion, Yeltsin went on national television to call the strikes
``unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Interfax news agency, quoting unnamed defense ministry
sources, said units of the Russian air force and navy were put on
alert in response to the attacks on Iraq. But it was unclear for
what purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. has the false idea that it is the world's policeman
who has the right to do away with any nation without considering
the position of the U.N.,'' said Communist Party leader Gennady
Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's strong reaction placed it into a direct and bitter
dispute with the United States and Britain at a time when Moscow
hopes to solicit Western aid to overcome its deep economic crisis.
The Russian foreign ministry said in a statement that the air
strikes ``represent a blow to Russian-American relations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of angry rhetoric. I hope there would not be
real long-term damage to the U.S.-Russian relationship. But
certainly this has driven a wedge between them,'' said Dmitri
Trenin, an analyst at the Carnegie Institute in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   China said there was ``no excuse or pretext'' to launch the
strikes. China's U.N. envoy Qin Huasun called on the United States
and Britain ``to stop forthwith all military actions against
Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin spoke by telephone to Chinese President Jiang Zemin. The
Kremlin said the two men ``noted with satisfaction that their
positions coincided'' on the Iraq crisis.
</P>
<P>
   France, which has close ties to Iraq, deplored ``the grave human
consequences'' of the military strikes, but added with regret that
Iraq could not ``show proof of the spirit of complete cooperation''
with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Britain, France, Russia and China comprise
the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council. The
decision by the U.S. and Britain to launch strikes has left the
body deeply divided and immobilized on a diplomatic course of
action on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The air strikes were launched only after diplomacy was exhausted
and chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler had documented
Iraq's failure to hand over documents and allow unrestricted access
to inspection sites, the U.S. and Britain said.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia and China called on Butler to be replaced, holding
him responsible for instigating the military action.
</P>
<P>
   China's Qin said Butler played a ``dishonorable role in this
crisis'' and that his reports to the U.N. were ``unfounded and
evasive of the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov said Butler misled Russian officials during his recent
visit to Moscow. ``He was in Moscow and said three or four files
would be closed, that the work was going fine, and then, without
consultation, he withdrew his personnel and a strike was
launched.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright compared the
criticism of Butler to an attempt to ``shoot the messenger.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China are traditional allies of Iraq and eager to
renew trading with Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq owes Russia about $7 billion for arms purchases dating back
to the Iran-Iraq war during the 1980s, when the Soviet Union was a
major arms supplier. Iraq cannot begin to repay those debts until
it can again export the bulk of its oil, now forbidden under the
U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Russia is increasingly dependent on Western help since its
economic collapse last summer, and analysts suggested that Russian
strong rhetoric would fade as the U.S.-British campaign wraps up.
</P>
<P>
   The threat to withhold approval of the Start II treaty has been
used before as leverage in diplomatic wrangling with America.
Russia's Duma has repeatedly delayed action on the START II treaty,
signed by the United States and Russia in 1993. The pact cut the
Russian and U.S. nuclear arsenals to about 3,500 warheads each.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma also sought to remind the world of President Clinton's
domestic problems, if it needs any reminder.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber agreed to consider a motion calling on Monica
Lewinsky to help halt the military action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The State Duma appeals to Ms. Lewinsky to undertake
corresponding measures to restrain the emotions of Bill Clinton,''
said the motion by ultra-nationalist lawmaker Alexander Filatov.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
