r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      12-17 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADDAM: DICTATOR OR DEMOCRAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - We've been duped.
</P>
<P>
   Foryears now, Saddam Hussein has pretended to be a bloodthirsty
dictator with a special hatred for the United States of America.
</P>
<P>
   He manufactured and stored weapons of mass destruction as part
of this clever deception. He defied U.N. weapons inspectors and
ignored international treaties. He rearmed his military and
brutally suppressed his own people.
</P>
<P>
   All with the sinister expectation that someday, when called
upon, he'd come to the aid of his good friend and fellow Democrat,
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the military operation against Iraq was officially
announced Wednesday, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott issued a
statement saying he can't support airstrikes because he finds
``both the timing and the policy subject to question.''
</P>
<P>
   If President Clinton's critics are correct, then his dark and
crooked plan to put off an impeachment vote by bombing Iraq could
not have been carried off alone.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam's got to be involved.
</P>
<P>
   And others.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the United Nations' chief weapons inspector, Richard
Butler, issued what must be a phony report saying his workers were
not permitted to search Iraq's arsenal of chemical and biological
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Butler claimed Iraq was ignoring a promise made only three weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Such statements only prove to men like Lott that Butler, who
(begin ital) claims (end ital) to be Australian, (just as Saddam
(begin ital) claims (end ital) to be Iraqi) is actually in cahoots
with his good friend and fellow Democrat, Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in his speech Wednesday that it was Butler's report
that prompted the United States and Great Britain to take action.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following the Butler report,'' Blair said, ``after more than a
year of obstruction and a catalog of broken promises . . . we have
no option but to act.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair, who (begin ital) claims (end ital) to be British, went on
to outline so-called objectives that include diminishing Iraq's
ability to build or use weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   All of it an obvious ploy _ in the eyes of some _ to delay an
impeachment vote on Blair's good friend and fellow Democrat, Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to act and act now,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed if we didn't act, Iraq would rebuild its chemical,
biological and nuclear weapons arsenal within months.
</P>
<P>
   The order to attack, Clinton said, was based on the unanimous
recommendation of his national security team, which includes fellow
conspirators like the vice president, the secretary of defense, the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the secretary of state and
his national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   These people, in turn, must have directed all the co-conspirator
lackeys within their departments to implement their part of the
dastardly scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Lott saw through it early.
</P>
<P>
   Others took a little more time.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, the Speaker-elect of the House of
Representatives, Bob Livingston, said, ``We support our troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, ``As to the matter of timing (of the attack), we
just would leave that to the best judgment of the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports indicated there are 24,000 military personnel located in
the Persian Gulf area on the ground and more than 20 ships.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four thousand men and women from the Army, Navy and Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four thousand husbands and wives, sons and daughters,
brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four thousand individuals (begin ital) claiming (end
ital) to be honest and patriotic, (begin ital) claiming (end ital)
to come from all parts of the country and to be of varied political
persuasions.
</P>
<P>
   But who are, if Lott and the others are correct, only performers
in an elaborate hoax to bail out their good friend and fellow
Democrat, Bill Clinton. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
