<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFLECTING ON THE AGE OF WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Age of Women is upon us.
</P>
<P>
   And as women cross more thresholds in corporations, government
and other playing fields, more books will document their climb.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is the recently published ``Powerchicks: How Women
Will Dominate America'' (Longstreet Press, 280 pages, $22) by Matt
Towery.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, I was less than impressed. The title was an
immediate irritant. The book is void of photographs or graphics and
appears to have extra space between the lines to make it appear
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the author is a former Georgia state legislator. How
enlightened could he be, I wondered. Towery is chairman of a
national printing company in Atlanta. Didn't Tom Wolfe just write
about the white male dominance of Georgia?
</P>
<P>
   But the topic intrigued me so much that I put my prejudices
aside and gave the book a try. I'm glad I did.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what prompted Towery to write this book, but he did
a fairly decent job. In the first few paragraphs, he explains his
title as a term that could insult older feminists, but that newer
generations of women seem to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   He then discusses where women are in terms of the news media,
government, business and voting power, and where they are predicted
to go.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers he gathers are impressive:
</P>
<P>
   _ Women make more than 80 percent of the consumer spending
decisions in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women have climbed from 3 percent of management and
administrative positions in the private sector in 1977 to between
35 percent and 45 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   _ By 2000, women will own half of all small businesses in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1992, women earned 53 percent of all bachelor's degrees and
52 percent of all master's degrees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forty-three percent of law school students and 40 percent of
medical students are women.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1992, there were 7.2 million more female voters than men.
Fewer than 50 percent of all women surveyed voted for the same
candidates as their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those statistics I had read before; some I had not.
What's interesting is that few have put this picture together in
such a way that the masses have caught on to the trend.
</P>
<P>
   Towery quotes Cynthia Tucker, the first African-American women
named editor of a major national newspaper, as saying that this
growing influence is ``a slow and quiet revolution.''
Interestingly, those are the same words used later in the book by
Elizabeth Dole, who is often mentiones as a possible GOP
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker and Dole are among many women Towery interviewed or
quotes from other media sources. Writing about the others, whether
they are in the news media, entertainment, politics or business or
are ``stay-at-home professionals,'' Towery finds the most
influential in the group, traces their careers and chronicles their
observations.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this is ``the most powerful story of our lifetime,''
Towery concludes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any politician, corporations, foundation or other enterprise
that hopes to be successful in the coming new century must accept
the reality of this inescapable shift in our society,'' he writes.
``Those who fail to recognize its existence, or refuse to take note
of its unfolding, will become relics of the past, struggling to
function in a new century unlike any before witnessed. A century in
which women will not only be equal to men but, in ever-increasing
aspects, their superior.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SHORT TAKES
</P>
<P>
   ``Public Relations on the NET: Winning Strategies to Inform and
Influence the Media, the Investment Community, the Government, the
Public and More''
</P>
<P>
   By Shel Holtz
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Shel Holtz tells readers upfront that this book is not about how
to generate publicity for products or services on the Internet.
Instead, he promises a return on investment for your online
program, as well as tactical tools. Still, using the Internet for
public relations is just in its infancy. Holtz plans to show
readers where it is now and, more important, where it's headed.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Essential Manager's Manual''
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Heller and Tim Hindle
</P>
<P>
   DK Publishing, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a how-to book that covers the waterfront, this
is it. The mammoth 864-page tome discusses topics from body posture
to creating self-managed teams. Robert Heller is a management guru
in England and founding editor of Britain's ``Management Today.''
Tim Hindle is a business writer and runs a London-based business
language consulting firm. Although myriad topics are covered in
short, two-page segments, the graphics keep this book more lively
than most on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaching, Counseling and Mentoring: How to Choose &AMP; Use the
Right Techniques to Boost Employee Performance''
</P>
<P>
   By Florence M. Stone
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Whether encouraging employees (coaching), fixing poor
performance (counseling) or helping top performers excel
(mentoring), managers have their work cut out for them. A business
writer and editor with the American Management Association,
Florence Stone discusses each of these three important aspects of
management. She provides numerous vignettes describing the real
work world and then offers principles and ideas on how a manager
should react to them successfully.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
