<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5120 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      12-17 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR OLD AGE TEST, SO BRING A PENCIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Last week, I got some good news. Jeff, a 34-year-old
bachelor and my last single friend, announced that he was getting
married.
</P>
<P>
   I hung up the phone and rushed into the living room to tell my
husband. He looked at me in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you . . . crying?'' he asked, pointing at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm very happy for him,'' I explained. ``Kristin is a
wonderful girl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kristin's not a `girl,' '' my husband emphasized. ``She's a
woman!''
</P>
<P>
   I sucked in my breath. ``Don't be ridiculous!'' I said, blowing
my nose. ``She's a girl. She wears a Size 2!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose you think you're a girl, too?'' he asked, cocking
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' I replied adamantly, and pointed to my chin.
``Acne!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, I hate to point out the obvious,'' he said. ``but you're
crying because you're happy. Last night when I told you I was going
to bed, you said, `I'll be there in a minute. I'm waiting for the
weather report,' and the other day when we took your car to the
store, you had a full tank of gas! You're not a girl. You're
getting old.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say. He was cutting with round scissors and
eating paste in an elementary classroom when the Challenger shuttle
exploded. I, on the other hand, heard about the disaster while
cutting with an X-Acto knife and breathing deeply around glue in a
college art class.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to argue, I wanted to deny the whole thing, but I
didn't. I retreated into my office, sat down and thought about it.
OK, so I've seen grandmothers on ``Jerry Springer'' who are my age,
but so is Cindy Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Was I past my prime? Were the days of youth behind me? Is there
a little expiration stamp someplace on my body that says ``Best if
used by 10/31/95''? I needed a test, I decided, and I grabbed two
pencils from the desk drawer and stormed into the bathroom. I had
to know the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Placing a pencil under each boob, I stood back and waited. And
waited. But the pencils didn't budge, they didn't fall, they didn't
wiggle, even when I shimmied. They were adhered to me as if I had
stuck them there with chewing gum or Polydent.
</P>
<P>
   Rocks in a sock. Past my prime. So past my prime, in fact, that
I could have leaned a little to the left and drafted an entire
letter or signed a check to my doctor for hormone therapy. I leaned
against the bathroom sink and sighed. When did this happen? How
could I have not seen the symptoms?
</P>
<P>
   My mind raced with excuses, but it was all there. In little
flashes, my mind clicked from one scene to the next. In the last
election, I voted for a Republican. A week ago, I watched the
Billboard Music Awards and didn't know who anyone was. Standing in
line behind a kid with a tattoo across his entire arm, my mother's
voice popped into my head and snarled, ``Now there's a wise
investment. The only time it really pays off is when you're lying
on a steel table in a morgue without a driver's license in your
pocket.'' I don't understand the new commercials for Levi's. I
saved $19.34 on groceries a couple of days ago by using coupons and
a Fresh Value card. When my mother asked me what I wanted for
Christmas, I replied that I wanted some moles removed. I just
finished reading something that had an ``Oprah's Book Club''
sticker on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   But those red flags of maturity can be explained, I told myself.
You can attribute all of it to stress or improper prescription drug
use in combination with alcohol. To a possible chemical imbalance.
Maybe I have a brain tumor. Radiation and psychoanalysis can fix
all of that. There's hope, I struggled. Maybe my boobs are just
taking a nap.
</P>
<P>
   I always knew this day would come, but so soon? Did it happen
one day when I realized that I was sitting at a KFC drive-through
window, dressed in a sweat shirt and slippers, waiting for my order
of popcorn chicken to come up? Or was it the moment a child cut
across my yard and I yelled out from behind the screen door, ``Hey
you! I just planted winter rye!''
</P>
<P>
   And if so, if I am maturing, what's next for me? Do I wake up
one day and find my uterus nestled at my feet, next to my cat? When
do I start sneezing and peeing at the same time? When do I get
teeth that I can keep in a glass of water or pull out at parties?
</P>
<P>
   It can't be true, I thought. I am completely immature. I'm in a
bathroom jumping around with yellow sticks in the folds of my
flesh.
</P>
<P>
   But after I put my shirt back on and went outside to check the
mail, it was all in front of me in black and white, and there was
no denying it. Waiting passively for me in the mailbox was a
letter. A simple little letter telling me that I had already been
approved for an unsecured Visa credit card.
</P>
<P>
   I thought it was an act of God when I got my long-distance phone
service reconnected. But an unsecured Visa? Could it be true? Have
I really been paying my bills on time? It's worse than I thought.
Just how old have I become?
</P>
<P>
   I ran inside to tell my husband, who was walking toward me with
arms outstretched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry I called you old,'' he said, putting his arms around
me. ``I just get so frightened when I see you show any kind of
emotion besides anger and hate. It's so unlike you!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK,'' I said, hugging him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the full tank of gas,'' he added, ``I thought,
`What has this creature done with my wife?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't me,'' I replied, hugging him harder. ``Nana filled
up the tank after we ran out of gas and had to walk a half-mile so
she could get her perm. Oh honey, you must have been so scared!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ow!'' my husband yelled suddenly, and pulled away. ``Something
sharp just stabbed me! Is that a pencil growing out of your body?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a little thing called `payback,' '' I said,
laughing. ``Now quit crying. A little lead never hurt anybody!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the ``Rep,'' P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or to
laurienotaro(at)usa.net via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
