<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   HANNUKAH-RELIGION-COX (Undated) _ It's a minor holiday in the
overall scheme of things, but this Jewish festival that celebrates
freedom has become a major happening because it falls around
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   HANUKKAH-HNS (San Francisco) _ On the scale of importance,
Hanukkah is a Jewish holiday that ranks with Purim _ far below
Passover, Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur. But don't tell David Eiland,
co-owner of Just For Fun, a gift shop. By Venise Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ A childlike faith should permeate
the whole Christmas season, not because of Santa, but because of
Christ's birth and what that means. You see, I love the blessing
and mystery that are Christmas. I like that it represents the
fulfillment of prophecy, the birth of the Messiah. And what could
be more mysterious than a virgin giving birth? What could be a more
perfect gift to us all? What, indeed, requires more faith? By
Gracie Bonds Staples.
</P>
<P>
   LADY OF GUADALUPE-TEX (Fort Worth) _ Our Lady of Guadalupe's
image as a prayerful Madonna framed by golden rays adorns the
interiors of large and small churches around the world. The famous
icon also dangles from rearview mirrors and is emblazoned on
T-shirts of gang members. It also has a special place in Arturo
Loredo's restaurant on Fort Worth's north side. By Jim Jones.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ ``God Can Heal Your
Wounded Heart'' is the holiday message outside a church in
Arlington, Texas. Why display such a sad message in the holiday
season? Curiously, it's a message that is entirely appropriate.
People often feel the greatest emotional pain during the holiday
season, say spiritual leaders and psychiatrists. By Jim Jones.
</P>
<P>
   CARDINAL-ANNIVERSARY-BOS (Boston) _ In his 14 years as cardinal
here, Bernard Law has changed noticeably from an aggressively
public figure to a gentler power broker. By Diego Ribadeneira. 1500
words.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-HANUKKAH-BOS (Undated) _ Many Jews worry that Hanukkah
is falling victim to rampant commercialization. Others say it's not
a bad thing if it helps to pass Jewish practices to children. By
Diego Ribadeneira. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ His Jesuit superiors encouraged
the talented young dancer and, as a result, the Rev. Robert
VerEecke has woven his passion into his ministry. By Diego
Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   DIVORCE-RABBIS-NYT (New York) _ While Orthodox Jews who want a
divorce in civil law still have to observe the same procedures as
any other Americans, obtaining a Jewish get, or divorce, is
necessary to remarry within Orthodoxy. Women have long complained
that Jewish courts, which act like binding arbitration panels, have
favored men, particularly on matrimonial issues. In many instances,
men have refused to grant their wives a get, leaving the women
unable to remarry. Men, conversely, face no such consequences. And
men sometimes obtain a get without their wives' consent or
knowledge. By Nadine Brozan.
</P>
<P>
   MENORAH-HOLIDAYS-LADN (Los Angeles) _ It may be most familiar as
a simple nine-branch candelabra, but collectors _ who today pay
anywhere from a few dollars to several thousand _ long have been
enjoying the menorah as art. By Carol Bidwell.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ People often feel the
greatest emotional pain during the holiday season, say spiritual
leaders and psychiatrists. By Jim Jones.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (New York) _ Ever since a 1990 study showed
that the intermarriage rate among Jews had recently gone over 50
percent, American Jews have been immersed in discussions of
``Jewish continuity.'' That study has provoked a ``profound
reorientation'' for Jewish organizations, John Ruskay, chief
operating officer of the UJA-Federation of New York. They have
shifted from an ``external agenda'' of combating anti-Semitism and
mobilizing support for Israel to an ``internal agenda'' of
confronting ``the full challenge of emancipation.'' By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
