<SLUG> BC-MESSINA-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKS LIKE MESSINA IS DOING ALL RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - You can tell a lot about country music listeners by
seeing how they react when certain names are evoked.
</P>
<P>
   Mention Reba, for example, and rising singer Jo Dee Messina
gives the expected response: ``She's just great,'' Messina gushes,
speaking in her rapid, no-twang style. ``I love her so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the subject of Sylvia comes up, a one-name goddess from the
``Breakfast Club'' decade who sported feathered hair and sang
feathery songs. ``Oh, my God!'' Messina yells, before she starts
singing: `` `Well, your nobody called today, and she hung when I
asked her name' _ I still know every word!''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it, Messina is a child of the '80s. She's vague
about her age (``I'm in my mid-20s'' is all the Massachusetts
native will say), but she still gushes with the enthusiasm of a
star-struck teen when she looks back at her formative years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God, remember Deborah Allen?'' she says in a rush of
words. ``I remember lying in bed, screaming that song:
``''`BAY_BEE! BAY-BEE! BAY-BEE! BAY-BEE, I LIED!' Man, Deborah
Allen actually wound up singing background on my record, it was
very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that a one-time major player such as Allen would be
singing for a relative newcomer like Messina shows how quickly
things change in Nashville. Messina already knows that. After her
1996 debut album was released, she went through some nasty
management problems that left her on the verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a witch when it comes to my savings account,'' she says.
``Now I don't get limos. I don't do private planes. I think those
things make you not approachable. I love for people to come up to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be part of her appeal. She's a bit of a musical
everywoman, with life-affirming songs such as ``Bye Bye'' and ``I'm
Alright'' (the title track of her second disc) giving her an
identity as a fiery, strong-willed survivor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, some of the fans cry when they meet me,'' she says.
``It's happened a few times this month. It makes me uncomfortable.
I don't know how to respond. I mean, hot peppers burn my mouth,
too! I'm afraid to walk down a dark alley alone at night. I'm the
same makeup as everyone else, so I don't know how to handle that
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Messina, who works with superstar Tim McGraw and producer Byron
Gallimore (both handled production duties on her two discs), has a
bright, brash eagerness and full-throttle energy that may recall an
earlier country singer.
</P>
<P>
   She recorded Dottie West's mid-'80s hit ``Lesson in Leavin'''
for ``I'mAlright.'' While the late West tends to get overlooked by
historians, the fiery singer has her disciples, Messina included.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's one of the first crossover stars,'' Messina says. ``She
sold a bazillion records before she died. I always tell in my show
how she is a person who shouldn't be forgotten.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
