 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, Dec. 18. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IRAQ/IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code on all stories; some cross-filing to
``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ The ledeall: military and
political developments, casualties. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-TIMING (Washington) _ On the timing of Butler's report and
of the attack and who knew what when. By John M. Broder, Jeff Gerth
and Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-MILITARY (Washington) _ As the United States and Britain
launched a second day of air strikes throughout Iraq, the Pentagon
announced Thursday that it was inflicting significant damage to
Iraq's defenses, airfields, intelligence headquarters and the
barracks of the elite Republican Guards that help keep President
Saddam Hussein in power. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ The Republican leaders of the House set
the impeachment debate for Friday and said they would restrict it
to only one hour, unless the Democrats dropped their opposition to
conducting impeachment proceedings while U.S. airstrikes against
Iraq are ongoing. The hardball tactic was the first act of Rep.
Robert L. Livingston, the incoming speaker. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-IRAQ-REPUBS (Washington) _ The outpouring of
recriminations from Republicans questioning President Clinton's
motives in bombing Iraq threatens the party's effort to make its
vote to impeach President Clinton appear non-partisan and a sad but
simple Constitutional duty. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-GOALS (Undated) _ What happens when the bombing ends? How
effective is bombing for accomplishing U.S. goals; and what are
those goals? By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET (London) _ Pinochet wins his appeal of a ruling that he
is subject to extradition. The House of Lords says the case against
the former Chilean dictator must be heard again because of a
judge's links to Amnesty International. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ The earth's average surface
temperature in 1998 is the highest by far since people first began
to measure it with thermometers in the mid-19th century, the World
Meteorological Organization reported Thursday. Seven the 10 warmest
years on record have occurred since 1990, and the other three
occurred after 1983. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
</TEXT>
