<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS DEBATE HOW BEST TO DEFEND CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The chance to defend the president against
charges of impeachment in a Senate trial would be the ultimate
dream case to some defense lawyers, but others said their skills
would be useless in what will amount to a political event, not a
legal one.
</P>
<P>
   With impeachment by the House of Representatives all but
certain, with a trial in the Senate to follow, President Clinton
will need a good criminal defense lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a tricky situation. The president's lawyers will have
to balance the chance of future criminal prosecution if he admits
he lied and tried to cover up his affair with a White House intern,
against the need to head off what could turn out to be a sordid
parade of witnesses and excruciating details about his relationship
with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Brown, the San Francisco public defender, said he would
advise getting a grant of immunity from future prosecution and then
offering a full-blown mea culpa.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton is likely to avoid being removed from office by
the Senate, Brown said the president could find his margin of
support dissolve if senators believed he was contorting legal
definitions to claim innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Brown advised, ``Get up there and say, `Look, I was in
a situation that was untenable and I misrepresented what happened.
I did play around with the definitions, but it's not enough to boot
me out of office.'''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Johnson, the only other president to face an impeachment
trial, snubbed the Senate and was tried in absentia 120 years ago.
But Brown said Clinton could not do that because it would force
Congress to call a parade of witnesses to recount the sordid
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he gets a factual trial, he's going to be damaged even
more,'' Brown said. ``Then the Senate has to listen to direct
testimony from Monica Lewinsky about some unsavory sexual acts.
`What did he do next, Miss Lewinsky?' `Now, where did he put the
cigar, Miss Lewinsky?' Who wants to listen to that?''
</P>
<P>
   But actually getting the president to follow a defense lawyer's
advice may not be that easy, said Jim Collins, a criminal trial
attorney in San Francisco. Collins said whoever represents the
president isn't going to have a lot of control over strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not just a lawyer _ you're dealing with the White
House, politics, Clinton's place in history and Clinton and his
wife who are used to controlling things,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he did not know enough of the nitty gritty to give
specific advice, but once the matter hit the Senate, his strategy
would rely more on politics than the law anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be telling him, `Look, you don't need me for the
Senate. All you need is for your political people to get to those
20 or 30''' senators who can be counted on to vote against removing
the president, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   When the House convenes, it will debate impeachment charges that
Clinton committed perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of
power in connection with the cover-up of his affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have a 228-207 majority in the House where a
majority vote in favor of one or more articles of impeachment would
trigger a Senate trial. If convicted by a two-thirds majority in
the Senate, Clinton would automatically be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Choper, who teaches constitutional law at the University
of California at Berkeley, said the chief concern for the
president's lawyers should be to keep Clinton from saying anything
that could later be used to prosecute him in a criminal court _
after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a no-brainer in terms of winning,'' Choper said.
``This is a question of not getting him into more trouble. ... If
he testifies, he better not say anything that's contrary to what he
said before, and he should just put the best light on what his
answers have been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
