<HEADLINE>
MUSIC ANGEL AMY GRANT BRINGS JOY TO CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - It was completely unplanned on her part. But the way
things are going, Amy Grant may just become the Perry Como of her
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Something about her warmly reassuring voice and comfortable way
around a Christmas tune have permanently linked her with the
holiday. And once she donned a wintry white gown and sat down for a
photographer, a new Christmas ambassador was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have a natural affinity and love for all things
Christmas,'' Grant says, calling from her Nashville farm.
``Traditions evolve and so do associations. I was 22 when I
recorded my first Christmas album. My gosh, I'll be 38 next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Her two seasonal collections _ 1983's ``A Christmas Album'' and
1992's ``Home for Christmas'' _ have firmly entrenched themselves
in households, the same way Bing Crosby and Johnny Mathis a lbums
did before hers.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of a holiday concert came about naturally for the
Christian popster, whose long string of hits includes such bubbly
fare as ``Baby Baby'' and ``The Lucky One.'' In 1993, she was
approached by the Nashville Symphony to perform at a Christmas
benefit show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was `very' low-key,'' Grant recalls. ``A friend volunteered
to put together a backdrop. We invited some local guests. Then we
did two shows at the Grand Ole Opry house, and they both sold
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent years saw more Nashville holiday shows, with each
growing a little more extravagant. Last year, she took the
production on the road for the first time, and audiences simply
didn't stay away. The show sold out more often than not, even if
Grant's recording career was in a mild slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``This works on a lot of different levels,'' Grant says. ``First
off, you don't have to be a fan of mine to enjoy the show. There
are several moments highlighting different symphony players. It's
ball gowns and extravagant lights and quite exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Grant hit the road, touring in support of her
acclaimed ``Behind the Eyes'' disc. That show was stripped down and
low-key, a long way from the big-scale festivities planned for
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two tours just appeal to such different sensory
experiences,'' Grant says. ``With `Behind the Eyes,' I was really
front and center. It was like, `Come crawl through my head while I
sing for you.' This is simply a lavish celebration of the holiday
season. I love it _ it's a thrill to do this every night.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a cheap thrill, that's for sure. She has lined up heavy
hitters Michael W. Smith and CeCe Winans (Grammy winners both) to
share the stage with her, as well as the Nashville Symphony
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 150 of us on the road,'' she says, pausing to count
the numbers. ``It's 14 trucks and 14 buses to move us around. There
are 28 drivers. It's just huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with sponsorship from Chevrolet and Target, it's a costly
proposition. The big question: Why do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it and I can,'' she says. ``And I don't mean that in a
flippant way. It takes an incredible amount of manpower to put on a
Christmas tour. Because of my Christmas records, I eventually found
myself in the prime position of having the opportunity to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are emotional paybacks in addition to
monetary ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like everybody that walks in the door has a sense of
being part of something so magical and so much bigger than any one
of us could generate on our own,'' she says. ``I simply love an
evening like that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
