<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RAMADAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   RAMADAN MEANS FASTING, PRAYER FOR MUSLIMS
   400 words
   By NICHOLE MONROE
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the new moon appears _ most likely on Sunday _
about 120 million Muslims worldwide will observe the holy month of
Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   The most holy time of the year for Muslims, the monthlong
Ramadan requires fasting, prayer and goodwill to the poor. The
purpose is to develop discipline, restraint and a closer
relationship with Allah, or God.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and British forces launched massive air strikes on Iraqi
military and communications sites late Wednesday, and the strikes
continued during the night Thursday. Though President Clinton said
when the strikes began Wednesday that his administration decided
not to initiate attacks on Iraq during the Islamic holy month, he
has still met criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite compassionate of him that he is considerate to the
feelings of Muslims, but it is very unfortunate that he would take
lightly killing people while respecting the holy days,'' said
Shaker Elsayed, secretary general of the Muslim American Society, a
nonprofit, charitable organization based in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   During the month of Ramadan, Muslims forgo all food and drink
from dawn to sunset, according to literature from the American
Muslim Council, a political activist organization based in
Washington. Sexual relations during daylight hours is prohibited,
and honorable behavior is expected. Muslims also are obligated to
give a financial donation to the poor, the council said.
</P>
<P>
   The extended daily routine of Muslims during Ramadan includes a
modest meal before dawn, morning prayers, possibly a brief nap in
the late afternoon, sunset prayers and a complete meal.
</P>
<P>
   After the meal, families often go to their places of worship for
evening prayers before returning home at about 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. national security officials said Thursday that no
``artificial deadline'' would be set for the attacks on Iraq, but
some critics are saying it would be foolish to continue bombing
through Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   Aly Abuzaakouk, director of the American Muslim Council, said if
the attacks continue through Ramadan, Clinton will continue to
receive disapproval from Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
   Elsayed agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be outrageous that while Muslims are fasting and
preparing for the holy month, bombs would be falling over their
heads,'' Elsayed said. ``If you can imagine someone bombing the
United States during Thanksgiving dinner, it would be similar.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
