A5174 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-LASVEGAS-96     12-17 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-LASVEGAS-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOT MACHINES RING, ARE YA LISTENIN'; IN THE CASINO, COINS ARE
GLISTENIN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL GERST 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ It's Christmas morning, and it's a Norman Rockwell
tableau: hundreds of twinkling lights dancing, the pungent pine
scent of the tree filling the air, children eagerly eyeing gaily
wrapped packages.
</P>
<P>
   From the kitchen, the warm, comforting aroma of roasting turkey
whets the appetites of all, while from everywhere else comes the
discordant clanging of quarters spilling into a hundred coin trays.
And suddenly, a raucous alarm bell heralds one more Christmas wish
come true: Three red, white and blue 7s finally line up, and
someone is going home with pockets full and spirits lifted.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture? Absolutely nothing. It's
Christmas in Las Vegas, and nothing could be better.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the holidays, there are two types of people:
those who love the celebration and those who hate it. Vegas is the
perfect destination for both.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you're a holiday-hater. The very idea of sitting around
drinking eggnog with relatives you barely know and care for even
less makes you shudder. Maybe you have no children to share in the
celebration. Maybe for you Christmas is just another dreary winter
day when everybody but you seems to be having a good time.
</P>
<P>
   Vegas is the antidote. Vegas is nonstop fun, and Christmas _ or
any other holiday _ only intrudes if you really want it to. Go
ahead and ignore the minimal tributes to the season, the extra
strands of lights and random boughs of holly sparingly placed
throughout the glittering pleasure domes. For most of Las Vegas,
Christmas is just another workday. Of course, that work consists
primarily of helping you to have a good time, feeding you,
entertaining you and offering you a world of strange delights to
sample.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty easy to see how Vegas could suit the holiday-hater.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you're a person who loves the holidays, who sees it
as a time when families gather to embrace the magic of the season?
That holiday spirit doesn't reside just at Grandma's house or in
Cousin Bill's new rec room. It lives within the hearts of those who
cherish it, and if the people who count are gathered around a
festive table at a magnificent restaurant in Las Vegas, Christmas
will be there.
</P>
<P>
   On the Strip and downtown, the hotels and casinos pay a cursory
tribute to the season. Look closely at the glitter and lights, and
you begin to pick out the Christmas decorations. Random poinsettias
among the tropical foliage at the Mirage. An out-of-place-looking
Christmas tree dwarfed by the Statue of Liberty replica at New York
New York. A giant wreath hanging incongruously between the
bas-reliefs of pagan Egyptian gods at the Luxor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, drive a few miles off the Strip into the residential
neighborhoods, and you'll swear you were in any other medium-sized
city in America. The homes are aglow with traditional seasonal
decorations, complete with reindeer on the roofs and manger scenes
in the yards. Lighting contests are being judged, kids are visiting
department-store Santas, and adults are frenziedly trying to find
that last-minute gift.
</P>
<P>
   If you still have doubts about Las Vegas as a Christmas
destination, here are a few other reasons to have a very Vegas
Christmas:
</P>
<P>
   It's cheap. December is a relatively slow month for the Las
Vegas tourism industry. Hotel occupancy hovers around 80 percent _
compared with the annual average of 90 percent _ and that means you
can probably find an excellent deal on a room. The holiday season
also sees a slowdown in convention activity. You can benefit from
their absence.
</P>
<P>
   The food is outstanding. Las Vegas has long been known as the
home of the inexpensive, all-you-can-eat buffet. But don't stop
there. Many of the finest restaurants in town plan special dinners
for Christmas. For instance, last year at Gatsby's in the MGM
Grand, you could have feasted on caviar, foie gras,
roasted-chestnut soup, Louisiana ostrich, potato-wrapped lamb
chops, garlic mashed potatoes and a pear tart with cranberry ice
cream for $75, wine extra.
</P>
<P>
   At the Brown Derby, the fare was more traditional: roast turkey,
smoked ham, prime rib and lamb chops with all the trimmings for
only $32.50. Or you could have had dinner Southwest-style at Mark
Miller's Coyote Grill, where, for $39.50, you could take your pick
of lobster-and-sweet potato bisque, cornmeal-crusted prawns or a
Navajo elk tostada, then select an entree of potato-crusted salmon,
seared duck breast or a Black Angus fillet.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
