<HEADER>
A5176 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AOL-MAILVOICE18-COX     12-17 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MAILVOICE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   AOL voice plays Cupid in big-screen Net romance
   By Jill Vejnoska
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got Elwood.
</P>
<P>
   Right there, on the other end of the phone line: the voice that
launched thousands of chat room forays and uttered the unnaturally
upbeat phrase that comforts the lonely and annoys the already
overworked.
</P>
<P>
   The voice you hear whenever you log onto America Online. The one
so omnipresent, so chirpily there, it has to be computer-generated.
Right?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think I'm not real,'' Elwood Edwards, 49,
confirmed by phone from his Ohio home last week.
</P>
<P>
   Please. As if anyone could make this up. Nine years ago, Edwards
spoke three little words into a tape recorder at the small company
where his wife then worked. Now that same phrase is the title of a
big budget holiday movie, and Edwards, who has a speaking part (and
nothing else) in the film, got to schmooze with stars Tom Hanks and
Meg Ryan at last Thursday's glittering New York City premiere.
</P>
<P>
   In ``You've Got Mail,'' opening Friday in Atlanta, Hanks and
Ryan play business competitors who unwittingly fall in love online.
Logging onto their AOL software-loaded laptops at various times,
each is thrilled to hear Edwards' recorded voice trill, ``You've
got mail!,'' signaling another enchanting e-mail received from an
admirer they know only by a screen name.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? After all, true love doesn't come around too often.
Not so Edwards' voice, which AOL estimates is heard 27 million
times a day by its 14 million subscribers. That's about 13,950,000
more subscribers than the nascent AOL had in 1989, when employee
Karen Edwards suggested that her husband's friendly voice greet
users logging on.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of the broadcasting industry who got his first radio
job while still in high school in New Bern, N.C., Edwards needed
only a few takes to record four phrases that remain as much a part
of AOL today as modems and secret passwords. (He's also heard
saying ``Welcome'' and ``Goodbye'' in the movie; only ``File's
done'' didn't make the cut.)
</P>
<P>
   But it's the irresistibly imitable ``You've got mail!'' that has
become embedded in our collective '90s subconscious, so much so
that when writer/director Nora Ephron wanted to update the 1940
film ``The Shop Around the Corner,'' she turned to AOL and its
ripe-with-symbolic-possibilities catch phrase.
</P>
<P>
   The giant online company won't disclose the terms of its
agreement with the filmmakers, who prominently display AOL's logo
on Hanks' and Ryan's laptops; nor will it say how it compensates
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Even the voice himself is somewhat mute on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will go so far as to say I have a great relationship with
AOL,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   What he does like to talk about is how he and Karen met, online,
back in 1987. Given the story line of ``You've Got Mail,'' it all
sounds a bit too perfect, too manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   Too much like that voice pouring out of cyberspace 27 million
times a day?
</P>
<P>
   But the couple really did ``meet'' in 1987 in a Christian chat
room on AOL precursor Q-Link, exchanging messages for about three
months before meeting and finally marrying in 1988. And anyway,
Edwards says, his ``You've got mail!'' message definitely isn't
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people tell me it's grammatically incorrect, but I
think perhaps that has added some of the charm and humanity to
it,'' said Edwards, who recently left his job as general manager of
a Houston TV station to open his own voice-over business. ``I think
sometimes people are a little wary of perfection.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
