<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5177 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHESNUTT18-COX     12-17 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHESNUTT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER20
   Vic Chesnutt's big break
   By Steve Dollar
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a few months ago, Vic Chesnutt was pondering an uncertain
future. Capitol Records, which had signed the celebrated
Athens(Ga.) singer-songwriter to his first major-label deal in
1996, dropped him just as the company would have been preparing to
release his sixth album, ``The Salesman and Bernadette.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they just didn't understand at all what was going on
with me, and rightly so,'' says Chesnutt, 34, who was released from
his contract as the label underwent major management shifts. A
performer who genuinely lives or dies on the unpredictable tangents
of his personality, a guy whose mood ring hums like a neon sign,
Chesnutt occupies a curious niche: He's the rare artist who doesn't
fit any. ``They pretty much gave the record to me and said, `Go
find somebody who cares.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Capricorn Records did. The Atlanta-based
semi-major label, whose '90s roster includes alt-rock hit machines
Cake and 311, released ``Salesman'' last month. ``Ahhh,'' Chesnutt
offers, talking from his home in a quiet neighborhood on the
fringes of Athens. ``No more Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the loosely conceptual song cycle about a traveling
salesman and his long-lost love has generated the best reviews of
Chesnutt's decade-long recording career.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a trembling quiver that's loose, self-possessed and amply
self-mocking, plus music that dips and flows just as thoroughly,
Chesnutt's oeuvre is passive/
</P>
<P>
   aggressive indolent: The same song can put you to sleep, then
beat you up,'' wrote critic Eric Weisbard in an eight-out-of-10
review in Spin magazine. Upcoming appearances on Conan O'Brien and
the PBS concert series ``Sessions at West 57th'' promise to put the
singer more prominently in the public eye than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for him, the notoriously diffident Chesnutt has a lot of
backup: the sprawling Nashville ensemble Lambchop, a kind of
lopsided C&AMP;W big band whose numbers can swell to more than a dozen
at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   Both acts perform, separately and together, at Variety Playhouse
tonight. ``I'm always on the verge of belting it out with
Lambchop,'' says Chesnutt, who expects to perform ``Bernadette''
straight through, much as it was recorded, complete with funeral
dirges, memory plays, alcoholic reveries, jaunty Ellingtonian
shuffles and inspired lines such as ``Last night I nearly killed
myself chasing rum with rum; There were crows flying all around my
head and I sure caught and ate me some.''
</P>
<P>
   As you'd expect, the band lends Chesnutt's twisted literary
ramblings a musical range they've never enjoyed before: ``Those 12
people blasting at one time really gives me power. It made me want
to rise to the occasion, which I occasionally did.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambchop co-founder and songwriter Kurt Wagner has been a
Chesnutt fan for years, and had long relished the opportunity to
make a record with him, since first seeing him perform in a
Nashville bar in the late 1980s. It was an evening so seemingly
dismal as to be transcendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was amazingly drunk and amazingly articulate at the same
time,'' Wagner recalls. ``It was pretty much a life-changing sort
of thing. There was nobody there to see it but me and a couple of
cops and some friend of mine's wife. The cops were on their rounds.
I don't know if they knew what they were seeing. There was no peace
to be kept. I guess they were waiting for him to fall off the
stage. He had made a sign that said, `I suck: Tapes $5,' out of a
piece of cardboard slapped to the stage. At the end, I went and
bought as many (cassettes) as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a measure of how far Chesnutt has come that, these days,
Emmylou Harris wants to sing with him. The vocalist makes a cameo
appearance as ``the recollected voice of Bernadette'' on the
album's ``Woodrow Wilson'' track. It turns out that members of
Harris' band, Spyboy, are Chesnutt fans, and a mutual friend,
singer-songwriter Joe Henry, acted as a go-between.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried that she wouldn't like the song,'' Chesnutt
says. ``The lyrics are odd. It doesn't have a big chorus or
anything. But she loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
