<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   RESIGNATION CALLS MOUNT AS IMPEACHMENT VOTE NEARS
   By NICHOLE MONROE
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as U.S. troops engage in battle abroad,
members of Congress from both parties are calling on President
Clinton to resign in order to spare the nation the trauma of an
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show substantial support for the idea, but
Clinton said this week he would not even consider stepping down.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-led air strikes against Iraqi targets were already under
way Wednesday night as Republican House members gathered to discuss
how the war should affect impeachment procedures scheduled for this
week, but some angry members were ready to drum out the commander
in chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an insult to the American people. He should resign,''
said Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the president refuses to resign for the sake of the nation,
I believe
</P>
<P>
   he should be impeached and face Senate trial,'' said House
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Even one Democrat, Rep. Louise Slaughter of New York, said
Wednesday that if the House impeaches Clinton, ``I believe he would
have to resign at that point because his usefulness would be lost
in dealing with other nations.''
</P>
<P>
   The resignation bandwagon started rolling in earnest with
appearances on last Sunday's talk shows by House Judiciary
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and Mouse Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said that if Clinton resigned, he would be the ``savior of
his party'' and that it would be a way of ``going out with honor.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a press availability during his Mideast trip Sunday,
Clinton declared, ``I have no intention of resigning. It's never
crossed my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   And when White House spokesman Joe Lockhart was asked at a
Wednesday briefing about polls that showed broad support for
resignation if Clinton were impeached, he dismissed their
significance, noting that a ``wide disparity'' exists depending on
how the questions are phrased.
</P>
<P>
   In its Thursday editions, The Washington Post acknowledged that
polling methods were a factor in a widely publicized finding this
week. An ABC News/Washington Post poll published Wednesday said
that 59 percent of respondents said Clinton should quit because
``it was the quickest way of bringing this matter to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Post noted Thursday that in another survey taken at the
same time, it had asked simply whether Clinton should resign or
``remain in office and face trial in the Senate. Only 43 percent of
people responding to that question said Clinton should quit.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in a CBS News/New York Times poll published the same
day, only 43 percent agreed ``it would be better for the country if
Bill Clinton resigned from office.''
</P>
<P>
   The Post concluded that the differing results indicate that
``most of those favoring resignation do so mainly because they want
the scandal to end and not because of Clinton's behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the reasons, history indicates that Clinton could
be endangered if polls show steady, strong support for resignation.
</P>
<P>
   When President Nixon resigned in 1974 as the House prepared to
consider articles of impeachment, he did so after loss of public
confidence led his allies in Congress to withdraw their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the disappearance of the (political) base, I now believe
that the constitutional process has been served, and there is no
longer a need for the process to be prolonged,'' Nixon said in his
resignation address to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
