</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-EGYPT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   A princely epic, but no classic
   By Eleanor Ringel
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The powers that be at DreamWorks talked to everyone from
evangelists to ministers to rabbis to Muslim theologians to make
sure the world's major religions found nothing overtly offensive
about their new animated musical epic, ``The Prince of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only person they didn't contact was the ghost of Cecil
B. de Mille.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. He could have told them he'd already done this movie.
</P>
<P>
   Though unquestionably impressive on its own terms, ``The Prince
of Egypt'' can't help but summon echoes of de Mille's Oscar-winning
``The Ten Commandments.'' They have the same awesome visuals, the
same cast-of-thousands scale, the same insistently reverential
approach, though God sounds less patriarchal here, more like a
cross between a talk-show host and a New Age guru.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt'' tells the story of the Hebrew people's
liberation from slavery in Egypt. All the big scenes, with
occasional embellishments, are here: Moses being discovered in the
bulrushes by the Pharoah's family; his run-of-the-palace
coming-of-age and getting his adopted brother Rameses into trouble
with his high-spirited pranks; his discovery of his true birthright
and ensuing banishment; his finding a new home and family in the
desert; his being summoned by God to lead the Israelites out of
bondage; the 10 plagues (the killing of the firstborn Egyptian
males is especially chilling, recalling the finale of ``Raiders of
the Lost Ark'').
</P>
<P>
   The movie gets us as far as the climactic parting of the Red
Sea, then pretty much backs out gracefully. We glimpse Moses
delivering God's sacred words from Mount Sinai, but for stuff like
the orgiastic worship of the Golden Calf, you'll have to go back to
de Mille. After all, for all its well-researched solemnity and
righteous eschewing of fast-food tie-ins, ``Prince'' is still a
family film.
</P>
<P>
   A huge amount of care has been lavished on this movie, and it
shows. All the bases have been covered, from the spectacular
animation to the spectacular voice talent: Val Kilmer as Moses;
Ralph Fiennes as Rameses; Jeff Goldblum as Moses' brother, Aaron;
Michelle Pfeiffer as Moses' wife, Tzipporah; Sandra Bullock as his
sister, Miriam; Patrick Stewart as the Pharaoh Seti, Rameses'
father; Steve Martin and Martin Short as charlatan court magicians.
</P>
<P>
   But is ``Prince'' the sort of animated classic that will be
embraced (think ``Beauty and the Beast'' or ``Toy Story'')? Not
really. Though the writers have worked hard to give Moses a certain
spunk, and they do avoid cute sidekicks, they can't escape a kind
of squeaky-clean Sunday-school-lesson aura. The picture isn't
sanctimonious; it's too smart for that. But it is reined in. It's
dressed for church (or temple or mosque), and you can sense that
the clothes itch just a little.
</P>
<P>
   That said, you don't want to miss it. This movie is too well
done. The kids, who may not be all that familiar with de Mille or
the Book of Exodus, will be blown away by the story and the
effects. Everyone else will appreciate the sheer artistry on
display. But overall, ``The Prince of Egypt'' is just a bit too
kosher. It could have used a little ham.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Val Kilmer and Ralph Fiennes. Directed by
Brenda Chapman, Steve Hickner and Simon Wells. Rated PG for
violence and intense themes. 1 hour, 39 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An impressive but somewhat chilly mixture of
Hollywood and the divine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
