</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GODS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   By grace of `Gods,' maybe an Oscar
   By Eleanor Ringel
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``To a new world of gods and monsters!''
</P>
<P>
   So says a ``mad'' scientist in James Whale's masterful ``The
Bride of Frankenstein.''
</P>
<P>
   That toast _ inspired, insane and ever so slightly campy _
provides the title for Bill Condon's fine new film, ``Gods and
Monsters.'' It's an inspired, insane and ever so slightly campy
reimagining of Whale's final days.
</P>
<P>
   Openly gay before it was even borderline acceptable, Whale rose
from being a working-class British lad to prominence as one of
Hollywood's most successful directors. He was (and still is) best
known for his classic horror films _ especially the first two
Frankenstein movies. ``The rest were done by hacks,'' he sneers in
``Gods.''
</P>
<P>
   Whale died in 1957 under mysterious circumstances. He hadn't
made a movie in more than a decade and had been largely forgotten
by the fickle, power-hungry Hollywood community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters,'' which is based on a speculative novel by
Christopher Bram, gives us Whale at twilight, played by the
marvelous Ian McKellen as an elegantly sardonic recluse whose
swimming pool and Cezannes can't erase his memories of a dirt-poor
childhood and the horrors of World War I or the encroaching
bitterness of a discarded artist. A stroke has left him physically
frail, and his mental state is increasingly precarious despite the
constant vigilance of his sternly devoted housekeeper (Lynn
Redgrave).
</P>
<P>
   Whale's hermitic existence is occasionally interrupted by a
worshipful monster-movie fan; in one scene, we see him subject a
young male visitor to a wry interview-by-striptease. But his
routine is totally thrown askew by the appearance of the new
gardener. He's Clay (Brendan Fraser), a hunky, decidedly hetero
ex-Marine who becomes Whale's unwitting object of desire.
</P>
<P>
   What ensues is less a tale of predatory seduction than a daring
danse macabre. It's a pas de deux of death and desire, of
self-invention and self-destruction, of passion and poignant
remembrance of things past.
</P>
<P>
   There's terrific work everywhere you look. From Redgrave's
fussily funny fraulein _ she's like a parody of Cloris Leachman's
parodic performance in ``Young Frankenstein'' _ to Fraser's
not-quite-naif. The former ``George of the Jungle'' transforms a
potentially one-joke role into a fully dimensional character. His
symbolic value as Whale's final ``monster/creation'' is laid on a
little thick, but Fraser manages to carry it off, right down to the
squared-off head and shambling gait that began with Boris Karloff
and reached its pop-culture apotheosis in Herman Munster.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film's gnawing, unsettling center is McKellen. He
captures it all: Whale's impishly insinuating lasciviousness, his
malignant self-loathing, his tragic isolation. He gives us a wary,
weary genius, trapped in his own private Sunset Boulevard. The
critics' prizes have already started piling up. An Oscar nomination
seems a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ian McKellen and Brendan Fraser. Directed by Bill
Condon. Not rated, but there are sexual themes and brief nudity. At
Tara. 1 hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It's alive! Thrillingly so.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
