</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-OZONA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   `Ozona' an oasis of cliches in desert
   By Steve Murray
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer-director J.S. Cardone came up with the idea for ``Outside
Ozona'' during nighttime drives through the desert: He wondered who
else was out there, traveling through the dark, listening to the
same lonesome, small-town radio station.
</P>
<P>
   It's a poetic idea (if a tad reminiscent of ``American
Graffiti''), but he buries its potential under movie cliches and
caricatures. His band of strangers in the night include ex-stripper
Earlene (Penelope Ann Miller) and her carny-clown boyfriend Wit
(Kevin Pollak); Odell (Robert Forster), a trucker who befriends
Native American Reba (Kateri Walker) and her dying grandmother; and
a pair of bickering sisters (Sherilyn Fenn and Beth Ann Styne) who
give a lift to a nebbishy fellow named Alan (David Paymer), a
serial killer who specializes in carving the hearts out of women.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, dope-smoking DJ Dix (Taj Mahal) fills the airwaves
with C&AMP;W and R&AMP;B and opens up the phone lines, to the consternation
of his manager, Floyd (Meat Loaf). You hear those names and know
you're in for a long night with so-called ``colorful characters.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie's intended tone is impossible to guess. It tries to
balance its white-trash caricatures and clown jokes with the grisly
butcheries of the killer. Forster provides some laid-back appeal,
and Lucy Webb as an agent on the killer's trail has some nice
deadpan moments. But the material inspires most of the actors to go
cartoonish.
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame them. The characters are as superficial as the
blue eye shadow and pink lipstick Miller has to wear. The writing
never rises above homespun philosophizing, such as, ``Sometimes
you're the windshield, and sometimes you're the bug.'' Watching
this, you'll sympathize with the bug.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside Ozona''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Robert Forster, David Paymer, Taj Mahal and Meat Loaf.
Written and directed by J.S. Cardone. Rated R for nudity,
profanity, violence and gore. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 38
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A tedious mixture of B-movie plotting and
``colorful'' small-town characters.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
