<HEADER>
A5183 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-LASVEGAS-2n     12-17 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-LASVEGAS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
LAS VEGAS: Black Angus fillet. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gambling never stops. From the slots that greet you at the
airport to the packed casinos along the Strip, you can make or lose
a fortune in a night. But legalization of gambling in other parts
of the country has diminished the city's role as a gaming resort
destination. A tourist poll done for the Las Vegas Convention and
Visitors Authority shows that, for the first time, more people are
coming for the entertainment than the gambling. Even so, no other
city can boast casinos as opulent, gaudy, hectic and enormous as
those in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ]The entertainment is amazing. Whatever your taste, you'll find
it in Las Vegas. Be prepared, though. Many top-line stars take
their own vacations during this time of the year. Mirage mainstays
Siegfried and Roy always take the week off.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are fewer stars to go around, it's wise to plan
early which show to see so you can reserve good seats. Pick up the
latest copy of Showbiz Weekly at your travel agent or go to its Web
site at www.lvshowbiz.com for a searchable schedule. What's On/Las
Vegas also has a helpful site at www.whats-on.com. Be sure to check
hotel Web sites, where the schedules may be more up-to-date. And
you may get lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Last Christmas night, Rodney Dangerfield opened at the MGM, and
he'll be back this year. Across the casino, in the main room,
Jackie Chan took time out from breaking things with his head to
host a cavalcade of Asian superstars.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, George Carlin _ the best bargain in town at
under $40 _ had the audience screaming at Bally's; Lionel Ritchie
had them rocking at the Mirage; and the Temptations had them
doo-wopping at the Desert Inn.
</P>
<P>
   And even if you don't find a headliner you like, the big hotels
feature opulent production shows at a reasonable price, usually
around $40. Take your pick of magicians, impressionists or
showgirls. And, if you've wondered whatever happened to David
Cassidy since ``The Partridge Family,'' he's at the MGM, starring
in EFX.
</P>
<P>
   If your taste runs toward the mildly prurient, the topless shows
and strip joints don't close for the holidays. As one tired-looking
dancer at Girls of Glitter Gulch succinctly put it on Christmas
Day, ``It's just another day, baby. Want a dance?''
</P>
<P>
   The shopping is unparalleled. Las Vegas has shops and malls that
make your local upscale mall look like a two-bit strip center.
Visitors spend about $25 billion a year, and that has attracted all
the top names in retail.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes south of the Strip is the Fashion Outlet Mall,
with more than 100 stores and restaurants. The shopping gallery at
the new high-roller hotel Bellagio features Chanel, Hermes,
Tiffany, Gucci, Prada and Armani.
</P>
<P>
   But the crown jewel of malls is the Forum Shops, adjacent to
Caesars, a neoclassical masterpiece with a domed ceiling that
imitates the changing sky. Inside, find statues and enormous Roman
fountains _ even an animatronic Atlantis fountain that comes to
life each 90 minutes as the story of the lost continent unfolds
with flame and thunder. And when you're not gaping at the
architecture, visit FAO Schwarz, Gucci, Bernini, Versace, Ralph
Lauren, Niketown or the Virgin Megastore.
</P>
<P>
   The weather is outstanding. No snow and slush in Las Vegas.
During December, you can expect highs in the low 70s during the
day, dropping to the mid-40s at night, all under cloudless skies.
It's cool enough for a sweater or light jacket and perfect for golf
or tennis, although you'll find the pool areas empty of all but the
hardiest swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   The weirdness is everywhere. Las Vegas truly is one big theme
park of enormous proportions. If you have a car, the first thing
you must do is make the drive from the south end of Las Vegas
Boulevard _ the Strip _ all the way downtown, not just to orient
yourself to this strange new world, but to see some of the most
remarkable architecture on the planet. Admittedly, a lot of it is
bad taste, but consider what you'll see:
</P>
<P>
   The pyramid-shaped Luxor, fronted by an obelisk and a replica of
the Sphinx, stands like an otherworldly sentinel at the far south
end of the Strip. Next door is the medieval castle Excalibur.
Across the street and down the block is the largest hotel in the
world, the emerald-tinted MGM Grand with its new, colossal golden
lion standing guard. The Manhattan skyline, Brooklyn Bridge and
Statue of Liberty wait across the street at New York New York.
</P>
<P>
   Farther up the Strip, you'll pass the Bellagio's Mediterranean
village and the Eiffel Tower under construction at the Paris. The
canals are being readied at the Venetian. The frenetic light show
of Bally's and the Flamingo Hilton are a contrast to the majestic
Roman edifice of Caesars Palace, and the exploding volcano in front
of Mirage and the pirate battles in Treasure Island's lagoon draw
young and old.
</P>
<P>
   Drive on past some of the older Strip hotels and the gaudiest
McDonald's you'll ever see, then past the Stratosphere needle
rising more than a thousand feet in the air, restaurant revolving
at the top, the scary-looking Big Shot roller coaster circling the
tower's mast. Downtown, park and walk to Fremont Street, now a
pedestrian mall, but still home to many of the city's oldest hotels
and casinos, including the Horseshoe and the Golden Nugget. This is
the Vegas you remember from old movies, though now a high-tech
canopy above the street treats visitors to a remarkable video show
at night.
</P>
<P>
   So, go ahead and place your bet. The odds of having a merry
Christmas in this weird winter wonderland are excellent.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
