</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-BRITAIN-1218-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   U.S.-BRITISH COOPERATION ON IRAQ HIGHLIGHTS CLINTON-BLAIR
PARTNERSHIP
   With US-IRAQ-1218.
   By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
   c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In the November episode of the Iraqi crisis, Prime
Minister Tony Blair logged eight phone calls to U.S. President Bill
Clinton in 12 hours before the decision was made to call off the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, as the cruise missiles again were being
targeted to strike Iraq, the phone lines between No. 10 Downing
Street and the White House again were heating up. Afterwards, it
was Blair who first informed the world of the attacks offering the
rationale for the joint American-British action, setting the stage
for Clinton's Oval Office address.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to military action, Britain is the United States
best -- and at times, only -- friend.
</P>
<P>
   And while much of the rest of Europe spent Thursday equivocating
over the attack -- even hinting the air strikes may have had more
to do with Clinton's domestic problems -- than the world's quarrel
with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, Blair maintained a strong
defense of his close, yet troubled friend.
</P>
<P>
   In Parliament, Blair was challenged about the timing of the
attack. George Galloway, a member of Parliament from the Labor
Party, said that the attack amounted to a new Crusade against an
Arab capital. ``But this time led not by Richard the Lion Heart,
but Clinton the liar,'' Galloway said.
</P>
<P>
   Blair denied Clinton's troubles were a factor, saying he was
convinced to act by the evidence and his experience. ``I know that
President Clinton reached the same conclusion for the same
reasons,'' Blair said. ``And had he acted differently out of regard
for the internal matters of U.S. politics that would have been a
dereliction of his duty as President of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, not for the first time, he has shown the courage to
do the right thing, and he has my full support.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   While Blair has his political difficulties, his day after the
first round of attacks was blissful to what his friend was
encountering in Washington. With a few exceptions, the House of
Commons -- not always the friendliest chamber in the world --
offered little but support. Even William Hague, the leader of the
opposition Tories gave his proud blessings.
</P>
<P>
   The news media seemed solidly behind the attack with the
tabloids seeming to revel in headlines such as The Express's ``We
had to Bomb Him'' and Sun's ``BLITZED.'' From the front pages,
Blair -- and Britain -- seemed powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, people who called in television talk shows and sent e-mails
to the BBC's web site expressed nevertheless suspicion about the
timing, suggesting that Blair had gone along with the attacks to
help his old friend.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   Like their predecessors, Ronald Reagan and Margaret Thatcher,
they are close in ideology and political styles. Close in their
ages and political backgrounds, the biggest difference between
Clinton and Blair is their private lives: Blair's is as smooth as
Clinton's is turbulent.
</P>
<P>
   While Blair argues that the Monica Lewinsky affair is an
American problem, the scandal also has dogged Blair for the past
year. Last summer, as Blair welcomed his friend to Northern Ireland
where the two leaders had worked hard to forge a peace, the visit
was undercut by constant questions about the president's problems.
</P>
<P>
   When the prime minister was in New York earlier this year to
address the United Nations, it was the same day that Clinton's
televised grand jury testimony was released.
</P>
<P>
   Blair frequently has been forced into the position of defending
the honesty and integrity of his country's most powerful ally.
</P>
<P>
   For Blair, the main problem with his special relationship with
Clinton appears to be convincing skeptics at home that he is not
merely submitting to the wishes of his senior partner. He at times
is referred to as America's poodle.
</P>
<P>
   Blair shrugs off such attacks. ``When people ask me about
standing by President Clinton,'' Blair said Thursday, ``I've never
been a fair-weather friend and I don't intend to start now.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
