<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5202 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GODS-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      12-17 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODS-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE-AFFIRMING `GODS' GOES DEEP ON RELATIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KYLE LAWSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Gods create. Always been that way, no matter the
mythology. So try this syllogism on for size. Moviemakers create
worlds out of cheesecloth, dreams out of celluloid, idols out of
flickering phantoms. Therefore, moviemakers are gods.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider this old Hollywood wives' tale, attributed to
several producers, most often Sam Goldwyn: ``Make a star, make a
monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps director Bill Condon had something like that in mind
when he conceived his cinematic fantasia on the life of '30s film
director James Whale, titled not so coincidentally ``Gods and
Monsters''?
</P>
<P>
   Whale, of course, did create monsters. The Frankenstein monster,
and the monster's bride, most famously; and the spooky villains of
``TheOld Dark House'' and ``The Invisible Man.'' And he was
cognizant of his role. The preamble to ``Frankenstein'' states,
</P>
<P>
   ``We are about to unfold the story of Frankenstein, a man of
science who sought to create a man after his own image without
reckoning upon God.''
</P>
<P>
   Such audacity is seldom destined for a good end. Whale's career
did not survive the '30s by much. Not because he was gay, as is
usually said. He simply ran out of hits, and nothing offends
Tinseltown's sense of smell more than a man with bad box office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1957, the English-born filmmaker was found floating in his
Hollywood swimming pool. It is generally agreed he was a suicide,
but there are those who persist in believing it was murder.
</P>
<P>
   Condon has used Christopher Bram's novel, ``Father of
Frankenstein,'' which imaginatively and fictionally posits what
happened on that fatal day, as the basis for a film that is one
part tribute, one part eulogy to the golden age of motion pictures
and the artists who gave it its luster _ and to those who sat in
the darkened theaters and were forever changed by what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   If that were all Condon's film had to offer, cinephiles would
get their fix and the picture would make a quick exit from the
multiplexes. ``Gods and Monsters'' is destined for a larger
audience because it is concerned with much more. It is a powerfully
acted, movingly directed story about the dangers and pleasures of
connecting to another human being. A love story, if you will,
although no one in the film ever really commits themselves. It is a
parable that teaches that the creation of love, like the creation
of life, seldom turns out as the gods intend.
</P>
<P>
   The film takes place during the last weeks of the director's
life. Whale (an almost certain to be Oscar-nominated performance by
Ian McKellan) is recovering from a stroke when he conceives a
passion for his gardener, the hunky Clay Boone (Brendan Fraser,
proving that he can be as affecting and serious an actor as he was
a funny one in ``George of the Jungle'').
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished painter, Whale offers to sketch the naive Boone,
who does not realize at first that he is dealing with a gay man. By
the time he does, the relationship between the two has passed
beyond the issue of sex into something far more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Since his stroke, Whale has been victimized by a series of
``brainstorms'' that make him an unwilling voyeur of the past: He
is constantly flashing on scenes from the abusive family life he
has spent his adult life denying; on his traumatic experiences in
the trenches of World War I; and on his unconsummated relationship
with the only man he suspects ``may have ever loved me.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone's childhood and adolescence were equally troubled. He,
too, has never really loved someone, or felt he has been loved.
Slowly, painfully, Whale draws the bleakness out of Boone and is
greatly moved, seeing in him the son he never had. But his mind is
spinning out of control. As Boone begins to think of him in a
fatherly way, Whale begins to regard Boone as that long-ago lover.
</P>
<P>
   Boone, who is straight, finds it difficult to cope with this, as
does Whale's devoted Hungarian housekeeper Hanna (Lynn Redgrave, in
the film's third memorable performance). She is a devout Catholic
who abhors her ``Mister Jimmy's'' sexual proclivities but respects
him as a kind and sensitive man.
</P>
<P>
   Neither love nor hard-learned lessons in tolerance protect them
from watching helplessly as one fuse after another blows in Whale's
brain. To Boone's horror, he finds himself drawn into the
director's plan for ending the misery. In a climatic night of
horror, an attempted rape leads to tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliance of ``Gods and Monsters'' lies in Condon's
skillful mix of reality and metaphor. After watching Whale's 1935
masterpiece, ``The Bride of Frankenstein,'' and blossoming under
his regard, Boone comes to think of the director as his friend and
mentor, his ``creator,'' in fact, since Boone is literally born
again as a functioning human being.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the movie in turn, Whale begins to see Boone as his
``beloved monster.'' Suddenly, it is no longer Colin Clive and
Boris Karloff ``we'' are watching in the clips from ``The Bride of
Frankenstein,'' it is Whale and Boone. The line between the screen
and the auditorium is erased and, as in so much of today's
movie-made America, it becomes difficult to tell which is which.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters'' is a serious movie, dealing with serious
issues, but Condon never loses his sense of humor. His screenplay
is often witty and sometimes just plain funny, as in a poolside
interview with a geeky college student that a bored Whale turns
into a game of strip poker.
</P>
<P>
   There's also an extended set-piece at a party at George Cukor's
estate, which involves Princess Margaret, Elizabeth Taylor, Karloff
and Elsa Lanchester, the real ``bride'' of Frankenstein. Condon has
a marvelous time (as does the audience) puncturing the egos and
pretensions of the film industry.
</P>
<P>
   The ending itself, which it is to be hoped no one gives away, is
wonderfully life-affirming.
</P>
<P>
   Movies, James Agee once said, are a chance to travel the paths
we would otherwise avoid. So it is with ``Gods and Monsters.''
James Whale is consumed with a nostalgia for what never was, Clay
Boone for what might never be. Such a collision of hopes is a
forceful reminder that those who wait to know the outcome of the
journey never take the first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters'' is unrated. There is moderate profanity
and a brief instance of male frontal nudity. 4 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
