 UNDATED: `Bonfire''' (Holden). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRONGFULLY ACCUSED
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $104.16. 85 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Proft's film sets up some potentially funny situations for
Leslie Nielsen, who has shown he can make the most of them in the
``Naked Gun'' series. In Proft's takeoff on ``The Fugitive,'' he is
Ryan Harrison, Lord of the Violin, wrongfully convicted of a
killing committed, he claims, by a one-armed, one-eyed, one-legged
terrorist. ``Titanic,'' ``Baywatch'' and other productions are ripe
for spoofing, but too much of this is adolescent humor with no real
comic payoff. ``Unfortunately, most of the jokes just aren't very
funny'' (Anita Gates). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLADE
</P>
<P>
   1998. New Line. $107.37. 121 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a different kind of disco, sprinkler heads in the ceiling
spew blood for a crowd of vampires. Enter Blade (Wesley Snipes), a
ridiculous figure draped with what looks like automobile seat
belts, who blows the celebrants to bits. A half-human, Blade has
been dedicated to ridding the world of vampires, who claimed his
mother moments before he was born. That sounds like a low-rent
``Batman,'' but though the limited Snipes seems to have found a
role he is comfortable with, the vehicle is no more than a
``cartoonish futuristic action-adventure yarn'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW TITLES OF INTEREST, SOME OF WHICH MAY HAVE HAD A
THEATER RELEASE AT ONE TIME OR APPEARED ON TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   ANTOINE ET ANTOINETTE and RENDEZVOUS DE JUILLET: The French
director Jacques Becker, who began as an assistant to Jean Renoir
and is remembered primarily for his masterpiece, the period love
story ``Casque d'Or'' (1952), made only 13 films. But Becker was
also highly regarded by New Wave filmmakers for lesser works that
blended love and social settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antoine et Antoinette'' (78 minutes), about the troubled
relationship of a young Parisian working-class couple, won the
Grand Prix at the Cannes International Film Festival in 1947.
``Rendezvous de Juillet'' (1949) follows a group of young people
who spurn the bourgeoisie in postwar Paris. Water Bearer. $29.95
each. French with English subtitles. Release date: Tuesday.
Information: (800) 551-8304.
</P>
<P>
   GORILLA BATHES AT NOON: In Dusan Makavejev's film, the collapse
of the Soviet Union takes on a certain poignancy through the
goofball adventures of Maj. Victor Borisovich, who is stranded in
Berlin after his unit deserts. Riding a bicycle decorated with the
hammer and sickle and wandering as a kind of post-Communist
Candide, Victor visits a Siberian tiger at the zoo and watches a
huge statue of Lenin being dismantled. Facets. $59.95. 83 minutes.
English, German and Russian with English subtitles. Information:
(800) 331-6197.
</P>
<P>
   SAM SHEPARD: STALKING HIMSELF. Bits of his plays and interviews
with actors are capped with a close, revealing conversation with
the playwright himself, a notably private man who discusses his
troubled youth and relationship with his father. 1998. Fox Lorber.
$19.98. 60 minutes.
</P>
