<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Fighting Video Piracy  
 Where Do All the Old Films Go?  
 New Releases of Video Cassettes: Reviews by New York Times
Critics  
 Other New Titles of Interest  
(mk) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THEATERS FIGHT PIRATING OF FILMS: When reached on his cell
phone, Bill Shannon was in Brooklyn helping police shut down
another video piracy operation. ``It was one of the bigger ones,''
he said. ``A lab and warehouse, 173 VCRs, 7,000 pieces of finished
product. There were 10 arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon directs the antipiracy efforts of the Motion Picture
Association of America, the studios' trade association. Bootleg
videos have been everywhere for years, of course. But recently,
Shannon said, the association has been devoting more resources to
the problem, and prosecutors and police have been taking it more
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The association announced on Monday that it was enlisting the
public. Through Dec. 31 in 33 theaters in New York City, messages
on screen before films are shown ask audiences to watch for people
using camcorders to shoot the films while they are on the big
screen and to report them to theater managements.
</P>
<P>
   Tapes from camcorders are duplicated to make usually very poor _
but occasionally quite good _ copies of movies, which are then sold
on street corners, in flea markets and similar outlets.
</P>
<P>
   New York City is a hotbed of such activity. ``I don't know why
New York,'' said Jack Valenti, the association's president.
``Everybody there is a wannabe filmmaker, I guess.'' Earlier this
year 70,000 bootleg copies of ``Titanic'' were confiscated in New
York. The overwhelming demand for that film made it a special case,
but piracy is always rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Bootleg videos often appear before a film opens in theaters,
which means they have been made from prints that have been stolen
or otherwise misappropriated with the help of someone with access
to them. Camcorders, which are better and smaller than ever (making
them harder to detect), appear during the theater run. ``They've
always been a problem because you don't have to steal something or
bribe somebody,'' Valenti said.
</P>
<P>
   By the association's estimate, the studios lose $250 million a
year to piracy.
</P>
<P>
   SALVAGING OLDIES: It's surprising how often well-known older
films fall out of video distribution. For example, until recently
Woody Allen's ``Take the Money and Run,'' John Huston's ``Prizzi's
Honor,'' Jonathan Demme's ``Melvin and Howard'' and Mike Nichols'
``Silkwood'' were around only in old cassettes.
</P>
<P>
   One small distributor, Anchor Bay of Troy, Mich., is very
aggressive at recycling titles like these. All four films are out
in new Anchor Bay editions, and next year they will be joined by
``Lovers and Other Strangers'' (Diane Keaton's film debut), ``The
Ipcress File,'' with Michael Caine and Nigel Green, Werner Herzog's
``Fitzcaraldo,'' and many other older and highly regarded films.
</P>
<P>
   Why do studios seemingly ``let go'' of notable old movies?
``They're under the gun to sell new titles,'' said Jay Douglas,
Anchor Bay's vice president of acquisitions. Emphasis on the new
sometimes loosens the grip on the old. Studios hang on to
television rights but consider it too expensive to keep marketing
many of their old movies as packaged goods.
</P>
<P>
   Often video rights revert to producers, directors or
institutions like banks. ``That's opened the doors for us to make
licensing deals,'' Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   HAVE PLENTY
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $104.96. 92 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Young black New York professionals convene for mating and power
games, but fortunately a certain screwball element slips through in
Christopher Scott Cherot's film. The savior is Lee Plenty, a
self-deprecating aspiring novelist who, by reason of having
attended college with these people, finds himself in the same shark
tank. The only one without money, Lee camps out in the apartment of
the avidly materialistic Havilland (Chenoa Maxwell), who is about
to be engaged to an arrogant singer (Hill Harper). Lee's relaxed,
engaging response to the situation, Stephen Holden wrote in The New
York Times, makes him ``one of the most original and likable
characters to pop up in a movie in quite a while.''
</P>
<P>
   COUSIN BETTE
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox. $100.96. 107 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In tackling a film version of Balzac's novel, Des McAnuff's film
tries to connect a feverish mid-19th-century tale, an antecedent of
``The Bonfire of the Vanities,'' to today's egomaniacal movers and
shakers. Out to avenge her mistreatment at the hands of cloddish
relatives, the black-clad title character (Jessica Lange) gives
back as good as she gets. If only she weren't so grim and
monochromatic about it, we might get more satisfaction. But on
screen such an elaborate literary tale ``feels as rushed,
overstuffed and devoid of texture as Brian DePalma's hopelessly
stunted screen adaptation of `Bonfire''' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
