<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5214 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAIL-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      12-17 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAIL-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYAN, HANKS LOG ON TO A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - You'll have to get over the idea that they've made a
sequel to ``Sleepless in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``You've Got Mail'' does have the same two stars and the
same writer-director, and, yes, it's a romantic comedy about people
who haven't met _ but it's a different one.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``You've Got Mail'' becomes quite romantically
wonderful at times, it may work better for people who didn't like
``Sleepless in Seattle'' than for people who started meetin g all
their dates at the Empire State Building.
</P>
<P>
   How should you approach ``You've Got Mail''? Think Hepburn and
Tracy. That's the kind of easy comic grace that the re-pairing of
Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks brings to the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Kelly (Ryan) and Joe Fox (Hanks) are Net friends,
conducting a long-running e-mail relationship without ever having
met.
</P>
<P>
   Or so they think.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they have met in non-cyberspace, but they don't know
it because they despise each other.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen has good reason for her feelings. She owns a small
children's bookstore on Manhattan's Upper West Side, while Joe owns
the new giant bookstore moving into the neighborhood and
threatening to run her out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Though the story spins slowly around the eventuality of their
realizing who they are and what they might mean to each other,
writer-director Nora Ephron uses their situation to explore several
provocative, but non-romantic, themes.
</P>
<P>
   Through their thoughtful e-mail messages, Ephron establishes a
literary communion that mirrors the intellectually seductive lure
of ``84 Charing Cross Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Ephron pours out her love for books and for people who care
about the written word. She takes her time to create complex
characters so that Kathleen and Joe rise beyond the moony looks of
a sentimental love affair.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, Ephron reduces the number of one-liners. The movie
is often amusing, and ultimately winning, but rarely causes you to
laugh out loud. Ephron builds the story, not slowly, but leisurely,
so we have time to share their lives in full dimensions. The
director can succeed without fast, snappy comedy because Ryan and
Hanks carry the movie over the gaps in its laugh lines.
</P>
<P>
   With those eyes and that smile, Ryan begins the movie in her
typically adorable fashion, wearing socks with her flannel PJs. But
she grows with the character until, like Hanks, she isn't only
funny or romantic but a real person struggling with her future.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks and Ryan are so comfortable working together, in the
sparring comedy and the deeper moments, that they allow each other
room to express a range of emotions. There's nothing rushed or
forced about them. They click when they fight, and they blend when
they fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``You've Got Mail'' is a re-imagining of the Jimmy
Stewart-Margaret Sullavan comedy ``The Shop Around the Corner,''
people will more often compare it to Ephron's ``Sleepless in
Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it isn't as sentimental as ``Sleepless,'' ``You've Got
Mail'' is for people looking for a little less volume in their
romances and a little more sophistication in their comedies. Go to
see it when you feel like taking the time to settle in, as you
would with a good book. The movie grows on you until you don't want
to leave it.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG, ``You've Got Mail'' contains some minor profanity but
no sex or nudity. 4 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
