<HEADLINE>
`PRINCE' RAISES ART TO NEW LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Cast of thousands! Years in the making!
</P>
<P>
   It's rare to see that kind of film promotion anymore. With the
rare ``Titanic'' exception, studios can't afford such costly
spectacle. Except in the wonderful world of animation, where
artists are set free to create as spectacular a movie as ``The
Prince of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   This animated Bible story raises the level of film artistry to
new heights, and it's a joy to go along for that ride.
</P>
<P>
   In lively fashion, ``The Prince of Egypt'' traces the story of
Moses (voiced by Val Kilmer), the Hebrew baby raised in the royal
house of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   In this version of the Moses story, the boy grows into a
teenager, thinking he is an Egyptian prince. He prepares to take
his place with his brother, Ramses (Ralph Fiennes), and continue
the expansion of the Egyptian empire, which is built upon the bent
backs of Hebrew slaves.
</P>
<P>
   When Moses discovers the truth of his Hebrew heritage, he leaves
Egypt and lives in the wilderness until God appears and instructs
him to go back and lead his people to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   These adventures are told in bright, lively style that will
please kids and parents alike, with vibrant use of songs to
dramatize the story and just enough humor to leaven it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt'' comes from DreamWorks Pictures, headed
by Steven Spielberg and former Disney executive Jeffrey Katzenberg.
Other studios have tried to move in on Disney's profitable family
animation market _ most notably Fox Studio, with its
Phoenix-produced ``Anastasia'' _ by imitating Disney. DreamWorks
tries something new: raising the level of animation to challenge
Disney.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how Disney reacts to the
challenge. If it raises its own standards, we could be in for a
whole new realm of animated delights.
</P>
<P>
   The artwork in ``The Prince of Egypt,'' vastly aided by
computer-enhanced animation techniques, is spectacular and so
gorgeous that you often forget you're watching animation.
</P>
<P>
   The parting of the Red Sea is a marvel that would awe Cecil B.
DeMille himself.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also takes a good deal of the cute out of the typical
Disney animated fairy tale. ``
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt'' has its funny moments, but it tells the
Bible story with the intention of illuminating the historic issues
of slavery and faith.
</P>
<P>
   Biblical scholars and fundamentalists may object to the
liberties taken with the story.
</P>
<P>
   But any movie that gets families talking about religious issues
has performed a valuable service to our society.
</P>
<P>
   That makes ``The Prince of Egypt'' a good film for children,
although kids younger than 5 may find a couple of scenes of
Egyptian cruelty a little too realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg, the film's producer, has said the movie may be
inappropriate for children under 7 _ not because there's anything
untoward but because the story may be too difficult for young
children to follow.
</P>
<P>
   I think young kids will get caught up in the excitement of the
action, the music and the artwork, and not mind what story
subtleties they miss.
</P>
<P>
   They don't care about the adult jokes in such movies as
``Mulan,'' and they won't be affected by the things that go over
their heads here.
</P>
<P>
   Even though this is more sophisticated than the typical animated
film, it's thoroughly enjoyable, and kids should find it a
thrilling experience.
</P>
<P>
   If you're taking young kids to see ``The Prince of Egypt,'' you
may want to talk to them about the Bible story before they see it,
as the movie is bound to raise questions for discussion afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Most animated movies are rated G, which is as family-friendly as
the ratings get. While ``The Prince of Egypt'' is on a par with the
others, it is rated PG because of its more sophisticated subject
matter. 4 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
