<HEADLINE>
GOLF SCORES NO LONGER A HANDICAP FOR SOFTWARE INVENTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN D. ABBEY  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON PARK, N.Y. _ John Pritchard, a bank association
executive and avid golfer, had a problem. He wanted to play exotic
golf games with complicated scoring methods such as Nassau,
Scramble, Vegas and others even more obscure for those who like to
bet a few dollars on the side.
</P>
<P>
   But he couldn't keep up with the scoring _ and didn't like
relying on a partner who kept scratching out numbers on a small
piece of paper with a nub of a pencil. So he did something about
it. He invented a computer program that fits on certain types of
hand-held computers, allowing individuals and golf foursomes to
keep score of one or even multiple golf games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a golfer, I knew what I needed,'' he said. Now, three
years after first coming up with the idea, the businessman and
councilman in the upstate New York town of Clifton Park wants to
license the program to a computer manufacturer and sell it over the
Internet to other golf-obsessed individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The program, Score Pro, allows entry of golf course information,
player handicaps, game choices and wagers prior to a golf round.
The program automatically calculates scores and winnings. Unlike
some other golf scoring programs, he said, it permits recalculation
is someone enters an incorrect score.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more or less a hobby for me,'' said Pritchard, who is
now entering into negotiations with Philips Electronics,
manufacturer of a hand-held computer with enough computing power to
operate the software. But the project has occupied him for evenings
and weekends as he ran, tested and debugged the software through a
contract with the General Electric Co. He is now at the stage that
the product is being marketed for $39.95 on its own website
(http://www.scorepro.com).
</P>
<P>
   He also plans ads in the catalogs that come with certain
hand-held computers. The program runs on hand-held machines with
16-bit processors, a hefty amount for a small machine, as well as
certain Psion devices. At the moment the machine does not run on
the popular Palm Pilot series of pocket organizers, which do not
have enough computing power.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard would not say how much he has invested in Score Pro,
only saying that the figure is substantial. Nor will he say how
much he expects to earn from the project. But he said he is turning
down initial offers of investment capital because he does not want
to give up any equity in the company he has created to own the
software, Sandtrap Software Llc.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not give up his job as executive director of
the Independent Bankers Association of New York State Inc. in
Albany, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
