<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5355 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-MAIL18-COX     12-17 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-MAIL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   It's tough taking on a 1940s classic loved by all, but Tom Hanks
and Meg Ryan are up to the task
   By Steve Murray
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of seemingly sure-thing movies that tanked _ think
``Meet Joe Black'' and the ``Babe'' sequel _ you can't take
anything for granted in Hollywood. You might even fear the worst
from the can't-miss reunion of the ``Sleepless in Seattle'' team,
re-creating a classic film. But you can stop holding your breath.
``You've Got Mail'' delivers.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Ernst Lubitsch's beloved 1940 film ``The Shop Around the
Corner'' hits the Internet age, giving director and co-writer Nora
Ephron a chance to reunite Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan in a story ideal
for their charms.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks plays Joe Fox, scion of a book-chain business that's
inexorably wiping out mom-and-pop shops. Such as the one owned by
Kathleen Kelly (Ryan), a children's book nook called, yes, the Shop
Around the Corner.
</P>
<P>
   A legacy of her mother, now deceased, the store represents the
human touch that seems nearly extinct in today's corporate,
electronic landscape. But here's an irony: Even though she's
suspicious of the cultural globalization represented by the
computer, Kathleen gets her biggest kicks online. She's carrying on
a romantic e-mail correspondence with a man she knows only as
``dear friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you haven't seen Lubitsch's movie or the two musical
versions of the story (``In the Good Old Summertime'' onscreen and
``She Loves Me'' onstage), you can probably guess the rest. Yep _
unbeknownst to either party, Joe and Kathleen, who openly spar over
the buffet table at West Side parties, are each other's electronic
sweethearts.
</P>
<P>
   The movie further complicates things by giving our leads
significant others. Kathleen's neo-Luddite boyfriend, Frank (Greg
Kinnear), is a newspaper columnist so opposed to technology that he
writes on a peculiar machine called a typewriter. Joe's editor
girlfriend, Patricia (Parker Posey), is so high-strung that, as he
puts it, she makes coffee nervous.
</P>
<P>
   They're both broadly drawn enough to pose no threat to the
central romance. Besides, Joe and Kathleen are their own biggest
obstacles, battling ever more fiercely in the real world while
their online attraction deepens.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's update to the Internet era is more than just a
logical change. There's something about the disembodied nature of
chat rooms and e-mail that contains both anticipation and
loneliness. And while ``Mail'' (written by Ephron and her sister
Delia) ignores some of the darker edges in ``Shop Around the
Corner,'' Hanks and Ryan make their characters' search for love
delicate and real.
</P>
<P>
   The Ephrons give us a glossy, storybook Manhattan of clean
streets and cozy, well-decorated apartments. The lively supporting
cast includes Steve Zahn, the stoned crook from ``Out of Sight,''
and Jean Stapleton as Kathleen's employees. Kinnear is pleasant in
a two-dimensional part, while the manic Posey has too little to do
but steals every scene she's in.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan threatens to go into overkill on cuteness, hopping around
her apartment in her pajamas at the movie's beginning. But she
calms down and delivers a lovely, modulated performance _ even if
she's not Margaret Sullavan, who did the role for Lubitsch. It also
helps that Ryan has Hanks to play off of. With every new movie,
through his charm and his range, Hanks continues to prove that he
really is
</P>
<P>
   our best replacement for Jimmy Stewart _ who, by the way,
starred in ``The Shop Around the Corner.''
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``You've Got Mail''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan. Directed by Nora Ephron. Rated
PG. 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: ``The Shop Around the Corner'' hits the Internet
age, and retains much of its charm.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
