<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5356 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER18-COX     12-17 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   MTV special proves 'twas a hip-hop year
   By Phil Kloer
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Barbara Walters counts down her ``10 Most Fascinating
People of 1998'' on Tuesday night, you can bet she'll be
hard-pressed to get a mention in of the Beastie Boys, Jay-Z,
Marilyn Manson or Courtney Love. For those, you'll have to turn to
``Ultra Sound: Year in Rock '98'' (4 p.m. E.S.T. Saturday on MTV),
the music channel's annual retrospective of those who try so hard
not to be retro.
</P>
<P>
   As the special points out, 1998 wasn't much of a year for rock.
Albums by Pearl Jam and Smashing Pumpkins didn't live up to sales
expectations; the aforementioned Manson and Love's band Hole
debuted well but soon went south, even if ``Celebrity Skin'' had
maybe the greatest hook of the year. But they have a little fun
with the idea of interchangeable one-hit wonders, going to a
Matchbox 20 concert and asking fans if they can name even one
member of the band. They can't.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was a hip-hop year, with MTV paying the most
attention to Lauryn Hill, Jay-Z, DMX, Master P and the Beasties.
(It would have been cool if they could have spared a few seconds
for Outkast.)
</P>
<P>
   There's a segment on boy bands, those quintets like Backstreet
Boys and 'N Sync known for their shaved chests, step dancing and
squealing teeny-fans, and one on Mariah Carey, who's interviewed
lounging on a couch, her hair spread out behind her in an effect
that must have taken hours to capture, saying she leads a ``boring
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra, who hated rock, gets a passing mention for his
death, which is more than he would have wanted in a special like
this.
</P>
<P>
   And it all winds down, as the year itself does, with the
Clinton-Lewinsky scandal, with video clips played while Offspring
sings its signature line: ``And all the girlies say I'm pretty fly
for a white guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
