<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5378 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-NYTSF     12-17 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELL KIDS THE TRUTH ABOUT SEX AND VALUES 
 FOR USE FRI., DEC. 18 OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: With the headlines from Washington being what they
are, how do you explain to young kids issues about sex? I didn't
think I would have to tell them for years!
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: The basic rule in talking to kids about sex is to be
honest and straightforward. Answer the questions that are asked and
not the ones that you assume they'll want to know. Kids should know
about sex from very early on, not because they need the information
but because you'll get the practice of being honest and
straightforward about a subject that is difficult for all of us to
talk about. The earlier you start telling them about the basics,
the easier it will be for you when they really need the
information. Don't assume it's EVER too early and when it comes to
headlines, you can just explain in a straightforward manner not
only about sex but about your value system, understanding they will
evolve their own.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: What do you do about ``difficult'' people at work?
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Realistically we all know that some people are more
difficult to get along with than others because we clash in style,
because they don't do what we want them to do, because they remind
us of our mother or our father. The first thing NOT to do is to
define them as difficult, as your enemy, as the bane of your
existence Once you define someone as ``difficult,'' you have given
them an enormous amount of power. See if you can problem-solve
instead of label. See if you can say, for example, ``Listen, if you
can tell me what would make you happier, I would be glad to do it''
rather then telling an audience how difficult the person is.
Complaining will just convince you that the person has more power
than you do.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: Monday, Monday, why do I always have the Monday
morning blues and is there anything I can do about them?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. JOY: Before you decide that's what everybody has, let's take
a look at your lifestyle. Are you changing your sleep patterns over
the weekend. It may be that you are catching up on sleep by
sleeping late. Then when Monday morning comes and you have to get
up at the usual time, your mind is saying ``Oh, no!'' as your body
is following suit. So see if you can't take naps over the weekend
rather than sleeping in.
</P>
<P>
   Second, are you over imbibing over the weekend? That Monday
morning blahs may be a simple hangover. OK, I know I sound like
your Aunt Matilda, but you know what I'm saying.
</P>
<P>
   Third, make sure your work isn't just so stressful for you that
you just dread going into work. Monday morning can be just another
day of the week. It's never going to be like Friday, but at least
you can get rid of some of those blahs.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: You wrote the book ``Dating for Dummies,'' so how do
you find the perfect date?
</P>
<P>
   DR.JOY: Don't look for ``the perfect date,'' because then you'd
be looking for ``the perfect date 2'' and then where are you? Most
of us aren't perfect. The first thing to do when you're starting
dating is making sure that you're not particularly needy. It's not
appropriate to use another person as the Spackle and the plaster of
your life. What you want to do is be your best, most self-assured,
most you-ish self. Then if you meet somebody, terrific. And if you
don't meet somebody, then hey! your life is working very well on
its own.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that this is Noah's Ark and you have to have somebody
of the opposite sex or you're going to drown because a storm is
coming is just not accurate. The weather forecast isn't all that
bad. You can learn to swim, you can buy a boat or you can float.
The point is that before you start looking for someone in your life
make sure there already is a special someone in your life. And that
special someone is Y-O-U.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: Hi, Dr. Browne! I want this girl to notice me but how
should I approach her. She does not know me. I don't know her. I
see her in my grandmother's apartment building Do you have any
ideas that would help me?
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: The way to make contact with anybody at any age is
first of all through the eyeballs. Look them in the eye, SMILE.
That's all you have to do to begin with. What you want to do is
neither be frightened by the experience or frighten the other
person. As people get to know you, as they see you, as you look
familiar and non-threatening, they will open themselves up a little
more to you.
</P>
<P>
   The whole experience, young or old, dating or not dating, is
just a little bit of discovery. Smile and if she smiles back and
makes eye contact, then you can move on that important subject the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, NY 10168, or to
drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered in
this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters cannot
be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1998 by Dr. Joy Browne Distributed by New York Times
Special Features
</P>
