<HEADLINE>
LEONARD M. RIESER, 76; WAS KEEPER OF THE `DOOMSDAY CLOCK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The keeper of the ``Doomsday Clock'' has died.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard M. Rieser of Norwich, Vt., who as chairman of the board
of the Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists was seen in numerous news
photographs resetting the hands of the ``Doomsday Clock'' that the
journal uses to dramatize the threat of nuclear war, died of cancer
Tuesday in Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center in Lebanon, N.H. He
was 76.
</P>
<P>
   A participant in the Manhattan Project, which developed the
first atomic bomb, Mr. Rieser was a professor and administrator at
Dartmouth College for 30 years
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rieser was born in Chicago. He attended Dartmouth for two
years before transferring to the University of Chicago, where he
graduated in 1953 under an accelerated program while serving in the
Army. He did research for the Manhattan Project in Chicago and then
in Los Alamos Laboratory in New Mexico, where he witnessed the
first atomic bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he earned a doctorate at Stanford University,
where he taught before joining the faculty at Dartmouth in 1952. He
was chairman of Dartmouth's physics department from 1957 to 1959.
From 1964 until his retirement in 1982, he alternately served in
the posts of dean of faculty and provost of the school.
</P>
<P>
   He had been chairman of the board of the Bulletin of the Atomic
Scientists since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rieser was interested in making sure children got a chance
to learn about science. When he discovered that his children's
elementary school didn't have a science program, he began making
regular visits to the school with magnets and test tubes, sporting
his electric light bow tie to spark the youngsters' enthusiasm. He
helped establish the Montshire Museum of Science in Norwich and was
president of its board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Rosemary; a daughter, Abigail, of
Northampton, Mass.; three sons, Leonard of Philadelphia, Timothy S.
of Washington, D.C., and Kenneth Willis of Princeton, N.J.; two
brothers, Lawrence of Jackson, Wyo.; and William of Perkasie, Pa.;
and three granddaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1759EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
