<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HALL-SANDLIN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   EAST TEXAS LAWMAKERS STILL OPPOSING EACH OTHER ON IMPEACHMENT
   450 words
   By EUNICE MOSCOSO
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the nation braced for the possible impeachment
of President Clinton and the consequences of a military strike
against Iraq during the busy holiday season, a Texas lawmaker
summed it all up in five words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a strange time,'' said Rep. Max Sandlin, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of all the chaos, Sandlin of Marshall said
Thursday his decision to vote against impeachment has not wavered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the U.S. Constitution requires that impeachment is
only used for fundamental offenses against our system of
government,'' he said. ``This does not reach the standards of
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Democrat Rep. Ralph Hall of Rockwall is equally staunch
in his decision to vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he believes the president committed perjury at least
11 times and that perjury is a felony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took an oath to uphold the law,'' he said, adding that
``there is no pleasure'' in casting a vote to impeach the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders decided Thursday to begin the impeachment
debate Friday on the House floor and finish action on the four
articles of impeachment against Clinton by Saturday even if U.S.
attacks against Iraq are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin said he thinks it is ``inappropriate'' and
``outrageous'' to consider impeaching the president in the middle
of an armed conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to go ahead and vote,'' he said. ``The
Congress has to set an agenda just as the president set his.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he doesn't think the attacks on Iraq ``strengthened
the president at all.'' When asked if an impeachment debate could
hurt the morale of U.S. troops, Hall said he couldn't answer that
question but added, ``Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   A simple House majority of 218 votes is enough to impeach
Clinton. If the House approves articles of impeachment, the Senate
would be forced to hold a trial. It takes a two-thirds Senate
majority to convict a president and remove him from office, and few
people believe the Senate, which will have 55 Republicans and 45
Democrats next year, will find the 67 votes needed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin said it would be a ``misuse'' of the system to use
impeachment to ``dispose of'' the problem, knowing that the Senate
will not convict the president. He added that a Senate trial would
be ``very divisive for the country'' and would ``certainly put the
brakes on'' dealing with several important issues such as Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin said he has spoken to about 100 House members in the
past few weeks and that some Republican House members are searching
for ``a way out'' but are concerned their party leaders would
object.
</P>
<P>
   ``They simply can't find a graceful exit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
