A5424 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     12-17 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANGOLD SWITCHES DIRECTORIAL GEARS 
THE INTERNET AS A PLOT DEVICE 
ROCK 'N' ROLL REUNION, SORT OF
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa., N.Y.)   (mk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Ever since the witty war film ``King of Hearts''
demonstrated with hilarity that ``crazy people'' locked up in
asylums may well be saner, or at least more humane, than those
outside, movies have occasionally flirted with the notion of
whether we should trust the guard or the inmate. Think of ``One
Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,'' or even ``The Dream Team,'' films
that were both poignant and comic.
</P>
<P>
   The ``King of Hearts'' for the new generation may be ``Girl,
Interrupted,'' which is based on the powerful memoir by Susanna
Kaysen about how her rebelliousness and uncertainty as a teen-ager
at the height of the 1960s got her committed to an institution.
This time, don't expect a lot of laughs.
</P>
<P>
   The director of ``Girl, Interrupted'' is James Mangold, who was
also one of the writers of the screenplay. The film stars a host of
strong young actresses, including Winona Ryder, Angelina Jolie,
Brittany Murphy and Clea DuVall. Shooting will begin in late
January in Harrisburg, Pa., and though there is a relatively modest
$20 million budget, Mangold promises that the film will have great
emotional heft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to play the women as just victims,'' Mangold
said. ``There is not going to be a misty gauze over this
institution. There's a way to tell this story with an aggressive
point of view, without pulling punches. These characters have a
clear lens on their world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mangold was not the most obvious choice to make this difficult
movie, which involves a harrowing emotional journey. His last film
was ``Cop Land,'' a critically well received police drama that
starred Sylvester Stallone, Ray Liotta, Harvey Keitel and Robert De
Niro. That movie had a lot of testosterone, not fine emotional
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   But Mangold said that ``Cop Land,'' not ``Girl, Interrupted,''
was the aberration and that he was more comfortable with wordplay
than gunplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``After `Cop Land,' I missed working with women characters,'' he
said. ``I felt like I'd spent 12 weeks in a locker room. I was
suddenly perceived as a guy who was going to make these cop movies,
or guy movies. I've always been interested in dramas that really
mean it, that have a point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Mangold said he read an early script for the movie shortly after
finishing ``Cop Land'' and immediately sat down to write his own
version, focusing on creating a clear narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book is really episodic and I wanted to build a strong
narrative structure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he said, the story has much in common with ``The
Wizard of Oz,'' another sort of journey. As in that story, Mangold
said, the journey is harrowing and, at times, joyful. But at the
critical moment, when Dorothy learns that she has had the key to
escaping Oz in herself all along, she can move on only by leaving
behind the companions who helped bring her this knowledge. And so,
too, Susanna grows by saying goodbye to the friends in the
institution who were essential to her passage.
</P>
<P>
   Computer Couple
</P>
<P>
   Will young people line up to see an old-fashioned romantic
comedy?
</P>
<P>
   That is a question Nora Ephron is testing in ``You've Got
Mail,'' her latest effort to make falling in love funny and
compelling. The movie is expensive _ $60 million before marketing
costs _ so unlike the cheaper ``Sleepless in Seattle,'' her last
foray into the genre, this film is going to require a broader
audience to deliver a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ephron, who directed and was a writer and producer of
``You've Got Mail,'' to be released on Friday, acknowledged that
this movie had to bring in a more youthful audience and could not
be for women only, as some romantic movies tend to be. Her solution
was using the Internet as a plot device; it is how the fated lovers
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Shuler Donner, one of the producers, said the Internet
was the movie's ``insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is basically a young person's thing,'' Ms. Donner
said. ``They like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't call ``You've Got Mail'' a sequel to the highly
successful ``Sleepless in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's at all similar,'' said Ms. Ephron, although
she admitted that having Meg Ryan (who just received a Golden Globe
nomination for her role) star opposite Tom Hanks again and having
them follow a tangled path before finding each other, and love,
again might lead some to that conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleepless'' frequently referred to a film from the golden era,
``An Affair to Remember.'' And ``You've Got Mail'' is essentially a
remake of a film from the golden era romantic comedy, ``The Shop
Around the Corner,'' which starred James Stewart and was set in
Budapest.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the story has a long provenance. It was originally a
play, ``Parfumerie,'' by Nikolaus Laszlo, then ``The Shop Around
the Corner,'' the film directed by Ernst Lubitsch. It was
transformed into a musical, ``In the Good Old Summertime'' and then
transformed again into a Broadway musical, ``She Loves Me.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``You've Got Mail,'' the couple has moved from Budapest to
New York; in fact, Ms. Ephron described the film as a valentine to
the Upper West Side of Manhattan, where she lives and which is
lovingly portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
