<P>
   IRAQ-GINGRICH - Speaker Newt Gingrich on Thursday cautioned
critics of President Clinton's decision to attack Iraq that ``there
is no alternative'' to U.S. leadership. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-BOMBING _ WASHINGTON _ Has the United States really done
any good by launching air strikes against Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein? Developing. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RAMADAN _ WASHINGTON _ The significance of the Muslim holy
period of Ramadan has been mentioned by many as a major factor in
the timing of the U.S. air strikes. What is it? Why is it
significant? (Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-WORLD _ WASHINGTON _ A wrap-up of the world reaction to the
U.S.-Britain bombing of Iraq. Developing. (Mollison, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ Russia, China and France deplored the
U.S. and British attacks on Iraq, with the harshest rhetoric coming
from Moscow. Russia said the attacks could scuttle a plan by
Russia's parliament to approve the long-delayed START II nuclear
reduction treaty. Russia, China and France -- long supportive of
more conciliatory posture toward Iraq -- faulted the Clinton
administration for refusing to seek approval from the U.N. Security
Council before launching the strikes. Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov called on U.N. chief weapons inspector Richard Butler to be
replaced. The Duma, the lower house of parliament, accused the U.S.
and Britain of international terrorism. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-BRITAIN _ LONDON _ At the height of the last crisis over
Iraq, Prime Minister Blair and President Clinton spoke together by
phone eight times in 12 hours. There is no reason to believe that
the two leaders communicated any less this time. Among world
leaders, Blair stands nearly alone in his support of the United
States particularly his close personal friend Bill Clinton. On
Thursday, Blair defended Clinton against assertions that the
military strike was launched to help Clinton with his domestic
crisis. Blair said that after consulting with Clinton, it became
clear that they would have been derelict in their duties not to
launch the attack. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-DEPLOY _ Specialized air groups from Georgia bases,
including the Air Force's only all-weather airborne target locator,
have been ordered to the Persian Gulf but so far there are no
unscheduled large-scale deployments. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-FAITH _ Hanukkah, Ramadan and Christmas make this holiday
season a special and spiritual time for observant Jews, Muslims and
Christians. But Wednesday's bombing of Iraq by U.S. forces is a
sober reminder that the problems of the world never go away. We
talk with ministers, rabbis and, hopefully, an Iman to guage the
reaction of Atlanta's faith community as military action continues
in the Mideast. (White/Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-INFO _ List of books to read and web sites to visit if you
want more information about the impeachment process. (Clark, Dayton
Daily News). 12.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-BABYDOC _ MIAMI _ Inspired by the extradition case against
General Augusto Pinochet of Chile, Haitian exiles are seeking a
trial for Jean-Claude ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier, the former dictator of
Haiti. A committee has been formed to seek his trial for crimes
against humanity. An estimated 60,000 people were killed during his
regime and that of his father, Francois. Duvalier is apparently
living in France. We get reaction from Haitian communities in
Florida, Georgia and elsewhere. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRESSURE _ WASHINGTON _ A week that began with tough
talks for peace in Jerusalem, careened into political battling to
save the presidency from impeachment and wound up with the United
States making war on Iraq has put a set of pressures on President
Clinton few chief executives anywhere might imagine. How has he
held himself together, and how is he holding up? (Deans, Cox News
Service 650).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RESIGN _ WASHINGTON _ Even as U.S. troops engage in
battle abroad, calls are continuing for President Clinton to resign
in order to spare the nation an impeachment trial. A look at the
polls and the White House position. (Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BASE _ WASHINGTON _ Despite a last-minute flurry of
activity from Democratic allies, such as an anti-impeachment rally
at the Capitol on Thursday, many of Clinton's champions were barely
visible for the past five weeks as momentum gained for impeachment
in the House. (Malone, Cox News Service 520).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Updating a story first moved Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DOUBTS _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton found himself
Thursday having to defend his decision to attack Iraq from critics
asking whether the raids were timed to impact impeachment
proceedings. True or false, the allegations themselves complicate
the presidential decision-making process, make it difficult for
Clinton to get across the message behind his moves and raise
questions, in the minds of some, about his motives. Similar
questions have dogged Clinton all year and appear certain to
continue well into next year. (Deans, Cox News Service 700).
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON When it comes to Iraq and impeachment,
the wag-the-Buddy theories aired on Capitol Hill and in foreign
capitals miss the point. It's that Saddam Hussein and President
Clinton enable each other. In other words, the rocks in Saddam's
head fit the holes in Clinton's. (Glass, Cox News Service 560).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Due to rapid news developments, Andrew Glass's Sunday
column is moving this week for immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   CONGSCENE _ WASHINGTON _ Color from Capitol Hill as Congress
meets, including anti-impeachment rally lead by Jesse Jackson..
(Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BYRD-GRAVE-VANDALISM _ JASPER _ Somebody has removed the
nameplate from the grave of James Byrd Jr., the East Texas man who
was dragged to death behind a pickup. The local NAACP president
says it was likely vandalism. We're checking with authorities and
the Byrd family. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   GA-FLA-ALA-WATER _ Georgia, Florida and Alabama governors are
expected this week to extend the deadline for reaching a settlement
in the states' interstate water war, possibly delaying for at least
a year plans to build two _ and possibly more _ key reservoirs in
Georgia. Under two interstate water compacts adopted by Congress,
the three states were supposed to develop by Dec. 31 allocation
formulas to share the waters of two river basins. (Seabrook,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ Advance on summit meeting between Big Tobacco and
tobacco farmers on issues ranging from the recent $206 billion
national settlement to survival of the quota system. Tobacco
companies are considering a plan to provide growers with $5 billion
over 10 years to cushion the economic blow. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
