<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE     12-17 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOLLYWOOD: lovingly portrayed. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Ephron and Ms. Donner said they hoped men might be lured
into theaters even if there isn't a single car chase or explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men, I think, won't mind getting dragged to this,'' Ms. Donner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ephron said: ``It's meant to be a divine little fairy tale.
No, don't use the word `divine.' It's a fairy tale. But so many
people have met through the Internet. We'll have slightly more
women than men, but I think men can relate to this, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Fade Away
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll can save your life.
</P>
<P>
   Given the dark-rimmed perspective on rock music in movies like
``The Doors'' or even the sendup ``This Is Spinal Tap,'' it might
be difficult to embrace rock as a savior. In the film ``Still
Crazy,'' rock gets a good going over as egocentric and sometimes
silly. It comes through, nevertheless, not just as a banner for the
younger generation but also a means for aging boomers to pass into
middle age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy,'' which is distributed by Columbia Pictures, is
getting a brief run to qualify for the Academy Awards; it will be
in wider release on Jan. 22. It has received two Golden Globe
nominations. It was directed by Brian Gibson and stars Stephen Rea,
Billy Connolly, Bill Nighy, Jimmy Nail, Juliet Aubrey and Helena
Bergstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll is really the backdrop to a touching if amusing
drama about a group of old friends _ the now down and out members
of the once hot rock band Strange Fruit, better known as the Fruitz
_ dealing with the vulnerabilities of middle age. But the music
plays an important role in the story.
</P>
<P>
   That should come as no surprise, given that the film was written
by Ian La Frenais and Dick Clement, who also wrote ``The
Commitments,'' the acclaimed movie about a group of Irish youths
who try to escape poverty by forming a band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Save us from what?'' Clement responded, when asked if the
movie was intended as a tribute to the salvation power of rock
music. He went on to say, though, that his views on the power of
music were shaped by the documentary he made of Elton John's tour
of the Soviet Union in 1979, which offered a vision of a sort of
freedom the concertgoers could only imagine. ``I learned that in
some way rock 'n' roll is a very potent force, much more for good
than evil,'' Clement said.
</P>
<P>
   La Frenais said of the Elton John tour and its impact, ``There
was something about the universality of the rock 'n' roll
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The writing partners said they had been offered many projects on
rock themes after the success of ``The Commitments'' and had turned
them down because they did not want to be seen as rock writers.
They embraced ``Still Crazy,'' about a reunion of the Fruitz 20
years after breaking up, because of its treatment of middle age and
the rough passage of the characters into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to make this wise as well as witty,'' La Frenais
said. ``It's about entering middle age after having peaked too
early.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the reunion is mostly disastrous and filled with
misadventures, but it does illuminate at least for a moment the
grim lives of the band members.
</P>
<P>
   As for their own age, Clement and La Frenais would only say,
``We have been around as long as the Stones, but not as long as the
Kinks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
