<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EGYPT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSES MOVIE AN EPIC IN ANIMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story of Moses has been brought to the screen before, most
familiarly in Cecil B. DeMille's 1956 extravaganza, ``The Ten
Commandments.'' That spectacle now seems leaden and weighed down by
corny acting, dated special effects and a miscast Charlton Heston
as Moses.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a pleasure to report that DreamWorks' animated retelling
of Moses' journey from slave to youthful prince, and from prince to
the king of the Hebrew people, is more visually breathtaking,
subtle in its delivery and as thrilling as any blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   In the tale of Moses, from the biblical book of Exodus, an
infant is placed in a basket and set adrift in the Nile by his
mother and sister. They are trying to save the baby from the mass
infanticide that Egyptian King Rameses has ordered after a vision
warns him a Hebrew prince will rise and overthrow his empire.
</P>
<P>
   The baby in the bulrushes will touch shore at the door of
Rameses' wife, the Queen of Egypt. He will be named Moses and
raised alongside her son. He will be loved and adored despite his
unknown heritage. And while one son is destined to rule Egypt, the
other will become a prince of slaves, dividing a dynasty in the
struggle for his people's freedom and faith.
</P>
<P>
   Shade and subtlety are what mostly elevates ``The Prince of
Egypt'' above its cinematic predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   It's too easy to simply turn the brothers into mortal enemies,
making one a hero and the other a villain, as DeMille's epic
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   The animated version, with its inspired blend of voice talent
including Ralph Fiennes as the Egyptian king-to-be, Rameses, and
Val Kilmer as Moses, carefully examines the crisis of heart and
duty that erupts from the legacy of the sin of the father.
</P>
<P>
   After all, these are brothers who have loved each other deeply.
They are marvelous, playful creatures, full of fun, mutual respect
and affection. Ultimately, they are both defined by birthright as
well as what they have been bred to do, with Fiennes making Rameses
as compelling and tragic as Moses, who, after considerable
soul-searching, remains courageous and true to his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time a woman director has been called upon to
head the production team for an animated feature and Brenda Chapman
(with co-directors Steve Hickner and Simon Wells) brings a unique
voice to ``The Prince of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Fiennes and Kilmer, the talent in the movie is a marvel.
Danny Glover, Sandra Bullock, Helen Mirren, Michelle Pfeiffer,
Steve Martin, Martin Short and Patrick Stewart lend their
distinctively identifiable vocal chords to their characters. And
the casting of both British and American actors creates a dramatic
chasm between the Egyptian and Hebrew factions.
</P>
<P>
   The libretto of Stephen Schwartz, who won an Oscar for
``Pocahantas,'' and a fine score by Hans Zimmer, winner of an
Academy Award for his ``The Lion King'' soundtrack, convey
emotional plight and conflict and contribute harmony and melody
without overwhelming the delicate balance between story and song.
</P>
<P>
   More than 350 animators and technicians from some 35 countries
took four years to bring ``The Prince of Egypt'' to the screen,
using modern technology to recreate an elegant ancient world's
architecture and environment. The result is a film that seamlessly
blends time, legend, effects, backgrounds and character.
</P>
<P>
   It's also another in a series of animated movies this holiday
season that have delivered more inspired and innovative filmmaking
than most of their live-action counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The Prince of Egypt. Directed by Brenda Chapman, Steve Hickner,
Simon Wells. Cast: voices of Val Kilmer, Ralph Fiennes, Sandra
Bullock, Michelle Pfeiffer, Helen Mirren, Patrick Stewart, Steve
Martin, Martin Short, Jeff Goldblum. Dreamworks SKG. 90 minutes.
Rated G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
