<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIE THAT BINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The Netherlands' Prince Claus started something _
although it's not clear just what _ when he had a bad neck day
recently and ripped off his tie, throwing it at the feet of wife
Queen Beatrix and growling that it was ``a snake'' around his
throat.
</P>
<P>
   This unexpected royal fashion rebellion was greeted with cheers
in some places but will run into trouble in the Washington power
scene, where the official male dress code requires jacket and tie
for all serious business.
</P>
<P>
   The prince has a prominent ally in screen legend Paul Newman,
who recently told Vanity Fair his greatest extravagance is owning
two ties and one suit. Tongue in cheek, he deplored the trait of
others to own 40 ties and 60 suits. Asked what quality he most
likes in a man, he replied ``two ties.'' Asked what quality he most
likes in a woman, he said,``no ties.''
</P>
<P>
   Famous actors, of course, can get away with dressing any way
they want without regard to making a good first impression on
bosses, clients and friends. Maybe princes can get away with it
too, although in Great Britain stuffy Charles hasn't gotten that
message yet.
</P>
<P>
   Ties, despite their apparent lack of any useful function, have
over the centuries become an elementary part of the male uniform.
Somebody must appreciate them. What else can women give their mates
that's relatively cheap?
</P>
<P>
   Male neckwear apparently first caught on about 1688, when
Croatian mercenaries appeared in France wearing linen scarves
around their necks. The French called it a ``cravate'' and the fad
was popularized by Louis XIV, the autocratic Sun King who reigned
until 1715. The habit quickly spread to Great Britain, which claims
credit for inventing the hang-down version.
</P>
<P>
   These days we live in a far more informal world than that of the
foppish Sun King.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the nation's capital, ties are king. The
official dress code of the U.S. Congress mandates jackets and ties
for male members who appear on the floor, although they may get
away with sweaters if they hide out in their offices unseen by
cameras. Female members have more leeway, ordered only to wear
``appropriate attire.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago Alaska Sen. Ted Stevens showed up on the Senate
floor in a classy Western bolo tie and was rebuked for violating
the rules. An exception, however, has been made for Colorado's Ben
Nighthorse Campbell, the only American Indian in the Senate, who
insists bolos are part of his cultural heritage and refuses to wear
anything else around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, the Pentagon and the White House are equally
formal. No president has ever been spotted without a tie except on
a boat or beach on vacation. A tie figured in the President
Clinton-Monica Lewinsky saga. When he wore one she had given him on
a day she testified, cynics wondered if it was meant to be some
sort of silent signal to her. (If it was, she missed it.)
</P>
<P>
   Not only male officials but even reporters working in those
hallowed corridors are expected to appear in appropriate neckwear.
Except for the guys lugging cameras, the media's days of looking
scruffy are over. Now they blend into the rest of official
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At the high court, there is no written rule, but any man failing
to measure up sartorially would be socially shunned. Even the male
justices wear ties under their black robes, although the ties are
hidden. Justice John Paul Stevens is considered a maverick because
he is the only one who prefers a bow tie to the down-the-chest
thing. The two female justices wear white jabots.
</P>
<P>
   But for those not bustling about on self-important business,
Prince Claus may reflect a growing trend. When the most
sought-after ties can cost well over $100, it becomes a thrifty
cultural statement not to wear one.
</P>
<P>
   The wearing of ties, in fact, has been increasingly criticized
by rational men fed up with them. Ties have been accused of
reducing the flow of blood to the brain, causing men to make
mistakes. The neckwear has been ridiculed as an ornament that does
nothing but provide an excuse for bad taste. It has been called the
chador of male fashion, the men's clothing equivalent of Hindu and
Muslim women's headgear.
</P>
<P>
   And in some settings ties are in trouble. Few restaurants in the
nation's capital or any other city care any more about the attire
of either men or women, so long as the individuals are clean,
decently covered and wear shoes. Turtlenecks are good. Only the
most exclusive joints and the private clubs have the clout to
insist on coats and ties.
</P>
<P>
   Theater-goers also show up in virtually anything they please,
including knit shirts and khakis, although spandex and collarless
tee-shirts are considered tacky.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago it became fashionable for corporations to set
aside Friday for casual wear, particularly among young employees.
Once greeted with enthusiasm, however, this concept has been
declining in popularity because some workers can't tell the
difference between being informal and looking like a homeless
beggar.
</P>
<P>
   There's a happy dress-code medium in here somewhere. And maybe
the world can do without ties, but some of us would be nostalgic
for those with rows of petunias, cavorting elephants or Santa
Clauses on them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
