<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SPIN IS ALL 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Patriots spent most of Thursday's media session
responding to questions about their opponents. At least during the
buildup to Sunday's game against the San Francisco 49ers, the
Patriots will be in a supporting role.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have the better record (11-3), the marquee players,
and the momentum. The Patriots (8-6) are trying to salvage what
began as a promising season but has deteriorated with only four
wins in their last nine games.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots seem willing to capitalize on being in a
position of possibly being overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with being the underdog,'' wide
receiver Tony Simmons said. ``You can't underestimate anybody. You
have to go out and do what you need to do, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what is going to happen. If things don't happen
the way you want them to, you have to adjust very quickly. You have
to go out and try to win and expect to do your best.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons could be in the starting lineup for the first time since
Nov. 23, when the Patriots began a three-game winning streak with a
26-23 victory over Miami. Simmons returned to the bench and has
caught only two passes in victories over Buffalo (25-21) and
Pittsburgh (23-9) and a loss to St. Louis (32-18).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity for me,'' he said. ``I have to go out
and do it. You keep saying it, but you've got to go out and prove
it and make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, who has a reputation as an effective blocker, has
mostly capitalized on his chances. He caught four passes for 109
yards and a touchdown in a 21-16 victory over Indianapolis in his
second start. He had four receptions for 95 yards in a 41-10 loss
to Atlanta the next week and benefited by working with Scott Zolak
_ Sunday's starting quarterback _ for a spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an adjustment everyone has to make,'' Simmons said.
``Other guys have played with Scott before I got here, so it's not
any more or less of an adjustment for me. Everyone just has to
understand that he's been out there before.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons caught one pass against St. Louis after replacing Terry
Glenn, who broke an ankle. Now Simmons and another potential
starter, Troy Brown, will be expected to duplicate some of Glenn's
achievements. Brown missed six games but returned to catch two
passes for 42 yards against St. Louis, his first receptions since
Oct. 19. Simmons has 17 catches for 374 yards and 2 touchdowns, and
Brown has 23 receptions for 346 yards and a touchdown. Glenn caught
50 passes for 792 yards and 3 touchdowns before being sidelined for
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony will be a factor,'' coach Pete Carroll said. ``We will be
counting on him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
