<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS BACK CLINTON ON IRAQI ATTACK, FOUR POLLS FIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IRAQ-IMPEACH-RDP, IRAQ-MILITARY, IRAQ-GOALS, IRAQ-TIMING,
IRAQ-REACT, IRAQ-CLINTON, IRAQ-CABINET, IRAQ-GINGRICH, IRAQ-GORE,
IRAQ-ISRAEL, IRAQ-EUROPE, IRAQ-BRITAIN, IRAQ-ARABS, IRAQ-SOUTH,
IRAQ-SOLDIERS, IRAQ-RUSSIA, IMPEACH-IRAQ-REPUBS,
IMPEACH-IRAQ-LOTT.) (nk) 
 By MARJORIE CONNELLY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American public overwhelmingly supports the military action
in Iraq and accepts President Clinton's explanation about its
timing and its purpose, according to four national polls taken on
Wednesday evening after the bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread public support is customarily the first reaction to
any military action by the United States, as the public rallies
around the president. These first opinion polls show that that is
occurring this time as well, despite questions raised by Clinton's
critics about the timing of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The air strikes against Iraq were viewed favorably by about
three-quarters of the public _ 73 percent in the ABC News poll, 79
percent in the CBS News poll, 75 percent in the NBC News poll and
74 percent in the poll conducted by the Gallup Organization for CNN
and USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   Only a minority expressed reservations about the timing of the
attack. Most Americans accept that immediate action by the United
States was warranted and proper, rather than a ploy to delay
Thursday's scheduled congressional debate on impeachment. In the
Gallup poll, for example, 62 percent said Clinton ordered the
military strikes ``solely because he felt it was in the best
interests of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS News found that respondents supported the air strikes
regardless of their attitudes on whether Clinton should be
impeached. But opinion on the timing of the strikes differed
depending on people's views of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Those who supported impeachment were evenly divided on whether
the timing of the air strikes was motivated by Thursday's scheduled
debate, while those who opposed impeachment overwhelmingly rejected
the notion that Clinton's decision was connected to those
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans (60 percent in the ABC News poll) continued to
oppose the impeachment proceedings against Clinton. The decision by
the House of Representatives to temporarily delay the vote was
supported by 61 percent of the respondents in the NBC News Poll.
</P>
<P>
   In the CBS News poll, 62 percent said the military action was
worth the costs of attacking Iraq, even if it meant that American
lives were lost. Last month, slightly fewer, 54 percent, agreed
that forcing Saddam Hussein to comply with United Nations
inspections was worth the potential costs.
</P>
<P>
   But the public is divided on whether this military action will
achieve its goal. In the ABC News Poll, 41 percent said the attack
would interfere with Iraq's ability to produce weapons of mass
destruction, while 46 percent said it would not accomplish that
goal.
</P>
<P>
   The national polls were conducted by telephone on Wednesday
night; ABC News interviewed 510 adults, CBS News 413 adults, NBC
News 503 adults and Gallup 543 adults. The margin of sampling error
for each poll is five percentage points in either direction. In
addition, polls conducted entirely in one night introduce
additional potential error because only people at home during a
limited time period can be reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1807EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
