<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EAGLE-THEATER-REVIEW-     12-17 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAGLE-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPREAD EAGLE': AN AGING ACTOR'S DANGEROUS LIAISON IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By PETER MARKS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In May 1988 the Tony-winning British-born actor
George Rose was murdered in the Dominican Republic, where he
maintained a home.
</P>
<P>
   At first the police called the death an accident. But further
investigation revealed that Rose, best known for his performances
on Broadway in ``The Pirates of Penzance'' and ``The Mystery of
Edwin Drood,'' had been beaten to death and that his body had been
placed in a car that was then pushed into a ravine to create the
appearance of a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Four men were charged with the murder, including an 18-year-old
man who had lived with Rose and whom he had adopted. At a news
conference in Santo Domingo, the suspect was quoted as saying he
had planned the killing out of jealousy over Rose's affection for a
younger boy who was living in the house.
</P>
<P>
   (At the time, some of Rose's acquaintances disputed that
characterization of the relationship, saying that the 68-year-old
actor had adopted the teen-ager _ whose biological father was also
charged with the killing _ principally because he wanted an heir.)
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Spread Eagle,'' the new play at the WPA Theater
starring Brian Murray, does not acknowledge any connection to the
bizarre circumstances of Rose's killing, it's impossible for
playgoers not to note the similarities between the real and
fictional events.
</P>
<P>
   Murray plays Toby Arundel, an aging British stage actor who buys
a vacation house in Mexico, where he falls in love with his
teen-age house boy, Javier, played by Matthew Saldivar. Toby makes
arrangements to adopt Javier and declare him his heir but becomes
enamored of a younger servant, Diego (Joe Quintero), in whom he
discovers a latent acting talent. After arguing with Javier and his
father over Toby's plans to take Diego to New York, Toby is
murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Luigs, the author of ``Spread Eagle,'' appears to have in
mind the kind of story of sacrificial love conjured by ``M.
Butterfly,'' David Henry Hwang's Broadway play, based on actual
events, examining a French diplomat's devotion to a Chinese man
masquerading as a woman.
</P>
<P>
   As in Hwang's play, Luigs' protagonist is a worldly dupe, an
older man who enters into a dangerous liaison with a younger man of
questionable motives that brings the hero both ruin and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Until the final 20 minutes of ``Spread Eagle,'' however, Luigs,
the author of the off-Broadway musical ``Das Barbecu,'' strikes up
nothing close to the vibrant theatricality of Hwang's work.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the outstanding contributions by Murray, who invests
Toby with a complexly engaging mixture of cynicism, passion and
compassion, and by Quintero, a real discovery as a serving boy who
finds his calling in the pages of ``Antony and Cleopatra,''
``Spread Eagle'' feels long and rather ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   It is padded with digressive scenes seemingly borrowed from
other plays _ like an embarrassing one in which Toby, a la Maria
Callas, gives an attenuated master acting class back in London _
that are drags on the pacing and tend to rob the affecting ending
of its full power.
</P>
<P>
   How specifically the playwright intended the parallels to the
Rose case is unclear. Luigs is more interested in spiritual than
temporal matters. Toby is an unlikely candidate for sainthood, yet
his only real sin in Luigs' eyes is his blindness to the social
mores of the alien culture he meddles with.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The writer develops this core issue in a clever climactic scene
in which Steve Mones, as Javier's father, angry over Toby's
attentions to the younger boy, protests that promises had been
made, as if his son were a bride left at the altar.
</P>
<P>
   Luigs and the director, Constance Grappo, were lucky to secure
Murray's services. His Toby _ the second he's played this year,
following his darkly captivating Sir Toby Belch in Lincoln Center
Theater's ``Twelfth Night'' _ is neither a stereotypically rancid
British ex-pat nor brittle gay outsider.
</P>
<P>
   There's a delicate balance in his performance, a world-weariness
that makes his escape to the Mexican coast a practical retreat, and
a boyishness that allows him to appreciate it as an adventure. To
his credit, he never lets go of either quality.
</P>
<P>
   His scenes with Quintero, an actor who reveals his depth in
almost imperceptible increments, are lovely. It's fun to watch the
technically gifted Briton and the emotive Mexican break down the
text of ``Antony and Cleopatra'' and actually to sense the magic
being passed from the stage veteran to the unlikely tyro.
</P>
<P>
   When in the end Quintero's Diego pleads with Toby to take him to
New York, you virtually hear the volcano erupting in Diego's heart.
All his hopes, awakened by Toby, now rest tragically in Toby's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   The inconsistency of ``Spread Eagle'' leaves you a little
wistful. There's too much glib predictability, for example, in
Toby's British friends, played by the blameless Patricia Kilgarriff
and Graeme Malcolm, and in the slightly creepy relationship between
Toby and Javier, a surfeit of sentiment that sounds whipped up by
the copywriters at Hallmark. If only it were all up to the level of
Murray and Quintero.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SPREAD EAGLE'
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Luigs; directed by Constance Grappo; sets by Debra Booth;
lighting by Jack Mehler; costumes by Ilona Somogyi; sound by Robert
Murphy. Presented by the WPA Theater, Kyle Renick, artistic
director; Lori Sherman, managing director. At 519 West 23rd St.,
New York.
</P>
<P>
   With: Brian Murray (Toby Arundel), Anne James (television
hostess, stage manager, Tita), Graeme Malcolm (Humphrey Pritchard),
Patricia Kilgarriff (Gywneth Lambert), William Meisle (Mark,
television director), Steve Mones (Arturo), Matthew Saldivar
(Javier), Joe Quintero (Diego) and Mark H. Dold (Andrew, Nigel,
Michael, television assistant director).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
