r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFRARED-CYBERTIMES-T     12-17 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFRARED-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTINUED ADVENTURES IN THE INFRARED 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was backing up my hard drive recently when it suddenly
stopped. The cable connecting the backup device to my laptop had
come unplugged. Once again I cursed being part of the wired
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Most laptop peripherals have some sort of wire or cable to
connect to the computer. At times, the cables come loose, short out
or just don't work for some unknown reason. PC Card modems are a
particular problem because many models have two cables: one
connecting the card to the phone cord, and the phone cord itself,
which connects to the wall jack.
</P>
<P>
   My recent experience with wireless communications has started me
on the quest to get rid of as many wires as possible and have
peripherals talk to my laptop and each other via infrared.
Fortunately, the standard for how devices communicate by infrared
is set. Most manufacturers of infrared-enabled devices are members
of the Infrared Data Association (IrDA). Microsoft, a member, has
built infrared support into Windows 95/98.
</P>
<P>
   My latest foray into the wireless world was with the new DI 27
infrared modem for the Ericsson 600/700 series GSM phones. The DI
27 is a small unit that snaps on to the bottom of the phone. Since
the phone I have, the CF788 model, is only four inches long, the
phone/modem combo stretches to a whopping 5 inches. The DI 27 comes
with a CD-ROM, called the Mobile Office. The software lets you
manage the phone book and compose short messages from your laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Installing the modem follows the same procedure, a Windows
Wizard, as any other modem. The difference is that no wires are
required. Once the DI 27 was installed, I was able to dial out to
my Internet service provider and get my e-mail and surf the Web the
first time I tried it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, going wireless affects the modem speed. You can't get
the same kinds of bandwidth that one gets over telephone wires. But
the DI 27 is rated at 9600 BPS, and with compression I was able to
get a 19.2 connection. That's acceptable speed for e-mail. It's a
little slow for any serious Web surfing because of large graphics
on many sites.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a minor problem compared to the convenience of
having the ability to connect from anywhere. During a recent trip,
I got lost on the way to meet friends for dinner. I kept getting a
busy signal when I tried to call for directions. I finally just
pulled off the highway, got out the laptop and the cell phone and
went to MapBlast for directions. I got back on track and arrived a
few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   I was not, however, able to use the phone and message manager
</P>
<P>
   software on the laptop. Every time I tried to install that piece
of the software, it crashed. After finally getting through to
Ericsson's technical support, I discovered that the DI 27 Mobile
Office has a conflict with Microsoft Outlook. Ericsson said it is
working on a fix for the problem, but in the meantime, you can't
use both. But I can manage the phone book from the phone and I'm
not going to be sending that many messages from the phone. Of
course, I heard that someone has written a program to do the same
thing from the Palm III.
</P>
<P>
   With all this wireless stuff, have I lost my membership in the
wired generation?
</P>
<P>
   -----------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Infrared Data Association: irda.org/
</P>
<P>
   _ MapBlast: mapblast.com/
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Stephen C. Miller is assistant to the technology editor at The
New York Times.)
</P>
<P>
