<HEADER>
A5483 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PINOCHET-COURT-BOS &LR;      12-17 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-COURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REVERSES PINOCHET EXTRADITION RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In the latest twist to a convoluted legal odyssey,
England's highest court reversed itself Thursday and said the
former Chilean dictator, Augusto Pinochet, deserved a new appeal
because one of the three judges who ruled against him last month
had not disclosed a potential conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision, by a panel of five judges in the House
of Lords, was a rare rebuke of a colleague. It means Pinochet's
lawyers will be allowed to argue again next month that Pinochet
should not be extradited to Spain to face charges that he engaged
in torture and murder during his 17-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   The new panel will be drawn from seven Law Lords who did not sit
during the initial appeal.
</P>
<P>
   While not ruling whether Lord Leonard Hoffmann was biased
against the former dictator, five of his colleagues concluded that
Hoffmann's failure to disclose his association with Amnesty
International had given the appearance of a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers from Amnesty International argued before a panel of five
Law Lords, including Hoffmann, who sits on the board of a charity
that raises money for Amnesty International. Hoffmann's wife has
worked for Amnesty International for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Nicolas Browne-Wilkinson, who oversaw the latest appeal,
said, ``The earlier decision of this house cannot stand and must be
set aside. Lord Hoffmann, who did not disclose his links with
Amnesty International, was disqualified from sitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers here say Lord Hoffmann may be forced to resign
because of the controversy, which has deeply embarrassed the
judiciary and has undermined its credibility. Lord Chancellor Derry
Irvine, Britain's highest legal authority, underscored the
seriousness with which the legal community is taking the matter by
writing a letter to Lord Browne-Wilkinson which said, ``We must
make every effort to ensure that such a state of affairs could not
occur again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann cast the deciding vote against Pinochet, breaking a 2-2
tie by saying the former dictator was not entitled to immunity from
prosecution because he was a head of state.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 Law Lords form the highest court in England and Wales.
Historians said that aside from an obscure property case in 1823,
this was the first time anyone had challenged a Law Lords decision.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann, a native of South Africa, was one of three Law Lords
who ruled that Pinochet did not have sovereign immunity because he
had engaged in gross violations of human rights by engaging in the
torture and murder of political opponents during and after the 1973
military coup in which he seized power.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International says attempts to paint Hoffmann as biased
are specious. It says the charity on which he serves as an unpaid
director was also supported by the chief justice of the High Court,
whose decision to initially grant immunity to Pinochet was
overturned by the Law Lords. They also argued that the London law
firm representing Pinochet had donated to the charity.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bunting, a spokesman for Amnesty International,
acknowledged Thursday's ruling was ``a step backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``We will remain optimistic that any future
Lords' decision will come to the same conclusion as last time.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was the first victory for Pinochet's lawyers since
October, when the British High Court agreed with them that Pinochet
was entitled to sovereign immunity because the allegations against
him had stemmed from actions he took as a head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Spain and several human rights organizations,
including Amnesty International, appealed the High Court ruling in
the House of Lords, which ruled in their favor on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jack Straw, the British home secretary, cleared the
way for the extradition proceedings to begin, saying the former
dictator was not entitled to any form of immunity and did not
deserve to avoid prosecution on compassionate grounds.
</P>
<P>
   A Chilean government report says at least 3,197 people were
killed or disappeared during Pinochet's reign, while human rights
organizations say the figure is much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet remains under house arrest at the mansion he is renting
20 miles southwest of London during the extradition proceedings,
which could drag on for months.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's determination to go ahead with the proceedings has
severely strained relations with Chile, which recalled its
ambassador from London to protest Straw's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Pinochet is returned to Spain and is convicted, he will
not be sent to prison, because under Spanish law no one older than
75 can be incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   But in what is a warning to despots everywhere, Pinochet could
spend years defending himself, as other countries have formally
lodged warrants for his arrest or have hinted that they want to try
Pinochet for murdering and torturing citizens who got caught up in
his coup.
</P>
<P>
   While the Spanish will get first crack at Pinochet, France and
Switzerland have formally asked that he be extradited to face
charges for the murder of their nationals. Italy is considering
making a similar request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
