<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GATECH-COLLIER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Bleeding ulcer won't keep Jackets' Collier off the court
   By Norman Arey
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech was bitten again by the injury bug. This
time its budding star Jason Collier, who has played only two games
for the Yellow Jackets.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot-1 transfer from Indiana, who has 44 points and 16
rebounds in his first two starts, was diagnosed Thursday as having
a bleeding ulcer. Collier had gone through a bout with the flu two
weeks ago and then continued losing weight last week, but he
thought it was becaue of his exam schedule and the lingering
effects of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night after the Yellow Jackets' win over Wofford,
Collier began throwing up blood. Tech team physician Angelo Galante
provided the diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to be careful about what I eat,'' Collier
said. ``(Trainer) David (Chewning) is coming up with a diet that
I'll have to stay on, and I'll be taking some anti-acid-type stuff.
But it shouldn't affect my playing, and I don't think I'll miss any
games or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier's ulcer is the latest problem in a year gone bad for
Tech coach Bobby Cremins and his basketball program. The Jackets
lost superstar Dion Glover for the year with a knee injury on the
first day of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Babul, a starter at small forward, has missed three games
with a severe ankle sprain and is not expected to play against
Kentucky Saturday With starting guard Travis Spivey and backup
center Pablo Machado gone via transfer, the roster already was
depleted.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
