<SLUG> BC-FILM-MAIL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPHRON GETS SPAM-HAPPY WITH `YOU'VE GOT MAIL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would someone please tell director Nora Ephron that less is
invariably more?
</P>
<P>
   As she did in her 1993 hit ``Sleepless in Seattle'' and in the
John Travolta comedy ``Michael,'' Ephron denies audiences any
spontaneous emotional response to her movie's action. She unleashes
a torrent of song designed to trigger every impulse we're supposed
to feel at any given moment.
</P>
<P>
   In a movie as well-cast as ``You've Got Mail,'' which is the
third screen pairing of Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan, peripheral noise is
a detriment. They're more than capable of holding their own for a
couple of hours of screen time.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on the play ``Parfumerie'' by Miklos Laszlo,
which was made into ``The Shop Around the Corner,'' a 1940 comedy
directed by Ernst Lubitsch and starring Margaret Sullavan and Jimmy
Stewart, and into a 1949 musical ``In the Good Old Summertime,''
with Judy Garland and Van Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shop Around the Corner'' was a deft romantic work rife
with pretense and ulterior motives and, of course, its two sparring
protagonists ultimately fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   Ephron pays homage to that clever film here: it's the name of
Kathleen Kelly's (Ryan) children's bookstore in Manhattan's Upper
West Side. There is a tranquil, small-town appeal to this
neighborhood shop that is about to be obliterated by tycoon and
heir Joe Fox (Hanks), who is the brains behind a Barnes &AMP;
Noble-type enterprise called ``Fox &AMP; Sons Book-sellers.''
</P>
<P>
   He's planning to build another of his discount super-retail
outlets _ where else? Just around the corner from Kathleen's barely
surviving business.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Joe and Kathleen have discovered the intimate
anonymity of e-mail. Since they met in a chat room, they've begun a
fast friendship that overwhelms their relationships with their
``significant others.'' Kathleen lives with Frank Navasky (Greg
Kinnear), a champion-of-the-underdog columnist for the New York
Observer, and Joe cohabitates with book editor Patricia Eden
(Parker Posey), who is so hyper ``she makes coffee nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair find tranquility and companionship online while waging
a war in public. And, naturally, neither knows the business rival
is the ideal ``other'' sending electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
   As with all of Epron's films, the mystery of illusion and
wishful thinking is a huge component in the plot. And the film's
look suggests a yearning for better times gone by and almost
too-perfect values. This is a New York that is immaculate and
shiny; it's safe for a lone woman to walk down the street at
midnight and there is no whiff of industrial waste blowing in off
the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   It's a privileged fairy tale that's been updated with late
20th-century techno-wizardry to make it click. Despite the chaste
chemistry and easy familiarity that always makes watching Ryan and
Hanks a joy, there's a surprising lack of menace in Ephron's
prettified threats of buyouts and bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   She never lets us forget that this is only make-believe and,
worse, she belabors the point, letting the terminally cute charm of
the story push what's essentially a 90-minute date flick into a
thinly stretched two-hour therapy session.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe and Kathleen finally realize they're perfect for each
other despite different approaches to business ethics, Ephron
blasts swelling strains of ``Somewhere Over the Rainbow'' atop
their first chaste kiss. They may be over the rainbow, but we're
just about around the bend, dying to reach the theater exit.
</P>
<P>
   You've Got Mail. Directed by Nora Ephron. Written by Samson
Raphaelson. Cast: Tom Hanks, Meg Ryan, Greg Kinnear, Parker Posey.
Warner Bros. 120 minutes. Rated PG for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
