<HEADER>
A5485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     12-17 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: sets (Maslin).  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``LITTLE VOICE,'' starring Jane Horrocks, Brenda Blethyn, Ewan
McGregor and Michael Caine. Directed by Mark Herman (R, 99
minutes). The main attraction here is watching wispy Ms. Horrocks
put on a spectacular one-woman diva festival, with her phenomenal
mimicry of musical grande dames from Judy Garland to Marilyn
Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   What works less well is the broad and stagy story built around
her. As the timid title character, she is harangued by her blowsy
mother (Ms. Blethyn), latched onto by the talent agent who is the
mother's boyfriend (Caine) and courted by a nice young man who
loves his pet pigeons. In that last role, McGregor makes a
telephone installer scintillating and once again shows that he can
do anything. Incidentally, the soundtrack is divine (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``MEET JOE BLACK,'' starring Brad Pitt, Anthony Hopkins and
Claire Forlani. Directed by Martin Brest (PG-13, 170 minutes).
Hopkins zestily plays a noble tycoon in this otherwise somnolent,
emotion-free, nearly three-hour (!) weepie. And Pitt appears
blankly as Death with blond highlights, serving as a kind of
personal afterlife trainer to the tycoon, whose number is up. Ms.
Forlani plays the big man's beautiful daughter in a story based on
``Death Takes a Holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   In a suffocatingly lavish film that cries out for a trip to the
cutting room, virtually every character is allowed to overstay his
or her welcome, with Pitt especially diminished by the
watching-paint-dry pace. The story drags on so slowly that there's
room for a subplot about party planning, and several scenes
establish how much Death loves peanut butter (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``PSYCHO,'' starring Vince Vaughn and Anne Heche. Directed by
Gus Van Sant (R, 100 minutes). It turns out that the apparent rocks
in Van Sant's head, as he contrived this near-exact color replica
of Alfred Hitchcock's 1960 classic, were only pebbles.
</P>
<P>
   His remake (a modest term, but it beats plagiarism) is artful
and good looking, faltering only when it tries to improve on the
brilliant original blueprint. The casting of Vaughn as Norman Bates
is the film's biggest Achilles' heel, since the performance
Hitchcock elicited from Anthony Perkins remains an impossible act
to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Van Sant has tried an outlandish experiment and come up
with what are, especially for fans of the original, intriguing
variations on a theme (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE,'' starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth
Paltrow, Geoffrey Rush and Judi Dench. Directed by John Madden (R,
113 minutes). A witty, sexy and merrily literate delight, with an
exhilaratingly clever premise that only gets better as the film
unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm and
turned by Tom Stoppard into razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of his
``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' dares to imagine
whatever it likes about the link between Shakespeare's artistic
passions and his mad yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, this tirelessly inventive comedy also envisions an
Elizabethan theater fraught with the same backbiting and conniving
we enjoy today, and has great fun presenting the creation of
``Romeo and Juliet,'' glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow
make a fine, tempestuous duo, and she gives the first great, fully
realized starring performance of her career (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``A SIMPLE PLAN,'' starring Bill Paxton, Billy Bob
Thornton and Bridget Fonda. Directed by Sam Raimi (R, 120 minutes).
This onetime cult horror director makes a flawless transition to
mainstream storytelling with a quietly devastating thriller. And
its fine cast plays out the consequences of a harmless-sounding
error in judgment that winds up leveling everything in its path.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst is $4.4 million that literally falls out of the
sky, and Scott Smith's story proves how deadly the morality of
expediency can become. When you get the shivers watching this
wintry tale, which features an especially memorable performance
from Thornton, it won't be from the cold (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``WAKING NED DEVINE,'' starring Ian Bannen, David Kelly
and Fionnula Flanagan. Directed by Kirk Jones (PG, 91 minutes).
Delightful shenanigans greet the news of a winning lottery ticket
in a tiny Irish village. Especially after the winner turns out to
be dead. Bannen and Kelly are wonderfully funny as two old coots
who concoct a plot to claim the winnings and unite the town's cast
of hearty characters in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' prize-winning career directing television commercials
means that everyone here is an amusing eccentric with colorful
quirks, and that the septuagenarian stars' naked motorcycle-riding
scenes are played for all they're worth. This comedy doesn't have
the tart edge of ``The Full Monty,'' but it knows how to coax
laughs from making a spectacle of elderly gentlemen in the buff
(Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   ``THE LODZ FILM SCHOOL OF POLAND: 50 YEARS.'' Among the notable
alumni of the Lodz Film School in Poland are: Krzysztof Kieslowski,
Roman Polanski, Barbara Sass, Jerzy Skolimowski, Andrzej Wajda and
Krzysztof Zanussi. The school was founded 50 years ago, and to
honor its anniversary, the Museum of Modern Art today begins a
128-film retrospective spanning its history.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these student and diploma films _ fiction, documentary,
animated, experimental and short _ have never been seen outside
Poland. The first of 2 of the 16 programs, presented at 6 and 8
p.m. Friday, are samplers that include works by Zanussi, Polanski,
Skolimowski, Kieslowski and Wajda.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing through Jan. 10 at the museum in Manhattan, the
series, organized by Joshua Siegel, assistant curator of the
department of film and video, is free with museum admission: $9.50
for adults, $6.50 for students and people 65 or older; free for
visitors under 16 accompanied by an adult. Pay what you wish on
Fridays from 4:30 to 8:30 p.m. Screening information: (212)
708-9400 (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
