<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET WINS FIRST APPEAL IN EXTRADITION CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (htv) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a step that raised Gen. Augusto Pinochet's hopes of
escaping extradition to Spain and returning home to Chile, the
House of Lords on Thursday set aside its decision denying him
immunity from arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The Lords scheduled a new hearing a month from now, and if the
83-year-old former Chilean dictator succeeds in convincing a new
five-judge panel of his claim to immunity he will be free to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Before the decision Thursday, Pinochet faced an extended stay in
custody in England while his case proceeded through motions and
appeals that could stretch on for more than a year. Spain is
seeking to try him in Madrid on charges of genocide, terrorism and
torture in the deaths and disappearances of more than 3,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The decision Thursday was the first time in the history of the
Law Lords, England's highest court, that a verdict had even been
reviewed, much less rejected. A five-judge panel set up for the
purpose heard arguments Tuesday and Wednesday, and Lord
Browne-Wilkinson, the chief Law Lord, announced their unanimous
verdict on the floor of the ornate upper chamber Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   While he said the judges had not had time to compose their
opinions and would make them public in January, there was no doubt
that they had accepted arguments from Pinochet's lawyers that the
3-2 verdict reached last month was tainted by bias.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' sole point in pressing the appeal was that Lord
Hoffmann, the judge who cast the decisive vote in the ruling that
denied Pinochet immunity, had erred in not declaring his
association with Amnesty International, which was an active
participant in the case. The group had been given permission to
make its own case against Pinochet alongside British prosecutors
during the six days of hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Hoffmann, it emerged, has been a director and chairman of a
principal Amnesty International charity since 1990, and his wife,
Gillian, has worked in the press and publications office of the
human rights group since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Clare Montgomery, Pinochet's lead trial lawyer, told the panel
of Law Lords on Tuesday that ``what judges must not do once they
have accepted a post with a charity is to hear a case touching on
the very subject matter that charity has sworn to abolish.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Montgomery pointed out that Amnesty International considered
her client an enemy and associated him with the very crimes he is
charged with in the Spanish petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider how it appears,'' she said, ``there are
reasons to fear that Lord Hoffmann, as a director of a company
sworn to secure the end of torture and extra-judicial
disappearances, would be predisposed to find that no state immunity
would attach to such acts.''
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling Nov. 25, the Law Lords said that crimes like
torture and hostage-taking did not enjoy sovereign immunity because
they could not be considered functional acts of a head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Browne-Wilkinson made his announcement in the
characteristically understated manner of the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a loose leaf notebook to largely vacant red
leather benches, he said: ``I am satisfied that the earlier
decision of this House cannot stand and must be set aside. It is
impossible in the time available to prepare and give full reasons
for that view _ on the other hand it is essential that the parties
should know where they stand as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling brought a sharp reversal in the reactions of
opponents of Pinochet, who have been cheered by a series of
unexpected turns in their favor, and for the general's supporters,
who have become increasingly angry at the government for not
setting him free.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case should now be brought to an end,'' said Sir Norman
Fowler, the Conservatives' chief law enforcement representative,
hailing the ruling. ``This is a case which should be settled in
Chile, not here in Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Reyes, spokesman for Chile Democratico and Chileans in
Exile, said he was ``in total shock'' at the decision and feared
that this ``could be the way out for Pinochet.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy McEntee, the chairman of Amnesty International, said:
``Augusto Pinochet has very inventive lawyers. They are very good,
very effective. They will make this a long case, one that is hard
for him to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is being brought by Baltasar Garzon, a Spanish judge
investigating atrocities during the ``dirty wars'' in Latin America
in the 1970s and 1980s. The British police arrested Pinochet on
Oct. 16 while he was recuperating from back surgery in a London
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The general won the first legal round, winning a unanimous
decision from a three-judge panel of London's High Court on Oct. 28
upholding his claim to sovereign immunity. It was that decision
that the House of Lords overruled a month later in the verdict that
was laid aside Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
