<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON WEEKEND TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As an example of unvarnished courage, it would be hard to beat
Nargess Nateghi, 16, who has spent all her life fighting cystic
fibrosis. The drugs that have kept her alive have stolen her
hearing and damaged her kidneys. Now her only hope of survival is a
lung transplant. During an interview, this young woman seems to
understand the severity of her plight yet retains a remarkable
composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any reason to worry,'' she says quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nateghi is one of the patients encountered in the first
edition of ``Health Diary,'' a no-frills half-hour magazine program
produced for public television stations at KTCA in Minneapolis-St.
Paul. The series, which began this fall, reaches the New York
region Saturday on WLIW, Channel 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health Diary'' has production values somewhere between a
snippet of the 11 p.m. news and a 2 a.m. infomercial. But its
subjects exemplify human values that carry the day.
</P>
<P>
   The first program also has a report on glaucoma, including an
interview with Kirby Puckett, the former Minnesota Twins slugger
whose baseball career was abruptly ended by the disease. As a
professional athlete, he says, he had received so many physical
examinations that he never guessed there could be a common
condition for which he was not being screened.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors get their say in these reports, too, but the patients'
own words have a natural grace. Tears glisten but never fall. The
second program, on gastric bypass (or stomach stapling) introduces
45-year-old identical twins whose special bond was severely tested
when one had the operation, slimming down to a size 8 and leaving
her sister a size 26. (She, too, has now had the surgery.)
</P>
<P>
   In the third program, Scott Burton, a professional juggler whose
cancer was successfully stopped by a bone transplant in his leg,
must execute a tricky emotional maneuver. He has to give up his
dream of being a great juggler because he can no longer do the
flips and jumps that amazed the crowds. But he concludes, ``It
really wasn't all that bad, considering that I didn't die.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the carefully chosen patients, the series has another
big asset, its host, Sioban Cleary. Ms. Cleary comes from Ireland,
where she conducted a similar program. She projects a common-sense
warmth toward her interview subjects and the audience. And when she
closes each installment with ``Goodbye and take care,'' it sounds
like a heartfelt benediction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
