A5527 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEAD-JOURNALIST-BOS &LR;      12-17 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-JOURNALIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD JOURNALIST WAS HOMICIDE VICTIM, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ An American journalist whose body was found two
weeks after disappearing in a remote area of the Sierra Madre
mountains in western Mexico was strangled, a state coroner and
federal officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy performed on Philip True, the Mexico City-based
correspondent for the San Antonio Express-News, showed the cause of
death to be asphyxiation by strangulation, and that something had
been wrapped tightly around the victim's neck, said Mario Rivas
Souza, coroner for the state of Jalisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a homicide, not an accident,'' Rivas told reporters in
Guadalajara, where True's body was being held Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's developments contradicted initial reports that True,
50, had accidentally fallen to his death in a ravine.
</P>
<P>
   Express-News editors said that Mexican offficials also told them
that True had been struck on the head with a blunt object.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members in San Antonio were told about True's death at a
meeting Wednesday _ hours before the company's holiday party _ by
Publisher W. Lawrence Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the killing remains unclear, although one
forensic official said True still had his watch and wedding ring,
signs suggesting that robbery was not the primary reason.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Simon, America's program coordinator for the New York-based
Committee to Protect Journalists, said there was ``compelling
evidence that this death was related to his work as a journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Thursday, Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo ordered federal and state authorities to investigate True's
death.
</P>
<P>
   True, an experienced hiker, left Mexico City on Nov. 29 on what
was supposed to be a fact-finding vacation. He planned to explore
the mountain regions of Jalisco and Narayit in search of the
Huichol Indians, an isolated tribe, for future articles.
</P>
<P>
   True was due back in Mexico City on Dec. 10, but never returned
and didn't return phone calls from worried relatives. On Tuesday,
dozens of Mexican soldiers began scouring the area in search of
True.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, there was hope. Searchers reported finding a lost
and hungry foreigner named Philip in the same area. The man turned
out to be Philip Truempler, a 25-year-old Swiss researcher.
</P>
<P>
   True's body was found Wednesday in the 300-foot-deep Chapangana
Canyon by army aircraft sweeping the area.
</P>
<P>
   A former union organizer and wallpaper hanger, True entered
journalism when he was in his mid-30s. Later, he joined the
Express-News as Laredo bureau chief and was the Mexico
correspondent since January 1996. He is survived by his wife,
Marta, and his sister, Bonnie Biggs, of Reno, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always at home in Mexico,'' Walker said in a telephone
interview Thursday. ``He just blended in. There was nothing about
him you couldn't like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1832EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5528 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIAN-SINGERS-ART-2     12-17 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-SINGERS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING) 
</HEADLINE>
   UNDATED: sunny Iberia. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The record begins with a rarity, Shostakovich's colorful
``Spanish Songs,'' six ballads based on poems by two Russians. To
these evocative pieces, Ms. Borodina brings a plummy tone and
plenty of spunk. ``Farewell, Granada,'' finds a woman departing her
homeland after the death of her lover, and ``Little Stars'' tells
of a cheeky youth who trades guitar and astronomy lessons for
kisses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronda'' is a call to make merry, and this mezzo's warm,
inviting tone makes the offer hard to resist. For the tender ``Eyes
of Ebony,'' Ms. Borodina becomes a girl driven to distraction by
unrequited love.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the fire that pervades Ms. Gorchakova's account of
Glinka's ``Bolero,'' Ms. Borodina favors sultriness, and one can
practically see the mezzo shimmying up to some young gallant and
seducing him.
</P>
<P>
   Falla's ``Seven Popular Songs'' are a bold choice for a Russian
singer, but Ms. Borodina, adopting a Castilian lisp, fully steps up
to the challenge. Naturally, her diction is not as idiomatic as
Victoria de los Angeles's, yet the mezzo connects with these
passionate strains.
</P>
<P>
   Even tongue-twisters like ``Seguidilla From Murcia'' do not
defeat her. She brings poignancy to ``Asturian Song'' and a dreamy
calm to ``Lullaby.'' And she presents a searing account of
``Polo,'' one woman's curse on love itself.
</P>
<P>
   Semyon Skigin's assertive piano accompaniment suits Ms.
Borodina's bold approach. He is a gifted player with more than a
few ideas of his own. (Listen to the extra bounce he lends the
introduction to Falla's ``Jota,'' for example.) Yet Skigin proves
no stranger to nuance, either, as his playing on Minkov's bucolic
``Landscape'' shows.
</P>
<P>
   Hvorostovsky is the most famous singer to have emerged from the
former Soviet Union. In 1989, he won the BBC's Cardiff Singer of
the World Competition, beating Bryn Terfel for top honors. His
latest disk, ``Arie Antiche'' (289 456 543-2), with the Academy of
St. Martin-in-the-Fields conducted by Neville Marriner, breaks new
ground by featuring the baritone in Italian arias of the 17th and
18th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Though the popularity of these ardent works has declined over
the years, Beniamino Gigli, Ezio Pinza, Janet Baker and other
singers memorably recorded many of them, and the pieces _ by both
famous composers like Handel, Gluck and Vivaldi and neglected ones
like Durante, Caccini and Stradella _ have much to recommend them.
A few, like Gluck's ``Che faro senza Euridice?'' and Handel's
``Ombra mai fu,'' have retained their renown, but most will be
unfamiliar to listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Hvorostovsky begins on an exultant note, with Giacomo
Carissimi's ``Vittoria, mio core,'' in which a man heroically
proclaims his freedom from ``love's vile servitude.'' Here, the
plush-voiced baritone is at his swaggering best, dispatching
coloratura with ease. He's no less fine in Vivaldi's ``Se il cor
guerriero,'' where a martial antiwar cry is set against ``Four
Seasons''-like accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   In Giuseppe Giordani's ``Caro mio ben,'' the baritone delivers a
declaration of love in a resonant, fervent voice, easily displacing
Pinza's late-in-life recording of the song. Yet Hvorostovsky falls
short of the standard set by Gigli's incomparably sensitive
account, now sadly out-of-print.
</P>
<P>
   Vivaldi's ``Orribile lo scempio,'' yet another antiwar jeremiad,
affords the baritone an opportunity for vocal gymnastics, which he
gleefully seizes. Antonio Caldara's sublime ``Selve amiche,'' is
much gentler stuff, with the singer imploring the woods to grant
his aching heart refuge. But though the baritone feels Caldara's
music, he lacks Gigli's clutching desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Gigli also lingers in the memory when hearing Hvorostovsky in
Alessandro Scarlatti's hymn to the sun, ``Gia il sole dal Gange.''
The baritone takes the tune at an impressively speedy clip and
lends it bluff ardor, but he lacks Gigli's gay, celebratory sense.
</P>
<P>
   This CD concludes with Hvorostovsky's plaintive performance of
Alessandro Stradella's ``Pieta, Signore,'' the longest work on the
record. A plea to God's mercy, the piece benefits from the
baritone's supple treatment and exquisite diction. Actually,
Hvorostovsky's Italian is crisply idiomatic throughout the disk.
</P>
<P>
   For support, the baritone couldn't have done better. Marriner
conducted a similar album for Ms. Baker two decades ago, and his
appreciation for these scores seems only to have grown with time.
Under his keen baton, the academy plays in typically polished
fashion, its strings lissome, winds pellucid and brass glinting.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, circumstances would not have permitted Ms.
Gorchakova, Ms. Borodina and Hvorostovsky their international
careers. Now, Western ears regularly seek out the bold, viscous
sonorities of the Russian singer, and a rudely interrupted line
that began when the gramophone was young thrives yet again. How
lucky for music lovers that times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-15-98 2132EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1832EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-4TAKES-NYT &LR;      12-17 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK ART GUIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy art, design and photography exhibitions at New
York City museums and art galleries this weekend. Addresses, unless
otherwise noted, are in Manhattan. Most galleries are closed on
Sundays and Mondays, but hours vary and should be checked by
telephone. Gallery admission is free. X denotes a highly
recommended show.
</P>
<P>
   Museums
</P>
<P>
   `BAULE: AFRICAN ART/WESTERN EYES,' Museum for African Art, 593
Broadway, near Houston Street, SoHo, (212) 966-1313 (through Jan.
3). Once again this exemplary museum proves that connoisseurship
and anthropology do not make strange bedfellows. These 135
breathtaking objects include elegant portrait masks, spirit spouse
figures, feared and fearful animal masks and items for everyday
use. Supplemented by an unorthodox but effective use of dioramas
and videotapes, they illuminate nearly every aspect of Baule life _
private and public, religious and secular _ and belief systems.
This rare, sharply delineated cultural portrait was organized by
Susan M. Vogel, the museum's founding director, who spent three
decades studying the Baule of the Ivory Coast. Tuesdays through
Fridays, 10:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays, noon to 6
p.m. Admission: $5; $2.50, children, students and the elderly.
(Roberta Smith)
</P>
<P>
   `CUBISM AND FASHION,' Metropolitan Museum of Art, Fifth Avenue
at 82nd Street, (212) 535-7710 (through March 14). After the
over-the-top high-priced kitsch of its entertaining Gianni Versace
survey, the Costume Institute's latest offering is so pure and
restrained that it seems almost penitential. It traces the
reverberations of modern art's most earthshaking movement through
the work of several generations of modern designers, from Callot
Soeurs to Geoffrey Beene. The star of the show is the 1920's
designer Madeleine Vionnet, still radical after all these years.
The show begins on a high note, with a vivid demonstration of the
emergence of modern dress and the female body from the stand-alone
upholstery of Edwardian ball gowns. Otherwise, the exhibition comes
to life only intermittently, and is marred by irrelevant
inclusions. One is left wondering if this is because Cubism was too
intellectual and austere for its effect on fashion to be easily
defined, or if more space was required to give the subject its due.
Hours and admission: Fridays and Saturdays, 9:30 a.m. to 8:45 p.m.;
Sundays, and Tuesdays through Thursdays, 9:30 a.m. to 5:15 p.m.
Admission: $8; $4, students and the elderly. (Roberta Smith)
</P>
<P>
   X `INSIDE OUT: NEW CHINESE ART,' Asia Society, 725 Park Ave., at
70th Street, (212) 517-2742, and P.S. 1 Contemporary Art Center,
22-25 Jackson Ave., Long Island City, Queens, (718) 784-2084
(through Jan. 3). Art in China has changed dramatically in the last
few decades, and this big, stimulating show gives a sense of
vanguard developments on the post-Mao mainland and in Hong Kong and
Taiwan and among expatriate Chinese artists in the West. The work
ranges from video to Western-inspired Pop painting, from
spectacular, room-filling installations to ink scrolls. The
messages are complex and contradictory: myth, humor, pessimism and
nostalgia rub shoulders, often in a single work. There are ups and
downs in this tip-of-the-iceberg showcase, but it's a benchmark
event. Asia Society: Tuesdays through Saturdays, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m.;
Thursdays to 8 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 5 p.m. P.S. 1: Wednesdays
through Sundays, noon to 6 p.m. Admission: $4 to Asia Society, $5
to P.S. 1; $2, students and the elderly, at both. (Holland Cotter)
</P>
<P>
   X `MIRO'S BLACK AND RED SERIES: A NEW ACQUISITION IN CONTEXT,'
Museum of Modern Art, 11 West 53rd St., (212) 708-9400 (through
Feb. 2). An ogre-ish head of Franco dominates a powerful series of
eight small etchings produced in 1938 by the Spanish artist Joan
Miro (1893-1983). In stark black and bloody red on white grounds,
the etchings speak _ in Miro's eloquent language of signs and
symbols _ of the horror and mutilation occasioned by the Spanish
Civil War. Recently acquired by the museum, the prints are the
cornerstone of a show that includes some 150 prints, illustrated
books, drawings, posters, photographs, paintings and sculptures by
Miro and his Surrealist predecessors and contemporaries. It not
only documents Miro's intense preoccupation with etching at the
time but also shows the impact of Surrealism on his art and the
international reverberations of the Civil War. The all-star cast of
works demonstrates yet again the remarkable depth of the Modern's
resources. Hours: Saturdays through Tuesdays, and Thursdays, 10:30
a.m. to 6 p.m.; Fridays, to 8:30 p.m. Admission; $9.50; $6.50
students and the elderly. Open, free, this Wednesday. (Grace
Glueck)
</P>
<P>
   X JACKSON POLLOCK, Museum of Modern Art, 11 W. 53rd St., (212)
708-9400 (through Feb. 2). A landmark. If you care about art, you
live for exhibitions like this, in which an artist, against the
heavy odds of his skewed talent and unhinged personality, pursued
something so wild, untested and mysterious that its full meaning
was unclear even to him, yet who briefly wrung from his peculiar
system of painting one variation after another. Pollock was a
quintessential American because of his aspiration to make something
from what seemed like nothing. Sometimes he botched the results,
but this was intrinsic to a process that consciously flirted with
incoherence: accidents, on which his art depended, had to be held
in tension with acts of extreme control, and the exhibition is
instructive for letting you see some of his failures, which by
contrast clarify his successes. His biggest triumphs, the classic
paintings from 1950, ``Autumn Rhythm,'' ``No. 32'' and ``One,'' are
hung together here so that you can scan them by swiveling your head
180 degrees. It's an amazing sight. Hours and admission: See above.
(Michael Kimmelman)
</P>
<P>
   X `RENDEZVOUS: MASTERPIECES FROM THE CENTRE GEORGES POMPIDOU AND
THE GUGGENHEIM MUSEUMS,' Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, 1071 Fifth
Ave., at 89th Street, (212) 423-3500 (through Jan. 24). With its
landmark Paris home under renovation, the cream of the Pompidou
collection has hit the road, joining forces with the Guggenheim's
in an unusual, perhaps unprecedented exhibition that fills the
Fifth Avenue building to the brim. The familiar story of modernism
is told, but in contrasting voices and with a cornucopia of
unfamiliar works and telling juxtapositions. Not to be missed.
Hours: Sundays through Wednesdays, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.; Fridays and
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. Admission: $12; $7, students and the
elderly. (Roberta Smith)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   X `ROYAL PERSIAN PAINTINGS: THE QAJAR EPOCH, 1785-1925,'
Brooklyn Museum of Art, 200 Eastern Parkway, at Prospect Park,
(718) 638-5000 (through Jan. 24). Think ``Persian painting'' and
what comes to mind? Small illuminated miniatures with diminutive
landscapes and teensy figures. But the Qajar emperors thought big.
They liked their portraits life-size, their battle scenes
Cinemascopic. Even their collectibles _ lacquered boxes, gilded
enamels _ have a trumpeting, clear-the-way flair, like props in a
Handel opera. This extraordinary show is the first major Western
survey of a self-promotional dynastic art of almost hallucinatory
strangeness and brilliance. It holds many surprises, none more
mesmerizing than the power portraits of the ruler Fath Ali Shah:
with his dainty, high-heeled slippers, extravagant beard and
Napoleonic hauteur, he projects a preposterous, inimitable glamour.
Hours: Wednesdays through Fridays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Saturdays, 11
a.m. to 6 p.m. (until 11 p.m. on the first Saturday of the month);
Sundays, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission: $4; $2, children 12 and up;
$1.50, the elderly. (Holland Cotter)
</P>
<P>
   X `SACRED ARTS OF HAITIAN VODOU,' American Museum of Natural
History, Central Park West at 79th Street, (212) 769-5100 (through
Jan. 3). The 500 objects in this exhibition _ shimmering, sequined
flags, plaster Madonnas, medicine packets wrapped like Christmas
gifts, miniature coffins, carved wooden drums _ weave African,
European and indigenous New World influences together in an art of
visceral excitement and disquieting beauty. The installation is
expertly organized. It begins with paintings depicting the growth
of Vodou among African slaves in the Caribbean. (The show avoids
the Anglicized voodoo, with its history of racist associations, in
favor of the Creole Vodou.) And it concludes with three big,
glamorous assemblage-style altars that catch the essence of what
this religion is: a magnificent, spiritual tour de force. Hours:
Sundays through Thursdays, 10 a.m. to 5:45 p.m.; Fridays and
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 8:45 p.m. Admission: $8; $6, students and the
elderly; $4.50, children. (Holland Cotter)
</P>
<P>
   `UFA FILM POSTERS, 1918-1943,' Museum of Modern Art, 11 W. 53rd
St., (212) 708-9400 (through Jan. 5). Ufa was the German movie
studio that produced such films as Fritz Lang's ``Metropolis'' and
Josef von Sternberg's ``Blue Angel.'' The 50 mostly large posters
on view here, ranging in style from Expressionistic to Art Deco to
proto-Pop collage, don't have the esthetic quality of the best
early modern graphic design, but they are interesting as vintage
kitsch and, along with the informative catalog, should be
compelling for film buffs. Hours and admission: See above (Ken
Johnson). Galleries: Uptown.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL GEORGES, Salander-O'Reilly Galleries, 20 E. 79th St., (212)
879-6606 (through Dec. 31). A fine, juicy painter who has for many
years retained his figurative approach through movements thick and
thin. The handful of canvases here sample his recent range of work,
from a fiery ``Dr. Faustus'' series to quiet views of his farm in
Normandy. His skill as a strong colorist and paint-handler
prevails. (GraceGlueck)
</P>
<P>
   X ARSHILE GORKY, ``Paintings and Drawings 1929-1942,'' Gagosian,
980 Madison Ave., at 76th Street, (212) 744-2313 (through Jan. 9).
This small museum-quality show makes an excellent companion to the
Pollock retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art. Here we see
Gorky still working mostly in Picasso's shadow but beginning to
discover _ in ``Garden in Sochi,'' for example, a delicate,
surrealistic mindscape from 1942 _ the gravitationally liberated
space and elegant line that characterize his great works of the
mid-1940's (Johnson).
</P>
<P>
   X SIGMAR POLKE, ``New Paintings, Printing Mistakes,'' Michael
Werner Gallery, 21 E. 67th St., (212) 988-1623 (through Jan. 16).
This German painter is a major artist who has never really taken
off in the United States. He's an antimastery master who produces a
post-epiphany, post-ego painting, an impure hybrid that mixes ideas
and formal ploys like so many chemical additives. His works
preserve a tradition, and they also turn it into something else.
That something else can be sampled in this show of two dozen
strange, beautiful, sort-of-abstract new paintings based partly on
newspaper misprints. (Holland Cotter)
</P>
<P>
   Galleries: 57th Street
</P>
<P>
   GUSTAVO LOPEZ ARMENTIA, Reece, 24 W. 57th St., (212) 333-5830
(through Dec. 30). Armentia represented Argentina in the 1997
Venice Biennale. He combines cartoon drawing, expressionistic
painting, found objects and relief modeling to create layered,
dreamy collage allegories of free-floating modernity. The best
piece here is a big, surrealistic table-top landscape with giant
cutlery. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   NELL BLAINE, Tibor de Nagy, 724 Fifth Ave., (212) 262-5050
(through Dec. 30). Paintings and watercolors from the '70s, '80s
and '90s by an artist who studied with Hans Hoffman and belonged to
a group of feisty modern traditionalists that included Fairfield
Porter and Jane Freilicher, who kept faith with representational
painting. The best works among the still lifes and landscapes here
are several table settings that have a Bonnardian intimacy and
radiance. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   LAURENT DE BRUNHOFF, ``Babar in Process,'' Mary Ryan Gallery, 24
W. 57th St., (212) 397-0669 (through Jan. 9). More than 70 studies
for various books about the lovable elephant Babar. Though aimed at
children, there is a visual magic, emotional resonance and epic
sweep to the Babar stories that is still engaging for grown-ups.
It's fascinating to see how de Brunhoff works through painterly
sketches, pencil drawings and finished watercolors toward final
images that seem effortlessly achieved. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   JOHN GILL, Kraushaar, 724 Fifth Ave., (212) 307-5730 (through
Dec. 31). Chunky ceramic works in which traditional, utilitarian
forms like vases, teapots, bowls and platters are animated by
Cubist distortions both sculptural and painterly. The exhibition
exudes a spirit of playful, continual metamorphosis (Johnson).
</P>
<P>
   X GABRIEL OROZCO, Marian Goodman Gallery, 24 W. 57th St., (212)
977-7160 (through Jan. 9). This clear-eyed romantic is one of the
more ingenious artists to come along in years, and if you doubt it,
go to the show and play a little Ping-Pong. He has concocted an
X-shaped Ping-Pong table with a lily pond in its center _ Giverny
for the rumpus room _ which, besides being a lot of fun, is a sly
meditation on our interaction with the space he has created. He has
also made an elaborate, pitched-roof pavilion with pianos for
walls, a big installation that includes stuff he found by rummaging
through trash, and several deceptively casual videos. Orozco's work
consistently inclines us toward empathy, which is the ultimate goal
of good art; and it asks, What is the point of looking if your mind
isn't open to what you see? (Michael Kimmelman)
</P>
<P>
   X `JACKSON POLLOCK: THE PICASSO INFLUENCE,' Washburn, 20 W. 57th
St., (212) 397-6780 (through Dec. 30). This dense little show could
just about hold down one of the side galleries in the early end of
the Museum of Modern Art's landmark Pollock retrospective. It has
more than 20 drawings and small paintings, most of them from the
artist's estate and previously unexhibited, all made in the four or
five years after Pollock saw ``Guernica'' for the first time, in
1939. Filled with indelibly Picassoid motifs, but animated by
Pollock's nervous searching line and continual experimentation with
materials, the works vividly attest to a confrontation that left
the younger artist stirred but not shaken (Smith).
</P>
<P>
   X KEN PRICE, Franklin Parrasch Gallery, 20 W. 57th St., (212)
246-5360 (through Jan. 23). A Los Angeles artist who deserves to be
better known for the small, suggestive glazed or painted ceramic
sculptures he has been perfecting for nearly 40 years. Maybe his
latest efforts, among his most perfect, will do the trick. Their
rippling, bulging shapes are animated by a single all-purpose
orifice, and have exquisite surfaces dotted with thousands of tiny
starlike pores. They sum up a lifetime of interests and tap Price
as a precursor to the current pursuit of biomorphic abstraction in
painting and sculpture. Not many artists start out good, get better
and remain pertinent. Like Stuart Davis and Philip Guston, Price is
one of them. (Smith)
</P>
<P>
   Galleries: SoHo
</P>
<P>
   X KAHN/SELESNICK, ``The Circular River: Panoramic Photographs,
Siberian Expeditions, 1944-1946,'' Monique Knowlton, 568 Broadway,
at Prince Street, (212) 966-2625 (through Jan. 9). Nicholas Kahn
and Richard Selesnick produce elaborately staged faux antique
photographs. Each of the 59 pictures from their most recent project
is a sepia-toned, six-foot-long panoramic print that purports to
document an expedition to Siberia undertaken in the mid-1940's.
Together with its long journalistic text, it's a funny, Monty
Pythonesque parody of the generic scientific adventure narrative.
(Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   SUZANNE McCLELLAND, Paul Kasmin, 74 Grand St., (212) 219-3219
(through Dec. 31). Paintings mixing verbal graffitti and
expressionistic gesturalism. The best part of the show is a grid of
two dozen small gouaches based on phrases like ``Tit for Tat'' or
``Checkered Past'' that range freely from open and washy to densely
marked and layered. Ms. McClelland generates a lot of painterly
energy, but overall her work has an unfocused, distracted feeling.
(Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   `THE RISK OF EXISTENCE,' Phyllis Kind Gallery, 136 Greene St.,
(212) 925-1200 (through Dec. 31). A riveting group show of
paintings, drawings and prints that range from William Blake to
Lisa Yuskavage, with Myron Stout, Francis Bacon and Henry Darger in
between. Despite the existential title, form and color are as
important as subject, and the installation carefully links each
work to its neighbors in unexpected, illuminating ways. Best of
show is a hard call, but Jim Nutt's ``Pug,'' a quirky portrait with
the concentrated perfection of Northern Renaissance painting, is a
strong candidate. (Smith)
</P>
<P>
   ANDY WARHOL, ``Camouflage Paintings,'' Gagosian Gallery, 136
Wooster St., (212) 228-2828 (through Jan. 9). Full of optical
cheer, the 47 paintings in this double-hung exhibition come in all
shapes and sizes, but only one motif. They subject a modest swath
of United States Army regulation camouflage to countless changes in
color, scale and finally composition, reflecting the
approach-avoidance dance with abstraction that dominated Warhol's
final years. Their banal origins are never obscured as they move up
the scale of visual complexity, but move they do. (Smith)
</P>
<P>
   Other Galleries
</P>
<P>
   `COUNTER CULTURE: PARISIAN CABARETS AND THE AVANT-GARDE,
1875-1905,' Grey Art Gallery, New York University, 100 Washington
Square East, Greenwich Village, (212) 998-6780 (through Jan. 16).
For a clever young thing in turn-of-the-century Paris, the place to
hang out was Montmartre. In its avant-garde heyday, from 1875 to
1905, cabarets provided what today we'd call alternative spaces for
the Paris culturati, promoting poetry, art, performance and musical
entertainments, sowing the seeds of Dada, Surrealism and even
conceptual art. The more than 300 objects in this show celebrate
the famous quartier at its peak: displaying posters by
Toulouse-Lautrec and Jules Cheret, prints, drawings photographs,
illustrated books and ephemera. Among the livelier exhibits is a
functioning replica of the shadow theater developed by the artist
Henri Riviere, a popular entertainment that presaged the cartoon
film. (Grace Glueck)
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY CRANE, Cheryl Pelavin, 13 Jay St., lower Manhattan,
(212) 925-9424 (through Dec. 31). At his best, in magically real,
panoramic views of semirural Hudson Valley landscapes, Crane
creates the feeling of seeing the world through the eyes of someone
_ an Emerson or a Thoreau _ in a transcendentally (or
psychedelically) elevated consciousness. Color and paint are lush;
smoke plumes, rainbows and odd clouds animate the sky and a
visionary light transforms mundane reality. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   JANNIS KOUNELLIS, Ace Gallery, 275 Hudson St., near Spring
Street, West Village, (212) 255-5599 (through Feb. 6). New,
huge-scale work by the Italian Arte Povera master. Live starlings
flutter in cages hung by meat hooks in front of massive steel
plates; antique wooden armoires dangle absurdly by thick ropes from
overhead I-beams. His work is grandiose, but Kounellis' poetic
imagination can be charmingly capricious. (Johnson) Last Chance
</P>
<P>
   X JOHN BALDESSARI, ``The Commissioned Paintings,'' Sonnabend,
420 West Broadway, near Spring Street, SoHo, (212) 966-6160
(through Saturday). Vintage deadpan conceptualism. In 1969,
Baldesarri commissioned 12 painters he discovered in county fair
art exhibitions to copy a photograph of a hand pointing at
something utterly mundane, like a messy kitchen counter or a roll
of sheet metal. A professional sign painter captioned each painting
with the words ``A Painting by'' and the name of the copyist.
(Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   `BIOMORPHIC ABSTRACTION,' Curt Marcus, 578 Broadway, near Prince
Street, SoHo, (212) 226-3200 (through Wednesday). This judiciously
selected five-artist show offers a useful occasion to ponder the
popularity of biomorphism in today's art. It includes a creepy
painting of something green by Max Ernest; a beautiful blue blob by
the ceramicist Ken Price; antic, erotic abstraction by Paul Henry
Ramirez; richly colored, near-abstract cartoon paintings by Carl
Ostendarp and a cerebral juxtaposition of a pink hourglass-shaped
chair and Vera scarves by Pae White. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   ROSS BLECKNER, Lehmann Maupin, 39 Greene St., SoHo, (212)
965-0753 (through Saturday). The downtown segment of a two-gallery
exhibition includes big, beautiful grisaille abstractions whose
strikingly optical cell-like patterns (a result of careful use of
an airbrush) count as some of the most convincing images Bleckner
has made. The artist's political conscience has been relegated to a
series of high-minded photo appropriations that seem about 20 years
too late. (Smith).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
