<P>
   ATTENTION NEWS EDITORS, FOREIGN EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Here are two changes in the Cox News Service budget for Friday
papers. If you need more information, call the CoxNet desk in
Atlanta at 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   updated budget line:
</P>
<P>
   US-IRAQ _ WASHINGTON or BAGHDAD _ U.S. military forces, joined
by those of Great Britain, launched missiles against Iraqi targets
for the second day in a campaign with no clear end in sight.
Defense officials, while lauding the efforts of the American
military at hitting their targets, refused to be pinned down on a
definite time period for the bombings _ despite the approach of the
high Muslim holy period of Ramadan. The officials also continued to
decline to specify Iraqi targets, but said assassinating Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein was not a stated goal of the mission.
Meanwhile, Iraqi officials continued to try to paint the United
States and Britain as the bad guys to their own people. Developing.
(Deans/Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 9 p.m. EST. Will be updated.
</P>
<P>
   subs for IRAQ-AIRSTRIKES, to run with US-IRAQ:
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SCENE _ BAGHDAD _ As U.S. and British missiles pounded the
Iraqi capital for a second straight night Thursday, its weary
citizens insisted upon life going on as usual. One couple that was
scheduled to be married on Friday, said they planned to go ahead
with the wedding, despite the sudden shatterings of silence
followed by thick plumes of smoke. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 7 p.m. EST.
</P>
