</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: late. (Smith)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSS BLECKNER, Mary Boone, 745 Fifth Ave., near 57th Street,
(212) 752-2929 (through Friday). The uptown segment of a
two-gallery exhibition shows the artist continuing to cultivate a
dazzling new painting technique that is responsible for the
relatively impressive paintings in the show's downtown half in
SoHo. Here, he seems to have shifted into overproduction, adding
pleasing color and a surface slickness that pushes the abstract
toward the Photo Realist. (Smith)
</P>
<P>
   JEFF BURTON, Casey Kaplan Gallery, 48 Greene St., SoHo, (212)
226-6131 (through Saturday). Sex, death and immortality, Hollywood
style, are the subjects of Burton's apparently ultra-casual, often
obliquely angled photographs. Adjacent knees from two bodies
suggest sexual coupling; a cemetery looms; a celebrity name is
enshrined in a sidewalk. This is the Los Angeles artist's best New
York show (Cotter).
</P>
<P>
   X `WILLEM DE KOONING: DRAWING SEEING/SEEING DRAWING,' the
Drawing Center, 35 Wooster St., SoHo, (212) 219-2166; ``Willem de
Kooning: Drawings and Sculpture,'' Matthew Marks Gallery, 523 West
24th Street, Chelsea, (212) 243-0200, and Mitchell-Innes &AMP; Nash,
1018 Madison Avenue, near 79th Street, (212) 744-7400 (all through
Saturday). These three shows don't pretend to add up to a survey of
de Kooning's drawings, but they have fine stuff and lots of it:
high-spirited warm-ups for paintings, ultra-refined finished
pieces, all manner of glorious doodles. The Drawing Center show is
thematically the most coherent and includes a series of fascinating
Crucifixions. The other shows highlight links between drawings and
sculptures. It's great to have all this coincide with the Pollock
retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art. (Cotter)
</P>
<P>
   KIM DINGLE, Sperone Westwater, 142 Greene St., SoHo, (212)
431-3685 (through Saturday). This Los Angeles artist, known for
paintings and sculptures featuring malevolent schoolgirls and
toddlers called Prisses, is making her subjects behave themselves,
and the shift from truly nasty to just naughty indicates that her
work is formally pallid and unadventurous. Best is an installation
in which two Prisses break through a plaster wall like
Supergirl-cherubs, but even that wouldn't be out of place in a
Christmas store window on Fifth Avenue. (Smith)
</P>
<P>
   JACKIE FERRARA, ``Red Arches,'' Frederieke Taylor/TZ'Art
Gallery, 470 Broome St., SoHo, (212) 966-9059 (through Thursday).
Known for her site sculptures and large public commissions, Ms.
Ferrara uses an austere vocabulary of Minimalist forms to build
architectural structures. They can be useful or purely sculptural,
but are in any case admirable for their subtle geometries. She has
redone the gallery's walls in a design of large, repetitive arches
rounded off at the top by stepping back the plywood segments in
ziggurat fashion. Like the walls of a Moorish harem, they bestow a
soft, sensuous effect on the entire space. (Glueck)
</P>
<P>
   HAMISH FULTON, John Weber Gallery, 529 W. 20th St., Chelsea,
(212) 691-5711 (through Wednesday). Fulton, the British
Conceptualist, says walking is his main artistic activity. In the
gallery, the interest is in the unpredictable, abstract ways he
memorializes his walks, as in seven black sticks in a zigzag to
represent a seven-day hike, or, most impressively, a mural-scale
wall of words (sky, sea, tree) arranged into an abstract gray,
black and white landscape. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   DEWITT GODFREY, Sculpture Center, 167 E. 69th St., (212)
879-3500 (through Thursday). An impressive gallery-filling metal
sculpture in the form of a huge collapsed tube made of 300 sheets
of riveted Cor-ten steel. You can walk on it, which causes it to
squeak and squeal. It's accompanied by a mural-scale drawing of a
single, thick black line that repeatedly bifurcates as it
progresses from left to right, becoming a confusing mass of lines
at the end. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   ANTON HEYBOER, Baron/Boisante, 50 W. 57th St., (212) 581-9191
(through Saturday). Nine esoteric etchings and three drawings, from
1957 to 1980, by a famously eccentric Dutch artist who lives
reclusively on a farm with four wives. His works, based on a
personal mystical system represented by lines and numbers, are raw,
unintelligible amalgams of pattern, figures, diagrams, scribbling
and writing. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   FREDERICK KIESLER/LEON POLK SMITH, Jason McCoy, 41 E. 57th St.,
(212) 319-1996 (through Thursday). Two under-known modernists. In
1954 Kiesler (1890-1965), a visionary architect, designed the
environmental construction ``Horse Galaxy,'' on view here. It is
mainly a multipanel abstract painting on the wall with additional
elements on the floor and ceiling. It suggests aerial views of
Southwestern landscapes. The hard-edged paintings from the 1950s,
mostly small works on paper by Smith (1906-1996), are flat,
deceptively simple compositions in vibrant colors. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   `MOUSE: AN AMERICAN ICON,' Alternative Museum, 594 Broadway, at
Houston Street, SoHo, (212) 966-4444 (through Saturday). This
selection of works by 24 artists, every one featuring a more or
less politicized image of Mickey Mouse, has a few good things in
it. In Luis Camnitzer's ``Reality Check,'' a real stuffed mouse has
been absurdly equipped with round Mickey ears; John Fawcett's drawn
and collaged mixes of pop culture and hallucinogenic Mickeys are
dizzyingly complicated; Jaune Quick-to-See Smith's ``McFlag,''
which sports big, round, earlike speakers at each upper corner, is
a strident takeoff on Jasper Johns' iconic ``Flag.'' (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   X DANICA PHELPS, ``Funny Money,'' Jack Tilton, 49 Greene St.,
SoHo, (212) 941-1775 (through Wednesday). Goofy systems by which
the artist, a young Brooklynite having her New York solo debut,
records the getting and spending of money. ``Providence'' is a
giant, messy, homemade calendar on which day-by-day activities are
recorded in words, cartoony drawings and little rolls of green
paper that Ms. Phelps glues on to represent earnings and tears off
to represent expenditures over three months. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   MONIQUE PRIETO, Pat Hearn Gallery, 530 W. 22nd St., Chelsea,
(212) 727-7366 (through Wednesday).With a computer, Ms. Prieto
generates shapes of blobby, biomorphic contour, then paints them
flatly in bright, toylike colors. They are smart and knowing, if
not particularly consequential. (Glueck)
</P>
<P>
   X LAWRENCE SEWARD, Andrew Kreps, 529 W. 20th St., Chelsea, (212)
741-8849 (through Saturday). A zany population of faceless little
plaster men, all in blue jeans, white T-shirts and sneakers, fill
this gallery. One lies face down in a pool of glue; another pulls
off his leg. Several different ones climb or embrace mounds of
amorphous black matter. Spinning variations on one dumb idea with
impressive ingenuity, Seward has produced a funny, touching theater
of human striving, frustration and folly. (Johnson)
</P>
<P>
   JAMES TURRELL, Barbara Gladstone, 515 W. 24th St., Chelsea,
(212) 206-9300 (through Wednesday). New work by the much-revered
light artist. In ``Cross-Cut,'' you behold a hazy scrim of light
and, some distance away, a glowing red wall slanted so that it
recedes in space, turning blue at its far edge; it's almost
beautiful, but too dim. In a couple of small works, barely
perceptible flickers are emitted from television-tube-shaped
apertures, an ironic conjunction of the sacred and the profane.
(Johnson)
</P>
</TEXT>
