<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With holiday vacations looming, producers were wrapping up a
bundle of deals this week. The result is a clear picture of the
spring season. And it can be summed up in a single word: plays.
Lots of them.
</P>
<P>
   The first comes from a rare creature on Broadway: a young
American playwright. The author? Tennessee Williams, whose ``Not
About Nightingales'' will land at the Circle in the Square in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Williams wrote ``Nightingales,'' the story of a prison uprising,
in 1938 and 1939, well before his breakthrough with ``The Glass
Menagerie'' in 1945. Much to his chagrin, the script was never
produced and was essentially lost until 1991, when Vanessa Redgrave
discovered a copy among Williams' papers at the University of Texas
at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   It was written when he was in his early 20s when ``no one
believed in him,'' said Carole Shorenstein Hays, who is producing
the show with Stuart Thompson and Marsha Garces Williams. ``It's
just amazing to think this is where it all came from.''
</P>
<P>
   The play received its premiere under the direction of Trevor
Nunn at the Royal National Theater in London in March and was at
the Alley Theater in Houston in June, receiving good notices both
times. The New York production, set to open on Feb. 25, is expected
to have much the same cast as its previous incarnations, including
Corin Redgrave, Vanessa's brother, in a leading role.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the Cort Theater, where ``The Blue Room'' reigns
supreme, another West End import, ``Marlene,'' by Pam Gems, will
begin performances on March 30.
</P>
<P>
   Described by producers as a musical play, ``Marlene'' tells the
story of Marlene Dietrich, played by the Irish actress Sian
Phillips, during the hours before her final public performance in
1969.
</P>
<P>
   Also confirming an opening was ``Amy's View,'' David Hare's new
play, arriving at the Barrymore Theater in April. Other straight
plays already booked for Broadway include another by Hare, ``Via
Dolorosa''; a new play by Patrick Marber, ``Closer,'' and two
acclaimed revivals, ``Death of a Salesman'' and ``The Iceman
Cometh.'' Also scheduled are revivals of ``Night Must Fall'' and
``Lion in Winter,'' and Conor McPherson's play, ``The Weir,'' is
expected in April.
</P>
<P>
   Add the news that ``Electra,'' the season's unlikeliest hit,
will extend until March 28, and you can expect some serious money
to be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule of thumb has been: Broadway can support two straight
plays, one with a star and one with a Tony Award,'' said Rocco
Landesman, president of Jujamcyn Theaters. ``If there ends up being
five hit plays on Broadway this season, I'd be the most surprised
guy on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Off Broadway, change has been the byword for the last several
weeks. Two long-running shows, ``Shakespeare's R &AMP; J'' and ``Power
Plays,'' announced their closings, and a promising newcomer,
``Duet!,'' failed to find an audience and is closing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most topsy-turvy case is that of ``This Is Our
Youth.'' The show, which opened to stellar reviews at Second Stage
in November, had been said to be on the verge of moving to a
commercial run at the Minetta Lane Theater in January.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Despite renegotiating the actors' contracts for more
money in the commercial run, its commercial producers, Fran and
Barry Weissler, announced to a bewildered cast after the show's
Sunday performance that the play would stay at Second Stage until
the end of February. Not moving seems to be a result of prudence or
procrastination, depending on whom you talk to.
</P>
<P>
   Weissler, producer of the Broadway hit ``Chicago,'' said on
Wednesday that he had decided to stay at Second Stage after he
became convinced that moving the show would be impossible without
the director, Mark Brokaw, who has left the city to direct another
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will find its eventual home,'' Weissler said, ``but I can't
move without my director.''
</P>
<P>
   Some associated with the drama grumbled that the Weisslers had
squandered the momentum of the reviews by negotiating contracts
slowly. And Alan Schuster, the Minetta Lane's owner, said there was
never a formal deal for the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Weissler defended his tactics, saying that January, usually a
bad box office month, was not a good time to move. He added that
the actors would still receive their raises now and and that he was
continuing to look at other Off Broadway houses. ``I haven't missed
the crest,'' he said. ``It's alive and kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hit has emerged Off Broadway: ``The Most Fabulous Story
Ever Told'' by Paul Rudnick, at the New York Theater Workshop. The
comedy, which received mostly positive reviews after opening on
Monday, sold about $26,000 in tickets in six hours on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, the remainder of its eight-week run was about 90
percent sold out. By comparison, ``Rent,'' which also originated at
the workshop and moved on to Broadway, also sold about $29,000 in
the hours after its glowing notices.
</P>
<P>
   The sales have caught the attention of Scott Rudin, a frequent
producer of Rudnick's screenplays, who is looking to move the show
to a larger house: the Variety Arts or, you guessed it, the Minetta
Lane.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Joe Morton has had the kind of career most actors only dream of.
</P>
<P>
   His professional stage debut was on Broadway in ``Hair.'' His
resume is crammed with television and film credits, a sure sign of
some financial security. Still, the business is fickle, and
Morton's last effort, ``Mercy Point,'' a television series shot in
Vancouver, was short lived. ``I came back really upset,'' he said.
``And really depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morton has landed the plum role of Serge, the snobby
esthete, in the latest cast of ``Art.'' He begins performances on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was in several Broadway musicals, including a
Tony-nominated turn in ``Raisin,'' this is Morton's first straight
play on Broadway. It is also the first time a black actor has been
in the cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's refreshing that the black actor is not playing
the least intelligent character on stage,'' he said. ``And I think
there's a nice irony when a black man turns to a white canvas in
the play and says, `But it's not white.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
