</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DENIES TIMING OF IRAQ ATTACK WAS TO THWART IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton denied Thursday that he timed
U.S. attacks on Iraq to sidetrack House impeachment proceedings,
emphasizing that the approach of the Muslim holy month of Ramadan
dictated his timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton devoted his only public remarks Thursday to countering
criticism that he had launched Operation Desert Fox in an effort to
divert attention from the threat of impeachment that imperils his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not true,'' Clinton declared. ``What I did was the right
thing for the country. I don't think any serious person would
believe that any president would do such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he ordered the attack Wednesday night to avoid
starting combat operations during Ramadan. His subordinates said
that the open-ended U.S. bombing campaign may be completed without
spilling over into the Muslim holy month that begins with the first
sight of the new moon late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan heralds the beginning of the ninth month of the Muslim
year when God revealed the Koran to the Prophet Mohammed before the
death of the father of Islam in the year 632. Muslims are called
upon to fast between dawn and dusk during the holy month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he ordered the attack to maximize ``the surprise
factor'' and ``to avoid initiating any military action during the
Muslim holy month of Ramadan, which is slated to begin in just a
couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright also cited the start of Ramadan as a deadline for
initiating the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said U.S. forces ``will take whatever time is necessary to
carry out the operation, but we're sensitive to the Ramadan
period.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright used almost the same formulation, saying the
U.S.-British military campaign ``is going to continue,'' but
adding: ``We are sensitive to the beginnings of Ramadan, but this
campaign will continue to its completion.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said the United States was
eager to avoid aggravating U.S. relations with Muslim countries or
the more than 1 billion followers of Islam worldwide. Among the
personal telephone calls that Clinton made Thursday were calls to
Jordanian King Hussein and Egyptian President Honi Mubarak.
Albright also called top officials in more than 20 nations,
including some Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders announced that lawmakers will begin
their debate Friday on whether to impeach Clinton, despite
Democratic complaints that U.S. military operations in the Persian
Gulf should delay the debate.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders had postponed House action scheduled Thursday on
four articles of impeachment against Clinton for perjury,
obstruction of justice and abuse of power in connection with his
efforts to conceal a sexual relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton was rising
to the twin challenges of Iraqi military operations and
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's been tested, but I think what you can see and
what he's demonstrated is he's up to the challenge,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton, Cabinet officers and senior
administration aides were resuming behind-the-scenes efforts to
persuade House members to reject impeachment in favor of censure.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart said there were no plans for Clinton to appear on
Capitol Hill or to make a nationally televised address to try to
stem what aides describe as likely impeachment by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the White House believed impeachment was inevitable,
Lockhart invoked the words of resignation once offered by Yankee
catcher and sidewalk philosopher Yogi Berra.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over 'til it's over,'' Lockhart said, adding that
Clinton's only hope was for lawmakers to cast their votes ``based
on the facts, the Constitution and the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration signaled continued resolve _ and
potentially long duration operations _ by dispatching
reinforcements to the Persian Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
   A second aircraft carrier, the USS Carl Vinson, joined the USS
Enterprise in the strategic waterway. Another 2,000 Army troops
were en route to the region to bolster 3,000 GIs already in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty five additional combat aircraft were dispatched, as well,
to join more than 200 warplanes already in the region.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton's spokesman declined to say whether
U.S. military operations would halt with the onset of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to speculate on the duration or length of this
military operation,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
