<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Dec. 18. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
CLINTON-CYNICS (Undated) - Even in the era of a crook like
President Nixon, there was no one except the wildest fringes who
would have suggested that he could manipulate the American military
to save his political hide. And yet, today, all of America is
questioning the timing of President Clinton's raid on Iraq. What is
it about society that has made us so jaded, and willing to believe
almost anything? We are trying to talk with some local veterans,
retirees, etc., but also some national experts. By MARTIN VAN DER
WERF. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN (Undated) - For a minute I felt frightened, a soul
chill that drew me back to boyhood, to the age of 10, 11, 12. To
nights when I regularly snapped out of sleep to a vision of
shadows, ashen blemishes cast on charred concrete. Nuclear
silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't felt such a fear in 20 years, maybe longer. Then I sat
at my desk staring at the television set Wednesday afternoon,
taking in the face of our president and the greenish glow of
Baghdad at night. These images made me feel young again but not
youthful; young, but at the same time, too old. By DAVID LEIBOWITZ.
Story will move in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Undated) - Welcome back, Acura. All is forgiven. Well,
maybe not all. Some of the boneheaded mistakes that have blurred
Acura's image are still just a little hard to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Acura still manages to build excellent cars, noted
for comfort and reliability, just like its proletarian stablemate,
Honda. That's what keeps 'em coming to the showrooms and ensures
Acura's continued success. And for '99, there's the TL 3.2. By BOB
GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L'' category. EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY,
DEC. 19 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Am I past my prime? Are the days of youth
behind me? Is there a little expiration stamp someplace on my body
that says ``Best if used by 10/31/95''? By LAURI NOTARO. Story
moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MAIL-MOVIE (Undated) - You'll have to get over the idea that
they've made a sequel to ``Sleepless in Seattle.'' Yes, ``You've
Got Mail''
</P>
<P>
   does have the same two stars and the same writer/director, and
yes, it's a romantic comedy about people who haven't met - but it's
a different one. How should you approach ``You've Got Mail?'' Think
Hepburn and Tracy. That's the kind of easy comic grace that the
repairing of Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks brings to the affair. 4 stars.
By BOB FENSTER. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PRINCE-MOVIE (Undated) - This is a spectacular animated Bible story
about Moses (voiced by Val Kilmer), the Hebrew baby raised in the
</P>
<P>
   royal house of Egypt, who leads his people to freedom. The art
work, vastly aided by computer animation, is so gorgeous that you
often forget you're watching animation. Although the movie is more
sophisticated than the typical Disney animated fairy tale, young
kids will get caught up in the excitement of the action and the
music, and not mind what story subtleties they miss. 4 stars. By
BOB FENSTER. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GODS-MOVIE (Undated) - ``Gods and Monsters,'' an adaptation of
Christopher Bram's novel ``Father of Frankenstein,'' is a
fictionalized account of the last days of James Whale, one of the
most influential directors in Hollywood history. Whale set the
pattern for all horror films to come with the 1931 Universal
production of ``Frankenstein.'' By KYLE LAWSON. Story moved in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) - We've been duped. For years now, Saddam
Hussein has pretended to be a bloodthirsty dictator with a special
hatred for the United States of America.
</P>
<P>
   He manufactured and stored weapons of mass destruction as part
of this clever deception. He defied U.N. weapons inspectors and
ignored international treaties. He rearmed his military and
brutally suppressed his own people.
</P>
<P>
   All with the sinister expectation that someday, when called
upon, he'd come to the aid of his good friend and fellow Democrat,
Bill Clinton. By E.J. MONTINI. Story moved in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GRANT-MUSIC (Undated) - It was completely unplanned on her part.
But the way things are going, Amy Grant may just become the Perry
Como of her generation. Something about her warmly reassuring voice
and comfortable way around a Christmas tune have permanently linked
her with the holiday. And once she donned a wintery white gown and
sat down for a photographer, a new Christmas ambassador was born.
By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MESSINA-MUSIC (Undated) - You can tell a lot about country music
listeners by seeing how they react when certain names are evoked.
Mention Reba, for example, and rising singer Jo Dee Messina gives
the expected response: ``She's just great,'' Messina gushes,
speaking in her rapid, no-twang style. ``I love her so much.'' Then
the subject of Sylvia comes up, a one-name goddess from the
``Breakfast Club''
</P>
<P>
   decade who sported feathered hair and sang feathery songs ``Oh,
my God!'' Messina yells, before she starts singing: `` `Well, your
nobody called today, and she hung when I asked her name' _ I still
know every word!'' By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COLLINS-MUSIC (Undated) - Judy Collins has never been shy about
speaking her mind. She is of the Dylan-Baez-Seeger generation that
addressed the ills of 1960s America with protest songs and folk
music. Next year she will mark 40 years since she was first paid to
sing.
</P>
<P>
   She has not stopped since. By BARBARA YOST. Story will move in
the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
