<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-THREATS-PA     12-17 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-THREATS-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  PENN. LAWMAKER SAYS DEMS THREATENED HIM FOR CALLING FOR PREZ
TO RESIGN By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 17. -- Rep. Paul McHale said he received
threats of ``political retaliation'' from other Democrats since he
called on President Clinton earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is has been the most difficult period of my political
career - one that I would never want to relive again,'' Mchale,
D-Lehigh Valley, said. ``I have received sharp criticism in writing
and verbally -- some are what could only be described as threats to
my political future. There have been some heavy-handed tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, McHale he became the first Democrat in the House of
Representatives to publicly denounce Clinton amid the scandal
surrounding his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, McHale and a Republican House lawmaker sent
Clinton a letter asking the president to resign. He also hit the
national television circuit condemning Clinton's actions.
</P>
<P>
   He authored a censure resolution. He has not said whether he
will vote to impeach Clinton but has hinted he is strongly leaning
toward doing so.
</P>
<P>
   In the months that followed, McHale said he received phone calls
from former employees, constituents and fellow Democrats
criticizing and second-guessing his actions.
</P>
<P>
   As the House prepares to vote this weekend on whether to impeach
Clinton, McHale said his experience has been illustrative of ``the
heat of the partisan-driven process of this impeachment inquiry.''
McHale, who is retiring next month, said he doesn't plan to run for
office again. But Democrats told him in letters and comments that
they would remember his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was made clear to me by some of the more partisan members
of my party and defenders of the president that if I decide to
enter public life again or seek office that they have long
memories,'' McHale said.
</P>
<P>
   McHale would not say specifically who sent the letters or made
the comments.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Wyche, a spokesman for the Democratic National Comittee
said ``strong-arming'' tactics or threats of any kind are not
condoned or tolerated by the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is something we are definitely opposed to a member
doing,'' Wyche said. ``The impeachment vote is a vote of
conscience. Congressman McHale has talked about censure being a
better course and we agree with him on that. I would take offense
to anyone who is making threats to him like that.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale said his criticisms of Clinton has stemmed from
Democratic principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how we Democrats can pass laws to help sexual
harassment lawsuits and then excuse Clinton's conduct in the Paula
Jones case,'' McHale said. ``How can you send the message that it
is okay for the president to act this way and then expect a CEO of
a company to take testimony seriously in a sexual harassment case
against him?''
</P>
<P>
   McHale said he feels badly that his critical comments of Clinton
were met with claims of disloyalty from members of his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply regret that what I have done and will do will hurt
the feelings of close friends and political supporters,'' McHale
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would like to have had the support of some in his
party, but acted in a way that was ``true `` to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires a great deal of courage to go out there on your
own,'' McHale said. ``It's the most courageous thing I've done in
my 20 years of public life. I feel I have tried to make a
difference.'' -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
