<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DOUBTS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   DOUBTS ABOUT CLINTON'S MOTIVES SUBTLY SHAPE HIS PRESIDENCY
   By BOB DEANS
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Thursday found himself having
to defend his decision to attack Iraq from criticism that the raids
were timed to disrupt impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not true,'' Clinton told reporters as he began a
closed-door briefing on the strikes with his national security
team. ''I don't think any serious person would believe that any
president would do such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   While no previous Clinton initiative has generated the
skepticism of Clinton's order to strike Iraq, every major action
since the Monica Lewinsky affair erupted last January has been
scrutinized for scandal-related significance.
</P>
<P>
   And whether they are true or false, the allegations of ulterior
motives themselves
</P>
<P>
   affect Clinton's presidency in several ways.
</P>
<P>
   First, they complicate presidential decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has more than proven his ability to compartmentalize
issues over the past 12 months. But the administration's obsession
with public opinion and its intensive coordination with the
Congress makes clear that, at some level, considerations are made
about how any given statement, initiative or policy might be
perceived in light of the ongoing impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   The charges also make it difficult for Clinton to get across the
message behind his moves.
</P>
<P>
   At his most recent press conference in Jerusalem last Sunday,
Clinton's efforts to discuss the Mideast peace process were so
thwarted by repeated impeachment-related questions, from Israeli as
well as American reporters, that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
was reduced at one point to asking that reporters stick to the
subject of war and peace.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the current environment virtually assures that
Clinton's motives will be questioned, at least by his detractors,
no matter what he tries to do.
</P>
<P>
   With a lengthy Senate trial likely in the event that the House
votes in the days ahead to impeach the president, nagging questions
from the press and from Clinton's political foes about how White
House actions play into the impeachment process appear certain to
continue well into next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president's in an extremely difficult position, where
people are naturally suspicious,'' said Thomas E. Mann, director of
governmental studies at the Brookings Institution, a Washington
research center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Impeachment isn't thought to be a normal, regular activity
certainly, it's extraordinary,'' said Mann. ''Now it's happening,
and so of course every member of the press is going to ask the
question. It comes with the territory. There's no avoiding it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iraq attack makes the point.
</P>
<P>
   Every administration official Clinton sent out to try to explain
the purpose and goals of the air strikes _ White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart, Defense Secretary William Cohen, Joint Chiefs of
Staff Chairman Gen. Hugh Shelton, national security adviser Samuel
Berger and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright _ has been forced
to deal with the question of whether the ongoing raids have
political purposes behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Each has stridently denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the facts as they are, given the fact that (Clinton)
makes
</P>
<P>
   decisions based on what's in the national security interest,''
said Lockhart, ''he
</P>
<P>
   believes that you can have a debate on the policy, but not a
real debate on the timing.''
</P>
<P>
   White House staffers can see no clear way out of their current
dilemma. Clinton himself has prescribed the only cure: simply keep
showing up for work and do the best job possible.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials adamantly reject, though, the view that
the scandal-poisoned environment undercuts Clinton's authority or
ability to perform his job as the nation's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the president has demonstrated his ability to lead
both our country and lead within the international community,''
said Lockhart. ''I don't think the president has trouble separating
the vital national security interests of this country with some of
the domestic politics that are going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the American public must make similar distinctions.
That, said Mann, won't necessarily hurt Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''My tentative political reading is that the Republicans have
greatly overplayed their hand,'' Mann said, by suggesting that the
Iraq raids were politically timed and by then rushing forward with
House impeachment debate on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''They run a risk of looking like zealots,'' said Mann,
''determined, at any price, to get their hated president.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
