<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NAGANO-SPI &LR;      12-17 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NAGANO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GLITZ, JUST SOLID GOLD IN `NAGANO '98'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bud Greenspan's films always induce a little deja vu because
there doesn't seem to be much difference from one to the other. For
some viewers, one athlete overcoming daunting obstacles to win gold
in the '60s will seem pretty much like another overcoming daunting
obstacles to win gold in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan, the dean of sports documentarians, has the heart
of a romantic storyteller. ``I'm pretty idealistic about the whole
philosophy of the Olympics,'' he told TV critics last summer.
``It's almost a religious concept to me.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Greenspan's latest effort for Showtime, premiering
Sunday at 8 p.m., is numbingly familiar in its Greenspan-ness, but
still good for a couple of lump-in-the-throat moments and a tingle
or two.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, who began covering sports before the Dodgers left
Brooklyn, is that rare breed with an eye for arresting images and
an ear for well-chosen words. His filmmaking isn't precocious; it
isn't cute.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the occasional slow-motion clip for dramatic effect,
it is straightforward, almost archaic in an age of quick cuts and
jarring edits. And, even if narrator Will Lyman's deep drone is
reminiscent of a National Football League highlight reel, there is
a quiet dignity to Greenspan's work that is soothing, despite the
chaotic nature of the subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nagano '98 Olympics'' is similar to the features that NBC and
CBS used in their telecasts of the Games in '96 and '98. But where
the networks caught flak for ignoring the action in favor of the
inspirational warm-and-fuzzies, Greenspan's job is exactly that: to
find the human aspect of an athletic competition where the stated
goal is to celebrate ``the honor and glory of sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is still more about the athlete _ and the single-minded
athletic quest _ than it is about the athlete at home. The networks
love to give us shots of athletes cooking breakfast or giving the
dog a bath, but Greenspan doesn't go in for that. Away from the
competition venue, the athlete may be seen on his or her home turf
_ for winter Olympians it's usually a mountain village _ but
there's not a lot of up-close-and-personal stuff going on here.
</P>
<P>
   Straight-ahead interviews, often with the voice of a translator
providing the athlete's words, are more Greenspan's style. Not
flashy, but starkly effective in an uncluttered, just-the-facts
way.
</P>
<P>
   The Nagano film doesn't pretend to cover the entire spectrum of
Olympic events. No curling. No luge. No biathlon. Instead, it
focuses on the stories of 11 athletes. Some of them won gold last
February, some won much more than a medal.
</P>
<P>
   The subjects of ``Nagano '98 Olympics'' are alpine skiers
Jean-Luc Cretier of France and Brian Stemmle of Canada; figure
skater Lu Chen of China; cross-country skiers Bjorn Daehlie and
Thomas Alsgaard, both of Norway; speed skaters Kirstin Holum of the
United States and Gunda Niemann-Stirnemann of Germany; bobsled
drivers Guenther Huber of Italy and Pierre Lueders of Canada;
alpine skier Deborah Compagnoni of Italy; and ski jumper Masahiko
Harada of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The common thread tying this group of uncommon athletes together
is a determination that most of us can only marvel at. Whether it's
one athlete's legendary effort to win an eighth Olympic gold medal
or the enormously satisfying tale of two rivals who end up tying
for the gold, or another athlete's emergence from a bout of
self-doubt, Greenspan is adept at showing that, while there's
nothing quite like the thrill of victory, there doesn't have to be
agony in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at a time when we hear regularly about athletes being
suspended for drug use and, even more recently, about bribes being
made by some groups to secure rights to host the Olympic Games,
Greenspan concentrates solely on the basic concept of athletic
achievement. It may be naive to think that sports can exist in such
a vacuum. It's also most pleasant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
