A5585 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLINS-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      12-17 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOES ONLY STRENGTHEN JUDY COLLINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Judy Collins was there, speaking in that lovely,
lilting voice we've been listening to for almost four decades.
</P>
<P>
   And then she was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry to cut this short,'' she was saying from her hotel
room at the Beverly Hills Hotel. ``But I have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   She was gracious. She was polite. She thanked me for my time.
</P>
<P>
   But she was gone, barely 10 minutes into a telephone interview
that had twice been interrupted by calls waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of Collins' cheery hello, I was on hold,
consigned to the hotel's version of Muzak: Beethoven's ``Ode to
Joy.''
</P>
<P>
   After several minutes, she returned, sweet Judy blue eyes, happy
to answer questions about a president who admired her singing so
much he named his only-begotten daughter after one of her hits,
``Chelsea Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins was at Bill Clinton's first triumphant inauguration
where it seemed all the promise of the future could be summed up in
a Fleetwood Mac song ``Don't Stop Thinking About Tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   She has seen both sides now of the man whose personal foibles
have alienated him from disenchanted people who once fawned. At 59,
her own life a series of ups and downs, marked by sensational
musical success and also by such tragedies as the suicide of her
only son, Collins has never wavered in her devotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wonderful president. He will go down as a great
president,'' she said with conviction.
</P>
<P>
   While confessing that ``I'm not thrilled with some of the things
he's done,'' Collins blames groups that she believes have raised
huge sums of money to discredit Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   She does not use the term ``right-wing conspiracy.'' But it is
clear she sees forces at work hounding the president. Of Clinton
nemesis Ken Starr, she says bluntly, ``I don't like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Collins has never been shy about speaking her mind. She is
of the Dylan-Baez-Seeger generation that addressed the ills of
1960s America with protest songs and folk music. Next year she will
mark 40 years since she was first paid to sing.
</P>
<P>
   She has not stopped since. All of the temptations of the
flower-child era (pills proffered at parties, alcoholism, affairs
with such notables as Stephen Stills, who wrote the exquisite
``Suite: Judy Blue Eyes'' to mark their breakup), bouts of illness
(childhood polio, tuberculosis, hepatitis, bulimia) and surgery on
her vocal cords only seem to have made the woman stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Even throat surgery could not daunt her. In 1977, a hemangioma
(swollen capillary) on the vibrating surface of her vocal cord
threatened to silence her gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid I would never sing again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But after undergoing risky laser surgery, Collins recuperated
miraculously in just a few months and returned with a clear voice
and an even wider vocal range. She attributes her recovery to the
solid voice training she had as a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Today Collins is as amazing as ever. She is currently enjoying a
three-week Christmas tour that has taken her across the country to
serenade an audience that includes not only fans who still thrill
to ``Both Sides Now,'' ``Someday Soon,'' ``Send in the Clowns'' and
her rendition of ``Amazing Grace,'' but a new generation that
clamors for her CDs, including last year's ``Christmas at the
Biltmore Estate.''
</P>
<P>
   But true to the first cut on her Christmas album, Collins will
be home for Christmas in New York, where she enjoys a rich life
with second husband Louis Nelson, a close-knit circle of friends
and a voracious appetite for reading.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is as much a writer as a reader. With five books already
published, including a novel, she added a sixth this year,
``Singing Lessons.'' The book is part autobiography and part
exorcism of the pain that has plagued her since 1992 when her
beloved son Clark committed suicide at age 33.
</P>
<P>
   The hurt is palpable. So is the feeling of redemption evident in
the last lines: ``In the midst of winter,'' she quotes Albert
Camus, ``I discovered that in me there was an invincible summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderfully cathartic,'' Collins said of writing her
book.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's death inducted her into the sisterhood of celebrity
survivors of family suicides _ Mariette Hartley, Joan Rivers,
Gloria Vanderbilt _ who have spoken out about the despair and
shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suicide is the last taboo,'' Collins said. ``People are afraid
to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Collins. For her, there was no question her agony would be
vented in a book: ``I'm a writer. So I wrote. That's how I
process.''
</P>
<P>
   She will also launch a Web site (www.caretolive.com) in the next
few weeks on which she will share chapters from ``Singing
Lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing the book has changed her, she said, and she is better
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst has happened. Now I don't fear anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Her only fear, apparently, is running out of time. The lilting
voice politely dismissed me.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps she had a sound check. Perhaps it was lunch time. Joan
Baez might have stopped by to protest the crack in the ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Monica Lewinsky wants to record an album. Send in the
clowns.
</P>
<P>
   There was no explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merry Christmas,'' Collins said breezily.
</P>
<P>
   And then she was gone. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 1859EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
