<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER GIVES THIEF A HARD LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our friend is a wonderful woman _ tender, but also no-nonsense
strong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She happens to be the daughter of the university athletic
director who, in 1911, came up with the idea of a homecoming
weekend for a football game and alumni reunion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband have raised three fine children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She has battled cancer and won. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And she retired not long ago after a 30-year career as a teacher
in urban public schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The long and short of it is that the purse-snatcher picked the
wrong mark. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our friend was in the grocery at midafternoon in the friendly,
safe neighborhood near home _ her purse in the basket beside her as
she made a selection from the shelf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, out of the corner of her eye, she noticed her purse
leaving the basket, and a woman in a red sweatshirt and jeans
headed out the door with it under her arm. Our friend ran after her
into the street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady, you have my purse!'' she cried. ``Do you want me to call
the police?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lady ran on, into a parking lot, where she momentarily
disappeared. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seemed to notice the commotion. Our friend asked a man in
rough work clothes, standing nearby and smoking, if he'd seen the
woman in a red sweatshirt run by. The man shrugged his shoulders,
replied with a curt ``No,'' and bent aside to tie his shoe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It appeared everything was lost _ the purse, the money it
contained, credit cards and, most important, pictures of the
children. But the victim of this heist didn't give up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She climbed up on the side of a trash container in the lot to
get a better vantage. She waited. And, sure enough, she spotted the
red shirt and the woman headed toward a rusty, dented old car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the thief got in, our friend put her foot in the door to
prevent it from being closed. Then she reached inside and seized
back her property. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't do that!'' she told the woman sternly. ``Why did
you take my purse?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The woman looked to be 30 or 35 years old, with unkempt dyed or
bleached blonde hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you need money?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The woman hung her head. ``Yes,'' she said tearfully. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon our friend opened her recovered purse and took out a
$10 bill _ most of what she was carrying. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Take this,'' she said. ``If you need money, there are other
ways to get it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go,'' said the woman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``All right. (Begin ital) But don't you ever steal anybody's
purse again!'' (end italic) Spoken like someone whose life work has
been teaching _ not just academic subjects, but also in matters of
character and behavior. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The woman backed the old car, picked up the man who'd been
approached for help, and the two of them rode away together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The obvious lesson is that a red shirt isn't an ideal thief's
choice. Whether the larger lesson will register can't be known. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What seems likely is that the urban school systems of this
country are peopled by a great many teachers with that blend of
courage and compassion. And if only bureaucrats and bickering
administrators would stand aside and let them teach, we'd be
hearing less about the shortcomings of public education. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
