<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEDICARE PROGRAM WILL LEAD TO CONFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you understand the following paragraph? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can return to your Medigap policy if you dropped it to
enroll in a Medicare health plan or a Medicare SELECT policy.
However: (1) this must be the first time that you enrolled in a
health plan or a SELECT policy; (2) you must leave the health plan
or SELECT policy within one year after joining; and (3) after
leaving your health plan or SELECT policy, you must choose a
Medigap policy within 63 days. If you meet these requirements, you
can return to your original Medigap policy, if it is still offered,
or policies A, B, C, or F.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Would your 85-year-old mother understand it? asks Jerry Nebbia,
who heads the William M. Mercer health-care and group benefits
consulting practice in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The quote is from ``Medicare &AMP; You,'' an enrollment handbook
from the federal Health Care Financing Administration, the agency
publicizing upcoming Medicare changes. Even if you're not a
Medicare recipient _ yet _ it pays to know what's ahead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reports about the status of Medicare and its new managed-care
option, Medicare (plus) Choice, published Monday in The Kansas City
Star, indicated confusion ahead. Nebbia says Medicare recipients
won't suffer alone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Mercer survey found that more than half of all employers who
offer retiree medical benefits ``have not done anything specific to
prepare for the barrage of phone calls, letters and e-mails
expected when the Medicare (plus) Choice information reaches
recipients this month.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The consulting company says 62 percent of mid-size and large
organizations offer retiree medical benefits. Yet only about half
have done anything to educate their benefits staff about Medicare
changes, much less provide information to their retirees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The question barrage may not hit small businesses immediately.
Typically, larger businesses are the ones that extend health-care
benefits to retirees. But many small-business operators also
provide financial information to their retirees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The question barrage may not hit the Kansas City area
immediately. Missouri and Kansas are not among the five states
(Arizona, Florida, Ohio, Oregon and Washington) introducing
Medicare (plus) Choice in 1999. But beware the national rollout in
2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the options is complicated. Even persons familiar
with managed care and health maintenance organizations will wade
through dense Medicare (plus) Choice information. Retirees, many of
whom know only traditional indemnity plans for their health
insurance coverage, will have extra questions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At the minimum, company benefits offices need to let their
retirees know how their benefit plans will coordinate with
Medicare,'' Nebbia said. ``They need to be ready to help their
retirees choose options that make sense for them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's a tall order for busy benefits offices. Many businesses
have their hands full helping employees cope with annual enrollment
periods for multiple health-care plans. Many questions already
exist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's why consulting companies are sounding the alert.
Somebody's going to have to provide a lot of answers soon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
