<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-OFFER-KAN </SLUG>
  
 BLUE CROSS BLUE SHIELD OF KC hopes buy its St. Louis counterpart  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS KARASH  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City is prepared to make an
offer of $278 million to buy St. Louis-based Blue Cross and Blue
Shield of Missouri, the head of the Kansas City company said
Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such a deal would amount to the biggest combination among
Missouri health insurers in recent memory, said Randy McConnell, a
spokesman for the Missouri Department of Insurance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John P. Mascotte, president and chief executive officer of Blue
Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City, discussed the proposal at a
hearing in St. Louis by a special court master acting on behalf of
Cole County Circuit Judge Thomas Brown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The special master is reviewing a proposed settlement of
litigation involving an attempt a few years ago by Blue Cross and
Blue Shield of Missouri to convert to a for-profit company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The proposed settlement calls for the assets of Blue Cross and
Blue Shield of Missouri, including its 15 million shares of stock
in RightChoice Managed Care Inc., to endow a charitable health-care
foundation to be known as the Missouri Foundation for Health. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The foundation would fund health-care programs for uninsured and
under-insured residents throughout much of Missouri. The proposed
endowment was valued at $150 million earlier this year, McConnell
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mascotte said under his proposal a ``powerful statewide,
multisite, efficient operation would be created. Significant
economies would be realized.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City is the leading health
insurer in the Kansas City area. It provides health insurance
services to 774,000 people in 30 counties in western Missouri and
Johnson and Wyandotte counties in Kansas. The Kansas City insurer
and its affiliates have more than 1,300 employees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Missouri has more than 2 million
members, including members of RightChoice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite intense competition from big, national managed-care
companies that have entered the Kansas City market, Mascotte said
the proposed merger was not a make-or-break situation for the
company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is an opportunity to achieve greater efficiency
and more effectiveness in the marketplace as a result of the
combination,'' Mascotte said. ``We believe that a statewide Blue
Cross and Blue Shield organization would allow us the opportunity
to write more business and do it more efficiently than would be the
case if the two plans remained separate.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Mascotte said ``retaining the non-profit status of
Blue Cross on a statewide basis is the best way of maintaining the
health insurance capacity that Missourians need.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mascotte said the headquarters of the combined entity would be
in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Mascotte's proposal drew a chilly response in St. Louis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John O'Rourke, the head of RightChoice and Blue Cross and Blue
Shield of Missouri, said his companies earlier had declined to
enter such talks with the Kansas City insurer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Rourke said the proposed settlement with the state ``is an
integral part of our long-range strategic plan and offers a
superior alternative.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``After implementation of our settlement agreement as agreed to
with the state, RightChoice will be better positioned to consider
combinations with other entities to ensure that value to all
shareholders is maximized,'' O'Rourke said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mascotte said his proposal was discussed in September and
October among officials of Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas
City, Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Missouri and RightChoice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``While Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Missouri and RightChoice
management informed us, after a preliminary discussion, they had
determined not to enter into further discussions with us, we
continue to believe the alternative we are proposing actually
builds on the proposed settlement agreement and offers greater
benefits,'' Mascotte said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Kansas City insurer denied it was in merger
talks with the St. Louis company but left the door open to such
talks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, with the Missouri Department of Insurance, said the
department had been aware for some time that the Kansas City
insurer wanted to acquire its St. Louis counterpart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such a sale would be subject to approval by Cole County Circuit
Judge Thomas Brown and the department of insurance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The deal would include payment to RightChoice shareholders of
$13.50 per share in cash. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
