<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-SYMPTOMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS BLOCK ASTHMA IN MICE, RAISING HOPES OF NEW DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists say they have shut down the symptoms of asthma in
mice by blocking a single chemical messenger in the immune system,
raising the prospect of new, finely tuned drugs to treat the
disease that afflicts 15 million Americans and annually kills
several thousand.
</P>
<P>
   In a report in the current journal Science, researchers say they
have shown that a chemical messenger known as interleukin-13, or
IL-13, can by itself trigger the abnormal immune response that
causes breathing passages to become ``twitchy'' _ oversensitive to
irritants _ and narrowed, plugged with mucus and inflamed.
</P>
<P>
   And when the scientists used a laboratory-made protein to sop up
excess IL-13 in the lungs of mice in which asthma attacks had been
triggered, it dramatically reduced the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, no single part of the complex immune system had been
identified as both necessary and sufficient to set off the entire
cascade of reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big step forward,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Drazen, chief
of the pulmonary medicine division at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've recognized for quite a while that asthma is an
inflammatory disease, and we've been looking for something that
could be at the root of it,'' said Drazen, who was not involved in
the study. ``If IL-13 is at the root of it,'' as the new findings
suggest, ``you would think you could get rid of that inflammation
and make the patient better'' if a drug could be found that blocks
the action of IL-13.
</P>
<P>
   A narrowly targeted asthma treatment would be welcome news for
patients who currently rely on a mixture of lung-clearing
inhalants, steroids, and anti-inflammatory and other drugs to
control the wheezing and shortness of breath caused by asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is the leading cause of school days missed by US
children, is a major cause of work absenteeism, and causes about
5,000 deaths a year.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse studies were carried out by Marsha Wills-Karp and
colleagues at Johns Hopkins University, using a protein developed
by Debra D. Donaldson of Genetics Institute Inc. in Cambridge to
block IL-13.
</P>
<P>
   That protein is being investigated as a potential asthma drug,
said L. Patrick Gage, former president of Genetics Institute and
currently president of Wyeth-Ayerst Research in Radnor, Pa.
Wyeth-Ayerst and Genetics Institute are owned by American Home
Products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty promising, but we have a lot more work to do,''
said Gage in a telephone interview. Among other things, any side
effects of blocking IL-13 in human patients must be analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely to be 18 months or more at the earliest before
clinical trials could begin, said Gage.
</P>
<P>
   In a companion study in Science, researchers at the University
of California in San Francisco led by Gabriele G. Grunig and Dr.
David B. Corry report similar findings. They also showed that
applying IL-13 directly to mouse nasal passages brought on the
symptoms, and did so more potently than another form of
interleukin, IL-4, which had previously been implicated in asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is the result of an overreaction by the immune system to
substances in the environment that in themselves are not
particularly harmful. The mistaken reaction occurs when, in
response to inhaled substances such as pollen, insect droppings, or
smoke, immune cells called CD4 cells rapidly multiply and release a
variety of messenger chemicals called cytokines.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the cytokines produce antibodies and activate so-called
mast cells, which release histamines and other substances that
constrict the breathing passages, stimulate the production of
mucus, and attract inflammatory cells called eosinophils.
</P>
<P>
   It had been thought that the cytokine known as IL-4 was the most
important player in this cascade. But the new studies show that
IL-13 is the single most important immune system element _ it can
cause the asthma symptoms by itself, and when it is blocked, the
manifestations subside.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists used mice that have a tendency to develop
asthmatic symptoms. When the mice were given the protein that
blocks IL-13 in an aerosol form and then were exposed to a foreign
substance known to trigger asthma, they did not develop narrowed
and clogged airways and other symptoms, said the researchers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
