<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times will lead Friday's issue with a 6-column,
2-line headline on the continuing attacks on Iraq and Republican
plans for the full House to begin Friday the debate on the
impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, The Times plans 7 pages of coverage for Iraq and
impeachment stories.
</P>
<P>
   The two lede stories will move by  &UR; 9:30 p.m. Eastern time &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ The ledeall: military and
political developments, including tonight's disclosure by
Speaker-elect Bob Livingston's of past marital indescretions. By
R.W. Apple Jr. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Ledeall on impeachment developments. By
Alison Mitchell. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   These are the other stories in the package:
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-MILITARY (Washington) _ As the United States and Britain
continued air strikes in Iraq for a second day, the Pentagon
announced that it was inflicting significant damage to airfields
security and intelligence headquarters and barracks of the elite
Republican Guards that help keep President Saddam Hussein in power.
By Steven Lee Myers. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-GOALS (Undated) _ As American and British air strikes
continue, there are persistent questions, both inside the
Government and outside, over what American strategy toward Iraq
should be after the bombing stops. Despite a series of discussions
and the exchange of papers between London and Washington, there is
still no agreed, coherent strategy, officials of both countries
concede. By Steven Erlanger and Serge Schmemann. (1200 wortds)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-TIMING (Washington) _ On the timing of Butler's report and
of the attack. By John M. Broder, Jeff Gerth and Barbara Crossette.
(1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-POLL (Washington) _ Overnight poll shows support for
Clinton. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-CLINTON (Washington) _ Day developments at the White House.
By James Bennet. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-REACT (Washington) _ More reaction, from Capitol Hill and
around the country. By Eric Schmitt. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-GORE (Washington) _ With bombs falling on Iraq and an
impeachment vote nearing in the House, Vice President Gore has
taken an unusually visible role in defending President Clinton and
the military actions that have spurred deep skepticism from many
Republicans. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Netanyahu makes a
veiled warning to Iraq not to attack Israel; Israelis are urged to
get gas masks. By Joel Greenberg. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-EUROPE (Paris) _ European reaction, focusing on the French
and Germans. By Craig R. Whiteny. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ARABS (Kuwait City) _ Reaction from Arab Governments and
people. By Douglas Jehl. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ARAB-AMERICANS (Dearborn, Mich.) _ This week's American
attack on Iraq has divided this city, the nation's largest and most
concentrated Arab-American community here, for while Saddam Hussein
is almost universally loathed, opinions differ on whether renewed
air strikes will do any good. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SOUTH (Dateline to kum) _ What do Southerners, often
bedrock supporters of military, say about the attack? By Kevin
Sack. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Russia assailed the U.S. air strike
against Iraq today, in one of the angriest broadsides against
American policy since the end of the Cold War. President Yeltsin
denounced the attacks as a violation of the U.N. Charter. The
Russian military said the attack had undermined Moscow's already
frayed relations with NATO. The Communist-dominated parliament
signaled its opposition by delaying the ratification of the START-2
treaty, which would slash strategic nuclear arms. By Michael R.
Gordon. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON (Washington) _ Rep. Robert Livingston, the
incoming House speaker, discloses that he had marital indiscretions
in the past and, according to Roll Call Magazine, tells his
Republican membership that he is willing to resign. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-IRAQ-REPUBS (Washington) _ The outpouring of
recriminations from Republicans questioning President Clinton's
motives in bombing Iraq threatens the party's effort to make its
vote to impeach President Clinton appear non-partisan and a sad but
simple Constitutional duty. By Richard L. Berke. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-IRAQ-LOTT (Washington) _ Why Trent Lott, the Senate
Republican leader, broke with the code of supporting presidents
when American troops in action. By David E. Rosenbaum. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-PROTEST (Washington) _ Jesse Jackson and others protest
on the Capitol steps. By Steven A. Holmes. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ The wild day on Capitol Hill. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LAMEDUCK (Wahington) _ The lame ducks in the House, 21
Republicans and 17 Democrats, not including two Republicans and one
Democrat who won election to Senate seats. And with the House
taking up impeachment on Friday, they have streamed back into
Washington to vote one last time. Will they vote their consciences?
By Richard W. Stevenson. (850)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STANDARDS (Washington) _ What standards for impeachment
did the Judiciary Committee put before the House for debate.
Impeachable offense? Standard of proof? Public or private conduct?
Is all perjury the same? By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-JOHNSON (Undated) _ Swept up in rhetorical passion for
the sanctity of the Constitution and the Republic, the House of
Representatives debated for a scant 14 hours and then voted for the
first _ and then, the only time _ to impeach a president. A look at
the case of Andrew Johnson. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SOLOMON (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ A visit to the
district of the upstate N.Y. congressman who ripped Clinton. By
Mike Allen.
</P>
