<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP, DEMOCRATS CLASH OVER IMPEACHMENT DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House will proceed Friday
with a debate on impeaching President Clinton despite strong
Democratic objections to taking up the issue while American forces
attack Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we engage in conflict, democracy does not stop,'' said
Majority Leader Richard K. Armey of Texas, who was among the
leading Republicans who defended the decision to move ahead with
the impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   The precise rules governing the debate and the length of
deliberations were still being hashed out late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats bristled at taking up the issue so soon after
Clinton ordered the airborne attacks, saying a vote on removing the
president from office should not be taken in a time of military
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David E. Bonior of Michigan accused the Republican leaders
of showing ``a lack of judgment ... a lack of common sense'' in
proceeding with the impeachment issue while military forces are
engaged in a conflict with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must think of not only how this act will be received by
Americans,'' said Democratic leader Richard A. Gephardt of
Missouri. ``We also have to look at how Saddam Hussein will
perceive the idea and information that while he is under physical
attack ... we are having a debate to remove the commander in
chief.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Nancy Pelosi said it was ``disrespectful of the
troops'' to seek to impeach the president. ``We're going to weaken
the U.S. by impeaching the commander in chief and Saddam Hussein is
going to have a big chuckle about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston and other Republicans insisted that the debate and a
likely vote to impeach Clinton must proceed. The debate, scheduled
to start Thursday, was postponed when American and British forces
began bombing Iraq Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In one break from the partisanship that has dominated the
impeachment issue, the House Thursday overwhelmingly approved a
resolution supporting American troops in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The House will consider charges that Clinton committed perjury,
obstruction of justice and abuse of power in connection with the
cover-up of his affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have a 228-207 majority in the House, where a
majority vote in favor of one or more articles of impeachment would
trigger a Senate trial. If convicted by a two-thirds majority in
the Senate, Clinton would automatically be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   A chorus of Republican lawmakers sought to separate impeachment
from the Gulf crisis, saying domestic business must go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken a day of thoughtful stepping back, and then you
move on,'' said Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Rules Committee Chairman Gerald B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y., said the
president should have ordered the airstrikes on Iraq three months
ago, on another occasion when Saddam defied international weapons
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people want this done and over with and the only
way to get it done is to start (Friday) morning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to move this legislation,'' said Solomon, who is
retiring from Congress at the end of this year. ``We want to move
it because so that Congress can get back to its work.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon dismissed arguments that troops in the Persian Gulf
would be demoralized if the impeachment debate goes on while they
are in combat.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, as House members prepared to vote on a
resolution to support the use of U.S. troops in the Persian Gulf,
some lawmakers appeared to be taking pot shots at Solomon, who had
accused Clinton of launching airstrikes to avoid impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the resolution was 417 to 5 with Elizabeth Furse,
D-Ore., voting ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting against the resolution were Barbara Lee, D-Calif.,
Cynthia McKinney, D-Ga., John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., Mark Sanford,
R-S.C., and Ron Paul, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla., who was impeached as a federal
judge before coming to Congress, said it was ``crass'' to question
Clinton's motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``To question the integrity of his decision is insidious and
dangerous and can be destabilizing to our troops,'' Hastings said.
</P>
<P>
   But Solomon said he spoke to several representatives of major
veterans organizations who assured him it would not harm U.S.
troops if Congress proceeded with its impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Calif., also appeared to be aiming his
comments at Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never underestimate a desperate partisan whose lust for the
president's blood will cause him to make statements that will give
aid and comfort to the enemy,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., also sharply criticized those who
questioned Clinton's motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``To our colleagues who have questioned the president motives,
shame on you,'' Meehan said. ``Shame on you for ending the
tradition of setting aside partisanship at the water's edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said suggestions that Clinton's
decision on Iraq was an attempt to avoid impeachment should be
dismissed because the Defense Department supports the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was any reason to doubt, you'd hear all kinds of
squawks out of the Pentagon,'' Frank said.
</P>
</TEXT>
