<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Tobacco industry to offer ways to protect growers during N.C.
meeting
   By Peter Mantius
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Zell Miller and Gov.-elect Roy Barnes will lead a
contingent of Georgia officials to Raleigh-Durham, N.C., Friday to
listen to the tobacco industry's pitch on how best to protect
tobacco growers from being hurt by the recent $206 billion
liability settlement between the industry and more than 40 states.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Thurbert Baker and State Agriculture
Tommy Irvin will also attend the gathering of political leaders
from the six leading tobacco-producing states.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin said the industry appears to be divided over how to deal
with the expected decline in demand for domestic tobacco resulting
from the liability settlement, which has driven cigarette prices up
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leader Phillip Morris favors compensating tobacco quota
holders for the anticipated decline in value of their holdings. But
No. 2 R.J. Reynolds Tobacco wants to try to prop up the value of
the quotas by committing to boost its domestic tobacco purchases
over the next 10 years, thereby guaranteeing a predictable market
for the product.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin said he supports RJR's approach, and most growers like it,
too. However, many quota holders who lease their right to grow
tobacco lean toward Phillip Morris' cash compensation approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we can come away (from today's meeting) with assurance
that they'll commit to continue buying tobacco,'' Irvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is the nation's fourth largest producer of tobacco. The
state has roughly 9,000 tobacco quota holders and somewhat fewer
growers, Irvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The system of quotas or allotments was created by Congress in
the 1930s and limits the amount of tobacco individual farmers can
grow. The system all but assures quota holders of turning a profit
on their crops.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is attending the meeting in case the state is called on
to make an immediate commitment, while Barnes is going as an
observer, according to Barnes spokesman, Gary Horlacher.
</P>
<P>
   Baker is attending because he was the state's point man in
agreeing to the liability settlement, which included a provision
requiring the industry to develop a plan to assist tobacco growers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
