<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Jungle of predictions make it hard to map course of Amazon.com
   By Mark Clothier
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Trying to predict the value of an Internet stock is a
little like trying to nail a bubble.
</P>
<P>
   In two days, analysts from two separate investment houses priced
one stock, Amazon.com, $350 apart.
</P>
<P>
   CIBC Oppenheimer's Henry Blodget's $400 target price came
Wednesday. It shot Amazon.com's stock higher still. The stock was
already inflated by a pending split and online holiday shopping
expectations. Amazon.com rose to $301.75, before closing Wednesday
at $289, up 19 percent, or $46.25.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Jonathan Cohen, of Merrill Lynch Global Securities,
set Amazon.com's 12-to- 18-month target price at $50. In reaction,
the market ran real fast the other way. Amazon.com dropped as low
as $260.56 1/4 before closing Thursday at $276.75, down $12.25.
</P>
<P>
   The online retailer lost $78.1 million on sales of $357.1
million for the first nine months of 1998. And the Seattle-based
Amazon.com lost $20 million on $81.7 million in sales over the same
period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Horen, an analyst for NationsBanc Montgomery Securities,
has his Amazon.com 12- to 18-month target price set at between $150
and $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock is overvalued,'' Horen said. ``I also think that,
when you get into these sorts of bubbles, that it just doesn't make
sense to be constantly changing ratings. You could, but it's not a
thing to do. The price level, when you get a bubble like this, I
think is driven by people trading electronically, running
valuations up very high,'' he said. ``My experience is that the
prices don't really sustain.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
