<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-WORLD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   WORLD SPLITS IN REACTION TO U.S.-LED RAIDS ON IRAQ
   665 words
   By ANDREW MOLLISON
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While powerful Security Council members wrangled
fruitlessly behind closed doors Thursday at the United Nations
headquarters in New York, officials and opinion-shapers began
choosing up sides in the worldwide debate over the British-aided
U.S. attacks on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Sympathizers offered tolerant regrets and rather quiet support
for the bombings. Frustrated critics of the military strikes
condemned the United States and Britain with harsh words. However,
because both countries possess veto power at the Security Council,
they could block all efforts by Russia and China to arrange for an
immediate ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, American use of refueling facilities in Spain and
some Middle Eastern countries where verbal support was tepid or
nonexistent apparently continued undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the strongest endorsement came from Israel, where Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu praised the actions as ``the only way
to dispossess Iraq of the weapons of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   China was one of the first nations to object to the strikes. But
the strongest condemnations came from Russia and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``These activities constitute international terrorism,'' said a
resolution passed by the lower house of the Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin said the strikes ``crudely
violated'' the U.N. charter. Prime Minister Yevgeny Primaklov said
it was ``outrageous'' to launch a strike without explicit
permission of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's Senate overwhelmingly approved a resolution stating,
``This house condemns the U.S. military strike on Iraq and
considers it as an affront to the entire Moslem Umma (nation).''
</P>
<P>
   However, other predominantly Moslem nations were more
circumspect. Tunisia confined itself to expressing ``dismay and
deep concern.''
</P>
<P>
   While Iran described the strikes as ``quite unacceptable,'' the
foreign ministry's spokesman, Hamid Reza Assefi, also called on
Iraq ``to cooperate with the United Nations and comply with the
Security Council resolutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong supporters of the air strikes as listed by the Associated
Press include such English-speaking countries as Canada, Australia
and New Zealand, and also South Korea, the Netherlands, Austria,
Spain and Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein has brought this crisis on himself,'' Canadian
Prime Minister Jean Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developing of mass-destruction weapons is a threat against
stability and security in the whole region,'' Norwegian Foreign
Minister Knut Vollebaek said.
</P>
<P>
   France offered even-handed criticism of both sides _ deploring
``the grave human consequences'' of the strikes, but regretting the
failure of the Iraqi leaders ``to show proof of the spirit of
complete cooperation'' with U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, Japan was an outspoken defender of the raids, and India
a severe critic. Cambodia, the Philippines, Singapore and Vietnam
expressed regrets.
</P>
<P>
   In Mauritania in west Africa, police broke up student
demonstrations against the U.S. and British strikes, but the
government itself took no public stance.
</P>
<P>
   In Latin America, Operation Desert Fox, known in Spanish as
``Zorro del desierto,'' was condemned by Communist Cuba as an
``imperialist abuse.'' But President Carlos Menem of Argentina said
the strikes were ``the direct result of the Iraqi government's
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of force, rather than diplomacy, was criticized by
Venezuela and Costa Rica and regretted by other Latin countries
such as Brazil. Mexico expressed sorrow that ``''it was not
possible to find space for a diplomatic solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most unexpected reaction came from Cyprus, the
island nation in the Mediterranean uncomfortably divided between
Greek-held and Turkish-held territories.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's press service, the Islamic Republic News Agency, reported
that Yiannakis Omirou, defense minister of the pro-Greek Republic
of Cyprus, asked, ``Why didn't they use the same measures towards
Turkey?''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Associate Press and Reuters news service contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
