<SLUG> BC-AFC-ALIJAVA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Coffee and buns to go: AFC to franchise in Middle East
   By Shelia M. Poole
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based AFC Enterprises announced Thursday it
has signed an agreement to develop 65 Seattle's Best Coffee cafes
and 65 Cinnabon bakeries in six Middle Eastern countries.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, with Ali Java Cinnamon, represents the first
franchising venture outside North America for Seattle's Best Coffee
and the first franchising deal since 1992 for Cinnabon.
</P>
<P>
   Both brands were acquired by AFC earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabian-based Ali Java Cinnamon will open the bakeries and
cafes in Saudi Arabia, Lebanon, Bahrain, Qatar, United Arab
Emirates and Oman. The franchise is owned and operated by Fahad Al
Rashoodi, a prominent Saudi businessman, and Prince Mishari Bin
Abdullahl Al Saud, a member of the Saudi royal family.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Java will complete development over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coffee consumption is very high in the region as well as the
use of cinnamon in cooking,'' said Bill Van Epps, president of
AFC's International Division, who expects both brands to do well in
the Middle East. When all units are completed, the deal will bring
AFC $5 million in revenue annually.
</P>
<P>
   Epps said when Cinnabon was acquired last October, the database
included more than 600 inquiries from outside the United States
about possible franchise deals. Part of the reason for the
high-level of interest, he said, is because Cinnabon bakeries
usually are located in airports and shopping malls, sites that see
a lot of international traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Java already operates bakery cafe concepts in mall areas in
the Saudi Arabian cities of Riyadh, Jubail and Jeddah. Those sites
will be converted to SBC cafes and Cinnabon bakeries.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, coffee in that region is stronger than coffee in the
West, said Gary Goldstein, spokesman for the National Coffee
Association, a trade group based in New York. But an AFC
spokeswoman said the coffee will be among the same flavors sold in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a broad variety of roasts and blends to meet the
palates and tastes of the people of the Middle East,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   AFC also plans to continue to expand abroad. Remaining
international markets available include Asia, Korean, The
Netherlands, Japan, South Africa, the Caribbean and Singapore, the
company said. AFC said it hopes to develop company-owned stores in
the United Kingdom and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   AFC is the parent company of Church's Chicken, Popeyes Chicken &AMP;
Biscuits and Chesapeake Bagels, Bakery &AMP; Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
