<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-FLA-ALA-WATER18-CO     12-17 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-FLA-ALA-WATER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   No truce expected in 3-state water war
   By Charles Seabrook
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Plans to build two key reservoirs in Georgia may be
delayed for at least a year as Georgia, Florida and Alabama
governors are expected today to extend the deadline for reaching a
settlement in the interstate water war.
</P>
<P>
   The governors, meeting in Montgomery, are expected to push the
deadline back to Dec. 31, 1999. Under two interstate water compacts
adopted by Congress last year, the three states were supposed to
develop by the end of this year allocation formulas to share the
waters of two river basins: the Apalachichola-Chattahoochee-Flint
(ACF) basin, and the Alabama-Coosa-Tallapoosa (ACT) basin. The
headwaters of both basins are in Georgia. The ACF's waters are
shared by all the three states; Alabama and Georgia share the
waters of the ACT basin.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators appointed by the governors are attempting to produce
a regional water-use plan that would guarantee each state a
specific amount of water from the rivers. At stake for Georgia is
enough water to sustain growth in metro Atlanta and most of North
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for those guarantees of enough water for growth
during the next 30 to 50 years, Georgians may have to pay higher
electricticty rates as hydropower production is reduced. Strict
limits on water for irrigation may be imposed on southwest Georgia
farmers. In metro Atlanta, permanent restrictions on outdoor
watering and other stern conservation measures may be put in place.
</P>
<P>
   With the three states still in wide disagreement over the terms
of the settlement, there is little chance the water-sharing
formulas will be agreed on by the date set by Congress. The
governors of the three states have the authority to extend the
deadine.
</P>
<P>
   If the governors don't agree to push back the deadlines, the
compacts, under terms set by Congress, will dissolve and the
decade-old water war will be thrown into the Supreme Court for
settlement. If that happens, the states could face a bitter,
protracted legal battle and no state may get what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how and when the water war is settled, Alabama
officials are demanding that plans for building a 3,500-acre
reservoir on the Tallapoosa River in west Georgia and a 476-acre
reservoir on the Flint in Pike County be put on hold until a
water-sharing formula is reached. Until then, say the officials,
none of the states knows for sure what its share will be. Also in
possible jeopardy are plans to add 1 billion gallon storage
capacity to Douglas County's reservoir on the Dog River.
</P>
<P>
   Alabamians are fearful that Georgia will stockpile water
upstream that Alabama needs for growth downstream if Georgia
proceeds with the dam-building before a water formula is worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Gov. Zell Miller, however, has put Alabama and Florida
on notice that Georgia will not put all of its development plans on
hold until a water-sharing agreement is devised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia cannot place its entire future on hold,'' Miller told
negotiators for the three states in October. ``It must, as a part
of its own sovereign responsibility, move forward with its own
water development and its own internal solutions that protect its
muncipal, industrial, agricultural and environmental interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia officials say a ``live and let-live'' clause in the
interstate water compacts would allow them to proceed with plans
for the reservoirs absent a water-sharing plan.
</P>
<P>
   A squabble over the reservoir proposals may add more strife to
the already contentious water war negotiations among the three
states, and could even wreck the process, officials say. In
particular, says Walter Stevenson, chief of Alabama's Office of
Water Resources, ``the State of Georgia will be in violation of the
spirit, if not the letter, of the (ACF) compact'' if plans for the
Pike County reservoir proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency also has serious
concerns. ``EPA finds this project could have significant impact on
the current negotiations'' to settle the interstate water squabble,
said John Hankinson, the agency's regional adminsitrator in
Atlanta, in another letter to the corps.
</P>
<P>
   While the lake would be in Pike County, it is being pushed by
city of Griffin and Spalding County officials, who say the
reservoir is vital for fueling growth in their area and satisfying
ever-increasing demands for water. While population growth in
Spalding, which now has 55,000 residents, has been slow but steady,
officials there believe the county is poised for an explosion in
new large scale subdivisions because of changes in zoning
ordinances. ``This reservoir is a top priority for us,'' says
Rodney McCord, the mayor of Griffin, Spalding's county seat.
</P>
<P>
   In west Georgia, a similar battle may be shaping up. The West
Georgia Regional Water Authority, which serves Haralson, Paulding
and Carroll counties, has been been trying to build the 3,500-acre
reservoir on the Tallapoosa for more than a decade. ``We've waited
long enough,'' says Haralson commissioner Amos Sparks. ``We need
this reservoir, and we need to get it built.''
</P>
<P>
   The reservoir would provide drinking water, recreation and flood
control.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama officials, however, are vehemently opposed to the
reservoir until the water war is settled. In fact, the announcement
of plans in 1990 to build the reservoir in Haralson only a few
miles from the Alabama line helped trigger the water war. A
memorandum of agreement signed in 1992 by the governors of the
three states put plans to build the lake on hold until the states
could agree on a solution to their interstate water woes. The
governors' agreement also will expire on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   West Georgia officials have remained frustrated. When they
announced a year ago that they would seek a permit to build the
reservoir despite the lack of a water war settlement, it was enough
to bring more than 10 busloads of Alabamians to a hearing in
Buchanan, Ga., to protest the plan. The Georgia officials withdrew
their proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Amos and other west Georgia officials say they once again
will apply for state and federal permits in January to build the
reservoir. They contend that the 1992 memorandum of agreement that
delayed the project expires at the end of the year, and they are
not bound by the interstate water compacts that Congress passed
last year.
</P>
<P>
   State officials acknowledge that they are confused whether the
plans for the project can proceed while the water war negotiations
are still in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something we're going to be talking about in the next
few days,'' says Bob Kerr, Georgia's chief neogotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
