</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-GINGRICH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Gingrich cautions Clinton critics, backs military action
   By Mark Sherman
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich on Thursday cautioned critics
of President Clinton's decision to attack Iraq that ``there is no
alternative'' to U.S. leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In what was probably the final floor speech of his 20-year
career in the House, Gingrich took issue with fellow Republicans
who have accused Clinton of ordering military strikes to divert
attention from pending impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker said congressional leaders had been consulted on an
ongoing basis. ``There were conversations of substance,'' Gingrich
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the first speaker in a two-hour debate about a congressional
resolution of support for U.S. armed forces, Gingrich sounded
familiar themes about the projection of U.S. power and the nation's
ability to separate political squabbles from national security
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must carry the burden of leading the world,'' Gingrich
said. ``It does not suspend for elections. It does not suspend for
Christmas. It does not suspend under any circumstances. The U.S.
has to lead. There is no alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   He made only oblique references to impeachment proceedings,
which the House delayed Wednesday because of the air attacks on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. can both govern itself and lead the world
simultaneously,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his five-minute talk, the speaker said, ``No
matter the temporary arguments or temporary issues ... no one on
the planet should doubt the will of the American people to support
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   At several points during the year, Gingrich has expressed
similar sentiments when the U.S. has been on the brink of using
military force or in the aftermath of military action.
</P>
<P>
   But the speaker also called on Clinton to articulate a plan to
bring about Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a parallel to the appeasement of Adolf Hitler in the
1930s, Gingrich said that the nation would one day regret its
reluctance to get rid of Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, Gingrich said, ``He'll get weapons of mass
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said the president also should bring Congress proposals
to increase the defense and intelligence budgets when he delivers
the State of the Union address in January. ``We cannot lead the
world on the cheap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich made no mention of his imminent departure from
Congress, or the fact that he will no longer be a member of the
House when Clinton addresses a joint session of Congress on Jan.
19.
</P>
<P>
   He opened Thursday's session as presiding officer, again
probably for the final time. He left the chamber soon after making
his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the speech as he headed to an intelligence briefing,
Gingrich said: ``It was an easy speech. It was from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
