<HEADER>
A5680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-BOMBING-1218-COX     12-17 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-BOMBING-1218-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   BOMBING WILL HELP BUT NOT END PROBLEMS WITH SADDAM
   With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
   EDs: Optional add begins at 500 words.
   With US-IRAQ-1218.
   By BOB DART  
   c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration said Thursday that air
strikes had reduced the ability of Iraq to attack its neighbors but
conceded that bombings probably could not accomplish the greater
goals of removing Saddam Hussein from power and eliminating his
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is,'' vowed Defense Secretary William Cohen,
``we're going to continue to contain him.''
</P>
<P>
   However, while bombing can contain Saddam, such attacks also
complicate longer range strategies, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the air strikes could end any hopes of diplomatic
disarmament where Saddam would comply with inspections by the
United Nations Special Commission or UNSCOM. And the bombing could
actually strengthen his domestic standing as the beleaguered Iraqi
populace unites against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategically, it is doubtful that bombing would get rid of
Saddam Hussein or make him comply with UNSCOM. In fact, it could
end UNSCOM's role,'' said Simona Sharoni, a professor of peace and
conflict resolution at American University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The UNSCOM process is dead,'' agreed Scott Ridder, a former UN
arms inspector in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Several days of bombing is ``a campaign with no end games,''
Ridder said on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show. ``We've tried to crack this
wall of protection Saddam has built around himself for years now
and failed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Thursday morning attacks, the warships in the Persian
Gulf fired more than 200 Tomahawk cruise missiles, and Navy EA-6B
attack planes struck Iraqi air defense radars, Pentagon officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are 24,100 U.S. troops, 22 warships, 210 aircraft and the
aircraft carrier U.S.S. Enterprise in the Gulf off the coast of
southern Iraq. The forces are bolstered with 15 B-52 heavy bombers.
</P>
<P>
   In a Pentagon briefing Thursday, Cohen admitted that air strikes
can meet only limited objectives. But he said those objectives are
being achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is not to destabilize (Saddam's) regime,'' he said.
``The goal is to decrease and diminish his capacity to threaten his
neighbors and to either deliver weapons of mass destruction and,
hopefully, be able to hit some of the facilities that would put him
in a position to be making them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said UN inspectors had reported that Saddam Hussein had
``effectively emasculated UNSCOM'' anyway and ``they were on the
ground but not able to do their job.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the bombing pushes Saddam to oust the inspectors
completely, Iraq would be able to resume its programs to build
biological, chemical or even nuclear weapons. Those developments,
of course, would likely compel the United States to bomb again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be my hope that -- following this operation -- that
Saddam Hussein would see the wisdom of finally complying by
allowing UNSCOM to return and do its job,'' said Cohen. ``Failing
that, we intend to maintain our forces'' and ``to continue the
containment strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And should he either threaten his neighbors or try to
reconstitute his weapons-of-mass-destruction program, we are
prepared to take action again,'' Cohen warned.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Bombing is also unlikely to either kill Saddam -- who is
relatively safe in underground bunkers -- or to inspire an
insurrection against him. Some analysts said that the Iraqi
dictator may even be empowered by Americans bombing during Ramadan,
the Islamic holy month that begins on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Iraqis welcome bombing at this point,'' said
William Arkin, an MSNBC military analyst. He explained that the
attacks not only enhance Saddam's hold on power, but also drive a
wedge between the United States and Britain, who are conducting the
mission, and other U.N. countries who don't support it.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate briefing, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said the bombing is only a limited solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The short-term goal at the moment through this military
campaign is to degrade his ability to develop and deploy his
weapons of mass destruction,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   It will take more than air strikes to meet the longer range
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A medium-term goal is in fact to have him comply with the
Security Council resolutions,'' Albright added. ``Longer term, we
have come to the determination that the Iraqi people would benefit
if they had a government that really represented them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so we know that this is something that cannot be done
overnight, and we are working with the various opposition groups on
a longer range way of trying to help them help themselves to have a
regime that represents them,'' She said.
</P>
<P>
   And that would take more than even smart bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
