<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   No mass deployment to Persian Gulf underway
   By Jack Warner
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Specialized units from Georgia bases, including the
Air Force's only all-weather airborne ground target tracker, are
being ordered to the Persian Gulf, but so far there has been no
mass deployment of troops.
</P>
<P>
   The only deployments ordered as a result of the new attacks on
Iraq involve Air Force personnel from Robins Air Force Base in
Middle Georgia and Moody Air Force Base near Valdosta, and military
intelligence personnel from Fort Gordon near Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Stewart at Hinesville, which supplied key troops for Desert
Storm, is deploying 1,500 soldiers from the 3rd Infantry Division
this week, but their departure for Kuwait was a rotation placed on
the calendar a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Public Affairs Sgt. David Schad said the departing troops were
originally intended to replace 1,500 3rd Division personnel due to
return home. Schad said there had been no word on whether those
troops would return as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant deployment from Georgia involved
150 members of the 93rd Air Control Wing from Robins. They will be
taking big E8-C jets from which they operate the JSTARS, or Joint
Surveillance Target Attack Radar System, which can locate and track
enemy ground units under any conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Banks, a civilian public affairs official at Robins, said
the 19th Air Refueling Group got its orders for Southwest Asia _
where the military locates the Persian Gulf _ on Wednesday. There
are already 165 personnel from Robins in the area, she said, 140
from the 5th Combat Communications Group and 15 from the 78th
Security Forces Squadron.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to carry on with what's going on here, even though
your thoughts and prayers are with those folks over there,'' said
Staff Sgt. Bob Pullen at Robins. ``This is a tough time of year for
people to deal with something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The 347th Fighter Wing based at Moody is deploying a combat
search-and-rescue unit consisting of three HH-60G helicopters,
three HC-130 aircraft and about 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   The only non-Air Force troops specially deployed from Georgia so
far are 20 members of the 513th Military Intelligence Brigade at
Fort Gordon near Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence unit left Wednesday. The 3rd Division
deployment will go on for about a week, Chad said, and other
departures will take place over the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   No troops had been alerted yet at Fort Benning, Georgia's other
large infantry installation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
