<SLUG> BC-TELEMARKETING-SCAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO ANNOUNCES STING OPERATION TO CATCH TELEPHONE SCAM ARTISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno warned telephone scam
artists Thursday that the person they are trying to bilk just might
be an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the Justice Department is 2 1/2 years into Operation
Double Barrel, a massive federal and state sting operation to catch
telemarketers who fraudulently promise people prizes or other
special items in return for a fee. The victims, mostly elderly, pay
by credit card, but the prizes never arrive.
</P>
<P>
   To stop this illegal activity, the FBI and 35 state attorneys
general have used police and elderly volunteers recruited by the
American Association of Retired Persons to field phone calls from
unsuspecting, dishonest telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1,000 people have been charged with violating federal or
state fraud laws and 150 have been convicted since Reno announced
the operation about 30 months ago, the Justice Department reported.
Those found guilty have been sentenced to up to 14 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time (dishonest) telemarketers pick up a phone they are
taking a risk,'' Reno said. The FBI will keep trying to ``con the
con artist'' in its effort to stop illegal telemarketing, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Double Barrel is the latest and broadest of three
Justice Department efforts since 1990 to catch illegal
telemarketers. The current effort relies most heavily on state and
private-sector involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people have been victimized by this crime,'' said
Georgia Attorney General Thurbert Baker, who joined Reno in
announcing the operation. ``We're going to be very aggressive in
prosecuting these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   The first federal effort to catch illegal telemarketers was
Operation Disconnect during George Bush's presidency. The
three-year FBI operation resulted in the conviction of 402 people
and the recovery of $7 million in ill-gotten gains.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in Operation Senior Sentinel, the FBI first used private
citizens in its effort to uncover telemarketing fraud. AARP helped
the FBI recruit the volunteers, and the operation led to the
conviction of 598 people between 1993 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The legitimate telemarketing industry employs more than 3.4
million people and enjoys revenues of more than $500 billion
annually. Meanwhile, telephone scams cost the public $40 billion
per year, the Justice Department reported.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, consumers must be cautious when they receive
unsolicited calls from people making enticing, seemingly
inexpensive offers. ``If it sounds too good to be true, it probably
is,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Dishonest telemarketers usually target the elderly and use
brazen tactics to trap their victims, Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   In one scam, telemarketers call people who have already been
victimized and, posing as law enforcement agents, offer to recover
the lost money in return for an up-front payment, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who calls you, tells you they're from the FBI and asks
you to pay a fee so they can get your money back is lying,'' Reno
said. ``No federal law enforcement agency will ever charge fraud
victims a dime when they try to get money back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
