<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-FAITH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Parishoners find `Peace on Earth' elusive during crisis,
Christmastime
   By Gayle White
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ During a cosmic convergence of religious celebrations,
Atlanta clergy and their congregations are attempting to sort out
the meaning of the U.S. bombing of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Coming as Jews celebrate Hanukkah, Muslims prepare for Ramadan
and Christians are in the midst of pre-Christmas activities, the
bombing ``does not speak of peace on Earth, good will to men'' said
the Rev. Gerald Harris, pastor of Eastside Baptist Church in
Marietta and president of the Georgia Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe we have a responsibility to protect national
security, and I believe we have responsibility to other nations of
the world to protect them from weapons capable of mass
destruction,'' he said. ``But I must say the timing of this if not
ill advised is suspicious at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he applauds the heroism and response to the call to
service of the military people who are involved in the exercise. As
for President Clinton, ``Even though he is in a personal crisis, I
feel like we're partly to blame because of our failure to pray for
him,'' Harris said. ``Prayerlessness is a sin as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Steven Lebow of Temple Kol Emeth in suburban Atlanta says
he'll probably mention what's happening in the Mideast during
sabbath services on Saturday
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of servicemen in our congregation and our
number one need right now is to support our servicemen,'' he said,
adding that Iraq has been an ``aggressor'' and he certainly ``would
have to support containing Iraq . . . and the danger they pose in
that part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he adds, this is all coming at an inopportune time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, this is happening during a time of year when
all of us are thinking of 'peace on Earth' and how precious peace
is,'' he says. ``But peace doesn't come unless you're willing to
stand up to bullies, which is what Iraq is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Agnes Norfleet, pastor of North Decatur Presbyterian
Church, said as a Christian she also finds it ironic that ``when
we're awaiting the Prince of Peace, we've gone to war.''
</P>
<P>
   Her church will have a presentation of Handel's ``Messiah'' on
Sunday, but Norfleet said she will deal with the crisis in Iraq
during prayers.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Eve, she plans to incorporate a personal story
about rounding a corner in Wiesbaden, Germany, at Christmastime
while studying abroad. Suddenly, she heard familiar Christmas
carols coming from an American military brass band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I was away from my family, that made me feel at
home,'' she said. ``We will remember our troops especially this
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, she is also thinking about ``those Iraqi children
Saddam has used as pawns in his reign of terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Episcopal Bishop Frank K. Allan said he always has concerns when
the United States resorts to military action. ``The question I have
is what follows the bombing?'' he said, ``Do we bomb them and then
everything's back to normal? What does it accomplish? How many
civilian lives are lost and children killed?''
</P>
<P>
   Allan said the U.S. has a ``legal right'' to bomb Iraq, but he
has concerns about the moral justification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to be one who does not believe in the idea of
redemptive violence,'' he said. ``We say we do evil that good might
come, and in fact the good doesn't come. Rarely do you see good
coming out of the use of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Tim McDonald, president of Atlanta's Concerned Black
Clergy, said the Iraq bombing has put a damper on the holiday
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're striving to enter the Yuletide season and would not want
to be in this tense period in history,'' McDonald said. ``However,
based on what we have heard from those who were charged with the
investigation over there, it seems like we did not have any
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
