<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT SAYS SENATE MUST HOLD TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate majority leader Trent Lott dismissed
suggestions Thursday that a deal on censure could be reached to
prevent an impeachment trial, saying the Constitution requires that
a trial must begin if the House approves articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an effort to stop a Senate impeachment trial by
obtaining promises of acquittal from 34 Democrats has been dropped
because Senate rules require every senator to sit as a juror with
an open mind, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, may go ahead with plans to introduce a
motion to dismiss the articles of impeachment after the trial
begins. It would take 51 votes to dismiss the articles, meaning
that six Republicans would have to join the 45 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, in an interview on CNN, ruled out any possibility that a
deal might be made for a censure resolution before a trial begins.
That appeared to end discussion of a deal proposed by Lott's
predecessor, former Senate majority leader Bob Dole, that the House
and Senate pass a joint resolution censuring Clinton before Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will go to a trial and there won't be any deal-making,''
Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's comment came after Democrats put aside a separate idea
that they had hoped would lead to the cancellation of the Senate
trial. Some Democrats had suggested they could obtain signatures of
34 members who promised to acquit the president, which they hoped
would lead to the abandonment of a trial. It would take 34 votes
out of 100 to acquit the president.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea fizzled when senators realized they are required
under the rules of an impeachment trial to sit as a juror with an
open mind _ something that would be impossible if they had said
beforehand they planned to vote to acquit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter idea was floated, but it is dead,'' said Senator
John F. Kerry. ``I have got to reserve judgment until I review what
they have sent to the Senate,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kerry said he or another senator might make a motion to
dismiss the case shortly after the trial begins. But it is far from
clear whether Lott would agree to such a motion.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Christopher Dodd, a Connecticut Democrat, suggested that
Democrats still have options to avoid or adjourn a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Senate, by unanimous consent, we can do almost
anything,'' Dodd said, referring to a motion that requires approval
of all senators. ``I would anticipate that consideration would be
given to alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats came up with the idea of obtaining a letter promising
acquittal signed by 34 senators after studying the history of
Louisiana Governor Huey P. Long. Long was impeached in 1929 and
avoided conviction by obtaining the necessary promises of acquittal
from his backers in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark D. Preston of States News Service contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MARCH-BOS &LR;      12-17 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCHERS BRING `VOTE NO' MESSAGE TO CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Above the sea of signs reading ``Just Vote No,''
``Impeach Congress,'' and ``Judge Not,'' one stood out for its
attempt at levity in a capital roiled by bitter accusations and
dire predictions amid a bombing campaign and a vote to impeach the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Starr,'' it read, ``Your Mother Had Sex Too ... (Big
Mistake).''
</P>
<P>
   Holding up the sign was Maryland resident Jon Inskeep, one
several thousand East Coast residents who traveled here to voice
support for President Clinton Thursday on the back steps of the
Capitol Building under a dark sky threatening a cold morning rain.
</P>
<P>
   The rally, organized by the Rev. Jesse Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH
coalition and promoted by the internet site, moveon.org, was
addressed by members of Congress, labor, feminist and religious
leaders angrily condemning a Republican Congress they said was bent
on damaging their man, overturning their votes, and subverting
their will.
</P>
<P>
   As the bombs rained down on Iraq and House members fought over
the wording of a resolution supporting American troops, the
speakers asked members of Congress to exercise compassion in
dealing with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the invocation prayer was Rabbi Donna Berman, chaplain
of Mt. Holyoke College, who said, to a crowd roaring ``Yes'' at the
end of each sentence, ``Law without mercy leads to cruelty and
injustice. To ignore the will of the people is to dismantle
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson in his prayer emphasized hope and healing at a time
when, he said, the lives of American men and women were on the
line, the presidency imperiled, and the votes and voices of average
people ignored:
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's dark but the morning cometh,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Jackson said, has ``done wrong,'' and ``fallen short of
the glory of God.'' But, he added, a reprimand, not impeachment,
was a fit punishment that would not divide the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``A scab was developing over the wound and we thought it was
healing,'' said Jackson. ``Now Hyde and the Republican majority has
taken the scab off and there is blood everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Rev. Al Sharpton of New York also reflected the
sentiment expressed on a sign that read: ``Forgiveness can cross
party lines,'' and echoed Jackson's comments on punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't take a sledge hammer to kill a cockroach,'' he
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   And although the majority of attendees were African American,
there were people of all races and ages present.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year-old Carrie Chafin of Crofton, Md., said she
received permission from her teachers to miss school. She came, she
said, because, ``I like nothing less than hypocrites, which is what
Clinton's opponents are.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the age spectrum were two New Yorkers in
their seventies dressed in black coats, black handbags, black
glasses and black hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're incensed,'' said Florence Aron, who drove down with her
friend Martha Friedman, a psychotherapist. ``This is a farce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a political coup d'etat,'' interrupted Friedman. ``I
don't know one single person who wants impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   There were strong racial overtones in many of the speeches,
highlighting the sense already expressed by some members of the
Black Congressional Caucus that Republicans don't hate Clinton,
they hate ``us,'' and ``they hate what he is doing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lowery, a 51-year-old African-American Republican who
grew up in the South, said the Judiciary Committee reminded her of
the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself lying awake at night feeling that hatred, the
kind that blacks felt in the old days from the KKK just because
they were black,'' said Lowery, a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Ed Markey, Democrat of Massachusetts, was one of
only a few white members of Congress to address the crowd. It was,
he said in an interview before speaking, part of his continuing
effort to rouse the public in support of the president and the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, the Republicans came to Congress saying they wanted a
contract with America,'' he said. ``In 1999, they want a contract
to shut down the executive branch, the Supreme Court and the White
House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
