<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDS OUTRAGE RUSSIA, BUT FEW CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ What if the world's second-most powerful nuclear nation
screamed and shook and threatened reprisals _ and nobody cared?
</P>
<P>
   Angered over air attacks against Iraq by the United States and
Britain, Russia's quarreling leaders responded Thursday with a
united condemnation of America of a kind not heard here since the
Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   From the Kremlin to breakaway Chechnya, Russian leaders
denounced the United States as a rogue superpower and demanded that
Washington halt the strikes or face unspecified ``serious
consequences.'' Thursday night Russia recalled its ambassador to
Washington in protest.
</P>
<P>
   But the fierce barrage of criticism could not overshadow two
larger realities that are hard for Moscow to accept. The attack
against Iraq served as a humiliating setback to Russia's efforts to
end the crisis by diplomatic means. The other is that cash-strapped
Russia is too weak to mount any viable response beyond rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of that in Moscow Thursday, and in a rare
departure from Russia's post-Soviet politics, it came in a united
front from all ends of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``These activities constitute international terrorism,'' the
State Duma, the usually divisive lower house of Parliament,
declared in a resolution. The house voted 394-1 after it learned
that one of its members had been wounded in the bombing. It also
paused for a moment of silence to honor the Iraqi victims of the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomahawk missiles are the best method for bringing Russian
politicians together,'' commented NTV television.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yevgeny M. Primakov, who in his past role as
foreign minister helped avert US-led military strikes against Iraq,
said it was ``outrageous'' that the current attacks circumvented
the United Nations Security Council. President Boris N. Yeltsin
said the strikes ``crudely violated'' the United Nations charter.
Television showed the two men in the Kremlin with military leaders,
poring over maps of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin was especially angry that President Clinton, who in the
past has consulted with the Russian leader on such things, did not
notify Moscow that the strikes were under way. The Kremlin said
Yeltsin, who found out from French President Jacques Chirac, saw
``no need to call Clinton at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreshadowing possible tension with the Western military
alliance, Yeltsin recalled his defense minister from a planned
meeting with NATO leaders in Brussels. Yeltsin also made a point of
issuing a message to Russia's Strategic Rocket Forces, saying they
and the 7,000 nuclear warheads at their disposal give the country
the status of a ``great nuclear power.''
</P>
<P>
   But the United States has made it clear it does not see Russia's
military power as a deterrent to punishing Iraq for failing to
comply with United Nations resolutions on destroying its weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been trying to lift UN sanctions against Iraq, not
just because it wants to collect Baghdad's $7 billion Soviet-era
debt. To halt the crisis would have reasserted Moscow's role as a
major world player, which has become increasingly difficult after
the 1991 fall of the Soviet Union. Instead, Russian officials were
left to claim a moral victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia has become the clear leader of all sensible forces in
the world which favor the rule of law,'' Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov told the Duma.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russians observed that Moscow had to accept a lesser role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing Russia can do now is to try to act out a role
it cannot play,'' the influential Russian financier Boris
Berezovsky told the Interfax news agency. ``That would only
humiliate Russia more. We can be a great and powerful state only
when we learn to solve our own problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov agreed, saying that Russia's
hands were tied by its economic crisis, which has forced the
government to seek urgent loans from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, a Russian delegation was on its way to London to
seek restructuring of billions of dollars in overdue loans to
private Western creditors that Moscow has no hope of paying back
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma heard calls to increase Russia's defense budget, but
that would wreck any chance of an IMF loan. Angry Communist leaders
vowed the Duma would never ratify the 1993 Start-2 treaty reducing
nuclear weapons in Russia and the United States. But that, too, is
probably more harmful to Russia. Yeltsin's own government has been
arguing that the treaty made financial sense for Russia, which
cannot cope with the cost of maintaining its Soviet-era arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most sinister and credible threat Thursday came from
Chechnya, the Muslim Caucasus republic where last week four
hostages, three Britons and a New Zealander, were found beheaded
after a failed raid to free them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reserve the right to launch a no-less-significant strike
against the interests of the USA and Great Britain in the Caucasus
region, in Russia, and in the Middle East,'' Chechen President
Aslan Maskhadov said in a statement. ``Chechnya will start
preparations for a series of specific actions, directed against the
USA and Great Britain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
