   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Netherlands' Prince Claus
started something when he recently had a bad neck day and ripped
off his tie, throwing it at the feet of his wife Queen Beatrix. But
this fashion rebellion won't get very far in Washington, where the
brass insists on jacket and tie for all serious business. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ELWAY (Undated) _ They came into the league together in 1983
as the young guns, and they will undoubtedly will both leave as
first-ballot Hall of Famers. Yet Dan Marino and John Elway have met
only twice during their storied NFL careers. They will face each
other a third time Monday in a battle between the Denver Broncos
and Miami Dolphins. By JOHN McCLAIN and ALAN TRUEX.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBN-MARINO
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ It was just five years ago that the
Houston Rockets were not only the talk of the town but also of the
entire NBA. A look back at their stirring 15-0 streak and
subsequent 22-1 start that ignited the Rockets to the first of
their two NBA Championships. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-EAGLES (Undated) _ A look at the downfall of the
Philadelphia Eagles over the past four years, going from a solid
playoff contender to one of the NFL's worst teams. By JODY
GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Like Richard Nixon a quarter
century ago, Bill Clinton is not going to give up the power and
perquisites of the presidency without a struggle. But if the
``comeback kid'' is to save his presidency, he is going to have to
give the performance of a lifetime when the 106th Congress convenes
in January. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
