<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-BUTLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUTLER GIVEN PROTECTION AMID FLURRY OF ALLEGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Two days after Richard Butler gave the United
States a green light for military force in Iraq, the chief UN
weapons inspectors has himself come under fire.
</P>
<P>
   Russia Thursday called for the Australian diplomat's
resignation. China called him ``dishonorable.'' UN Secretary
General Kofi Annan's closest aides say they believe that Butler
intentionally sought to provoke a confrontation with Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The political threat to his future was matched by a more
physical danger. Concerned about a personal attack, the United
Nations placed Butler under protective guard with five bodyguards,
two marked police cars and a bulletproof vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to allegations that he was acting on behalf of the
United States, Butler defended a highly critical report of
Baghdad's efforts to block UN inspections of its chemical and
biological weapons program. He said the report, which President
Clinton cited as the justification for the air war, was based
strictly on the experiences of UN Special Commission arms
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It danced to no one's tune,'' Butler said. ``It was not
written to anyone's purposes, including as some of you have
suggested for the purposes of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Thursday that Butler
had presented a distorted version of Iraq's cooperation with the
United Nations. Russia contends that Baghdad's overall record of
cooperation with the United Nations has been good _ more than 300
inspections with only five incidents. And he called for the
replacement of Butler and the re-establishment of the UN team not
dominated by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   China also made it clear that it would like to see Butler go.
</P>
<P>
   And other Security Council members privately suggested that a
future UNSCOM would be more effective without Butler at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand their concerns,'' he said. ``I would prefer they
understand better my concern, which is to enable us to . . . which
is to have Iraq cooperate to enable us to do our job.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would quit, Butler told a group of reporters
Thursday: ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration insisted that the problem is Saddam
Hussein's evasions not Butler's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooting the messenger is not the way to go about this,'' said
US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright. ``He is an outstanding
individual and he deserves the support of the international
community.''
</P>
<P>
   UNSCOM officials say that they have been dealt a raw deal by the
Council. They say that Butler has been maligned for simply carrying
out the council's own mandate _ the destruction of Iraq's nuclear,
chemical, and biological weapons. And they say that Iraq has
consistently sought to prevent them from carrying out their
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that we haven't made some mistakes in
presentation,'' said Charles Duelfer. ``But we have a divided
council, and when you have a boss with multiple personalities it
makes working for them very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler's blunt public diplomacy has poisoned his relationship
with the cautious UN Secretary General Kofi Annan. In recent weeks,
Annan has repeatedly cited Butler's lack of diplomacy, what he
calls ``megaphone diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   UN sources say the UN chief has been irritated by what he views
as Butler's provocative approach to the inspections and by his
refusal to consult with him and with other key council members on
significant issues, including his decision to withdraw the UN
inspectors hours before an American strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butler's objective over the past several weeks appeared to be
not so much continuing inspections but collecting compelling
evidence of Iraqi noncompliance, which is what the Americans
wanted,'' the source said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
