<HEADER>
A5730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBES-REACT18-COX     12-17 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBES-REACT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Globes like `Truman,' `Shakespeare'
   By Steve Murray
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's been a good morning,'' actress Lynn Redgrave says from
her Los Angeles home Thursday, shortly after learning she'd gotten
a Golden Globe nomination for her supporting role as the frumpy
housekeeper in ``Gods and Monsters,'' the story of ``Frankenstein''
director James Whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect it,'' she says. ``Of course, you get these
hopeful moments, but you know, there are so many people for them to
choose from.''
</P>
<P>
   Notable mainly for its lack of big surprises, the list of
nominees include a couple of films and performances from earlier
this year that could have been forgotten in the traditional
December glut of trophy-seeking releases. To that extent, the
nominations are less about ``Saving Private Ryan'' than about
resurrecting ``Truman.'' An early June release, ``The Truman
Show,'' starring Jim Carrey as an unwitting TV star, earned six
slots on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the more recent movies weren't overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Dec. 25 in Atlanta, ``Shakespeare in Love,'' in which
Gwyneth Paltrow plays muse to Joseph Fiennes' bard, tied ``Truman''
with six nominations. ``Gods and Monsters,'' which opens here today
and whose star, Ian McKellen, has been already dubbed best actor by
several national critics groups, got three nods: picture, actor and
supporting actress.
</P>
<P>
   Checking out the nominees, IMAGE Film and Video Center's
executive director Anne Hubbell found few surprises, except Todd
Solondz's screenplay citation for ``Happiness,'' the controversial
indie fave that features pedophilia as one of its themes. ``That
was one of my favorite films of 1998,'' she says. ``I hope this
acknowledgment increases his chances for the Oscar.''
</P>
<P>
   So who votes on the Golden Globes, and why do we care?
</P>
<P>
   Good questions. The awards are bestowed by the 92 members of the
Hollywood Foreign Press Association, an amorphous membership
ranging from full-time writers to people who once upon a time did
report on the entertainment industry. So while the Academy Awards
are chosen by members of the industry (directors, writers, actors,
etc.), the Globes are chosen by a bunch of ink-stained outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a tinge of tawdriness to the setup, the Golden Globes
are seen as a fairly accurate predictor for the choices academy
voters will make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose it's looked on as a sort of beacon,'' Redgrave says.
``It makes people notice things, and then it seems to mold choices
for other awards.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's no big surprise that Globe nominees often turn up
on Oscar's list. After all, the Globes divide films into two
categories: drama and comedy/musical. That means they nominate 10
or more movies, not just five, and the acting slots are also
doubled.
</P>
<P>
   So sure, last year's best picture nominees included the
academy's choices. But the Foreign Press also nominated ``The
Boxer,'' ``Amistad,'' ``Men in Black,'' ``Wag the Dog'' and ``My
Best Friend's Wedding,'' none of which were Oscar's big favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, if you watch a lot of movies, you could list 10 of your
own favorites of '98 and probably predict the Oscars. There aren't
that many great flicks per annum.
</P>
<P>
   The nominated films are a good mix of studio titles (Robert
Redford's ``The Horse Whisperer'') and smaller, independent works
(``Elizabeth,'' based on the life of England's ``Virgin Queen'').
While the nominee list doesn't include any left-field surprises, it
has its peculiarities. One is the nomination of Carrey for
``Truman.'' Sure, it was an OK performance, but didn't approach the
skill of Tom Hanks' transition, years ago, from comedy to drama.
Another oddity: the complete snub of the highly anticipated
Terrence Malick-directed war film ``The Thin Red Line,'' due here
in January.
</P>
<P>
   And it's hard not to suspect that Sharon Stone got a supporting
actress nod for her role in ``The Mighty'' because the Foreign
Press members really, really want to meet her.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of the acclaimed Italian film about the Holocaust,
``Life Is Beautiful,'' looks like a gross oversight, but there's a
reason. According to the Foreign Press rules, it was ineligible,
having been released in Italy in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy,'' one the flicks nominated for best picture, is a
low-profile British comedy that only the voters seem to have seen.
(It opened last Friday in Los Angeles and is slated for a limited
run elsewhere in January, though Atlanta is not a confirmed city
for distribution.)
</P>
<P>
   To find out who wins or loses, you'll have to wait for the
Golden Globes ceremony Jan. 24. On Feb. 9, the Academy Award
nominees will be announced.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Redgrave has a big issue to ponder. What will
she wear?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' she says with a laugh. ``Everybody seems to
borrow a frock these days. Maybe I'll borrow a frock.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
