<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-ATTACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIFFERENCE SETS IN AS MISSILES EXPLODE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD - As night descended and more punishing missile attacks
approached Thursday, this city shrugged its shoulders with weary
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   The streaking red tracers and the wailing sirens that erupted
moments before incoming missiles were barely noticed at the Al
Meeland Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   A young, bow-tied waiter reflexively opened the door so the air
pressure from the impending blast would not shatter the windows.
Then he quickly returned to serve lamb kebabs.
</P>
<P>
   As he stepped from the door, what was reported to be a
1,000-pound cruise missile slammed into a seven-story government
building several blocks away, in the heart of Baghdad. Thick black
smoke poured from its windows. Then a second missile plunged down
the middle of the building, igniting a plume of fire that engulfed
the structure.
</P>
<P>
   The blast shook the restaurant. Diners casually looked out the
window at the damage and the acrid smoke that filled the sky.
Standing on the street outside, a chef named Ali Al Dahab, said,
``We've gotten used to it. Nothing new. We just hope it finishes
soon. Sometimes we feel scared for our families.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dahab said he did not expect to get the night off: ``I'll go
on working. If I go home or stay here it is still the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi leadership was not so complacent.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference, Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed
Al-Sahhaf issued a blistering attack on President Clinton's
rationale for the bombing, dismissing it as ``cheap lies to deceive
the world for a pretext to carry out an agression.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahhaf maintained that Iraq has acted in good faith. He claimed
that since the Nov. 17 resumption of United Nations weapons
inspections, eight inspection teams had carried out 427 inspections
at as many sites. He listed all of the targets attacked Thursday
night and claimed that each of them had been either inspected or
placed under the surveillance of monitoring cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The total damage from Wednesday night and Thursday morning
attacks was difficult to assess. Foreign reporters, permitted to
travel around the city only with a government ``minder,'' were
given only limited access.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi radio reported that President Saddam Hussein visited some
of the targeted areas, including the house of his daughter, Hala.
The house of the youngest of her three daughters was demolished,
but she was reported safe.
</P>
<P>
   Another missile reportedly fell in an area near one of Saddam's
sprawling presidential palaces in Baghdad. Still another attack was
reported to have caused damage in the area of al-Adil, where a vast
military camp and a series of radio relay stations are located.
</P>
<P>
   Angry Iraqis seem acutely aware of the term ``wag the dog.'' On
one street a group of young Iraqi men, when asked why they thought
the US was bombing, replied with ``Ms. Monica'' in a thick Arabic
accent.
</P>
<P>
   Sahhaf also referred to the perjury allegations and sex scandal
that has left Clinton facing possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desperate liars can commit dirty crimes. We are the victims of
crime in Washington. There's no crisis in Iraq. There's a crisis of
corrupt politicians in Washington trying to divert attention from
their dirty life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us see their crimes tonight,'' he added, at the end of the
press conference, as warning sirens began to wail for an impending
attack.
</P>
<P>
   There was a perverse quality to the night of bombing. One
military analyst on CNN referred to ``the beauty of B52 bombers,''
while the air strikes occurred amid a complacency that bordered on
nihilism.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the evening, a shopping boulevard called Karada was
crowded with Iraqi families. Young couples and mothers pushing baby
strollers sauntered past a 20-foot-wide and four-foot deep crater
left by an American cruise missile the night before. None seemed in
a hurry to get home before nightfall and the promise of more
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting that's all. We endure. We lasted through 41
days of bombing in 1991, so two or three days of this is not bad,''
said Abdel Karem.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Kader, dressed in blue pajamas, looked up at the sky as
his father spoke.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old postal worker sat with his five year-old son on
his knee. They had come to watch a bulldozer grind away at the
crater in an attempt to repair a water main that had been ruptured
during the attack, leaving more than 20 percent of Baghdad's 6
million people without water. The bright yellow bulldozer, Karem
said, kept his son's mind off the idea of another night of
thundering attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thursday night my daughter asked me, `What is it?' when the
bombs started,'' said Kader, describing how his three children
cowered in fear and cried next to him in bed as the missiles rained
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her it was America. She asked me `Why does America do
this to us?' And I told her it is because they have hatred for the
Iraqi people... There is no factory, no presidential palace, no
weapons site here. There are only people. So why do you bomb us?''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he was sitting in the street if he knew the
attacks were coming, he replied, ``Where am I to go?''
</P>
<P>
   Around him, couples shopped in sparsely stocked stores, some of
which had windows blown out. Young boys climbed through the rubble
of a three-story house demolished by the missiles that landed on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   People seemed indifferent to the fact that American battleships
and aircraft carriers were poised in the Persian Gulf to unleash a
second night of pounding Cruise and Tomahawk missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is wedding night in Baghdad. And like any other
Thursday, there was the sound of wedding parades across the city.
Led by drummers and trumpeters, wedding parties marched along side
brides in cream-white gowns and grooms in neatly pressed suits.
</P>
<P>
   At the Al Mansour Hotel, a 31-year-old groom named Saad Atiyah,
sat beside his new bride as the first warning sirens of the evening
began to sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've grown used to it,'' he said, of the impending bombing.
``We're not going to let it interfere with our night.''
</P>
<P>
   Another wedding couple celebrating at the hotel had a similarly
defiant tone that captured the child-like loyalty among many Iraqis
to their president.
</P>
<P>
   If the US intends to destabilize the regime through this
bombing, discussions with Iraqis Thursday suggested it would have
precisely the opposite effect. The more the US targets Saddam, the
more he paints himself as the embattled defender of the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bravery comes from the bravery of our leader, Saddam,''
said Entivar Jamil, 21, in a sequined wedding dress. ``He stands
with us through this American agression.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
