<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   In Alford, there's no great urge to make anything `run'
   By Celestine Sibley
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you live in Alford, Fla., you could probably get along fine
without a car. My mother lived there for 38 years and managed.
</P>
<P>
   But my son loves his wheels and is bereft when they don't turn.
Recently, he had call to make a trip _ 13 miles away to the county
seat _ and the engine turned over and ran, but the wheels did not.
I followed the car vicissitudes with daily telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be all right,'' he assured me. ``I have
ordered a part somebody told me it needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later he told me the part had come, costing a good bit
more than the $50 price his friend had quoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you install it yourself?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was trying, but it was complicated. He had spent some
time studying the vitals of his car and trying to figure where the
new part would fit in. If he has a book to go by, he will tackle
any job by following directions. Unfortunately, no directions came
with the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you ask your friend who suggested the part to show
you how to install it?'' I asked
</P>
<P>
   He was shocked. ``Oh, I couldn't do that! I wouldn't want to
impose on him. He used to be a good mechanic, but he has progressed
beyond that now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has?'' I can't conceive of getting beyond being a good
mechanic. Everybody needs that kind of skill from time to time, and
it must be very comforting to know that you can fix anything in
time of breakdown. ``What does he do now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he's the city engineer,'' he said. ``Has a nice home _
brick. ''
</P>
<P>
   Was it up to my mother's standard of excellence and taste? ``Oh,
she married well,'' she would say of a neighbor. ``She has a nice
brick home with hardwood floors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he have hardwood floors?'' I asked of the now-affluent
ex-mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I've never visited him at home. But
I see him at the City Hall. You know, the city engineer.''
</P>
<P>
   We-ell! I took a deep breath. It did sound affluent until I
remembered the size of the city _ perhaps a dozen blocks where
streets with names such as Park Avenue have residents who still
plow mules. Total population is 500 souls, if you count environs. I
mulled over the problem for long long-distance minutes, and then I
said, ``What does the city engineer do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he drives the garbage truck,'' my son said airily.
</P>
<P>
   You can see there's no way of asking a man of such eminence to
come down off that high seat in the big truck and give expert
counsel on the subject of the nonmoving car and the new part.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the car sits there under the big live oak tree going
nowhere. It's not urgent so far. If anybody gets sick, the nearest
doctor is 12 or 15 miles. But otherwise, everything is in walking
distance _ the grocery store, the City Hall, even the barbershop.
If I had not entertained notions of having my son and his wife
drive to Atlanta for the holidays, I wouldn't keep calling down
there and asking, ``How's your car? Running yet?''
</P>
<P>
   My son is philosophical. He figures in all good time he will
dope out the place for that part and mayhap get it installed. If
not, he won't fret unless some disaster involving travel strikes.
It's a good country town attitude. People who live there will never
jam expressways with their cars, making life hazardous for
themselves and other people. They will pick up a book, and take a
rocking chair on the porch, and possess themselves with patience
until life takes a more urgent turn.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
