<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-CLARICOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLES BUYING CLARICOM HOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Staples-Charge)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The same mid-sized business that buys paper clips and legal pads
is also in need of such telecommunications services as voice
messaging and video conferencing, and that may largely explain why
office-supply giant Staples Inc. said Thursday it plans to buy
Claricom Holdings Inc. for $140 million.
</P>
<P>
   As Staples sees it, Staples and Claricom, a Connecticut
telecommunications firm, offer different services and supplies to
the same customer _ businesses with 10 employees or more.
</P>
<P>
   By combining forces, Staples now believes it can offer a broader
range of products and services to those core customers and provide
them with one-stop shopping, something that none of its big
office-supply rivals can do at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Staples, we can sell you a two-line phone,'' said Staples
chairman and chief executive Thomas G. Stemberg, adding, ``but we
don't sell phone systems.''
</P>
<P>
   And phone systems, as well as Internet services, are something
the Staples business customer is clamoring for, he said. With the
Claricom acquisition, Staples would have the capacity to provide
such services and products at low prices.
</P>
<P>
   To further target those Internet services, the company Thursday
said it would establish its newly launched World Wide Web business,
Staples.com, as a separate business unit under Jeff Levitan, who
had been the company's senior vice president for strategic
planning.
</P>
<P>
   The site has ``come out of the box so strongly'' that Staples
plans to nearly double its investment in electronic commerce to
about $23 million next year, Stemberg said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to plans to acquire Claricom, which counts Bain
Capital Inc. of Boston as one of its owners, the Westborough-based
chain of roughly 900 office-supply superstores said it would take a
$57 million charge to move 58 ``outdated stores,'' mostly in the
Northeast and California, to larger sites near their current
locations.
</P>
<P>
   From Wall Street's standpoint, the proposed acquisition of
Claricom elicited the most comment.
</P>
<P>
   At Salomon Smith Barney, analyst James Stoeffel sees Staples and
Office Depot Inc. as rapidly pulling away from the office-supply
competition and in need of new worlds to conquer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next trend in this industry is, `How do we expand our
market share?' '' and the Claricom acquisition offers Staples a
vehicle to do that by offering ``new products and value-added
services to its core customer base,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Claricom acquisition may provide Staples with a ``major
growth opportunity,'' agreed A.G. Edwards analyst Donald T.
Spindel. With telecommunications, Staples can set itself apart from
Office Depot and OfficeMax Inc., the player that seems to be
falling behind in the office-supply superstore industry.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Office Depot nor OfficeMax can now offer such an array
of telecommunications products, Spindel said. So customers have a
big reason to choose Staples over the other two.
</P>
<P>
   It had been rumored that Staples might acquire Corporate Express
Inc., a Colorado office-supply company.
</P>
<P>
   But why buy a struggling firm in an industry in which Staples is
already one of the giants? said Stoeffel, who added, ``you could
get it cheap but then you'd still have to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Stemberg, Staples was mulling over strategic
opportunities when it decided to check out fast-growing
telecommunications companies. Claricom, he said, was one of the few
independent companies with a national network.
</P>
<P>
   ``And guess who owned it? A guy sitting on our board of
directors,'' Stemberg said, referring to Mitt Romney, a managing
director of Bain Capital, an early Staples investor.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Bain, Claricom is also partly owned by its senior
management team and by Triumph Capital, an investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   On the e-commerce front, Stoeffel thinks there are big
opportunities for Staples and Office Depot. Many products, such as
paper and pens, are not ones an office manager needs to see before
he or she is willing to place an order.
</P>
<P>
   And both Staples and Office Depot already have efficient
delivery systems to get these products to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street seemed to shrug off the $57 million fourth-quarter
charge Staples plans to take to close old stores, the first charge
Staples has taken in five years.
</P>
<P>
   On Nasdaq, shares reached an all-time high of 41 7/8 Thursday
before closing at 39 13/16, up 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Staples seems to be rolling along. Earlier this week, it
formally opened its new headquarters, and last month, it reported
third-quarter earnings had jumped 33 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
