u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-PALESTINIANS-HNS &LR;      12-17 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-PALESTINIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS WHO CHEERED FOR CLINTON NOW BURN U.S. FLAGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ Yards from a banner welcoming President
Clinton to town, Palestinians angry about U.S. strikes against Iraq
burned the American flags they had waved just days earlier to greet
the president on his first visit here.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, meanwhile, opened gas mask distribution centers and
deployed Patriot anti-missile batteries in the Negev Desert,
central Israel and Haifa in the north as precautionary measures,
but downplayed the chance of attack by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are preparing for every eventuality,'' Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu told Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   In Bethlehem, about 500 teen-agers and their teachers marched to
protest the bombing, lobbing rocks at Israeli soldiers and filling
the brisk winter air with smoke from burning U.S. flags. Two
protesters were slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
   Similar protests took place near Ramallah, Nablus and Hebron as
Palestinians vented anger at a U.S. president who had impressed
many here with talk of peacemaking during his first visit to
Palestinian-ruled territory earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to make peace, to be a man of peace,'' said Ehab
Hawari, a 16-year-old Palestinian student who joined in the
demonstrations. ``So if he wants peace, why is he making war with
Iraq?''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian President Yasser Arafat, who sided with Saddam
Hussein during the 1991 Persian Gulf War, has since refrained from
comment on the repeated crises with the Iraqi leader over United
Nations inspections.
</P>
<P>
   But one of his senior negotiators spoke out, calling on the
United States and Britain to stop the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We demand an immediate end of the attacks against Iraq,'' said
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erakat. ``We believe only through
peaceful means that problems can be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   With each mini-crisis with Iraq, Palestinians have responded
with fewer demonstrations, in part because the Palestinian
government, which doesn't want to jeopardize growing ties with the
United States, has prevented public protests. But most still
sympathize with the suffering Iraqi people, even if they don't
support Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is hitting Iraqi children. They are bombing
families,'' said Nadir Shweiky, a Palestinian restaurant owner in
Bethlehem. ``If they want to do something, why don't they do it
against Saddam?''
</P>
<P>
   This time, with so many U.S. flags handy, the demonstrations
were larger than before. But they were still small in comparison to
demonstrations in support of Palestinian prisoners locked in
Israeli jails, an emotional issue that easily brings thousands out
into the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinians credited Clinton for the low turnout. ``When
Clinton came here, he made a good impression, he was like one of
us,'' said Shweiky. ``We felt he was respecting our people, but we
don't like what he's doing in Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   But many said they didn't expect the bombing to last long,
particularly with the onset of the Muslim holiday of Ramadan on
Saturday and Christmas next week. Few believe Saddam will strike
Israel. And the repetitiveness of the crisis has blunted the sense
of urgency here.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, 65 gas mask distribution centers opened across the
country, but most were empty most of the time. Streets were filled
with lights for the Jewish holiday of Hanukkah and Israelis went
about their day as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli intelligence officers said that despite Saddam's
denials, Iraq still possesses a few missile launchers, several
dozen missiles and chemical warfare capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   But they predicted there was little chance Saddam would repeat
the missile strikes of 1991, when the Iraqi leader launched 39
Scuds at Israel, except as an act of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is on the brink of extinction, he certainly may take
suicidal steps involving the launching of a few missiles against
Israel,'' said Gen. Amos Gilad, head of research in Israel's
military intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Israel is better prepared this time to deal with an
Iraqi missile attack than it was in 1991. Patriot missiles then
provided by the United States proved ineffectual against the Iraqi
Scuds.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said he first learned that a strike against Iraq was
imminent from Clinton during his trip to Israel and the Palestinian
Authority and stressed that his country was not part of the
confrontation with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel is outside the dispute,'' Netanyahu said, but added
that Israel would prepare for the worst, just in case Saddam
attacked. ``Who knows what is going on in that man's brain?'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
