<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENDER MOMENT FOR SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ First things first. Before the Red Sox make plans for a
run at the 1999 American League East pennant, they will set the
stage friday by sending contracts to the eligible players they wish
to retain from the 1998 club.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of Sunday's deadline, they will formally tender
contracts to players without multiyear deals. Players who don't get
such offers by Sunday become free agents, but that's highly
unlikely in Boston's case.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean new life for veterans like Darren Bragg, Damon
Buford, Midre Cummings, John Wasdin, Scott Hatteberg, and Ron
Mahay, all of whom have value on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   During the recent winter meetings at Nashville, general manager
Dan Duquette indicated that the Red Sox would likely keep all their
key players from last season and that there would be no surprises.
But given Boston's poor record on the free agent market, Duquette
will no doubt be scanning the lists of castoffs from other clubs
for a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Boston took a major hit in free agency, losing slugger Mo Vaughn
to Anaheim. In addition, five pitchers who at some point worked for
the Sox last season are gone. Pete Schourek became the latest,
signing Thursday with the Pittsburgh Pirates for $4 million over
two years. Schourek, 29, went 8-9 in 25 games with Houston and
Boston in 1998 and became part of Red Sox lore when he was selected
over ace Pedro Martinez to start the do-or-die fourth game of the
American League Division Series against the Cleveland Indians.
Schourek pitched superbly but got a no-decision as the Sox were
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say the lefthander can earn up to $5.3 million on his
new contract if he reaches incentives based on appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, the Sox lost lefthander Greg Swindell, who signed
with the Arizona Diamondbacks for $5.7 million over three years.
They did not offer arbitration to Steve Avery, who wound up with
the Cincinnati Reds (one year, $1.5 million), and Butch Henry, who
has agreed to terms with the Seattle Mariners, pending a physical
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also gone are retired reliever Dennis Eckersley and infielders
Tim Naehring and Mark Lemke, and pitcher Robinson Checo was
designated for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox signed two free agents for 1999, second baseman Jose
Offerman (four years, $26 million) from the Kansas City Royals and
pitcher Mark Portugal (one year, $3 million) with the Pittsburgh
Pirates. Rumors persist that Boston has an interest in the Chicago
White Sox' Frank Thomas. But White Sox general manager Ron Schueler
continues to tell sources the two teams don't have a match. Owner
Jerry Reinsdorf acknowledged in a Chicago television interview that
Thomas might be available, but the offer from any club seeking his
services would have to be ``overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette is still checking out possible free agents. Club
spokesman Kevin Shea confirmed Thursday that free agent first
baseman John Jaha, a Milwaukee Brewers last season, underwent a
day-long examination at the University of Massachusetts Medical
Center in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   (Material from Associated Press was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
