<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-SCENE-1STLEDE-12/18 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   AMIDST FALLING MISSILES, MOST IRAQIS SAY 'LIFE GOES ON'
   EDS: Restores dropped word in lede; corrects spelling of Tigris
in 11th graf; other minor editing throughout.
   With US-IRAQ-1218.
   By LARRY KAPLOW
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ When the first blast thudded against the windows of
this kabob restaurant at about 10 p.m. Thursday, a young bow-tied
waiter ran to open the front door _ just what Iraqis recommend to
protect a building against shockwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Diners at the Al Meelad (it means ``The Birthday'') walked out
to view a fireworks show of anti-aircraft fire and a plume of smoke
from a nearby high-rise. But they soon returned to their meals, and
the waiter hurried back to serve them.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight night, U.S. missiles and Iraqi
anti-aircraft batteries periodically lit up the sky above this
battered capital. But Iraqis, in a mixture of defiance and
helplessness, kept to their routines. They took walks with their
families and celebrated weddings.
</P>
<P>
   During the first visible exchange of fire Thursday, a cook came
out from behind his counter to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become very normal to us,'' said Ali Al Dhahab, a
26-year-old who stood on the sidewalk in his yellow paper hat and
fry-cook uniform. ``We wish it would end soon. Sometimes we feel
afraid for our families.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he would work several more hours anyway. ``Whether I go
home or stay here, it's the same thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1 a.m., the firing was still sporadic, though air raid sirens
wailed frequently. This would be another sleepless night for the 5
million residents of Baghdad, but it was unclear if the barrage
would be as bad as the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic moment had been a strike on what were said to
be offices of Iraq's military industries. A direct hit sent a ball
of flame shooting from the top of the downtown building. Somehow,
the electricity stayed on. But the blast blew out several ground
floor windows of the Al Rashid Hotel a few hundred yards away, home
to most of the foreign journalists in town.
</P>
<P>
   The quick air strikes were followed by excruciatingly long
periods of quiet. And the evening was filled with incongruous
images of war and peace.
</P>
<P>
   The city is flat and dotted with palm trees, somewhat
reminiscent of coastal South Florida but with scores of billboards
and murals glorifying Iraqi President Saddam Hussein. It could be a
pretty city, but eight years of crippling economic sanctions have
left its buildings and cars run down. And anti-aircraft guns can
occasionally be seen on rooftops or trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night there were fewer cars than usual on the wide
avenues, where diners ate seafood at restaurants along the banks of
the Tigris River, or bellied up to counters for ice cream, the
favorite Iraqi treat.
</P>
<P>
   People carried on with an almost eerie disinterest in the
explosive events around them. When asked to explain, they cited the
bloody 1980-1988 war against Iran and the 45-day assault in the
1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Iraqis have faced U.S. air strikes in September 1996
and twice in 1993. They have also endured several threatening U.S.
military build-ups aimed at containing the weapons-making ability
of their renegade leader. Iraqis tell their stories with a mix of
resignation and defiance _ a sort of you-can't-scare-me-anymore
tone.
</P>
<P>
   Even as more air strikes were expected, people stopped to gaze
at a four-foot-deep, 10-yard-wide crater in a road in a busy
shopping district, the result of a missile that landed the night
before.
</P>
<P>
   The blast cut a major water line, disrupting service to more
than 2 million residents, according to Faris Alasam,
director-general of the city water department.
</P>
<P>
   An earth mover worked in the dark to fill the hole while about
50 people looked on from the muddied street. Iraqi Health Minister
Omed Medhat Mubarak said as a many as 30 people were killed, and 75
injured from the two rounds of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Postal worker Abdul Kareem said his six-year-old daughter, Asra,
woke up when the missile landed nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked, 'Why does the United States attack us,' `` said the
40-year-old father, ``I told her that they hate us.''
</P>
<P>
   But while hate was the subject on this street corner, it was
love that was in the air in the posh Mansour Hotel, where couples
arrived in suits and bridal gowns for wedding celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   One couple, in particular, said their separate men's and women's
parties Wednesday night, traditional in Muslim weddings, were
played out to the noise of missile explosions. But, they were not
about to reschedule their nuptials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are happy tonight, and we hope that all the Iraqi youth
will marry and challenge the United States,'' said 29-year-old
groom Ahyee Khazal.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
