<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AS USUAL FOR EMBATTLED PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He stands where no American president has been
before _ on the field of battle and the precipice of impeachment.
Yet, Thursday President Clinton hardly seemed to notice.
</P>
<P>
   As with many of his days, there were phone calls and meetings
about matters of state, capped off by a black-tie gala at the White
House that featured no shortage of celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   While impeachment and Iraq converged on the White House for the
second day in a row, Clinton left one to his aides while he spent
his energy working on the other.
</P>
<P>
   As first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, aides, and supporters
began working the phones in a last-ditch effort to argue his case
against impeachment, Clinton focused on doing his job rather than
trying to keep it.
</P>
<P>
   Though the White House had suspended its efforts against
impeachment for 24 hours after the United States and Britian began
bombing Iraq Wednesday, the battle was renewed Thursday. Aides
seemed in no mood to give up, even if the boss had all but done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take the view of the great philosopher Yogi Berra, it's not
over till it's over,'' said White House press secretary Joseph
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, according to his aides and advisers, has resigned
himself to accepting whatever decision the House renders on
impeachment this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   They described the president as stoic, even philosophical, about
the possibility of impeachment. And sensing there is little he can
do personally to get Republicans to vote with him, he has turned
his focus to, among other matters, carrying out the bombing against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Clinton met with his national security team to get an
assessment on the damage in Iraq, and made a series of phone calls
to foreign and congressional leaders to update them.
</P>
<P>
   He later met with his economic advisers to work out details of
the 1999 federal budget. Then Thursday night he and Mrs. Clinton
hosted a black-tie gala honoring the Special Olympics' 30th
anniversary under a stadium-sized, heated pavilion on the South
Lawn with guests that were to include Whoopi Goldberg, Tracy
Chapman and Eric Clapton.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the over 30 years that I've know him, there is nobody that
I know better able to compartmentalize issues and problems than
Bill Clinton,'' said Lanny Davis, former White House special
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can totally focus his mind and his energy on one problem
even though swirling around him are five other problems that need
his attention,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Lockhart ticked off the big issues that
Clinton has had to confront this week: the looming impeachment
vote, the missile strike against Iraq, peace negotiations in the
Middle East. The president returned late Tuesday after a four-day
trip to that region to find many Republicans in Congress whom he
had counted on to vote against impeachment saying they now planned
to vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an understatement to say the president has been
tested over the last week,'' Lockhart said. ``What you can see and
what he's demonstrated is he's up to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to bomb Iraq has been second-guessed by his
critics, and Thursday the president defended the timing of the
decision, coming as it did on the eve of the originally scheduled
House impeachment vote, which had been set for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meeting in the Oval Office Thursday morning with Vice
President Al Gore and other top security advisers, denied that the
bombing was a diversionary tactic to delay the vote, as some of his
critics have claimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any serious person would believe that any
president would do such a thing,'' said a weary-looking Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   To believe that, he said, would require accepting complicity on
the part of Defense Secretary William Cohen and the chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, General H. Huge Shelton, and his other
national security advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe any reasonably astute person in Washington
would believe that,'' he said. ``This was the right thing for the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, Clinton's former aide, vouched for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absurdity of the charge strikes those of us who are
supporting President Clinton as simply further proof of the
mean-spiritedness and partisanship of this process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that Clinton, contrary to some reports, was not
consumed with being impeached. ``Some of us would like him to be
more consumed,'' he said. ``He is more philosophical and more
concerned about his own personal healing and closure and family
isses than he is about his presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a presidential scholar at the Brookings
Institution, said impeachment was a problem of Clinton's own making
that he cannot now control, unlike the situation with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Clinton's resiliency under pressure that makes it hard
to count him out, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real counterpuncher and he does come off the matt,''
Hess said. ``But every time he seems to be up and doing well, he
slips.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I fully expect he will limp across the finish
line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
