<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS VOICE SKEPTICISM AND PATRIOTISM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Mich., Calif., Ga., Texas, S.C., N.Y., Tenn., Mass.)  (See also IRAQ-IMPEACH-RDP, IRAQ-MILITARY, IRAQ-GOALS, IRAQ-TIMING,
IRAQ-POLL, IRAQ-CLINTON, IRAQ-GINGRICH, IRAQ-GORE, IRAQ-ISRAEL,
IRAQ-EUROPE, IRAQ-BRITAIN, IRAQ-ARABS, IRAQ-SOUTH, IRAQ-SOLDIERS,
IRAQ-RUSSIA, IMPEACH-IRAQ-REPUBS, IMPEACH-IRAQ-LOTT.) 
(lb) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans walked a fine line Thursday
between saluting the patriotism and sacrifice of U.S. troops and
voicing their distrust of President Clinton's Iraq policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question _ Democrat, Republican, liberal, moderate,
conservative stands in unequivocal support of our troops in the
Persian Gulf,'' said Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., who heads the House
Intelligence Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The House overwhelmingly voiced official support for the troops
in combat, but the Republicans argued that the Clinton
administration's air offensive against Iraq did not go far enough
and should include the ouster of President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Goss said, ``I implore the administration not to be satisfied
with the interim result of containment, but rather to work toward
dismantling Saddam Hussein's destructive regime; otherwise we will
be doing this again.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, Congress approved a bill that Clinton signed,
providing up to $97 million in military aid for opposition groups
supporting Saddam's removal. But Republican leaders have criticized
the Pentagon and State Department for not disbursing the money fast
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution of support for the troops was approved, 417-5.
Three Democrats voted against the measure: John Conyers Jr. of
Michigan, Barbara Lee of California and Cynthia McKinney of
Georgia. Two Republicans opposed it, Ron Paul of Texas and Mark
Sanford of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers had different reasons for voting no. Sanford, for
example, said there were ``too many red flags around the timing of
this vote.''
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of the U.S.-led air strikes, the Senate
majority leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, contended he was merely
questioning why the president had not bombed Iraq sooner, when he
said on Wednesday that he doubted the official assurance that
``there is no connection with the impeachment process'' and the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Livingston of Louisiana, the speaker-designate,
opened nearly four hours of floor debate on the Iraq resolution
Thursday by calling on the man he replaced, Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has to lead,'' said Gingrich, adding that
administration officials fully consulted him and Livingston before
the strikes. ``There is no other country capable of organizing
against an Iraqi dictator who wants to get weapons of mass
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans voiced support for the bombing, arguing that
it was essential to punish Iraq for violating U.N. resolutions and
for trying to take advantage of the domestic uproar over
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not permit Saddam Hussein to defy the U.N. Security
Council,'' said Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., chairman of the House
International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But other House Republicans criticized the aerial bombardment as
insufficient to topple Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that our military action against Iraq attacks
only the symptoms of the problem rather than the problem itself,''
said Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., who heads the House National
Security Committee. ``The root cause of our problem with Iraq is
Saddam Hussein.''
</P>
<P>
   And even as Clinton's national security advisers briefed
senators on the Iraq operation, many Republicans still harbored
doubts about the timing. ``The fact that there is skepticism about
the timing of these attacks reminds us that America should always
have a president whose motives are unassailable,'' said Sen. Fred
Thompson, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Democrats lobbed counterattacks against the
president's critics.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., said: ``To my colleagues who have
questioned the president's motive in the midst of this crisis, I
say shame on you. Shame on you for playing into the hands of
Saddam, who clearly staged his latest act of defiance to coincide
with the impeachment process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
