<HEADLINE>
MARKET GIVES EVENTS A `BEEN THERE, DONE THAT' SHRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When economically tiny Russia defaulted on its
foreign debt last August, world financial markets came close to
collapse. But now that economically gigantic America is bombing
Iraq and apparently about to impeach President Clinton, markets are
rallying. What gives?
</P>
<P>
   Asked that question Thursday, investment professionals conceded
that the placid response of financial markets to the recent
upheavals is puzzling. Most traced it to a combination of investor
weariness after a year of sharp ups and downs, and to a conviction
that, absent unexpected catacylsm, events in Washington and Baghdad
no longer matter as much to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Markets react to things they've never seen before,'' said Greg
A. Smith, chief investment strategist for Prudential Securities in
New York. ``But we've had a Gulf War, we've had an impeachment,''
Richard Nixon's, said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been there, done that,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, behind Wall Street's complacency are signs of deep
confusion, especially about impeachment, a confusion that some
analysts warn could be dangerous if investors suddenly decide that
the possibility of President Clinton's departure from office
matters after all.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it appears that Wall Street is not paying much
attention to the unfolding drama in Washington, D.C. For example,
one chief strategist for a major investment house said she thought
the House would be allowed to vote on a censure resolution against
Clinton though House leaders are adamant they will permit no such
vote. Another investment professional seemed thunderstruck by the
idea that a Senate trial of the president could set off such an
outcry that Clinton could no longer govern and might be forced to
step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're no different than anybody else. Denial runs deep on this
impeachment issue,'' said Stephen S. Roach, chief economist for
Morgan Stanley, Dean Witter in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in for a very tough reality check'' if the House
actually votes to impeach the president in the next few days, Roach
added. ``The markets are neither prepared nor priced for an
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, Wall Street and Washington are always out of
sync. What one considers historic, the other often treats as
trivial. But in the natural course of things, one would have
expected stock prices to fall in recent days because of uncertainty
over Clinton. And one would have thought that the price of
commodities like oil would rise because of worries a US attack on
Iraq could reduce supply.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, the opposite has happened.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 85.22 points, or 1
percent, Thursday, to close at 8875.82. The broader Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index went up 18.02 points, or an even greater 1.6
percent, to close at 1179.96. And perhaps most surprising, oil
prices fell 11 percent to some of their lowest levels in a dozen
years.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some markets have behaved as expected. The US
dollar, for example, slid in trading Thursday against the German
mark and the Japanese yen as foreign investors grew increasingly
concerned about what a Clinton impeachment might mean for the value
of their holdings. And the stock market is off almost 5 percent
from its record highs of three weeks ago, a decline some analysts
said is partially attributable to growing nervousness about
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors' reaction so far has been drastically different
than the last time they confronted war and impeachment. In 1974,
for example, the Dow tumbled almost 20 percent between late July
and the days immediately following Nixon's resignation in August.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said there were several reasons behind the market's
blase attitude toward the impeachment and Iraq crises:
</P>
<P>
   --Clinton's impeachment and Iraq's intransigence are only some
of the issues with which the market has been trying to deal, and
recent news from others areas has been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been particularly worried that the economy is
slowing and corporate profits, which had been growing steadily, are
stalling. But recent statistics suggest that far from slowing, the
economy is still barreling along. And a string of companies have
said recently they will make even more than they were predicted to
make this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   --Clinton doesn't oversee the nation's economic policy. Federal
Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
do. So the president's departure would not make that much
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton adminstration's economic policies are of trivial
consequence and have been for years,'' said Mickey D. Levy, chief
economist of BankAmerica Corp. ``If Clinton were to disappear, the
markets might sigh. If Greenspan were to stub his toe, the markets
would go ballistic,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   --After a wild year like the one just finishing, money managers
have arranged their portfolios to lock in their gains and have
little interest in making changes.
</P>
<P>
   --Investors are so exhausted from the year's wild ride that they
simply are not paying attention. But they will have to shortly.
``We weren't prepared for the Asian crisis. We weren't prepared for
Russia. And we're not prepared for an impeachment,'' said Roach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
