<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-IRAQ-1218-COX     12-17 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-1218-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   U.S., BRITAIN LAUNCHES SECOND WAVE OF AIR STRIKES AGAINST IRAQ
   With IRAQ-SCENE-1218, IRAQ-RUSSIA-1218, IRAQ-BRITAIN-1218,
IRAQ-BOMBING-1218, IRAQ-RAMADAN-1218-1STLD, IRAQ-WORLD-1218.
   By BOB DEANS 
   c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. and British missiles tore at the heart of
Iraq's military and intelligence operations Thursday, pounding to
rubble more than 50 sites as the strikes rolled toward a third day
early Friday with no sign of let up.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi officials condemned the attacks, with Foreign Minister
Mohammed Said Al-Sahhaf lashing out at ''corrupt politicians,'' in
London and Washington he accused of using ''cheap lies,'' in order
''to have the pretext to commit aggression against Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   With Iraqi defense systems, airfields, military barracks and
communications systems in the crosshairs, U.S. warships, fighter
jets and giant B-52 bombers launched scores of cruise missiles deep
into Iraq as an operation the Pentagon has dubbed ''Desert Fox,''
continued.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the possibility that the attacks could continue through
the weekend, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said Thursday
that he does not regard the beginning of the Islamic holy month of
Ramadan -- expected to begin on Saturday night -- as a deadline for
halting strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will take whatever time is necessary to carry out the
operation,'' Cohen told reporters at a Pentagon briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal is to complete it as soon as we can without
restricting the military operation,'' Cohen said. ''But we're
sensitive to the Ramadan period and that's all I care to say about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In early signs of success, U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman
Gen. Hugh Shelton showed reporters at the briefing military
pictures of two key Baghdad sites -- a military intelligence
headquarters building and barracks for units of Iraq's elite
Republican Guard -- reduced to smoke and ash by multiple cruise
missile hits early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing left but rubble,'' Shelton told reporters, as
they looked on at a shot of what had been military intelligence
headquarters in Baghdad. Thursday's attack began about 11 a.m. EST
and lasted nearly twice as long as Wednesday's six-hour strike.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton showed shots of the Republican Guard barracks in a
similar state, saying that ''four of the five barracks (targeted)
were destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere around the country, Shelton said, attacks were ''as
successful or more successful than this was, some of it not quite
as successful.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no U.S. or British casualties reported as of 9 p.m.
EST Thursday night, according National Security Advisor Samuel E.
``Sandy'' Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that the Republican Guard units and the agents who
worked at the military intelligence unit in Baghdad were central to
Iraq's efforts to spy on and obstruct the work of United Nations
weapons inspectors in Iraq. The inspectors have been working there
to try to identify and dismantle Iraq's alleged chemical and
biological weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on air defenses were designed to make it safer for
piloted aircraft to strike deeper into Iraq in attacks that are
expected to continue Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Some 51 combat aircraft from the United States, including F-117
Stealth fighters and F-15 fighters, were ordered to the gulf
Wednesday, along with a Navy carrier and 5,600 Army soldiers from
Georgia, Texas and New York. They will join the 24,000 troops
already in the region and are expected to arrive this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But Iraq's Al-Sahhaf said the United States was unjustifiably
targeting sites that United Nations weapons inspectors had been
allowed to visit.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference, he noted several that he said had been
hit. He said that some had cameras in place that monitored the
developments of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are examples to show what cheap liars the leaders of the
British and American regimes are,'' Al-Sahhaf said. ``They think
they can get away with their crimes by deception.''
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, there were lines at some gas stations Thursday as
residents stocked up on fuel in apparent anticipation of more air
strikes. But for the most part, there was a sense of normalcy in
the capital city of 5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi Health Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak said the two nights of
bombings had killed as many as 30 people and injured 75 others.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to obtain independent damage assessments.
Foreign reporters are not permitted to roam the city without
government escorts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, President Clinton told reporters he had no regrets
about launching the attacks -- criticized by some of his political
opponents as being timed to somehow interfere with a looming
impeachment vote in the U.S. House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am convinced the decision I made to order this military
action, though difficult, was absolutely the right thing to do,''
Clinton said in remarks before a White House meeting with his
national security team to discuss the ongoing strikes Thursday
morning. ''It is in our interest and in the interest of people all
around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   With the House set to open debate on four articles of
impeachment against him on Friday, and a vote set for Saturday,
Clinton said the proceedings would have no impact on Desert Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to complete this mission,'' Clinton said. ''And
the Republican leadership have to decide how to do their job.
That's not for me to comment on.''
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. and British forces pressed the attacks, world reaction
to them was deeply divided.
</P>
<P>
   Most NATO members generally backed the attacks, as did U.S.
Pacific allies Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin denounced the attacks, however,
warning that they could shatter regional stability. China and
France also called for immediate end to the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Arab world, Iran, which fought a 10-year war against Iraq
in the 1980s, denounced the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Palestinians in Israeli-occupied West Bank
territories and Gaza protested the strikes, burning American flags
that, in Gaza at least, were waved in support of Clinton only
Monday, when he journeyed there to lend the aura of American
legitimacy to the cause of Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   As Iraqi officials began alleging that the strikes were killing
civilians, Cohen reiterated that the mission had been planned to
reduce such casualties, though he did not rule out further such
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are targeting military or militarily-related targets,
period,'' said Cohen. ''We are not attacking the people of Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox Middle East correspondent Larry Kaplow in Baghdad
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
