u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.S.-EMBASSIES-N     12-17 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-EMBASSIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CLOSES 38 EMBASSIES IN AFRICA AS A PRECAUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IRAQ-IMPEACH-RDP, IRAQ-MILITARY, IRAQ-GOALS, IRAQ-TIMING,
IRAQ-REACT, IRAQ-POLL, IRAQ-CLINTON, IRAQ-CABINET, IRAQ-GINGRICH,
IRAQ-GORE, IRAQ-ISRAEL, IRAQ-EUROPE, IRAQ-BRITAIN, IRAQ-ARABS,
IRAQ-SOUTH, IRAQ-SOLDIERS, IRAQ-RUSSIA, IMPEACH-IRAQ-REPUBS,
IMPEACH-IRAQ-LOTT.) (nk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States has closed 38 embassies in Africa
for at least two days to protect employees against possible
terrorist reprisals for the American air strikes on Iraq,
administration officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the administration
was taking the highly unusual step of closing so many embassies
``because we are concerned about general threats and the heightened
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials said that two of the largest and
busiest American embassies, in South Africa and Nigeria, remained
open.
</P>
<P>
   The embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, which were hit by terrorist
bombs in August, were among those closed Thursday. Administration
officials said the 38 embassies were closed, in part, to avoid a
repetition of such attacks, which killed more than 250 people and
injured more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Other embassies closed Thursday include those in Angola,
Ethiopia, Ghana, Kenya, Liberia, Mozambique, Namibia, Senegal,
Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Several State Department officials expressed doubts about
whether it was necessary to close so many embassies. But a
spokeswoman for the department said: ``This action was carefully
considered. A number of African posts have received threats in
recent weeks, and our caution is fully justified in the current
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials said that, as a precaution, they had
instructed dependents of American diplomats to leave the American
embassies in Israel and Kuwait and the consulate in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they were concerned that the dependents could
not be adequately protected if Iraq used chemical or biological
weapons in retaliation for the American air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   At the American embassy in Abidjan, Ivory Coast, a spokeswoman
said, ``We haven't received any specific threat, but it is better
to be on guard and take precautions instead of having regrets
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said Thursday that they had also ordered extra
security at government buildings here and at airports around the
United States. Additional police officers and guards were on duty
at the Capitol, and the General Services Administration said
security had been increased to a ``maximum state of alert'' at
federal buildings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
