<SLUG> BC-BYRD-GRAVE-VANDALISM18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   James Byrd's grave disturbed by vandals
   By Denise Gamino
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Vandals have disturbed the grave site of the
black man whose hideous dragging death behind a pickup inspired a
national outcry about racism in America.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-by-16-inch nameplate that adorned the grave of James Byrd
Jr. has been stolen from the Jasper city cemetery. The theft leaves
Byrd's grave unmarked and his family with more hurt to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' said Betty Boatner, one of Byrd's
sisters. ``Why take it? Why take it? Why take it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a hurting thing,'' she said. ``I just couldn't
understand why.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to show what people will do.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows when the stainless steel plaque, attached with two
screws, was stolen from Byrd's casket vault. His family believes it
has been missing for more than a month because Boatner saw the
nameplate Nov. 10, but another relative who visited the cemetery
the next day doesn't recall seeing it.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd was buried in the cemetery June 13, a week after he was
dragged by a pickup until he was beheaded. Three white men are
charged in the murder, which law officers call a racially motivated
hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it wasn't done in meanness or hatred toward the grave.
It was done as someone trying to take something as a symbol of what
happened,'' said Jasper's incoming police chief, Stanley
Christopher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think it's cool to have this, but in actuality
they're just a common thief,'' Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   The police department never received an official report about
the theft. Christopher said he did not learn of the missing
nameplate until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Boatner said she had planned to file a police report, but time
got away from her. ``With the hurt and with everything else, I just
didn't do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The family has arranged to replace the nameplate and to fasten
it permanently with cement or solder.
</P>
<P>
   Few people in Jasper are aware that Byrd's grave has been
disturbed. But Booker T. Hunter, founder and president of the
Jasper NAACP, said he was not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate. That's what it is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flora Bartee, whose husband was a pallbearer at Byrd's funeral,
said no one should feel a need to take Byrd's nameplate for a
memento of the horrific murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to go stealing that off the grave to remember
that,'' she said. ``You're going to remember it for the rest of
your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
