<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Though Most Gurus Are Upbeat, Some Say Stocks on Skaky Ground       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The awkward confluence of war and impeachment could easily make an
already choppy stock market even more erratic, but efforts to expel
President Clinton are not expected to trigger a market collapse or
economic recession.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom on Wall Street is that investors
consider impeachment by the House of Representatives a foregone
conclusion, and they have already factored that into what they pay
for stocks. The Dow Jones industrial average closed yesterday at
8,875.82, up about 1 percent for the day. The impeachment effect
already was ``baked'' into the Dow after it tumbled for five days
in a row beginning December 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock markets hate uncertainty, (but) you can assume that a
lot of the uncertainty surrounding President Clinton has already
been discounted in the market,'' said Paul Siegel, president of
Hollis Capital Management, a San Francisco private investment
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   For now, House Republican leaders have briefly delayed an
impeachment vote while the United States and Britain launched their
military strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1990 Persian Gulf War did trigger a significant
economic recession and stock sell-off, most financial pros don't
expect the markets nor economy to get seriously wounded by any
military conflict this time. For the most part, the current
domestic economy is far more sound than it was then.
</P>
<P>
   More important, though, the assault on Iraq now further delays
impeachment action by the House, which in turn creates more angst
for the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   What is driving Wall Street crazy is that there will not be a
quick resolution to President Clinton's status. Investors are less
concerned about whether the president remains in office or whether
he is ousted. What they would like to see, and it is precisely what
they probably won't see, is a rapid end to the saga that has
crippled the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, investors are saddled with the unpalatable likelihood
of having an already lame duck president being rendered totally
ineffective for the duration of protracted Senate hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the market cares if Bill Clinton is in the White
House or if Al Gore is in the White House, but if you tie up the
Senate with an impeachment trial then you tie the hands of
government,'' says portfolio manager James Carroll of Loomis,
Sayles &AMP; Co., a Bloomfield Hills, Mich., investment firm with $75
billion under management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern, then, is that the whole country gets distracted
and the economic slowdown continues,'' Carroll says.
</P>
<P>
   And while institutional investors, for the most part, don't
envision that Senate hearings would cause financial markets to
crater, they do expect a trial would add more volatility and
churning to the roller-coaster market.
</P>
<P>
   Once the House of Representatives conducts its vote and the
Senate embarks on impeachment hearings as anticipated, financial
markets are likely to experience sharp, short-term swings driven by
dramatic developments in the Senate testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see some ups and downs, but it will be very
short-term stuff,'' says investment adviser Bob Bingham, a
principal of Bingham, Osborn &AMP; Scarborough LLC in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that an impeachment trial should be construed
as a positive influence on financial markets. During the
impeachment process, investors ''may well get whipsawed as the
ultimate resolution swings in the balance,'' says PaineWebber Chief
Strategist Edward Kerschner in a research note.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, over the long haul, financial markets should be able to
weather a Senate trial as long as there are no new crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to a Clinton scandal and the stock market, one
has to ask, 'What else is new?''' Kerschner asks.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has been living with Clinton scandals for
several years, and it is up more than 150 percent since 1995,
Kerschner points out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ultimately, it's the performance of the economy that
matters, and most financial pros do not expect either the Iraq
attack or a Clinton impeachment will have a direct effect on the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   While impeachment hearings normally would hurt the value of the
dollar, war usually bolsters the greenback because the world views
the United States as a safe haven. Thus, one of the things that
might ordinarily suffer from impeachment _ foreign investment in
the dollar _ likely will be a wash. Consequently, the current
strengths of the U.S. economy _ low inflation, a federal budget
surplus and low interest rates _ are expected to prevail over
political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think an impeachment trial would have no discernable impact
on the economy'' as long as Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin remain in their current jobs,
says Harry Smith, a principal and chief strategist of Harris
Bretall Sullivan &AMP; Smith, a San Francisco investment firm with $3.1
billion under management.
</P>
<P>
   While Greenspan still has a number of years left in his term,
there have been rumblings that Rubin might leave. But PaineWebber's
Kerschner asserts that Rubin would depart only if he thought the
global financial system had ``turned the corner toward stability.''
</P>
<P>
   So, based on this overwhelming optimism from Wall Street, can we
assume that the stock market will continue to rise?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. A number of economists and market strategists say
there are plenty of fundamental reasons why the stock market is on
shaky ground.
</P>
<P>
   Many are concerned that any hot air let out of the market during
the late summer downturn has been replaced. In fact, their biggest
concerns are that corporate earnings continue to go down while
stock prices continue to hover at pricey levels.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are sitting on a boiling keg of water,'' says Sung Won
Sohn, chief economist at Well Fargo Bank, a contrarian who believes
that impeachment hearings actually could be a catalyst for a
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we could really see this Clinton thing as the straw
that breaks the camel's back and could precipitate a correction in
the stock market,'' Sohn says.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reuss, chief strategist for Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis,
also is concerned about deterioration of corporate earnings. While
he does not place much fear on war or impeachment, he finds the
frothy and volatile stock market scary in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried that we have a lot of new (stock) players who
aren't seasoned. And once these people get their heads on straight,
and they start paying attention to fundamentals, we could be in for
a good correction,'' Reuss says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, for some, the market has been somewhat of a
substitute for the casino,'' Reuss says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
