<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVANT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Avant's CEO, 7 Others Are Indicted by Jury       
 By David Einstein 
    c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Avant Corp. and eight individuals, including the company's chief
executive, have been indicted on charges of stealing trade secrets
from rival Cadence Design Systems.
</P>
<P>
   In an eight-count indictment handed down Wednesday, the Santa
Clara County grand jury said the defendants, who all used to work
for Cadence, stole that company's code to create products for Avant
that competed directly against those of Cadence. Both companies
make software for designing computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   Each defendant faces a maximum of 12 years and four months in
prison and $17 million in fines and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment was the latest in a series of legal setbacks for
Avant. Earlier this month, a federal judge in San Jose ordered the
Fremont company to stop selling its Aquarius software and cleared
the way for a trial in a 3-year-old civil suit brought by Cadence
of San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Indicted by the grand jury were Avant CEO Gerald Hsu, Vice
President Stephen Wuu, Vice President Yuh-Zen Liao, board member
Eric Cho and Eric Cheng, an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Also named were former Avant President Mike Tsai, former
employee Leigh Huang and Mitsuru Igusa, who was accused of
delivering stolen code in return for thousands of dollars in
payments.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleged that the theft and misuse of trade
secrets _ from February of 1991 to last October 17 _ cost Cadence
an estimated $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably one of the largest cases ever in the country
involving trade-secret theft,'' said Julius Finkelstein, deputy
district attorney for Santa Clara County.
</P>
<P>
   Finkelstein brought criminal charges against Avant and the same
individuals in April of last year, only to have the the case
delayed repeatedly by motions and appeals by Avant attorneys. In
November, the district attorney's office turned to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our office believes the filing of this new indictment will
result in a speedy trial,'' Finkelstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants are scheduled for arraignment on January 11. They
are expected to surrender at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Wuu, Cho, Liao and Tsai founded Avant in 1991 under the name Arc
Systems, which later became ArcSys. Their first product, ArcCell
was developed in 1993 using stolen Cadence source code, the
indictment stated.
</P>
<P>
   In September of 1997, responding to Cadence's suit, a U.S.
appellate court blocked the sale of ArcCell. Avant replaced it with
Aquarius, a second-generation product that it said contained no
Cadence code. However, Cadence claimed that Aquarius was really
just ArcCell with some minor changes.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's indictment came as no surprise to Avant officials.
``Once we were notified in November of the beginning of the grand
jury investigation, we knew this was the eventual outcome,'' said
the company's general counsel, David Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   He called the case ``a dispute that has been orchestrated by our
main competitor'' and said, ``When this does come to trial and
we're able to put on our case, we will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the indictment, coupled with the recent injunction
against Avant's product, could hurt the company with its customers,
potentially slowing what has been steady growth. Avant had revenues
of $147 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Cadence _ a far larger company, with revenues of more than
$900 million _ the indictment was seen as a vindication of its
claims. In addition, analysts said it could give the company the
opportunity to take away some of Avant's business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
