r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUC-SFCHRON &LR;      12-17 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PUC Lets Pac Bell Cut Refund by $33 Million       
 By Deborah Solomon and Rebecca Smith 
    c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pacific Bell got an early holiday gift yesterday when state
regulators approved its request to refund a lower amount to
consumers than previously expected.
</P>
<P>
   Although consumer groups and the Public Utilities Commission
staff said Pac Bell should refund $47 million, the PUC instead said
Pac Bell could provide a rate cut of just $13.9 million _ about 2
percent of one month's bill for the average customer. The refund
would happen over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   In a marathon, end-of-the-year PUC meeting, the commission also:
</P>
<P>
   _ Rejected Pac Bell's request to provide long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ordered an investigation into PG&AMP;E's performance before and
during the December 8 blackout.
</P>
<P>
   _ Required Pac Bell to give competitors affordable access to its
telephone network.
</P>
<P>
   _ Voted to adopt a statewide policy regarding area-code changes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fined GTE California $9.8 million for abusive marketing
practices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Told Pac Bell it could not separate the White Pages from the
Yellow Pages without making a formal request.
</P>
<P>
   _ Approved Southern California Edison's request to provide
telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   The most contentious issue was the rate reduction, which
prompted several consumer groups to cry foul and say they would
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was a giveaway to Pac Bell, and it really stinks,''
said Paul Stein, staff attorney with The Utility Reform Network.
``That extra $33 million may not have amounted to a whole lot per
customer, but it's still a rip-off.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  The discrepancy stems from a commission decision in July,
which ordered Pac Bell to refund $305 million to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The commission ordered the refund after a new California law
allowed Pac Bell to place a surcharge on customers' bills to
subsidize rural and low-income phone service. In the past,
customers had paid inflated rates to subsidize the service. In
order to prevent Pac Bell from collecting the money twice, the
commission ordered the company to refund the amount _ $305 million
_ that it assumed Pac Bell would earn from the surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell said it collected $352 million but that it actually
refunded customers $338 million, not $305 million. Therefore, Pac
Bell said, it only had to cut rates again by $13.9 million, not $47
million.
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted to allow Pac Bell to use its own
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   The other controversial issue of the day was Pac Bell's
long-distance application, which, as expected, was rejected by the
full commission.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, a PUC judge said Pac Bell had not opened the
local telephone market to competition _ a prerequisite for becoming
a long-distance carrier _ and should not be granted entry into
long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   The commission laid out about 200 requirements yesterday that
Pac Bell must meet before getting PUC approval. The company has
until July 1999 to either reapply or tell the commission what it
plans to do.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Blase, vice president of regulatory at Pac Bell, said the
company was satisfied with the PUC's rejection of the application
because the commission indicated that it wants to see Pac Bell
competing in long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   Blase said Pac Bell would reapply in the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to do the things that are required in the order,''
Blase said. ``We're doing it in a very thorough manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell's competitors, such as AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom, also
praised the PUC decision, saying it proves that Pac Bell has not
released its stranglehold on the local phone market.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the commission postponed a vote on an order that
would have created statewide service-quality standards for
incumbent telephone companies, including Pacific Bell. That draft
decision followed a six-month investigation of service issues
resulting from a huge increase in consumer complaints about Pac
Bell installations and repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates said the proposed rules aren't strong enough
to assure uniform good quality, but that isn't why Commissioner
Neeper urged the issue tabled until January. He said he isn't
convinced there is any need for standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about an order that appears to pick on Pacific
Bell,'' Neeper said. ``Maybe the answer ought to be that we
shouldn't regulate at all.''
</P>
<P>
   With the departure of Commissioner Jessie Knight Jr., whose
six-year term expires December 31, Neeper yesterday became the
commission's new point man on telecommunications issues. The
assignment puts him in a pivotal position to influence how
telephone users' interests are balanced against utility interests.
</P>
<P>
   One of the big issues Neeper will tackle next year is how
California should deal with the proliferation of area codes.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the PUC voted to hold hearings during the next year
and adopt a statewide area-code relief plan by December 1999. The
commission will choose one of three plans:
</P>
<P>
   _ Geographic area-code splits that divide a region into two or
more area codes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Overlays, which require callers to dial 1 plus the area code
and phone number for every call, even calls within their own area
code.
</P>
<P>
   _ A combination of the geographic splits and overlays.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, regulators pick one of those options on a
case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area could be affected by whatever policy the commission
adopts. Area-code relief currently is planned for 415, 510 and 650.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also voted unanimously to commence an
investigation into PG&AMP;E's performance before and during the
December 8 blackout that brought San Francisco to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   The utility was ordered to submit a report by January 6 so that
the PUC can issue its preliminary conclusions by February 15.
Hearings, if any are ordered, would begin February 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
