A5832 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-CONGRESS18-COX     12-17 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-CONGRESS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   GOP sets debate as fighting goes on
   By Rebecca Carr and Mark Sherman
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House decided to proceed
today with a debate on impeaching President Clinton after pushing
aside Democratic objections to taking up the matter while Americans
are in combat in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Livingston (R-La.), the Republicans' choice to be the
new speaker of the House, pleaded with Democrats on Thursday to
abstain from invoking parliamentary maneuvers that would stall a
vote on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let them cast their votes without pressure; let us debate the
issue; let them cast their votes and live up to exactly the
principle to which our young people in the armed forces are risking
their lives for,'' said Livingston, speaking from the House floor
after lawmakers approved, 417-5, a resolution supporting the U.S.
troops taking part in the operation in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at 9 a.m. today, the House is to consider four
articles of impeachment against the president, alleging that he
lied under oath, obstructed justice and abused his presidential
powers in concealing his affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Responding in a passionate speech from the House floor, Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.) attempted to postpone the impeachment
vote until after the military mission in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say that we strongly object to this matter coming up
tomorrow or the next day or any day in which our young men and
women are in harm's way,'' Gephardt said. ``We believe we've got to
also look at how Saddam Hussein will perceive the idea and
information that while he is under physical attack by the United
States and its people, we're having a debate in the U.S. House of
Representatives to remove the commander in chief from his office.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats echoed his objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would think of removing Gen. (Norman) Schwarzkopf in the
middle of Desert Storm?'' commented Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri,
ranking Democrat on the House National Security Committee.
</P>
<P>
   To that, Rep. Duncan Hunter (R-Calif.) said going forward with
the impeachment debate is a sign of strength, not weakness.
</P>
<P>
   The troops taking part in the mission in Iraq ``will be
demoralized if we do stop this constitutional process,'' said
Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, lawmakers met behind closed doors to discuss
how to proceed. At first Livingston sought 16 hours for debating
the articles of impeachment today and finishing on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That drew immediate opposition from Democratic leaders, who said
they found it unfathomable that the Republicans would vote to
impeach the president while the country was engaged in military
action in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would look down upon any activity in this body to go
forward with impeachment while our American men and women are
engaged in Iraq,'' said Minority Whip David Bonior (D-Mich.).
</P>
<P>
   The debate on impeachment was delayed after Clinton ordered air
strikes against Iraq on Wednesday, just minutes before the
Republican House leaders met to discuss their game plan.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the attack prompted many Republicans to suggest
that the president ordered the air strikes in a desperate effort to
save his political life.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to respond to that criticism, Clinton said, ``I don't
think any serious person would believe that any president would do
such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.), who backed away
from his criticism Wednesday of the timing of the attack on Iraq,
ruled out a deal with the White House to spare the president an
impeachment trial. ``We will go to a trial, and there won't be any
deal making,'' Lott said in an interview with CNN.
</P>
<P>
   If the vote goes against him, Clinton would be the second
president to be impeached by the House. In 1868, Andrew Johnson
faced a similar fate, but the Senate declined to remove him from
office by one vote. President Richard Nixon resigned in 1974 before
articles of impeachment were voted on by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans want to vote now to avoid inconvenience,
Gephardt said. ``I'd like all of us to think about the
inconvenience that our young people are going through. I want them
to see nothing from us but support and unity of purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   To that, House Majority Leader Dick Armey (R-Texas) argued: ``As
we engage in conflict, democracy does not stop in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican moderates continued to jump on the impeachment train
Thursday, dimming hopes among White House aides that they could
derail impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio (R-N.Y.), who traveled to the Middle East with
Clinton last week, announced he would vote for impeachment. And
Republican Reps. Jim Nussle of Iowa, Steve Horn of California and
Heather Wilson of New Mexico announced they would do the same.
Outside the Capitol, 2,000 protesters led by the Rev. Jesse Jackson
rallied against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Rep. Maxine Waters (D-Calif.), a member of the Judiciary
Committee, got into a verbal feud with Rep. Gerald Solomon (R-N.Y.)
over his accusation that Clinton ordered the air strikes to divert
attention from the impeachment effort.
</P>
<P>
   As Solomon left the House floor, Waters said she asked him why
he had attacked the president in that fashion, telling him that he
had accused the president of a ``diabolical scheme,'' and that it
was ``unpatriotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon replied, ``No one can question my actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after a briefing by Defense Secretary William Cohen, a
former Republican senator from Maine, House Republicans remained
suspicious of the timing of the attack. Rep. Tillie Fowler (R-Fla.)
said she still questioned the timing of the bombing. But, she said,
once the bombs had fallen, it was important to ``stand together and
support our troops'' and she supported the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
