</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Donating To Gift Fund At the Office       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; QUESTION: &LR;  I'm a white-collar professional in a government agency.
There is a long-standing tradition of the professional staff each
donating $30 to a holiday gift fund that is divided among the
clerical staff. The clerical staff has come to rely on this money:
One secretary said she'd spent her Christmas money even before it
was handed out! I have problems with this whole process. Holiday
gifts should be a personal gesture from the heart, not an automatic
payment that people expect as a matter of course. And giving cash
rather than a gift seems mercenary. What should I do?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANSWER: &LR;  Ah, the holiday season. It brings joy, camaraderie and
eggnog to otherwise-staid workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   It also occasionally brings cultural clashes and tension.
</P>
<P>
   If you worked for a big private-sector company, the personnel
budget might very well include money for holiday treats for the
staff _ such as cash bonuses, an office party or luncheon, or gift
certificates.
</P>
<P>
   But as government employees, you can't very well use taxpayer
dollars to buy turkeys for all the secretaries. So someone came up
with a creative way to thank the support staff for their help _ an
idea that over time has become such a tradition that it no longer
feels spontaneous or personal to you.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the idea of all the professional staff chipping in for
holiday gifts for their subordinates seems reasonable to me. It's a
way to give presents without getting into potentially awkward
comparisons: ``Gee, Ms. Smith gave me an $80 watch but Mr. Jones
only gave me a coffee mug.''
</P>
<P>
   It also seems reasonable that the staff has come to rely on this
money _ just as the relatively low-paid doormen in the New York
apartment building where I grew up counted on a pile of envelopes
with tips from tenants each holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if this tradition feels oppressive to you, it's worth
trying to change it.
</P>
<P>
   The time to bring this up is after the emotions and pressures of
the holiday season have faded. Wait until March, and then talk to
your co-workers about updating the way your agency celebrates the
holidays. Don't be accusatory: Couch things in positive terms of
wanting to make sure the holiday rituals are meaningful to
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   And for now, swallow your distaste and write that $30 check. It
may not be spontaneous, but it still will help make someone's
holiday season happier.
</P>
<P>
   The Exit Interview
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently gave notice that I was quitting my job at a
nonprofit group. The director has said she won't release my final
paycheck unless I do an exit interview. Can she do this? Frankly, I
have no desire to do an exit interview. I've already let the
director know my feelings about the organization on several
occasions and don't want to get into another argument.
</P>
<P>
   A: Employers like to do exit interviews for several reasons.
They can take care of final logistical details, such as collecting
office keys from departing employees. They can inform people about
helpful post-employment benefits like COBRA, the program that lets
people continue their company health insurance at their own
expense.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies also use exit interviews as a way to improve
their operations _ finding out what employees liked or disliked
about working there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an exit interview is done properly, in a relaxed and
friendly atmosphere, there's often a great deal that a company can
learn about supervisory relations,'' said Conley Baker, a human
resources consultant with The Employers Group in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the key is to keep it relaxed,'' Baker added.
``Threatening to withhold someone's paycheck is not the way to
establish a relaxed atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   In your case, it doesn't sound like much would be gained by
either side from an exit interview.
</P>
<P>
   And your former boss actually has no legal right to withhold
your paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   California law says that employees who resign without notice
must be issued their final paycheck within 72 hours. Employees who
are terminated or who resign with notice must be given their final
check on their last day of work.
</P>
<P>
   If the director refuses to pay you, you should file an
unpaid-wages claim with the state labor commissioner at (415)
557-7878. Your former employer could face penalties of one day's
wages for every day that it fails to issue your check.
</P>
<P>
   When Do I Get Overtime?
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many days in a row can an employee work before overtime
is required? I work for a health care provider, and my schedule
often has me working Thursday through Sunday of one week, followed
by Monday through Friday the next. That makes a total of nine days
without a break. Is this legal?
</P>
<P>
   A: Overtime in California isn't based on the number of days you
work _ it's based on the number of hours worked over the course of
a week.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, most nonunion employers are required to pay overtime
after you put in 40 hours over a seven-day work week. (A few
employers, like hospitals, don't have to pay overtime unless
workers put in 80 hours over a 14-day period.)
</P>
<P>
   There are some laws that limit the number of consecutive days
that people can be asked to work. For instance, most California
employers are required to give their workers one day off out of
seven. But those days off can be postponed due to business
necessity, as long as people receive the equivalent of one day off
out of seven by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, the company clearly is giving you one day off each
week. And unless your hours add up to more than 40 in one work week
(or 80 hours over two weeks in cases like hospitals), you're not
owed any overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot? Your schedule may be inconvenient, but it's probably
legal.
</P>
<P>
   Want to double-check the overtime rules for your particular job?
You can find wage orders for different industries on the Web site
of the California Department of Industrial Relations, at
 &LR; www.dir.ca.gov/dir/Labor(UNDERSCORE)law &LR;   &LR; /DLSE &LR; 
 &LR; /IWC(UNDERSCORE)Order(UNDERSCORE)Index98.html &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
