A5837 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV20     12-17 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASE FOR TIME OFF  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn., N.Y.)  (EDS: (AT) in the last graf should be replaced with the
typographical `at' symbol, as for an e-mail address.) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I work for a small company with 30 or so employees. People
who have been with the company a year receive only four days of
sick and vacation time combined. All of us feel overworked and
underpaid. How we can get the owner to give us more time off? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Everyone, with the possible exception of Bill Gates, feels
overworked and underpaid. So before you go to the boss, conduct a
quick, if unscientific, survey to see how similar companies
approach the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do some benchmarking in your industry,'' advised Virginia
Byrd, president of the Work-Life Coalition, a nonprofit group in
San Diego that promotes workplace policies to help people balance
their professional and personal lives. Check vacation and
sick-leave policies at rival companies of about the same size in
your area. You don't want to raise the issue, only to discover that
the competition grants even less time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the likely event that four days is comparatively
stingy, you shouldn't march en masse into the boss' office to make
demands. There may be safety in numbers, but putting your boss on
the defensive is not the best way to succeed, warned Tom Jackson,
chairman of Equinox Interactive, a human resources consulting firm
and software developer based in Woodstock, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to shame your boss will probably prove unproductive,
too. Grousing about how much vacation Competitor X gives its
employees just might earn the suggestion that you go work for
Competitor X.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to go at this in a positive way,'' said Susan Seitel,
president of the Work and Family Connection, a consulting and
information firm in Minnetonka, Minn. Instead of talking about how
everyone wants to work less, Ms. Seitel advised, frame the issue as
part of a broader quest to make workers more committed and
productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In business, everybody is looking for what's in it for them _
and certainly the boss is,'' she said. ``Help him share a vision of
what could happen if people in the company were as committed as
they could possibly be, rather than point out to him what a jerk
he's been.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky, management will take the bait and ask for
supporting data. ``There is an enormous amount of evidence that
helping employees achieve work-life balance pays off in increased
morale, reduced turnover, increased loyalty and a better public
image,'' Ms. Seitel said.
</P>
<P>
   A Web search can put you in touch with many groups that conduct
or compile research on work-life issues; the best known may be the
Families and Work Institute in Manhattan (www.familiesandwork.org).
It notes, for example, that a study at Johnson &AMP; Johnson found that
the average number of days absent among all company workers
declined over the two years after the introduction of more generous
and flexible time and leave policies.
</P>
<P>
   By linking an increase in paid time off to the company's bottom
line, you may convince your boss of the error of his ways. But as
the reins are loosened, take care not to let productivity slip.
Otherwise, management may grant you a permanent vacation. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she will
respond to readers' questions about career and workplace issues.
Send them by E-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to
Working, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
