A5840 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     12-17 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREW MIGHT GO FROM SCOUTS TO STARTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They toil in the soil all season, known only by
their numbers, with nothing at stake except their future.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's scout players spent three months impersonating opponents
to prepare the Bruins' starters for weekly competition. A few
freshmen managed to impress the coaches and will compete for
starting spots when spring practice begins:
</P>
<P>
   __ Rusty Williams, an outside linebacker/defensive end from San
Diego. He plays with limitless energy and was named defensive scout
player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mike Saffer, an offensive lineman from Tucson, Ariz., and the
son of former UCLA basketball player Don Saffer. The younger Saffer
can play either guard or tackle but might be more suited for guard
because of his athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be outstanding,'' said Bruins coach Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   __ Joe Hunter, a cornerback from Vacaville who overcame a
preseason knee injury to show promise in man-to-man coverage.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sean Phillips, a 290-pound defensive lineman from Missouri
City, Texas, who started slowly but has played well in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   __ Audie Attar, a strong safety from Claremont who is, by far,
UCLA's hardest hitter.
</P>
<P>
   __ Cory Paus: In his leadership skills, the quarterback reminds
coaches of a young Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lovell Houston: The touted freshman defensive back had
shoulder surgery two months ago but will be ready for spring
practice.
</P>
<P>
   __ Toledo contract: Athletic director Peter Dalis met with
school officials again last week about securing a long-term
contract for Toledo, 52, who is signed through 2003 and wants to
finish his career at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo makes $453,000 per year and will be the ninth-highest
paid coach in the Pac-10 when Arizona's Dick Tomey receives a
five-year, $2.5 million deal next month.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo and Dalis initially met with UCLA administrators before
Thanksgiving, a source said, after Toledo was contacted by
Oklahoma. Toledo's name has surfaced in conjunction with NFL
openings in Baltimore and San Diego, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not pursuing anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Maybe next year: Sophomore nose guard Micah Webb tore
ligaments in his left knee and will need reconstructive surgery.
The damage was serious; he won't play in the Rose Bowl, he won't be
ready for spring practice and he might not play next season.
</P>
<P>
   True freshman Ken Kocher probably will replace Webb, meaning the
starting defense against Wisconsin will consist of four freshmen,
three sophomores, two juniors and two seniors.
</P>
<P>
   __ Short stuff: Linebacker Ryan Nece and tailback DeShaun Foster
were named to The Sporting News' freshman All-American team. . . .
Toledo suffered a concussion and a separated shoulder in an
automobile accident last week in Atlanta. Offensive line coach Mark
Weber, who was driving, has a grotesque bruise on his back. . .
Twenty recruits will be on campus this weekend, and today's
practice was canceled as a result. (Someone needs to pick the
players up at the airport.) . . . The Bruins have received four
oral commitments _ Anaheim linebacker Asi Faoa, Temecula safety
Ryan Wikert, Bakersfield defensive lineman Rodney Leslie and Venice
quarterback J.P. Losman _ and hope to sign 18 players in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
