<HEADER>
A5842 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-GREECE-SPI &LR;      12-17 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-GREECE-SPI </SLUG>
  
 GREEK DECISION CLOUDS POTENTIAL BIG bOEING F-15 SALE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Greece's decision this week to purchase what defense
experts say is a much inferior airborne early warning system from
Europe rather than from Northrup Grumman may have implications for
Boeing winning an important fighter plane order from the Greek
military early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Defense experts believe Greece caved in to considerable pressure
from the European Union not to buy the system from a U.S.
manufacturer, and similar pressure is being applied to the fighter
competition.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly for Boeing, the ``Fortress Europe'' that now
appears to be going up on the other side of the Atlantic could in
the long term make it harder for the U.S. aerospace giant to sell
commercial jets to European airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The walls are going up, brick by brick,'' said Richard
Aboulafia, senior aircraft analyst with the Teal Group, a closely
followed market research firm in Virginia. ``It's not fully in
place yet, but it can only get worse ... and it has very serious
implications for Boeing and other U.S. defense companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and Lockheed Martin in the U.S. are vying for a
multi-billion-dollar contract to supply Greece with up to 60 modern
fighters. For months, defense experts believed Boeing's F-15 strike
fighter was the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eurofighter, a joint European venture by Germany,
Britian, Italy and Spain, now has the edge, the trade publication
Defense Daily reported. If it does pick the Eurofighter, Greece
would be the first export customer for the multinational fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Greece is likely to name the winner in January or February next
year.
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions about the Greek fighter competition,
Jim Schlueter, Boeing's spokesman in St. Louis for international
fighters sales, issued this statement:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greek military has proven to be a very sophisticated and
knowledgable customer. As with their other programs, they are
continuing a very detailed and thorough evaluation of the new
fighter aircraft. We are confident they will select the solution
that best meets their requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Without new orders, Boeing will have to shut down its F-15
production line after December 1999. The F-18 Hornet line will meet
the same fate in mid 2000 without new orders. Both fighters are
built in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Those fighter lines provide several hundred million dollars of
profit annually for Boeing. While that is a small percentage of
Boeing's total profits, the company can ill afford to see the
fighter money disappear at a time when the commercial side is
hurting and investors are demanding higher profits.
</P>
<P>
   At the Farnborough international air show in September, Boeing
President Harry Stonecipher told industry analysts that he was much
more optimistic than before that the F-15 line will soon get new
orders. But he said he was less optimistic about the F-18 line.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has been working hard behind the scenes to win fighter
competitions not only in Greece, but in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the Farnborough show, Mike Sears, head of
Boeing's Military Aircraft and Missile Systems Group in St. Louis,
flew from London to Athens for further talks with that country's
military on its fighter competition.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Boeing opened a new office in Athens to support its
efforts to develop long-term business relationships with Greece. It
has a similar business relationships with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is considering a $2 billion order for either the F-15 or
Lockheed Martin's F-16.
</P>
<P>
   And Saudia Arabia has indicated it may want more F-15s once
Boeing fills a previous order for 72 of the fighters. About half
have so far been delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia said Boeing is still alive in the Greek competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't kill Boeing's chances (to sell Greece the F-15),
but it's not a welcome sign,'' Aboulafia said of the decision by
Greece to accept a proposal from Sweden's Ericsson for $600 million
worth of airborne early warning planes.
</P>
<P>
   Ericsson will supply the radar system for four EMB-145
twin-engine passenger planes built by Brazil's Embraer. That system
would be integrated into the planes by Thomson-CSF, the French
aerospace giant.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop Grumman and Lockheed Martin also had submitted
proposals to the Greek military.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop's E-2C Hawkeye 2000 was thought to be the clear
front-runner. Updated versions of the Hawkeye have been in service
with the U.S. Navy since the 1970s, and is used by Japan, Egypt,
Singapore and Taiwan. Even France has ordered two for its new
carrier the Charles de Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ericsson proposal selected by Greece is for an untested
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like comparing a Volkswagon to a Ferrari,'' Aboulafia
said. ``It's like comparing a Fisher-priced toy to a Ferrari ....
This decision was either an extreme cost-cutting measure by Greece
or there was a great deal of political pressure applied, which is
not a welcome sign of things to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Daily quoted U.S. government sources as saying Greece
decided to go with the Ericsson proposal after a meeting of the
European Union in Vienna last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Greece and other European countries such as Spain receive
important EU subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Daily quoted an unnamed senior U.S. executive as saying,
``This is a blunt message that's hard to compete against. The
Germans, French and Swedes are saying, `We give you money, then
you've got to buy our products.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. defense companies are worried that a Fortress Europe will
make it more difficult for them to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their worst nightmare,'' said Aboulafia.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for U.S. defense companies is that most of their
foreign military sales are in Asia and the Middle East, not Europe,
said Cai von Romohr, a defense analyst with Cowen &AMP; Company
</P>
<P>
   ``These political issues don't have the significance there that
they do in Europe,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   But if the military aspects of a Fortress Europe are extended to
the commercial sector, that would be an even bigger concern for
Boeing, Aboulafia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly the prospect that airlines would be coerced
in this effort,'' Aboulafia said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nisbet, aerospace analysts with JSA Research, said European
airlines have long felt pressure from the European Union to buy
from Airbus Industrie rather than from Boeing, but that pressure is
getting more aggressive as Europe moves toward a common currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to have a rival to the dollar and keeping
business in Europe is all part of it,'' he said. ``International
politics plays a big part in the selection of aerospace
purchases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
