<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   CLINTON ADMITS EXTRAMARITAL AFFAIRS
   By CHRISTI HARLAN
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a confession that will add fuel to an already
overheated impeachment debate, incoming House Speaker Bob
Livingston, R-La., said Thursday that he had ``on occasion
strayed'' during his 33-year marriage but was quick to distinguish
his infidelity from the one that threatens Bill Clinton's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to assure everyone that these indiscretions were not
with employees on my staff and I have never been asked to testify
under oath about them,'' Livingston said in a statement distributed
after he admitted the affairs in a meeting with House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's admission came less than 13 hours before the House
is scheduled to begin debate Friday morning on whether Clinton
should be impeached on charges that he lied under oath about his
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. He had
decided some days ago not to preside over the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the speaker-to-be's confession is sure to further enrage
House Democrats who were already furious Thursday that the
Republicans would schedule a debate and vote on impeachment while
Clinton is performing his duties as commander-in-chief of the U.S.
armed forces attacking Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans, including Livingston, were bristling Thursday
night that yet another GOP leader had been forced to acknowledge
marital problems under the threat of possible exposure in the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   The last and, until Thursday, most visible target was Judiciary
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., whose long-ago affair was
reported by the Internet magazine Salon as the committee began
considering impeachment articles against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, in his statement, said he was confessing, in part,
``because of forces outside of this institution seeking to
influence the upcoming events and/or media coverage of these
events.'' He did not elaborate, and said, ``this will be the only
statement I will make on this subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans were quick to point down Pennsylvania Avenue:
``We feel like the White House is behind a lot of this,'' said Tony
Rudy, deputy chief of staff to House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas. DeLay had asked in September for an FBI investigation of
the source of Salon's story on Hyde, saying Republicans ``will not
be intimidated by this kind of sleazy activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican leaders, including the outgoing fourth-ranking
leader, Rep. John Boehner of Ohio, bypassed reporters and cameras
without comment, looking weary and disbelieving after a week in
which House members reassembled in Washington to deal with
impeachment, only to be confronted with bombing in Baghdad and
another bombshell under their own roof.
</P>
<P>
   Both a White House spokesman and aides to House Minority Leader
Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston had been nominated as House speaker by Republicans
just five weeks ago to replace Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., whose decision
to resign in the days after his party's poor showing in the Nov. 3
election rocked the Capitol. Challenges to other leaders roiled the
Republican delegation for days, until the conference settled on
Livingston, who had been chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee and was prepared to try to unseat Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, in the basement of the Capitol, Republicans rallied
again around their selected speaker, who said the other reasons for
his admission were the ``tremendous trust and responsibility my
colleagues have placed in me.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who in March suggested that because Clinton ``cheated on
his wife, he will cheat on the American people,'' spoke out for
Livingston on Thursday night, Rudy said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston ``didn't lie under oath. He didn't lie in a
deposition. He didn't lie to a grand jury,'' Rudy said. Livingston
admitted his infidelity ``in a forthright, honest and honorable
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., agreed Thursday ``there's no
comparison here, there's no parallel'' between Livingston's and
Clinton's situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is here under articles of impeachment because he
refused to deal with the Paula Jones case, and he swore under oath
before a grand jury and in a deposition, and there is good evidence
that he obstructed justice,'' she said. ``The issue before the
Congress is did the president disobey the law ...not sex, or the
president and Mrs. Clinton's private family life.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
