<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., BRITAIN HAMMER IRAQ IN SECOND WAVE OF BOMBINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and Britain launched a second
wave of missiles at Iraq on Thursday as President Clinton defended
the mission as ``the right thing to do'' despite the House vote
pending on his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of the U.S.-led campaign to destroy Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein's weapons program, Russia recalled its
ambassador to the United States in a surprising show of protest.
And in an extraordinary and unprecedented day in the nation's
capital, the House voted 417-5 for a resolution backing U.S.
troops, pointedly omitting references to the commander in chief,
and then opted to begin debate Friday on impeachment of the
president regardless of the on-going military mission.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials reported no U.S. casualties during
``Operation Desert Fox.'' Air-launched cruise missiles from U.S.
B-52 bombers and British Tornado bombers pelted Iraqi military
targets again Thursday, following an initial night assault
Wednesday from more than 200 ship-based Tomahawk cruise missiles
and 70 attack warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   CNN reported 25 Iraqi dead and 75 wounded in Baghdad, based on
Iraqi statements.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended the mission as necessary to prevent Saddam from
dismantling the United Nations weapons inspection operation
instituted after the 1991 Persian Gulf War, and to stop him from
rebuilding his chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced the decision I made to order this military
action, though difficult, was absolutely the right thing to do. It
is in our interest and in the interest of people all around the
world,'' Clinton told reporters while awaiting a briefing from his
national security team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein has used weapons of mass destruction and
ballistic missiles before; I have no doubt he would use them again
if permitted to develop them,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart called the mission ``a
success,'' but military officials offered a more measured
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our early assessment of the military action against Iraq shows
that our forces are performing well. There have been no American
casualties and we are achieving good coverage of our targets. And
as a result, we are advancing our goal of containing Saddam
Hussein,'' said Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., warned that America's
enemies should not see the confluence of the Iraqi action and the
impeachment issue as a sign of possible U.S. weakness. ``We have a
chance to say to the world today no matter what our constitutional
process, whether it is an election or it is the eve of a
constitutional vote, no matter what our debates at home, we are, as
a nation, prepared to lead the world,'' Gingrich said as debate on
the resolution began.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, one of the five members to oppose the
resolution voicing support for U.S. troops, said he voted against
it for policy and constitutional reasons. He said Congress should
have approved the military action before it occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking for months so much about the need to follow
the Constitution. I don't know why we can't follow it when it comes
to waging war,'' Paul said. He added ``bombing never wins a war''
and Clinton ordered the strikes to divert attention from
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans continued to question the timing of the mission,
which occurred on the eve of the scheduled impeachment debate. Some
suggested it was a deliberate move to alter the impeachment
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any serious person would believe that any
president would do such a thing. And I don't believe any reasonably
astute person in Washington would believe that Secretary Cohen and
(chairman of the Joint Chiefs) Gen. (Hugh) Shelton and the whole
rest of the national security team would participate in such an
action. This was the right thing for the country,'' Clinton
responded.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., backtracked from his
press statement issued as the bombing began and maintained he did
not believe the timing of the military mission was tied to
impeachment. Lott voiced support for U.S. troops but again
questioned the strategy of the administration's Iraqi policy.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, air raid sirens sounded throughout the night as the
missiles sought out military and intelligence targets as well as
suspected sites for biological and chemical weapons in outlying
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Said Al-Sahaf accused the United
States of ``lying shameless'' about Iraq's level of cooperation
with the United Nations Special Commission, or UNSCOM. ``They call
it `Operation Desert Fox.' In fact, it is `Operation Villains in
the Arabian Desert,''' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   He maintained there were only five cases of noncooperation out
of 427 inspections. He also charged that the missiles damaged the
home of Saddam's daughter as well as nonmilitary sites such as a
training center for mechanics and a plant producing brake oil for
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the minister did not rule out further cooperation with
UNSCOM, the arms inspection group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is premature, to have an answer on it. We are dealing
with the circumstances, and we will see after that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq found allies on the U.N. Security Council as Russia and
China continued to demand a halt to the bombing and the resignation
of UNSCOM chief Richard Butler. France also voiced objections to
the military response.
</P>
<P>
   Russia took the rare step of recalling its ambassador, the first
time it has taken such action since the breakup of the Soviet Union
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin took the action despite appeals from
Vice President Al Gore. Officials said Clinton, who called several
world leaders Thursday, would try to speak to Yeltsin on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said in Moscow that ``Russia demands an immediate end to
military action, to show common sense and restraint and not to
allow further escalation of the conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler's report to the United Nations on Tuesday outlined the
level of noncompliance by Iraq since Nov. 15, when it averted a
U.S. military strike by promising unconditional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say simply, slowly and plainly that any suggestion
that that report was not factual, was not objective is utterly
false,'' Butler told reporters. ``There is no doubt in my mind that
the conclusion I came to that Iraq did not keep its promise of full
cooperation is correct, whether we are talking about inspections or
documents or interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright acknowledged the
criticism from Russia and China but added, ``over the past year
they have failed to provide any viable alternative.'' Albright
called 20 foreign ministers to inform them of the U.S.-British
operation, and administration officials were informing all foreign
missions in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
