<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-OPERATIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKS DEVASTATE KEY ELEMENTS OF SADDAM'S FORCES, SAY PENTAGON
OFFICIALS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pentagon officials said Thursday that the first
wave of attacks on Iraq knocked out key elements of Saddam
Hussein's air defense system and military command structure.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more than 50 targets hit by Tomahawk cruise missiles
launched from ships in the Persian Gulf and from U.S. and British
warplanes were Saddam's intelligence headquarters in Baghdad and
facilities housing his Republican Guard troops and secret security
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
four out of five barracks buildings where some of Saddam's most
loyal troops may have been sleeping were completely destroyed and
that the intelligence headquarters had been reduced to ``rubble.''
He could not say, however, whether any of Saddam's troops had been
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, pointing to satellite photos of the destroyed
buildings, said the targets were just a few of the more than 50
that were hit over the course of the initial U.S.-British attack
that began at about 5 p.m. EST Wednesday and continued for about 4
1/2 hours. He said suspected weapons sites, air fields, air defense
systems and other military targets had been hit as well in the
strikes involving more than 200 cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen also emphasized that U.S. and
British forces involved in the operation, dubbed Desert Fox, had
sustained no casualties. He said the crews of about 70 aircraft
involved in the first assault had returned safely to the aircraft
carrier USS Enterprise in the Persian Gulf or to nearby allied land
bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no American casualties, and we are achieving
good coverage of our targets. And as a result we are advancing our
goal of containing Saddam Hussein,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that the goal of the operations is to
``significantly degrade'' Saddam's ability to threaten his other
Middle East states and build weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are diminishing his ability to attack his neighbors _
either conventionally or with weapons of mass destruction,'' Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   As Cohen spoke, a second round of cruise missiles began falling
on targets in Baghdad and in key areas in the southern and northern
parts of Iraq where Saddam is believed to be hiding key elements of
his weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   The missiles were launched primarily from B-52s. Smaller fighter
planes also flew along Iraq's border dropping laser-guided bombs on
various sites, including suspected storage and manufacturing
facilities for chemical, biological and nuclear weapons. Air
fields, air defense sites and a number of military bases were also
targeted. Military food storage facilities and other infrastructure
sites that could be used to sustain his army were also hit,
Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Strikes also took place on or near a number of palaces or other
complexes known to be used by Saddam on occasion, although U.S.
officials were quick to point out that the Iraqi dictator was not
being targeted specifically. The palaces have also been identified
as possible hiding places for elements of his chemical, biological
and nuclear programs, as well as his centers of his command and
communications operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been tracking Saddam Hussein by day and Saddam
Hussein was not the objective established for this operation,''
Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen emphasized that the U.S. and British firepower was
concentrated primarily on military targets to minimize the chance
of civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not attacking the people of Iraq, and we have no desire
to increase the suffering that Saddam Hussein has imposed on his
own people,`` Cohen stressed.
</P>
<P>
   He added that there ``are a number of facilities that could
probably be characterized as dual-use'' that house both legitimate
civilian manufacturing operations as well as questionable
activities related to Saddam's weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have civilian activities on certain floors and
inappropriate activities on others,'' he continued. ``So we have
been careful in our targeting to try to limit it to military types
of targets that would minimize the potential for harm to innocent
civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that targets had been scrutinized closely before
the attacks began to determine which ones housed chemical or
biological elements that might be released if bombed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very scrupulous in looking at those targets and
trying to minimize any possibility of that,'' Cohen said, adding
that there's been no indication thus far ``that any kind of release
or anything has taken place.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also noted that no activities have been detected that
would suggest Saddam is preparing to launch retaliatory strikes at
U.S. and British forces, Israel or Kuwait as he did with his Scud
missile attacks during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
