A5867 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-REPORTER-HNS &LR;      12-17 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-REPORTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN AUTOPSY REPORT INDICATES TEXAS REPORTER STRANGLED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW DOWNIE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A Texas newspaper reporter found dead in the
mountains of western Mexico had been strangled and his body left in
a ravine, authorities and friends said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo ordered federal police to
assist the state police investigation of the murder of Philip True,
50, the Mexico City-based correspondent for the San Antonio
Express-News. True disappeared while on a hiking trip through a
remote section of mountains of western Mexico, about 150 miles
northwest of Guadalajara. His body was found Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Press and writers' organizations, among them the hemisphere-wide
Inter American Press Association, urged Zedillo to spare no effort
to bring True's killers to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely anxious that the circumstances surrounding
Philip True's death should be established,'' the IAPA's president,
Jorge E. Fascetto of Argentina, said in a letter to Zedillo, ``and
we therefore welcome your announcement that `no effort will be
spared in investigating this regrettable crime.'
</P>
<P>
   ``However, we remain concerned at the fact that the majority of
similar cases in Mexico go unpunished.'' In the last year, Fascetto
said, five newsmen have been killed in Mexico and their assailants
had not been brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
   True, an experienced hiker who enjoyed writing about people in
remote areas of Mexico, left for the Sierra Madre Occidental
mountains Nov. 29 for a vacation and an opportunity to research the
region's Huichol indians. He had agreed to call his wife, Marta, on
Dec. 8, but a call never came.
</P>
<P>
   She raised an alarm several days later, and friends, state
police and soldiers began tracing his route. A friend, Fred Chase,
located the body in a deep ravine near the border of Jalisco and
Nayarit states.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the searchers said they believed that True had fallen
to his death. But an autopsy carried out on Thursday by the Jalisco
state medical examiner, Dr. Mario Rivas Souza, found that True had
been strangled with a piece of cloth, possibly a cord or a
neckerchief.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a murder,'' said Rivas Souza, ``not an accident.`` The
medical examiner's report also listed numerous cuts among the
reporter's injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the killing was unclear. Although True's backpack
and camera were missing, his assailants did not take his watch or
wedding ring, said Express-News reporter Susana Heyward.
</P>
<P>
   Even though drugs are sometimes cultivated in the area, True did
not intend to report about anything controversial during the trip,
his colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Simon, Latin American coordinator for the New York-based
Committee to Protect Journalists, said that ``based on what I have
heard so far, it seems that he was killed because of his work.'' He
called on Mexican federal authorities to take over the
investigation and expressed concern that state police officers
might use heavy-handed methods to obtain false testimony from local
Huichol indians.
</P>
<P>
   The PEN International writers' group also called on Zedillo to
carry out ``an exhaustive investigation to discover the
circumstances of True's death.''
</P>
<P>
   A presidential spokesman said that although there was at this
time ``nothing to suggest he was killed because of his work as a
journalist,`` authorities would carry out a thorough investigation
before ruling definitively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all still a bit confused and it is difficult to say
exactly what happened,'' the spokesman said. ``I think we have to
wait for a more detailed investigation, identify all his personal
items and other such things so that we don't enter into
speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Attorney General's Office said late Thursday that
True's remains would be brought to Mexico City where federal
investigators would conduct a second autopsy aimed at establishing
``the type, origin and cause of injuries and the time of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Born June 18, 1948, in San Fernando, Calif., True graduated from
the University of California at Irvine. He moved to New York, where
he worked on the docks and as a maritime union representative,
before heading to Texas. He changed professions, and got his first
newspaper reporting job in 1990 at the Brownsville Herald. He
joined the Express-News in 1992 and became the paper's Mexico City
reporter in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of friends and family, as well as colleagues from both
the foreign and Mexican press corps, were expected to attend a
memorial service Friday in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   His wife is pregnant with the couple's first child. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Andrew Downie is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the
Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
