<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      12-17 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OIL PRICES FALL 10.9 PERCENT AS IRAQ OUTPUT FEARS EBB
</P>
<P>
   With the air strikes on Iraq causing no damage to its ability to
pump and ship oil, prices plunged, wiping out a large part of the
gains of the last week.
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil fell 91 cents, or 8 percent, to $10.45 a
barrel, on London's International Petroleum Exchange. It also
plunged to $11.03 a barrel, down $1.35, or 10.9 percent, in trading
on the New York Mercantile Exchange. The decline also reflected
disappointment with a meeting in Madrid by the oil ministers of
some of the world's largest oil producers _ Saudi Arabia, Venezuela
and Mexico _ to initiate further production cuts.
</P>
<P>
   A prolonged bombing attack on Iraq, a terrorist attack against
the West or an Iraqi strike against Israel would most likely bring
international travel to a halt. The current fighting has caused
relatively little concern.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of improved demand for American products abroad, the
Commerce Department said the trade deficit unexpectedly dropped to
$14.2 billion in October after having narrowed in September to a
revised $14.4 billion. In a separate report, the Labor Department
said the number of first-time jobless claims filed last week fell
to the lowest level since September.
</P>
<P>
   LIVENT COULD FACE FRAUD CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators intend to file civil charges against Livent,
the Broadway theater producer, and some former employees for
securities and accounting fraud, according to documents the company
has filed in bankruptcy court. And the U.S. attorney in Manhattan
is deciding whether to bring criminal charges against Garth
Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb, the company's founders, a lawyer
representing Gottlieb said.
</P>
<P>
   COLTEC DISPUTES CRANE SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Coltec Industries, before agreeing to merge with B.F. Goodrich,
never received a formal purchase offer from Crane, raising serious
doubts about Crane's interest in the company, Coltec's chief
executive said. As a result, Crane's lawsuit seeking to block the
deal is without merit, Coltec said.
</P>
<P>
   BIG SHARE BUYBACK BY PHILIPS ROYAL
</P>
<P>
   Philips Electronics, Europe's largest maker of consumer
electronics, will reduce the number of its outstanding common
shares by 8 percent, the company said. Philips received about $6
billion in cash last week from the sale of its 75 percent stake in
Polygram, and the company said it had earmarked about $2 billion
for a share buyback. The American depository receipts of Philips
rose $2.625, to $64.625 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT DENIES SABOTAGE CLAIM
</P>
<P>
   Stung by a government witness' testimony that Microsoft had
sabotaged a program designed to gather evidence against the
company, lawyers for the software giant offered an explanation to
the judge presiding at the trial of its antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS AT NIKE FALL 51 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Nike, the world's top athletic shoe and apparel seller, said
that its second-quarter earnings dropped 51 percent amid soft
conditions in retailing. The company said earnings fell to $68.9
million, or 24 cents a share, compared with $141.1 million, or 48
cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier. The results slightly
exceeded Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-DRINK SHOWDOWN IN VENEZUELA
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico, which once held an overwhelming lead over Coca-Cola in
Venezuela but then lost it when its bottler switched to Coke, is
battling back in the country's soft-drink market. This marks the
first time Coke and Pepsi have been simultaneously present in the
Venezuelan market at full strength, and analysts predict it will be
a long and costly entanglement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 2149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5872 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-CHRISTIAN-CLOTHES     12-17 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CHRISTIAN-CLOTHES-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, ADDING ART NOTE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: N.J., Vt.)  
 THE GOSPEL, WITH SUGAR ON TOP  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
(af) 
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
