<HEADER>
A5874 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-ROLLS-ROYC     12-17 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-ROLLS-ROYCE-$ADV20-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLS-ROYCE SILVER SERAPH: LAST-MINUTE GIFTS UNDER $250,000  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20)
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Your internet stocks have sizzled. Your law firm had
record billings, having represented various parties called before
the independent counsel. Against Denver, you took the Giants and
the points.
</P>
<P>
   Or, perhaps, you were simply born with a silver spoon in your
mouth and a Silver Dawn in your garage.
</P>
<P>
   It's the season for giving, and you'd like to share your good
fortune with the object of your affection. A diamond is forever and
fur may be what becomes a legend most, but nothing says ``I love
you'' quite so conspicuously as a Rolls-Royce. And this year there
is an all-new Rolls, the Silver Seraph, that outshines the lights
on almost any tree. It will also make a dent in the average wallet,
with a price that starts at $216,400, plus luxury tax of nearly
$13,000.
</P>
<P>
   But what the heck, toss in the most popular options _ it's the
holidays, after all. The top five are full wood-veneered door
panels ($990); light burl oak trim, instead of walnut ($1,055);
four umbrellas fitted into the trunk ($300); an electric sunroof
($1,820), and chrome-plated wheels ($2,990). And who would object
if you dug a little deeper to cover the $65,000 tea set sold in
conjunction with Wedgewood?
</P>
<P>
   The Silver Seraph replaces the Silver Spur and is the first
all-new Rolls-Royce in nearly two decades. It is the last developed
under British control, and the last produced at the company's
historic plant in Crewe, England, where Rolls-Royces are now built
alongside Bentleys.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in a takeover tale filled with as many intriguing
twists as the Cornwall coast, two German companies, BMW and
Volkswagen, battled to gain control of Rolls-Royce Motor Cars,
which had put on the block by its parent, Vickers PLC. After a
series of offers and counteroffers, VW sealed a deal for $790
million, many times the initial estimates of what the company was
worth.
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, it was disclosed that BMW had actually obtained
for $65 million the rights to the Rolls name, which were held
separately by Rolls-Royce PLC, the jet-engine maker that had been
split off from the car company in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   VW was forced into negotiations with BMW, and the companies
agreed to split the baby: VW will keep Bentley, and until 2003 will
keep producing Rolls-Royces. BMW will continue to supply engines,
and after 2002 it will have exclusive rights to the Rolls name, the
distinctive grille and the elegant Flying Lady hood ornament _
which on the new Silver Seraph retracts under pressure into a trap
door on the hood, so as not to impale a pedestrian.
</P>
<P>
   A Rolls for the 90s and beyond, the Silver Seraph is trimmer
than its predecessors and tailored like a Savile Row suit. Yet it
is immense, timeless and readily recognizable as a Rolls. Its
designers were inspired by the classic Silver Cloud of 1955-65.
Even the name continues to draw on celestial imagery.
</P>
<P>
   The Silver Seraph is precisely and everything one expects a
Rolls to be, with a fillip: As the last blue-blood British design,
it may have special resonance with collectors. (On the other hand,
if Rolls' new owners carefully nurture the brand, as Ford has done
with Jaguar, there may be little price difference between this and
future models.)
</P>
<P>
   Hand-stitched Connolly leather covers virtually every interior
surface including, quite wonderfully, the headliner. Aside from the
black-leather dashboard, the color is creamy vanilla, and dark
piping accents the curvaceous seats.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Once seated, you are tempted to remove your shoes and socks and
wiggle your toes in the furry Wilton carpet. All the instruments
are new, the gauges encircled with chrome bezels for a timeless
look. There is nary a speck of plastic, and only the unexceptional
controls of the Alpine stereo, familiar to BMW owners, seemed out
of sync with the elegant motif.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to many automobiles, the Silver Seraph pampers
rear-seat passengers as much if not more than the occupants up
front. That is only fitting, since many Rolls owners rely on
chauffeurs to get them around. (Bentley owners are more likely to
drive themselves.) With enough legroom for the NBA's tallest
players, the rear seats heat and electrically adjust the lumbar
support.
</P>
<P>
   Back-seat passengers also have their own large heating ducts and
polished wood writing tables that fold from the back of the front
seats. The trunk is big enough for multiple sets of Louis Vuitton
luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Even before its ownership of Rolls, BMW participated heavily in
the development of the Silver Seraph and it supplies the car's
powerful V12 engine, the same one used in the BMW 750iL. Nearly a
third of the parts in the Silver Seraph are already shared with BMW
models, and more parts-sharing is likely with BMW becoming the
future owner.
</P>
<P>
   Though hidden from view, BMW's influence _ in the parts and
engineering _ apparent when driving the Silver Seraph, which is the
most capable Rolls of recent times. The body structure is extremely
rigid, providing a ride that is nothing short of heavenly even over
the hellishly potholed roads of southern Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The handling is appropriately ponderous but with no wallowing,
it is far better than any Rolls built before. The 322 horsepower
under the hood, coupled with a smooth and modern five-speed
transmission, moves the three-ton Silver Seraph rather quickly,
from 0 to 60 miles an hour in less than six seconds. Modern
features include a refined suspension system and a stability
control that keeps the rear-drive car from spinning out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Silver Seraph is less about how it drives than about how
it parks. The Silver Seraph earns the best parking spots in town,
and it will make sure your loved one gets the attention that he or
she deserves. Valet parking attendants at the finest restaurants
leave it right up front as testimony to their clientele.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night at the symphony, the Silver Seraph won a spot
right outside the door of the auditorium. (Numerous concert goers
tried to claim the Rolls as their own, the attendant reported;
other times, passersby posed for pictures around the car, as if it
were a historic landmark.)
</P>
<P>
   Such reactions, so common around the Rolls, underscore the car's
appeal as a first-tier status symbol. The new Mercedes-Benz S-Class
is technologically superior. The Jaguar Vanden Plas also exudes
British class.
</P>
<P>
   A Lexus LS 400 rides nearly as smoothly and quietly. All three
cars cost far less. And the Rolls lacks rather mundane features
like side air bags, which one can now have on a $16,000 Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   But like a $30,000 Patek Philippe that keeps no better time than
a $300 Seiko, value and practicality are beside the point. If it's
better to give than receive, what better way to give the gift of
status?  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
