u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SALT-LAKE-CITY-81     12-17 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALT-LAKE-CITY-815(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE REPORTS OF IOC FAVORS EMERGE IN UTAH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The son of a leading International Olympic
Committee member from Africa worked as an intern at City Hall while
Salt Lake City was attempting to become the host city for the 2002
Winter Games, the mayor's office said Thursday. The admission
raised more questions about the extent to which an effort was made
to sway votes in landing the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   And Tom Welch, the former president of the Salt Lake City
organizing committee, said in an interview that visiting IOC
members had been given presents such as shotguns, skis and free
lift tickets, airplane flyovers of Utah's arresting canyons, and
tickets to the opera and Utah Jazz basketball games, and had been
taken on hunting trips for pheasant in a successful attempt to
attract their votes.
</P>
<P>
   These were the latest eruptions in a mushrooming vote-buying
scandal among cities seeking to play host to the Olympics that has
been alleged by Marc Hodler of Switzerland, the
second-highest-ranking member of the IOC. Salt Lake officials have
acknowledged spending about $400,000 on scholarships and athletic
training for 13 people, including six relatives of IOC members, but
they have denied Hodler's charge that this money amounted to
bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Two investigations of the Salt Lake charges are being conducted,
one by the IOC and one by the ethics panel of the Salt Lake Olympic
organizing committee. Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday
that the Justice Department's criminal division was reviewing the
matter amid reports that the scholarship fund was not reported on
federal tax forms.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has said that it will not take the 2002 Winter Games
away from Salt Lake City, which won in a landslide vote in 1995
over Ostersund, Sweden; Sion, Switzerland; and Quebec. But there
has been a furor here, and embarrassment over allegations of vote
buying is widespread.
</P>
<P>
   One Salt Lake City councilwoman reiterated her call for the
resignation of top local Olympic officials. A meeting of the
organizing committee's executive board is scheduled for Friday, and
members are under pressure to come forward quickly and openly with
details of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   One issue certain to be investigated is the employment of
Sibusiso Sibandze of Swaziland in the management-services office at
City Hall from Oct. 25, 1993, to Oct. 28, 1994, and whether that
was an attempt to curry favor with IOC members who determine which
city will hold the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Sibandze is the son of David Sikhulumi Sibandze, the IOC member
from Swaziland, said Ken Connaughton, a spokesman for Salt Lake
City Mayor Deedee Corradini.
</P>
<P>
   Connaughton said, ``As near as I can determine, no one knew'' of
Sibandze's family connections. He said there was no apparent
evidence that the internship was connected to the Olympic bid.
Sibandze worked for $6 an hour at City Hall while he was a student
at the University of Utah, where he received a bachelor's degree in
1995 and a master's degree in business administration in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Both Connaughton and the office of the university's dean of
students said they did not know whether Sibandze had attended
school on an Olympic-related scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake Olympic officials declined to discuss the matter,
saying they preferred that it be handled by the two current
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, details of lavish gift-giving to IOC members
continued to emerge. Welch said that ``two or three'' IOC members
had been given shotguns and pairs of skis.
</P>
<P>
   Browning Arms, the Utah-based maker of Browning shotguns,
acknowledged that Salt Lake Olympic officials had bought one
12-gauge shotgun in 1997 for $1,039.50, and said it was
investigating whether other guns had been purchased or donated. IOC
members are not allowed to accept gifts with a value of more than
$150.
</P>
<P>
   Welch and other Salt Lake Olympic officials have also
acknowledged doing what all bid cities do _ flying IOC members in
on first-class tickets, putting them up in the best hotels and
taking them to the nicest restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's largest health-care provider, Intermountain Health Care,
has also said that at Welch's behest three people with apparent
Olympic connections were given medical services ranging from
treatment for hepatitis to eye surgery to a knee replacement at a
total cost of $27,675 in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Welch said that he and other Salt Lake Olympic officials were
simply playing by the long-accepted rules of the bidding game, and
that IOC members were wooed as if they were corporate executives
who might relocate their headquarters to Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we did anything that was different'' from other
bid cities, Welch said. ``It is a process of wining and dining and
building relationships. I don't know any other way you could have
done it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said reports of bribery were ``way out of proportion'' and
that ``anticipation far exceeds reality.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   IOC members have long had a reputation as elitists whose votes
can be bought with gifts and favors, but as many as 40 of the 115
members have become so concerned about that reputation that they
have stopped visiting cities bidding on the Olympics, according to
Dick Pound, an influential IOC member from Montreal who is
conducting the investigation of Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an uncomfortable feeling,'' Pound said. ``I don't want
people to look at me sideways when they see I'm an IOC member.
There's no reason to put up with it. Some of us are so concerned
with the perception, we don't go.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough IOC members do visit, however, that the reputation
persists. Howard Peterson, a former president of the U.S. ski
federation, said that Welch and another high-ranking Salt Lake
Olympic official, Dave Johnson, complained to him in 1990 or 1991
about being placed in an uncomfortable position by members of the
IOC over expensive jewelry and airplane tickets.
</P>
<P>
   One incident, Peterson said, involved the failure of an IOC
member to reimburse Salt Lake officials for the purchase of a
$10,000 diamond brooch. The other, he said, involved a complicated
scheme by which IOC members stood to make thousands of dollars by
redeeming airline tickets provided by cities seeking to hold the
Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were clearly irritated'' over what they considered IOC
pressure, said Peterson, who served in various leadership positions
at the ski federation from 1981 through 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Welch denied ``absolutely, categorically'' that these events or
conversations with Peterson took place. Johnson did not return
calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Deeda Seed, a councilwoman, said that for more than a year she
had heard rumors about a scholarship fund, but that they were
denied by Welsh, Johnson and Frank Joklik, the current president
and chief executive officer of the Salt Lake organizing committee.
She called for the resignations of Johnson and Joklik. Welch
resigned last year after pleading no contest to a charge of spousal
battery.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys need to go,'' Seed said. ``This is the epitome of
the corruption that has crept into the Olympic movement. It's not
about the glory of sport; it's about the glory of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake lost by four votes in 1991 to Nagano, Japan, to hold
the 1998 Winter Games and appears to have concentrated on wooing
the votes of African IOC members for the vote in 1995, which
awarded Salt Lake the 2002 Winter Games. Approximately 20 IOC
members are from Africa and they can form a powerful voting bloc.
Africans were most of the recipients of Salt Lake's $400,000
scholarship and training program, officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake scandal broke in November when a local television
station reported a leaked 1996 letter from Johnson discussing the
final tuition payment of $10,000 to Sonia Essomba, the daughter of
an IOC member from Cameroon who attended American University in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Rene Essomba, who died this year, was head of the
association of Olympic committees in Africa and exerted
considerable influence. Salt Lake officials have described the
scholarship money for Essomba's daughter and others as humanitarian
aid, not an attempt to buy votes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that have angered many here is that Salt
Lake's bid for the 2002 Winter Games was technically superior and
stood a strong chance to win on merit alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say we had to do this because everybody else was doing
it, but we don't ever have to be immoral or unethical,'' said Henry
Marsh, a four-time Olympic steeplechaser and a member of the Salt
Lake organizing committee's board of trustees. ``If somebody broke
the rules, they've got to be held accountable. Paying for
scholarships for relatives of IOC members is not humanitarian aid.
If you stretch the definition that far, you have stretched
definitions farther than President Clinton has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
