<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5883 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-NY-TIPS-$ADV20-AR     12-17 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-NY-TIPS-$ADV20-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS: GREASE FOR THE GEARS OF CITY LIFE  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Wash., Conn., Ill., Nev.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of what to tip the help in Manhattan is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When toting up expenses to determine New York City's
sky-high cost of living, don't forget to include the tip.
</P>
<P>
   Not just the bucks doled out each day to cab drivers and coffee
jockeys. It's those year-end holiday checks to doormen and dog
walkers, porters and parkers, nannies and dry cleaners and barbers
and personal trainers that really add up.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, people in other cities tip the help, too, but an informal
canvas shows that the tab in the Big Apple is as outsized as most
everything else.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that follows the pattern of higher wages. House
cleaners all over the country, for example, generally get an extra
day's pay for the holidays. For Virginia Dangerfield in Sun Valley,
Nev., that means $35, but for maids in Manhattan, it is closer to
$100.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, New Yorkers pay more because more people have
their hands out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a steady group of people in your life who help your
life run _ and that's what living in New York is about _ then you
have to show your appreciation,'' says Kathy Braddock of the
Intrepid New Yorker Co &UR; . &LR; , a consultant that helps people adjust to
life in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Braddock said the $100 she gives her Upper East Side doorman
more than pays for itself. If she's running late, for example, she
just calls and asks him to drop a quarter in her parking meter to
avoid a $55 ticket. ``It's amazing that you can sit in your home
and they deliver your liquor, they deliver your laundry,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Braddock estimates that she spends about $1,500 a year on
tips, far more than on Christmas gifts for her husband and two
children. In contrast, Jean Gamble, a management consultant who
lives in a high-rise in Chicago's Gold Coast area, puts her total
at $350. And even that dwarfs the largess of Judy Skillman, a poet
and professor in suburban Seattle, who slips maybe $20 to the house
cleaner, end of story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm stingy, maybe I'm Scrooge,'' Ms. Skillman said. ``I
just never think of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside New York, frugality rules. Sherman Reiner, a retired
sweater salesman in Stamford, Conn., gives the paper boy, mailman
and garbage collectors $10 each. He raised it from $5 about 20
years ago. ``I didn't take the cost of living into account,'' he
said. ``I also don't give them vacations.''
</P>
<P>
   While most people interviewed in Chicago, Seattle and Nevada
said they tipped out of guilt or habit, many New Yorkers were
motivated by fear. At one Manhattan parking garage, the holiday
tote board shows that the guy in space 41 gave $450; other regulars
might well wonder what might happen to their cars if they failed to
return the envelopes left on their windshields. Likewise, some
veteran city dwellers say, &UR;  &LR; ignore the Christmas card from your
building's superintendent at your peril.
</P>
<P>
   Building staffs prefer cash, of course. ``Cookies are for kids,
not for me,'' said Michael Grabsky, an Upper West Side doorman. But
etiquette experts say other service personnel should get a personal
gift, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gamble gives her hairdresser Champagne or some soaps. ``If
you don't tip your hairdresser, you'll be bald,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The transactions, however, can be complicated. ``I used to make
bottles of quite powerful eggnog, but it's hard to know now,'' said
Frank Gould, who owns three ranches along the Nevada-Utah border.
``Half the world has problems with spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Gould is giving his 10 ranch hands winter jackets and
sending them to the annual Cowboy Poetry Gathering in Elko, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Some people insist on the personal touch. George Gorham, a
doctor who lives in Manhattan House, a block-long building on the
Upper East Side, hand-delivers about 25 checks to the staff instead
of giving a lump sum to a fund that distributes contributions.
 &UR;  &LR; Workers in service industries say they rely on tips to make ends
meet _ but also spend some of the loot on holiday gifts or on tips
to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't thought a lot about holiday tipping until I became
this kind of worker,'' said Mrs. Dangerfield, the house cleaner in
Nevada. ``Now I give Christmas bonuses to the garbage collector,
the newspaper deliverer and the recycling guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write them a nice thank-you card, too,'' she added. ``When
you do work that's at the lower end of the social order, your own
dignity can take a battering, and the sense of appreciation is even
more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Newman, who runs Mitchell's Newspaper Delivery Service, a
Manhattan company with 40,000 customers, remembers the tips he
received as a paper boy on Beekman Place when he was 9, including
shirts from a woman who owned a clothing company; shaving lotion
from Lee Bristol, a former head of Bristol &AMP; Myers (now
Bristol-Myers Squibb), and $100 from Irving Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Newman's company sends out a collective Christmas card and
splits the proceeds among the drivers. Most tips range from $10 to
$50, he said, though he got one for $1 this year and another for
$400.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started out saying on the card, `This is not a
solicitation,' '' he recalled. ``One or two people a year say, `Yes
it is.' They're right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
