<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5888 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-17 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP TO BEGIN HISTORIC IMPEACHMENT DEBATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans on Thursday announced their
intention to begin a historic impeachment debate Friday morning
despite Democrats' accusations that it was irresponsible to
consider removing the commander in chief while U.S. forces were
dropping bombs on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the debate, set to begin at 10 a.m. EST, even many
Democrats concede the president is likely to become only the second
president in U.S. history to be impeached by the House.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton faces four articles of impeachment on perjury,
obstruction of justice and abuse of power, stemming from his
efforts to conceal a sexual relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Capitol, Democrats and Republicans jousted over the
procedure for the debate. Democrats refused to agree to a
Republican proposal to have a 16-hour debate over two days, with a
vote on the four articles of impeachment Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders responded that they would fall back on
established procedure, which calls for a vote after one hour of
debate.
</P>
<P>
   The House could extend the debate each hour if the majority of
the members approve. A vote to impeach would send the matter to the
Senate for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., dashed any hope of a
quick end to the ordeal by ruling out suggestions that the Senate
might move to censure the president rather than hold a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be any deal making. The Senate has to go forward
with a trial,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Speaker-designate Robert Livingston, R-La. said
that his chamber must proceed with the impeachment debate because
the voters want the matter dealt with and no one could predict how
long the military action may take.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terribly unpopular item,'' he said. ``Nobody wants
to deal with it. But we must deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the incoming speaker may have further clouded the debate
when he chose to admit to the Republican caucus Thursday night that
he had been unfaithful to his own wife of 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   Most members said Livingston's confession was not likely to
change any votes on impeachment, though some thought it might
affect the tone of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston already had agreed to postpone by one day the
impeachment proceedings, originally scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been under severe pressure from GOP colleagues who
are furious with Clinton for launching the military strike a day
before impeachment proceedings were to begin.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats fired back that beginning debate while military
action is under way would be demoralizing to U.S. troops and would
send a dangerous message to Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas, said he envisioned split television
screens ``showing bombs being dropped while Republicans are saying
you can't trust this commander in chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., charged that Republicans were
guilty of trying to undermine the president's job as commander in
chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``In times of war anyone who conspires against the commander in
chief, that comes a lot closer to high crimes and misdemeanors than
where the president's hands were at any given moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, seized on Clinton's comments that the
impeachment debate would not affect his intention to complete the
military action in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   And some lawmakers dismissed the suggestion that servicemen
would be affected by events in Washington
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Vietnam coming down in a parachute I didn't give
a rat's rear what Congress did,'' said Rep. Duke Cunningham,
R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The wrangling over the timing of the impeachment debate capped
another surreal day in the nation's capital as the grave realities
of the bombing of Baghdad clashed with the partisan maneuvering
over efforts to remove the president.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Capitol several thousand people protesting the
impeachment listened to civil rights leader, the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, and others attack Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did in the House Judiciary Committee was a toppling of
the presidency of the United States. There was no fairness. There
was no integrity,'' said Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, a member of
the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bickering over timing it has become increasingly
clear what the outcome will be as most of the moderate Republicans
whom the White House had hoped would side with the president have
indicated in recent days they will vote to impeach. On Thursday two
more GOP lawmakers, Rep. Steve Horn, R-Calif., and Rep. Heather
Wilson, R-N.M., said they would vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Barney Frank, D-Mass., a member of the Judiciary
Committee and staunch supporter of the president, conceded, ``it
looks pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank was one of the few Democrats who said it did not matter to
him when the impeachment occurred saying, ``I don't think it makes
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Public polls taken Thursday night showed that feelings about
impeachment had not changed as a result of the Iraq bombing. As
before the bombing, most of those surveyed opposed impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   While the moderate Republicans said they were voting their
consciences and had not been pressured by their leadership, Frank
said they were succumbing to ``right-wing pressure.'' He said that
many feared a primary challenge from conservatives if they vote
against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Those who gathered outside the Capitol vowed to return for the
Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just angry,'' said Doug Reimel, a 30-year-old computer
analyst of Sterling Va. ``Angry that even though what Clinton did
is despicable, it is by no means worth dragging the country through
this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a coup d'etat by the conservative right wing,''
said 74-year old Betty Fenton of Lancaster, Pa., who noted that she
had not been to a demonstration since her son returned from the war
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
