<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE DECIDES TO GO AHEAD WITH IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House leaders cleared the way Thursday for
President Clinton's impeachment, scheduling the historic debate for
Friday despite scathing dissent from Democrats about deciding
Clinton's fate during the US attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The move preceded another bizarre twist in the impeachment saga,
as the House speaker-designate, Robert L. Livingston, Thursday
night disclosed to the 228-member Republican caucus that he has
engaged in adulterous affairs during his 33-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Both developments foreshadowed an extraordinary session Friday
when the House debates whether Clinton is fit to remain in office
in the face of four impeachment charges stemming from his
extramarital affair with the former White House intern, Monica S.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, there will be turmoil and chaos on the House
floor,'' said Representative William D. Delahunt, a Quincy Democrat
who opposed Clinton's impeachment as a member of the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The House will vote on the four articles of impeachment Friday
or Saturday, depending on the outcome of a parliamentary protest by
Democrats who accuse GOP leaders of trying to bring down the
president at the possible expense of military morale and national
security.
</P>
<P>
   The procedural skirmish erupted as lawmakers in both parties
predicted the House will send at least one impeachment charge to
the Senate for the first presidential impeachment trial in 130
years.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown also formed the backdrop for charges and
countercharges over the timing of the attack on Iraq. Lawmakers in
both parties tossed about terms like ``treason,'' ``treachery,''
and ``high crimes and misdemeanors,'' referring either to
colleagues or to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to believe that if we have this debate while bombs
are being dropped . . . that we do not invite some action on the
part of our enemy to take advantage of this situation at the cost
of our men and women in uniform,'' said Representative Patrick J.
Kennedy of Rhode Island, a member of the National Security
Committee and chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, several hours before his stunning personal
disclosure Thursday night, said the House had a constitutional duty
to act on the impeachment charges despite the military assault on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need to go forward Saturday,'' Livingston said on
the House floor. ``Let's not prolong the harm to the country by
hanging the issue out in this body.''
</P>
<P>
   In the showdown, Democrats blocked a plan by Republican leaders
to hold 16 hours of debate Friday and Saturday on the impeachment
charges: two counts of perjury and one count each of obstruction of
justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, GOP leaders said they would pursue several options,
including a bipartisan compromise to extend the debate longer than
the one hour that is permitted under the House rules.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a deal, Republican sources said, they will use an
unspecified parliamentary procedure to expand the debate throughout
the day, with votes on all four charges likely Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is scheduled to start Friday at 9 a.m., although it
could be delayed an hour or more as party leaders engage in final
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the House Democratic leader, Richard A. Gephardt, showed
little willingness to yield, saying he would object to staging the
impeachment debate ``Saturday or the next day or any day'' while
the attack on Iraq is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they also plan to exploit the parliamentary
arsenal to protest the refusal by House leaders to permit a vote on
an alternative to impeachment, such as censure.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of the leadership's resistance to the censure option,
Representative Amo Houghton, a New York Republican who had
discussed his censure proposal Wednesday with Clinton, Thursday
withdrew it in futility, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic whip, David E. Bonior, a Vietnam veteran from
Michigan, said he will file a motion to adjourn the proceedings
Friday until US military action has ended, an effort that
Republicans are certain to reject.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment debate, originally scheduled to start Thursday,
was postponed by GOP leaders so the House could pass a resolution
praising US troops participating in the attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   During the one-day political truce, Clinton continued to lose
the support of one Republican after another and picked up only two
of the remaining undeclared lawmakers. Notable among the GOP
moderates turning against him was Representative Stephen Horn of
California.
</P>
<P>
   Although members of both parties estimated that more than 220
lawmakers will support at least one impeachment charge _ 218 votes
are needed for impeachment _ a survey by the Associated Press
showed that 197 members favor impeachment, 192 oppose it, and 46
are undeclared or not disclosing their positions.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, White House officials held out little hope of Clinton
surviving the House vote. But they refused to concede publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately we think that members, when they go in to the House
of Representatives and cast one of the most important votes in
their life, if they move forward based on the facts, the
Constitution and the law, we don't believe the president will be
impeached,'' said White House spokesman Joseph Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution supporting the US troops in the Persian Gulf
passed 417-5, but the apparent consensus was hardly on display as
the debate unfolded for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, numerous Republicans had accused Clinton of
launching the air strike on Iraq to try to stave off impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on you for breaking the long-standing tradition that
leaves party politics at our nation's shores,'' said Representative
Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat on both the Judiciary
and National Security committees. ``Shame on you for playing into
the hands of Saddam, who clearly staged his latest act of defiance
to coincide with the impeachment process.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy went further. ``I think it actually borders on treason
to assume that this president would actually sacrifice men and
women in uniform for his own political objectives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Gerald B.H. Solomon, a New York Republican and
former marine, had blasted Clinton the night before, saying,
``Never underestimate a desperate president.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Representative Brad Sherman, a California Republican,
said: ``Never underestimate a desperate partisan whose lust for the
president's blood causes him to make statements which
unintentionally give aid and comfort to the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon and others retreated in part from their assault on
Clinton's motives. But they refused to grant Clinton more than a
one-day truce.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a crippled, weakened president, and he can't be damaged
any more than he is now,'' said Representative Tillie Fowler of
Florida, vice chairwoman of the House Republican Conference. ``The
American people want to get this over with.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's leading congressional foes, Representative Dan
Burton, an Indiana Republican, said the House had put off the
impeachment vote as long as it needed to by passing the resolution
praising the US troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting around here is not going to change anything,'' Burton
said. ``We might as well go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon and a battery of war veterans held a news conference to
defend the decision to proceed with the impeachment debate
</P>
<P>
   ``As a prisoner of war'' in Vietnam, said Representative Sam
Johnson, a Texas Republican, ``I remember Democrats calling for
Nixon's impeachment. I haven't seen a war of any sort that has
stopped the Congress of the United States from doing its
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats disagreed. Representative Maxine Waters, a California
Democrat, confronted Solomon on the House floor about his comments
the previous night, saying his remarks were ``unpatriotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Charles B. Rangel, a New York Democrat, drew on
language in the impeachment resolution to denounce some
Republicans. Rangel, who won a Purple Heart and a Bronze Star
during the Korean War, told reporters that the initial GOP
criticism of Clinton over the US military effort was tantamount to
``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel added: ``You can't separate the president from the
commander in chief. You can't salute him in the morning and lynch
him in the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Rangel and Waters expressed reservations about the
bombing of Iraq. ``I don't like it. I wish it hadn't happened,''
said Waters. ``But I'm not going to question the president. I
support these soldiers because they're in it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Don Aucoin of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
