r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-WEDDING-SPI &LR;      12-17 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-WEDDING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE ABANDONS FANCY WEDDING FOR HURRIED VOWS IN BASE CHAPEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACK HOPKINS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCHORD AIR FORCE BASE, Wash. _ Senior Airman Manolito Carrabis
and Faith Schuerch had a lovely wedding planned for Saturday _ but
President Clinton's decision to launch air strikes against Iraq got
in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Carrabis was told Wednesday night that he was likely to be
somewhere in the Persian Gulf when it came time to exchange his
vows this weekend. So the couple had a hurry-up wedding Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The bride wore white.
</P>
<P>
   The groom wore military fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   Carrabis, a 25-year-old former Las Vegas resident, was one of a
limited number of McChord-based airmen expected to be deployed to
the Persian Gulf as early as Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Carrabis and Schuerch decided on a quick wedding at one of the
base chapels after rejecting the idea of putting off their nuptials
until after his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been waiting for a long time to get married,'' his
19-year-old Spokane bride said. ``So it had to be now or never.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrabis' impending overseas deployment had come with so little
warning and their wedding was rescheduled so quickly that the
couple wasn't even able to reach the bridesmaid to tell her of the
change in plans.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerch made do without a bridesmaid.
</P>
<P>
   She also had to go through the ceremony without her father
walking her down the aisle. He's still flying in from California
this weekend. But now it will be for a visit, not a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   The couple told the chaplain they were ready to tie the knot at
the earliest possible minute _ whenever he was available to perform
the ceremony. And that was early Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplain Gary Ranson married the couple in a simple, double-ring
ceremony in a base chapel decorated with a Christmas tree, 12
poinsettias and eight wreaths.
</P>
<P>
   Then they kissed and hugged in what was to be one of their few
embraces before he was to leave for foreign soil in a time of
military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job,'' said Carrabis, a specialist in defenses against
nuclear biological weapons. ``I promised to defend my country and
that's what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll miss my family,'' he said, glancing over at the
couple's son nearby. Little Michael Carrabis celebrates his first
birthday on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The couple now must finish calling this weekend's wedding guests
and tell them the marriage ceremony already had been held.
</P>
<P>
   Carrabis was able to retain the services of his best buddy, Jeff
Berry, as best man. And his mother and several of the men and women
he serves with were on hand for the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   But it was nothing like what they had planned for this weekend _
lots of Christmas flowers, holiday music and a big spread of food
for the reception attended by lots of family members and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Those elaborate plans have been scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerch, who describes herself as ``a military brat,'' took the
situation with some stoicism yesterday. But that may have been
because she got most of the crying out of her system Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never easy. And it never gets easier,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what can I do? I can't go to the president and say, `Don't
take him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Carrabis and Schuerch met two years ago in Japan. He was
swearing about something and she turned around and chewed him out
for using bad language in her presence. He immediately apologized.
That chance encounter eventually led to yesterday's marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Carrabis, like thousands of military men and women across the
country, was ready to go do his duty for his country last night. He
wasn't happy about going. But he was willing to do his part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not scared or nervous,'' he said. ``In fact, I was fine up
until the 45 minutes of crying she did (Wednesday) night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
