<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5905 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-BO     12-17 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVINGSTON DISCLOSES INFIDELITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the most politically sensitive of moments, House
Speaker-designate Robert L. Livingston was forced to disclose
Thursday night that that at some time in the past he had been
unfaithful to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The man who is set to replace House Speaker Newt Gingrich said a
media investigation of his past had prompted the unusual
announcement, which came as he and other House Republican leaders
were trying to work out the rules for Friday's debate on
impeachment charges stemming from President Clinton's affair with a
former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana Republican made the disclosure to his House
Republican colleagues Thursday night after a Capitol Hill
newspaper, Roll Call, first reported the affairs on its Web site
Thursday. Livingston tried to draw sharp distinctions between his
behavior and the president's, saying in a written statement that
``these indiscretions were not with employees on my staff, and I
have never been asked to testify under oath about them.'' He said
the impeachment process would continue with no delay.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers said there was no call for Livingston to
resign at a party caucus Thursday night, and his colleagues had
given him a standing ovation and words of support after he read a
statement about his infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my 33-year marriage to my wife, Bonnie, I have on
occasion strayed from my marriage, and doing so nearly cost me my
marriage and my family,'' said Livingston, a 55-year-old father of
four daughters. ``I sought marriage and spritual counseling, and
have received forgiveness from my wife and family, for which I am
eternally grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure drew immediate criticism from groups working to
save the president from impeachment. ``The hypocrisy of the
Republican right wing that is driving this impeachment is
shocking,'' said Eleanor Smeal, president of the Feminist Majority
Foundation, a women's rights group. ``Mr. Livingston may not have
lied about his behavior, but he certainly fooled the public,
including voters in his district.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Livingston's announcement would not delay the
impeachment proceedings against the president, which they said are
based on Clinton's alleged perjury and abuse of powers, not on the
mere act of conducting an affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts haven't changed,'' said Representative Lindsey
Graham, a South Carolina Republican on the House Judiciary
Committee that drew up the impeachment charges. ``Bob's sins
haven't changed the facts. My sins haven't changed the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Richard Armey of Texas said, ``Previous
mudslinging tactics did not distract this House from its
constitutional duty. This most recent attempt will not prevent this
House from executing its duty to protect and uphold the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's disclosure follows recent confessions of affairs by
Representatives Henry Hyde of Illinois, chairman of the Judiciary
Committee that approved four articles of impeachment last weekend,
Dan Burton of Indiana and Helen Chenoweth of Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was selected by House Republicans on Nov. 18 to
replace Gingrich, but he does not take office until next month.
Livingston had served since 1994 as chairman of the powerful House
Appropriations Committee, and had emerged as the consensus choice
of Republican members dissatisfied with Gingrich's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said he would not discuss details of his affair or
affairs. ``Because these were personal relationships, I have no
intention or desire to reveal any specifics in order to avoid harm
to others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also did not reveal which media outlet had undertaken the
investigation. In October, Larry Flynt, publisher of Hustler and
other sex-oriented magazines, offered up to $1 million to anyone
who provided details of adultery by Repubican leaders and other
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston disclosed the infidelity during a GOP caucus that had
been called to discuss Republican strategy for Friday's impeachment
debate. Well into the meeting, according to people at the session,
Livingston rose and said his colleagues would soon be hearing
something unusual about him.
</P>
<P>
   He then read a statement and added: ``My fate was in your
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The response was applause and support, including encouraging
words from House Minority Whip Tom DeLay, people in the meeting
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus was on our loyalty and respect for Bob Livingston,
and the trauma he and his wife are going through,'' said
Representative Marge Roukema, Republican of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   She said Livingston was emotional but stoic in addressing the
GOP lawmakers. He spoke with ``the sincerity of apology,'' but ``he
didn't go into any quivering lips.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican conference is fully behind him and moving on to
the next piece of business, and the next piece of business is the
impeachment of the president of the United States,'' said one
congressional staff member.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Livingston has struggled in recent days to keep his
Republican colleagues unified behind him. On Wednesday night, he
had presided over a divisive meeting of Republican House members to
debate whether to proceed with impeachment while US forces were
attacking Iraq. Conservative members of the party wanted to vote
Thursday on impeachment, as leaders had originally planned, while
moderate members said it would be better to delay.
</P>
<P>
   With Gingrich absent, Livingston opened the Wednesday meeting
with a brief statement that his Navy experience told him it was
better not to open the impeachment debate immediately. He then
yielded the floor and listened to his colleagues for nearly three
hours.
</P>
<P>
   When the talking was done, Livingston's light touch had worked.
The Republicans deferred to Livingston, and the impeachment debate
was delayed for a day.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary Leonard of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
