<SLUG> BC-FBN-FLUTIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLS OWNER WILSON A BONUS FOR FLUTIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What the National Football League took away, Ralph Wilson gave
back. And then some.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful day for Doug (Flutie),'' said Boston-based
agent Jack Mula of the Buffalo Bills quarterback. ``He made the Pro
Bowl one day, and then the next, Mr. Wilson really took care of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 15, the officials took a victory away from Flutie and
the Bills with two admittedly bad calls at the end of the game in
Foxborough that set the Patriots up for a 25-21 comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   The decision dropped the Bills to 7-5 and could have cost Flutie
even more dearly. Assuming he's in for 70 percent of the Bills'
plays on the season, his contract calls for him to get $250,000 in
bonus money for each victory from the ninth to the 12th. So 12 wins
would be worth $1 million to Flutie, and in fact, that would be
doubled, because whatever he makes this year would be added to his
contract for 1999. The Bills now are 9-5, and the best they can
finish is 11-5, meaning Flutie can't reach the maximum bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but not so fast. Enter Bills owner Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke with the Bills (Thursday),'' said Mula, ``and they
wanted to rework Doug's contract for this season because the bonus
money we made to date was going to cause them a problem under the
salary cap. We said sure. They said in return for helping them this
year, they would add some money to next year's contract.''
</P>
<P>
   For doing them the favor and rewriting this year's contract now,
the Bills are giving Flutie another $500,000 on next year's pact.
And when Wilson heard about it, he told general manager John Butler
to give Flutie another $250,000 for the ``lost'' win in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Flutie would not have qualified for the bonus the way
this year's contract was structured unless he had been in for 70
percent of the plays, and that won't be the case unless he starts
and finishes the game against the Jets Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bills, elated by his performance, his Pro Bowl
selection, and the team's surprising success, have told Flutie not
to worry about the 70 percent. They're giving him the bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great story,'' said Mula. ``Doug signed for the
minimum ($300,000) for someone with his amount of time in the
league. We had more than 20 bonus provisions put on the back of his
contract that we didn't know that he would ever have a chance to
earn.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, he has earned $2,135,000 in bonus money. That inclues
the playing time, wins, passing yards, rushing yards, touchdown
passes. This will be added to his base pay next year, but he could
do better than that. The Bills told us that when the season is
over, they want to talk about a contract extension to make sure
Doug stays in Buffalo as long as he can still play.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the 36-year-old Flutie's conditioning and enthusiasm, that
could be another 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
