<HEADER>
A5911 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     12-17 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY SETS HIS STANDARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike other KCAL Channel 9 sports anchors who've left the
station in the last decade, Tom Murray doesn't figure to move on
and host ``Entertainment Tonight,'' begin a career as an
infomercial potato-peeling pitchman or scramble around as a weekend
fill-in at another L.A. outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Steines, Joe Fowler and Gary Cruz have their reasons for
doing those things. Murray, who finished a nine-year run with his
last ``Final Quarter'' desk shift Tuesday night, feels he has
personal and professional standards to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really want to know the job I've dreamed of since I was
a kid, it's to work for `60 Minutes,' '' Murray said. ``Doing that
kind of work, I have a better chance of separating myself from
what's become the `traditional' sportscaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray's departure shouldn't be interpreted as something similar
to what happened to KABC's Todd Donoho or Rick Lozano several
months ago. The tradeoff KABC made by not renewing cream-puff
Donoho or Lozano and replacing them with an even creamier puff in
Bill Weir was labeled ``a change in direction'' by the station
decision-makers. KCAL's battle with Murray's not wanting to be a
team player _ for what should be the right reasons _ goes back to
the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   KCAL head man Don Corsini wanted to dress up the nightly sports
reports on the Angels _ whose games the station carries _ by adding
a loyal advertiser's logo. He created the ``Angels Toyota
Clipboard'' highlight segment.
</P>
<P>
   To most polished sportscasters, it's a grin-and-bear-it,
I-get-a-nice-paycheck-and-would-like-to-continue-doing-so decision.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray balked.
</P>
<P>
   When his agent and station lawyers became involved, Murray
finally agreed to do it _ only during the '98 Angels season _ and
then instructed his producer to leave the logo on the screen for as
short a time as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, knowing Murray's contract ran out at the end of this
year, Corsini had a window to hire Alan Massengale, who worked
under him when they were at Prime Ticket. Massengale had been let
go by the Fox Sports News show because of erratic on-air
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Murray clearly saw the writing on the wall. But rather than quit
when he was demoted to two days a week behind colleague John
Ireland, Murray rode out the rest of his contract, freelancing as a
reporter for Fox Sports Net on ``Goin' Deep'' and Jim Rome's ``Last
Word.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray's run at KCAL started when Disney bought the station in
1990. He was turned loose to work with seemingly unlimited
resources for extended sports reports and documentaries on the then
three-hour weeknight newscasts. Murray did memorable pieces on the
dark sides of Raiders boss Al Davis, convicted Kings owner Bruce
McNall and USC-fired assistant athletic director Marvin Cobb. This
year, Murray's best piece was on Carson stadium financier Michael
Ovitz _ but that story was done for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Young Broadcasting bought KCAL two years ago but is rumored to
have been trying to sell it ever since. And while the 15-minute
``Final Quarter'' turns out to be the longest weeknight block of
locally produced sports news in L.A., it's seemingly treated now as
nothing more than the lead-in to the 11 p.m. ``Jerry Springer''
show _ and even then, the sports segment usually runs past the top
of the hour, so early Springer viewers are counted in the sports
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a much different place than it was nine years
ago,'' said Murray, trying not to sound bitter. ``Most of the
people there when I began are gone, so I'm just the latest in a
long line.''
</P>
<P>
   In a town where most other anchors _ sports or otherwise _
wouldn't think twice about crossing the line to help a sponsor,
Murray agrees that maybe his journalistic ideals don't fit here.
That's something former KTLA and KCBS sports anchor Keith Olbermann
also discovered before moving into the all-sports and all-news
network world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not optimistic about the future of sportscasting here in
the way I've tried to do it,'' Murray admitted. ``It's apparent
L.A. isn't the right place to do it. Here, there are guys who are
not so much trying to inform but entertain. I believe I can do both
but not in the way entertainment is being emphasized. A lot of that
kind of stuff wouldn't be tolerated anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hoop it up: Any resemblance between the Lakers' famed
``Showtime'' to what they're calling ``The Game on Showtime''
Saturday night _ live from Atlantic City, N.J. _ is purely comical.
</P>
<P>
   For what's been reported as a $1.5 million rights fee, Showtime
will provide its 18 million viewers with a broadcast of this NBA
exhibition/infomercial that so far includes no Lakers or Clippers
players _ or Michael Jordan. L.A.'s only link will be participation
from famed sports-talk show host and squirrel hunter Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime's Jay Larkin, more adept at promoting boxing events for
the premium channel (which is a bit less sports-savvy than HBO),
says other cable outlets and networks were offered the game.
Showtime was able to clear out a movie or two to televise it and is
trying not to appear to be acting as an influential partner in the
NBA-lockout talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important for Showtime that we are understood
here,'' Larkin told a group of reporters on a conference call
Wednesday. ``People have been putting a cynical spin on this game
and this is unwarranted and without justification. . . . This event
was going to take place with or without our participation. We are
covering it as an event. The fans, we hope, will appreciate it and
won't watch it with any kind of political agenda. It's a basketball
game.''
</P>
<P>
   However. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving beyond this event,'' Larkin also said, ``it's a great
big question mark. We have to see how it performs as a television
product. If the season is not reinstated and there are more
opportunities to do games like this, we are certainly interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for game highlights on NBC or TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Lakers of the '80s are featured on the
reprocessed infotainment show ``NBA Inside Stuff'' that KNBC will
air on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see the real stuff.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   __ The Angels' decision to use Rex Hudler as its one-and-only TV
analyst for both KCAL Channel 9 and Fox Sports West took both
outlets by surprise. Each found out when Hudler blurted it out
during Jim Rome's radio show Wednesday. But the Hud Man's
enthusiasm will be contagious if he does the games as he does
interviews with Rome.
</P>
<P>
   __ I want my HDTV: Check out CBS' special high-definition TV
feed of Saturday's 10 a.m. N.Y. Jets-Buffalo contest at any of the
27 Good Guys stores throughout Southern California. Leave all
credit cards and checkbooks at home unless you can fight the urge
to walk out with an early Christmas gift.
</P>
<P>
   __ John Ireland hopes to have an agreement finished before he
leaves today on two-week vacation (for the holidays and to get
hitched) to remain with AM-1150's morning show for the first six
months of 1999. Partner Steve Mason, already committed to a radio
job in New York, signed off Wednesday. Ireland's new sidekick
hasn't been determined.
</P>
<P>
   __ Set the VCRs, pop in the cassette, recruits pay attention:
Cal State Northridge's basketball team gets a rare double dose of
media exposure Saturday night because it's playing playing UCLA
(7:30 p.m., Fox Sports West 2 and AM-1150). CSUN might want to stop
running those local cable-TV ads touting radio coverage of its game
Tuesday against James Madison. That was a pre-Paul Bubb departure
arrangement that ain't gonna happen now. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   __ Why get rid of Sparky Anderson? And why abandon Jerry Reuss?
Fox Sports West, for one, wasn't thrilled having to learn about it
from the Angels' move this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, we would have liked to keep him on
board,'' said Fox Sports West chief Kitty Cohen of Anderson, ``but
we respect Disney's desire to have the same analyst for both home
and road games.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Anderson understands. ``I never had a disagreement
with the Angels,'' said the future Hall of Fame manager who lives
in Thousand Oaks. ``They've always known I didn't want to do road
games. And for three years, it worked for me. Maybe I was a little
disenchanted thinking about doing 50 games (next season) and
driving an hour-and-a-half each way. But I knew they wanted just
one guy. And nothing against Rexy, but I wish Reuss woulda been the
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   There could be discussions soon about Fox using Anderson on its
regional Saturday game-of-the-week package as long as the game is
at Dodger Stadium or Edison Field. &QL; 
__ CBS might consider redefinition television for its ``NFL Today''
heading into the playoffs. Charisma-challenged George Siefert,
missing in action last week, will also be gone this weekend as
``insider'' Mike Lombardi cozies up with Marcus Allen and Brent
Jones. &QL; 
__ And why do we care so much about NFL pregame shows?
</P>
</TEXT>
