<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-TICKETS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Falcons playoff tickets are hot
   By Matt Winkeljohn
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Call it Falcon fever.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 90 percent of the Atlanta Falcons' 29,715 season-ticket
holders have reserved about 35,000 playoff tickets. The remaining
27,000 tickets will go on sale Saturday at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 2,000 fans have reserved playoff tickets by making
a $50 down payment on season tickets for next year, and another
8,000 tickets are handled by Georgia Dome officials and distributed
for other uses, including suites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that's a pretty good rate (of sales),'' ticket
manager Jack Ragsdale said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (12-2) have assured themselves of at least one home
playoff game, either the weekend of Jan. 2-3 or the weekend of Jan.
9-10.
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta wins at Detroit (5-9), it will clinch just its second
NFC West title and earn a first-round bye, meaning the first
playoff game will be on the weekend of Jan. 9-10.
</P>
<P>
   Camping out will be useless because fans will have their place
in line determined by a lottery drawing at 8 a.m. Saturday between
Gates A and D.
</P>
<P>
   In the lottery, fans will draw numbers out of a bucket to
determine their places in line. They can buy tickets for the first
playoff game without having to purchase at the same time $72
tickets for the second home playoff game, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum purchase will be 20 tickets per person. Tickets can
also be purchased by phone at 404-223-8000 or 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   The last home playoff game was Jan. 4, 1981, a 30-27 loss to
Dallas. Atlanta's only other home playoff game was a 14-13 victory
over Philadelphia on Dec. 24, 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
