</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Lions' injured Batch may still play Sunday
   By Matt Winkeljohn
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Detroit Lions rookie quarterback Charlie Batch, who
twisted his lower back in Monday night's 35-14 loss at San
Francisco, did not practice again Thursday, but coach Bobby Ross
has not yet ruled him out of Sunday's game against the Falcons
(12-2).
</P>
<P>
   Batch, who has stolen some of Colts rookie quarterback Peyton
Manning's thunder by amassing a 83.3 passer rating while starting
the last 12 games , was a second-round draft choice out of Eastern
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   When Ross benched Scott Mitchell in the second game, Batch took
over.
</P>
<P>
   He completed 16 of 19 passes for 218 yards and two touchdowns in
a 27-20 win over Green Bay Oct. 15, setting an NFL rookie record
with his .842 completion percentage for one game. He has a rating
of 83.5.
</P>
<P>
   The top three rookie passer ratings in history belong to Dan
Marino (96.0 for Miami in 1983), Greg Cook (88.2, Cincinnati in
'69), and Charlie Conerly (84.0, N.Y. Giants in '48).
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Batch has completed 173 of 303 passes for 2,178 yards,
11 touchdowns and six interceptions. He had a streak of 107
attempts without an interception and has a current streak of 136
passes without a pick.
</P>
<P>
   Batch also is a threat to run, with 41 carries for 229 yards
(5.5-yard average) and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who has tremendous poise for a young guy,'' Ross
said. ``He has an excellent mental approach to it. He knows where
to go with the ball most of the time, and that's the thing that has
surprised me the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Batch said he'll be able to practice today.
</P>
<P>
   In practice Wednesday and Thursday, 14-year veteran Frank Reich
got most of the repetitions with the No. 1 offense. Mitchell has
gotten some reps for the first time since his benching.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves release
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves, who has been recovering at Piedmont
Hospital since heart bypass surgery on Monday, is expected to be
released today, but will not go to Detroit. He may have a role in
preparing for the Dolphins game on Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   For all the fuss over Batch, the right shoulder of Lions' middle
linebacker Stephen Boyd is as big a deal. He's Detroit's leading
tackler, with 112 first hits and 43 assists to go with six passes
defensed, four sacks, three fumbles forced and three recovered _
even though he missed a game.
</P>
<P>
   He reaggravated a strained labrum at San Francisco and will not
play. He is scheduled to visit famed orthopedist James Andrews at
the Alabama Sports Medicine Clinic in Birmingham. Team doctors
anticipate surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lions rookie wide receiver Germane Crowell, who has
caught 25 passes for 464 yards, won't play either.
</P>
<P>
   His season may have ended Monday night as well. The
second-rounder from Virginia injured his shoulder in the midst of
his best game (five catches, 83 yards). That figures to take the
teeth out of the Lions' three-wide receiver set.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett to return
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta weakside linebacker Cornelius Bennett (sprained knee)
and left defensive end Lester Archambeau (broken thumb) were both
held out of practice again Thursday, but interim coach Rich Brooks
expects both to play.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett is waiting on a special knee brace after suffering a
unique tear to the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee last
Sunday at New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need to do surgery, but there is an old tear and a
new tear,'' Bennett said. ``The first tear is ... very, very rare.
I don't know when I did it, but it was sort of frayed. The knee is
stable, but it's sore.''
</P>
<P>
   Matchups
</P>
<P>
   It's likely that Falcons Pro Bowl cornerback Ray Buchanan will
match up chiefly with wide receiver Johnnie Morton (65 catches, 978
yards, two touchdowns) rather than Herman Moore (69 catches, 829
yards, four touchdowns in 13 games) because Morton is faster.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, Atlanta often will roll Pro Bowl free safety
Eugene Robinson toward Moore (6-foot-4, 210 pounds) who will be
covered by starter Ronnie Bradford (5-10, 188) or reserve Michael
Booker (6-2, 203).
</P>
<P>
   Moore has caught 20 passes in the last three games for 345 yards
and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Morton is 6-foot, 190 pounds, to Buchanan's 5-9, 198.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could easily be a Pro Bowl tandem if they had a
quarterback who could get them the rock,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Big numbers
</P>
<P>
   After combining for 14 catches, 307 yards and two touchdowns
last Sunday against New Orleans, wide receivers Terance Mathis (61
catches, 1,085 yards, 10 touchdowns) and Tony Martin (59 catches,
1,034 yards, five touchdowns) lead all NFL receiving tandems with
2,119 yards. That's more than Minnesota's Randy Moss (1,209) and
Cris Carter (906), who total 2,115.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, and perhaps Martin, could end up catching more passes
than any receiver on a Reeves-coached offense. Steve Watson caught
69 passes for 1,170 yards on Reeves' 1984 Broncos squad.
</P>
<P>
   Lotsa Lions games
</P>
<P>
   This will be the sixth consecutive year the Falcons have played
Detroit, and the fifth game in that stretch in the Silverdome.
Atlanta has lost five in a row in Detroit, including a 31-17 defeat
in 1988. The Falcons last won there in '86 by a 20-6 score. The
Lions hold a 20-6 edge over Atlanta, 12-2 in Detroit. Counting
preseason games in Detroit, the Falcons have played four games
there in two years. Atlanta won there 7-3 on Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Be wary of Barry
</P>
<P>
   Lions Pro Bowl running back Barry Sanders hasn't hurt the
Falcons as badly as he's hurt a lot of teams. In last year's
2,053-yard season, Atlanta was one of just two teams that didn't
allow him 100 or more yards in a season during which he set the NFL
record with 14 consecutive games over the century mark.
</P>
<P>
   He had just 33 yards on 15 carries against the Falcons in the
opener, a 28-17 Detroit win.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, 30, will continue his assault on the NFL record book
Sunday. He needs just five carries to move past Marcus Allen
(3,022) and into second place behind Chicago Bears Hall of Famer
Walter Payton (3,838) for carries in a career.
</P>
<P>
   He's currently second in NFL history with 15,133 rushing yards,
trailing Payton (16,726), and needs just total 10 yards from
scrimmage to pass Herschel Walker (18,168) and move into second
place behind Payton (21,803).
</P>
<P>
   Sanders also has 76 career 100-yard games to Payton's record 77.
</P>
<P>
   Double reward
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson's received a $25,000 bonus for being
voted into the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
