<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-REAX-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        WELDON QUESTIONS TIMING OF IRAQ ATTACK AND WILL IMPEACH,
FATTAH CALLS CRITICISMS OF MILITARY ACTION IRRESPONSIBLE
</HEADLINE>
    By Lisa Fine  
   c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 17 -- Rep. Curt Weldon announced he will vote
to impeach President Clinton and questioned the timing of the
American attack launched on Iraq Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Weldon said President Clinton had several other opportunities to
order an attack on Iraq since November, but chose to do it on the
eve of the scheduled impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   After the announcement of the attack, House leaders decided to
postpone until Friday the impeachment debate originally scheduled
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Chaka Fattah, D-Philadelphia, who will vote against
impeachment, called anyone who would criticize the timing of a
military attack, ``irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Weldon, R-7th District, made a statement in a closed-door House
meeting Wednesday that called the timing of the attack on Iraq
``suspiciously coincidental,'' his spokesman Pete Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Fattah said he thought comparisons to the situation in the movie
Wag The Dog, which is about a president who stages a war to divert
attention from a sex scandal, are ``insulting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider the U.S. military a dog to be wagged,''
Fattah said. ``There is sufficient evidence that this attack was
needed, that should quell any questions raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Fattah said he felt the military attack wouldn't change any of
his colleague's votes on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans have the votes,'' Fattah said. ``Their
rabid desire for political lynching will have to wait a day. They
are upset about an inconvenience of having to delay the inevitable
partisan impeachment of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fattah said he believed even if the House votes to impeach
Clinton, sending the case to a trial in the Senate, there were not
the 2/3 votes needed there to convict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Weldon said he made his decision to vote to impeach Clinton on
charges of perjury and abuse of power because the president should
not be above the law.
</P>
<P>
   Weldon said he was unsure whether Clinton should be removed from
office and viewed the House vote as a public rebuke of the
President's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As difficult as it may be for our nation, I think that the
President must face the consequences of his actions,'' Weldon said.
``To simply overlook any President's violation of the law would set
a terrible precedent for future generations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
