<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOMEZ MIGHT RIDE INTO ELITE CIRCLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ At Southern California racetracks, it's not
only the horses that go round and round. So do the jockey titles.
</P>
<P>
   They are passed around among a select circle of riders, the same
handful of Hall of Famers and Eclipse Award winners and Kentucky
Derby stars taking turns leading the local standings season after
season.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett Gomez won his 21st race of the Hollywood Park season
Thursday aboard Dramatic Gold and will go into the last four days
of the meet with a two-victory lead over Alex Solis. If Gomez holds
on, he'll certainly break the monotony. There hasn't been a
first-time titlist on the Hollywood-Santa Anita-Del Mar circuit
since 1994, when Corey Nakatani broke through at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the ideal place for racing,'' said Gomez, 26, an
Arizona native and second-generation jockey who moved west 13
months ago from the shrinking Illinois circuit. ``It's got the
ideal temperature, it has the best horses in the country and it has
the best money.''
</P>
<P>
   And for all those reasons it has the best riders, as many
out-of-staters before Gomez learned the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, who has ridden in a meet-high 114 races, is ahead at
Hollywood in part because perennial local leaders Solis, Nakatani,
Chris McCarron, Kent Desormeaux and Gary Stevens have been out of
town a lot.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not to minimize his achievement. He came here without
a big name and has to overcome personal setbacks _ a 1995 divorce
and battle with alcoholism _ that nearly caused him to quit riding.
He went through rehab again earlier this year after a brief slip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up,'' Gomez said while eating a bowl of watermelon and
oranges in the jockeys' room Thursday. ``It made me pick up my
head, take a look at myself and not take anything for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the new house I've bought (in Arcadia) and realize
how far I've come . . . after I pretty much threw everything
away.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: Garrett Gomez and 6-year-old River Keen will go
for their second straight win together Sunday. They'll face Puerto
Madero and as many as five others in the Native Diver Handicap, the
highlight of Hollywood Park's closing weekend. The 31-day meet ends
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   River Keen was claimed for $100,000 out of his front-running
victory Dec. 4 by trainer Bob Baffert. The Irish-bred is 3 for 4 at
Hollywood Park, starting with the 1997 Californian, run at this
1[-mile distance.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's biggest contests might be quarterhorse races in
Orange County. The $1,114,605 Los Alamitos Million Futurity on
Saturday will be the richest race in California _ for any breed _
this year. The $350,000 Champion of Champions on Sunday features
six of the top eight quarterhorses in recent rankings, including
defending champion SLM Big Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   __ Risky business: The National Thoroughbred Racing
Association's 11-race series next year will offer some eye-popping
bonus money. Curiously, though, a horse will have to finish in the
top five in the Aug. 29 Pacific Classic at Del Mar or his owners
will collect none of it.
</P>
<P>
   That rule is meant to insure a solid field for the Del Mar race,
which is the series finale and one of five to be televised on ABC.
The rest are being scheduled for Fox Sports. The problem is that it
ensures nothing, and it could inspire an owner to run an injured
horse in the Pacific Classic, hardly the image the NTRA wants to
show the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California fans will remember when an off-form Luthier
Fever was entered in the Pacific Classic a few years ago just so
his owners could satisfy the conditions of a bonus offer.
</P>
<P>
   And the money will be bigger in the NTRA series _ $5 million for
a horse who sweeps the five ABC races, $1 million for winning four
and $500,000 for winning three, as long as one of the wins comes in
the Pacific Classic. Beyond that the bonus formulas get pretty
complex.
</P>
<P>
   The series starts with the Jan. 30 Donn Handicap at Gulfstream
Park and includes the March 6 Santa Anita Handicap and the June 27
Hollywood Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   __ Thumbs up: The surprise about Frank Stronach's statement on
the future of Santa Anita isn't that the new owner plans to remove
the distinctive turf hillside and paddock gardens to make room for
an entertainment and retail complex.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise is the mostly positive reaction from horse owners
and trainers, as reported by the Daily Racing Form. It probably
means two things.
</P>
<P>
   One: Horsemen, traditionally fearful of diversification and
seeing it as a step toward the paving over of racing ovals, realize
now that if track owners can't make more profitable use of their
hundreds of acres of peripheral land it will be bought by
developers who don't care about the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Two: Stronach, the auto-components magnate and major
thoroughbred owner who bought Santa Anita from Meditrust for $126
million last week, is trusted by the horsemen because they believe
he cares about the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach spoke with horsemen en masse for the first time at a
dinner in Pasadena Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita's first season under Stronach opens Dec. 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
