A5935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-TV-SPORTS-NYT &LR;      12-17 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN WEARS ROSE-COLORED GLASSES WELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bud Greenspan knows what's happening in the real world of
Olympic politics. The film maker knows that Mark Hodler, a Swiss
member of the International Olympic Committee's executive board,
has alleged that agents have offered to sell IOC members' votes for
payments from cities bidding to play host to the Olympics. He knows
that the Salt Lake Organizing Committee has said that during its
successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games, it paid nearly $400,000
in scholarships for relatives of IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard about the realities, but he prefers to make
idealistic films that extol athletic competition.
</P>
<P>
   Vote-buying? Steroids? Human growth hormones? All are topics for
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do controversy well,'' he said Thursday. ``I wouldn't
know how to handle it. I'm thankful I'm not involved in the
bureaucratic or commercial side of the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   His new film, ``Nagano '98 Olympics: Bud Greenspan's Stories of
Honor and Glory'' (Showtime, Sunday at 8 p.m.), typifies his style.
There are no disquieting words _ unless you count references to the
awful, event-delaying weather _ just tales of triumph by Bjorn
Daehlie (over a rival, the Norwegian cross-country skier Thomas
Alsgaard); Lu Chen (over self-doubt, loneliness and the intrusive
Chinese figure skating federation); the downhill skier Deborah
Compagnoni (over knee injuries to win her third gold medal in
successive Olympics) and the ski jumper Masahiko Harada (against
the memory of his indelible failure to make a crucial jump in the
1994 Lillehammer Winter Games).
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to spend 100 percent of my time on the 90 percent
that's good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than the positive images of victory and defeat that
Greenspan films, the best indicators of his unrepentant Olympic
romanticism are his emotional scripts. As the 17-year-old speed
skater Kirstin Holum took a slow, post-race lap around the rink
with Dianne, her mother and coach, the narrator Will Lyman said:
``Kirstin Holum _ one in a galaxy of distant stars who for a few
moments broke through the clouds for a brief visit and while she
was here, left for those who saw her, lifetime dreams of what might
have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Or: Compagnoni is a ``a woman of uncommon bravery and talent who
for more than a decade has risen to meet every challenge while
living each day by the very simple principle: one who is strong can
afford to be gentle.'' Brian Stemmle's near-victory in the men's
downhill until he missed a gate (losing to Jean-Luc Cretier)
exemplified valor, ``and those who possess it never know for
certain if they will have it when the next test comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan more than admits to being old-fashioned, and
uninterested in muckraking. Even if this film had no official
sanction _ this work is the official film of the Nagano Olympic
committee _ he would undoubtedly ignore the negative to seek
uplift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the lone survivor of idealism,'' he said. ``I might be
from another century. I like the Olympics to be two weeks of
fluff.'' He knows it can't be like that, but he can pretend.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is the blithe-hearted alternative to reports that
presaged Hodler's charges. In a 1996 segment of HBO's ``Real
Sports,'' the correspondent Frank Deford reported allegations that
bidding cities were pressured to give college scholarships to the
offspring of IOC members. Deford confronted an unresponsive Juan
Antonio Samaranch, the IOC president, with a charge that
Swaziland's IOC member demanded a scholarship for his son in return
for his vote for Falun, Sweden, to be the host of the Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, Bob Simon of CBS' ``60 Minutes'' described how
Nagano snared the Winter Olympics, and how, during the bidding,
Japanese interests donated $25 million to Samaranch's pet project,
the Olympic Museum, in Lausanne, Switzerland. More broadly, the
report outlined the financial largess cities lay out to bid for the
Olympics. Could a city get the Olympics without spending a fortune?
Simon asked Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will be not easy,'' Samaranch said. ``Will be quite
difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
