<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5936 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-LIVINGSTON-HNS &LR;      12-17 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-LIVINGSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVINGSTON ADMITS TO EXTRAMARITAL AFFAIRS ON EVE OF IMPEACHMENT
DEBATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the latest bizarre twist to the impeachment
saga, incoming House Speaker Robert Livingston admitted Thursday
that he has had extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The confession by the Louisiana Republican came on the eve of a
historic debate over whether the president should be impeached for
lying under oath about sex.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston acknowledged his adulterous affairs in a closed-door
meeting with Republican House members who had caucused to finalize
the details of the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have on occasion strayed from my marriage and doing so
nearly cost me my marriage and my family,'' he told stunned
colleagues, who applauded after his confession.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said he would not reveal specifics about the
relationships, but the weekly newspaper Roll Call, which broke the
story, said the affairs occurred during his congressional career.
Livingston was first elected in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman also told his colleagues that his
``indiscretions were not with employees on my staff, and I have
never been asked to testify under oath about them.''
</P>
<P>
   He was clearly drawing a distinction between his case and that
of the president, who allegedly lied under oath about an affair
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman also said he decided to acknowledge the affairs
after he learned that individuals working with the media were
investigating his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Flynt, publisher of Hustler Magazine, in October offered
$1 million to women who would detail sexual affairs with prominent
politicians, and there was immediate speculation on Capitol Hill
that Livingston's statement might have been an effort to pre-empt
Flynt's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Thursday night from Los Angeles, Flynt
said that he had Livingston ``under investigation as a result of
receiving tips from four different women. However, we have not
concluded that investigation and therefore cannot comment further
at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston vowed not to be intimidated by those digging up dirt
from his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This effort will not deter me from doing my sworn duty under
the Constitution as a member of Congress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston suggested that he has not been dishonest about his
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I did an early interview with the media after announcing
my candidacy for speaker, I told a reporter that I was running for
speaker, not sainthood. There was a reason for those words,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The incoming speaker did not specifically offer to resign but
told lawmakers: ``Ladies and gentlemen, my fate is in your hands,''
according to Mike Scanlon, a spokesman for House Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were pretty much mum about Livingston's confession,
although they strongly denied allegations by Republicans that they
were the sources of the stories about his extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not going to touch this one,'' said one Democratic leadership
aide when asked to comment.``It's just too bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who would comment said Livingston's admission would likely
not change the outcome of the impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans generally united behind Livingston. But a few
conservatives said it was fair to draw parallels between Clinton's
situation and the incoming speaker's.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on CNN's ``Crossfire,'' Rep. Mark Sanford of South
Carolina acknowledged that while Clinton may be subject to
``legal'' recriminations because he lied about his relationship
with Lewinsky, Livingston must also be held at least morally
accountable for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is he lied ... He lied to his wife,'' Sanford
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford suggested that some Americans might legitimately
question whether Clinton's accusers in the impeachment process _
the Republican majority in the Congress _ are morally qualified to
pass judgment on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awful for everybody concerned, and it does cloud the
issue (of impeachment), there's no doubt about it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But most of those who attended the caucus where Livingston
revealed his past indiscretions were supportive.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who has criticized Clinton for committing adultery,
defended Livingston at the meeting, according to Scanlon.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon said DeLay reminded those present ``that there are many
in this room who have sinned.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that DeLay talked to them about how to cleanse sin and
said, ``Bob has walked through the steps of contrition, confession
and cleansing, and we should all stand behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the GOP whip was not so charitable when at a
breakfast meeting with reporters he condemned Clinton's
extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a president who in my opinion has cheated on his
wife he will cheat on the American people,'' DeLay said last March.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., also defended Livingston, saying
that having an extramartial affair is not comparable to the perjury
and obstruction of justice charges leveled at Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Republicans were dumbstruck by Livingston's statement.
``He's so strait-laced,'' said a New Orleans GOP activist who is
friends with Livingston's family. ``It must have been going on in
Washington, because if we'd known we would have been gossiping
about it down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's disclosure of infidelity is the latest in a stream
of confessions by House Republicans caught up in the scandal fever
sweeping Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year it was revealed that House Judiciary Committee
Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who presided over the impeachment
inquiry, had an extramarital affair over 30 years ago. And one of
Clinton's fiercest critics, Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., admitted to
fathering a child out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
