<SLUG> BC-MINIMED-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMED SHARES HIT NEW HIGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Stock of MiniMed Inc. surged 8.7 &UR;  &LR; percent Thursday
for its fifth consecutive all-time high, buoyed by investor
enthusiasm over a diabetes control device that may hit the market
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Shares gained $7.25 to close at $90.25 on heavy volume, after a
gain of $3.50 on Wednesday. The recent jump was fueled by the
company's presentation this week at an ING Barings Furman Selz
conference about its microsensor for monitoring insulin levels,
according to Salomon Smith Barney analyst Melissa Wilmoth.
</P>
<P>
   ``MiniMed's been acting like an Internet stock,'' Wilmoth said,
noting that she had set a price target of $83 seven weeks ago when
MiniMed shares slid to $54. ``People thought I was out of my mind
at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed's microsensor is under review by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration. ``It would be a breakthrough technology in the care
and management of diabetes,'' said Wilmoth, noting the worldwide
market for diabetes monitoring devices is about $3 billion and that
the MiniMed machine could go on sale four years ahead of competing
devices.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Sylmar-based company, which has annual sales of
about $100million, is now perceived as a potential takeover
candidate. ``It's fairly clear to sophisticated investors that
what's driving the stock up is the anticipated approval and
takeout,'' Wilmoth said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, pacemaker producer Medtronic made a $30 million
investment in MiniMed.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
