<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FRESNO18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   Tark tries to forget `terrible' year
   By Jack Wilkinson
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When last seen last month in ``Between the Madness,''
a TV documentary that aired on Fox, Jerry Tarkanian _ patron saint
of the wayward point guard and, to some, the Father Flanagan of his
very own Boyz Town _ slouched in a despondent locker room and
muttered, ``Boy, I'm glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant the season, not the game. Actually, that loss, a 95-79
rout by Georgia in the NIT consolation game in March, was merciful.
It euthanized one of the most lurid basketball seasons in recent
memory. Between the ``Midnight Madness'' opening practice and the
season-ending ``March Madness'' was the madness that was Fresno
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bad year,'' Tarkanian called it. ``The hardest year I ever
had. We never had enough guys to practice. We were like a CBA team.
Three new guys every week.''
</P>
<P>
   The CBA usually loses players to NBA 10-day contracts, European
leagues or waivers. Fresno suffered a litany of ills: academic
ineligibility, failed drug tests, substance-abuse rehab, suspension
for assaulting a girlfriend, one starter quitting the team and
dropping out of school, another arrested for assault with a deadly
weapon _ samurai swords and a loaded gun _ and grand theft. All
chronicled in ``Between the Madness,'' nearly all blistered by Mike
Wallace in a ``60 Minutes'' report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a bad year,'' Tarkanian said. His third season
at his alma mater began with high expectations and ended
disappointingly with a 22-13 record, no NCAA bid and a soiled
reputation nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some really talented kids,'' he said. ``If we had made
better decisions off the court and stayed together on it, we'd have
been really good.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Tarkanian returns to Atlanta, where he first
coached in the 1977 Final Four. He stormed the old Omni that March
with Reggie Theus, three guys named Smith and the rest of a UNLV
outfit that was the most runnin, rebellious in the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real excited. First time I ever coached in the Final
Four. I had a really outstanding team that wasn't real well known
'til the tournament,'' said Tark, whose Runnin' Rebels lost 84-83
to North Carolina in that semifinal. ``At the same time, we were
battling the N-C-2-A. They did everything to make it hard on us.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Fresno State reacquaints itself with Georgia at the
Georgia Dome in the opener of the Delta Air Lines Holiday Classic
for Kids. This time, Tarkanian returns to Atlanta as a man who
sounds his age _ 68 _ and seeks to forget last season and forge
this one. He also sounds like a basketball coach with more typical
woes: No height. Little depth. And a severely sprained ankle that
has point guard Chris Herren on crutches and out of action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to be a good team,'' Tarkanian said
about his 6-4 Bulldogs. ``Like every year I've been here, a couple
of guys are (academically) ineligible. We're always short
something. We only have eight scholarship players. We're getting
killed on the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Fresno State took its worst beatings off the court.
When the university hired one of its most celebrated alumni in
1995, it knew what it was getting in Tarkanian: a coach who took
UNLV to four Final Fours, winning the 1990 NCAA title; a 695-162
record in his 28th season in Division I-A, five wins away from 700
games; No. 3 in all-time winning percentage (.811), second to
Kansas' Roy Williams (.819) among active coaches.
</P>
<P>
   It also knew it was getting Tark the Shark, the NCAA's most
repellent Shark and most frequent target, whose UNLV program was
the constant target of NCAA surveillance. The Rebels eventually
were put on probation and Tarkanian forced to resign in 1992,
although he later sued the NCAA for harassment and won a financial
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State also was well aware of Tarkanian's longtime
penchant for recruiting talented, troubled kids, giving second
chances to players who were transfers, academic casualties and/or
in trouble with the law. It all boiled over last season and
resurfaced Monday when Tarkanian was a character witness for
Avondre Jones, last season's center, who was suspended twice for
failing drug tests before he was arrested in March on charges of
grand theft and assault with a deadly weapon. On Tuesday, Jones was
convicted on two misdemeanor counts for threatening a man with a
samurai sword, a felony charge of having a gun while on probation
and a misdemeanor marijuana charge. But Jones was cleared of six
other charges and, while he faces up to five years in prison at his
sentencing Feb. 3, he is expected to get probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he straightens his life out,'' Tarkanian said. ``He's a
talented kid. He's as happy as could be; he thought it was
Christmas (on Tuesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' arrest was the most disturbing entry in last season's
tale of woe. ``Terrible,'' Tarkanian called the entire season. ``I
was really down.'' Yet asked what sort of image that season
projected to the public, what picture is left, he said, ``I don't
know. That's not my business. I know this: If other schools had the
same (random drug-testing and athletes' code of conduct) policy we
have, they'd have the same problems. I'm not saying that's bad that
we do. (But) we're the only one that enforced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only had two (criminal) incidents. One was Avondre, and he
was acquitted (on some charges). The other was Rafer (Alston).''
</P>
<P>
   A former guard who had been suspended for assaulting his
ex-girlfriend, Alston started last season and was drafted by
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Tarkanian asked, ``How many other players have problems with
their girlfriends?''
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Alexander did at Virginia, where he starred in 1996-97
before being found guilty of assault and battery on his girlfriend
in July 1997. He was set to transfer to Connecticut, but the
university refused to admit him; he went instead to Fresno.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has reconciled with his girlfriend. After redshirting
last season, he's now a starting guard and 18th in the nation in
scoring (22.1 points per game).
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Courtney,'' Tarkanian said. ``He got off to a slow
start. He was pressing, trying to do more things than he could. But
he's going to be a great, great player for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tark? How long will he coach at Fresno State, where he's
70-40?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any plans at all,'' he said. In March, he reached
a new agreement with the school on a one-year contract with options
on the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd get here and get this thing turned around in a
hurry,'' Tarkanian said. ``And we haven't. I've done a bad job.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
