<SLUG> BC-BKC-KENTUCKY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
   Kentucky gets its man as Evans steps forward
</HEADLINE>
   By Mark Schlabach
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After losing three starters and a key reserve from
last year's national championship team, Kentucky coach Tubby Smith
was looking for someone to step forward and lead the Wildcats this
season.
</P>
<P>
   He might have found his man in senior Heshimu Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Evans has led the team to a 9-1 start and the nation's No. 3
ranking entering Saturday's game against Georgia Tech in the Delta
Air Lines Classic at the Georgia Dome. The 6-foot-6 forward leads
the Wildcats with 15.5 points and 3.7 assists per game. He's also
second in rebounding at 6.2 and has emerged as Kentucky's top
3-point threat.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who redshirted during the 1996-97 season after
transferring from Manhattan College, was the Wildcats' sixth man
last year, averaging 8.8 points and 5.4 rebounds. The emergence of
Evans has been a pleasant sight for Smith, who lost guard Jeff
Sheppard, forward Allen Edwards and center Nazr Mohammed from last
year's team.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Mu' has always had this type of potential,'' Smith said.
``We were very fortunate in that we had a lot of depth at the wing
position (last season). This year, (Evans) has really stepped up.
He really worked hard on his ball-handling and passing, and that's
why he leads us in assists and scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Wildcats' 103-91 win over then-No. 2 Maryland in Rupp
Arena Saturday, Evans scored a career-high 31 points on 8-for-17
shooting with six rebounds. Forward Scott Padgett scored 25 and
guard Wayne Turner added 17 as Kentucky's seniors outscored their
Terrapin counterparts 73-31.
</P>
<P>
   Evans had 22 points in a 70-61 overtime win over then-No. 11
Indiana in Louisville on Dec. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also hopes Evans can become the Wildcats' top defender.
Edwards filled that role for Kentucky last season. At 6-5, Edwards
was physical enough to guard larger players but quick enough to
handle smaller guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to develop someone on our team that has a defensive
stopper mentality,'' Smith said. ``I think Heshimu can do that for
us because he's athletic enough to play multiple positions and he's
versatile enough to guard guys who are bigger and smaller than he
is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
