<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LASTTRY18-COX     12-17 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LASTTRY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
   Stern sends letter to NBA players
</HEADLINE>
   By Jeffrey Denberg
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NBA commissioner David Stern made a bold move in the
lockout Thursday with an open letter to players detailing
conciliatory issues in the league's latest proposal.
</P>
<P>
   In a direct appeal certain to infuriate union leadership, Stern
wrote, ``It is important that there be no doubt about the precise
terms you consider to be such a 'bad deal' that you would prefer to
lose the entire season.''
</P>
<P>
   The major points are:
</P>
<P>
   _ The league is no longer asking for a hard cap and has included
several salary-cap exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   _ There will be a Larry Bird exception available to all players,
subject to percentage limits.
</P>
<P>
   _ The league says it is willing to modify its ``timing rule'' to
benefit the league's middle class.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limits will be placed on the NBA's version of an
escrow-and-tax system to come into play in the fourth year of a
six- or seven-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   _ The NBA guarantees its players will remain the highest-paid in
sports. Figures the league used for the 1997-98 season show a
median salary of $1.68 million for NBA players, against $1.05 for
hockey, $430,000 for major-league baseball and $410,000 for the
NFL. The average NBA salary is $2.624 million, $1.375 million for
baseball, $1.1 million for the NHL and $910,000 for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Other key points in the lette:
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``middle-class'' salary exception will be allowed every year
to each team over the cap.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bird'' contract players will be allowed 12.5 percent annual
raises, with 7.5 percent raises to other players.
</P>
<P>
   Minimum salaries would start at $250,000, with $50,000 annual
increases to as much as $1 million for 10-year players.
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft picks will get three-year scale contracts,
with a team option for a fourth year and right of first refusal.
</P>
<P>
   The league would pay the union 50 percent of the proceeds from
NBA Properties but would eliminate the $25 million flat payment.
</P>
<P>
   Some unspecified salary-cap rules are subject to negotiation,
the league said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
