<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
   Moreland makes leap
</HEADLINE>
   By Earnest Reese
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ During his high school career in Atlanta, Earthwind
Moreland was known as a talented basketball player with an unusual
first name. Now, he's one of the top defensive backs on a team one
victory away from a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   When top-ranked Georgia Southern (14-0) faces Massachusetts
(11-3) in the Division I-AA championship game Saturday, the Grady
High graduate will be a key player. The road to the brink of a
fifth national title for the Eagles has been a long one for
Moreland, whose mother named him after the R&AMP;B singing group Earth,
Wind and Fire.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10, 179-pound Moreland, who has a time of 4.31
seconds in the 40-yard dash, joined the Georgia Southern program as
a walk-on and spent the early part of his career as a receiver.
After being switched to defensive back, he has made an immediate
impression, playing well enough at cornerback this season to be
named first-team All-Southern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first got here, Earthwind was the fastest player on
the team,'' second-year head coach Paul Johnson said. ``With his
speed, we felt like we should move him from receiver and play him
on the corner. I think he could play on the next level _ at least,
his speed is going making a lot of (NFL) teams look at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Moreland believes that basketball has helped him
progress in his football career. Moreland teams with safety Arkee
Thompson, another former basketball player who also played receiver
at Georgia Southern, to form one of the best secondary tandems in
the Southern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has team-highs of 140 tackles (65 solo hits) and eight
interceptions. Moreland has three interceptions, returning them for
102 yards, and also ranks among the team leaders in tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think basketball helped both of us develop our leaping
ability,'' Moreland said. ``And playing in the secondary is almost
like basketball. You've got to keep your feet moving and your eye
on the guy you're playing, then when the ball is in the air, you've
got to act like it's a rebound you're trying to get.''
</P>
<P>
   To defeat Massachusetts, a team that had to beat higher seeds
McNeese State and Northwestern (La.) State on the road to reach the
championship game in Chattanooga, Moreland thinks he and his
teammates will have to muster the same kind of effort they did last
week against Western Illinois. Despite the presence of 2,000-yard
rusher Aaron Stecker, the Eagles' first-line defense allowed only
one touchdown en route to the 42-14 victory over the Leathernecks.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Minutemen will present a different kind of problem
for the Eagles' defense. Quarterback Todd Bankhead has passed for
3,767 yards and 34 touchdowns; senior wideout Jimmy Moore, with 86
catches for 1,431 yards, and senior tight end Kerry Taylor (70,
832), have been Bankhead's most frequent targets.
</P>
<P>
   That potent passing attack should give the Eagles secondary its
toughest test of the season.
</P>
<P>
   However, Moreland appears ready for the challenge, especially
considering all the obstacles he has had to overcome to put himself
in this position.
</P>
<P>
   ``(UMass) has a 2,000-yard rusher (in sophomore tailback Marcel
Shipp) and some of the best receivers we've faced all season,''
Moreland said. ``We've got to play equally as hard as we did last
week to beat them and win the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
