</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PIONEER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
   Livingstone seeking vindication
</HEADLINE>
   By Earnest Reese
   c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Livingstone College coach Ruby Abrams has run the
final seconds of last year's inaugural Pioneer Bowl through his
mind perhaps a thousand times.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, though, the reality is the same _ quarterback Pernell
Wilder fails to score on two tries from the 1-yard line and
Livingstone falls short in a 30-26 loss to Kentucky State. But
Abrams and the returning veterans from the Salisbury, N.C., team
get a chance Saturday for atonement, facing SIAC champion Tuskegee
(9-2) in Pioneer Bowl II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a total of 18 players from that team, and quite
frankly, we didn't think we'd get back,'' said Abrams, whose 1997
squad included All-CIAA running back Wilmont Perry, now a member of
the New Orleans Saints. ``But this was a goal we set at the
beginning of the season _ to get back to the Pioneer Bowl, so we
could redeem overselves.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing to Virginia Union in the second game of the season,
and due for a date with conference favorite Virginia State two
weeks later, the Blue Bears' prospects did not look promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly had our doubts after the Virginia Union game,''
Abrams said. ``But we beat Virginia State (42-29) and began feeling
good about ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the fourth game of the season for Livingstone (7-3),
the smallest football-playing school in Division II. By that time,
such first-year players as running backs Carlton Jones and Ray
Chambers had adjusted. Freshman linebacker Rodney Hunt, the team's
second-leading tackler, and Shavares Thompson, who led the CIAA
with eight interceptions, were making major contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, sophomore quarterbacks D'andra Hopper and Anthony
Kilpatrick, operating behind veterans LaTeef Williamson (6 feet 5,
295), Gerald Hilliard (6-2, 282) and Charles Cooley (6-5, 292),
were effectively running a grinding offense.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been Perry's replacement in the Blue Bears' backfield
who has helped bring the team back to Atlanta. Tailback Carlton
Jones, a 5-9, 180-pound freshman, has rushed for 1,220 yards and 21
touchdowns, gaining 7.5 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very exciting runner _ strong and hard to bring down,''
Abrams said. ``Of course, (5-11, 200-pound freshman) Ray Chambers
has done a great job for us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, with a 6.0-yard-per-carry average, has 738 of
Livingstone's 2,913 rushing yards. Sophomore Shannon Gainey (5-11,
200) is another offensive producer. Along with his 457 rushing
yards, Gainey leads the running-oriented team in receptions with 17
catches for 232 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get him on the field, because he's such a great
athlete,'' Abrams said. ``The way all of those guys have played for
us, we feel pretty good going into this Pioneer Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
