<HEADLINE>
L.A. COUNTY AMONG TOP 5 IN ANNUAL PAYROLL GAINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As if more evidence were needed that the local
economy has been booming, government statistics released Thursday
show that Los Angeles County ranked among the nation's top five
counties in the number of new businesses and annual payroll gains
between 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While the numbers released by the U.S. Census Bureau are 2 years
old, local business officials say the trend has continued in 1998
and will likely extend into the future as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering that we were in a recession and emerging from an
earthquake, it shows the inherent strength of the Los Angeles
economy,'' said John Rooney, president of the Van Nuys-based Valley
Economic Development Center. ``I think it shows the beginning of
significant increases that you're going to see in this year and
probably the next several years.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the statistics, Los Angeles County gained 1,271
businesses, to 215,591 in 1996 from the prior year's 214,320 _ an
increase of 0.6 percent, placing it fourth among the nation's
counties in number of businesses added.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Los Angeles County ranked third in annual payroll
gains. Payrolls increased by $4.6 billion, or 4.4 percent, to
$109.4 billion from $104.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The county with the loudest business boom was Maricopa County,
Ariz., which was among the top five in terms of business and
payroll gains and topped the list of counties in terms of employee
increases _ a list on which Los Angeles County didn't appear.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the census statistics showed a 0.7 percent employment
decline in Los Angeles County, from about 3.494 million to 3.47
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just means that (businesses are) getting smaller and
smaller,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los Angeles
Economic Development Corp. ``There's a message here _ the idea is
that larger firms are getting to be endangered species.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
