r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-TEXAS-HIGH-SCHOOL     12-17 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-TEXAS-HIGH-SCHOOL-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
 
STEPHENVILLE, LA MARQUE SET FOR THIRD TITLE-GAME CLASH OF '90s 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEPHENVILLE, Texas _ In 1993, it was the Clash at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, it was the Dual in the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   So what should Stephenville-La Marque III, Saturday's 4 p.m.
Class 4A Division II state championship matchup, be remembered as?
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Stadium Tussle?
</P>
<P>
   The Joust at Jerry's Place?
</P>
<P>
   No M s: Yellow Jackets-Cougars III?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the third championship game meeting between
Stephenville (14-1) and La Marque (13-0) is billed, the teams now
seem inexorably linked as two of the top 4A programs of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Between them are five state championships, impeccable
reputations on offense (Stephenville) and defense (La Marque),
towns draped in football tradition and a general fear factor both
bring to most opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say about them?'' Stephenville coach Art Briles
said of the Cougars. ``Six times in a row in the state finals.
That's unheard of in any era. They're a tremendous program, and
it'll take all we have to have a chance to beat 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Since losing to Stephenville, 26-13, in the 1993 4A championship
in Austin and 32-17 in the 1994 title game in Houston, the Cougars
have been on a three-year steamroll. For Stephenville, the playoffs
ended in 1995 and '96 in the state quarterfinals and in last
season's second round.
</P>
<P>
   If a return to the final for Stephenville was imminent, La
Marque always seemed the most logical opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of friends who have been coaching a lot longer
than I have and just want to go to \Ra title game\S,'' La Marque
coach Larry Walker said. ``I've been in this business long enough
to know the cycle runs out and picks up. A case in point is
Stephenville. They bowed out and now they're back. We are going to
enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, a La Marque assistant from 1990 to '96 who became the
head coach at Port Arthur Jefferson for one season in 1997 before
returning to lead the Cougars, said La Marque's program has been
``blessed for six years with good athletes.'' But he added that the
school's cycle will also run its course eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Until that happens, La Marque is ``the'' 4A team of the Gulf
Coast and South Texas regions, as well as most of the rest of the
state. Stephenville, though, might feel otherwise if Saturday goes
as planned.
</P>
<P>
   A Stephenville victory would give the Yellow Jackets three
titles, tying La Marque for the most by a 4A team this decade.
Sealy's four consecutive titles in 3A are the most by any team in
the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed since Stephenville-La Marque II. The teams'
current players were in eighth grade or younger. Walker replaced
his former boss, Alan Weddell, who became a Texas A&AMP;M assistant.
Stephenville's offense looks more futuristic than it did in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things Coach Briles is doing are innovative,'' Walker
said. ``They're mind-boggling and good for the game. The young man
throwing now \RKelan Luker\S is throwing just as good as Branndon
Stewart did.''
</P>
<P>
   Where both coaches are concerned, the past is the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids now can't really identify with what happened in '93
and '94,'' Walker said. ``They don't have a recollection.''
</P>
<P>
   At least not as players. Several current Yellow Jackets have
recalled a deafening Astrodome in 1994's convergence of both towns
for the championship rematch. As much as Stephenville-La Marque is
about the teams, their fans have built reputations of being rabid
and noisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these players and fans helped elevate our program back
into the upper echelon,'' Briles said. ``It's everybody working
together to have a chance to turn a dream into reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Denison's three championship losses to La Marque (1995, '96,
'97) bred a postseason rivalry between the teams. This year,
Smithson Valley broke a five-year string of semifinals matchups
between La Marque and Corpus Christi Calallen.
</P>
<P>
   If familiarity breeds contempt, a third Stephenville victory
against La Marque might push the Cougars into a realm to which
Denison and Calallen can relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what I was coming back to,'' Walker said of his return
to La Marque. ``I didn't treat it as a big challenge. I knew the
expectations were very high here, not just from the school, but the
community as well.''
</P>
<P>
   A third title would meet similar expectations in Stephenville.
Win or lose, the Yellow Jackets' offensive theatrics and
state-record 8,267 total yards this season won't be soon forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna do the best we can to bring a state championship
home,'' Briles said.
</P>
<P>
   (Troy Phillips writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7377. E-mail:
tphillips(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
high school section on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
