<SLUG> BC-FBO-TEXAS-HIGH-SCHOOL-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING BACK ROUNDS OUT STEPHENVILLE ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEPHENVILLE, Texas _ Watching defenses chase after Zac Hunter
sometimes reminds one of those pig-chasing contests at rural family
reunions.
</P>
<P>
   The difference? Some of the pigs probably outweigh Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-8, 170 pounds, Hunter, a junior running back, is one
of the smallest Stephenville players on the football field. He's
also one of the fastest.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's 1,542 yards and 10 touchdowns rushing this season have
caused more nauseous moments for defensive coordinators than their
pregame meals. It's not simply that Hunter can shoot through the
narrowest holes or dart to the outside like a rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   As if the state's top passing game wasn't difficult enough to
defend, Hunter's speed makes a dizzying attack even moreso.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the linebacker's eyes to see what he's thinking,''
Hunter said of trying to read the defense. ``They're looking for
the pass, but they don't really know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter began outrunning everyone in about the seventh grade. He
improved his leg strength in the weight room and sprinter's speed
(4.4 seconds in 40 yards) in track season, where he runs the 100
meters and 200 meters and 400-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it's natural,'' Hunter said. ``A lot of it had to do
with making my legs stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore, Hunter said he ran mostly on instinct and
breakaway ability. This season, he was expected to block more and
learn the finer points of running routes as a fifth receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really, really quick,'' Stephenville coach Art Briles
said. ``The thing that makes Zac so good is he's so strong and
carries his pads well. His strength is what saves him from getting
beat up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter also stays fresh in Stephenville's system, one with
numerous no-back sets. Backups Jimmy Ferrazas and Matt Tinklenberg
are bigger backs _ both close to 200 pounds _ who give Stephenville
different looks on short-yardage downs.
</P>
<P>
   Like 100-catch teammate Cody Cardwell, Hunter's open-field
ability is a dagger. He lines up about anywhere; shotgun back,
either slot, far or inside wideout, blocking receiver, fullback,
tailback _ anywhere he can trip up a defense. As a receiver, Hunter
has 16 catches for 183 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zac and Cody are a lot alike,'' Briles said. ``They're just
different types of players.''
</P>
<P>
   On counter and trap plays, Hunter can be easy to miss. Against
Wichita Falls Hirschi, he shot through a hole before anyone saw him
and went untouched for 81 yards to break open a 42-21 Stephenville
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter also won a 9-yard footrace to the left pylon against a
pack of closing Hirschi defenders, none of whom were exactly slow.
He finished with 177 yards for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he's at the peak of his game,'' Briles said. ``He's
improved on reading his blocks and has really complemented our
passing attack. He's a speed guy, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   With several offensive starters graduating, Briles said Hunter's
role could increase next season. His understanding of
Stephenville's system has improved weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know what to expect next year,'' Hunter said.
``Last year, they said to just take the ball and run. This year
they've had me blocking and catching. It's a lot of work, but it's
been worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when you're rarely caught, like those pigs.
</P>
<P>
   (Troy Phillips writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7377. E-mail:
tphillips(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
high school section on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
