<HEADLINE>
MARSHALS SEIZE PIANO, ROLLS ROYCE FROM MICHAEL JACKSON'S PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB AND LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The grand piano that Michael Jackson used to
compose songs from ``Thriller'' and a classic Rolls Royce were
seized Thursday from the superstar's parents' home on orders from a
bankruptcy judge.
</P>
<P>
   A locksmith and U.S. Marshals broke through a wrought-iron gate
in order to haul away property from Joseph and Katherine Jackson.
It was at least the second time since a $1.7 million judgment was
levied against them and all but the most famous member of the
Jackson 5.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson family attorneys said the seizure was improper.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things belong to Michael. He's written songs on this
piano, including from the `Thriller' album,'' said attorney Brian
Oxman. ``He owns everything in the house. ... Michael wants his
piano back, and we're going to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   HVV Corp. of New Jersey claims it sold part of Kramer Guitars to
the Jackson family and is owed $1.7 million. HVV declared
bankruptcy in 1996 and received a judgment against the Jacksons,
although the family attorney claims they never got a chance to
defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.7 million is owed by Joseph, Katherine, Jermaine, Tito,
Randy, Rebbie and Marlon Jackson, said attorney Steven Fernandez,
who is representing HVV. But he said it has been very difficult to
collect because family members have either declared bankruptcy or
kept their assets in someone else's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, a lot of these Jacksons have financial
problems and IRS problems,'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Multimillionaire Michael Jackson, 40, is not one of the siblings
liable to HVV Corp. Oxman said that both seized items belong to
Michael Jackson and that he will get them back.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-room home on Hayvenhurst Avenue has been in the
superstar's name since 1993, Oxman said. But property records
indicate that both Michael and his sister La Toya jointly own the
home.
</P>
<P>
   The marshals took action after a Dec. 10 court order from U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Kathleen March directing them to ``use whatever
reasonable force necessary to break open and enter the premises of
the Jackson family home.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshals had a locksmith break through a black towering gate
that hides the 10,476-square-foot home nestled south of Ventura
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   A woman inside the home allowed officers in the front door to
seize a grand piano and an inoperable white 1963 Rolls Royce Silver
Cloud, said Robert Sainburg, who also represents HVV.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and onlookers had the same question Thursday as they
watched marshals seize property from the estate: Can't the Gloved
One hand his parents a check?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think Michael would cut them some money,'' yelled out
one neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor said she's grown accustomed to the commotion
over the Jackson's financial woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen this happen before, so I figured it was happening
again,'' said Mary Giltner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't made any efforts to pay it. ... We had to
forcefully collect,'' Sainburg said as a towing company hauled away
the classic 4-door vehicle with large white-wall tires on a flat
bed at about 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   But Oxman argued that the Jackson family had no idea about the
default judgment because when court papers were served at the home
in 1996, the family had moved out for two years for the home to
undergo earthquake repairs.
</P>
<P>
   They learned about the case in September, when marshals came to
seize another Rolls Royce at the home, he said. &UR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
