<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PROMOTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TRACKS PUT BURDEN ON NASCAR SCHEDULE, PROMOTERS SEEKING
REVENUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Eddie Gossage admittedly is running out of
options to ``feed the monster'' that is Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage, executive vice president and general manager of TMS,
has upgraded the track's schedule for 1999 with the additions of
the Pep Boys Indy Racing League season-finale and a second NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series night race in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case in 1998, TMS will offer three major race
weekends to its ever-expanding base of season-ticket holders. That
figure, Gossage said, is approaching 50,000 fans. But a coveted
second NASCAR Winston Cup/Busch Grand National Series weekend
continues to elude Gossage and developer Bruton Smith, the chairman
and CEO of Speedway Motorsports Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario confronting and confounding Gossage is not unique
in the industry. The superspeedway building binge of the 1990s has
seen new facilities rise and shine nationwide, their promoters
banking on landing at least one Winston Cup race as a can't-miss
cash-cow.
</P>
<P>
   Like any superspeedway, Smith's $110-million rendition of
Gargantua residing in north Fort Worth has a voracious appetite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge we have is to hold more and more events _ and
feed the monster,'' said Gossage, borrowing a phrase coined by H.A.
``Humpy'' Wheeler, the president of Smith's Charlotte Motor
Speedway and motorsports' premier promoter. ``I have zero feel for
when that second date is coming \Rto TMS\S. Brian France \RNASCAR's
senior vice president\S has promised me that there will be two
dates in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was something else out there that made economic sense
to do, we'd do it. But I don't see it on the horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's 1.5-mile Texas Motor Speedway and Roger Penske's 2-mile
California Speedway played host to their first Cup dates in 1997.
Both high-profile owners will operate with a single Cup race for
the third consecutive year in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami-Dade Homestead Motorsports Complex in Homestead, Fla.,
whose ownership group features NASCAR president Bill France Jr. and
Penske, will stage its first Cup race on Nov. 14, 1999. The
addition of Homestead's 1.5-mile oval will bump the Cup schedule to
34 points-paying dates.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway International Raceway, located five minutes from St.
Louis in Madison, Ill., underwent a $25 million renovation in 1996.
The 1.25-mile oval has played host to NASCAR Busch Grand National
races the past two years, perhaps paving the way for a Cup event in
the manner that saw Bob Bahre steer his 1.058-mile New Hampshire
International Speedway onto the Cup schedule in July 1993.
</P>
<P>
   New racetracks are either under construction or in various
stages of planning near Chicago, Kansas City, Denver, Sacramento,
Calif., Baltimore and in Kentucky _ all with visions of hosting
``NASCAR-style'' oval racing. But even if every new facility is
successful in landing one Cup race _ a highly unlikely scenario
given the wall-to-wall, 10-month season booked by NASCAR for 1999 _
promoters will need alternative events to fill gaping vacancies on
their event calendars.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR star Jeff Burton said, sorry, the quest for a second Cup
race is not a major concern among his driving brethren.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's in the interest of the majority of the fans is what
we've got to be concerned about,'' Burton said during a Goodyear
tire-test at TMS, the track where he scored his first Cup victory
in April 1997. ``I'm at Texas Motor Speedway saying this and I'll
say it about any racetrack _ if a racetrack can't succeed on racing
one Winston Cup race a year, then you'd better not build it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the value of adding races needs to be seriously
reconsidered. That could mean TMS might never receive a second Cup
date from NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we race too much now,'' Burton said. ``I don't think
California needs a second date. If we are going to grow this sport,
and we are going to make it a true nationwide sport, we cannot
devalue the quality of a race. To give a race to Texas and then to
give a race to \Rfor example\S St. Louis and the next racetrack
that's being built, don't we get more impact from going to a new
market in St. Louis than coming to Texas twice? That goes the same
for Darlington, Daytona and all the racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't the sport better-served by going more places? I think it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gossage has been charged with filling and
re-filling TMS' 150,061 seats _ and the 4,800 being added in front
of the still-under-construction Speedway Club _ with paying
fannies.
</P>
<P>
   The season's main event at TMS is booked for the last weekend in
March. The inaugural Winston Cup Primestar 500 _ successor to the
Interstate Batteries 500 and Texas 500 _ is scheduled for March 28.
It will be preceded by the Coca-Cola 300 Busch Grand National race,
featuring reigning Cup champion Jeff Gordon in one of only five
series starts, on March 27.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage plans to aggressively promote the BGN race as a
one-on-one between Gordon and Dale Earnhardt Jr., the reigning
series champion and its hottest property.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why doesn't that surprise me?'' said Gordon, a veteran of
several SMI promotional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL's True Value 500K night race _ the first series event
after the 83rd Indianapolis 500 _ is booked for June 12. It will be
preceded by the Pronto Auto Parts 400K Craftsman Truck night event
on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   Over a year's worth of lobbying _ and an impassioned, three-page
letter written by Gossage in September _ convinced the IRL's
management to move the season-closer from Las Vegas to TMS as the
Lone Star 500K on Oct. 17. The companion event will be a second
Craftsman Truck race, the Bluebonnet 300K, on the evening of Oct.
15. TMS landed the IRL finale, in part, based upon its record of
gonzo promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to keep feeding the speedway with events,''
Gossage said, ``and keep revenue coming in the door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
