<HEADLINE>
LONE STAR PARK OFFERS $1 MILLION DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY RAMPELLINI 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ There are a million new reasons to come
to Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie next year.
</P>
<P>
   Track officials yesterday announced that seven stakes worth a
combined $1 million would be conducted at Lone Star Park on May 31,
making next year's Memorial Day the richest day in the history of
Texas thoroughbred racing.
</P>
<P>
   The program is the centerpiece of a $3.75 million thoroughbred
stakes schedule next year at Lone Star Park, where live racing
returns on April 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted to make an impact,'' Corey Johnsen, vice
president and general manager of Lone Star Park, said of the new
Lone Star Million Day. ``We wanted to do something special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lone Star Park Handicap, which has been increased in value
from $200,000 to $300,000, headlines the Lone Star Million Day.
Supporting stakes include the $250,000 USA Stakes; the $150,000
Prestonwood Distaff; the $100,000 Lone Star Turf Sprint; and the
$100,000 Wild Flower Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The races are scheduled to be televised on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   The Lone Star Derby, scheduled April 18, has been boosted in
value to $300,000 from $250,000 and is scheduled to be broadcast
live on ESPN along with the $250,000 Texas Mile. The Texas Mile was
recently awarded Grade 3 status from the North American Graded
Stakes Committee, which meets annually to select the most important
stakes races.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a graded stakes is a major accomplishment,'' Johnsen
said of the honor, which is a first for the state. ``We're really
pleased that \Rthe committee\S recognized Lone Star Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Other notable events on the schedule include the National
Thoroughbred Racing Association All-Star Jockey Championship,
scheduled for June 25, and the $125,000 Mesquite Mile Breeders'
Cup, one of 16 stakes races on the schedule worth six figures.
Mid-South Championship Day, a series of stakes for horses bred in
Texas, Louisiana, Oklahoma and Arkansas, has been dropped from the
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Purses during the thoroughbred meeting at Lone Star Park would
average about $220,000 daily, track officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
