<HEADLINE>
TOE KEEPS SANDERS OFF FIELD AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The chances of Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders
finally returning to action for Sunday's crucial matchup with the
Philadelphia Eagles were reduced yesterday when he did not
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey refused to rule out Sanders playing
but said it's unlikely he would play if he is unable to practice
today.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has missed the past three games with a sprained left big
toe. He tried to practice Wednesday, but limped off a few minutes
into the workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a setback,'' Gailey said. ``He's not out here. It's
something we hoped would happen. Looking at the facts, I'm more
pessimistic now. But listening to him, I'm optimistic because he
wants to get on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The outlook is better for receiver Michael Irvin (strained lower
back) and running back Emmitt Smith (sprained ankle), who each
missed practice on Wednesday. Smith returned to practice, while
Irvin did some conditioning drills. Both are expected to be ready
for the Eagles game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much better,'' Irvin said. ``I'm moving around a lot
better. There's been some pain but that's to be expected.''
CORNERBACK SWITCH Gailey declined to say whether Kevin Mathis has
replaced Kevin Smith as the starter at left cornerback. However,
another indication of the expected change was evident on the
practice field yesterday when Smith worked at Sanders' right
cornerback spot and Mathis worked at left cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   That will be the lineup if Sanders is unable to start against
the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Of Smith working at right cornerback, Gailey coyly said: ``He's
best at that position right now.'' EYEING THE PLAYOFFS The Cowboys
could clinch a playoff spot before they take the field against the
Eagles on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A loss by Tampa Bay (7-7) against the Washington Redskins on
Saturday guarantees a wild-card spot for the Cowboys, who can
finish no worse than 8-8. The Cowboys hold the tie-breaker edge
against an 8-8 Tampa Bay team.
</P>
</TEXT>
