<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSING TEAMS HAVE DISCOVERED IT'S FUN TO RUN AGAINST COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Charlie Williams and George Teague were sitting
at their lockers the other day when someone asked what they thought
about Bam Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man,'' Williams said, ``I don't even want to talk about Bam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Me neither, bro,'' Teague said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in too many of his highlight films,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defensive backs have not been alone in a horror
show _ call it The Cowboys' Rundown Run Defense _ that has been
feature length. Part of the reason the Cowboys are mired in a
three-game losing streak is because the Cowboys have yielded 100 or
more yards rushing to each of their last three opponents when their
run defense has plummeted from fifth in the league to 13th.
</P>
<P>
   The meltdown came to a boil last week as Morris, the Kansas City
Chiefs running back, rushed for 137 yards against the Cowboys.
After a look at the film, Cowboys coaches and players estimated
that there were 20 missed tackles, including three on Morris' final
17-yard run that let the Chiefs run out the clock on a 20-17 defeat
of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to get more physical,'' linebacker Randall
Godfrey said. ``Now, I can say that, but everybody knows how to
tackle. We've been playing this game a long time. I know I need to
wrap up better. I missed five tackles last week. You can't have
that many in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor execution when tackling has not been the only problem.
Injuries and the club's propensity for trailing at the end of games
have also conspired to send the Cowboys' run defense spiraling down
the NFL charts.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Eagles will attempt to extend the Cowboys'
misery. Coach Chan Gailey contends that the Eagles are not the same
team that had 96 yards rushing in a 34-0 drubbing by the Cowboys on
Nov. 2. In the six games since, Philadelphia is averaging 130.2
yards rushing. Running back Duce Staley has been the power gear in
the Eagles' 14th-ranked rushing attack. He is eighth in the NFC
with 901 yards. He had a career-high 141 yards on 30 carries
against the Arizona Cardinals last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our No. 1 goal is to stop the run,'' Gailey said. ``That's
something we've got to get back to. Our players realize we've got
to get back to stopping the running game, and it will be another
challenge this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' free fall against the run has occurred as
cornerback Deion Sanders has been on the inactive list. Sanders'
All-Pro talents in pass defense allowed strong safety Darren
Woodson to line up closer to the line of scrimmage as an extra run
defender in an eight-man front. With Sanders out, the Cowboys have
not been able to employ as many eight-man fronts, as Woodson has
often lined up away from the line of scrimmage in pass support.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Vikings, for example, Woodson spent the beginning of
the game lined up deep off the line of scrimmage to help in double
coverage on Randy Moss or Cris Carter. With the Cowboys' leading
tackler out of the fray, Vikings running back Robert Smith began
the game with carries of 15, 13, 6, and 14 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to stop teams with our front seven,'' Godfrey
said. ``We were bringing Woody down earlier in the year, and we had
success. We're getting away from that now.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-game losing streak has meant that the Cowboys often
have played from behind. To keep the lead, teams run the ball. No
one would call the New Orleans Saints' 113 yards rushing against
the Cowboys dominating. But they protected the lead by rushing 36
times. They held the ball for 34 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the same scenario from occurring Sunday, the Cowboys
must take the lead early and force the Eagles to pass. Philadelphia
has the 30th-ranked passing offense in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In situations where the Cowboys are trailing, they often try run
blitzing to create a big play. Too often, this strategy has led to
a big play for their opponent. The Cowboys have allowed nine runs
of 10 yards or longer during this three-game losing streak. When
the Vikings caught the Cowboys blitzing midway through the fourth
quarter on Thanksgiving Day, Leroy Hoard popped free for a 50-yard
touchdown run. Morris' longest runs, of 25 and 17 yards, also came
as the Cowboys blitzed.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have worked this week on all their problems. They
talked about playing with power and holding their gaps. They talked
about making sure tackles and carrying out their assignments. And
most of all, they talked about playing with pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking what has happened to us personally,'' Godfrey said.
``We've got to go out and play the way we are capable of playing.
If we do that, we'll be OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
