<HEADLINE>
STARS WINGING IT IN ATTEMPT TO KEEP THE JOE JINX DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stars won't be able to rely on their bullet-proof alternate
sweaters tonight. They won't have the magic of Friday the 13th to
comfort them. And, truth be told, Sister Eileen Marie Hunter never
performed the exorcism that Stars winger Pat Verbeek jokingly asked
for at Joe Louis Arena the last time he was there.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Stars have to win on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're looking forward to it,'' winger Dan Keczmer said
of the challenge of winning once again on the home ice of the
two-time defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars sauntered into Detroit on Nov. 13 _ Friday the 13th _
and made like the cinema's Jason. Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk
stabbed home a goal seven seconds into the game that night, and the
Stars rambled to a 5-1 victory, breaking a seven-game winless
streak in Detroit. Interestingly, the Stars were wearing their
``green star'' jerseys for the 13th time and ran their record in
those alternate sweaters to 11-0-2. They also were playing their
13th game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in their second and final trip to Detroit during the
regular season, the Stars are intent on proving the first victory
wasn't a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big steppingstone,'' center Mike Modano said. ``We know
that later on if there comes a time that we have to win in that
building, we want to know we can. We're going to have to sooner or
later in our journey to get to where we want to get.''
</P>
<P>
   The journey would end with the Stars clutching the Stanley Cup,
which has the Red Wings' fingerprints all over it. And although
neither team can win the Cup in December, a victory by the Stars
seemingly could help in the mental battle against the Red Wings.
The Stars are 2-0 against Detroit since being eliminated, four
games to two, by the Red Wings in the Western Conference finals _ a
series Red Wings coach Scotty Bowman called the toughest his team
has played in the past two seasons. A victory tonight will give the
Stars the season series with the Wings for only the second time in
the past seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Combine that with the Stars' 2-17-2 record in their past 21
trips to Detroit and that Modano, Keczmer, Verbeek, Derian Hatcher
and Shawn Chambers all grew up in the Detroit area, and there still
is a need for the Stars to prove themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're going to have to play well in that building to
win,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``And I think every one of
our players has taken the 5-1 game and thrown it out the window; it
was an aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not all players. Keczmer, a defenseman who has been
converted to a part-time left wing, got in a fight with Red Wings
captain and leading scorer Steve Yzerman that night after a Keczmer
hit caused the normally placid Yzerman to start throwing his fists.
While Keczmer has been a healthy scratch for the past five games,
he is expected to play against the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan played a great game the last time and kind of got under
their skin. They were more worried about him than they were the
rest of us,'' Modano said. ``I think it's a distraction for the Red
Wings for Dan to be in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Stars on a six-game unbeaten streak (4-0-2) and the
Red Wings winners of their past six games at The Joe, there will be
some pressure. With the Stars (17-5-5) and Red Wings (17-10-1)
ranking second and third, respectively, in Western Conference
winning percentage, there will be pressure. And with the game
televised nationally on ESPN (locally on Fox Sports Southwest),
there will be pressure.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe Verbeek could ask Sister Eileen, his high school
teacher who watches him play every time he's in Detroit, if she
might want to try that exorcism after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I leave the exorcisms to the priests,'' Sister Eileen has
said.
</P>
<P>
   So it looks like the Stars are going to have to do it the hard
way this time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
