<HEADLINE>
WHILE YOUNG STARS FALTER, VETERAN QBS ANSWER CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tell me again about NFL quarterbacks. Tell
me why Kordell Stewart teared up on the bench, why Kerry Collins
said, ``bench me, coach,'' why Ryan Leaf turned out to be a punk.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened, by the way, to that ready-for-stardom
quarterbacking group of Dilfer, Brunell, Bledsoe and McNair? The
next wave of great ones never hit the beach this season.
</P>
<P>
   Has anybody heard lately from Scott Mitchell, Elvis Grbac or Rob
Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   Why, out of nowhere, did the 1998 season turn into an
Oldies-but-Goodies festival for quarterbacks? The Pro Bowl squads
announced this week had its fraudulent vote-getters, like Nate
Newton, but all the QBs were most deserving.
</P>
<P>
   Except please give me the August odds on a foursome of Vinny
Testaverde, Doug Flutie, Randall Cunningham and Chris Chandler
being Pro Bowlers. Somebody should make a movie and call it
``Revenge of the Retreads''.
</P>
<P>
   There's no Favre, no Aikman, no Marino going to the Pro Bowl.
They have been replaced, at least this season, by guys once
considered lightweights, failures or has-beens.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a thought _ did Babe Laufenberg retire too soon?
</P>
<P>
   Old dependables like John Elway and Steve Young continue to hum
along, but overall, a case can be made that the NFL has never seen
a season like 1998 when it comes to quarterback roulette.
</P>
<P>
   Entire franchises rise and fall on this one postition.
Quarterbacks are coach-makers or coach-killers. There is probably
not a better quarterback teacher than Norv Turner, but Turner's
head-coaching career in Washington has been quicksanded by his
inability to find the right, yes, quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Other coaches, however, caught lightning in a jar this season
with a Testaverde, a Flutie, a Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without doubt, it's been a very strange season for
quarterbacks,'' said Laufenberg, who also wanted to stress that his
retirement was perfectly timed. Babe, of course, has moved on from
career quarterback backup status in the NFL to Channel 11 sports
guy and Cowboys' radio network commentator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing worth noting,'' added Laufenberg, ``is if you
take the six quarterbacks in the Pro Bowl, we aren't talking about
just 30-something in age. This is more like 35-and-over. There is a
reason for that, and it's called the zone blitz.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same theme Troy Aikman was talking about yesterday
at Valley Ranch. ``Quarterback is a position that demands
consistency,'' he said. ``The defensive strategy of today has
advanced so much, it takes away from that consistency. As a result,
a premium is being placed on those who have had some form of
exposure over a long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   As surprising as the emergence of a Cunningham or a Flutie has
been, these guys did have a lot of football mileage. Even while
once being labeled NFL failures, they obviously learned well from
the tough times.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of the retreads is mere reinforcement that
quarterbacking is not a young man's game, not at the moment. The
same Kordell Stewart who helped take the Steelers to the AFC
Championship game last January is the same Stewart who is a
confused, tear-stained wreck this season. And then there's Collins,
who two years ago was hailed as a star for guiding the Carolina
Panthers into the playoffs. Since then, it's been a long fall for
Collins, among others.
</P>
<P>
   No quarterback has ever had a rougher NFL introduction than
Aikman in '89, then again in '90. ``But I think it's tougher to
learn the position now than it was then,'' he said. ``The NFL went
through a period in the early nineties when the so-called West
Coast offense changed things. Because it was a quick release
system, defensive coordinators went to more coverage, thinking they
couldn't get to the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``But things changed back due to the zone blitz _ guys coming at
you from areas you least expect _ and for the last few years, the
name of the game has been get the quarterback. They come after you
with bigger, faster people and with very smart schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors figure in, however. ``Some of these young
quarterbacks don't have, or didn't have, an appreciation for just
how tough the position is to play,'' said Aikman. ``They were
oversold on themselves and undersold on what they would be facing.
And then some who had success, they thought it would be easier the
next season. It never is easier. The defense you saw last season,
will change on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacking success is based on many factors, but mainly it
comes down to mental toughness, health and, most important, the
players you have around you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that how a young quarterback handles the tough times
will define how his career will eventually go,'' added Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, 1998 has given us a boatload of test cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
