<HEADLINE>
STUDY RATES CALIFORNIA ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- As the nation's economic engine slows,
California's economy will cool down as well in 1999, but not enough
to trigger a recession, according to a study by an economic
forecasting group.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA Anderson Forecast, a widely followed economic report,
predicts that the continued impact from the Asian economic crisis,
a slowdown in Silicon Valley, moderate cooling off in the
entertainment sector, aerospace layoffs and other factors will
conspire to slow California's growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the state's economy should pick up again in 2000 and 2001,
as Asia recovers and other problems abate, the study indicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is really reaching a peak about now,'' said Tom
Lieser, executive director of the UCLA Anderson Forecast. ``There
are more negatives in the outlook than there have been for a while
. . . but this downturn should be relatively mild and not
particularly long-lasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 2000, we should see resumption of stronger growth in
California and nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy already has seen a shift: Southern California is now
outpacing Northern California in economic growth, a trend that
should continue, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley has been growing sluggishly, a victim of the
Asian crisis, an overheated housing market and a scarcity of
commercial space. The UCLA study predicted the labor market in the
San Jose-Santa Clara area will not resume its growth until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the study indicated corporate earnings growth will
be worrisome next year and that stock market volatility will weaken
investments and purchasing patterns, leading to a gross domestic
product slowdown from 3.7 percent in 1998 to 1.8 percent by
mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
   But the slowing economy should lead the Federal Reserve Board to
cut interest rates by 0.5 percent to keep the economy rolling, the
study showed. The economy should end 1999 up 2.5 percent, rising
2.8 percent in 2000 and 2.7 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The national unemployment rate should rise a little, from 4.4
percent at present to 5.1 percent by mid-1999 before dropping to 5
percent by early 2001, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, nonfarm job growth is expected to slow from 3.2
percent in 1998 to 2.4 percent next year and pick up again to 2.6
percent in 2000 and 2001, the study indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Slower job growth will keep the unemployment rate close to its
current level of 6 percent, the UCLA study said. Real personal
income, which is adjusted for inflation, should moderate from a 5.4
percent pace this year to 3.1 percent in 1999 and 3 percent in
2000. Taxable sales, minus inflation, should drop from 4.2 percent
in 1998 to 3.9 percent and 2.8 percent for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The aerospace industry will be weaker as well, the study
predicted, with employment dropping 3 percent next year and 0.9
percent in 2000, mainly due to the Boeing layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Job growth in the motion-picture and television industries was
flat this year due to layoffs, the Asian crisis and loss of
production business to Canada. But it's still a strong industry
overall, according to the study, which forecast a gain of 17,000
jobs in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Business services jobs, which include information technology
positions, should grow by 6.5 percent this year, the smallest
expansion in the last five years, the study showed. However, even
with the cool-down, job growth in this area still should expand at
almost three times the rate for the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Financial services jobs won't continue their double-digit growth
of the recent past, as mergers and layoffs continue, the study
predicted. Wholesale trade employment, which had been fueled by
booming international trade, should average a 2.4 percent gain
yearly in the next three years, down from 3 percent during 1993 to
1998. But retail job growth should rise a respectable 2 percent to
2.5 percent a year until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot is the real estate market, according to the
study, which indicated historically low mortgage rates should give
rise to robust sales and job growth.
</P>
<P>
   Residential building permits should rise from 125,000 units in
1998 to 150,000 next year and 182,000 in 2000, the study showed.
While home building should be strong, it still is not keeping up
with population growth.
</P>
<P>
   As such, home prices will stay up, the study predicted, with
construction jobs increasing by 61,000 in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   But even with an overall slowdown, the state's economy will grow
faster than the nation's, concurred the UCLA study and a report on
California's fiscal outlook prepared by the state Legislative
Analyst's Office in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the nation as a whole is losing manufacturing
jobs much faster than the state. It's also because California began
its economic recovery later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect California to do better than the rest of the
country,'' said Brad Williams, chief economist for the state
Legislative Analyst's Office.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
