<SLUG> BC-FBC-STEELE-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR EXPECTED TO HIRE CAROLINA ASSISTANT AS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Carolina Panthers assistant Kevin Steele is
expected to be introduced today as the new football coach at
Baylor, ending a lengthy search process that began when Dave
Roberts was reassigned on Dec. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Although Baylor officials would not confirm the decision
yesterday, Steele informed the Panthers organization and players
that he was leaving to take the Bears job. A news conference is
scheduled for 11 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll do a great job at Baylor and I'm happy for him,''
Carolina quarterback Steve Beuerlein said. ``The players will
respect him and play hard for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Jeff Brady said he was upset that Carolina is losing
Steele, who has coached the linebackers for the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quality coach, and there aren't enough of those
around,'' Brady said. ``Losing him will hurt, and I'm very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele, 40, a former Tennessee linebacker (1976-79), has had a
lengthy career as an assistant _ with stints at New Mexico State,
Oklahoma State and Nebraska (1989-94), in addition to Carolina.
This is his first head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   He has also had an eventful week. On Sunday, the day before he
interviewed at Baylor, he was attacked on the sideline by Carolina
linebacker Kevin Greene, who drew a one-game suspension and a fine.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he was described by a source close to the team as
``a good man and a really outstanding people person; the players
really liked him a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also has a great personality, and the alums will love him;
from what I've heard of that situation down there, they're in for a
welcome and dramatic change.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele's emergence as the choice for the job came after former
Alabama coach Gene Stallings _ considered the leading candidate for
more than a week _ withdrew his name from consideration late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad for him that he was able to get some sense of
resolve in his mind and glad that we had taken his advice that we
go on with the search,'' said Baylor President Robert Sloan. ``It
was a really good experience, not only to interview a man like him,
but he gave us a lot of good advice. He was a good consultant.''
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates included Southern Mississippi coach Jeff Bower,
Arkansas defensive coordinator Keith Burns and Highland Park High
School coach Scott Smith.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to making a strong impression in his interview,
Steele was strongly recommended by Dal Shealy, executive director
of the Fellowship of Christian Athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Shealy is also a former Grant Teaff assistant at Baylor with
close ties to Smith _ reopening speculation that the Highland Park
coach may yet land a job with the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   After going through consecutive 2-9 seasons under Roberts,
Baylor players seemed pleased with the choice _ and impressed with
Steele's NFL experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to put coach Roberts down, but to have a coach here that
everyone wants to play for, would be a big change,'' safety Rodney
Smith said. ``This team has really been down, and now we'll have a
coach that everyone respects. The fact that he has NFL experience
is really important, because that's what we all want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Running back Ben Gay] said he felt ``blessed to have a coach
come in with some NFL experience. We needed somebody with some
toughness, and this is going to be good for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
