<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALATE PLEASING  
 QUICK CONTRACT  
 PRE-PARTY PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They talked about the ornate ceilings (the work of a
second-rate architect from the 1920s, declared one woman with a
champagne glass in her hand, but a landmark even so).
</P>
<P>
   They talked about the caviar being served. And served. And
served.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly the people at a party for Daniel, DANIEL BOULUD'S
newly resuscitated restaurant, were not talking about the twin
``I'' words, Iraq and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Boulud's party on Wednesday evening began an hour after the
first flashes of exploding missiles were seen in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bombed Baghdad?'' Boulud said a couple of hours later, when
he was asked whether the president had stolen the party's thunder.
``Really?''
</P>
<P>
   True, a few people in the crowd had been following the events in
the Persian Gulf and Washington. ``I've been at CBS all day,
talking about nothing else but,'' said CARL BERNSTEIN, who with Bob
Woodward in The Washington Post unraveled the Nixon
administration's abuses of power in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was chatting with the writer GITA MEHTA and her husband,
SONNY MEHTA, the president and editor in chief of Alfred A. Knopf.
``It is frightening when that sort of firepower is unleashed and it
doesn't disturb anybody's drink orders,'' Mrs. Mehta said.
</P>
<P>
   But the crowd seemed more interested in the transformation of
the first-floor space that once housed Le Cirque, in the old
Mayfair Hotel at 65th Street and Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel is larger than Le Cirque was. Daniel's tables will be set
in what was the Mayfair's lobby, where there was talk about the new
wall-to-wall carpet _ all 950 yards' worth, which might not sound
like a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does when they're all handmade,'' said STEPHANIE ODEGARD,
who designed them. ``One hundred hand-tied knots per square inch.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman with the champagne glass, who was standing a few
square yards away, said, ``This is a wall-to-wall ego trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick Contract
</P>
<P>
   DAVID STERN, the commissioner of the National Basketball
Association, has been doing some negotiating. But not with the
players union.
</P>
<P>
   He needed only 30 minutes on Wednesday to wrap up a deal for the
vacant land next to his home in Scarsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Stern agreed to pay the Village of Scarsdale $78,000 for a
26,000-square-foot parcel next to land he already owns. Stern plans
to use the vacant land as a buffer, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a beautiful slice that's got old trees and the
like,'' Stern said. ``We offered to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pre-party Party
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ KEITH RICHARDS, who has written and performed rock
anthems for several generations as the lead guitarist of the
Rolling Stones, still leads a spur-of-the-moment life. He does not
bother with restaurant reservations when he and 12 friends go out
to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   They showed up one night last week at Nirvana, a restaurant on
Central Park South, for a head start on the celebration of his 55th
birthday, which is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave them the same table John Lennon used to sit at,'' said
Nirvana's owner, SHAMSHER WADUD, who was celebrating his own
birthday that night and soon referred to Richards by his first
name, as in ``I'm delighted Keith is a Sagittarius, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The group ordered something called the Badshahi Feast, which
consists of 35 dishes. As if that were not enough, they also
ordered the Nawabi Feast (27 dishes) and three bottles of wine.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was $1,200, including a $216 tip.
</P>
<P>
   Wadud did not hurry things along. The restaurant stayed open
until 1 a.m., an hour past closing time.
</P>
</TEXT>
