<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WILLIAMS-OBIT-HNS     12-17 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILLIAMS-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
For all the successes of Dave Williams' University of Houston golf
teams and the men who played on them, Williams will leave an even
greater legacy for the school he loved so much and for which he
worked so diligently.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Williams, whose 16 NCAA golf titles at UH are more than any
coach of a team sport in major-college athletics, died Thursday
morning in Wharton after a lengthy illness. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won in the beginning, in the middle and at the end,'' said
Steve Elkington, one of Williams' squadron of PGA Tour products.
``Most of the great coaches go out on a low note. Not Dave. He
brought the goods at the start, in the middle and at the last.''
</P>
<P>
   Elkington, who came halfway around the world from Australia to
play for the only American collegiate coach who recruited him,
added, ``You always came away from coach with a stronger belief in
yourself. He was a strength-builder. He had a way of making you
believe in yourself, that you could do on or off the golf course
whatever you set your mind to.''
</P>
<P>
   Long after his retirement in 1987, no NCAA coach of a Division I
team sport has matched Williams' 16 golf championships, recorded in
four decades, during his 36 years as the Cougars' coach.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the numbers _ and they include eight NCAA
individual championships won by seven golfers, 14 conference
championships, 340 tournament wins and 41 players who won 66
All-America honors _ Williams will be remembered best by colleagues
and former players for the energy he brought to the task.
</P>
<P>
   And for his most enduring greeting and most familiar farewell,
``You're the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams arrived at UH in 1946, one week after his discharge
from the U.S. Navy, to join the school's engineering faculty.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Guy V. Lewis, fresh out of the Army Air Corps,
came to play basketball. ``He hadn't been here but a week,'' Lewis
recalled recently during their induction into the UH Hall of Honor,
``and Dave came up and introduced himself like he had been around
here for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was Dave, and his enthusiasm for the school and for the
Cougars.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nantz, a former UH golfer and now lead sportscaster for CBS,
referred to the innate ability Williams possessed that was his
greatest strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loved him like a second father,'' said Nantz, ``and not a
day goes by that I didn't think of coach Dave. None of us ever saw
him hit a golf shot, but he had that ability to find your strength
and make you believe in yourself. His greatest attribute was his
energy to make people excel and become better than perhaps even
they thought they could become.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Jimbo, one of these days you're going to be
president of the United States.' The point is, he made me think I
could do anything I wanted, and he gave me and all his players that
inner confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who came to be called ``The Father of College Golf''
because of the changes he instituted in the college game, coached
NCAA champions in the 1950s, '60s, '70s and '80s after he was urged
by athletic director Harry Fouke in 1952 to take over the duties
Fouke was then handling.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 34, began using stroke play _ instead of the
match-play format then common _ in the All-America Intercollegiate
Invitational in 1955. That method eventually became standard in
college golf.
</P>
<P>
   What did not become standard was the way Williams could recruit,
in those days of no scholarship limits, from around the nation and,
in the case of Elkington and others, from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He convinced my mother that even though I was going thousands
of miles away, that I would be looked after, because that's the
kind of person he was,'' said Elkington, who won the 1995 PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   John Mahaffey, the 1970 NCAA titlist at UH and the 1978 PGA
champion, said: ``Playing in the number of tournaments and team
qualifying that he put us in came from his own competitive nature.
He wanted to win every time, and he also wanted to make sure he was
picking the right guys. He's a legend, like John Wooden (whose UCLA
basketball teams won 10 NCAA titles in 12 years).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have been part of a dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1918 in Randolph, Williams was a 1939 graduate of East
Texas State College.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his retirement, the Golf Coaches Association of
America began honoring the NCAA men's coach of the year with the
Dave Williams Award.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Fergus, a three-time first-team All-America pick (1974-76)
and later Williams' successor as UH coach, topped the list of his
former coach's talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, he had a passion for UH and UH golf,'' Fergus said.
``He loved that university. He always told you that you were No. 1,
and sooner or later you started to believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   Like nearly all of his former players, Fergus described
Williams' own golf talent: ``I never saw him swing a club. He used
to say that he would beat his own players and that he didn't want
to discourage us.''
</P>
<P>
   Elkington made the point that, ``I'd get sick and tired of
people who said Dave couldn't have been a great coach because he
wasn't a great player. When's the last time you saw Joe Paterno or
Bobby Bowden throw a pass? He was the best golf coach who ever
lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is survived by his wife, Virginia, son Joel, daughter
Peggy and four grandchildren. Services are scheduled for 2 p.m.
Sunday at the Wharton Civic Center. Visitation will be from 5 to 7
p.m. Saturday at the Wharton Funeral Home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
