<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6155 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MARINO-HNS &LR;      12-17 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARINO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ After five operations on his left knee and another on a
ruptured Achilles' tendon, Miami Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino
walks with a slight limp.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why he continually hears that he's wearing down,
that he can't keep pace with another 37-year-old quarterback, John
Elway of the Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos, who visit the
Dolphins on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But while legs were once a major part of Elway's game, they
never did much for Marino, strictly a thrower even when he was
playing for the University of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   If he's less nimble than ever, Marino is still adroit at eluding
sportswriters. He's usually polite but brief: ``Just a couple more
questions, guys. Gotta go, nap time.'' He meets with the media only
after games and on Thursday afternoons, and then only for five to
10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks carefully, trying to avoid offending his coach, Jimmy
Johnson, who isn't so careful not to offend his quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Johnson praises Marino, it's faint: ``I still think
Dan is in the upper half of the league's quarterbacks, even at this
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson makes Marino a scapegoat for much of what goes wrong for
the Dolphins, who are 9-5 but fighting for a postseason life and
close with the Broncos and the Atlanta Falcons _ teams that are a
combined 25-3.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was at it again after Miami's 21-16 loss to the New York
Jets last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson blamed an opening-drive stall on ``an overthrow,'' when
actually Marino was trying to throw the ball away to avoid a sack.
</P>
<P>
   And Johnson couldn't resist pointing out the one time in 57
passes that night on which Marino was intercepted. ``We get down
there later in the game,'' the coach said, ``and Dan wants to throw
to O.J. McDuffie and it got picked off.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Johnson became coach of the Dolphins in 1996, he let
it be known he wasn't entirely comfortable with Marino. Johnson
wanted an offense based on power running, like he had with Emmitt
Smith and the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tried for an instant personnel makeover in Miami,
shifting the focus from passing to running. And this year, he
completely rewrote the playbook he inherited from Don Shula.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's new offense left little room for Marino to make
adjustments at the line of scrimmage. Johnson, with another of his
subtle digs, claimed that of the 70 audibles Marino called last
season, 55 resulted in gains of three yards or less and three
resulted in interceptions that were returned for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be at the line of scrimmage with the
offensive linemen back on their heels waiting for a play to be
called,'' said Johnson, who fired the offensive coordinator, Gary
Stevens, ``because of the problems we've had running the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the changes, Miami still has problems running the
ball. The Dolphins are 19th in the NFL in rushing and average just
3.6 yards per attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Johnson, the team's general manager as well as head
coach, has provided Marino with pedestrian receivers _ no Mark
Duper, Mark Clayton or Irving Fryar in this bunch.
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie is a fine pass catcher, but he lacks separation speed.
The No. 2 wideout, Oronde Gadsen, is in need of rest, having played
arena football before stepping into the NFL this season. ``He's got
two turf toes,'' Johnson said, ``and it's starting to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Troy Drayton has a broken bone in his right hand. And
Karim Abdul-Jabbar and fullback Stanley Pritchett, besides being
sluggish runners, are not adept at catching passes or picking up
blitzers. In Sunday's game, Pritchett twice failed to look back for
passes that whizzed by his ear.
</P>
<P>
   So while Marino's passer rating has declined each year Johnson
has been in Miami (to its current 77.5), there is debate over who
is to blame: the coach/GM or the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Sharpe, Pro Bowl tight end for the Broncos, apparently
sides with Johnson. Last summer, Sharpe said Marino, unlike Elway,
``is no longer the player he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino avoids firing back insults at those who criticize him,
but he concedes little to age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say I can throw it as good as anyone who ever played,'' he
said. ``My arm strength is just as good as it has ever been,
although I do notice the endurance factor sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask him if Johnson's coaching limits him, and he tiptoes
delicately, as he did in his Thursday media session: ``I was pretty
lucky early on (in his career) because I had a great group of
receivers and a coach who was very willing to open things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running an offense now that's a little more controlled.
The passing game is not as sophisticated as in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino and Elway will be facing each other for the first time
since 1985. ``It's kind of weird that we've only played once and it
was 13 years ago,'' Marino said. ``You'd think the way the schedule
is, we'd have met more times.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, Marino has had the better career. He holds NFL
records for passing yardage, 58,238, and touchdown passes, 403.
Marino also leads Elway in completion percentage (.596-.569) and
yards per pass (7.36-7.10).
</P>
<P>
   But Elway has a Super Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was somewhat jealous, but I was very happy for him,'' said
Marino, who played on the losing team in the 1985 Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
