<DOCNO> NYT19981217.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6156 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ELWAY-HNS &LR;      12-17 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ Almost 16 seasons since the greatest quarterback draft in
NFL history, only two remain.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the six quarterbacks drafted in the first round in 1983, Todd
Blackledge (Pittsburgh) is a college football television analyst.
Jim Kelly (Buffalo) is part of ESPN's broadcast team. Ken O'Brien
(New York Jets) is the quarterbacks coach at Southern California.
Tony Eason (New England) works for a company in Northern
California.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway, the first pick (by the Baltimore Colts) in a draft
that was called the deepest and most talented in history, forced a
trade to Denver soon after he was picked.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino, who owns almost every NFL passing record, was
selected last among the six, taken 23rd by the Miami Dolphins in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Elway and Marino will face each other for only the
second time in their illustrious careers. Their only other
encounter on the field was on Sept. 28, 1985, at Mile High Stadium.
The Dolphins escaped with a 30-26 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Marino threw for 390 yards and three touchdowns that day. Elway
threw for 250 yards without a touchdown and failed to engineer one
of his now-patented comebacks. He had a chance but was intercepted
on the last drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be nice to go play on the same field, because it's
amazing that in 16 years we've only played each other one time,''
Elway said. ``I look forward to seeing Dan play, but even more
important, we've got to get back on track ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Broncos and Dolphins are coming off losses, the game
is much more than an intriguing confrontation. And because Denver
lost to the Giants to ruin its chance to join the 1972 Dolphins as
the league's only unbeaten and untied champions, the game has lost
some of its luster.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Elway-Marino angle on Monday Night Football is
getting a lot of attention _ as it should _ because both are headed
for the Pro Football Hall of Fame. Because they were drafted the
same year and are two of the greatest ever, their careers have been
entwined.
</P>
<P>
   ``That comparison has been there since we were seniors in high
school,'' Elway said. ``He went to Pitt, and I went to Stanford,
and being the same age and the same year in school and as well as
coming in the NFL the same time, I think we've paralleled each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have got a great deal of respect for him. Early in our
careers, he had more success than I did. Now, because of the teams
we've played on, it's kind of evened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway is 38, Marino 37. Because Elway played for Dan Reeves, a
conservative coach who believed strongly in the running game and a
more controlled passing game, he has not compiled the massive
numbers of Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Marino was fortunate Don Shula redesigned his offense to take
advantage of Marino's strong arm and quick release.
</P>
<P>
   In their first three seasons, Marino threw 98 touchdown passes
and 44 interceptions. Elway's comparable figures were 47 and 52.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the Elway-Marino comparisons affected him early in his
career, Elway said:
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot to it because we were both young. It was
difficult because I came to a team that was 2-7 the year before. He
went to a great team. He hit the ground running, and I kind of went
the other direction and had to climb my way out of a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Like almost everyone else in the NFL, Elway couldn't believe it
when Marino threw 48 touchdown passes in 1984, his first full year
as a starter. ``Pretty amazing,'' Elway said. ``I was hoping I
could do that in three years, but he did it in one.''
</P>
<P>
   But things change. Now, Elway works in the more wide-open
offense of coach Mike Shanahan. And Marino is being restricted by
the conservative Jimmy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Until last season, the Class of '83 had a combined Super Bowl
record of 0-9. Elway, who was 0-3, finally earned a ring when the
Broncos defeated Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   After going so long without winning a Super Bowl, Elway feels
for Marino, who has played in just one _ in his second season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Dan gets tired of answering those questions,'' Elway
said. ``No matter what he does, that's going to be the thing that
everybody goes back to. That's what happened to me after we lost
our last Super Bowl in '89. No matter what you do, numbers-wise or
anything else, it still goes back to how many Super Bowls you've
won.
</P>
<P>
   ``By us winning it last year, I no longer had to answer all
those questions. That's a big burden. I have got a great deal of
empathy for Dan, especially with the career he's had and what he's
done for the NFL. It's unfair, but unfortunately that's a way of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Fouts didn't play in a Super Bowl. Warren Moon hasn't. Kelly
played in four but lost them all.
</P>
<P>
   Elway has never been shy about speaking out about the injustice
of judging quarterbacks by Super Bowl victories. He still doesn't
like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is you don't have to talk about it (not winning
a Super Bowl) anymore,'' he said. ``The biggest burden got to be
that once I got into my 13th, 14th, 15th year, it no longer
mattered what we did on the field as far as wins and losses. There
was only one thing that counted _ winning a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mind-boggling and frustrating to realize that you are a
cog in the machine but everybody wants to point the finger at you
and say you hadn't won the big one.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Broncos don't repeat, Elway would like to see Marino win
a ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about that,'' Elway said. ``He's worked
hard. He's a team guy. His main mission is to win a Super Bowl. To
get the credit he deserves, I sure hope he can win one. I hope he
has to go through us. If we can't get it, I'd like to see him get
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-98 2345EST &QL; 
