<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6157 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BAYLOR-STEELE-HNS     12-17 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-STEELE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ Kevin Steele, the Carolina Panthers linebackers coach who
was a late addition to Baylor's coaching search, will be introduced
today as the new football coach for the Bears.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steele resigned from the Panthers on Thursday, telling Carolina
officials he needed to start recruiting at Baylor. The Panthers
(2-12) have two games left, but they are tied for the worst record
in the NFL and are out of the playoff picture.
</P>
<P>
   Only moments after Baylor athletic director Tom Stanton held a
media briefing Thursday morning to say something could be finalized
within 48 hours, Carolina officials announced Steele had resigned
to take the Baylor job.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor officials have refused to comment about Steele, but
sources say a news conference is expected at 11 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an emotional week for Steele, who found himself in
the national spotlight when Carolina linebacker Kevin Greene
grabbed him by the jacket during a sideline altercation in Sunday's
game against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Until that moment, you probably couldn't find half a dozen
Baylor fans who had heard of Steele, who never has been a head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Steele, 40, joined the Carolina staff in 1995 after five years
as an assistant coach at Nebraska. Sources say Steele was so
well-liked at Nebraska, many fans were upset he was not selected
last year to replace coach Tom Osborne, who retired and chose
longtime assistant Frank Solich as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Steele's selection by Baylor officials will come as a surprise
to many Baylor backers, who expected former Alabama coach Gene
Stallings to get the job. But Stallings withdrew his name from
consideration Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Many people thought Southern Mississippi coach Jeff Bower was
Baylor's second choice if Stallings declined, but sources close to
the program said Bower's interview did not go well in comparison to
Steele's. One Baylor official said Steele ``knocked their socks
off'' during his interview Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Steele, who attended high school in Dillon, S.C., played
linebacker for Tennessee from 1976-79. Friends say his lifelong
dream was to become a head coach at a school in a major conference.
His coaching stints include stops at Tennessee (1981-82 and
1987-88), New Mexico State (1983) and Oklahoma State (1984-86)
before going to Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Others who interviewed for the Baylor job include Bears
offensive coordinator Eddie Williamson, Arkansas defensive
coordinator Keith Burns and Dallas Highland Park coach Scott Smith,
a former Baylor player who might be hired as an assistant on
Steele's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Steele will replace Dave Roberts, who was reassigned Dec. 6
after posting back-to-back 2-9 seasons. Roberts, the former
offensive coordinator at Notre Dame, replaced Chuck Reedy, who was
fired by Stanton after the team went 4-7 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Though Steele is not the big-name hire Stallings would have
been, some longtime Baylor fans compare it to the situation when
Grant Teaff was hired in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Baylor alumni at that time hoped the school would
hire well-known and well-respected Johnny Majors instead of the
little-known Teaff, but Teaff would become the most successful
coach in school history over his 21 seasons at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor players seemed excited about Steele getting the job.
Baylor freshman running back Ben Gay was asked if it meant
something to the players to have a coach who has worked in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it does,'' Gay said. ``We're blessed to have a coach
coming here with experience in the NFL. That gives us a lot more
confidence because he knows what it takes to get to the next level.
I also hear he's somebody with some toughness, and that's what we
need. Now, it's time for us to come together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Baylor players approached Stanton last month saying they
would transfer if Roberts wasn't replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to put down coach Roberts, but having a coach everybody
wants to play for will be a big change here,'' junior safety Rodney
Smith said. ``The morale of this team has been pretty low, to tell
you the truth. To have a coach that everyone respects will be good.
</P>
<P>
   ``With (Steele) coming from the NFL, that's probably the best
credentials you can have because everybody is trying to get there.
Now, maybe my last year can be something special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina players were disappointed to hear Steele was
leaving, but they understand why Baylor officials want him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very upset,'' Panthers linebacker Jeff Brady said. ``He's
a quality coach. We lost Kevin, and it's going to hurt this team.
There are not enough good coaches in this business. Kevin is an
outstanding coach, and Baylor is lucky to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll do a great job at Baylor,'' Carolina quarterback Steve
Beuerlein said. ``The players will respect him and play hard for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible Steele would have been out of a job at Carolina.
Charles Chandler, who covers the the Panthers for the Charlotte
Observer, reported Thursday that head coach Dom Capers might be
fired at the end of the season. But Chandler believes Steele will
be a success at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man and a good coach,'' Chandler said. ``He's a
real people person, and all the players liked him a lot. And he has
such a good personality that the alumni there will love him. From
what I've heard about the previous situation there, you all are in
for a welcome change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
