<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-STUNTMAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS! CAMERA! FOOTBALL! FOR EX-USC PLAYER
</HEADLINE>
 -LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGOURA, Calif. _ At quarterback . . . Dennis Quaid.
</P>
<P>
   Which presents some peculiar challenges for the person directing
the stunts for Oliver Stone's new football drama, ``On Any Given
Sunday,'' which will begin shooting in Miami next month.
</P>
<P>
   Quaid stands 6-foot-1 and is 170 pounds. That's a healthy
physique in most walks of life but a bit scrawny when measured
against unemployed jocks who are capable of throwing tight spirals
_ the available pool of stunt doubles. Quaid is also left-handed,
further complicating the search. What's more, the filmmakers will
need not one of these stunt players but three.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   The stuntman, says Allan Graf, ``has got to know going in that
he's going to take some hits. He's going to get !ital!nailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember the 360-degree propeller ride that John Elway was sent
on at the last Super Bowl? Well, they're going to try to re-create
it in this movie. And it won't be Quaid going airborne.
</P>
<P>
   Graf relates all of this with a devilish chuckle over breakfast
at a deli near his home in Agoura.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Hollywood's football guru, the man who has delivered
astonishing realism as second-unit director and stunt coordinator
on such films as ``Jerry Maguire,'' ``The Program'' and a
made-for-TV movie on Dennis Byrd, the former New York Jets player
who suffered a serious spinal injury. ``The Waterboy,'' Hollywood's
recent box-office success? Yep, that was his handiwork, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been the man (for football action sequences),'' said
Frank Coraci, director of ``The Waterboy.'' ``I watched a bunch of
his movies. I was, like, `I like that. I like that. I like that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What was kind of cool, I saw different movies he did, and
stylistically they weren't all the same. `Jerry Maguire' has an NFL
Films look. `The Program' uses more wide angles on the field, so
you felt more like a player. I saw he could work with all different
kinds of (directorial) visions and still come up on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf got into the stunt business shortly after completing his
playing career as an offensive tackle on USC's 1972
national-championship team. (His son, Derek, out of Agoura High, is
a freshman for the Trojans at the same position.)
</P>
<P>
   Allan was like a lot of people who have spent time around elite
football and wince at the often-clumsy attempts to bring the action
to the big screen. He found the scenes bordering on laughable. (You
know the footage: Defenders mysteriously sprawl onto the ground,
unblocked, as the hero breaks off an absurd weaving run for a
touchdown.)
</P>
<P>
   So after doing football stunt work in such movies as ``Gus'' and
``Heaven Can Wait'' (``I pick up Warren Beatty in the end zone
after he scores,'' he said), Graf nearly tumbled over himself a few
years ago when given his first opportunities to coordinate football
stunts, notably in ``Oklahoma City Dolls'' (a TV movie) and
``Necessary Roughness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw movies where (the football action) takes you right out
of it if it's not realistic,'' Graf said. ``I wasn't going to be
laughed at. I'm going to make my football real. It goes back to my
football playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `The Waterboy,' I told them, `You're not going to make the
football comedy. We're going to make it real. The comedy is going
to come out of Adam Sandler's character.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That coincided with Coraci's plan. The football sequences, the
director said Thursday, ``were treated like full-on real stunts,
with real pain. Pain lends itself to comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Hollywood hokiness is inevitable in other aspects of
the movies Graf works on, however. He says he cringed when Cuba
Gooding Jr. broke into a seemingly endless celebration after rising
to his feet after a vicious hit in ``Jerry Maguire.'' And some
directors insist that opposing linemen jaw at each other even when
the quarterback has begun his cadence, which would draw a flag in
the real world.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he is thrilled to be working with Stone, who has
assured him ``On Any Given Sunday'' won't deviate from NFL realism.
</P>
<P>
   Graf welcomes invitations to deliver teeth-rattling authenticity
to the cameras. Throughout this month he has been conducting a
training camp in Miami, working with 200 potential stunt players _
refugees from the NFL waiver lists, the Canadian Football League,
Arena ball. Once he has selected his roster for the movie, he'll
cut the squad, just as they do in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   He'll also draw up plays and assignments and carefully
choreograph each highlight-reel completion and collision.
</P>
<P>
   When shooting starts in January, the stuntmen will really start
earning their money.
</P>
<P>
   That scene in ``Jerry Maguire'' in which Gooding's character
gets toppled on his head in the end zone? It required 29 takes,
with three different stunt players rotating as Gooding's Arizona
Cardinals wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Watch it closely the next time you see the movie. The director,
Cameron Crowe, wanted the scene to look just like a Monday-night
telecast on ABC. So the injury scene is one continuous shot from
the snap of the ball, with no cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Also, while it is not unusual for players to get hit in the legs
and flipped while reaching up for a pass (they can usually break
their fall with their free arm), in this scene a second defender
shoves the receiver in the back while he is upended.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week before we shot that, we rehearsed that,'' Graf said.
``We put a portable pit (the kind used for high jump competitions)
out there. We rehearsed and rehearsed, so the two defenders come
in, they hit him, he knows where he's going to land.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the actual movie scene, stuntman Horace Knight ``hit
right where we knew it was going to be safe,'' landing on the top
of his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Graf recalls another harrowing moment _ involving himself. In
``The Program,'' the filmmakers had been granted the field for 20
minutes during halftime of a Tennessee-South Carolina game.
</P>
<P>
   Graf had a camera rigged inside a helmet, so the audience's view
would be out through the mask, and he was to simulate a touchdown
punt return.
</P>
<P>
   First problem: The punter was nervous and shanked the first
three. After the third, Graf screamed, ``Just throw the (expletive)
ball!'' The ball was passed in his direction, and he took off
running, wearing no pads, gingerly holding the camera in front of
him.
</P>
<P>
   Second problem: The presence of a real stadium crowd had caused
the adrenaline of the stunt players to soar. All the blocks and
near-miss hits were rehearsed in advance, but ``I start running and
all these players are flying at me,'' Graf said. ``I'm totally
vulnerable with that camera. If something doesn't happen just
right, I get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   He's never been shy about taking risks, though.
</P>
<P>
   Graf gave up football after a brief stay in the World Football
League in the early 1970s. During one pro offseason, he got a stunt
job on ``Gus,'' the Disney movie about a mule that kicks field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   When the WFL folded, Graf gravitated to the Stuntmen's
Association, and soon was getting steady work as a stunt double for
Dick Butkus (the facial resemblance is uncanny).
</P>
<P>
   Because of his body type and background _ and high pain
threshold _ he got a lot of opportunities to play bodyguards,
bouncers, assorted heavies. ``When I started out,'' Graf said, ``I
did things everyone else didn't want to do. `Hey, let Allan run
through that wall.' I did the tough stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes voluntarily. He beams proudly while announcing that he
was the first stuntman to cannon-roll a bus, in the movie ``Another
48 Hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Not familiar with the technique? Picture this: Two five-foot
lengths of telephone pole encased in steel, positioned in vertical
cylinders inside the left wall of the bus, with an eight-ounce
black-powder bomb atop each pole. Drive the bus 60 mph, activate an
oil sprayer on the left tires as you turn sharply left. Activate
the bombs. The poles fire out of their cylinders, propelling the
bus into a sharp roll onto its right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus went 17 feet in the air,'' Graf said. ``We made two
full rolls. They'd wanted to set up a crash camera (in a cage,
remotely controlled) and asked where I thought I'd end up. I said,
`I have no idea.' Well, the bus landed right on top of the crash
camera. Perfect shot.'' (It was used in the movie.)
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the occupation isn't for everyone _ just ask those
poor saps who will stand in for Dennis Quaid when the blitz comes
roaring in.
</P>
<P>
   But Graf delights in this work, and apparently the passion is
reciprocal. Coraci said the stuntmen refer to Graf as ``Coach,''
adding, ``The players really give it up for him. We had some really
hard hitting in our movie. I think it's because they respect him as
a football player.''
</P>
<P>
   To maintain an appreciation of his chosen course, Graf need only
think back to when he left San Fernando High for USC and was
scraping up whatever summer work he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year,'' he said, ``it was one of the hottest summers
in the Valley, and I was putting in pools in the hills, in Encino,
Tarzana. I would wheel(barrow) concrete, dig footings for walls. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   ``Another year, I worked with (then-USC tight end) Charle Young
building high-rise parking structures in Beverly Hills. Hanging
60-70 feet over, tying steel, pouring concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incentive to me to find something that I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Something he could do and relish.
</P>
<P>
   There's little doubt that Allan Graf accomplished his
objective. &QL; 
CAMEO CHRONICLE
</P>
<P>
   In addition to doing stunt work, stunt coordination and
second-unit direction in more than 50 Hollywood movies, former San
Fernando High and USC tackle Allan Graf has had several bit-acting
parts _ mostly heavies. ``I've been beaten up by the best of
them,'' he said good-naturedly. Here are some examples: &QL; 
__ Golf coach: Opening sequence of ``Jerry Maguire.'' Gets a golf
club thrown at him by bratty prodigy. &QL; 
__ Prison-bus driver: Transports bad guy in ``Another 48 Hours.''
(Then rolls the bus in a stunt assignment.) &QL; 
__ Wife-beater: Opening scene of ``L.A. Confidential.'' &QL; 
__ Killer: Donut-shop scene in ``Boogie Nights.'' &QL; 
__ Convict: Beats up his cellmate, Kiefer Sutherland, in
``Flashback.'' &QL; 
__ Biker: In ``Cannonball Run,'' gets kicked in the crotch by
Farrah Fawcett and beaten up by Jackie Chan and Burt Reynolds. &QL; 
__ Limo driver: Chauffeurs Mr. Big in ``Wayne's World.'' As stunt
man, wheels limo into 180-degree spin on Woodley Avenue in the
Sepulveda Basin (quite a feat considering the movie is set in
Illinois). &QL; 
__ Bartender: In ``Fighting Back,'' gets beaten up by Tom
Skerritt. &QL; 
__ Baseball player: In ``Brewster's Millions,'' gets into a brawl
with John Candy and Richard Pryor. &QL; 
__ Bank customer: Holdup victim in ``The Long Riders.'' In same
movie, is also seen as train engineer. &QL; 
__ Next-door neighbor: Just wants to watch TV with his buddies in
``Poltergeist.'' &QL; 
__ Short-order cook: Gets into an argument, then a fight, with
Jean-Claude Van Damme in ``Universal Soldier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
