<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IN Los Angeles, there is now a third player in the NFL derby. It's
almost to the point where you can't tell the wannabe expansion
owners there without a scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Bob McNair and Steve Patterson are becoming experts
in revolving stadium signs and giant video screens.
</P>
<P>
   LA has gone from two contending stadium sites to three. Houston
is fine-tuning the detail work on state-of-the-art amenities. For
all we know, Mrs. McNair might be picking out wallpaper for the
family's 50-yard-line luxury suite.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not to be interpreted as arrogance or
overconfidence. McNair knows his fight isn't won. No matter how
many clamoring, issue-clouding factions try to enter the fray in
Los Angeles, he won't underestimate the city's immense clout. But
he wants the NFL's existing owners to understand, in no uncertain
terms, that he will be ready when they are.
</P>
<P>
   Something LaLa Land can't promise.
</P>
<P>
   With a ``yes'' vote for Houston in the spring, construction on a
21st-century Astrodome can begin right after the millennium, in
time for a 2002 debut. McNair's i's will be dotted and, knowing
him, the kicking tees purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Further, when completed, there won't be a finer football venue
in the kingdom. If a bell or whistle can be had, Bob wants it. He
also wants his would-be peer group of owners to understand that he
wants it. Truth is, the way the NFL works, stadiums are more
important than markets these days.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Patterson, McNair's right-hand man and the guy doing
most of the grunt work for Houston NFL Holdings Inc., spent his
weekend perusing the many wonders of Baltimore's new edifice,
accompanied by the rodeo's head honcho, Leroy Shafer. And why
McNair joined up with Patterson for a Monday-Tuesday tour of NFL
stadiums in Tampa, Miami and Jacksonville. McNair hopes to hit 20
league cities before he's done.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the current season, Patterson has traveled to
12, where he shakes hands, takes notes and looks behind as many
doors as his hosts open for him. These visits have served a dual
purpose. The schmoozing with NFL people, reminding them of
Houston's preparedness, enthusiasm and intensity level, is as
important as what can be gleaned from up-close observation of the
myriad fun stuff the thoroughly modern sports venue has to offer
the customer.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the latter Patterson finds fascinating. His favorite?
No question about it _ the two 100-foot-by-20-foot video screens in
Baltimore that permit the showing of three games per, or six games
at once.
</P>
<P>
   If the Ravens have a late start, their fans can come out and
theoretically watch every one of the early games simultaneously. Or
vice versa, staying afterward to enjoy what the Ravens are
marketing as ``the fifth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' Patterson said, noting that, yes, the screens have
been added to Houston's shopping list.
</P>
<P>
   Again, while it might sound like the cart is being put in front
of the horse, that's not the case. Because the McNair team can't
outglitz LA's unholy trinity, it must attack in other ways. The
NFL's owners need to be blown away by how thorough and how together
Houston's total package is. That's McNair's game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a great reception from all of the owners,'' Patterson
said of the east-by-southeast swing. ``Everybody was very helpful,
very positive. They want Houston back in the National Football
League.''
</P>
<P>
   But they want Los Angeles as well, assuming that sprawling,
diffuse metropolis can get its act together. The latest addition to
the city's franchise free-for-all is Jack Singer, a Canadian real
estate tycoon who has put the oft-discussed Hollywood Park complex
back in play.
</P>
<P>
   Singer, whose only sporting credentials are failed bids to buy
the Toronto Blue Jays and the Kansas City Royals, is negotiating an
option on 30 acres of the Inglewood horse-track site adjacent to
the Great Western Forum. It's not a paradise locale by any measure,
but it's more highly thought of by most Angelenos than Michael
Ovitz's former toxic-waste dump plot south of LA proper in Carson
or Ed Rosky's pie-in-the-skyish Coliseum redo.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners love or hate Ovitz, depending on how they perceive
his Hollywood connection. Rosky, they have begun to fear, is
underfinanced as well as geographically misguided, given the
league's antipathy toward the Coliseum area. As for Singer, he
might bring the best package to the plate, but isn't he a bit of a
Jack-come-lately?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still open to meeting with any other people who are
interested in bringing a team to LA,'' says Greg Aiello of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Figures. But the Houston group, plowing headfirst into the
details, doesn't have time to fret over the multiple-choice options
on the West Coast. The more the merrier. Divide and conquer always
has been a sound military strategy.
</P>
</TEXT>
